 PACIFIC BELL ADS TO INCLUDE DISCLAIMER  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Pacific Bell said Tuesday that it will add a
disclaimer to its comical ``Web Hog'' television commercials to
make it clear that its high-speed Internet service only offers
individual connections between users' homes and the nearest
switching office and not direct connection to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome, which provides a rival Internet service over cable
television lines, has threatened to sue the telephone company
unless it yanks the ads because they tout Pac Bell's service as
``Always Fast. Never Shared.''
</P>
<P>
   Redwood City, Calif.'s ExciteAtHome said the ads are misleading
because they imply that Pac Bell's service, called DSL or digital
subscriber line technology, gives users direct connections to Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell spokesman John Britton said the disclaimer is already
used for radio and print ads, but the company didn't use it in
television ads, because all the images in the commercial focus on a
neighborhood _ where users have separate connections over regular
phone lines. Once the phone lines reach the switching office,
e-mail and other Internet traffic are merged together _ so, in
theory, users' connections to the Net could slow down if too many
people send heavy amounts of data at once.
</P>
<P>
   But ExciteAtHome spokeswoman Alison Bowman said the company, the
largest provider of cable modem service, is still demanding that
Pac Bell halt the ads or drop the ``never shared'' tag line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that a legal disclaimer on the same ad won't be
enough,'' Bowman said. ``Even with the disclaimer (the ad) will
continue to mislead consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads lampoon cable modem service, like the kind offered by
ExciteAtHome, because cable lines are shared in a neighborhood much
like a party line. So as more users sign up, the service could
theoretically slow to a crawl. That's occasionally happened in a
handful of neighborhoods, including Fremont.
</P>
<P>
   But cable companies claim it's not generally a problem because
they can upgrade the equipment and split the neighborhood lines
into smaller and smaller networks as more customers sign up.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
