 STARS TAKING A SHINE TO THE INTERNET  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dozens of dot-coms are reconsidering their
options after the April 14 Nasdaq shakeout. But that does not seem
to be interfering with Pamela Anderson Lee's plan to launch her own
Web site. Pamtv.com is under construction, and the former
``Baywatch'' babe is asking fans to tell her what they really want
to see.
</P>
<P>
   Pam evidently is so intrigued by the B2C space that she attended
a Red Herring party three weeks ago to celebrate the opening of the
magazine's Hollywood bureau. She was accompanied by her
Internet-savvy agent, Leonard Armato, who has already helped other
clients set up shop on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   At Shaquille O'Neal's Dunk.net, for instance, visitors can buy
apparel and even participate in a contest to win Shaq's autographed
game-worn playoff shoes.
</P>
<P>
   One can only imagine what Pamtv.com will pitch. Red Herring
Chairman Tony Perkins said Pam is the most downloaded image on the
Internet. Apparently, she wants to make some money off of all those
eyeballs _ or ``monetize traffic'' as they say in dot-com circles.
</P>
<P>
   Many other entertainers also have taken an interest in Internet
opportunities and venture capital plays. Perkins notes that
comedian Dana Carvey has invested with Ron Conway's Angel Investors
limited partnership and gave a free stand-up performance at Red
Herring's charity auction last Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion designers also are catching dot-com fever and are
outfitting high-tech execs along with Hollywood stars for free. At
Red Herring's Venture 2000 conference for hot companies and
financiers this week at Squaw Valley, Perkins proudly displayed the
label on a free shirt from German designer Hugo Boss and said he
has a free tuxedo and plenty of other duds. Apple's Steve Jobs also
reportedly gets special deals from Hugo Boss.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign that Silicon Valley is no longer nerdy is the
latest GQ magazine spread on spring fashions. It features high-tech
leaders and financiers including Steve Jurvetson of Redwood City,
Calif.'s Draper Fisher Jurvetson venture capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   HOME DEAL KILLERS: High-tech millionaires have been driving up
the price of real estate around the bay. But the sudden high-tech
downdraft has killed some recent real estate deals. Some home
buyers in Silicon Valley have reportedly walked away from deals,
losing $100,000 in deposits.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean the Bay Area real estate market is
suddenly flush with bargains. Quite the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Word at the conference was that former department store owner
Mervyn Morris (Mervyn's) recently sold his 3-acre Atherton, Calif.,
spread to wireless communications pioneer Craig McCaw for $30
million or more. And Jim Clark reportedly returned to California
from Florida, which has no state taxes, and bought a 20-acre
Woodside estate for about $53 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there's a three-way race between Jim Clark, Larry
Ellison and Bill Gates on who can build the biggest house in
computerdom,'' suggested longtime Woodside resident Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign that the high-tech business is not about to go into
the trash is that financial printers are still getting plenty of
orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still printing a lot of IPOs, secondary offerings,
merger-and-acquisition deals and private placements,'' says Bob
Boyle, sales manager for Bowne &AMP; Co.'s San Francisco office.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, he says, Bay Area business is up about 50
percent from the same period last year. There was a slight pause
for two weeks after the mid-April high-tech stock sell-off, but he
said business has rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign that more deals are on the way, Bowne plans to open a
22,000-square-foot office in Palo Alto, Calif., in July. It will
have more than 20 conference rooms where entrepreneurs, financiers,
lawyers and accountants can thrash out confidential details.
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to  &LR; entrepreneurs(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
