<SLUG> BC-HERRING-ROADKILL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MARKET DROP CHANGES VC RULES OF ENGAGEMENT  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SQUAW VALLEY, Calif. _ The venture capital landscape has changed
dramatically since the week of April 10, when the technology-heavy
Nasdaq index fell nearly 1,000 points and many dot-com companies
with only faint profit prospects lost much of their value.
</P>
<P>
   The dream of most most privately funded startups is to enjoy a
rousing reception on Wall Street when they go public. But many
recent IPOs are not only selling well below their peaks, but below
their offering prices _ especially business-to-consumer companies.
In addition, many venture capital and angel investors are seriously
reconsidering what their investments are really worth.
</P>
<P>
   What better place to gain perspective than in the crystal clear
air of the Sierra. At Red Herring's second annual venture
conference at the Resort at Squaw Creek this week, more than 700
entrepreneurs and financiers listened to presentations from the
magazine's newly anointed top 50 private companies and the 10 hot
startups to watch.
</P>
<P>
   They heard Michael Dell and Nobel laureate Shimon Peres give
keynote addresses and sat in on panels about Linux, EcoNet and
mobile commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the informal discussion centered on how funding
formulas have changed and how valuations have tumbled during the
past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the public markets are not offering huge premiums on
Internet companies, that ripples all the way up the food chain,''
said Ron Conway, founding general partner of Angel Investors LP,
which has two funds totaling $180 million and counts Dana Carvey,
Shaquille O'Neal and Henry Kissinger among its individual
investors. ``The April downdraft was sobering, and valuations are
coming down 30 to 60 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he said, a company that was figured to be worth $50
million may now only be worth $25 million, which translates into
dilution for existing shareholders. It also means the startups have
to give away a greater stake in their companies to get additional
financing.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Larry Chiang, founder and CEO of Moneyformail.com in
Palo Alto, Calif., who took a booth at the Red Herring event to
show off his online startup to potential partners and perhaps
attract $20 million in second-round financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not pure euphoria anymore,'' he said. ``You have to have
specific plans for turning a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Moneyformail has that. The company's concept is simple: paying
consumers from 20 cents to $2.50 to read targeted e-mail ads that
they have agreed to receive.
</P>
<P>
   The company already has attracted about 70 advertisers and
260,000 consumers and expects to be profitable within four months.
</P>
<P>
   But Chiang, who started a successful college credit card company
when he was 19, says he is prepared for the change in the climate.
If venture capital dries up, ``I will stick to my model and grow
slowly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He figures that with $10 million or $20 million in new funding
he can grow much more quickly and gain perhaps 12 million users in
12 months. He notes, too, that venture capital investors are useful
``for contacts and general market validation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel Weiss, CEO of a Philadelphia online music education
and instruments site called Gvox.com, said VCs ``are using the
market as a bludgeon.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, whose company is looking for $5 million to close out a
$10 million financing round, noted that in some cases investors are
demanding double the stakes in new ventures for the same amount of
money they were discussing three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ERugGallery.com, a San Carlos online bazaar for handmade
carpets, also is seeing traditional valuation models unravel. The
company, co-founded a year ago by former Barclays Global Investors
Chairman Fred Grauer, has signed up 20 rug dealers, has an
inventory of 5,000 rugs online and is looking for $12 million in
third-round financing.
</P>
<P>
   The company has a clear profit model that is making from 10
percent to 35 percent commissions on rugs sold online. But Jean
Claude Brunache, the company's senior vice president of sales,
concedes there are knotty problems, including the lack of
credibility of the rug business and the difficulties in
establishing the equivalent of a Kelly Blue Book value for carpets.
</P>
<P>
   HotLinks, another company with a booth at Red Herring's
conference, also is feeling the post-April 14 fallout. The year-old
company with early financing from CMGI Ventures has created a
portal where more than 850,000 users have already recorded and are
sharing their bookmarks and favorite online sites.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Jonathan Abrams, a Netscape veteran, has been looking
for $10 million in financing and has attracted interest. But he
says that one potential investor ``got skittish'' after the market
decline.
</P>
<P>
   One reason might be that the Mountain View company's focus is
still product development and user acquisition rather than revenue
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Startups that are most vulnerable in the current shift in
venture capital markets are the ones that have a spend, spend,
spend mentality, advertise heavily and sell products below cost to
gain market share.
</P>
<P>
   One entrepreneur smiling a lot at the conference was Mark Porat.
The chairman and co-founder of Palo Alto, Calif., startup
Perfect.com had just lined up $31 million in second-round financing
March 31 from Softbank and other investors for his
business-to-business Internet services company.
</P>
<P>
   The money was committed before the market crash. But it was not
all good news. Investors have put out word ``this could be the last
money we ever get,'' said Porat, a former Apple Computer and
General Magic manager. ``So rather than celebrate, I said, `Dive,
dive.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Perfect.com decided to cancel plans for bigger offices and
instead will squeeze two employees to a cube. Porat cut hiring
plans for the rest of this year to 43, from about 70, and plans to
trim legal and other professional services.
</P>
<P>
   The days are over for companies with $100 million-a-year capital
``burn rates'' and no clear path to profitability. Red Herring
Editor John Mecklenburg pointed to some online dog food purveyors
and eToys as endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only Santa Claus stays solvent by giving away,'' he said.
``There's going to be a lot of roadkill out there,'' said Newport
Beach, Calif., merger and acquisition specialist Glen Lindenstadt.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Comaford, managing director of Artemis Ventures in
Sausalito, Calif., agreed. ``Any new Internet business built on
advertising and building a community of one million users who don't
spend money and are not loyal is not relevant,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she also says that fear and uncertainty are keeping some
good companies from getting financed. ``Some companies with great
ideas but without marquee executives are not getting financing,''
she noted. ``And some bad companies with known CEOs are getting
funded even though they may be one-trick ponies.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from who's at the helm, many VC investors are now more
interested in so-called ``Internet enablers,'' companies that help
traditional and new companies establish a Web presence and make
real money conducting business and communicating speedily on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The ventures capital community still has billions of dollars to
invest. The irony is that they have recently raised more money than
ever before but they are suddenly not so free with the purse
strings.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, VCs fell over themselves to give away $40
million or $50 million. Entrepreneurs were in the driver's seat.
But now the balance of power has shifted and VCs are dictating
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Packard, a director of the Draper Fisher Jurvetson
venture capital firm in Redwood City, Calif., said that during the
past few years investors ``lost sight of fundamentals'' and came up
with newfangled ratios like ``20 times forward loaded revenues'' to
justify market valuations.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some of his firm's initial public offerings such as Fogdog
are selling at less than half their offering prices, and VCs not
surprisingly are cutting valuations of the new companies they are
investing in.
</P>
<P>
   He suspects that more venture capital firms might also be
tempted to buy stock in some of their companies that have fallen so
far from their peaks. But companies with good prospects and profit
potential do not seem to be having much trouble lining up big
bucks. One of these is Restaurantpro.com, a business-to-business
online marketplace for the food service industry.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco company started by restaurateur Christopher
Hemmeter last year provides free PCs and DSL service to restaurants
to order supplies online. It then gets a transaction fee from
BankAmerica Merchant Services on every credit card charge plus a
small commission from restaurant suppliers on purchases of
everything from meat and produce to kitchen equipment and flatware.
</P>
<P>
   Hemmeter said the company, which expects 55 percent pretax net
income on revenues by late next year, is having no trouble raising
$40 million in its third financing round this month.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
