<HEADLINE>
CHRB: NO STABLE-AREA INVESTIGATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD -- The state agency charged with overseeing horse
racing in California will not conduct its own investigation into
working conditions in stable areas, officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the California Horse Racing Board said they will not
conduct their own investigation into labor and health issues at the
state's nine tracks and six county fairs. The board will instead
monitor and participate in several on-going probes of conditions
that may violate state and federal law.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday a spokesman for the state Department of Industrial
Relations said his agency has launched a probe into allegations
against the tracks, which include Santa Anita in Arcadia and
Fairplex Park in Pomona.
</P>
<P>
   A special gathering of three state Assembly committees will be
convened next week to address many of the concerns about the
conditions, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   CHRB chairman Robert Tourtelot said his organization began a
proactive program of improving backside conditions when it allowed
the sale of Golden Gate Fields to Santa Anita owner Frank Stronach
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put conditions on the sale,'' Tourtelot said. ``They had to
spend $5 million improving conditions before we would approve the
sale.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
