 NETWORTH: PRAYING FOR STOCK OPTIONS  &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's Friday afternoon and Umashankar Dixit, a
Hindu priest, is praying to the wealth goddess Lakshmi to bring
success and prosperity to Avakai Information Networks, an
e-commerce startup in Sunnyvale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Avakai CEO Manjunath Kashi has set up a small, colorful shrine
in a tiny conference room at his company for the Lakshmi ``pooja''
or ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   There is a basket with 108 U.S. coins, symbolizing the 108
different names and forms of Hindu gods; a platter with coconuts,
limes and other offerings; and small silver bowls of turmeric, the
yellow-orange seasoning signifying wealth, and kumkum, the red
powder that Indians use to dot their foreheads.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony, which involves a lot of chanting and tossing of
flower petals, lasts about 45 minutes. As an honorarium, Dixit will
receive $51 and 5,000 Avakai stock options.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion of Indian-led startups around the Bay Area _ there
are at least 900 according to one estimate _ is keeping Dixit busy
these days, and he has the portfolio to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu priest has received or been promised stock or options
in 15 high-tech companies that he has blessed. Most of the
companies are still private, so a lot of the options aren't worth
anything at the moment. But some have paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Dixit says he blessed K.B. Chandrasekhar, the chairman of Exodus
Communications, and B.V. Jagadeesh, the firm's chief technology
officer, in 1994. As a thank you, he got to buy 500 Exodus shares
at the IPO price. Dixit says he sold his shares in the Santa Clara,
Calif., Web-hosting company for a $12,000 profit. He used that
money, and some other funds, to build a temple in Bangalore, India.
</P>
<P>
   There are about a dozen Hindu priests in the Bay Area, but only
a few do Lakshmi poojas at high-tech companies. Dixit, who works at
the Shiva-Vishnu Temple in Livermore, says he is considered a
``lucky hand'' because his god is Ganesha, ``a remover of
obstacles.''
</P>
<P>
   Srinivas Kudaravalli, president of Key Solutions in Santa Clara,
Calif., had Dixit bless his e-commerce company and is going to give
him some stock in a health care subsidiary he's putting together,
in addition to a $500 gift. ``His blessing will help to make us
successful,'' Kudaravalli says.
</P>
<P>
   Another Indian entrepreneur who used Dixit's services is Rao
Neelamraju, chief technology officer of Jasmine Networks, an
optical networking company in San Jose, Calif. He plans to give
Dixit some options out of his personal option pool. ``Any gods'
blessings are welcome,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Dixit's ceremonies are in keeping with Hindu practice, says Mark
Juergensmeyer, a sociology professor at the University of
California at Santa Barbara who studies Indian religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the tradition to call on gods for prosperity in life,''
he says. ``What are gods for if not to help out in times like
this?''
</P>
<P>
   Although the options are a new twist, ``in Indian culture there
is nothing wrong with priests receiving compensation or being
supported by the public.'' Some Hindu priests, he says, receive
more than others, just as they do in other religions.
</P>
<P>
   MORE ON OPTIONS: My Friday column on sunken stock options
prompted this question from a reader:
</P>
<P>
   ``I recently moved from out of state to an e-commerce startup in
the valley and am benighted about prevalent stock-option packages.
My company is seed funded, about 10 months old, and I am employee
No. 7. I wanted to find out if my options package _ 90,000 shares,
four-year vesting, one year of waiting, exercise price of 5 cents _
is in line with the market average. I probably should have
researched even harder before I joined the company, but I did not
know anybody around here and I could not find much help on the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Because this is such a common question, I called Dave Bisson, a
senior consultant with WestWard Pay Strategies, a San Francisco
firm that advises companies on compensation issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bisson says that except for the vesting schedule _ which in the
reader's case is typical _ there is no ``average'' when it comes to
option packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the stage of a company, its capital structure
and how that many change over time, and the person's position,''
Bisson says.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, options are issued at the fair market value of
the company at the time of the grant. If the options are issued
with an exercise price of 5 cents per share, the company is worth 5
cents per outstanding share. As the company grows and raises
capital, the value of the company _ and the exercise price on
future option grants _ goes up.
</P>
<P>
   Employees typically get one option grant when they join the
company. They may get an additional round of options, exerciseable
at the IPO price, just before an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   The number of shares _ 90,000 in this case _ is meaningless
without knowing how many shares are outstanding, Bisson says. What
counts is the percentage of outstanding shares an option grant
represents. And that depends as much on job responsibilities as
date of employment.
</P>
<P>
   Employee No. 7, if he or she is a vice president, could get
options representing one-10th to 1 percent of the company's
outstanding shares. An entry-level programmer would probably get
less than one-10th of 1 percent. ``As the company raises additional
equity, that percentage is likely to be diluted down,'' Bisson
says.
</P>
<P>
   Options also depend on the person's background, salary,
negotiating skills and supervisor. ``Some managers (in the same
company) hold the line on options, some give away the store,''
Bisson says. ``There is greater randomness in options than base
salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there is no good source of information on
options, other than asking people in similar positions. Companies
like Bisson's don't give advice to individuals.
</P>
<P>
   If you would like to share your option intelligence, send me an
e-mail and I'll follow up in a future column.
</P>
<P>
   CLARIFICATION: In Friday's column on repricing stock options, I
said that under new Financial Accounting Stardards Board rules,
companies will have to start taking charges and credits to earnings
each quarter to reflect differences between the new, lower exercise
price and the current market price for all unexercised options.
</P>
<P>
   I should have said that the company can take credits only to the
extent that they offset prior charges.
</P>
<P>
   For example, say a company lowers the exercise price on employee
options to $5 from $10 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Then the stock recovers, and at the end of the quarter is
trading at $13. The company will have to reduce quarterly earnings
by $8 ($13 minus $5) for all repriced options. If at the end of the
next quarter, however, the stock goes up to $10, the company would
take a $3 credit.
</P>
<P>
   Now take an alternative scenario: After the repricing the stock
falls and at the end of the quarter is at $2. The company cannot
take a credit because it never took a charge.
</P>
<P>
   Got that?
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
