 REV. JACKSON WINDING UP SILICON VISIT  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson will conclude a three-day
stay in Silicon Valley on Wednesday with a conference where many of
the valley's most powerful chief executives will talk about how
they can bridge the ``digital divide.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's visit is part of the Rainbow/PUSH Coalition Silicon
Valley Project, a group Jackson started this year to urge
technology companies to take more responsibility for including
minorities and other under-connected groups in the high-tech boom.
In the past three days, Jackson has met with venture capitalists,
minority entrepreneurs, students and labor leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Cisco Chief Executive Officer John Chambers will sit
down at an executive round table with Hewlett-Packard CEO Carly
Fiorina and the leaders of Intel, Covad and Silicon Graphics to
talk about ``inclusion and digital connections,'' according to the
event schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Other workshops will focus on bringing into the digital age East
Palo Alto, Calif., the low-income, low-tech community sandwiched
between high-flying areas such as Palo Alto and Menlo Park.
Rainbow/PUSH's Silicon Valley headquarters are in East Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America is now the battleground for the civil rights
movement, Jackson said in a conference call before arriving in
Silicon Valley. While past advances in civil rights _ the end of
slavery, the right to vote and the end of segregation _ depended on
changes in laws, the next step demands change in business, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fourth stage is access to capital, access to technology
and access to enough education,'' Jackson said. ``There's such a
tendency to (ask), what will the government do? Corporate America
must take some leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   John Thompson, CEO of Symantec, who will speak at the
conference, said that a major theme Wednesday will be connecting
Silicon Valley's intense need for skilled employees with
disadvantaged groups' need to join the successful economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to think about this is enlightened self
interest,'' Thompson said. ``It's about how do we ensure that there
is talent to fuel our ability to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at Wednesday's conference, representatives from Goldman
Sachs, Viridian Capital and other groups will discuss expanding
funding opportunities for women and minority entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Jackson met with minority entrepreneurs, including Ron
Jones of Songboy.com and Ed Nwokedi of UrbanEvents.com. Monday, he
joined with several local groups including Plugged In to distribute
25 computers with Internet access and printers to low-income youth.
Hardware was donated by Hewlett-Packard, PeoplePC and other
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also appeared at a technology job fair for San Jose,
Calif., high school students, and met with labor leaders to discuss
the Silicon Valley ``Justice for Janitors'' campaign. Silicon
Valley janitors are pushing for raises when their union contract
expires May 31.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
