<SLUG> BC-KAISER-POLICY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 KAISER TO END CONTROVERSIAL PRESCRIPTIONS  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kaiser Permanente on Tuesday ended a
controversial practice in which psychiatrists in its San Diego,
Calif., office prescribed medicines to patients they had never
personally examined.
</P>
<P>
   The practice came to light last month in a lawsuit filed by
former Kaiser psychiatrist Thomas Jensen, who was fired after he
refused to rubber-stamp prescription recommendations by the
psychologists or social workers who screened new patients.
</P>
<P>
   Without admitting any wrong or making any apologies, Dr. Oliver
Goldsmith, medical director for Kaiser Permanente in Southern
California, said all new patients will have to be seen by a
psychiatrist before medication is prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Kaiser Permanente, we go down roads from time to time we
have to come back from,'' Goldsmith said, declining any comment on
Jensen's actions ``because it's a legal matter and I have to be
careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Palefsky, the San Francisco attorney representing Jensen,
said his client felt partially vindicated by Kaiser's reversal.
``Now that his ethical concerns have been addressed, we're ready to
start talking with Kaiser about making him whole,'' Palefsky said,
adding that his client ``really has been damaged personally and
professionally'' by his exercise in medical whistle-blowing.
</P>
<P>
   Palefsky criticized Kaiser for letting the matter drag on.
Before his firing, Jensen had tried to change the prescription
practice through internal channels. Palefsky said he also
informally contacted Kaiser attorneys three times before resorting
to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   According to Goldsmith, Jensen's complaints had been reviewed by
the medical authorities in San Diego, who never brought it up to
the next level, which would have brought the practice to his
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith said no punitive action was contemplated against Dr.
Dennis Cook, the chief of psychiatry in San Diego, who enforced the
earlier prescription practice and fired Jensen when the latter
refused to go along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our doctors ought to be trying different approaches,''
Goldsmith said, adding the Cook ``sincerely thought he was right.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his lawsuit, Jensen's complaints prompted a state
investigation into the practices of the Oakland, Calif., HMO. Julie
Stewart, a spokeswoman for the Department of Corporations in
Sacramento, said her office was ``encouraged'' by Kaiser's reversal
but would continue looking into Kaiser's prescription practices.
</P>
<P>
   The state investigation was also looking into allegations that
Kaiser psychiatrists in Northern California might have been issuing
prescriptions for patients they had never personally examined.
</P>
<P>
   When the matter first arose last month, Kaiser denied that
psychiatrists outside San Diego were using the procedure which
Jensen brought to light. Goldsmith repeated those denials
yesterday, saying so far as he could determine ``it was not being
employed anywhere else in Kaiser.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
