<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Friday, May 5, 2000) 
 
By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On this date in 1904, the first ``perfect game'' was pitched in
major-league baseball. Who was the pitcher who allowed no opposing
player to reach first base? (Hint: Baseball's highest pitching
honor today is named after him.) &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Today is also International Tuba Day.
</P>
<P>
   This week's featured wine won't throw you a curve, and it's so
good you won't have to toot your own horn when you serve it to
guests; you'll have all the flavor bases covered. The 1997 Tommasi
``Rafael'' Valpolicella _ 4 1/2 stars _ is a Joe DiMaggio of a
wine: graceful, supple, and when the wine game is on the line, it's
the wining run. Better even than the 1995 model, the '97 Tommasi is
redolent with dusty plum notes and a silky texture, and is so well
balanced it can match up with white-meat dishes or a robust pasta
with noticeable garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Valpolicella is a vastly underrated varietal, probably because
there are quite a few in the market that are cheap _ and taste like
it. But when you get a good one _ pow, it's out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   About $11.99, which is less than the price of a lot of
major-league baseball game tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Denton T. ``Cy'' Young pitched the Boston Americans over
the Philadelphia Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WINE RATING: &QL; 
5 stars: Outstanding &QL; 
4 stars: Fine &QL; 
3 stars:Good &QL; 
2 stars: Fair &QL; 
1 star: Poor &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
