<HEADER>
A3961 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-REPUBS-PRMARIES-ART-1     05-03 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PRMARIES-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP PANEL PROPOSES NEW PRESIDENTIAL NOMINATING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout) (With text box, REPUBS-STATES) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A high-level Republican committee on Tuesday
proposed a new presidential nominating system intended to build
suspense and interest from March through June, with smaller states
voting first and larger states casting the decisive final votes.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was a sharp reaction to the current system in which
both party nominations were effectively decided by March 7, the
first day with several major primaries, before millions of
Americans got a chance to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Brock, former Republican Party chairman, who led the
committee that offered the plan, said, ``Too many people in too
many states have no voice in the electoral process that names our
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, the Republican national chairman, said he
expected the party to adopt the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican willingness to scrap the system seems likely to
open up a national debate, even though the Democratic Party's
reaction was to point out that the present system had elected Bill
Clinton twice and therefore ``at this point, there is little
incentive to change.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Republicans adopt the plan at the convention in August,
Democrats might be willing to discuss changing the primary process.
A crucial provision would give the Republican National Committee
the authority, which it now lacks and the Democratic National
Committee has, to alter delegate selection rules between
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   James Roosevelt, co-chairman of the Democratic Rules and By-Laws
Committee, said, ``If the Republicans can get that kind of
flexibility, then between cycles we could have some real
substantive discussions about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Potential opposition from large states is a major obstacle to
the Brock plan. So is traditional Republican reluctance to impose
national rules on state parties. Democratic opposition, if it
persists, would be another hurdle, and even if both parties agreed
on a plan, getting almost every state to change its primary or
caucus date would be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the 12 least-populous states, the District of
Columbia and the territories would be allowed to hold primaries or
caucuses no earlier than the first Tuesday in March. Another group
of 13 slightly more-populous states, from Connecticut to New
Mexico, could go on the first Tuesday in April. Thirteen
middle-size states, including Kentucky and Massachusetts, could go
on the first Tuesday in May.
</P>
<P>
   The rest, including New York, New Jersey, California, Florida
and Texas, could have primaries on the first Tuesday in June. Any
state could go later, and in the early stages, some might do so to
get a Tuesday that was less crowded. The plan makes no allowance
for early votes in Iowa and New Hampshire, but that might be
adjusted by the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   State legislatures would have to vote to adopt new primary
dates. To pressure them, the Republican National Committee would
have the power to deny state parties 50 percent to 90 percent of
their delegates.
</P>
<P>
   That degree of central control may be an issue, at the
convention if not earlier, at next week's meeting of the Republican
rules committee.
</P>
<P>
   John Deardourff, a Republican consultant whose first primary was
in 1964, said on Tuesday, ``The unwillingness to impose
Washington-based decisions and the unwillingness to accept them is
pretty strongly ingrained in Republican theology, and whether it's
the government doing it, or the party, it just doesn't sit well.''
</P>
<P>
   The first hurdle is clearly within the party.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Jones, the California secretary of state, said the plan was
``absolutely not'' in his state's best interest because it would
mean that California always came in the last group. He said the
majority of members on the Brock commission on which he served were
mistaken in their belief that because nearly half the delegates
would not be chosen before June, a contest would keep going.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who had pushed to move the California primary up to March
7, said he did not think the suggested changes would be enough to
overcome the current way of nominating a candidate, which he called
``raise a lot of money, get it over quick.'' He said he thought a
system of regional primaries, in which different regions each got
their chance to go first, would be better.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumptive Republican
presidential nominee, could play a decisive role on the plan at the
convention. But his campaign had no comment on Tuesday night,
saying Bush looked forward to studying the report.
</P>
<P>
   The report was issued on the day when North Carolina and
Indiana, the 11th and 14th most-populous states, held presidential
primaries that drew virtually no interest. Early in the campaign,
primary turnout was high, at least among Republicans, but by March
7, known as Super Tuesday, two-fifths of Republican delegates and
one-third of Democratic delegates had been picked.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Gans, head of the Committee for the Study of the American
Electorate, who cheered the Brock report as ``the best thing since
sliced bread,'' said turnout since March 7 ``has been abysmally
low, and the citizens in the states which were after Super Tuesday
have felt left out of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brock report said the plan that it recommended could ease
``many of the problems that have come to plague the current
nominating process: front-loading, compression, low voter turnout,
early media frenzy, excessive `tarmac and media ad' campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans do adopt the plan, the process of getting
legislatures to alter primary dates (and abolish winner-take-all
contests), would be simplified if some agreement was reached with
the Democrats. Republicans might not press ahead without such
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   On tuesday, Roosevelt complained that the Republican plan gave
too prominent a place to ``states with no diversity.'' Brock
acknowledged that blacks made up only 6.2 percent of the population
in the first group of states. But he said the existing system, with
pre-eminence to Iowa and New Hampshire, rewarded two
even-less-diverse states, since Iowa is 2 percent black and New
Hampshire is 0.7 percent black.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, when Democrats were establishing new rules for
choosing delegates, most legislatures went along. The bipartisan
good feelings more typical in state capitals than Washington
frequently persuaded Republicans to let the Democrats have the new
procedures they needed to stay out of trouble with their national
party. Democrats could well do the same for Republicans over the
next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Prof. Thomas Patterson, a leading researcher in the Vanishing
Voter project at Harvard, said he doubted the plan would accomplish
its goals. Patterson said he believed if one candidate won most of
the primaries in the first two months, he would be acclaimed as the
likely nominee, even if most delegates had not been selected.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Brock did not argue that the plan, if in force this year, might
have produced a different candidate. But he noted that a shortage
of money had forced several Republicans out of the contest even
before the first votes had been cast. He argued that a calendar
that began with primaries in lightly populated, relatively
inexpensive states would have let them continue longer and ``bring
their ideas'' to the process.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   John Weaver, political director for Sen. John McCain, said he
had no idea how a different calendar would have affected McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've not been reflective about that,'' Weaver said. ``We were
pleased with the calendar. Why look back?''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, the national committee's satisfaction
with the existing system reflected the position of the campaign of
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Berman, campaign manager for former Sen. Bill Bradley, said
that having both parties hold primaries at the same time would have
helped Bradley, since interest in the Democratic race evaporated
when only Republicans were voting in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
