<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3971 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS &LR;      05-03 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
CHICAGO _ Kerry Wood's long-awaited return to Wrigley Field created
a playoff-type atmosphere. That was the first sign of trouble for
the Astros.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But it wasn't the last.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros endured another troublesome night in a season of
many, falling 11-1 to the Chicago Cubs on Tuesday. Pitching and
hitting aside, the Astros looked pretty good. However, it's almost
impossible to win in the absence of both.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to analyze everything that went wrong,'' Astros
manager Larry Dierker said. ``But obviously, a lot did.''
</P>
<P>
   It all started on the mound, where Wood had just about
everything going and Astros starter Jose Lima had nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Wood is coming off reconstructive elbow surgery and
hadn't pitched in a big-league game since 1998, it would have been
safe to bet Lima would outlast him. Don't everyone rush off to the
pay window at once.
</P>
<P>
   Wood picked up where he left off from his Rookie of the Year
season of 1998, dazzling the Astros for six innings. Dierker had to
pull the plug on Lima after 4 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Although he tallied only four strikeouts _ as opposed to the
record-tying 20 he logged the last time he faced Houston at Wrigley
_ Wood held the Astros to three hits and a run in six innings. In
three starts against them lifetime, he is 2-0 with a 0.78 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' only run came on Daryle Ward's solo homer in the
sixth. Roger Cedeno's infield single in the first and Lima's
end-of-the-bat hit in the fifth were the Astros' only other hits
against Wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched a great game,'' Astros second baseman Craig Biggio
said. ``All you can do is tip your hat to him, which we seem to be
doing every time we face him. He has our number; that's for sure.
He's the same guy he was a couple of years ago, and he's just going
to get more comfortable the more times he goes out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros can only hope the same is true for Lima, who looks
nothing like the pitcher who won 37 games over the past two
seasons. As if the Astros didn't already have reason enough to
worry about Lima, the struggling righthander gave them about 10
more in Tuesday's blowout loss. The Cubs tagged Lima for 10 runs
(nine earned) on 13 hits, including three home runs, each of which
was the hitter's first.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat me,'' Lima said. ``I can't make any excuses, and I'm
not going to kill myself. They were hitting everything I threw up
there. If I threw a ball in the dirt, they hit it into the gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima's dramatic decline begs the question: After establishing
career highs with 233 innings in 1998 and 246 in 1999, is his right
arm sound?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with my arm,'' Lima insisted. ``It feels
great. That's not the problem. I just have to pitch better.''
</P>
<P>
   While his arm may be strong, Lima's ERA continues to take a
beating. It jumped to 9.59 Tuesday. Lima has allowed 23 hits and 22
runs in his last two starts (9 innings) _ both against the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old righthander also has allowed eight home runs
during the most horrible stretch of a season with few bright spots.
Lima, who has lost five consecutive starts, has allowed a
major-league-high 13 home runs in just six starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't get any worse,'' he said. ``Things have to change.
I'm really disappointed that I'm not performing better. But I'm not
going to give up on myself. I'm still only 27 years old, and I
didn't win 21 games last year by being lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've still got a lot of starts left to turn it around, and I
believe I will. No one believes in himself more than I do. It's not
how you start; it's how you finish.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros started off on the wrong foot against Wood. They had
a runner in scoring position with less than two out on two
occasions but failed to capitalize each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some scoring opportunities early,'' Dierker said. ``But
we weren't able to make them pay off. After that, things got out of
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The first three batters reached base against Lima in the second
inning, including Willie Greene, who delivered an RBI double. Joe
Girardi drove in another run with a fielder's-choice grounder, and
Wood rubbed salt into Lima's wounds with a two-run homer to left
field.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, who was 4-for-4 with four RBIs, had an RBI single in the
third and a two-run homer in the Cubs' five-run fifth inning.
Girardi also hit a two-run homer in the fifth, and Mark Grace
chimed in with an RBI double, which finally chased Lima from the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lima threw a lot of pitches up and over the plate that they
hit out of the ballpark,'' Dierker said. ``That's been a problem
for him this season, and it was again tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   And with Wood on the mound, the Astros didn't need any more
problems.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
