<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEHTINEN COULD BE BACK FOR GAME 4
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD AND JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ The day-to-day status of injured Stars winger
Jere Lehtinen's return has an actual day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a player tonight,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said
before Game 3 last night. ``But if he continues to move along,
there is a real opportunity he's a player on Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   The upbeat prognosis came after Lehtinen, who hasn't played
since reinjuring his right ankle in the Stars' season finale, had
another good day of practice. He skated with the team during the
morning skate yesterday, the fourth consecutive day he has been
able to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches are evaluating him and he's evaluating himself,''
Stars trainer Dave Surprenant said. ``He's as close as he has
been.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen played in only 17 of the Stars' 82 regular-season games
because of a fractured right ankle.  &QL; 
Sharks gripe about holding
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose Sharks are grumbling that the Stars are holding
them up in the neutral zone.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock didn't sound too surprised to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are talking about our holdups, and we're talking about
their holdups,'' Hitchcock said. ``I'm sure someone is talking to
the refs about the holdups. I'm sure someone is talking to the
supervisor about the holdups. In the end, you usually get a couple
of calls and 25 get let go. It's the same every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock figured his talks with the supervisor of officials
sounds a lot like what Sharks coach Darryl Sutter says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except his might have more Canadianisms,'' Hitchcock quipped.
 &QL; 
Not a pleasant surprise
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock said an unpleasant surprise greeted him at
practice yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed up this morning with two or three hockey players
with strep \Rthroat\S,'' Hitchcock said. Backup goalie Marty Turco
was included in that unlucky few.
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Kirk Muller has been battling the flu, but played
last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're not in, you can go to the bank \Rthey're sick\S,''
Hitchcock said. ``Some guys left early because of it and some were
sent back to the hotel. ... It's going to be a hard thing this time
of year to keep a player out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' other non-injured scratches were Jamie Pushor, Jon
Sim and Brad Lukowich.  &QL; 
Hail, Roman
</P>
<P>
   Stars rookie Roman Lyashenko celebrated his 21st birthday last
night.
</P>
<P>
   The American passage into legal drinking age was lost on the
Russian winger, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in America,'' he said.  &QL; 
Morrow ranks high
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Brenden Morrow has carried over his successful
rookie season into the playoffs. Morrow ranks third among NHL
rookies in playoff scoring with four points on two goals and two
assists. He picked up an assist on Mike Modano's game-winner in
Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Morrow is behind Jochen Hecht of St. Louis (4-6-10) and Simon
Gagne of Philadelphia (3-3-6). Morrow is also a plus-4 in the
plus-minus rating, tied for third in assists (2) and tied for
second in power-play goals (1).  &QL; 
Modano's streak
</P>
<P>
   If Mike Modano keeps this up, you can start calling him Conn
Smythe. His power-play goal at the 3:35 mark of the first period
gave him a career playoff-high seven-game scoring streak, five
goals and three assists. The goal was in typical fashion for this
series. It came off a rebound from a Brett Hull shot.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Modano had a six-game point streak (2-4-6) from the
start of the playoffs through Game 2 of the Western Conference
semifinals against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Modano is first on the team in goals (4) and first in takeaways
(11) and, with eight points, is one behind Brett Hull for the team
lead. Hull had an assist on Modano's goal..
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
