<HEADLINE>
SHARKS BACK IN FRENZY, THANKS TO STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Hit or get hit. It's all about survival for
the San Jose Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   They promised a more physical presence and more traffic in front
of Stars goalie Ed Belfour. They brought a chippier attitude to
Game 3, although through almost a period and a half it did little
to aid their ailing forecheck. It was an atypically undisciplined
Stars crew that got the Sharks' machine churning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to penetrate the neutral zone with the way
they play, so it seems we are losing the puck a lot more than we
did against St. Louis,'' Sharks center Vincent Damphousse said.
``The key is to get our forecheck going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' defense, when at full strength, didn't allow that to
happen. They remained consistently strong in moving the puck
quickly out of the defensive zone. When they do that, it
drastically limits the Sharks' ability to light up the Stars with
punishing hits the way they had bullied the Blues in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it does is it frustrates teams when they rely on their
forechecking,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``I think that's
the reason San Jose beat St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Sharks finally broke through, thanks to a slew of Stars
penalties in the second period, two of which gave the Sharks a
five-on-three power play. Mike Ricci finally was able to do what
had been the impossible _ he deflected Gary Suter's shot past
Belfour. It was the Sharks' first goal in more than seven periods
against the Stars to tie the score at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``No two ways about it, discipline wins,'' Sharks winger Dave
Lowry said. ``You can't take selfish penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   When Owen Nolan poked in a Damphousse pass with one hand late in
the second period for a 2-1 lead and the Sharks' first lead of the
series, the San Jose Arena erupted, and the Sharks' high-energy,
hard-nosed play finally seemed to be breaking out of its shell.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they are going to be more physical every game we've
played them,'' Stars winger Brenden Morrow said. ``The games have
been pretty physical, but you haven't really been able to notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Take notice.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it's going to be. Both teams know it. The Sharks
are battling for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Said Ricci: ``We've got to make sure we're doing whatever we can
within the rules to play more physical and win more battles.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
