<HEADER>
A3974 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      05-03 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFF PAYOFF COULD BE RESULT OF BARRY BENCHING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ No record is kept in the NBA of an obscure category
called ``arrows taken for team.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame, really. Without it, the professional casualty rate
among coaches would be even more ridiculous than it is. Lately, it
might have included Paul Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Brent Barry took an arrow. A flaming one, right
in the caboose.
</P>
<P>
   After most of a season of creditable play as Gary Payton's
running mate, he was removed by Westphal from the starting lineup
for reasons having nothing to do with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul had no problems with the way I was playing,'' Barry said
after practice Tuesday. ``He told me he had to make a change for
certain reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   And those were...?
</P>
<P>
   Said the Sonics coach: ``I didn't want the headline to read,
`Westphal benches Vin Baker.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the politics of team sports, there is a diplomacy that
usually prevails when a star gets his chops busted. Particularly
when the star is as sensitive as Baker. Make what you will of
Baker's will, but Westphal was desperate for some victories _ the
Sonics had lost 9 of 11 _ while getting a fire lit under Baker
without burning him up.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of making Baker the sole change, Westphal replaced
Barry and Ruben Patterson as well. It was a large gamble, because
not only were the three new starters youngsters with minuscule
playing experience, the two veterans who went down with Baker had
every right to be hacked off.
</P>
<P>
   The drama isn't over yet, but Westphal is on the verge of a
payoff. If the Sonics can win Game 4 Wednesday night against the
Jazz in KeyArena and force a deciding game Friday in Utah, the
perhaps unprecedented late-season maneuverings can be said to have
produced results.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sonics wouldn't have come nearly this far had Barry and
Patterson done the familiar pro-sports pouts that are usually
measured in megatons.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson was definitely cranky after being ill-used in the Game
2 rout in Salt Lake City. But the mood passed, and his energy was
decisive off the bench in the Game 3 victory (sports archaeologists
carbon-date the game back to the past Saturday).
</P>
<P>
   Baker and Barry returned to the starting lineup for Game 3, and
although burdened by some of the cheesiest fouls outside Wisconsin,
Barry had seven points, four assists and three blocks in 23
minutes. He also used his face to slow down one of Karl Malone's
elbows, which in some jurisdictions passes for attempted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Barry not only denied his mutilation was intentional, he denied
any emotional injury over the earlier benching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider it getting benched,'' he said. ``I was still
playing. I consider it a benching if you don't play at all. That's
a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care (about a role). If coach wants me to start, or
come off the bench, or play in a thong ... it'll be uncomfortable,
but I'll do it. It's my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Barry already has a nickname, Bones, a pass will be taken
on the opportunity to name him Thong Boy. He might, however, be
given credit for reviving the word ``teammate'' in an era when most
franchises are collections of 12 mercenaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I was brought up,'' said the son of Rick Barry,
former NBA All-Star. ``That's the way a player should think. If you
work hard enough, you'll get the opportunity. That's what Rashard
(Lewis) took advantage of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad to say the professional level has gotten to a point
where you have a guy who `refreshingly' or `willingly' takes his
licks and accepts them. If that's not the norm, it's a sad
statement for basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   The sport is full of sad statements, but this isn't one of them.
Barry not only subsumed his ego lately, he's had to do it most of
the season to run with Payton, who dominates the Sonics' show.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, Barry has emulated his predecessor, Hersey
Hawkins, who forsook a lot of shots and glory for the sake of
Payton and the team. Barry's style makes a better fit at the moment
than with rookie Shammond Williams, who nevertheless played
splendidly in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shammond arguably had the best series so far among us,''
Westphal said. ``But the change was more about familiarity with
what we've been doing all year; a comfort zone. I really wanted to
help Vin put some of his problems behind him. We went with (the
three youngsters) until it stopped working. When it did, we went
back to what's most familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``With no blame on anybody, the results weren't there. More than
anything, Brent is just a more experienced player and the team is
more used to him, and maybe that's why we're a little smoother.
Because of his size (6-7), he gives us some easier rotations
defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Left unsaid was the fact that Payton wanted Barry back. Williams
has enough of a shoot-first persuasion _ he scored 38 points in the
first two games, second to Payton's 44 _ that Payton ended up
playing a different game, with less control of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Barry made his peace with the role a while ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not asked to do too much on the court _ chip in a few
shots, hustle on defense, make some plays. Basically I'm supposed
to facilitate what Gary and, hopefully, Vin do. Anything else is a
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it frustration, but there were times this year
I was hoping to get more opportunities to use the skills I have to
further our team. It seemed like those were curtailed. At the time,
I had no problem because we were playing pretty good basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   At 28 and in his fifth season, Barry figured that on Team
Tumult, where he is about the only midcareer veteran, it was useful
to have one or two guys who aren't running along walls and
ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   ``An even keel,'' is how he described it. ``I like to think of
myself and Horace Grant in that way _ guys you can rely on. If I'm
anything like Horace, I can live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as the arrow hits him near the thong.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
