<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WIN GAME, LOSE KAPLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Rick Helling pitched terrifically, Rafael
Palmeiro returned to the lineup with a bang and the Rangers have
now actually won two games in a row for only the second time this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, a somber mood prevailed in the Rangers'
clubhouse after an 8-1 victory last night over the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays at Tropicana Field. The Rangers were unable to completely
enjoy the victory because the injury menace that has dogged them
since spring training struck again.
</P>
<P>
   This time Gabe Kapler was the victim, leaving the game in the
fifth inning with a strained hip muscle. He is scheduled to undergo
an MRI, and trainer Danny Wheat said Kapler could miss at least two
to four games until the Rangers determine how seriously he's hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't plan on missing tomorrow,'' Kapler said. ``But I don't
think I have a choice. That's somebody else's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates and assistant general manager Dan O'Brien
met after the game to discuss the club's options. If Kapler can't
play today, that leaves the Rangers with only three healthy
outfielders: Jason McDonald, Ruben Mateo and Chad Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was guessing, I'd imagine we'd probably try to have
somebody here tomorrow,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have four possibilities at Triple-A Oklahoma:
Scarborough Green, Pedro Valdes, Mike Zywica or Ruben Sierra.
O'Brien said the Rangers are still discussing the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem is that designated hitter is not an
option for Kapler. That role is reserved, at least for the time
being, for Palmeiro, who homered and had a two-run single last
night after missing two games because of a strained left hamstring.
Palmeiro is still bothered by the injury and is unable to play in
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Last night really belonged to Helling, who had to wait a full
week between starts because the Rangers had two days in the past
week. That left him stronger than normal, although his control
wasn't as sharp as it has been.
</P>
<P>
   Put it all together and it was still a dominating performance,
until he ran out of pitches in the eighth inning. He walked six and
hit a batter but only allowed one hit through 7 1/3 innings, a
sixth-inning single by Fred McGriff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt really good ... but with a week between starts, you're
not going to be as sharp,'' Helling said. ``I felt my curve ball
was the best it's been all year. I bounced some in the dirt early,
but that didn't bother me. It's easier to adjust from the dirt up
than from a hanging breaking ball down.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling, who threw 136 pitches, took a no-hitter into the sixth,
but McGriff ruined any chance of glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was still close at that point, so I was really
focused on getting outs,'' Helling said. ``The count was 0-1, and I
threw a changeup that I left up. McGriff got the bat on the ball
and hit it through the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   An eighth-inning error by third baseman Mike Lamb led to an
unearned run, keeping the Rangers from getting their first shutout
of the season. But the Rangers, despite their poor start, remain
encouraged by the performances they've been getting from their
first four starting pitchers: Helling, Kenny Rogers, Darren Oliver
and Esteban Loaiza.
</P>
<P>
   Those four have a combined earned-run average of 3.73 after 21
starts, and they've pitched at least seven innings in 11 of those
21 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind \Rstarting pitching\S is one of
our strengths,'' Oates said. ``We have the personnel here to fix
what's wrong. April wasn't pretty, but it's not like we have to
start over. We have the personnel to fix it. If we can get healthy,
with our starting pitching and if we get our bullpen fine, then
we'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just that getting healthy seems to be the elusive part of
that equation.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
