<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BLOW LEAD IN NINTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE -- The Angels have done everything they can to rid
last season from their memory, but they got a jolt of reality
Tuesday night when they were reminded of something.
</P>
<P>
   They still can't beat the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels rallied from a 5-0 deficit, took a 6-5 lead into the
ninth inning only to see the Orioles score two runs off closer Troy
Percival for a 7-6 win before 34,923 at Camden Yards. The Orioles
have beaten the Angels nine consecutive times and 14 of the past 15
going back to last season.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, it looked like the trend would continue without a fight
as the Orioles scored once in the third, twice more in both the
fourth and fifth innings to take a 5-0 lead against Angels starter
Scott Schoeneweis.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels rallied against Orioles starter Sidney Ponson.
Bengie Molina singled home two runs in the sixth, and Tim Salmon
hit a three-run homer in the seventh to tie the game at 5. Troy
Glaus hit his team-leading eighth homer later in the seventh to
give the Angels a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were 12-0 this season when leading after the seventh
inning, but that doesn't take into account Percival's struggles
against the Orioles. With Tuesday's loss, Percival is 0-4 with a
6.08 ERA in his career vs. Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   He faced five batters in the inning and didn't retire any of
them. After getting two quick strikes on Jeff Conine to start the
inning, Percival (0-2) walked him on a 3-2 pitch. Cal Ripken
followed with a double off the fence in left-center field to score
Conine to tie the game at 6.
</P>
<P>
   After an intentional walk to pinch hitter Harold Baines, Charles
Johnson singled to left to load the bases for Mike Bordick, who
began the day leading the American League with 29 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia not only brought the infield in, he
brought left fielder Darin Erstad in to play between first and
second base, moving second baseman Adam Kennedy over to the second
base bag and giving the Angels five infielders.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy didn't work because Bordick lined Percival's first
pitch to right field past Salmon for a game-winning single.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said he thought Percival might have lost his rhythm,
but Percival wasn't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I lost my rhythm, I still felt pretty good,''
he said. ``I didn't throw good pitches and they hit me. The took
some good swings off me. What can I say?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get balls down and away and every one was down
the middle. The one to Ripken was right down the middle. I've got
to make a better pitch than that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to happen,'' Scioscia said. ``In the big picture
there are going to be some blown saves.''
</P>
<P>
   But this was Percival's first blown save of the season in seven
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days are better than others,'' Percival said. ``Some days
the ball is jumping out of your hand and some days you have to
pitch a little better. Tonight I needed to pitch and I didn't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis gave up only six hits in 7 2/3 innings, but the
Orioles made them count. Of the six, Schoeneweis said only a
hanging slider to Brady Anderson was a mistake. Anderson hit the
pitch for a two-run homer and a 5-0 lead in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hung it, but I was still keeping the ball down and
getting ground balls,'' Schoeneweis said. ``If I can stay in the
game I feel I get better as the game goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels hitters got better after Ponson shut them out for
five innings, scoring twice in the sixth and four times in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been in situations when you get down, it's all over,''
Mo Vaughn said. ``That's not the situation here. We know we can
play with everybody. We just need a little luck to go with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
