<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-WOOD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOOD RETURNS WITH DOMINANT STUFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Don Baylor eagerly awaited Kerry Wood's return to the
Chicago Cubs rotation because of the tall Texan's ``John Wayne
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first major-league start since Oct. 3, 1998, Wood
provided just that.
</P>
<P>
   The Irving native and Grand Prairie High School graduate had a
night that would make any Western legend proud.
</P>
<P>
   Making a comeback from career-threatening elbow surgery, Wood
both pitched and hit his team to an 11-1 victory against the
Houston Astros last night at a sold-out Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, feeling no pain in his surgically repaired elbow, held the
Astros to one run on three hits in six innings, and hit a two-run
home run off the first pitch he saw from Houston starter Jose Lima
in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was better than scripted for me,'' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The only drawback was the fact that it was a night game. Had it
been played in the afternoon, Wood could have finished his day like
all Texas heroes, by riding off into the sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Wood had no complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good pitching,'' he said. ``I'm very pleased with that.
The home run is just a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   By almost any measure, Wood's comeback was a success. He was
able to throw 96 pitches. His fastball was clocked as high as 97
mph. He had a two-hit shutout through five innings, losing it only
when Daryle Ward hit a one-out homer in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my stuff is pretty close,'' Wood said. ``My command
has to come back as far as the breaking stuff, and I wasn't able to
put the fastball where I wanted to early, but that came around
after a couple of innings. I've still got a little work to do, but
I'm pleased with the first outing.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing lacking was a typical pre-surgery strikeout
total. This start came four days from the two-year anniversary of
the day he fanned the Astros 20 times, tying Roger Clemens'
major-league record. He whiffed only four last night, rarely
exhibiting the dominance that led to an average of 12.6 strikeouts
per nine innings and a .196 opponents' batting average when he was
a 20-year-old rookie in '98.
</P>
<P>
   That, though, could be attributed to rust and adrenaline, a
combination that prompted catcher Joe Girardi to simplify the game
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called for more fastballs than I will down the road,''
Girardi said. ``When you're too hyped up, it's harder to control
your breaking ball. I was most encouraged because I thought he got
better as the night went on. His fastball got better, his changeup
got better, his breaking pitches got better.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood was at his best in the fifth inning, when the Astros had
runners at second and third with two outs and the dangerous Jeff
Bagwell at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Wood got ahead with a 97 and a 96 mph fastball, just missed with
a 96 mph fastball, than froze Bagwell with an 84 mph slider on the
outside corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did to Bagwell, not too many people do that,'' Cubs
first baseman Mark Grace said. ``It was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   That strikeout heightened an already festive atmosphere at
Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs fans began arriving early, ready to welcome Wood back. A
few wore Cubs jerseys with Wood's name on the back. They carried
signs reading, ``Welcome Back,'' and ``Finally Kerry Has Come Back
To Wrigley.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros also seemed to be caught up in the pregame buzz.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives this game a certain electricity, and I kind of like
being part of this scene,'' manager Larry Dierker said. ``It's not
hard to figure out that something special is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood was excited even before arriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today seemed a lot longer than yesterday,'' he said. ``I woke
up at 6:30, afraid I was going to be late for the park.''
</P>
<P>
   His adrenaline flowed even faster as he went to the bullpen to
warm up, accompanied by the first of several standing ovations from
the fans.
</P>
<P>
   While Wood was excited, his teammates were nervous for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many emotions run through your mind,'' Grace said. ``You
worry about the worst-case scenario, if he hurts himself, and you
think, `Please don't happen.' Then, I didn't want him to get
shelled. I wasn't thinking about no-hitters or 20 strikeouts. I
just wanted him to pitch good, and he did.''
</P>
<P>
   John Wayne would have been proud.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
