<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT PARTNERS GET SHORT SHRIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the analyses of Microsoft's future, precious little has
been said about the company's business partners.
</P>
<P>
   Much ink has been spilled and air time given over to the
shareholders, employees, consumers and competitors, but what about
those whose business fates are inextricably linked to Microsoft?
These partnerships embrace a wide variety of enterprises, including
big personal computer makers, software firms and retailers. How
will the government's bid to break up Microsoft affect their
prospects?
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Times, one of the few business journals to pay
heed to these forgotten players of the Microsoft drama, estimates
that in America alone there are 10,000 technology partners and
115,000 retailers, smaller personal computer companies, resellers
and other peripheral businesses closely associated with Microsoft.
Globally, the Financial Times noted, the number of such firms is so
high the company doesn't bother to keep track of them.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, they have millions of employees whose economic
fortunes now ride on judicial whim and Microsoft's ability to fend
off its government foes.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction from key competitors such as Oracle and Sun
Microsystems has been muted, probably because the case has a long
way to go through the appeals process. Meantime, nobody can say for
sure how Microsoft's primary competition will fare even if
government trustbusters get everything they seek.
</P>
<P>
   For industry partners with important ties to Microsoft, however,
the future may be now as they assess how to prepare for the worst,
should government prevail. History suggests the outlook is
reasonably bright for employees and shareholders. Job security
isn't likely to be a problem regardless of how the company might be
reorganized, and past big breakups have tended to enhance
shareholder value rather than diminish it.
</P>
<P>
   However, as the Financial Times points out, the worst-case
scenario doesn't bode well for companies whose business has been
built on the dominance of Windows. The work of lifetimes will be at
risk for some key Microsoft partners.
</P>
<P>
   The government's antitrust chief, Joel Klein, indicated that the
proposed remedy would be a ``surgical strike,'' but the job of
creating two companies from one as dominant and complex as
Microsoft defies such a tidy characterization.
</P>
<P>
   The early fallout already signals how chaotic this intrusion by
government may prove in the years ahead. Much of the stock market's
tech sector swoon is probably attributable to the uncertainties
created by Washington in the Microsoft case. Moreover, as investors
begin to further ponder the implications of government's heavy hand
on industry affairs, the industry's golden age as a Wall Street
darling may become a distant memory.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever government pursues such radical actions, the means and
ends are critical considerations.
</P>
<P>
   As for means, it's most important to remember Microsoft was made
a target for legal action by its competitors, not its customers.
Polls consistently show overwhelming approval by consumers familiar
with Microsoft products.
</P>
<P>
   As for possible ends, one critic called the government's
proposed breakup remedy ``like trying to fix a traffic jam by
dropping an atom bomb.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 0048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
