<HEADLINE>
KEMPER MILITARY ACADEMY PLANS TO CLOSE NEXT WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH and LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The oldest military academy west of the
Mississippi River will close next week unless it can find $1.3
million, said an official at Kemper Military School and College in
Boonville, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to do a lot of things to pull ourselves out of
the fire,'' retired Lt. Col. Tom Challender, director of alumni
affairs, said Tuesday. ``But every parent who has paid for summer
school or fall semester will get their money back. We're going down
honorably and with integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   On a Web site, www.kemper.org, a statement posted Tuesday
attributed to school President Edward E. Ridgley said: ``...it will
be problematic, if not impossible, for the institution to meet its
financial obligations if it continues to operate after May 13.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridgley would not accept phone calls Tuesday seeking further
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The official announcement of the 156-year-old school's closure
came Monday afternoon, said Judith Delaney, dean of women. Ridgley
first told the department heads, then the faculty, then the
corpsmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids were devastated,'' Delaney said. ``It's very sad to
talk with the kids who love this place. These kids are doers.
They're on the phone, calling their parents. Calling alumni.
They're praying for a miracle. They didn't see this coming. We
hoped that it wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   There was an inkling of financial trouble late last fall when
the school, about 115 miles east of Kansas City, Mo., decided to
close its football program, which long had been a source of pride
for the school. Later, the school shut down its basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   The school began with three students in the 1840s as a boys
boarding school founded by Frederick Thomas Kemper. From the same
family came a Confederate general, an Episcopal bishop and Kansas
City financier William T. Kemper. The school later focused on
military training.
</P>
<P>
   During the prelude to World War II, the school's enrollment
expanded to more than 500 students. But after the Vietnam War, its
enrollment dropped. Women were admitted in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the Vietnam War, there were 600 military schools across
America,'' Challender said. ``By 1980, the numbers dropped to 100,
and now they're at 80. There seems to be a real anti-military
feeling we're living with right now.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the school had 338 students, a climb from a decade
earlier when it had 167 students. Last fall, the school did not
report its student enrollment to the Missouri Department of Higher
Education. But according to the Web site, there are 256 students _
79 in junior college living at the academy, 145 boarding students
in seventh through 12th grades, and 32 nonboarding junior college
students.
</P>
<P>
   The school has almost closed its doors twice before: in
mid-1970s and in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``But both times we were able to sell properties and get some
cash flow in,'' Challender said. ``We told alumni in January that
we'd hit a wall in May. Some people told us we'd probably close in
late January, but we didn't. These kids will graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Ike Skelton is to speak at Kemper's graduation
ceremony May 13. Skelton is a graduate of Wentworth Military
Academy and Junior College in Lexington, Mo. But even Skelton was
unaware of Kemper's financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did tell me it was going to close a couple of weeks ago,
but I thought they meant for the summer,'' Skelton said from his
office in Washington. ``This is surprising. We need these schools.
We need what they offer to students and the country. I'm very
saddened by this news. Very saddened.''
</P>
<P>
   Other famous Kemper Military School and College graduates
include James Stowers Jr., a Kansas City philanthropist and founder
of American Century Investments; humorist Will Rogers; actor Hugh
O'Brian; and chicken magnate Don Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hate to see this institution die, but just because it's the
bottom of the ninth with two strikes it doesn't mean we're down
yet,'' Challender said. ``We're going to fight until the game is
over. We have a lot of alumni out there who care about this school.
They may save us yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
