<HEADLINE>
LIBRARY GIVEN PILES OF WORTHLESS BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY EDYTHE JENSEN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What would happen if someone donated 15,000 books to Gilbert's
library and nearly all of them had the same title?
</P>
<P>
   Librarians are finding out the hard way this week as they sort
through a loading dock full of books that arrived as part of a
Cracker Barrel restaurants promotion. The gift includes 11,796
copies of a preschool book titled ``What Would Happen If ''.``
.''`` .'' . The rest of the gift is just as useless, including
1,000 ``Quick and Easy Pasta'' paperbacks, hundreds of outdated
textbooks and 200 copies of ``How To Use Microsoft Windows 95.''
</P>
<P>
   The Maricopa County Southeast Regional Library had agreed under
pressure in December to take the books after it was accused of
ingratitude for questioning whether the books would really be
usable.
</P>
<P>
   The library's director predicted then that it could be stuck
with thousands of ``The Grinch Who Stole Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't that far off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're disappointed,'' Maricopa County Library
Director Harry Courtright said. ``We can find a creative way of
doing something with the children's books . . . but ``Windows 95''
is of no value to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first such problem for Cracker Barrel's literacy
sweepstakes award. Promoted by country music star Faith Hill, it
gave 10 lucky winners a trip to the Country Music Awards in
Nashville, along with a donation of 10,000 children's books in
their name to a library of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   Libraries in Columbus, Ind.; and Gasden, Ala., have received
similarly worthless shipments. Gasden's librarian plans to haul
hundreds of copies of an outdated microbiology text to the local
dump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Cracker Barrel and told them, `The concept was really
great, but it didn't work out the way y'all thought it would,' ''
said librarian Becky Buckner, who suspects that the prize books are
publisher rejects used as tax write-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Cracker Barrel spokeswoman Jennifer Presley said she is as
surprised as everyone else. She said the Lebanon, Tenn.-based chain
didn't know who shipped the books or where they came from. She was
sure restaurant officials did not get a chance to review the
titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was intended to be a useful gift,'' she said. ``We are
extremely disappointed that this has created difficulties . . . and
are trying to determine what we can do to alleviate the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Presley did not say what Cracker Barrel would do, and Hill did
not return messages left with her agent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But in Gilbert, librarians are already making plans. Courtright
is hopeful that the local Friends of the Library group may be able
to sell some of the books at a fund-raiser. He said its massive
``What Would Happen If...'' collection could be distributed to
day-care centers or as prizes in summer reading programs.
</P>
<P>
   For Lillie Holmes, it wasn't supposed to end this way. The
Gilbert woman who won the contest after stopping in the Casa Grande
Cracker Barrel last year said she was promised ``new and gently
used children's books.'' She saw the new, nearly empty library as
the perfect home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of disappointed,'' Holmes said Tuesday. ``I still
think the library can make some use of the books, but my
understanding was they would send novels for children.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, Holmes complained when the library seemed less than
thrilled with her offer to donate the books.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County Library officials were concerned about the
usefulness and potential cost of processing so many books. They
became the target of public criticism when they first told Holmes
they couldn't take all of them.
</P>
<P>
   They later agreed to accept the entire shipment.
</P>
<P>
   Much of it now sits in the loading dock behind the library while
officials wait to see whether Cracker Barrel will do something
about the piles of such titles as ``Why Women Live Longer than
Men'' and ``Rotary Cutter Quilts. ''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert's library also has 1,000 copies of another book that
Cracker Barrel may find particularly useful now: ``Corporate
Comeback.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
