<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
 
SHOULDER PROBLEMS AGAIN PLAGUE DiSARCINA 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE -- Shortstop Gary DiSarcina left Tuesday's game after
five innings because of tightness in his right shoulder, the same
injury that bothered him late last season.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina made two throws in the dirt that were dug out by first
baseman Scott Spiezio, but after throwing the ball over Spiezio's
head for an error in the fifth inning, he finally admitted
something was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously something was not right in his release,'' manager
Mike Scioscia said. ``I talked to him about it (early in the game)
and he said he felt good. But later in the game he said his arm was
bugging him. He got progressively worse as the game moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said DiSarcina will not play today, but ``I don't see
it as anything long term.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina missed 14 games when on the disabled list with a
bruised left thumb and has played in only 11 of the team's 27 games
overall.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Mercker was so disappointed he wasn't named to the starting
rotation at the end of spring training, he said he didn't expect to
get another chance to start all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity was there,'' he said at the end of March.
``Now it's not there. I don't see it coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   It's coming back. Scioscia said Mercker will start Saturday's
game against the Mariners in Seattle, in place of the injured Jason
Dickson.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker was 3-0 with a 3.78 ERA in Arizona, but Scioscia chose
Scott Schoeneweis for the rotation instead. Mercker was sent to the
bullpen, where he is 0-1 with a 6.61 ERA in 10 appearances,
pitching mostly in middle- and long-relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the dept of our pitching that Merck can step in and
get a start,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   Relievers Eric Weaver and Mike Holtz joined the club Tuesday
after spending the first month of the season at Triple-A Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz gives the Angels something they haven't had all season --
a situational lefty. His ERA at Edmonton was 10.80, but Scioscia
was quick to point out Holtz gave up six runs in one-third of an
inning on a cold and windy night in Colorado Springs in his first
appearance of the season, but hasn't allowed a run since in five
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on a roll now and he meets our needs,'' Scioscia said.
``Now we do have a lefty that can come in and get a left-hander
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The last few years, Holtz has been up and down between the
majors and minors, and it reflected his confidence level. His goal
now is ``The same as always,'' he said. ``Establish my fastball in
a good location and get my breaking ball over. I know I can get
people out, it's a matter of having the confidence to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver did not allow a run in spring training but was sent down
anyway. He was coming off surgery to remove bone chips in his
elbow, and had to show he was healthy again. He did that, then
pitched well (3.52 ERA) as Edmonton's closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sucks in Triple-A,'' Weaver said. ``There's a good group of
guys and the coaching staff is great, but I hope I never see 'em
again. It was a step I had to take to get back to the big
leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels media relations department continues to scramble to
determine what records Darin Erstad broke with his torrid April.
Besides setting a club record for hits in a month (48) and setting
the major league record for hits in April, Erstad also tied the
club record for batting average in a month (.449). He now shares
the record with Rod Carew, who hit .449 in April 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS AT ORIOLES
</P>
<P>
   Time: 4:05 at Camden Yards
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: No TV; KLAC-570, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Ramon Ortiz (1-2, 5.06 ERA) will start for Anaheim
against Baltimore's Jason Johnson (0-0, 2.72). Ortiz hasn't won
since his first start of the season on April 11. The Angels hit 34
home runs to set a club record for the month of April. The old mark
of 33 was held by the 1986 team.
</P>
<P>
   -- Joe Haakenson
</P>
</TEXT>
