<HEADLINE>
SHARKS GET BOOST, WINNING GOAL FROM NOLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Sharks captain Owen Nolan put aside his
ailing shoulder or foot, or both, and was in the lineup last night
in a do-or-die situation for the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   He proved to be one of the heroes, scoring the game-winning goal
in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   After missing Game 2, Nolan resurfaced at yesterday's morning
skate, but it wasn't certain if he would play.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he plays, he plays,'' Sharks coach Darryl Sutter said.
``I'm not answering anymore Owen Nolan questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars fully prepared to play against him. Inside their
dressing room, on a board where the team posts the opposition's
tentative lines, Nolan's name was in his usual right-wing spot on
the No. 1 line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the guy's on crutches, he's out there,'' Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock said. ``You don't want to show anything. He was
leading the troops there just like he does on a regular basis, and
he looks like a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan played for the first time this series with center Vincent
Damphousse and winger Jeff Friesen.  &QL; 
Can't be shaken
</P>
<P>
   The talk around San Jose before Game 3 was if the raucous crowd
could rattle Stars goalie Ed Belfour, who recorded shutouts in
Games 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   The chant: BEL-FOUR started before the first faceoff, but coach
Darryl Sutter thought the notion was preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you can't. I said all along he is in the top three in the
league; he was probably their MVP,'' Sutter said. ``Tell me a guy
that's played like that under pressure, you're going to rattle him?
I don't think so.''  &QL; 
Speedy Marleau plays
</P>
<P>
   Coach Darryl Sutter opted for more speed in his lineup last
night. For the second consecutive game, he used 20-year-old center
Patrick Marleau. Marleau has been a bit of a head-case this year,
having found his way to Sutter's doghouse more than once.
</P>
<P>
   He finally played in Game 2 after being benched after his first
series of the second period in Game 2 against St. Louis when he was
a minus-2 in 3:31 and was beaten both times on the goals. But
Sutter wants more speed, so he again sat Ron Stern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more speed in our lineup,'' Sutter said. ``I think he
is capable of generating some offense and hopefully he can be sound
defensively.''  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Steve Shields is beginning to break his shaky reputation. He
made two game-saving stops in the second period. Richard Matvichuk
jumped out of the penalty box and received a pass. He was all alone
with only Shields to beat, but Shields blocked him low for the
save. Later, Mike Modano had a short-handed breakaway. He tried to
go five-hole, but Shields made the save to keep the Sharks alive.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks spent half of the second period on the power play,
scoring their first power-play goal and first goal of the series.
Mike Ricci redirected a Gary Suter shot from the high slot. It was
Ricci's fourth playoff goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks registered 19 shots on goal after two periods to
match their total output of Game 2. It bettered their Game 1 output
by one goal.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
