<HEADER>
A3989 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-PIGGIE-INDICTMENT-3RD     05-03 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIGGIE-INDICTMENT-3RD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS and KATIE FUNK  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring 1998: With Young and JaRon Rush firmly set on their
respective paths, Piggie focused his attentions in the spring of
1998 on Kareem Rush and Andre Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Piggie) stated that it was Williams' and Kareem Rush's year
and that he would take care of them like he took care of JaRon Rush
and Young,'' states the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer representing Williams said his client would have no
comment on the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout that spring and summer, Piggie paid Kareem Rush $300
for playing in basketball tournaments and $200 for prom at Pembroke
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   But after receiving $250 from Piggie, Williams had a change of
heart, and he and his uncle went to Grant and reported that Piggie
was paying players for basketball. Under the direction of an
investigator hired by Grant, Williams tape recorded conversations
with Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   Grant then called Piggie in late June to confront him. Piggie
vigorously denied paying players, and Grant testified on April 17
of this year that Piggie then threatened him when he revealed he
had tape recordings.
</P>
<P>
   On a tape played at his bond hearing, Piggie said, ``If people
want to start a war with me, I can guarantee you I can start a war
and do it in a way that I don't care how much money people got.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant also told Piggie he was cutting off the severance
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Piggie collected thousands of dollars in the summer of
1998. In addition to the $50,000 Nike paid Piggie in the second
year of his consulting contract, Poston made payments totaling
$26,700 to Piggie, the indictment notes.
</P>
<P>
   Also that summer, Piggie paid for JaRon Rush to travel to
Houston to meet Poston and several of his clients, including
Anfernee Hardaway of the Orlando Magic, Charles Woodson of the
Oakland Raiders, Ty Law of the New England Patriots and Robert
Horry of the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   By the fall of 1998, federal agents and prosecutors would be
reviewing the tapes made by Williams and information about Piggie
provided by Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Shoe dealings
</P>
<P>
   Unaware of the emerging probe, Piggie soon would begin a scheme
that would threaten his most valuable economic asset, the Nike
contract, the indictment alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Falsely describing himself as a Nike wholesaler, the indictment
alleges, Piggie negotiated a deal with Mark Tilford, the co-owner
of an interior design business, to sell basketball shoes to high
schools. Under the agreement, Tilford would contribute $6,000, and
Piggie would put up $7,000. They were to split equally the expected
$22,000 proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   After giving Piggie a cashiers check on Nov. 17, 1998, Tilford
waited for Piggie to deliver the shoes. He never did.
</P>
<P>
   Tilford soon learned why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myron didn't have the authority to resell Nike equipment,''
Tilford said in a court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   After making repeated unsuccessful attempts to get his money
back, Tilford threatened to report Piggie to Nike.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Piggie to arrange a meeting in late December 1998
at a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, Tilford testified, Piggie arrived with two large
associates and announced that unless Tilford signed an agreement
settling the dispute, Tilford would ``leave the restaurant
injured.''
</P>
<P>
   After a tense standoff, the restaurant owner intervened, and
Tilford left the restaurant unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Tilford testified that his phone calls to Nike prompted the
company to investigate. According to the indictment, Nike soon
canceled Piggie's contract.
1999
</P>
<P>
   Myron Piggie's life soon turned more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 18, 1998, he was arrested on a municipal charge of
carrying a concealed 9mm Smith &AMP; Wesson pistol after he was pulled
over for making an illegal U-turn.
</P>
<P>
   His arrest and subsequent guilty plea in August 1999 to the
municipal charge provides the basis for the least flexible federal
charge Piggie now faces: a single count of being a felon in
possession of a handgun, which carries a 10-year sentence upon
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   By that point, Piggie was clearly in the sights of federal
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1999, the first hints of the federal investigation
began to appear in the press, when UCLA sophomore JaRon Rush was
suspended for taking payments from Piggie and from a sports agent.
</P>
<P>
   The university sidelined Rush after he appeared before a grand
jury in Kansas City and after federal investigators visited the
school.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the NCAA suspended eight players _ including the
Rush brothers and Williams _ for taking improper benefits from
summer-league coaches or having contact with agents. The
association, facing a storm of criticism from players, coaches,
fans and commentators over its current regulations, also has
pledged to reform the ``culture'' of summer basketball with new
rules.
</P>
<P>
   No one predicts that the federal pursuit of Myron Piggie, alone,
will solve the problems that bedevil amateur basketball.
</P>
<P>
   But Vaccaro, the adidas executive, thinks that if Piggie decides
to cooperate with investigators, the entire sport could be shaken:
``In my opinion, if the guy plea bargains, he'll bring the whole
pyramid down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
