<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SIDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS TAKE EARLY LEAD, BUT CAN'T HOLD IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ The Stars knew exactly what San Jose was
going to do last night. They remember Game 3 of their first-round
series against Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   More noise than a monster truck rally. More animosity than a
Senate hearing.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose Arena was all that, but the Stars caught their break
less than two minutes into the game when the Sharks' Mike Rathje
was sent to the penalty box for an obstruction tripping call.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than 90 seconds later, Stars winger Brett Hull's
shot deflected off Sharks goalie Steve Shields' stick to Mike
Modano, who thrust the rebound past Shields for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars survived the first-period tempest but were swamped in
the second round en route to a 2-1 loss. Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said that is the problem. His players were trying to weather the
storm, when they should've dived right into the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really disagree with that 100 percent; I hate that
statement; I can't stand it as a matter of fact,'' Hitchcock said
of weathering the storm. ``That's like standing up there saying to
Mike Tyson I am going to absorb body punches for the first three
rounds and I should be OK after that. ``You are dead. That's what
happened in Edmonton; you aren't weathering anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had said they felt they could take control if they
controlled the first 10 minutes. Well, they did, but they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars scored their early goal and made it stand up
throughout the first period but faltered in the second period. The
once left-for-chum Sharks are suddenly back in a series, trailing,
2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first 10 minutes is huge,'' Stars winger Kirk Muller said.
``You can go as far as the first period. You try to be even or
better after the first. The biggest thing is to have a real solid
good road first period.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars already knew what the possible outcome could be with a
flat first 20 minutes. Remember Game 3 at Edmonton in the first
round? The Oilers outshot the Stars, 22-7, scored two goals in the
first 10 minutes and another seven minutes late for a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's first period went the Stars' way. Aside from
Modano's goal, goalie Ed Belfour and the Stars' defense deflated a
once vociferous crowd with yet another scoreless period _ No. 7 in
a row _ as Belfour stopped all 12 shots he faced. Two San Jose
power plays netted Stars winger Blake Sloan as many shots as the
Sharks had on the man-advantage: two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to put pressure on them and maybe they start taking
chances,'' Stars center Guy Carbonneau said. ``Once you get in the
playoffs every first goal is the big part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   How big? Well, they were 6-0 heading into last night when they
scored first in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, for the Stars, the formula isn't perfect.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
