<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3993 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-PIGGIE-INDICTMENT-2ND     05-03 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIGGIE-INDICTMENT-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS and KATIE FUNK  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1997: The cash for basketball increased in the spring and summer
of 1997. Now flush with a $40,000 annual salary from Grant and
travel money from Nike, Piggie took the '76ers to the best
tournaments in the country.
</P>
<P>
   From the April Boo Williams Invitational in Hampton, Va., to the
Michael Jordan Flight School in Santa Barbara, Calif., in August,
with stops in Indiana, Kansas, Georgia, Florida and the Las Vegas
Grand Finale in July, the '76ers cruised from coast to coast, with
some players collecting up to $1,000 per tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment says that in total, from March, when JaRon Rush
was allegedly given money for competing in the Missouri State High
School basketball tournament, to July 30, Piggie paid Korleone
Young, JaRon Rush, Corey Maggette, Kareem Rush and Andre Williams
$6,450.
</P>
<P>
   ``These payments were made secretly to the players who were told
by (Piggie) to keep the payments confidential,'' the indictment
notes. ``Additionally, it was part of the scheme that (Piggie)
developed cover stories for the players to explain the payments in
the event the NCAA learned of their existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Piggie's players were created equal, the indictment
suggests. At one tournament that summer, Maggette, a Duke
University prospect, collected $300, while JaRon Rush picked up
$150 and Kareem Rush $100.
</P>
<P>
   Also, ``(Piggie) accorded preferential treatment to Young, JaRon
Rush and Maggette as opposed to the remainder of the team,'' the
indictment reads. ``Specifically (Piggie) provided these players
with extra tennis shoes and clothing, and took them to more
expensive restaurants for dinner than their teammates during
out-of-town tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment quotes Piggie as saying: ``They are Division 1
(caliber players) and the other guys are nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Maggette nor his agent returned calls from The Star
seeking comment on the indictment. Maggette told The Orlando
Sentinel recently that he received no payments from Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   Piggie's interest in Young was rooted in the player's potential
earnings as a professional, the indictment alleges. An example of
the payoff that could come Piggie's way had just occurred.
</P>
<P>
   In late June 1997, Tracy McGrady, a dazzling high school senior,
jumped directly to the NBA, bypassing college. In setting up a
six-year deal with adidas, McGrady agreed to split $300,000 a year
between his high school coach and a talent scout that discovered
him in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Piggie was soon on the phone with the man who brokered McGrady's
deal.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Star, adidas' Sonny Vaccaro said he
remembered a late June 1997 phone call in which he claims Piggie
expressed interest in structuring an endorsement deal that would
provide payments to him. Piggie offered to bring Young to adidas'
upcoming premier summer basketball camp to ``make an alliance''
with Vaccaro.
</P>
<P>
   ``My answer was it's preposterous to talk about a junior in high
school at that point,'' Vaccaro said. ``I said no, there's no
need.''
</P>
<P>
   Rejected by adidas, Piggie took Young, JaRon Rush and Maggette
to Nike's invitation-only super camp, the All-American Camp in
Indianapolis. Scouts there rated Young as the camp's top power
forward, and speculation increased that Young would jump from high
school straight to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of camp, on July 10, Nike rewarded Piggie's
cultivation of basketball talent with a five-year, $50,000-a-year
consulting contract that included $15,000 a year for travel
expenses and $100,000 in Nike shoes and apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Later in July, Piggie met with Raveling and Stanley in Las Vegas
to hash out Young's financial future. Within days of the Las Vegas
meeting, Stanley had made a $20,000 payment to Piggie, the
indictment alleges.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Piggie continued to make $100-a-week payments
to JaRon Rush, the indictment says.
</P>
<P>
   In a tape recording made last year and obtained by The Star,
Rush acknowledged the payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me $100 a week...,'' he said. ``...I would go over
secretly to Myron Piggie's house so I could get money from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Other payments to JaRon Rush during the fall allegedly include
$300 for Pembroke Hill's homecoming; $200 at Halloween; $150 for a
weekend trip to the University of Kansas; and $300 at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Rush also received about $1,000 during this period.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment notes Piggie delivered some of the payments
packed in Nike shoe boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Rush has acknowledged to The Star that he received money
from Piggie, though he disputed the amount alleged in the
indictment.
Late 1997, early 1998
</P>
<P>
   In the autumn of 1997, Grant and Piggie had a falling out. An
article in The Basketball Times focused on the recruiting blizzard
surrounding Rush, and painted Grant as a University of Kansas
booster who was pushing JaRon Rush to Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   The article also detailed Piggie's felony conviction for selling
crack cocaine in the late 1980s and accused him of selling Nike
shoes that he was supposed to be giving away for free.
</P>
<P>
   Although Piggie vehemently denied the allegation, Grant had
second thoughts and told Piggie he would no longer sponsor the
'76ers. He gave him $16,100 in severance pay over the next several
months.
</P>
<P>
   Though Grant now regrets the relationship and denies strongly
that he was pushing Rush toward KU, he said recently that he agreed
to the severance arrangement because he thought Piggie needed the
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a friend, and I liked him,'' Grant said. ``I didn't
want to leave him high and dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other issues marked the fall of 1997: JaRon Rush wavered on
his announced intent to attend KU, and money began to flow again
from Stanley to Piggie after a three-month lull.
</P>
<P>
   From November 1997 through February 1998, while Rush publicly
dithered on his college choice, the payments from Stanley to Piggie
steadily poured in. Of the nine payments to Piggie, six _ totaling
$20,400 _ were made during these months, according to the
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Several came in close proximity to important moments in Rush's
decision-making process.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the recruiting whirlwind, Rush on Nov. 20 announced he
could not complete his letter of intent to Kansas because his
mother would not sign. He explained that she wanted him to consider
all his options.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 24, the indictment alleges, Stanley made a $6,000
payment to Piggie. On New Year's Eve, Stanley made another $6,000
payment.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, the indictment alleges, Piggie gave Rush
``$5,000 in cash in an envelope at (Piggie's) residence...for the
lease of a 1998 Chevrolet Blazer on the condition that Rush not
accept a basketball scholarship to the University of Kansas.''
</P>
<P>
   In early February, Stanley made yet another $6,000 payment to
Piggie, and on Feb. 23 Rush announced he would accept a basketball
scholarship from UCLA. Four days later, Stanley made a $500 payment
to Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley recently has described the payments to Piggie as loans.
Prosecutors are skeptical. ``...No loan documentation exists to
substantiate this claim,'' the indictment reads.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley made his eighth payment _ $5,000 _ to Piggie on April 1,
1998, the indictment reads. On April 8, Rush formally signed his
letter of intent to attend UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, that same day, Young announced he would bypass
college and apply for the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment notes that Stanley quickly negotiated a $500,000
endorsement contract for Young with Nike.
</P>
<P>
   But the indictment shows no provision in the contract for
payments to Piggie or to a nonprofit foundation he had created to
support his basketball program after Grant released him.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment notes that Piggie knew such payments were at
least a possibility. Piggie had met the year before at his home
with Detroit sports agent Kevin Poston to discuss such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   A month after Young's Nike deal and just three days after
Stanley made a final $4,000 payment to Piggie, Poston made a $5,000
payment to Piggie, the indictment says.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, Young dropped Stanley and signed with Poston.
</P>
<P>
   Poston's luck with Young wasn't much better.
</P>
<P>
   Young soon washed out of the NBA and now plays on a minor league
team in Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Poston did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3994 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-PIGGIE-INDICTMENT-3TA     05-03 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIGGIE-INDICTMENT-3TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDICTMENT, TESTIMONY OUTLINE EVENTS LEADING TO SUMMER COACH'S
CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS and KATIE FUNK  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In late July 1997, a summer-league coach, a
shoe company consultant and a pro sports agent met over cigars in
Las Vegas to discuss the future of one of the best high school
basketball players in the country.
</P>
<P>
   What the men were doing, according to a recent federal
indictment, was talking about how much money Wichita's Korleone
Young could make when he turned pro the next year and joined the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Young was one of the coach's stars on a team playing in the Las
Vegas Grand Finale basketball tournament, and the coach, Myron
Piggie of Kansas City, expected to receive a slice of his earnings
as a pro, the indictment says.
</P>
<P>
   Using the 40-page indictment, court records and testimony, The
Kansas City Star has reconstructed events from the spring of 1995
through January 1999 that led to 11 fraud and tax counts against
Piggie. Piggie has denied doing anything improper and has pleaded
not guilty to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   In the indictment, the culmination of a two-year federal
investigation by FBI and IRS agents, federal prosecutors identify
more than $400,000 in payments to Piggie from a sponsor, a shoe
company and two sports agents.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation also drew on months of grand jury testimony
from players, sponsors, coaches and shoe company representatives.
</P>
<P>
   In unusual detail, the charges also recite more than 130
instances in which Piggie allegedly paid money to players in return
for their basketball skills and a piece of their professional
contracts should they make it to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The money, which sometimes came in shoe boxes, also went for
proms, holiday gifts and, in one case, a sport-utility vehicle, the
indictment alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Most striking in the indictment is how the payments to the
players increased the further they progressed and the more notice
they received from college recruiters and sports agents.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the indictment provides one of the most penetrating
looks at the seeds of this season's basketball scandal, which saw
several big-time college players temporarily suspended for
accepting improper benefits before they were in college.
</P>
<P>
   If what is alleged in the indictment is true, it exposes what
many say are the most corrosive elements _ shoe company money,
free-spending sponsors, unscrupulous coaches and pro agents _
surrounding summer-league amateur basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the NCAA moved to curtail the ``unsavory influences''
of summer league basketball by sharply curtailing the ability of
coaches to recruit during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Such action was welcome news to Dan Schnell, president-elect of
the Missouri Basketball Coaches Association. ``I'm sure this has
gone on for years, but now it's gotten enormous and scary,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Las Vegas meeting was the high-water mark for Piggie.
According to the indictment, he was at the meeting because of his
cousin, Young. But also on Piggie's summer team were JaRon Rush,
Kareem Rush, Corey Maggette and Andre Williams. Observers said it
was the finest collection of high school hoopsters in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Only a couple of weeks before, as coach of the ``dream team,''
Piggie had signed a five-year consulting contract with Nike Inc.
worth $425,000.
</P>
<P>
   George Raveling, a former college basketball coach and TV game
analyst, had become friends with Piggie and also was at the meeting
to discuss Young's future. Raveling is a Nike consultant and works
in the shoe company's summer league basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Stanley, a Los Angeles sports agent, was there because
Raveling had recommended him to Piggie. With Piggie's blessing,
Stanley hoped to become Young's agent. Over the next year, the
indictment says, Stanley paid Piggie $49,400.
</P>
<P>
   Though their names appear repeatedly in the indictment, Raveling
and Stanley were not charged.
</P>
<P>
   Piggie's lawyer has declined to comment. Piggie himself is in
custody and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Raveling declined to comment for this article. In an interview
with The Star earlier this year, Raveling described his dealings
with Piggie as professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do anything with Mr. Piggie that I would regret,''
Raveling said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley in the past has denied doing anything improper. He also
declined to comment for this article.
1995 and 1996
</P>
<P>
   The indictment traces Myron Piggie's serious involvement in
summer league basketball back to 1995, two years before the Las
Vegas meeting. That's when Tom Grant, a Johnson County businessman
and chief executive officer of LabOne Inc., hired Piggie to coach a
summer league team he was sponsoring, the CMH '76ers.
</P>
<P>
   Grant had taken an interest in JaRon Rush as a child and was
paying his tuition at the Pembroke Hill School. Through his family,
Piggie also had known Rush for years.
</P>
<P>
   Grant agreed to pay Piggie a $10,000 salary and gave him $13,100
to assist at a Kansas City basketball camp.
</P>
<P>
   That summer Young and Rush, both high school sophomores, were
the key players on the '76ers. At a Los Angeles tournament, the
team came to the attention of a Nike executive.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer of 1996, with Young and Rush now high school
juniors, Nike took formal notice of the team, and the company gave
Piggie $5,000 for the '76ers' travel expenses.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Grant had bumped Piggie's coaching salary to
$37,260 a year.
</P>
<P>
   And here, the indictment says, Piggie's means of recruiting and
keeping players also changed _ he began paying them.
</P>
<P>
   That spring and summer, the indictment alleges, Piggie paid
Young $200 to $500 for each of nine tournaments he played in. When
Young broke his foot during one tournament, Piggie eased the pain
with $750.
</P>
<P>
   Total payments to Young in 1996 reached $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment alleges that Piggie made the payments ``to ensure
that Young remain loyal...and compensate (Piggie) after Young
received a professional contract.''
</P>
<P>
   With the same intention, the indictment alleges, Piggie made
$100-a-week payments to Rush from August through December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Young did not return several phone calls from The Star seeking
comment on the indictment. JaRon Rush declined to comment for this
article through his lawyer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
