A3997 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-PIGGIE-LAW-KAN &LR;      05-03 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIGGIE-LAW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL OBSERVERS SAY KEY TO CASE MAY BE GUN ALLEGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS and KATIE FUNK  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Take your eye off the ball, legal observers
say.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, the government's elaborate basketball fraud
case against former Kansas City summer league coach Myron Piggie is
an immense glittering distraction.
</P>
<P>
   The ``hammer'' in this case, as criminal defense lawyers call
it, is the gun charge.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 11 conspiracy, fraud and tax counts in the
basketball case, Piggie faces a single federal charge of being a
felon in possession of a handgun. Such charges make up about 30
percent of the most recent criminal charges filed in the U.S.
Western District of Missouri. Because the elements of the crime are
simple _ you're a felon; you got a gun; you're guilty _ it's an
almost impossible charge to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like shooting fish in a barrel,'' said Kansas City
criminal defense attorney John P. O'Connor. ``He's looking at a
mandatory 10 years in prison without parole.''
</P>
<P>
   And when combined with another case, such as the basketball
fraud counts, a felon in possession case can give federal
prosecutors a powerful advantage to encourage a plea bargain and
require subsequent cooperation in an ongoing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Only then will the intricate, and more scholarly, defense
arguments get in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Roscoe Howard, a University of Kansas criminal law professor,
said prosecutors won't be shy about applying that advantage.
Already, he noted, prosecutors have succeeded in having Piggie
denied bail. Unless a district judge overrules the magistrate who
denied bond, Piggie will remain in jail until his June trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives him a taste of his life for the next decade,''
Howard said. In that situation, ``you ask, why am I doing this?
What do I owe these people? What do I owe myself?''
</P>
<P>
   ``These people'' are other possible co-conspirators. By charging
Piggie with conspiracy, prosecutors believe other people
participated in the alleged fraud. And Piggie may have information
that could lead prosecutors to other alleged conspirators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want you to think we're done fleshing out the
conspiracy,'' U.S. Attorney Stephen L. Hill Jr. said in announcing
the charges against Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in a nutshell, is the government's theory of what
prosecutors think was illegal about Piggie's actions:
</P>
<P>
   According to the federal indictment charging Piggie with 11
counts of conspiracy, fraud and tax violations, Piggie paid money
to five summer-league players while they were still in high school.
With the exception of Korleone Young, each of the other players was
recruited and played basketball at a federally funded, member
university of the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the scholarship contract between schools and
athletes, athletes must sign a statement certifying they have not
received money or benefits because of their athletic talents.
</P>
<P>
   If athletes who received money sign the statement, and the NCAA
or the school finds out about it after the athletes have competed
in NCAA events, the school could be penalized. Schools have been
forced to forfeit games in which the inelgible athlete played.
Schools also have forfeited money received from the NCAA or funds
given by athletic conferences for participating in NCAA events.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment alleges that by paying players who intended to
accept scholarships, Piggie and unnamed conspirators defrauded
federally funded universities of their right to offer valuable
scholarships to eligible athletes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0037 </DOCNO>
