<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANNETT-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANNETT CO. NAMES NEW CHIEF EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Gannett Co., the nation's largest newspaper publisher, said
on Tuesday that John J. Curley would step down as chief executive
in June, and named Douglas H. McCorkindale, who has been the
company's president since 1997, as his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Curley, who is 61, will remain chairman until he retires next
year. At that time McCorkindale, who is 60, will assume the
chairman's title.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are longtime Gannett executives. Curley joined the
company in 1969; McCorkindale, two years after that. Since the men
are nearly the same age, Wall Street analysts said Curley's
decision to step down represented the start of a transition to the
next generation of leadership at Gannett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little surprised at the timing, but when you think about
it, it probably makes some sense,'' said Douglas M. Arthur, an
analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curley and McCorkindale are so dominant that investors have
not been thinking about who the next generation of leaders will be.
With Curley retiring soon, McCorkindale gets his day in the sun.
And it gives younger players a chance to step up.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur and others identified Tom Curley, publisher and president
of Gannett's USA Today, and Gary Watson, who heads the company's
newspaper division, as likely candidates for the top jobs in the
post-McCorkindale era.
</P>
<P>
   ``For both to leave in one fell swoop would have been too
disruptive,'' said Kevin Gruneich, an analyst at Bear, Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have now is a transition that is ongoing. Over the
next couple of years you will see other executives groomed for the
top jobs. When McCorkindale decides to leave will depend a bit on
how comfortable he is that the next generation of management is
ready to run the shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Curley, 51, is the younger brother of the outgoing chief
executive. Watson is 54.
</P>
<P>
   Curley announced his decision to step down at the company's
annual meeting. He was named chief executive in 1986 and has been
chairman and chief executive since April 1989.
</P>
<P>
   He gave no reason for his decision to step down. But in a
statement he said he intended ``to do what I want to do when I want
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCorkindale was named president in September 1997. A lawyer, he
joined Gannett as general counsel and secretary. He was named chief
financial officer in 1984, chief administrative officer in 1986 and
vice chairman in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time in Gannett's history that an executive with
no newsroom experience has been selected as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Curley, who succeeded Allen H. Neuharth, joined Gannett as an
editor in Rochester after working for The Associated Press in New
York and New Jersey and for newspapers in Pennsylvania and New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug McCorkindale and I have worked together for almost 30
years,'' Curley said in his statement. ``I am extremely confident
Gannett will continue to prosper under his leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Curley picked a good time to leave because Gannett
is flourishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is in great shape,'' said Lauren Rich Fine, an
analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``USA Today has been gushing with
double-digit top-line growth, the newspaper group excluding USA
Today has been generating advertising revenue growth with some of
the highest margins in the industry, and their broadcasting
operations are in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tuesday was not one of Gannett's best days on Wall
Street. In a tough day for newspaper stocks, Gannett's stock closed
at $62.5625, down $1.1875.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
