<HEADLINE>
WAKE UP AND SMELL A HORSE TRADE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Memo to whoever supplies coffee to the Examiner's
top brass: No more decaf!
<P>
   Examiner Editor and Publisher Tim White testified Monday that he
offered to do a little ``horse trading'' with Mayor Willie Brown
last August _ the Examiner's editorial support for Brown in return
for Willie's help in greasing the sale of The Chronicle to the
Hearst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it sounds ghastly, but White later explained that he
didn't really offer to sell his newspaper's soul. It just came out
wrong in court because: ``I was tired and confused by the
question.''
</P>
<P>
   White must have been tired and confused after that lunch, too,
when he fired off an e-mail to his boss outlining the horse trade.
</P>
<P>
   And the Hearst bosses must have been tired and confused when
they didn't respond to that e-mail by doing what they did Tuesday _
suspending White (replacing him with George Irish, president of
Hearst Newspapers).
</P>
<P>
   It was the right move, if eight months late. Maybe the coffee
just kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   Examiner Executive Editor Phil Bronstein was at that power
lunch, and since Bronstein has always stood for honest journalism,
we'll assume he was either tired and confused, or was busy feeding
quarters to the jukebox when the horse deal came up.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Phil would have given White a subtle sign, like a
right cross to the jaw.
</P>
<P>
   ZIPPER ACCIDENTS. That could be one of many unfortunate
consequences of the new trend in wireless e-mail devices such as
the BlackBerry.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported that these handheld e-mail
gizmos are the big thing. One man e-mailed relatives while his wife
was giving birth. In the men's room of a restaurant, one man was
punching his BlackBerry while standing at the urinal.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Moose fights the good anti-cell fight at his North Beach
restaurant, but he fears the BlackBerry. ``I don't think we can
station monitors at the urinals,'' Ed sighs.
</P>
<P>
   NO, WINE FANS do not call themselves cork sniffers.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an official name for people who really really enjoy
wine.
</P>
<P>
   Care to guess? Is it grape nuts? Vino weenies?
</P>
<P>
   According to Andrew Fulton and Chuck Victory, the affectionate
term is: Cork dorks.
</P>
<P>
   BARRY BONDS' home-run trot is so slow that if you're in the back
of the beer line when Barry bombs one, by the time he toe-taps home
plate, you've got your brewski.
</P>
<P>
   That's style.
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting that Barry was the first guy to hit a ball into
the Bay Monday night. And it's not like Bonds was forcing the
issue. Two days earlier, he gave the Giants their first win in the
new ball yard by hitting a homer to left-center.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the suggestion has been popping up that the Giants
trade Barry. But if you're charging arms and legs for beers and hot
dogs, you better give the fans a Barry Bonds kinda guy.
</P>
<P>
   The man's so cool he's even got his own navy, that scraggly
fleet of vessels that lurks in McCovey Cove every game, waiting for
homers. Barry's Boats.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN MAIL: California's branch of the U.S. Postal Service will
soon be buying electricity for 1,103 post offices from San Jose's
Go-Green.com. The juice comes from 100 percent renewable sources,
like wind and sun.
</P>
<P>
   And 500 all-electric postal putt-putts are on order.
</P>
<P>
   If only the post office could develop a steam vehicle powered by
burning junk mail.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S TEEMING with giant flying cockroaches, is the San Francisco
Conservatory of Flowers in Golden Gate Park.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of using a pesticide, a team of hungry gecko lizards
has been unleashed to snack on the roaches.
</P>
<P>
   Great idea, except: ``Somebody is not reading their history,''
says Paul Jaqua. ``Some 25 years ago, the New York Housing
Authority got the same idea. One catch: Rats love geckos,
dinnerwise.''
</P>
<P>
   So pretty soon, the flower people are going to need an army of
cats to control the rats, then wolves to thin the herd of cats,
then ... Eventually we'll have to bring back the dinosaur. Them
roaches are pesky.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD FOR the new millennium:
</P>
<P>
   Ken Holford checked the expiration date on his Swanson Hungry
Man frozen dinner: May 01 02070.
</P>
<P>
   Which means that not only is the Boneless Pork Rib Shaped Patty
good for 70 more years, but with a five-digit year stamped on the
box, it also looks like Swanson is developing a TV dinner that will
be good well into year 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   BRING BACK the good old words.
</P>
<P>
   Like  &UR; kine.  &LR; A recent column about an artist whose paintings
were nixed by a hotel because they showed cows in ``provocative''
poses, was headlined, ``Art is fine, but not the sexy kine.''
</P>
<P>
   I had to look it up. Kine is the archaic plural of cow.
</P>
<P>
   On the radio someone used the word  &UR; ganch.  &LR; It means to execute
or kill by impaling on stakes or hooks. George W. Bush hasn't said
whether or not he supports ganching.
</P>
<P>
   These are good words to know, and to use if you want to turn a
readable column into crinkum-crankum _ ``something full of twists
and turns, or a thing fancifully or excessively intricate or
elaborate.''
</P>
<P>
   SAUNTERING in the Big Apple, Noel Hartzell overheard a
conversation between a male model and a ballerina.
</P>
<P>
   The model was saying he had been jilted by his boyfriend, but
was coping, with the help of an antidepressant. His doctor
prescribed the pills because, ``You know, therapy is a major time
commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   The ballerina nodded sympathetically.
</P>
</TEXT>
