<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LATINO VOTE ON AGENDA AS BUSH RETURNS TO STATE  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush will arrive in
California Wednesday for a flurry of fund raising and political
campaigning intended to stress education and outreach to Latino
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's visit marks his second to the state in the weeks since
the March 7 primary, and his supporters say the trip indicates that
the Republican presidential hopeful will wrestle with Vice
President Al Gore for support of the nation's most populous state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race in California is a race we can win,'' said Gerry
Parsky, who co-chairs the Bush campaign in California. Parsky said
Republicans are buoyed by Bush's commitment to return to California
frequently, to raise money for the state GOP and to continue to
push for the critical Latino voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Bush arrives in Palm Springs this afternoon for a private
fund-raiser for the Republican National Committee and the
California Republican Party at the estate of Walter Annenberg.
</P>
<P>
   He will travel to Orange County, where he will mark National
Prayer Day by attending a morning Catholic Mass at Mission San Juan
Capistrano Thursday. Later, he is expected to attend an event at a
Mission Viejo charter school to stress education, another lead
issue in California.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has scheduled another fund raiser tomorrow at the Los
Angeles home of investment banker Brad Freeman, who heads Bush's
state finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the governor will be in San Diego to mark Cinco de
Mayo by attending a breakfast where he'll push for Latino votes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's California trip comes on the heels of a new Field Poll
that indicates that virtually all the growth in the state voter
rolls in the past last  &LR; decade _ 1 million new voters _ is Latino,
and that Democrats will largely benefit from the change.
</P>
<P>
   But both the governor's national and California campaign staffs
say the repeated emphasis on attracting Latino voters in the state
_ a theme in all his recent California state  &LR; visits _ will
continue through November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not conceding any vote to the Democrats,'' Mindy Tucker,
spokeswoman for Bush's campaign, said Tuesday. ``Governor Bush was
able to earn the vote of 49 percent of the (Latino) vote here in
Texas ... and we feel confidence he will continue to earn the vote
(in California).''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Goodman, a Bush supporter and Republican consultant in
Sacramento, said Bush has taken ``a unique Republican approach'' to
winning the Latino vote in California, where he has chosen to make
major policy addresses on issues such as like  &LR; education to Latino
groups in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to great lengths to say, `Welcome to my house'
because he believes they are a dynamic (voter) group,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats supporting Gore say Bush's campaign efforts in
California are little more than window dressing because, they
argue, on issues such as abortion, guns and the environment, he
can't win in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even surgery can't take the Proposition 187 tattoo off Bush's
head,'' said Bob Mulholland, the Democratic campaign adviser. He
said the Republican Party's support of the controversial
anti-illegal immigration measure, which alienated many Latinos,
will continue to haunt Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president, talking about crime, health care and
protecting Social Security, is communicating powerful messages to
the people,'' said Mulholland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
