<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ROGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIM ROGERS, 84, RANCHER AND SON OF THE HUMORIST WILL ROGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Rogers, a horse and cattle rancher who was the last
surviving child of the cowboy humorist Will Rogers, died on Friday
at his home in Bakersfield, Calif. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was also a consultant to three memorials to his father:
the Will Rogers Memorial Museum in Claremore, Okla.; the ranch
where his father was born, near Oologah, Okla.; and the Will Rogers
State Historic Park in Pacific Palisades, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   As a child the younger Rogers performed in three of his father's
films. He also appeared in three Hopalong Cassidy westerns, made
Army training films and was in three cowboy comedy movies produced
by Hal Roach Jr.
</P>
<P>
   For a time he ran the family-owned newspaper, The Beverly Hills
Citizen, with his brother Will Rogers Jr., and he was a skilled
polo player.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in New York, the third son and last child of Will
Rogers and his wife, Betty. The family moved in 1919 to Southern
California, where Jim Rogers attended Pomona College. He left
school in 1935 after his father and Wiley Post were killed in a
plane crash in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   His brother Will Rogers Jr. died in 1993; his sister, Mary, died
in 1989; and his brother Fred died in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was married for 50 years to Astrea Kemmler Rogers, who
died in 1987. He is survived by his second wife, Judith Braun; two
sons, James Kemmler Rogers of Nashville and Charles Edward Rogers
of Cave Creek, Ariz.; a daughter, Astrea Elizabeth Rogers Brandon
of Chowchilla, Calif.; six grandchildren; and 11
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
