r n BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-SFCHRO     05-03 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE BUDGET SURPLUS NOW BETWEEN $11 AND $13 BILLION
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SACRAMENTO _ State budget writers learned Tuesday that they
will have a windfall of between $11 billion and $13 billion to
spend in the next budget year _ nearly double the amount expected
last week.
<P>
   But as the Senate prepares to approve a nearly $90 billion
spending plan Thursday instead of making the job easier the record
``surplus'' could spell friction between the more tight-fisted Gov.
Gray Davis and his more liberal fellow Democrats who control both
houses of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats give cities and counties $1.5 billion for
housing transportation and general expenses. Davis offers $200
million, all in grants to law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate budget also gives public schools $1 billion more than
Davis although the Democratic governor has promised schools more
money.
</P>
<P>
   Davis proposed $20 million to continue a pilot mental health
program for a full year. Senate Democrats pour $200 million into a
variety of mental health efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be asking a lot but there should be sufficient funding
to do the things on the governor's agenda and on ours,'' said Sen.
Hilda Solis, D-Los Angeles, who coordinated the Senate's work on
health and welfare programs. ``We're giving major relief to
constituencies that have not seen any kind of relief in the last 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   As reported last week in The Chronicle, tax revenue has been so
strong this year, the state has already taken in nearly $5 billion
more than expected in just the first months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative Analyst Elizabeth Hill told the Senate budget
committee Tuesday that the state will take in between $5.5 billion
and $6 billion by June 30, the end of the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Because the state already has a budget for this fiscal year, the
$5 billion won't be spent until the next fiscal year, which Begins
July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the higher-than-anticipated cash comes from more
Californians having jobs and more of them moving into higher income
brackets, a trend that will lead to at least another $5.5 billion
in additional revenues during the next fiscal year, Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   That could climb to $7 billion if the amount of capital gains
increase by 10 percent, which they have in recent years, Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen anything like this since the 1970s,'' said
Hill in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' Department of Finance agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's premature for us to make an official forecast but if
revenues continue the way they have we are going to be in that
ballpark,'' said Sandy Harrison, a spokesman for the department.
</P>
<P>
   The fight between Davis and lawmakers will be how to spend the
money. The Decmorats who control the Legislature believe much of
the new money should be spent to expand health and welfare programs
which saw reductions or little growth during the eight years of
Pete Wilson, Davis' GOP predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Solis said her health and welfare budget subcommittee spent $800
million more in those areas than Davis proposed in his January
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has yet to agree to those spending increases and, looking
his budget record last year, may never do so.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year in office Davis has been more inclined to
earmark money for one-time expenditures, like transit or public
works projects, than expand the state's ongoing financial stake in
social programs.
</P>
<P>
   He also socked away more than $2.4 billion in a reserve account
for emergencies and another $500 million in an account to pay off
any pending lawsuits the state loses.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic governor has, however, already said how he would
spend some of the new money rolling into state coffers.
</P>
<P>
   A $5 billion transportation plan he unveiled in April will cost
$1.2 billion next year.
</P>
<P>
   A cut in state park day-use and camping fees costs another $30
million. He also agreed to an expansion of the state's Cal Grant
college scholarship program sought by lawmakers at a cost of $40
million.
</P>
<P>
   He has also promised to give public schools more money generally
and more money that can't spent on district priorities as opposed
to programs imposed on schools by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has said education is his first, second and third
spending priorities and I'm confident this budget is going to
reflect that,'' said Sen. Jack O'Connell, D-San Luis Obispo, chair
of the Senate's education budget subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Like Solis, O'Connell spent more on public schools than Davis
proposed in January, including $1 billion schools can spend as they
wish and $175 million to increase starting teacher salaries above
the state average of $32,500.
</P>
<P>
   Davis will outline his new spending priorities on May 15, when
he revises the budget he proposed in January with the new revenue
figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
