<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOLAN, SHIELDS END SWEEP TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Talk about a sudden reversal of substance,
form and poise. After one period here last night, the Stars
appeared to be showing their Stanley Cup savvy to the wide-eyed San
Jose Sharks. The series looked sweepable. Who would be next?
Avalanche or Red Wings?
</P>
<P>
   After two periods, all of the above was null and void.
</P>
<P>
   And after 60 minutes, well, buckle up and buckle down. There
will be a Game 5 back at Reunion Arena, and if last night was any
indication of where this series is headed, be prepared for
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in playoff hockey beats grit, unless it's goaltending.
Over the final two periods of Game 3, and particularly the middle
20 minutes, the Sharks welcomed back Owen Nolan, and with him came
the grit. And then, out of nowhere, there was Steve Shields, who
became the best goalie on the ice in this one. No way that's
supposed to happen, right, Eddie?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Mr. Belfour wasn't so bad himself. It's just that for
the final 40 minutes last night, he wasn't Shields. In the end,
that's why the Sharks are breathing fire again after a 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars can blame several items for what happened in the
second period, when both San Jose goals were scored. They can also
give an Oscar to Shields for an acting job that drew a critical
goalie-interference call on Blake Sloan, setting up a 5-on-3 power
play.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, the Stars can blame themselves. Taking the
smart penalties is one thing, particularly with the best kill unit
in the NHL. But eight penalties in the second period? It was
overkill and it changed the course of a game the Stars totally
controlled in what was supposed to be the telltale first period.
</P>
<P>
   That Sloan penalty on Shields was questionable to say the least,
but the referees were leaning on their whistles at that point, and
the 5-on-3 allowed the Sharks to finally break the Belfour shutout
spell. Mike Ricci delivered from the point on the two-man advantage
at 5:42 of the second.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a beauty from Nolan, who was not supposed to play
after missing Game 2 with a variety of injuries. But he's the guy
who sets both the physical and scoring tone for the Sharks, and
this was the game of the season for San Jose. Nolan played, and
scored what turned out to be the game-winner on a sliding tip of
the puck past Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Shields, however, made the win happen. Gifted with a lead, he
wouldn't budge. Late in the second period, Shields stuffed Mike
Modano on a short-handed breakaway when Modano tried to go
five-hole. Minutes earlier, Richard Matvichuk had also found
himself on a breakaway after leaving the penalty box. Again,
Shields answered.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were all over Shields in the third period. But there
was nothing. Speaking of a scoring slump _ the Stars have two goals
in the past two games. And Shields is supposed to be beatable. Ask
anybody except St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The series lead is still 2-1 for Dallas, but a shaky 2-1 after
last night, and after Shields' work for two consecutive games.
Friday night will be interesting here in the Shark Tank.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny, but the first period last night was about
expectations becoming reality.
</P>
<P>
   The easy guess said San Jose would open the game desperate and
daring, fueled by a 2-0 series deficit and an on-edge, supportive
crowd that piled into San Jose Arena refusing to believe the Stars'
dominance could stretch across two time zones.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there is the constant ``Bell-Four Thing,''
which is something about Eddie once making this city feel inferior,
the same as neighboring San Francisco has always done. San Jose
civic pride is at stake _ these people must try to rattle Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   So the Sharks started Game 3 with their best push of the series.
They put 12 shots on Belfour in the first 20 minutes, which was
massive improvement for a team with 37 shots total in two games.
But when all the fire and fury had cleared, San Jose had been
outplayed, out-skilled and remained on the outside looking in when
it came to putting the first dent in Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Modano blistered home a power-play goal just 3/12 minutes
into the game, and the crowd suddenly became docile, as did the
Sharks. One thing about Shields _ he gives up a rebound or two or
ten. On the Modano goal, Shields stopped a Brett Hull shot from a
severe angle, but the puck went off his stick into the slot. Modano
was waiting.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, it was 20 minutes of perfection for the
Stars. Man, did the evening start off right, or what? Except the
first period didn't start to tell the story of Game 3. In fact, a
big change was coming. Nolan made that change happen. And so
certainly did Shields by doing a ``Bell-four'' impersonation that
on this evening was better than the original.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
