u s BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT     05-03 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DEFEAT INDIANS, 4-2 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ There was heavy editing to the first lineup card
posted by the Yankees' hitting coach, Chris Chambliss, on Tuesday
night. It was covered with black blotches, the names and
accompanying positions obliterated and then revised.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch was out with a sprained wrist, and the new
leadoff hitter had a batting average of .170 _ but Ricky Ledee hit
a home run, his first of the season. The new second baseman, Wilson
Delgado, ripped a two-run double. The catcher, Chris Turner, played
in his first game for the Yankees, hit an important double and
guided Andy Pettitte through most of the 4-2 victory against
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't seem to matter who plays for the Yankees these days.
They are getting strong starting pitching and strong relief and
scraping together enough offense, and their 17-8 record is the
American League's best. The Yankees have won 23 of 32
regular-season games in Jacobs Field, this victory coming with a
makeshift lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was scratched from the starting lineup because of his
sprained left wrist, and unless he feels markedly better Friday, he
will probably be placed on the 15-day disabled list. Delgado
started at second base, in the 67th game of his major league
career. He is not hard to miss when the Yankees take batting
practice. Delgado is generously listed at 5 feet 11 inches and 165
pounds _ he is probably shorter and lighter _ and he tends to dump
a lot of balls over the infield, rather than launching rockets over
the fences. When asked about Delgado's offensive potential, Manager
Joe Torre replied, ``Well, he's a good defensive player.''
</P>
<P>
   Delgado does not have the experience of the man he is
essentially replacing, Luis Sojo. The Yankees don't have someone
like Darryl Strawberry on their bench, the big left-handed slugger
who frightens opposing managers; Lance Johnson hits singles and
steals bases.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Homer Bush came off the Yankee bench with his
awesome speed and he stole a few bases and won a few games. Now
there is Clay Bellinger, whose strength is versatility. Joe Girardi
was once the Yankees' backup catcher, and now the backups are Jim
Leyritz and Turner.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Yankee bench doesn't seem as deep or as strong, it
is contributing in meaningful ways. Leyritz is hitting .125, but on
April 16, his home run in the seventh inning snapped a 4-4 tie with
the Kansas City Royals. Three days later, Johnson started and
spurred the offense with four hits and two steals against the Texas
Rangers. When the Rangers tied the game in the ninth inning that
day, Bellinger slammed a game-winning home run in the 10th inning.
Even Alfonso Soriano slugged an important home run in his otherwise
turbulent and temporary tenure as third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado and Turner stepped in on Tuesday night, with Ledee
moving to the leadoff spot. The Yankees led by 1-0 after Bernie
Williams hit a solo home run in the fourth inning. Scott Brosius
singled to open the fifth, and Turner _ who found himself nervous
all day, ``feeling butterflies'' before his first start with the
Yankees _ hammered a double against the center-field fence. Brosius
stopped at third.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado was next. He learned just before batting practice that
he would play, and he didn't know anything about Knoblauch's injury
until reporters told him after the game. But what Delgado did know,
as he batted in the fifth inning, was that Cleveland's Bobby Witt
would challenge him with fastballs. ``They wanted me to show what I
can do,'' Delgado said after the game, before pausing, then adding.
``But I can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Delgado lined a ball between the outfielders in right and
center, the ball rolling and rolling, Brosius and Turner scoring.
Delgado stood at second with two RBI _ matching Knoblauch's total
for the first month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Turner had never worked with Pettitte in spring training, only
watching him from afar. They sat together in the dugout during
Monday's game, discussing how they might try to pitch against the
Cleveland hitters, something the American League has done with
great success this year. Coming into Tuesday night's game, the
Indians had scored only 121 runs, third fewest in the league, ahead
of the Detroit Tigers (84 runs) and, amazingly, the first-place
Yankees (114).
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte retired the first 12 batters he faced, nine of those on
groundball outs, and no Cleveland batter hit the ball out of the
infield in the first four innings. Manny Ramirez opened the fifth
with a single and Pettitte wavered, walking home a run.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte recovered, and in the seventh, Ledee lifted a home
run deep into the right-field stands; he muted his smile until he
returned to the dugout, and then, Torre said, ``He was cheesing
from ear to ear.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelson took over in the seventh and pitched two innings,
Mariano Rivera overcame an error and an unearned run in the ninth,
whiffing Enrique Wilson to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen has an earned run average of 1.31 over its last 11
games. The starters have an ERA of 1.67 in the last turn through
the rotation. The names in the lineup can be obliterated, blacked
out, changed and switched, but so long as the Yankees get that kind
of pitching, there won't be any revisionism in the American
League. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
