<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS PUSH LAKERS TO GAME 5
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO - If one playoff loss put an unsightly scuff on the
Lakers' glimmering aura as presumed champions-in-the-making, the
second loss ripped the shine right off.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they can't even be presumed as victors of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento Kings made that point emphatically Tuesday night,
sending the heavily favored Lakers to a stunning 101-88 Game 4 loss
at Arco Arena, tying this best-of-five series at two games each.
</P>
<P>
   The doubts about the Lakers rose exponentially with a second
straight defeat.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 3, they merely coughed up the game in the fourth
quarter. This time, they couldn't even forge a lead, trailing from
buzzer to buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a long time, they couldn't even muster a
decent run, or much of an offense at all, shooting 37.9 percent
from the field. In an odd role reversal, it was the Kings who won
with defense, and with higher-percentage shooting (43.9).
</P>
<P>
   Chris Webber, still uncontainable, led the Kings' charge with 23
points, 12 rebounds and eight assists. Six Kings scored in double
figures, with 41 points coming from the bench. Onetime Laker Jon
Barry led the bench scoring with 17 points. The hot-shooting Kings
hit 9 of 21 attempts from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant had another huge night, with 32 points, and
Shaquille O'Neal bounced back from his Game 3 performance with 25
points and 16 rebounds. But O'Neal had another rough night at the
line, making 5 of 12 foul shots.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Lakers got no help from their role players, and
the reserves supplied just eight points.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers never got closer than six points in the fourth
quarter, having lost control long ago, trailing by double digits
for most of the first three quarters. And it was a tense first
three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Webber and Glen Rice each drew flagrant fouls in the second
quarter. By the third, Bryant and Vlade Divac were mixing it up,
earning a double-technical foul for a post-whistle scuffle under
the Lakers basket.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kings were inspired out of the gate, it might have been
more than just a product of their emotional Game 3 victory and
another insanely amped home crowd; the Kings were also irritated by
the Lakers' comments that they had given away the game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Phil Jackson seemed amused by the Kings' anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been trying everything over there, you know, from
attacking officials to everything else,'' he said before tipoff.
``But how many minutes did we lead that ballgame, probably 40
minutes? ... They just climbed over the mountain at the end and
went by us. From that standpoint, when you lead for 40 minutes of a
48-minute game, the basic conclusion is that you probably gave the
game away, because you had the momentum, you had the lead, you
didn't extend it, didn't get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yes, they're a good basketball team, we're not taking
anything away from them. But we have trailed them in a lot of games
for three quarters and had to come back in the fourth quarter with
our energy and beat them. In fact, two games I can remember quite
well we had to do that. So we know what it's like to play form
behind against this basketball club and when we play from the other
side, we feel like we just didn't do the right thing. We had all
the opportunities and didn't carry it out.''
</P>
<P>
   That description also was appropriate for most of Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long before signs of another possible upset
became apparent. Jackson's body language told the story.
</P>
<P>
   After the Kings grabbed an early 7-2 lead, Jackson - who rarely
rises from his courtside seat - stood up, arms folded. And he
stood. And stood.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficially, Jackson logged a season high for upright minutes
in the first quarter. Not that it helped, as the Lakers fell to an
11-point deficit and eventually were outscored 27-18 in the opening
period.
</P>
<P>
   Having just posted their lowest quarter of the playoffs, the
Lakers showed signs of life in the second quarter, using a 10-3 run
to pull within three points, 36-33. But the Kings, who never
trailed in the half, had an answer for everything.
</P>
<P>
   A flagrant foul by Glen Rice against Chris Webber fueled a
four-point Kings burst that pushed the lead back to seven points.
The Lakers pulled within three again, 46-43, only to watch Nick
Anderson hit a 3-pointer that started a 10-2 Kings run to close out
the half.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento had a 56-45 lead at the intermission, the Kings'
largest lead of the series and their first halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal started slowly once again but muscled his way to 14
points and seven rebounds in the half. Bryant had 11 points and
Rice 13. But the Lakers' poor shooting (38.6 percent), a bad
rebounding disadvantage (31-22) and a Kings 3-point barrage (6 for
14) tipped the scales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0050 </DOCNO>
