<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS CRUSH METS, 7-1 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There are a lot of unusual things about Pacific
Bell Park, the quirky yard that has played host to 10 games by the
San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   An 80-foot Coca-Cola bottle, doubling as a children's slide,
looms over left field. Next to that is a giant old-fashioned
baseball mitt. A robot named Rusty emerges from a shed in right
field now and then, waving goodbye to opposing pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, the unusual can be found on the scoreboard. The
New York Mets have seen a lot of crooked numbers on this road trip,
and the San Francisco Giants posted another in the fourth inning on
Tuesday night: 6.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' starter, Glendon Rusch, was undone by one big inning,
and the Giants defeated the Mets, 7-1. Rusch allowed six runs in
the fourth _ the third six-run inning the Mets have allowed in five
games on this trip. Four other times, an opponent has scored at
least three runs in an inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first unsuccessful start for Rusch out of four he has
made this season. He had been virtually invincible until Tuesday
night, permitting just five runs in 222/3 innings, walking just
two. He walked no Giants on Tuesday night, but five hits and a hit
batsman ruined his evening.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied, 1-1, Barry Bonds doubled to lead off the
fourth. Two singles gave the Giants a 2-1 lead, and Rusch faced
J.T. Snow. With a 2-2 count, the left-handed-hitting Snow leaned
into a curveball with his front shoulder, a hit-by-pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Mets Manager Bobby Valentine argued, suggesting Snow made no
effort to get out of the way of the pitch. Two weeks ago, the Mets
had gotten such a call, when the Cubs' Eric Young was not awarded a
hit-by-pitch after leaning his shoulder into a John Franco pitch.
But Valentine was unsuccessful this time, and the bases were
loaded.
</P>
<P>
   The next hitter, Rich Aurilia, poked a single to right field to
increase the Giants' lead to 3-1. Catcher Bobby Estalella then came
up and ripped a line drive to left that never stopped carrying
until it had barely cleared the eight-foot wall in left-center
field. Suddenly the Giants had a 7-1 lead on the grand slam, and
the Mets never got close off Livan Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Rush was lifted after six innings, having allowed seven runs on
11 hits. His record dropped to 1-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets did score off Hernandez in the first inning, but they
could have had more than one run.
</P>
<P>
   The right-field corner is only 307 feet from home plate here,
because the Giants wanted space for a public walkway between the
fence and the bay.
</P>
<P>
   But they also wanted a field that would play fairly for pitchers
and hitters. Heeding the advice of their broadcaster and former
pitcher, Mike Krukow, designers made the right-center-field gap a
distant 421 feet from the plate.
</P>
<P>
   That dimension sometimes inspires extra-base hits at the expense
of home runs, as the Mets' Robin Ventura discovered in the first
inning. Hernandez struck out the first two Mets on breaking balls,
and he got ahead of Edgardo Alfonzo. But Alfonzo walked, and
Ventura followed by slamming a pitch high off the brick wall in
right-center. It would have been a homer almost anywhere else, but
it went for a double here.
</P>
<P>
   No Mets runner got farther than second for the rest of the game.
Hernandez, who was 0-5 against the Mets last season and has gone
19-28 since winning the most valuable player award for Florida in
the 1997 World Series, beat the Mets for his first victory this
season. He worked all nine innings, allowing eight hits on three
walks and five strikeouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 0156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
