<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4024 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     05-03 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>

(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By JENNIFER FLOYD c.2000
Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ The key call of Game 3 between the Stars and
the Sharks proved to be what is or isn't goaltender interference.
</P>
<P>
   The referees thought Stars winger Blake Sloan did it. They
didn't think Sharks forward Mike Ricci did. The difference is the
biggest reason the Stars lost, 2-1, to the Sharks last night at San
Jose Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you have the opportunity to agree or disagree with the
referee,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``I didn't agree with
some of the calls. I didn't think Ricci's goal should've counted.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricci scored on a five-on-three power play at 5:42 of the second
period. Ricci tipped in a shot by Sharks defenseman Gary Suter from
the point. Stars captain Derian Hatcher argued that Ricci had
interfered with Stars goalie Ed Belfour, but the goal stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricci backed into me, and I tried to make a save, but I think
he turned a little bit,'' Belfour said. ``I might have been hit,
but that is going to happen in playoff hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal snapped Belfour's playoff shutout streak. He had gone
164 minutes and 34 seconds without allowing a goal. His streak
dated back to Game 5 of the Stars' first-round series with
Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Sharks were back in the game, San Jose captain Owen
Nolan proceeded to win it.
</P>
<P>
   His goal at 14:56 of the second period proved to be the
game-winner, although a number of solid save were needed from
Sharks goalie Steve Shields before the game was officially won. He
finished with 30 saves, including 13 in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played very well,'' Stars winger Mike Keane said. ``You
have to make every shot a perfect shot. ... But you can't play
five-on-four for a whole period.''
</P>
<P>
   A floundering Sharks bunch in desperate need of life got it when
Sloan was called for goaltender interference at 5:02 of the second
period. Stars forward Aaron Gavey was already in the box for
slashing, giving the Sharks had 52 seconds with a two-man
advantage. It was one of their five power plays in the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   Ricci's goal went in with 12 of them remaining. The goal broke a
streak of 14 power plays without a goal for the Sharks in this
series. They're 1-for-18 in the series.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, the best penalty-killing unit in the league
was no match for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks power play didn't do as much damage to the Stars as
the endless stream of their own players traipsing to the penalty
box.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars suffocated the Sharks' first power play. Nos. 2, 3 and
4 were handled as well. No. 5, a five-on-three no less, proved to
be the one that allowed the Sharks to get back in Game 3 and
eventually the best-of-seven series. Game 4 is scheduled for Friday
at San Jose Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the best penalty kill in the league,'' Stars winger
Kirk Muller said. ``But you are playing with danger.''
</P>
<P>
   They gave the Sharks one too many chances, too.
</P>
<P>
   Their power play wasn't working. The Stars had a 1-0 lead.
Belfour looked invincible.
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly why Nolan was in the game. Nolan, who missed
Game 2 because of ``flu-like symptoms,'' returned to the lineup for
Game 3 against Dallas last night. The foot, the shoulder, all his
ailments encapsulated by ``flu'' still ached, but the Sharks were
in desperate need of exactly what Nolan brings in a best-of-seven
series, where they hadn't scored a goal against the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't disappoint, scoring the game-winning goal at 14:56 of
the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's banged up a little bit,'' Ricci said. ``Got the flu, I
mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing cures a flu like a 2-0 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it didn't look like even the return of Nolan would
be enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had been clinging to a 1-0 lead since 3:35 of the
first period, which is when Stars center Mike Modano scored a power
play goal of his own.
</P>
<P>
   The play began when Stars winger Brett Hull took a shot from
along the boards. Shields made the save, but, as has become his
modus operandi, left the rebound out in front. Modano swooped in on
the puck like a kid on candy. Before Shields had time to say ``no
more rebounds,'' the puck was over his shoulder for a 1-0 Stars
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Modano extended his streak of points in consecutive playoff
games to a personal-best seven games.
</P>
<P>
   He had chances for more, too. A shorthanded breakaway with 1:08
remaining in the second period stands out more than the others.
</P>
<P>
   Modano wasn't the only one with a bunch of could'ves and
should'ves either. Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk had two tips that
easily could've gone in, one in the first period and one in the
frantic final minutes of the third. Stars defenseman Richard
Matvichuk on a breakaway as he came out of the penalty box.
Matvichuk had been in for unsportsmanlike conduct at 13:36 of the
second period. They thought he took a dive.
</P>
<P>
   Which turned out to be the story of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars just couldn't seem to get out of the penalty box.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
