<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS NOT GOOD, BUT GOOD ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ It was not a well-played game, as is often the
case in the Metrodome these days.
</P>
<P>
   But after three hours and 25 minutes, 14 walks, a dozen stranded
Mariners, 10 pitchers, two errors, a hit batter and a passed ball,
an otherwise ugly game finally ended on a play worth savoring _
shortstop Alex Rodriguez's bare-handed fielding gem that preserved
Seattle's 5-4 win over the Twins Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   With two out in the ninth and Minnesota's Jacque Jones at first
base, Cristian Guzman hit a sharp grounder off closer Kazuhiro
Sasaki's glove. On the run near second base, Rodriguez reached back
with his bare hand, grabbed the ball and threw to first for the
game's final out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had it real easy, but when Sasaki touched it the rotation
took it behind me,'' Rodriguez said. ``It was like a golf ball. It
had a lot of english on it. It was the only play I had. If it gets
by me, Jacque Jones scores easily because he was running on the
play and the ball would have spun off ... into no-man's land.''
</P>
<P>
   The play ended what had been a frequently exasperating game, the
sort so common to the Metrodome in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota franchise is in bad shape, on its way to an eighth
consecutive losing season and drawing the smallest crowds in the
majors. With the Timberwolves playing across town in the NBA
playoffs, the announced attendance was 6,780, but far fewer
actually showed up. Those who did were not rewarded by the Twins
pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota pitchers walked 10 batters _ four in a row at one
point _ and hit another. Reliever Hector Carrasco threw 13 pitches,
only one of them a strike, and walked the three batters he faced.
LaTroy Hawkins walked the bases loaded as well.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Mariners were much better, making two errors and
taking little advantage of Minnesota's wildness. Of the 10 Seattle
batters who walked and the one hit batter, only one scored. With a
chance to do some heavy damage, Seattle left the bases loaded in
the fourth, sixth and the eighth innings. Once again, they failed
to get a bunt down in a critical situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a strange game,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``I
don't think you ever win ugly. It may seem that way, but when it's
over and you win, it's very pretty. We got it done, what can I
say?''
</P>
<P>
   The game moved along fairly quickly the first couple of innings
before the Twins started walking everyone in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like putting a parachute out,'' said Seattle starter
John Halama.
</P>
<P>
   Halama pitched poorly in his previous starts, allowing eight
runs in 72/3 innings. He was far from exceptional Tuesday night,
but gave the Mariners a good-enough performance, allowing three
runs (two earned) in five innings to raise his record to 3-0
despite a 5.79 earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as the game got on, I started getting the first-pitch
strike,'' Halama said. ``I had a lot of movement on my sinker
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama breezed his first trip through Minnesota's lineup before
allowing a run on a walk, a ground-rule double and an infield
single in the fourth inning. He allowed two runs in the fifth on a
leadoff single and some shoddy fielding.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mariners rallied for four runs in the top of the sixth
on three singles, four consecutive walks and a passed ball,
Piniella yanked Halama abruptly as he warmed up in the bottom of
the inning, replacing him with struggling Jose Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just decided to get Mesa into the game and see if he could
get through the inning,'' Piniella said. ``As it was, we used four
relievers, but they all needed work, so it really doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa struck out a batter and allowed two hits before Arthur
Rhodes came in to clean up the mess. Rhodes allowed a run in the
seventh, Paul Abbott took over in the eighth and Sasaki came in to
begin the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki had only one save opportunity in the past three weeks
prior to Tuesday night, but thanks in large part to Rodriguez, got
the job done for his fourth save of the season.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out the first batter he faced, retired Todd Walker on
a long fly to deep center and walked Jones before Rodriguez made
his bare-handed play.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
