<SLUG> BC-NET-CUMMINGS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRED MICHAEL JOHNSON PROVIDES VITAL STATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ To find out whether Michael Johnson had his
heart in anchoring the winning 4x400-meter relay team at last
weekend's Penn Relays, one can simply check NBCOlympics.com.
</P>
<P>
   There on the network's official Olympics site is a feature that
includes the rate of Johnson's heartbeat during his winning sprint.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, he literally had his heart into it, and NBCOlympics.com
has provided proof.
</P>
<P>
   With tiny sensors attached to his chest and legs, Johnson's
winning sprint in Philadelphia was recorded with every step.
According to the site, his heartbeat in the first 50 meters was 184
beats per minutes; in the final 50 meters it was 174 beats per
minute.
</P>
<P>
   The data fascinated even the coordinator of the project, Tom
Feuer, the coordinating producer of NBCOlympics.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RThe data\S told me, one, that he was clearly more nervous at
the beginning of the race; two, he is so danged fit that his
exertion of energy slowed his heart,'' Feuer said. ``That's an
amazing feat to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's this kind of information that Feuer envisions as the next
step in tracking an athlete's performance. Rather than sorting
through statistics, Feuer said fans can check a wired athlete's
performance, such as NFL players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine tracking a quarterback's heart rate in the fourth
quarter,'' he said. ``We can determine what contributes to an
interception.''
</P>
<P>
   Feuer said Johnson had seen Quokka Sports wire athletes for
hiking events and climbing exhibitions and approached the San
Francisco company suggesting it do the same with a track athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson agreed to participate in the joint venture between NBC
and Quokka Sports. But to make the technology work, Johnson had to
be outfitted with special Band-Aid-sized sensors developed by
FitSense Technology of Wellesley, Mass. FitSense's e-Go system
monitored Johnson's speed, distance, acceleration, cadence, stride
length, energy burn rate and heart rate.
</P>
<P>
   The technology was tested in the field at UT-Arlington in
December and unveiled at the Penn Relays. The 15-month project
wouldn't have worked without Johnson ``willing to take some
risks,'' Feuer said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes before the relay, NBCOlympics.com used clear
surgical tape to attach the sensors to his body. Once the relay was
in progress, Johnson activated the recording process.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of credit goes to Michael, who was willing to go before
40,000-45,000 people and try a never-before-tested device,'' Feuer
said. ``We think we have it perfected with Michael, but with other
applications there are a lot of things we still need to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the kinks is the turnaround time for posting the data. It
took less than 24 hours to post Johnson's data, but it's nothing
like real-time.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is quoted on the site as saying it's ``the first time
something like this has ever been done, so of course, I want to be
a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have done some things in this sport that nobody else has
ever done, and I see this as another way of getting something like
that under my belt.''  &LR; subheds:Bytes Downloads: Mavericks owner
Mark Cuban is scheduled to chat live on ABCnews.com at 10 tonight.
The chat will follow Cuban's interview with JuJu Chang on ABC's
``20/20 Downtown'' at 9 p.m. ... Indianapolis Colts running back
Edgerrin James signed a three-year contract with Broadband Sports
Inc., to develop his site on AthletesDirect.com.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
