<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4032 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-EXAMINER-PUBLISHER-SF     05-03 1483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-PUBLISHER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST PUTS S.F. PUBLISHER ON LEAVE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By WILLIAM CARLSEN, JANET WELLS and YUMI WILSON 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco Examiner Publisher Tim White was
placed on indefinite leave Tuesday afternoon, a day after he
testified in federal court that he was willing to ``horse trade''
favorable treatment in the paper's opinion pages in exchange for
Mayor Willie Brown's support of Hearst Corp.'s purchase of The
Chronicle.
<P>
   Hearst announced that it would begin ``an internal review into
the matter'' involving White, who testified at a federal antitrust
trial challenging the company's proposed purchase of The Chronicle
and the acquisition of the Examiner by the Fang family, publishers
of the thrice-weekly free San Francisco Independent.
</P>
<P>
   White's leave became effective immediately, and George Irish,
president of Hearst Newspapers, was named interim publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reaffirming our policy that the content of news and
editorial pages may not be negotiated or compromised in any way,''
Hearst spokesman Paul Luthringer said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Joseph M. Alioto, who is prosecuting the antitrust suit on
behalf of former mayoral candidate Clint Reilly, said at a news
conference Tuesday afternoon that Irish, Hearst CEO Frank Bennack
Jr., and other Hearst officials in New York had to know about
White's comments to Brown because they received the e-mail from
White describing the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   White is being used as a ``scapegoat,'' Alioto said. ``If any
action should be taken, it should be taken against Mr. Bennack and
Mr. Irish. Both of them knew about this in the summer of last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Irish could not be reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's decision to place White on indefinite leave came as
media experts around the country _ and the Examiner's own staff _
condemned White's testimony. Journalism ethics experts likened
White's exchange with the mayor to ``extortion'' and ``blackmail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is at the very core of the integrity of the press, when
you have a guy as high-ranked as (White) even implying that he
traded editorial coverage,'' said Michael Josephson of the Joseph
and Edna Josephson Institute of Ethics in Marina Del Rey, an
organization that has consulted with newspapers on ethics issues.
</P>
<P>
   White testified during questioning from Alioto about a lunch
that White and Examiner Executive Editor Phil Bronstein had with
Brown on August 30, just weeks after the Hearst's deal to buy The
Chronicle was announced.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail sent to Irish the same day, White wrote that
Brown's treatment by the Examiner was discussed at the lunch along
with Hearst's effort to buy The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Willie how I was going to justify to my superiors in
New York wanting to support him and cooperate with him,'' White
wrote, ``when he was seeming to go out of his way to make our lives
difficult (by opposing the sale).''
</P>
<P>
   In his e-mail, White also highlighted his impressions of the
relationship between Brown, Bronstein and The Examiner, which the
mayor has criticized for being unfairly critical of him. ``You
would think that (Bronstein and Brown) were the best of friends,''
White wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, White wrote, ``tells me Phil has always taken care of
any problems (the mayor) raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final touch,'' White wrote, ``is that the mayor invited
Phil and Sharon (Stone) to join him in his private suite at 3Com
Stadium for the 49ers' opening game. Phil lied and said he enjoys
football and would be happy to join the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   In court Monday, Alioto asked White if he was ``horse trading''
favorable treatment for Brown's help in closing The Chronicle deal,
and White answered: ``Yes.'' White then qualified his answer by
adding that he was referring to the paper's ``editorial side'' and
not its news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, in a statement released by Hearst Corp., White
said, ``I was tired and confused by the question. The implication
of my answer that the pages of the Examiner can be influenced,
under any circumstances, is absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronstein stated emphatically ``that there were no negotiations
of press coverage of any kind.'' Bronstein later explained that by
``press coverage'' he was referring to coverage in both news pages
and opinion pages.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Tuesday he doesn't remember ``any of the
conversations reported in the newspapers. I remember a very
pleasant lunch ... during the early part of the campaign. There was
no impropriety to speak of. ... There was certainly no substantive
conversation that took place.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the Examiner had been highly critical of his record
in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Examiner has been an incredibly nasty newspaper to me. You
have some very evil people working in that paper,'' Brown said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about White's testimony, Brown said, ``It sounds like
Mr. White was bushwhacked, so to speak.'' The mayor added, ``I am
frankly shocked (that White was placed on indefinite leave).''
</P>
<P>
   White appeared briefly in federal court in San Francisco Tuesday
where he was scheduled to continue his testimony under examination
by Hearst and Chronicle lawyers. But a Hearst attorney informed
U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker, who is presiding over the trial,
that his testimony would not be needed at this time.
</P>
<P>
   White left the courtroom a short time later and he could not be
reached for comment later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said that White's testimony was highly relevant in the
trial because Brown had been in contact with U.S. Attorney General
Janet Reno about launching a possible antitrust investigation of
the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a matter of the publisher making a connection with the
highest political officer in the area, who had ties with the
Justice Department to get him to support not only the Hearst
acquisition of The Chronicle but the closing of the Examiner,''
Alioto said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shulman, Alioto's co-counsel, added that if White had been
``tired and confused'' and had made a mistake, he had an
opportunity Tuesday to correct it on the witness stand, but Hearst
lawyers didn't call him.
</P>
<P>
   Bronstein broke the news of White being placed on leave to the
paper's stunned staff, which was already reeling from the fallout
from White's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members had drafted a petition sharply criticizing White's
testimony:
</P>
<P>
   ``The editorial employees of the San Francisco Examiner would
like it to be known that our editorial support is not, nor has it
ever been, for sale. We do not, nor have we ever, practiced
`horse-trading' at the Examiner.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Examiner staffers expressed shock at White's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got into work and read the trial story, I felt like I
had been kicked in the gut, kicked in the groin,'' reporter Jim
Herron Zamora said. ``It called into question the credibility of me
and all my colleagues. This isn't the Hearst I work for ... Most of
us were big fans of (White).''
</P>
<P>
   But few Examiner staff members wanted _ or even imagined _ that
White would be placed on indefinite leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim White was a decent guy trying to do his job, and his job
was this merger,'' said editorial writer Lynn Ludlow. ``A
suspension of this kind has got to be devastating to his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Examiner Editorial Page Editor James Finefrock said White never
tried to manipulate editorial direction of the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a deal offered, it certainly wasn't
consummated,'' Finefrock said. ``There was no direction to go easy
on Willie Brown on the editorial page. ... We've been very tough on
him throughout. It would be news to Willie Brown if we soft-pedaled
him. It didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper's endorsement of Brown in last year's mayoral race,
which some media observers found surprising, was the ``unanimous
result of an editorial board meeting,'' Finefrock said in a
statement to the Examiner staff Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   News of Hearst's decision to place White on leave prompted a
staff meeting in The Chronicle newsroom as well. At the meeting,
Chronicle Publishing Co. CEO John Sias was asked if it were true
that he had delayed publication of a lengthy story about the
paper's sale to Hearst Corp. and the Fangs' acquisition of the
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Sias confirmed that the story had been held one day because he
had concerns about publishing it so close to the beginning of the
trial and that the paper's senior editors persuaded him to publish
it. Managing Editor Jerry Roberts stated that Sias did not ask for
a single change in the story, which ran in last Thursday's
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   During the staff meeting, Chronicle Executive Editor Matt
Wilson, Roberts and Editorial Page Editor John Diaz reaffirmed the
paper's policy of editorial independence from financial or
political pressures, stressing that all news decisions are made in
the newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will resume in federal court Wednesday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
