<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4034 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-HEARST-EXECUTIVE-SFCH     05-03 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-EXECUTIVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERIM PUBLISHER OF EXAMINER DESCRIBED AS `MAN OF INTEGRITY'
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL NOLTE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   George B. Irish, the Hearst Corp. executive who is taking over
the San Francisco Examiner, was described Tuesday as ``a man of
integrity'' who is able to deal well with difficult situations.
</P>
<P>
   Irish, 55, replaces Examiner editor and publisher Timothy O.
White, who was placed on indefinite leave Tuesday, one day after he
testified in federal court that he was willing to ``horse trade''
favorable treatment with Mayor Willie Brown in the Examiner's
editorial pages for Brown's support of the Hearst purchase of The
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Irish, as president of Hearst Newspapers, received e-mails from
White outlining White's discussions with Mayor Brown. Tuesday,
however, Irish removed White and took over himself as interim
publisher of the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Irish has been in a difficult
situation. He was the publisher of the San Antonio Light in Texas
when the Hearst Corp. acquired the much larger San Antonio Express.
The two papers had been in a circulation war for years, and
Hearst's Light had lost an estimated $60 million in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst attempted to find a buyer for the Light, but was
unsuccessful. On Jan. 27, 1993, Irish announced that the Light
would close down. Hearst then took over the Express. The Express's
employees kept their jobs, but the staff of the Light lost theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult time,'' said Tam Harvey, who was
graphics editor at the Light and was laid off. ``Hearst bought the
other paper and fired their own people. There were feelings of
betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Harvey said, Irish emerged from the situation with his
integrity and honor intact. ``He handled a difficult and painful
situation well and with a lot of heart,'' Harvey said. ``He is a
good guy, and people have a lot of respect for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never forgets a name or a face,'' Harvey added.
</P>
<P>
   Irish became a Hearst executive in 1979 when the chain acquired
the Midland (Mich.) Daily News. He served as publisher there and
then became publisher of the Midland (Texas) Reporter-Telegram, the
Beaumont (Texas) Enterprise and the San Antonio Light.
</P>
<P>
   He then moved up the corporate ladder as vice president and
group executive for Hearst Newspapers, and in 1998 became president
of Hearst Newspapers and a vice president of the Hearst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been Hearst's rising star in the newspaper division,''
said Larry Kramer, who is now the CEO of Marketwatch CBS.com, and
reported to Irish when he was executive editor of the San Francisco
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's straight up,'' Kramer said. ``He's a man of integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   According to others who know him, Irish is a man with an
impressive personality who is willing to serve on community and
corporate boards of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very good citizen,'' said Tom Goldstein, dean of the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   Irish is a member of the school's board of visitors, a member of
the Associated Press Board of Directors, the American Press
Institute and chairman of the board of regents of Millikin
University in Decatur, Ill., his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is universally respected,'' said Goldstein, who was
formerly the dean of the Graduate School of Journalism at the
University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Irish's experience has been as a newspaper executive, not as an
editor or reporter. ``But he understands the appropriate roles of a
publisher and an editor,'' Goldstein said. ``He is the
quintessential publisher.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer does not think Irish will stay long in San Francisco.
``It is an interim role,'' Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   Irish and his wife, Mary, live in New York and have a vacation
home in San Antonio. Like many business executives, Irish enjoys
golf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
