<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4035 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-SPURS-SUNS-HNS &LR;      05-03 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-SUNS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
PHOENIX _ The Suns' Jason Kidd was starting and soon flying. Maybe
then the Spurs knew it was over. Perhaps they always knew.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It just never seemed right for the Spurs, from Sean Elliott's
kidney transplant to begin the season to Malik Rose's ripped right
knee to end it. They never seemed to have a chance, never seemed to
more than resemble the team that swept to last season's title. And
then it was over.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns ended San Antonio's reign Tuesday with an 89-78 victory
for a 3-1 win in their first-round NBA playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns got Kidd back from his fractured ankle Tuesday as if he
was never hurt. The Spurs looked at their bench to see Tim Duncan
in jeans, his torn knee ligament not allowing him to give it a
last-chance try. And as the Spurs limped home on crutches, the
championship reign was gone before they could truly defend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst feeling in the world,'' guard Mario Elie said.
``You work hard during the season. But we never had a healthy team
the whole year. It's frustrating. I wish we could have had our
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the champions of the NBA's shortest season, with one of
the swiftest playoff runs to a title, ended the league's shortest
reign since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   It could be even more fleeting. The last champion to fail to
repeat, the 1985 Lakers, won five titles in the '80s. The Spurs,
the first champions eliminated in the first round since the 1984
76ers, will have to struggle to stay together with every starter a
free agent save David Robinson, 34.
</P>
<P>
   But the possibility of a breakup seems to fit with their demise.
Lakers coach Phil Jackson derisively labeled the Spurs asterisk
champions as title-holders from the 50-game lockout season. They
became asterisk former champs for going down with forward Duncan in
street clothes and the Spurs' realistic chances impaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't going to go very far without Tim,'' Elliott said.
``That's just reality. The guys in this locker room overcame a lot
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Kidd to charge the Phoenix offense again, the Spurs
were outmanned, diminished when Rose went down four minutes before
halftime. Without Duncan, the Spurs could not muster an attack.
Robinson had 21 points and 16 rebounds. But he could make just
seven of 19 shots, and the Spurs needed much more.
</P>
<P>
   Elie was the only other Spur to score in double figures with 12,
and he was just 3-of-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really disappointing to go out like this,'' Spurs guard
Avery Johnson said. ``We were never really whole. Jason came back
and gave them a huge lift. If Tim would have suited up and given us
10 points, 10 rebounds (to answer Kidd's nine points and 10
assists) it would have given us the same lift.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd played 31 minutes, making four of five shots and putting
life in the offense. Rodney Rogers and Penny Hardaway each had 23
points, with Rogers adding 10 rebounds, Hardaway seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, any time somebody comes back, there's going to
be a lot of emotion at first,'' Kidd said. ``After we got back in a
groove and everybody settled down, that was the Suns team you've
seen all year.''
</P>
<P>
   And with so much coming from so many angles, there was no way
the Spurs could keep pace, their best hope unable to join them.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan had gone through the Spurs' Monday practice. But when the
soreness and swelling returned, he was held out as he had been
throughout the series. And as short-handed as that left the Spurs,
it would only get worse when Rose went out with a torn knee
ligament before halftime. The Spurs had lost Jerome Kersey in Game
2.
</P>
<P>
   Down to the last bodies at the end of the bench, the Spurs' last
stand came with the unlikely efforts of Antonio Daniels, Derrick
Dial and Jaren Jackson. With Daniels completing a dunk to a
three-point play, the Spurs found themselves within 70-66. But with
Kidd to guide them, the Suns could not be stopped. They scored on
six consecutive possessions after the Daniels slam with Kidd
getting the assist on every field goal, pushing the lead back to
10.
</P>
<P>
   As much as that might not seem insurmountable, the Spurs were
barely hanging on, outmanned and incapable to hold off the end of
their reign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't hit me,'' Robinson said. ``Until I see somebody else
raise that trophy up, that's when it will hit me. How many teams
get major injuries like we had? But you have to maintain your
character one through 12. That's a little disappointing. I'd say
it's more than a little disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the championship that came so quickly, so did the end. Only
the pain of a season wrong from the start seemed to linger.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
