<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4036 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-03 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE cameras usually have faded to a commercial or switched to a
sideline reporter when it happens. But almost always, it does. A
group of tired football heroes gathers at midfield after a game.
Players kneel and hold hands _ one bloody, stained arm pad
interlocked with another.
</P>
<P>
   They bow their heads. And they pray.
</P>
<P>
   In this era of so much political correctness, so much walking
gingerly along the safe, center line, Fellowship of Christian
Athletes members leading organized prayer is neither sanctioned nor
endorsed by public schools or professional sports. Usually,
athletic directors and team officials turn their heads and act as
if it's not happening.
</P>
<P>
   But it is.
</P>
<P>
   In a small weight room under the Compaq Center grandstands,
local FCA president Mike Myers leads Rockets players in chapel
services before every game. In the Astros' clubhouse, players
quietly bow their heads in prayer at their lockers. At college,
high school and youth games across the country, faith in God and a
commitment in the FCA are strong, even if media coverage is not.
</P>
<P>
   So often in interview settings, players thank God for their
gifts or deeds. But the words usually end up on the cutting-room
floor. It's just not always good copy, often too uncomfortable a
subject for media outlets to throw in front of the public. But it
is there. Always.
</P>
<P>
   And it is there because of Don McClanen and, as he emphatically
says, God.
</P>
<P>
   When did writing about God on the sports pages become foul? When
did acknowledging an athlete's faith become agitating? We are not
here to argue the political sides of sports and religion. We could
go on forever on that one.
</P>
<P>
   But McClanen, who founded the FCA 46 years ago with bold steps
into former Brooklyn Dodgers president Branch Rickey's office,
received the first Founders Award at the annual FCA banquet here
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   And, well, why not McClanen? He started this far-reaching
association, whose membership has grown into the thousands and
whose presence in sports is inspiring if often ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was simple obedience,'' said McClanen, 75, recalling his
days as a young basketball coach at Eastern Oklahoma State. ``I was
collecting clippings from people like Branch Rickey, Otto Graham
and Doak Walker talking about their faith. I thought, `This is
something that needs to be known.'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, McClanen took out a loan on his car with the idea of
founding the FCA. He then drove his wife and two young children
1,300 miles to New York, hoping Rickey could spare five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Rickey's secretary kept discouraging me from going,''
McClanen said, ``but I went anyway. With his stature in sports, I
knew Mr. Rickey could be a big help. Someone finally told him,
`This guy that's been bugging us is here for you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rickey agreed to speak with McClanen for five minutes. Five
hours later, the two emerged from Rickey's office with Rickey
promising to connect McClanen with the corporate world and lend his
support to the FCA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `If athletes are used to selling cars, razor
blades and cigarettes, why can't they testify for God? Kids won't
listen to their pastors or sometimes their parents, but they listen
to athletes,''' McClanen said. ``He told me, `This thing has the
potential for changing the youth scene in America.'''
</P>
<P>
   After many years and several more loans secured by McClanen, the
FCA's mission has not changed. It now is an international
organization with more than 600 staff members, an annual budget
near $50 million and many high-profile athletes playing prominent
roles.
</P>
<P>
   The FCA still rarely grabs headlines. But always it is there.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Religion) in athletics is very much frowned upon,'' McClanen
said. ``But there is a deeper significance in people's lives behind
the headlines. People look down on the relationship, but if people
think David Robinson is soft because he is faithful, David Robinson
won a world championship. Doak Walker was a winner. Winners who are
faithful are everywhere in athletics. Nice guys don't finish
last.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the public often sees only the controversial, criminal
side of sports personalities. We've all been guilty of not seeing
the good for all the absurd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The athletic world is unusually susceptible to distortion,
greed and materialism,'' McClanen said. ``Things have gotten worse.
We are working against society's attraction to overabundance. I'd
like to say the FCA has made definite progress, but I'm not sure.
Our deteriorating society still needs the FCA.''
</P>
<P>
   And whether it makes headlines or not, the FCA figures to always
be there. Under the grandstands. Away from the cameras' focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much has been given to athletes,'' McClanen said. ``Much
should be expected.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
