<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-TRIAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRONICLE PUBLISHER ADMITS NEGOTIATING WITH HEARST
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By WILLIAM CARLSEN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The top executive of the Chronicle Publishing
Company testified Tuesday that for the past several years he
negotiated repeatedly with the Hearst Corp. about forming some kind
of mutually profitable arrangement if the Hearst-owned Examiner
were sold or closed.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Chief Executive Officer John Sias explained that one
such arrangement would have given the Hearst Corp. 34 percent of
the Chronicle's profits ``for 50 years or perpetuity'' if the two
newspapers terminated their joint operating agreement, an exemption
to antitrust laws that for 35 years has allowed the two papers to
combine their business operations while keeping their editorial
staffs independent.
</P>
<P>
   But the family that owns The Chronicle rejected that proposal
and others, deciding instead last year to sell not only The
Chronicle but the family's other media holdings, including KRON-TV,
Sias testified.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony came during an antitrust trial in which former
mayoral candidate and San Francisco real estate investor Clint
Reilly has sued Hearst to block The Chronicle sale on the grounds
that it will result in a single daily newspaper in the city and a
monopoly for Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   In court Tuesday, his attorney, Joseph M. Alioto, sought to show
through Sias' testimony that The Chronicle and Examiner were
determined to eliminate any competition between the two papers
after their JOA expires in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto claimed that several of the proposed deals between the
two papers, outlined in confidential memos and letters, were
predicated on the closing of the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   But Sias was adamant that Hearst officials always said they
would put the Examiner up for sale first and would close the paper
only if no buyer emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Sias said, however, that he did not know if the Examiner _ with
a circulation less than a quarter of The Chronicle's _ could
survive after the termination of the JOA, which requires that the
two papers split all profits evenly.
</P>
<P>
   In his early testimony, Sias was clearly flustered by Alioto's
aggressive questioning. Alioto accused Sias of making an untrue
statement when he signed an affidavit stating that the JOA requires
The Chronicle to subsidize the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that's not true,'' Sias said.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, when Alioto insisted that Sias did not know
how much the Examiner would make if it operated alone, Sias joked:
``Now, that I've just been exposed as a perjurer, I don't know how
to answer.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted that he did not know from actual expense and revenue
records of the papers' combined operations whether The Chronicle
was actually subsidizing the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that he logically assumed, based on The Chronicle's
larger circulation, that it was carrying the Examiner, even if he
had no numbers to support the assumption. ``But I don't know this
from a cost-accounting breakdown,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sias also rejected as unrealistic one Chronicle study that said
that the Examiner could achieve success after the end of the JOA
with less than a quarter of the papers' combined current revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Models were flying all over the place,'' he said, ``and I
don't mean model planes.''
</P>
<P>
   A key contention of Reilly's suit is that the merger of the two
papers would result in the elimination of competition in subscriber
rates and advertising rates, restraints of trade that would form a
violation of federal anti-trust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst and The Chronicle attorneys have argued, however, that
since the two papers already have combined their business
operations under the JOA, there is no actual competition to
preserve.
</P>
<P>
   But Alioto confronted Sias with the confidential report that The
Chronicle family ordered last year from its investment bankers,
Donaldson, Lufkin and Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   The report lays out two scenarios of what would occur when the
JOA expires in 2005: the first with one surviving newspaper and the
second with ``newspaper war`` between the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``With one newspaper,'' Alioto said the report concluded,
``there could be a one-time 20 percent increase in national retail
ad rates.'' With head-to-head competition, there would be
significant ad-rate competition and a 10 to 15 percent decline in
rates, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sias rejected the report, saying that it was written by
``pulling figures out of thin air by people who don't know squat
about the newspaper industry.''
</P>
<P>
   He called them incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   When Alioto asked him if he really believed they were
incompetent, Sias said he had gotten a little ``colorful'' with his
language. While they didn't have newspaper experience, he said,
they were very competent at what they were hired to do, which was
to figure out the best price for each of The Chronicle family's
eight business assets, including The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto asked Sias why some of the memos, especially those based
on rejected proposals, had been kept so confidential, which he said
he found odd in a business that demands open public documents.
</P>
<P>
   Sias said that in 1997 word got out about one of the proposed
merger ideas, and the San Jose Mercury News wrote a story that a
deal for the Hearst purchase of The Chronicle was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A deal was not imminent,`` he said. ``That can be very
destructive to the employees,'' he said. ``They (the Mercury News)
issued an apology ... years later,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker feigned shock. ``You mean you
can't always believe what you read in the newspapers?'' he asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
