<HEADLINE>
KINGS PUSH LAKERS TO GAME 5
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO - If one playoff loss put an unsightly scuff on the
Lakers' glimmering aura as presumed champions-in-the-making, the
second loss wore the shine right off.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they can't even be presumed as champions of the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento Kings made that point emphatically Tuesday night,
sending the heavily favored Lakers to a stunning 101-88 Game 4 loss
at Arco Arena, tying this best-of-five series at two games each.
</P>
<P>
   Two elimination games played and the Kings are still alive. Two
games later, the Lakers are as close to elimination themselves as
they are to clinching a second-round appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They failed,'' coach Phil Jackson said of the Lakers' first
postseason test. ``It's not `the jury's out' - they failed
dramatically in this first step. But this team doesn't have to do
anything but win home games and in basketball you win the
championship. That's the reality of the situation. So now the
pressure's there to win on our home court.''
</P>
<P>
   It was nothing anyone could have expected when this series
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little down,'' Kobe Bryant admitted, ``because we
wanted to get the job done here. But it didn't happen. So we have a
big game on Friday - pressure situation, that's what you live for
as a basketball player.''
</P>
<P>
   It's back to Staples Center for Game 5 and the Lakers can only
hope some semblance of the team that won 67 regular-season games
reappears.
</P>
<P>
   The doubts about the Lakers' title hopes rose exponentially with
this defeat. In Game 3, they merely coughed up the game in the
fourth quarter. This time, they couldn't even forge a lead,
trailing from buzzer to buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a long time, they couldn't even muster a
decent run or much of an offense at all, shooting 37.9 percent from
the field. In an odd role reversal, it was the Kings who won with
defense, and with higher-percentage shooting (43.9).
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to play us incredibly well on their home court,''
Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' Chris Webber was a monster on offense (23 points,
eight assists), on the boards (13 rebounds) and on defense (seven
blocked shots). Six of his teammates scored in double figures, with
41 points coming from the bench, including 17 from Jon Barry.
</P>
<P>
   The hot-shooting Kings hit 9 of 21 attempts from 3-point range,
often in the midst of a Lakers push.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate for a team to do that,'' said Glen Rice. ``Every time
we made a run, they would really drive the dagger in a little bit
deeper. And that's what you've got to do. That's something we've
got to realize that we've got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant had another huge night, with 32 points, and Shaquille
O'Neal bounced back from his Game 3 performance with 25 points and
16 rebounds. But O'Neal had another rough night at the line, making
5 of 12 foul shots, and he only had one block.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Lakers got no help from their role players, and
the reserves supplied just eight points.
</P>
<P>
   Through all of it, including deficits as high as 14 points, the
Lakers, winners of numerous comebacks this season, felt they could
get back in the game. Even when they were down by 11 points with
1:12 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, to be totally honest, I felt it got away from us like
a minute and something left in the game,'' Rice said. ``We still
felt that if we could hit a couple of 3s, we'd get into the game.
But after that it was pretty much over.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, Jason Williams punted the ball into the upper deck
and the confetti rained from the rafters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confidence is not down,'' Rice said. ``We just realized
that we came in here and didn't play our best basketball. And we've
just got to try to regroup and come back Friday and not let this
slip away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' defense against O'Neal once again had Jackson
perturbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you play this game is that you play at the level the
referees allow you to compete at,'' Jackson said. ``That changes
from game to game, it's not consistent from one situation to
another. Their determination is, `We're going to foul Shaq whenever
he gets the ball in the lane, we're going to surround him, we're
going to bang away at him.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And this has been the most valuable player in the league, and
as a consequence (of the fouling), he's not capable of finding the
freedom or the space to operate that he's had in the first two
games of the playoffs. And now we go back and see what this brings
on our home court and see if the referees will use the same
style.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
