r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-SIDE-LADN     05-03 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS MUGGED AGAIN BY BENCH MOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO - And that fifth game again, was when?
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento Kings, all but left for dead at Staples Center -
what was it, a lifetime ago? - have now forced a fifth game no one
truly expected, and the Lakers definitely did not want.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings made the Lakers look very mortal, very Clark Kent, in
Tuesday night's 101-88 victory in Game 4 at what just may be
correctly billed as the world's loudest arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers left town, cow bells ringing in their ears, perhaps
fighting that shadow of doubt, and with a Kings team that now very
much believes in itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our self-confidence is very good,'' said Kings guard Tony
Delk. ``Game 3's win really helped. We learned we could play with
this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly when Delk and the rest of his ``Bench Mob'' are
absolutely dominating the Lakers' ``No-cinch Mob.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are a couple of numbers you can bet your Zen self-help book
on, that Phil Jackson will be pointing out: Kings bench 42, Lakers
bench eight.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the offensive output of the two teams' benches
Tuesday night. Sad but true, the Kings bench outscored their Lakers
counterparts by a whopping 34 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year and last year, the bench was a big part of our
success,'' said Sacramento center Vlade Divac. ``I think they're
the best bench in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can play like that, we can beat anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Laker Jon Barry led the Sacramento reserves with 17 points,
five rebounds and two assists. But Delk added 12 points, two
rebounds and two assists; Predrag Stojakovic 11 points and three
rebounds; and even Scot Pollard chipped in three rebounds and a
couple of points.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   Their reserves made a grand total of three baskets. Count 'em -
one, two, three. End of offensive production.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry did grab seven rebounds, but otherwise the L.A.
bench was about as effective as earplugs at Arco Arena.
</P>
<P>
   And not Horry, A.C. Green or anyone else from La-La Land, has
yet to come up with the slightest answer for forward Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
   Webber scored 23 points, grabbed 13 rebounds, had eight assists,
a franchise-record seven blocks and four steals.
</P>
<P>
   This is called a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thought it was over,'' Webber said. ``I'm just proud
of this organization and this team, because it would have been so
easy to quit the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been so easy to lose, just have a vacation and
say it's over because we played against some good guys. But we feel
good, because we're going back to L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are feeling sick. They had trouble from the get-go.
They trailed by nine at the end of the first quarter, 11 at the
half, seven after three quarter, and finally lost by 13.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was waiting, but the great Lakers' charge never came.
Every time they would start to rev up their offense, the Kings
would be ready with an answer. With a 3-pointer, a key rebound, or
maybe most unexpectedly, a big stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``They missed a lot of shots,'' said Divac, holding onto a
straight face. ``We don't play defense. We're an offensive club.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings played 48 minutes of complete basketball. From
beginning toend, they kept the pressure on. Truth is, they may not
be able to play much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who played, had a hand in this one,'' Barry said.
``We just attacked the basketball and looked for the open man. It's
a simple game. Sometimes we try to make it hard with behind the
back passes and stuff, but tonight we played hard and made it
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   And the fans at Arco Arena can certainly cause the ears to ache,
but can they really make that much difference?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they have a good crowd here, but they don't come out
and make a basket for you,'' said Kings guard Jason Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it when the crowd is against you. I hope Friday night,
everyone at Staples Center just let's me have it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we'll have to come out and play better on Friday,
because they're going to be jacked up.''
</P>
<P>
   By the game's end, the Lakers were reduced to Ron Harper - 3 for
9 from the field - flashing one of his championship rings to the
crowd by holding onto the back of his shaven head.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd responded by chanting, ``Not with Shaq!''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, for the Lakers, it was a rough night overall.
</P>
<P>
   And now the team with the league's best regular-season record,
goes home with a stunning prospect now possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chance,'' Barry said. ``And in any deciding game,
anything can happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
