<HEADER>
A4153 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-FASHION-SHOPPER-KANSA     05-03 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SHOPPER-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION THERAPIST HAS REMEMDIES FOR WHAT AILS YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She is a slim, small-boned woman with piercing
blue-green eyes and smartly cropped hair, and on a recent day she
wore a blue sweater, trousers and a charming smile.
</P>
<P>
   But the soft-spoken voice and gracious manner belie a deeper
power. Betty Halbreich has nudged, prodded, intimidated, guided and
mothered celebrities, socialites, stockbrokers and moms from
Scarsdale into clothes they might never have considered for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For 23 years she has been the personal shopper in residence and
director of the Solutions department at Bergdorf Goodman, an
upscale New York department store. She can boast a clientele that
includes the likes of Joan Rivers, Susan Lucci, Jane Curtin and
Stockard Channing.
</P>
<P>
   She says she can tell in nanoseconds what will enhance a
customer who walks into her sight, and it's unlikely anyone argues
with her. Given her poise and self-assurance, she probably knows
best.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, HarperCollins Publishing convinced her to do a
book, and the result was Secrets of a Fashion Therapist: What You
Can Learn Behind the Dressing Room Door (Cliff Street Books, $25)
with Sally Wadyka, published in 1997. The book, which has been
reprinted in Japan, Germany and China, was slated for reissue in
paperback ($15) in the United States in April.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Halbreich is more than a clothing stylist and far more
than a saleswoman. Her own phrase, ``therapist,'' might not be far
wrong. She looks beyond hair coloring and cellulite bulges and
understands that the consumer's quest for a new wardrobe may well
be a search for a new sense of self _ or a new life.
</P>
<P>
   In her time at Bergdorf, the fashion world has shifted from
haute couture to street power and from designer decrees to personal
style. The store executives have changed, and by her account, the
store has suffered diminished gloss and glamour.
</P>
<P>
   But ``I'm still alive,'' she says with a Scarlett O'Hara kind of
survivor's determination.
</P>
<P>
   She has watched fashion do flip-flops and observed the emergence
of business casual and the dressing down of America. She laments
the loss of interest in good lingerie among young women. And in the
old days, women would recite criticism from their husbands or come
looking for what spouses told them to wear. Maybe they would bring
back a dress: ``He didn't like it,'' they would say. But now it is
their children who are criticizing their clothes, Halbreich says.
</P>
<P>
   She is surprisingly outspoken, with a very modern perspective.
She believes the most common mistake women make is in buying too
much. ``They don't need so many clothes. Why, you could take that
suit,'' she says, pointing at the reporter, ``on a trip, wear it
every day (in different ways) and no one would realize it was the
same suit.''
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't put much stock in many designers because their ``ego
gets in the way of creativity,'' she says. But among Americans, she
most admires Geoffrey Beene because he ``always stuck to what he
believed.'' And Michael Kors, whom she has known since his youth,
has managed to stay with what is ``truly American.''
</P>
<P>
   In her personal wardrobe, her own favorite is a long Issey
Miyake skirt that she can pull up as a dress or wear down as a long
skirt, and it works for many special events. ``I can wear it
without a jacket and with a jacket,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the questions she gets from women have to do with body
size. They ask, ``How can I look thinner? Do you think my shoulders
are broad?'' she says. ``Most women see themselves as too large,
and they'll have on a size 6.''
</P>
<P>
   Her romance with clothing began when she was a child in Chicago
with a mother who delighted in clothes and showy hats. She
remembers how, well before the winter snow melted, her mother
brought out her cherries hat. In early fall, the feathered felt
appeared as regularly as the first chill. She learned quickly the
joy of playing dress-up in her mother's closet. ``Those things
stuck,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Later she married, raised children and never gave a thought to
working until her marriage ended in her middle years. She was then
able to fall back on the sense of taste and aesthetics she absorbed
so early in life.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the worthy points she makes in the book:
</P>
<P>
   - Before you go shopping, weed your closet. If you haven't worn
a garment in a year, toss it or donate it to charity or a friend.
</P>
<P>
   - Strip down in front of a full-length mirror and _ be brave _
analyze your figure flaws and assets. And remember everything you
wear is seen from every angle.
</P>
<P>
   - Before you go shopping think about what you need. Flip through
magazines. Repeat the mantra, less is more.
</P>
<P>
   - When it comes to accessorizing, rules can go out the window.
Hosiery doesn't have to match your shoes exactly if you're not
wearing skin-toned sheers. You can add another subtle color that
doesn't compete with the rest of the look.
</P>
<P>
   - Black is good because it does make you look thinner and it
looks expensive even if it's not.
</P>
<P>
   - But you can have too much of a good thing. You know you have
enough (black) if people start to console you for your recent loss
or when even you ``stop being able to tell your clothes apart.''
</P>
<P>
   - Mixing and matching is fine, but if you wear denim jeans with
a boxy jacket you'll ``look like a box with denim legs.''
</P>
<P>
   - Many colors can be mixed. And tones don't have to match to go
together.
</P>
<P>
   - You can almost always lose the oversized shoulder padding even
if you have narrow shoulders. If not, you look as if the hanger is
still in the clothes.
</P>
<P>
   - If you're brain dead when it comes to style, find a good
personal shopper _ as soon as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
