<HEADER>
A4155 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BOOKS-SAUNDERS-KANSAS     05-03 1547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SAUNDERS-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE SAUNDERS SHORT STORIES LAY EVERYDAY TRUTHS AT OUR FEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pastoralia, by George Saunders (188 pages; Riverhead Books;
$22.95)
</P>
<P>
   It may only be May, but George Saunders has already written the
short-story collection of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Pastoralia does everything a gathering of tales is supposed to
do: It touches the reader but also provokes reflection, mirth and
pain. It is a noisy collision of satire and pathos, where poor
wretches like you and me struggle to overcome corporate America or
classism or maybe just their own twisted egos _ and fall short.
Here are six yarns so strange that one must resort to a cliche to
describe them: You really won't know whether to laugh or cry.
</P>
<P>
   The natural thing for a critic to do with a book like this is
demand an explanation from the author. But in a recent telephone
interview from his home in Syracuse, N.Y., Saunders basically
admitted he has a hard time explaining himself to himself. Some of
his story ideas come from dreams. All his work is ``organic.'' And
yet he knows he's not exactly normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always imagine my talent as a dog, and I say, `OK, boy, go
out and get something,' and I think he's going to bring back this
big, classic pheasant _ but in my case he always comes back with
the lower half of a Barbie doll or something. When I try to write a
story about love or whatever, it always somehow gets warped in the
telling.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Saundersworld.
</P>
<P>
   `Pastoralia'
</P>
<P>
   His title story is the funniest riff on corporations since ...
well, since the title story of his last collection, 1996's
CivilWarLand in Bad Decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pastoralia'' is a theme park where modern Americans can go see
living history, or at least the version the park's owners provide.
There are fake shepherds, for example, and faux hermits.
</P>
<P>
   And a sham caveman and cavewoman. Our ``hero'' is the caveman, a
hard-working guy who spends his days grunting and pretending to
grub for bugs. His cavewoman partner is a slacker who instead of
grunting and cowering, chats with the park's paying customers. In
English. And gets argumentative visits from her doofus son. Right
there in the cave. Management is not pleased.
</P>
<P>
   The customers are no better. ``Where do they poop?'' one odious
woman asks.
</P>
<P>
   Most troubling to our caveman hero is that he has to evaluate
Janet, his querulous cavewoman. There's a fax machine in his living
quarters, out of sight of the customers. Every day he faxes in
chirpy lies to his superiors, trying to protect Janet. They're onto
him, though. Pretty soon Janet's in trouble. Pretty soon Janet's a
goner. Pretty soon our caveman hero is reassigned a go-getter
cavewoman partner who thinks he's a slacker.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pastoralia'' is a sendup of the workaday world and a wicked
riff on plastic-meets-rustic theme parks such as Silver Dollar
City. The story began as a dream Saunders had about wearing a
caveman costume in a cave.
</P>
<P>
   But he also once worked for an environmental company (his
undergraduate degree is in geophysics) where he had to evaluate his
co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd basically be living with these people,'' he says.
``You'd go out on the road and stay in bad hotels and be working in
swamps taking samples, and you'd come back and have to rat on them.
My policy was, `I'm not going to do it; I'll always say everything
was great.' But then there was this woman who was in trouble. I
thought her work was OK. But the company wouldn't accept my
reviews. My boss said, `You've been so consistently positive that
we know you lie.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And the company's communiques to its employees were just as
bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd get these e-mails alluding to a feud that we didn't know
existed or denying a layoff we hadn't even heard about yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Those e-mails provided inspiration for a note our caveman hero
receives one morning from headquarters regarding bathroom breaks on
company time:
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think your poop is a legitimate business expense? Does
it provide benefit to us when you defecate? No, on the contrary, it
would provide benefit if you didn't, because then you would be
working more. Ha ha! That is a joke. We know very well that all
must poop. We grant you that. But also, as we all know, it takes
time to poop, some more than others.''
</P>
<P>
   Saunders' view of the business world makes ``Dilbert'' look like
a company man.
</P>
<P>
   Broken hearts
</P>
<P>
   But Saunders is more than just a modern-day Swift. His
characters are misfits and fools, and yet they evoke pity,
compassion, even sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   In another story titled ``Winky,'' a man named Neil Yaniky goes
to a self-help seminar where a gung-ho guru will teach him to deal
with any person who is cramping his lifestyle. Neil decides he has
to give the boot to his sister, Winky, who lives with him. Winky,
Neil says, is ``crazy-looking and too religious and needs her own
place.''
</P>
<P>
   The self-help man wants Neil to be ruthless. As the story
progresses, though, Neil's resolve slowly breaks. His sister
genuinely is an idiotic mess of a human being, but she also loves
him.
</P>
<P>
   Without revealing the ending, let's just say Neil finds it
harder to extricate himself from his misery than he first imagined
in that seminar room at the Hyatt.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders has grown as a writer. The tales in his previous
collection often ended with a death ``or something extreme,'' as he
puts it. This time around, he says, ``I don't have those kind of
explosively escapist endings. Something happens from A to Z, but
it's not all the way finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Poverty stinks
</P>
<P>
   The narrator of ``Sea Oak'' is a male stripper at a nightclub
called Joysticks. Female patrons rate him and his co-workers
according to their cuteness, from Knockout to Honeypie to Adequate
to Stinker.
</P>
<P>
   Our stripper ``hero'' lives with his aged Aunt Bernie and sister
Min and cousin Jade in a squalid apartment complex called Sea Oak,
which is nowhere near the sea and has no oaks. Aunt Bernie works at
DrugTown. The foul-mouthed and feckless Min and Jade divide their
time among having babies out of wedlock, allegedly studying for
their GEDs, spouting malapropisms and watching porn infomercials
and TV shows such as ``How My Child Died Violently.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For dinner it's beanie-wienies,'' our stripper hero observes
one evening after a hard day's booty-shaking for 40 lousy bucks in
tips, $5 an hour in salary and only a Honeypie//Adequate rating.
``For dessert it's ice cream with freezer burn. `What a nice day
we've had,' Aunt Bernie says once we've got the babies in bed.
`Man, what an optometrist,' says Jade.''
</P>
<P>
   Saunders hasn't worked as a stripper (or at least didn't admit
to it) but has done time in bad jobs. His narrator in ``Sea Oak''
is lower-middle-class and culturally challenged but not stupid.
Saunders thinks the simple burden of too little money can wear down
the hardiest spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just read somewhere that the average CEO gets 700 times the
salary of the average line worker. I'm not a big political thinker,
but I had a run of luck, I guess I'll call it bad luck, when I was
in my 20s (he's 41 now) and bouncing around from job to job _
slaughterhouse to roofer to doorman in Beverly Hills. The
cumulative effect was to convince me that even on the material
level, a person can be greatly reduced by strife and hard work. And
the good things in life are less accessible when you're working
your ass off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the trick is to recognize (poverty's) manifestation in
each generation. It's certainly not The Grapes of Wrath in our
country now, but there's still something off.''
</P>
<P>
   Love those losers
</P>
<P>
   Saunders has a gift for making us care about his outcasts and
weirdos. Not since Ignatius J. Reilly and company in John Kennedy
Toole's A Confederacy of Dunces has their been a band of
dunderheads so delightful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The End of FIRPO in the World'' features a kid so dorky that
even his mother makes fun of him, and yet by the time something
really bad happens to him in the story, it feels like a death in
your family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Barber's Unhappiness'' tracks the movements of a man whose
lechery seems boundless. (The character is based on a real person
Saunders knew who ogled women without shame, including Saunders'
wife.) But somehow Saunders finds his humanity, shapes him into a
man who just might be capable of loving an imperfect female.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Falls'' walks down two paths, following two men to a
destiny that will reveal them as cowardly or courageous. One finds
strength within; the other is paralyzed by his instinct for
self-preservation; and yet the line that divides their characters
is almost invisible. They are both, after all, only human.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me the really interesting thing in the human story is
people's belief that the self we create is permanent and solid and
defensible. But in fact, as we know, in another 90 years or so,
none of us is going to be here in any form; the bodies are going to
go, the minds are going to go long before that.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it seems to me that one thing you can count on in writing
is to exploit our tendency to be silly and greedy and narcissistic
and self-absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of timeless, isn't it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1027EDT &QL; 
