<SLUG> BC-LIFE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 IN AMERICA BUGS 0504 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA 0504: Garner's bug place keeps Beetle lovers in
tune
 &HT;    (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters.
Photos and a sig/locator map are available.)
 &HT;    By Jeremy Desposito
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERTFORD, N.C. _ Joe Garner works on all foreign model cars. He
does paint work on all cars.
</P>
<P>
   But he only restores Volkswagens.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to spot his workplace next to his home on U.S. Highway
17 S. About 140 Volkswagens, mostly bugs, await their fate in the
yard surrounding the business.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 will be restored, and the others will be scrapped for
parts.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Beetles, you can find early- and late-model buses,
super beetle convertibles, jeep models, the sporty Carmen Ghias,
Baha dune buggies, kit cars and a few other foreign-model cars.
</P>
<P>
   A customer from the Outer Banks leaves his super beetle for
Garner to repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be careful, it's my baby,'' the customer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody that's got them calls them their 'baby,''' says
Garner.
</P>
<P>
   He's been restoring Volkswagens for about 25 years. His work
began with the second car he ever owned, a 1964 Baha bug. The
inability to afford a mechanic forced him to learn to repair it
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started as a hobby,'' Garner says.
</P>
<P>
   He rented his first hobby shop in Weeksville. There, he started
buying and restoring old bugs for himself. Once restored, he had a
difficult time keeping one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd fix it, then somebody would see it and he'd have to have
it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Garner relies on his Toyota and Dodge trucks for everyday use.
He won't keep a bug for himself because he feels it defeats the
job. He's got a wife and four daughters that come first, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money's money,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``My preference is a Toyota, second is a Honda.''
</P>
<P>
   He does have a suped-up beetle and a 20-foot long sand-rail dune
buggy that, if he chose, he could ride on his three acres behind
the shop. The sand rail has never been ridden, and both cars can be
sold at any time, he says.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Janet, shares Garner's passion for Volkswagens. She'll
go to the shows with him. His 14-year-old daughter is waiting to
drive a 1960 convertible model.
</P>
<P>
   Beetles can be fully restored for about $6,000, Garner says.
Full restoration takes about a year. Restoring special models can
cost anywhere from $900 to $1,400. All parts are still produced. In
fact, because the vehicles are so cheap to produce, third world
countries have bought the right to manufacture them. Mexico City is
one place that breeds the bugs. At each place, the German auto is
designed slightly differently as far as cosmetics, Garner says.
</P>
<P>
   Garner doesn't have a favorite, but he generally prefers the
older models, he says. People will buy them upon his
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer anything from 1967 on down,'' he says. He points to
one bug with glass over the headlights. ``The older car looks
better to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Other cars waiting to be restored include a Porsche 914.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the poor man's Porsche'' he says. ``It's got the same
motor as the bus, but it's a two-seater, so she'll scream.''
</P>
<P>
   There's one rare, jeep-style model called the Volkswagon Thing,
and a fiber-glass dune buggy that can hold two or four seats (''the
cartoon speed buggy'').
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kit cars are all Volkswagon underneath, the front end
and the rear end,'' he says. ``They just take the top half off the
Beetle.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a high demand for buses. Garner definitely can't keep
them on the lot. ``I get people all the time asking for the
buses,'' he says. ``But I don't know where to get them.''
</P>
<P>
   One model he hasn't restored yet is an old bus. He shows a
picture of one with the front windows opening out and long, narrow
windows along the side of the roof. ``The kind you steer with your
elbows,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Garner's goal now is for the business to expand. He's got
several handymen to assist, but he can't pay them yet. It's more of
an internship, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an investor there would be no wait,'' Garner says. ``The
handymen could earn a paycheck. We could do more. There's work
here, but it takes a while to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   One assistant, Jess Wood, attends College of the Albemarle. He's
busy cutting hoses to fit, cleaning air filters, and other jobs. He
also has the buggy passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're nice cars,'' he says. ``You can make them look any way
you want them to look. And the girls like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
