<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4169 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN04-COX     05-03 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Actress bares her age
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ You wouldn't normally think that an onstage nude
scene is the best way for an actress to strike a blow for feminism.
</P>
<P>
   But if your name is Kathleen Turner, and you're widely regarded
as a has-been at 45, you might feel differently.
</P>
<P>
   Too old for Hollywood? Not starved-looking enough?
</P>
<P>
   Turner is fighting back with a headline-grabbing turn as Mrs.
Robinson in the London production of The Graduate, including a
40-second nude scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of my feeling was, 'Why not a 45-year-old woman naked
onstage?''' Turner recently told USA Today. ``I am shapely. I am
not 25. I'm not gorgeous _ some kind of model _ but I am a
good-looking 45-year-old woman.''
</P>
<P>
   I am pleased to report that my husband, after catching Turner's
show-stopping performance during our recent trip to London, is
profoundly committed to her cause.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind all the postcards Jim mailed to all his old
frat-house buddies: ``I was in the same room with Kathleen Turner,
and she was 100 percent naked.'' I am convinced he is acting purely
out of feminist zeal. He even e-mailed all his friends a copy of a
Reuters story _ ``Let Over-40s Be Sexy _ Kathleen Turner'' _ he
pulled off the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very proud to know that you are so fully secure in your
masculinity that you can support such a worthwhile cause,'' replied
his friend Don. ``Without supportive males like you (and me) where
would the performing arts be? I shudder to think of the tripe that
the theater community would be forced to perform. God bless
Kathleen Turner and her cause!''
</P>
<P>
   It all started when we stopped in at the Gielgud Theater on the
off chance of snaring tickets for the show that had opened only a
few days earlier. The buzz hadn't yet reached locust level, and a
few scattered seats remained for the show that, only a few days
later, would be sold out for the entire run.
</P>
<P>
   Naively, I asked about the age-appropriateness of the production
for our 8-year-old son. (Hey, maybe this was the Disney, G-rated
musical version of The Graduate.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there will be a naked woman onstage,'' said the ticket
seller, shrugging, in a suit-yourself voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sold!'' Jim cried, landing a seventh-row seat.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that this play would hold more aesthetic and cultural
value for Jim, I volunteered to be the one who stayed at the hotel
readingThe Chronicles of Narnia to Alec.
</P>
<P>
   Jim came back elated. Turner, he reported, hadn't lost one
degree of Body Heat _ she looked beautiful and fit _ and the show
itself was terrific.
</P>
<P>
   Turner is, by all accounts, loving her star turn as Mrs.
Robinson _ and her chance to thumb her nose at a Hollywood that
won't look twice at a woman unless she is under 40 and borderline
anorexic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each day she (Mrs. Robinson) gets more interesting,'' Turner
told Hello! magazine. ``More and more I find, in the U.S.A. anyway,
when a woman is over 40 and attractive and strong, then she must be
evil ... either she is that or terribly frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   So there's something gratifying, for us 40-somethings, about an
international sensation caused by an actress who refuses to be
relegated to matron status.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jim, his theatrical coup has completely eclipsed all our
other adventures in England. Nobody wants to hear about the Tower
of London; everybody wants to hear about Kathleen Turner in the
flesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the culmination of a 20-year dream,'' Jim raved to
his friends.
</P>
<P>
   By which he means, of course, finally seeing Kathleen Turner in
a role worthy of her mature theatrical talents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
