<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4170 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS04-FILE     05-03 1661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS04-FILE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 2 of 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: Somewhere I believe I heard that Sen. John McCain's father
was an admiral in the U.S. Navy. Is this true?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, but the military heritage goes back even further. McCain
(R-Ariz.) comes from a long line of military commanders dating to
Capt. William Young, an ancestor who served on the staff of Gen.
George Washington during the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's father, Adm. John S. McCain Jr., was commander-in-chief
of all U.S. armed forces in the Pacific during the Vietnam War. A
much-decorated submarine commander in World War II, he led the U.S.
amphibious force that invaded the Dominican Republic in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's paternal grandfather, Adm. John Sidney McCain,
served in both world wars, becoming commander of all the aircraft
carriers in the Pacific in the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not all: The grandfather's brother was an Army
brigadier general, and his uncle was an Army major general.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain (1884-1945) and McCain Jr. (1911-81) were the first
father and son to become full admirals in U.S. Navy history.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the roles of Congress and the president in awarding
the Medal of Honor? What is the correct name, simply the Medal of
Honor, or the Congressional Medal of Honor? And when did the medals
originate?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Medal of Honor was established on Dec. 21, 1861, by
President Abraham Lincoln for enlisted men of the Navy and Marine
Corps, and later was expanded to include enlisted men and officers
of all services.
</P>
<P>
   The highest military award for gallantry in action that the
United States grants to members of its armed forces, it usually is
awarded by the president ``in the name of the Congress of the
United States.'' That's why it often is incorrectly called the
Congressional Medal of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the latest on Dr. Jerri Nielsen, who was stationed at
the South Pole when she diagnosed her own breast cancer? She had to
wait several months to leave the Pole because severe weather
prohibited access to her camp. She finally was rescued last fall,
but I haven't seen anything reported since.
</P>
<P>
   A: After she was plucked from the Pole Oct. 15 by the 109th
Airlift Wing of the New York Air National Guard, she was flown to
Indiana University where the tumor was removed.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, however, she has made plans, with the help of a
professional writer, to tell the story about her life on the ice,
her feelings of helplessness as an ill caregiver, and her reasons
for taking the job in the first place. Nielsen has received a
``high six-figure payment,'' according to Hilary Bass, publicist
for Talk Miramax Books. Nielsen's story is to be published this
fall and serialized in Talk magazine, and she also has optioned the
rights to her story to Miramax Films.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue effort reportedly cost taxpayers more than $500,000,
but Maj. Bob Bullock of the New York Air National Guard said money
isn't a factor in such rescues. ``We don't put a value on human
life in terms of dollars and cents,'' he said, adding that
performing such flights ``is part of our mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Congress recently passed the unlimited income bill for Social
Security recipients, and President Clinton said he would sign it.
Did that happen? If so, how far back is it retroactive?
</P>
<P>
   A: Clinton signed the Senior Citizens' Freedom to Work Act of
2000 into law on April 7. It eliminates the Social Security
retirement earnings test in and after the month in which a person
attains full retirement age (currently 65).
</P>
<P>
   The repeal is retroactive to Jan. 1, which means that about
415,000 working seniors or dependents will get refunds for the
money already deducted this year from their Social Security checks.
</P>
<P>
   Details are available at Social Security offices and can be
found online at www.ssa.gov/legislation/legisbulletin040700.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If a player selects the cash option for the Big Game, how
does the lottery board determine the amount the winner will be
paid? Of the advertised annuitized jackpot, how much would a winner
choosing cash option actually get?
</P>
<P>
   A: The cash option amount for the Big Game is based on sales and
current interest rates for each drawing. Since prevailing interest
rates and sales differ with every drawing, an exact figure for the
cash value of a hypothetical drawing can't be given in advance. For
example, two drawings six months apart with an estimated $30
million annuity amount may differ in sales and/or interest rates,
so the cash option value also would vary, even though the estimated
annuity amount is the same.
</P>
<P>
   You can get an idea of amounts, however, if you consider the Big
Game jackpot won by a Georgia couple in January. The advertised
annuity amount, based on taking the winnings over a period of 26
years, was $46 million. The couple chose instead to take the money
at once, making their winning amount $22.4 million. Of that, they
paid $7.6 million in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has President Clinton answered the disbarment complaint made
against him by the Southeastern Legal Foundation? An article said
April 21 was the deadline. What happens next?
</P>
<P>
   A: An administration official has indicated that Clinton met the
deadline. But more than likely it will be the middle of May before
much more is known.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Arkansas Supreme Court's committee on
professional conduct declined to comment, saying the matter is
confidential. But Matt Glavin of the Southeastern Legal Foundation
explained the process.
</P>
<P>
   As reported, the deadline for Clinton's response to the
foundation's disbarment complaint was Friday. The committee is
required to get a copy of the president's response to the
foundation within 10 days, Glavin said. If the president responded
with a defense and the foundation gets that copy within 10 days, it
will have seven days to reply. Then the complaint will go to the
committee members for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The committee probably will vote by May 18 on whether to disbar
Clinton, or what the sanctions should be ``for lying under oath and
obstruction of justice,'' Glavin said.
</P>
<P>
   When the foundation gets a copy of Clinton's response, that is a
privileged document and won't be released to the press by the
foundation. But the foundation will release its own response to it,
Glavin added, and from that it can be deduced what Clinton's
response was.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you provide information about procedures for requesting
practice round tickets for next year's Masters golf tournament?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 2001 practice rounds will be April 2-4. Applicants are
allocated tickets on a random selection basis. Tickets will be sold
in advance, and by application only.
</P>
<P>
   Practice round applications for 2001 will be mailed beginning in
May to those people who applied in 1999 and 2000, or who have
requested practice round information. Others may request an
application by submitting their full name, address, daytime
telephone number and Social Security number to: Masters Tournament,
Practice Rounds, P.O. Box 2047, Augusta, GA 30903-2047.
Applications being returned to Augusta National must be postmarked
by July 15.
</P>
<P>
   To hear recorded information, call 706-667-6700 and follow the
prompts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Q&AMP;A item about obtaining tickets for Masters practice
rounds indicated that applicants were asked to provide their Social
Security number, along with other information. Can you clear up,
once and for all, whether it is or is not against the law to
request one's Social Security number?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Social Security Administration says you can refuse to
provide your Social Security number if a business or other
enterprise asks for it. However, that may mean doing without the
purchase or service for which your number was requested. The agency
says you're welcome to ask why your number is needed, how your
number will be used, what law requires you to give your number, and
what the consequences are if you refuse. The answers to these
questions can help you decide if you want to give your Social
Security number. The decision is yours.
</P>
<P>
   While saying that it can't prevent others from asking for your
number _ and it can't control what uses are made of your number
once you give it to someone else _ the Social Security
Administration says you should know that giving it to them does not
give them access to your Social Security records. The privacy of
your records is guaranteed unless disclosure to another government
agency is required by law, or the information is needed to conduct
Social Security or other government health or welfare programs.
</P>
<P>
   More information can be found online at
www.ssa.gov/pubs/10002.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I always thought the first three digits of a person's Social
Security number referred to their state. But when I was filling out
my income tax return, I noticed that the number of one of my
children begins with 253, and the other two with 257. All three
were born in Atlanta. Why the difference?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ``area numbers'' _ the first three-digit field in the
nine-digit numbers _ are assigned to geographic locations,
according to the Social Security Administration. Those for Georgia
are 252 through 260. So your children's numbers are right in there.
</P>
<P>
   Area numbers assigned before 1972 indicate the Social Security
office that originally issued the number. Since 1972, the area
number corresponds to the residence address given by the applicant.
</P>
<P>
   Detailed information about the structure of Social Security
numbers can be found online at this address:
www.cpsr.org/cpsr/privacy/ssn/ssn.structure.html.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
