<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 1 of 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about the the Aspen Institute and
its Wye River Conference Center in Maryland, where Elian Gonzalez
and his father were taken?
</P>
<P>
   A: The institute describes itself as ``a global forum that
convenes leaders from diverse disciplines to address critical
issues that confront societies, organizations and individuals.''
Founded in 1950, the nonprofit institute has offices in Aspen,
Colo.; Chicago; New York; Santa Barbara, Calif.; Queenstown, Md.;
and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye River Conference Centers overlook the Wye River on
Maryland's Eastern Shore. They encompass three retreats with their
own meeting and dining rooms, accommodations, and recreational
facilities. Elian and his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, are said to
be housed at Carmichael Farm, about a mile north of the Wye River
Plantation and away from the shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   The complex has provided a secluded, secure location for
everything from congressional and business retreats to seminars
and, in 1998, the Middle East peace talks between Israeli Prime
Minister Bnjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
hosted by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can we buy tickets to the All-Star Game July 11 in
Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   A: An announcement about ticket sales will be made by the
Atlanta Braves on or around May 25, according to Major League
Baseball. Near that time, call 404-522-7630 or check online at
www.majorleaguebaseball.com or www.atlantabraves.com for
information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I distinctly remember reading months ago about a mass mailing
by Social Security of everyone's current statement of earnings. But
I have yet to receive mine. Can you update me?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Social Security Administration started mailing Earnings
Benefit Statements to everyone 25 and older last October, said
agency spokeswoman Patti Patterson. They are sent out about three
months before each person's birthday, and will be mailed
automatically, once a year, on the same schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Without knowing your birth date, she couldn't speculate on your
particular statement, but she said you can do what anyone has
always been able to do: Call 1-800-772-1213 and request a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I plan to leave my body to Emory University for research, but
I also am listing myself as an organ donor. Is there a conflict?
Can I do only one or the other?
</P>
<P>
   A: At most medical schools, you cannot donate organs and tissues
for transplantation and then donate the rest of your body for
anatomical study, said Jeff Al-Mashat of the Georgia Coalition on
Donation and Lifelink of Georgia. So you must decide which you want
to do.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read recently that Princess Juliana of the Netherlands was
91. Isn't she the queen mother? Why was she referred to as
princess, since at one time she actually was the queen?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's correct to refer to her as Princess Juliana, said a
spokeswoman at the Royal Netherlands Embassy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The only child of Queen Wilhelmina and Prince Henry of
Mecklenburg-Schwerin, Juliana Louise Emma Marie Wilhelmina was born
on April 30, 1909. She was princess until she became queen on Sept.
6, 1948, when her mother abdicated. Then on April 30, 1980, by her
own wish, Juliana abdicated in favor of Beatrix, the oldest of her
four daughters with Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld, whom she
married in 1937. When she abdicated, her title once again became
princess. She often is referred to simply as Juliana.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know that onions grown in a specific geographic area are
called Vidalia onions. Is there any difference between them and
sweet onions grown outside that area?
</P>
<P>
   A: It would seem so. This geographic area of Georgia is unique
in its soil type, rainfall patterns and other climatic conditions,
said Reid Torrence, University of Georgia Extension Service
coordinator in Tattnall County, which is in the heart of Vidalia
onion country. Those conditions allow for the production of onions
that are far milder than those grown in other parts of the state,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, research tests have shown that onions grown in the
Vidalia region are less pungent than onions produced anywhere else
in the world, Torrence added. Pungency in onions is related to the
presence or absence of sulfur in the soil during various stages of
production.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting: In 1986, Georgia passed legislation giving Vidalia
onions legal status and defining the 20-county production area in
southeast Georgia. The Vidalia onion was named Georgia's official
state vegetable in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard that members of Congress don't pay into Social
Security, but have their own retirement plan. How does that work,
and how much do they collect from it?
</P>
<P>
   A: U.S. senators and representatives began paying into Social
Security in 1983, as part of a government-wide pension overhaul.
This is a requirement, and members may not opt out of it.
</P>
<P>
   They then have the option of participating in one of two pension
plans, depending upon when they were elected. If before 1984, they
participate in the Civil Service Retirement System; if in 1984 and
after, in the Federal Employee Retirement System. These two plans
also are offered to rank-and-file federal nonmilitary employees,
except that the congressional plan's benefit is calculated on a
more generous formula.
</P>
<P>
   Also, members of Congress may participate in the government-wide
Thrift Savings Plan, which works like a federally managed 401(k)
salary reduction plan. Federal Employee Retirement System
participants are entitled to a government match of up to 5 percent
of salary; Civil Service Retirement System participants may set
aside 5 percent of their own salary, but they don't receive the
match.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers pay 8 percent of their salaries into the pension
system. This compensates for only about one-fifth of the typical
lifetime benefit, according to the National Taxpayers Union.
</P>
<P>
   With service of 20-25 years, a member of Congress could retire
with up to 80 percent of final salary, said the NTU's Pete Sepp.
The only cap on how fast their benefits rise is the rate of
increase in the Consumer Price Index. Congressional pensions can
exceed a member's final salary, but only after a few years in
retirement, when cost-of-living adjustments begin to kick in.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Regarding the three judges on the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals who ruled on the Elian Gonzalez case: Who appointed them?
Were they all Nixon appointees?
</P>
<P>
   A: None were appointed by President Richard Nixon. The order
keeping Elian in the United States until his appeals are exhausted
was issued by Judges J.L. Edmondson, Joel Dubina and Charles
Wilson. Edmondson was appointed by Ronald Reagan; Dubina by George
Bush; and Wilson by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After seeing ``Thunderheart,'' I'm curious about actor Graham
Greene, who also was in ``Dances With Wolves.'' What can you tell
me about him?
</P>
<P>
   A: A full-blooded Oneida, Greene is one of Canada's most
celebrated actors. He was born in Ohsweken, Ontario, on June 22,
1952. He was a draftsman, civil technologist and steelworker before
launching his acting career. After several outings on the English
stage in the '80s, he returned to Canada and was cast in the
British film ``Revolution,'' with Al Pacino.
</P>
<P>
   Greene subsequently was involved in theater productions in
Toronto, working often in productions of Native Earth Performing
Arts and appearing on TV programs and in films. His big break came
when he met Kevin Costner, who told him, ``Don't cut your hair.
We'll be in touch.'' Greene's performance as Kicking Bird in
``Dances With Wolves'' earned him an Academy Award nomination for
best supporting actor.
</P>
<P>
   Since then he has had roles in a number of films, including the
1999 adaption of Steven King's ``The Green Mile.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's often reported that President John Kennedy established
the Peace Corps. Wasn't Hubert Humphrey also instrumental in its
creation? Also, didn't Kennedy borrow the statement ``Ask not what
your country can do for you, but what you can do for your country''
from someone else?
</P>
<P>
   A: The idea of establishing an ``army'' of Americans to work for
peace dates to 1904, when the American philosopher William James
proposed it in a speech. In 1910, he developed the idea of a youth
peace army more fully in a pamphlet. After World War II, many
groups set up international work camps modeled on the American
Friends Service Committee, a Quaker organization.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1960, Sen. Richard Neuberger (D-Ore.) and Rep. Henry
Reuss (D-Wis.) asked Congress to study the possibilities of a youth
corps program. Later than year, Sen. Humphrey (D-Minn.) proposed
that Congress create a peace corps. Then Sen. Kennedy (D-Mass.)
picked up the proposal, using it in his 1960 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   About the famous ``ask not'' quotation, it's similar in spirit
to a remark Oliver Wendell Holmes Jr. made on May 30, 1884, in
Keene, N.H.: ``We pause to . . . recall what our country has done
for each of us and to ask ourselves what we can do for our country
in return.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: When was the first increase in Social Security benefits based
on a cost-of-living adjustment? What has been the annual percentage
increase since 1985?
</P>
<P>
   A: The first increase was in June 1979. Since 1985, these have
been the increases (year, percentage): 1985, 3.1; 1986, 1.3; 1987,
4.2; 1988, 4; 1989, 4.7; 1990, 5.4; 1991, 3.7; 1992, 3; 1993, 2.6;
1994, 2.8; 1995, 2.6; 1996, 2.9; 1997, 2.1; 1998, 1.3; and 1999,
2.4.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
