</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4177 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KELSO-COLUMN04-COX     05-03 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I'll keep my cheap beer, thank youBy John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I find it a little goofy that the federal
government is blaming cheap beer for causing gonorrhea.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean I should switch exclusively to high dollar Fat
Tire and other brands that cost you $6 to $7 a six-pack? What's
wrong with picking up a six-pack of Busch Tall Boys for $3.29 every
once in a while? Is Uncle Sam trying to turn us all into a bunch of
Bass Ale-belching suds snobs?
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought that Milwaukee's Best killed anything that
ailed you,'' said a friend of mine who carts the cheapest beer he
can find to University of TexasLonghorn football games.
</P>
<P>
   But despite what my friends and I know about the health benefits
of drinking Lone Star, Keystone and other inexpensive brands, the
studies by the national Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
concluded that raising the tax on a six-pack of beer by 20 cents
could reduce gonorrhea by up to 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that drinking beer leads to risky behavior among
youth. So raising beer prices this much will make it harder for
them to get beer.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. Raising the price of a six-pack by two dimes really
slowed me down when I was a kid. How many teen-agers do you know
who can't find an extra 20 cents to get loaded?
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the government has statistics to back its
conjecture. From 1981 to 1995, researchers followed changes in
alcohol policy in all states. In years after increases in beer
taxes, gonorrhea rates usually dropped among youth. For example, in
1991 a 9-cent tax increase per six-pack in California was followed
by a 30 percent drop in gonorrhea in 15- to 19-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean that the way to eliminate fat kids is to raise
the price of the cheeseburger Happy Meal from $2.29 to $2.38? I
don't want to sound like I'm practicing medicine. But maybe a
better solution than raising the price of beer would be to have the
beer man pass out condoms with every cold one at sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   It's unfair to single out the budget beers for blame. What's
next? Is the CDC going to call for a tax increase on all jug wines
that come with a twist-off cap? Trust me. You can get just as
stupid from sucking down a $7.19 six-pack of Guinness Extra Stout
as you can from inhaling a $2.69 six-pack of Schlitz.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as my friend so aptly put it, ``They may have the surgeon
general putting a clap warning on Pearl.''
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso can be reached at 512-445-3606 or at
jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
