<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4178 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX     05-03 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientific research is busy tracing human DNA to the original
parents
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The Baptist leaders at Baylor University are
establishing a think tank to see if they can use scientific methods
to validate the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   That may be a crude way of putting it. The supporters of this
controversial project are touchy about the way it is described.
Some critics have said the university is attempting to promote
creationism, the belief that the earth was created exactly as it is
described in the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor's administration, however, says the think tank will
attempt to build a bridge between religion and science.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the new think tank, called the Michael Polanyi
Center, promotes the argument of intelligent design, a discourse
that holds that some natural phenomena are so complex that their
existence is evidence of an intelligent creator. He uses statistics
to show that such phenomena can't be attributed to random chance.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who say that if all statisticians were laid end
to end, it would be a good thing. But that's another subject.
</P>
<P>
   While people are working themselves into a froth over whether
Baylor is forcing an unholy union between science and religion, a
dedicated group of scientists scattered around the globe are
gathering proof that all humans descended from one original father
and one original mother, Adam and Eve.
</P>
<P>
   These geneticists are using DNA to track the origins of the
human species. They have determined, according to a New York Times
article by Nicholas Wade, that all the people in the world are
descended from 10 sons of the genetic Adam and 18 daughters of the
genetic Eve.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of children, which may be why it was called
paradise.
</P>
<P>
   The genetic scientists also have determined that the original
Adam and Eve lived in Africa, perhaps somewhere between the
central, southern and eastern portions of the continent.
</P>
<P>
   It's fascinating to learn that scientists can use DNA to trace
ancestral lineage that shows the migration patterns of our early
family members out of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   One group of scientists uses mitochondrial DNA, which is
described as tiny rings of genetic material that come from the egg
cell, and which traces the maternal line to one of 18 daughters of
Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Another group of scientists use the Y chromosome to trace the
family tree for men back to one of the 10 sons of Adam.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists don't know the names of the individuals who gave
all humans their genetic heritage, but the names Adam and Eve are
convenient and comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The DNA branches are referred to as the daughters of Eve and the
sons of Adam.
</P>
<P>
   Since all the branches trace their roots back to Africa, the
scientists have used mitochondrial DNA testing of existing African
populations that remain closest to the ancestral origins of humans.
They found the Biaka pygmies of Central Africa and the Vasikela
Kung of southern Africa as being genetically closest to humans'
ancestral origins.
</P>
<P>
   The single main lineage that began in Africa split into three
branches. The youngest branch, which is common in East Africa, is
believed to be the source of both the European and Asian lineages.
</P>
<P>
   Native Americans have genetic lineages that come primarily from
Asia in several migrations but also from Europe, arriving in
America between 15,000 and 30,000 years ago. Sioux and Ojibwa
tribes, among other northern peoples, have DNA that show a European
ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   A private company, Oxford Ancestors, has a business that for
$180 will determine for European descendants which of the seven
daughters of Eve who populated Europe they are descended from.
</P>
<P>
   These scientific discoveries should give Baylor University's new
think tank something to think about.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethawayis the Senior Editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
