<HEADER>
A4214 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      05-03 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE ANCESTORS MOVE IN  
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The house was already turning into a museum, and now we have a
piano. No current resident has need for a piano, nor any working
knowledge of one, but how could we not take it in?
</P>
<P>
   For many years it presided in a serene living room in Woodland,
Calif., where my mother-in-law would on occasion shyly agree to sit
down and play for family members. She always added the necessary
footnote about the foolishness of a woman in her 70s taking piano
lessons. But we knew she was almost as proud of what she achieved
on those keys as she was of possessing such a fine beauty.
</P>
<P>
   After she died, followed six weeks to the day by my
father-in-law, the children slowly emptied their house, quickly
disposing of easy things like appliances but reluctant to part with
sentimental favorites. The piano stayed, but now the house is to be
occupied by new people who will want to make their own sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The piano is in our guest room, which I guess we will now call
the piano room.
</P>
<P>
   There's little space left for guests, anyhow, seeing as how the
room also contains a baby's high chair, vacated 15 years ago by the
youngest grandchild and also a part of our newly acquired Woodland
group.
</P>
<P>
   Also in that room we have portions of the Pennsylvania
collection, that being the furniture group that moved in after my
parents died. This includes a child's desk built by my father and
painted by my mother. There's also a wingback chair, three
generations old at least. I visualize it one day dressed in maroon
colored velvet but now its gaudy 1950s style turquoise sits in a
corner fading in the afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   All of these pieces wait, maybe for our children to find a spot
for someday, maybe for their children. Perhaps some Martha Stewart
type will envision the high chair as a plant holder. Who knows when
and how they will come alive again?
</P>
<P>
   All we know is that they can't be left to strangers.
</P>
<P>
   In the living room there is a Pennsylvania hutch and a rocking
chair, now sharing space with two Woodland chairs and a coffee
table that was never meant to hold coffee. It's a low sleek model
of highly polished mahogany, the kind found in expensive furniture
stores holding nothing more than a copy of ``Architectural
Digest.'' We've loaded it up with piles of newspapers and books
which is our way of preserving the finish.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it works. Eventually you become the family
repository, responsible for things left behind, more precious in
memory than dollar value. Everyone gets a turn at this. One
generation departs. The next moves to the front of the line. They
get the furniture.
</P>
<P>
   You see the same additions in friends' houses. Suddenly there
appears a gold framed portrait of a woman from the 1930s staring
from the wall next to the French travel posters and Victorian style
end tables incongruously bracketing the couch where the dog always
sleeps.
</P>
<P>
   A few generations back our ancestors moved here with nothing,
just like immigrant families still do today. They eventually filled
homes with bookcases carved by hand and dining tables paid for on
the installment plan. Some things were deemed important enough to
pass on, like grandma's yellow chair, and they move around the
country to continue the family connection.
</P>
<P>
   A piano does not travel easily. Nor is it something you stash in
a garage or on the top shelf of a closet. It can't be dismissed to
a basement or attic. This one weighs 600 pounds and was delivered
by two professional piano handlers, both musicians who juggle
pianos on the side. They were very gentle and respectful of their
cargo, complimenting my mother-in-law's taste.
</P>
<P>
   One is also a piano tuner. The other has a band and sings. They
are not dispassionate about anything that makes music.
</P>
<P>
   A piano requires delicate handling, said the man named Dave.
Even though it's the size of a refrigerator it needs to be carried
like a baby bird. A great deal of huffing and puffing went into
getting it inside and finally placed. They treated it with such
respect I felt bad that it was not going to a place of honor with
some eager musician waiting to test the keyboard. Put it next to
the high chair, I said.
</P>
<P>
   That morning my sister-in-law and brother-in-law were in
Woodland for the final cleanup and to wave the piano off. When they
called to say it was en route Stephanie reported in a small voice,
``Everything's gone now.''
</P>
<P>
   But she also said that when it arrived I should ask the delivery
man to play something. He'd given them one last tune.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't have to ask. Explaining that he wanted to make sure the
piano had withstood the journey Dave pulled up a stool and asked if
I preferred pop or classical. I said he should play what he did in
the old house.
</P>
<P>
   So he settled his big moving man's hands on the keys and played
``As Time Goes By.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
