u i BC-ISRAEL-WAGNER-BOS &LR;      05-03 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WAGNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAGNER PROGRAM REOPENS OLD WOUNDS IN ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV - An Israeli orchestra's decision to break the national
taboo on playing music by composer Richard Wagner, whose
anti-Semitic writings inspired Adolf Hitler and whose music was
adopted by the Nazi movement, has set off an angry debate months
before the first-ever scheduled performance.
</P>
<P>
   Some Holocaust survivors say it is cruel to inflict the music
and its memories on the very people who found refuge in the Jewish
state after surviving Hitler's plan of genocide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every orchestra has the right to play what they want, but
personally I feel that as long as we Holocaust survivors are here
on this earth, with our very sad and bad feelings about this
composer, then Wagner should not be played,'' said Shevah Weiss,
65, a Holocaust survivor from Poland and former member of the
Knesset, Israel's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are thousands and thousands of musical creations and
symphonies that the orchestra can choose from. Why did they have to
pick Wagner?'' asked Weiss, now chairman of the Yad Vashem
Holocaust memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The piece that the Israel Symphony Orchestra recently announced
it would play in October is ``Siegfried Idyll,'' which Wagner wrote
for his wife Cosima after the birth of their son Siegfried in 1869.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some of Wagner's music, such as the long and heavily
Teutonic Ring cycle, the chosen piece has been described by music
critics as an exceptionally beautiful love song without the
anti-Semitic tone some see in his other works.
</P>
<P>
   In the past Israeli audiences have shown that they do not
differentiate between Wagner's love songs and the operas that are
heavy with the German nationalism and glorification of a new type
of man that anticipated 20th century Fascist ideology.
</P>
<P>
   When, in 1981, the Israel Philharmonic Orchestra started to play
an encore taken from Wagner's romantic opera ``Tristan and
Isolde,'' listeners erupted in anger. One person jumped on the
stage and showed the concentration camp number tattooed on his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the New Israeli Opera, during a lunchtime seminar
on Wagner's music, planned to have one of its singers perform a
piece from Wagner. But the audience shouted down the idea even
before the seminar moderator could give the song's title.
</P>
<P>
   If the Israel Symphony Orchestra is able to go ahead with its
program - and, given the angry debate and threats of protests,
nothing is certain - this would be the first time that Wagner's
music was played in public from start to finish in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not trying to do something provocative, but the bottom
line is that more than 50 years after the Holocaust, I thought it
was the proper time to start playing Wagner in a delicate way,''
said Ehud Gross, director of the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music of Wagner does not belong to the Nazis, it belongs
to the world and there does come a time when what you have to do is
distinguish between art and politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Israel was founded in 1948, there has been an unofficial
ban on public performances of Wagner, although his music is
available in shops and even the state radio's music program on
occasion plays pieces by Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his notoriety as an anti-Semite - embodied in a pamphlet
Wagner wrote called ``Judaism in Music'' - many people hear in his
works profound psychological insights and beautiful music.
</P>
<P>
   Theodor Herzl, the father of modern Zionism, adored Wagner's
music, and the second Zionist congress in Basel, Switzerland, in
1898 included musical excerpts from the opera ``Tannhauser.''
</P>
<P>
   What poisoned Wagner's music for many people in Israel was not
his anti-Semitism as such - many famous composers, including Franz
Liszt and Frederic Chopin expressed such views - but how his music
and writings were used by Hitler to give cultural legitimacy to the
Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ``People came here from all over to be Jews and of all the
things that they can hear they don't want to hear Wagner's
operas,'' said Eric Zamir, a journalist at The Jerusalem Post who
has closely followed the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The question some people in Israel now ask is when it will ever
be a good time to play Wagner. Some people say when the last
Holocaust survivor dies, but others ask about their children and
their grandchildren, who may also feel uncomfortable in memory of
their relatives.
</P>
<P>
   One music specialist said that the issue might be less Wagner's
actual anti-Semitism - for example, another composer favored by the
Nazis, Richard Strauss, is now performed in Israel - and more that
this is the last real taboo in Israel relating to the Holocaust and
as such has become a symbol of its horrors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in Israel who lived through the Holocaust clings to
this symbol as if, if they let go, people would forget the
Holocaust,'' said Michael Ajzenstadt, artistic administrator of the
New Israeli Opera.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4217 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-TSVANGIRAI-B     05-03 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-TSVANGIRAI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR LEADER POSES THREAT TO MUGABE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KADOMA, Zimbabwe _ When the rally ended, Morgan Tsvangirai
didn't linger. His battered white pickup truck slipped through a
crowd still shouting his praise and disappeared into a maze of
cornfields, skirting the brick-wielding pro-government mobs lying
in wait along the tarred roads back toward town.
</P>
<P>
   For a man who is state enemy No. 1 in strife-torn Zimbabwe, such
acts of evasion are Tsvangirai's only concession to the danger he
faces daily in his electoral campaign to topple President Robert
Mugabe. Once safely out of town, he pulled off on the shoulder of a
darkened two-lane highway and jumped into a car to spar with
journalists on the two-hour ride back to Harare, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody phoned me, when was this, the night before last. This
guy phoned me, said `Are you Morgan?' I said yes. He said, `Oh, I'm
going to kill you.' I said, `People who kill people don't use
phones, they just shoot,''' Tsvangirai joked. His sandy voice was
raw from too many public speeches.
</P>
<P>
   His humor is neither act nor naivite. Tsvangirai galvanized a
limp and corrupt labor movement into the government's greatest
irritant, mobilizing workers against tax hikes and rising food
prices. Now, as leader of a recently formed opposition party, he
may just end Mugabe's 20-year lock on power.
</P>
<P>
   His gain has brought pain. Two years ago he was nearly beaten to
death. He's been imprisoned twice. Last month his driver was killed
in a roadside ambush. His family lives under armed guard. But
Tsvangirai still walks through Harare at will, protected _ at most
_ by a few aides or a bodyguard, and often alone. He refuses to be
intimidated and seldom wears a tie. He is motivated, his friends
say, by the people's desire for change.
</P>
<P>
   Tsvangirai for president? It is not far-fetched. Two decades
after leading Zimbabwe to independence, Mugabe and his ruling party
are decidedly out of favor with voters. The government is riddled
with corruption, the econonmy is in tatters. Unemployment and
inflation both exceed 50 percent. Interest rates float at more than
70 percent. Despite this, Mugabe is diverting an estimated $6
million a month to prop up embattled Congelese President Laurent
Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   In February, voters, led by Tsvangirai's Movement for Democratic
Change, delivered Mugabe his first ballot rebuke since 1980,
rejecting his proposed new constitution. Using a soccer analogy,
Tsvangirai said voters had given Mugabe a yellow card, or warning,
and would him a red card in the parliamentary election, throwing
him out of power.
</P>
<P>
   Stung, Mugabe unleashed veterans of the war for independence on
white farmers, resorting to violence and the issues of race and
land to stop Tsvangirai ahead of parliamentary elections, which
constitutionally must be held before August 11.
</P>
<P>
   However, opinion polls show Tsvangirai's party maintaining
support from 65 percent of voters. If his party wins a majority in
parliament, Tsvangirai said, he will launch impeachment proceedings
to drive Mugabe from power before the end of his term in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   He attributes his support to demographics. ``Young people are
very frustrated, and they see this old man who is always trying to
talk about the past,'' he said. ``Poverty, job creation, and all
those economic issues are the topmost issues. You can't confuse
land with poverty. People want jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Belonging to an emerging generation of African leaders,
Tsvangirai is more concerned with economics and government
accountability than the post-colonial heroism of Mugabe's age. He
has vowed economic austerity and a clean government. When Mugabe
raised the wages of civil servants up to 90 percent in January,
Tsvangirai objected. He vows to reduce the Cabinet's size and sell
off the state fleet of Mercedes Benzes.
</P>
<P>
   Critics worry about leadership under a trade unionist. They cite
Zambia, where labor leader Frederick Chiluba toppled autocrat
Kenneth Kaunda in 1990, but then oversaw steady economic decline in
the decade that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Tsvangirai rejects the comparison. ``We will seek a consensus
with business, labor, and government,'' he said. ``Continuing down
the current path is self-destruction. The trade unions must be
assured that down the line, economic discipline is the only way we
can create jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1952 in the dry, impoverished southern town of Buhera,
Tsvangirai was the oldest of nine children. His father, a
bricklayer, died while he was in his teens. Although a bright
student, Tsvangirai was forced to abandon school to support the
family. He worked in a textile mill and a nickel mine before rising
in union ranks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Tsvangirai slipped into Mozambique to join the freedom
struggle, but he never successfully linked up with the forces
fighting against colonial rule in his country. Some now regard his
lack of liberation credentials as a liability, and Tsvangirai
recently made what some say was a tactical mistake.
</P>
<P>
   In need of funds to finance his campaign, he met with the South
African Chamber of Commerce, a body still dominated by whites and
which recently urged its members not to invest in Zimbabwe.
Tsvangirai also accepted a meeting with visiting South African
opposition leader Tony Leon, also white.
</P>
<P>
   Those contacts, as well as his support among white farmers at
home, opened him to attack from critics claiming he is a puppet of
the former white regimes of South Africa and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mugabe was always going to use the race card against us, said
Welshman Ncube, an adviser to Tsvangirai. ``That's his only
weapon.'' Ncube said they have tried repeatedly to talk with South
Africa's ruling African National Congress, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   The father of six children, Tsvangirai lives in a modest suburb
of Harare. His cars are dented, his clothes rumpled, and friends
say he was not eager to lead the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tried his best to see it go to someone else,'' said Brian
Kadoro, his longtime friend and lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   But as Zimbabweans clamor for change, Tsvangirai seems
determined not to fail them. ``Any new generation of
post-independence leaders must start, first of all, the
pschological shift from blaming and start accepting responsibility
for their own decisions,'' he said. ``The post-liberation
generation can always raise emotions of colonialism, racism, and
all that. We cannot afford that. We have to push Africa to a
situation where it is respected again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
