<HEADLINE>
LEE ENDURES BIG BUMPS ON THE ROAD TO RICHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Upon close examination, the road to riches usually turns out to
be a bumpy path.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: the Thomas H. Lee Co., the Boston investment firm
that made a name for itself and fortunes for its institutional
clients through leveraged buyouts and other private equity
investments.
</P>
<P>
   The company and Lee himself made that name on the gaudy internal
rates of return posted by each of the company's investment pools.
The details of individual private equity investments rarely saw the
light of day, with the exception of the occasional blockbuster
sale.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Lee has more money in publicly traded stocks. And
that makes a lot more of the details, well, public. They aren't all
slam-dunks.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Lee's $500 million preferred stock investment in
Conseco Inc. got more complicated. The insurance company's chief
executive resigned under pressure, and Lee president David Harkins
was installed as interim chief.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco stock had sunk 73 percent since Lee's investment in
December, and talk had turned to the liquidation of at least some
of the company's assets.
</P>
<P>
   The news wasn't as bleak as it might appear for Lee. His
preferred position would at least break even short of bankruptcy,
and even then might do just fine. But Conseco isn't going to be
anyone's idea of a blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously disappointed by recent events, but we're
certainly not anticipating any loss of principal, and we still hope
to make a profit on the investment,'' Lee said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months earlier, the value of Lee's 11 million shares of
Mattel Inc. was sliced in half over two weeks in a corporate
meltdown that led to the departure of chief executive Jill Barad.
The stock has been dead in the water ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Lee ended up with Mattel stock when the toy company acquired
software maker The Learning Co., a significant Lee investment in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The good news: Lee has still doubled the value of his original
investment in less than three years.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: He had quadrupled his money as of last fall.
</P>
<P>
   What does he think about the future of Mattel stock? ``We
continue to hold those shares,'' is all Lee would say.
</P>
<P>
   The developments at Conseco and Mattel might seem jarring, but
step back for the big-picture view we normally get with Lee's
private investments and the results are as smooth and rich as
whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   The internal rate of return for a Lee fund launched in 1995 has
been about 70 percent a year, and another fund created two years
later has generated just over 120 percent annually, according to
people who have seen recent documents (for yet another new Lee
fund) that detailed the company's past performance.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the problems at Conseco and the trimmed profits in
Mattel, Lee points to other recent investments in companies like
MJD Communications Inc. and Big Flower Holdings Inc. as promising
and his 21 percent stake in Metris Cos. as a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record of our fund as a whole is excellent,'' said Lee.
</P>
<P>
   And that is what matters most to institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we invest with a private equity firm, we don't expect
that they're all going to be home runs,'' said one investor who has
bought into past Lee funds. ``The notion of one or two deals
(struggling) doesn't signify a trend in my mind,'' he said. ``These
people are taking significant risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The people who give Lee big money to invest think about other
things, like how his firm's operations will be affected over time
by the large stake in the business sold to Putnam Investments. Or
the latest, biggest new fund of all, which Lee intends to create.
</P>
<P>
   The new private equity fund, which had a stated intention of
raising $5 billion, will probably reach more than $6 billion before
it is completely closed. The first of several closings of the fund
took place within the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It will almost certainly become the largest private equity fund
ever, just ahead of the $6 billion investment vehicle launched in
1996 by Kohlberg, Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Since Lee started to raise money for his new fund, KKR has begun
work on a new fund of its own that's believed to be targeting $8
billion for investment.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the picture?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I would point out that none of these guys has a small
ego,'' said Steven Galante, publisher of Private Equity Analyst in
Wellesley. ``Any of them would be more than pleased if they wound
up with the largest fund.''
</P>
<P>
   You only get into that kind of league by earning huge returns
for investors over many years.
</P>
<P>
   That includes a few bumps along the way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
