<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVE AGGRESSIVELY, INVEST CONSERVATIVELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. Are my investments too risky? I recently switched the
403(b) account from Fidelity Magellan, Contrafund, Ginnie Mae etc.
to the current holding. I have never been able to save before my
current job as an administrative assistant. I have to be as
aggressive as possible, even if I push retirement back to age 70.
If I don't do much better than the average 10 percent return, I'm
going to be a bag lady. I am so frightened about how I will
survive. Am I too old and poor to buy a small condo in the next
year or two? Would I be better off putting more money into my
investments, or less into the 401(k) and buying property? I pay
$460 monthly rent because I live in a moderate income complex, but
it will go up to $550 in June and in several years I won't be
eligible for the apartment and would face going into the Boston
rental market, at which time the rental cost would exceed what I
would pay for a mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   J.M., Rockland, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think the picture is as bleak as you paint it,
although you probably will have to work past the usual retirement
age. I don't agree with your decision to assume the heavier risks
that go along with funds such as Fidelity Select Biotechnology,
hoping to make up for lost time. My approach has always been to
save aggressively and invest conservatively. Having that dormant
403(b) in the biotech fund is probably OK, but I don't suggest you
increase that position. And be cautious with additions to similar
funds.
</P>
<P>
   You don't specify how your 401(k) contributions are allocated.
I'd make heavy contributions to American Century Twentieth Century
Ultra and Vanguard Index 500 _ about 40 percent each _ and limit
contributions to the riskier Science and Technology and Emerging
Growth funds to 10 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring your suggestion that a 10 percent return wouldn't be
enough, I projected your accumulation after 16 years with that
presumed return and with contributions at current levels. The total
was $436,741. But it's only fair _ before I paint a picture that's
too rosy _ to point out that if inflation runs at an average 3.5
percent for 16 years, that would have the value of only a little
more than $250,000 in today's money, or only enough to supply a
$16,250 income stream (in today's dollars) without depleting the
principal.
</P>
<P>
   One big missing element is Social Security. If you will be
eligible, the fact that you probably will be retiring late should
push your benefits up. Moreover, if you continue saving the current
percentages of your income and increasing the dollar value of your
contributions every time you get a raise, that would push your
accumulation higher.
</P>
<P>
   The picture is by no means bright, but I don't think you need to
be frightened. Just keep plugging away and you should be in a
workable situation.
</P>
<P>
   Buying a condo also might work. But before you decide, calculate
the total cost, including taxes and the management and maintenance
fees. If you are still convinced that in a few years the monthly
cost will be less than that of renting, by all means go ahead. Home
ownership represents a form of financial security just as solid
(and a whole lot safer) than an investment portfolio. And if at
retirement age you find you have to liquidate that asset and go
where living costs less, you should be able to convert the property
to cash, especially if you have chosen it with long-term value in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   The only situation in which I would rule out a condo purchase is
if saving for the down payment would take your 401(k) contributions
below the point at which you would get the maximum matching benefit
from your employer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am trying to decide whether to invest a $50,000 inheritance
in a balanced mutual fund such as Vanguard Index 500 or use it to
buy a home. If I invest, I'd like average gains of 10 percent over
at least 10 years. I am in the 20 percent tax bracket. If I do buy
a home, I would wait for interest rates to fall below 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   S.M., El Cajon, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's start with the fund. In the language used in the
investment community, Vanguard Index 500 is not a balanced fund. A
balanced fund is one that divides its portfolio between the stock
and the fixed-income markets, usually with 50 to 66 percent of the
assets in stocks and the rest in bonds and other fixed-return
investments. Vanguard Index 500, on the other hand, is an all-stock
fund, keeping 99.9 percent of its assets in stock holdings,
retaining only a small portion of cash to facilitate redemptions.
Since over the long haul bond holdings tend to be less risky than
stock funds, if you bought a balanced fund you would see less
choppy investment results but probably lower returns.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 10 years, Vanguard Index 500 has produced average
annual returns of 18.71 percent, but you should remember that the
last 10 years have been a truly remarkable decade. Nonetheless, I
think your 10-year expectation of 10 percent average annual returns
for Vanguard Index 500 is reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   If you went with a true balanced fund, and Vanguard Balanced
Index comes immediately to mind, expectations of returns in the 8
to 9 percent range would be reasonable over the long haul. Like
Index 500, that fund is designed simply to track broad market
indexes as closely as possible, with 60 percent in stocks, 39
percent in bonds, and the remaining 1 percent in cash. It hasn't
been around long enough to build a 10-year record.
</P>
<P>
   I have nothing to guide me in guessing whether you would be
better off buying a home. I think of home ownership as one of the
greatest foundations of financial security. But before you make a
decision, you should consider the factors I mentioned to J.M.
above: total cost, including mortgage, taxes, insurance, and
maintenance, and whether you think home prices in your area are
reasonable and likely to hold their value and, ideally, to advance.
</P>
<P>
   If a home purchase is an affordable alternative, I'd lean that
way. But if you are indeed in the 20 percent tax bracket, my guess
is that you would have little tax advantage if you bought a home
and reaped the deductions for interest and taxes, versus taking the
standard deduction. There are too many unknowns for me to call that
one, although all things being equal, I would tend to favor the
home purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In a previous column, there was no factual basis for your
statement: ``I agree, it is risky to buy funds at banks, where the
advisor sometimes appears to know little more than the customer.''
This is unfounded, untrue, insulting, inaccurate, and so on. As an
investment representative at a bank, this undeserved broadside
appalls me. I have invested a great deal of time and money to
become as well informed as I can on the subject of investing and
mutual funds, specifically. I am currently working toward the
Chartered Mutual Fund Counselor designation. In March, I spent a
day in Chicago taking a Morningstar class in Analysis and Fund
Selection. Many people who have no interest, desire, or time for
managing their own investments are best served by an investment
adviser _ an honest, knowledgeable, component professional who is
just as likely to be found at a community bank as anywhere else.
Retract your insult.
</P>
<P>
   P.A., Middleton, Wis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm sorry to have given offense, but in the nearly 10 years I
have been taking questions from readers, the very heavy
preponderance of writers who had bought a fund with very little or
no idea of what they had purchased had done so at a bank. I'm sure
there are bankers who deal with mutual funds who are well informed,
talented, and give excellent service. However, their clients do not
tend to write to me. Those who write are usually people who bought
something such as a government bond fund from a bank, and while
they probably heard their adviser say the bonds the fund held were
guaranteed by the government, they had no idea that their
investment could lose value.
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad to hear you are working so hard to give fine service.
If more bank fund representatives were like you, I would get fewer
letters complaining about investments the customers did not
understand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
