<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for
 &UR; THURSDAY, May 4, &LR;  of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (Dateline to kum) _ Developments in the
seizure and reported slaying of U.N. peacekeepers by rebels in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   PANAM103-TRIAL (Camp Zeist, the Netherlands) _ Two Libyans plead
not guilty, accuse Palestinians as trial opens in 1988 bombing of
Pan Am Flight 103. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   EASTEUROPE-BIRTHS (Prague, Czech Republic) _ A United Nations
study finds that the birth rate is plunging in Eastern Europe. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-BRITAIN-MARKETS (London) _ Europe's two biggest stock
markets, London and Frankfurt, agreed on Wednesday to merge in the
first step towards creating a pan-European exchange which should
drive down the cost of trading. The London Stock Exchange and
Frankfurt's Deutsche Boerse also announced a tie-up with the
technology-laden U.S. Nasdaq market, offering up the prospect of an
eventual global market-place for stocks. The merged entity will be
called iX _ standing for International Exchanges _ and will command
53 percent of the traded volume in European equities and 81 percent
of the European market for high-growth shares. (Summary from wires)
By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   with
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-EXCHANGE (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Germany's stock exchange
has quietly amassed clout through acquisitions, new technology and
a readiness to start up new ventures. Much of the credit goes to
its chief executive, Werner G. Seifert, a devoted gourmet and jazz
pianist who was an outsider when he arrived at the exchange in
Frankfurt 1994. For starters, he is Swiss rather than German. Now
50 years old, he had been a partner in Germany at McKinsey &AMP; Co.,
the management consulting firm. And while he had little experience
in the nuts and bolts of securities trading, he had a strong sense
that technology would transform the markets and erode national
boundaries _ particularly in Europe. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   EURO (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The euro falls below $0.90. The
currency has lost more than 20 percent of its value against most
major currencies since its launch in January, 1999. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   BESTFOODS-UNILEVER (Undated) _ Following Unilever's spurned $18
billion offer for Bestfoods. By Constance L. Hays. (With reporting
from London by Andrew Ross Sorkin.)
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly Economic Scene column. By J.
Bradford DeLong. (J. Bradford DeLong is a professor of economics at
the University of California at Berkeley and co-editor of The
Journal of Economic Perspectives.)
</P>
