r e BC-FAIRCHILD-KUKI-GALLMA     05-03 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRCHILD-KUKI-GALLMANN-INTERVIEW-HOLLYWOOD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUKI'S FORTUNE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 By JULIE L. BELCOVE  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The first question Kuki Gallmann asks when she learns I have
seen ``I Dreamed of Africa,'' the Kim Basinger movie based on
Gallmann's best-selling memoir, is, ``Do you think people will want
to come to Africa?''
</P>
<P>
   For Gallmann, Italian by birth, Kenyan by choice, it is really
the only question.
</P>
<P>
   When she sat down to write ``I Dreamed of Africa,'' she had no
intention of seeing her story turned into a big-budget Hollywood
movie. She didn't even plan to have it published. She says she
simply needed to ``exorcise my ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the United States go a lot to psychoanalysts, and
they talk,'' Gallmann says over lunch in an Italian cafe near her
London flat. ``I also talk _ all Italians talk _ but in general,
the empty page is my psychoanalyst.''
</P>
<P>
   She filled the pages of the book with lyrical memories of
recovering from a devastating car accident in Venice _ doctors had
held out little hope she'd walk again _ and beginning life anew in
Kenya with her young son, Emanuele, and second husband, Paolo, in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   There, in the Laikipia region, they bought the Ol Ari Nyiro
ranch and struggled to make it viable. But the deeper she fell in
love with Africa, the more it seemed to extract from her as
payment.
</P>
<P>
   First, Paolo was killed in a car accident driving back from
Mombasa with a cradle for their unborn daughter. Three years later,
Emanuele, a passionate collector and scholar of snakes, was bitten
by one of his puff adders and died in Gallmann's arms. He was only
17, due to leave shortly for college in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Even after her second loss, Gallmann gave no thought to
returning to the comforts of Italy. She raised her daughter, Sveva,
on the ranch and started a foundation in memory of Paolo and
Emanuele.
</P>
<P>
   Gallmann agreed to publish the memoir only after a friend
convinced her it could help other parents whose children had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the only mother who has lost a son,'' she says.
``Children die all the time everywhere. But I wanted to transform
something negative, something immensely sad, because Emanuele was a
very intelligent, gifted, extraordinary human being. I wanted to
make sure his passing was not in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she resisted offers to sell the film rights. Gallmann
dreaded seeing the tragedies of her life played out on screen _ and
since she typically sees movies only on airplanes, she also had
doubts about the medium itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said no to everybody because there is a different dignity
about something written that you read alone,'' she says, ``as
opposed to something on the big screen that you share with people
chewing gum and eating peanuts.''
</P>
<P>
   But then friends introduced her to Stanley Jaffe, the producer
of ``Kramer vs. Kramer'' and ``Fatal Attraction.'' Jaffe had read
her book after a year of prodding from his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded like it was going to be _ not in a pejorative or
sexist sense _ more for a woman,'' Jaffe recalls. ``But I got to
the last eulogy, and I was awash in tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallmann decided to let Jaffe make the movie, with Hugh Hudson
(``Chariots of Fire'') directing, but not without trepidation. When
we first meet, in the fall of 1998, filming is under way, and
Gallmann is clearly uneasy. Most of the movie is being shot in
