from Laikipia as Sweden is from Spain.''
</P>
<P>
   She regrets not trying to write the screenplay herself and
worries about the star, Kim Basinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way: If I'd been given the task of interpreting
you in a movie, I would have come and met you,'' Gallmann says. ``I
would have made it my business.''
</P>
<P>
   A little more than a year later, however, she is somewhat
relieved after attending a private screening with her daughter,
saying Basinger ``did a very good job.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie, though, was still difficult to watch, particularly
the first scene in which the teen-aged Emanuele appears, because
the actor bears such a striking resemblance to her son.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very emotional,'' she recalls. ``We cried for two
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Larry Ashmead, executive editor and vice president of
HarperCollins, says, Gallmann is not a ``weeping widow.'' For one
thing, she has too much work to do. HarperCollins is publishing her
latest book, ``African Nights,'' a collection of autobiographical
