<SLUG> BC-EXCHANGE-MERGER-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON, GERMAN EXCHANGES TO MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN MAX   
 TheStreet.com   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Technology stocks from Frankfurt's Deutsche Borse and blue-chips
on the London Stock Exchange will trade under one roof in London as
part of a merger between the two exchanges announced Wednesday,
with the Nasdaq stock exchange forming an alliance with the merged
entity.
</P>
<P>
   The new exchange, to be called the iX, will open at 9 p.m EDT
after operations are under way, allowing Europeans to trade Nasdaq
stocks by day and Americans to trade stocks listed only on the
German and London exchanges by night. The new market will account
for 81 percent of Europe's growth market.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the European exchanges will own 50 percent of the new
entity, according to a statement from the London exchange. Don
Cruikshank, LSE's chief executive, will become the chairman of iX.
His German counterpart, Werner Seifert, will become the chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   The London-Frankfurt agreement is subject to approval by British
and German regulators, and by stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   The merger brings to a climax two years of fitful efforts by the
London and Frankfurt exchanges to combine.
</P>
<P>
   The combination spurs a shift toward around-the-clock trading,
and rivals the New York Stock Exchange, which has been reluctant to
accommodate Nasdaq stocks among its own issues.
</P>
<P>
   The iX market, however, will move quickly to capitalize on the
stalemate between the top two U.S. markets and cross-list Nasdaq
issues on the new exchange, Cruikshank told CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   The combined volume between the three exchanges could push it
past the volume on the NYSE, making it the world's largest bourse.
The compound annual growth of trading in stocks on the two
exchanges taken together is more than 35 percent over the past four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Executives behind the new exchange are also talking with
representatives from the Milan and Madrid exchanges about joining
the iX, according to a statement from the LSE.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Zarb, chief executive officer of Nasdaq, in a
teleconference from London, said, ``We have no pre-conditions as to
how far this can go, and will go, with respect to the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the IPO engine of choice for Europe,'' Zarb said.
</P>
<P>
   In the teleconference, Zarb would not answer a question as to
whether the NYSE will eventually be brought into the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert said in a statement that all market participants will
benefit from lower spreads due to higher liquidity. He added that
smaller trading firms will benefit from the trading system's remote
access and larger retail investors will have a wider choice of
products to trade.
</P>
<P>
   The new European exchange, to be headquartered in London but
operated in Frankfurt, will use the German trading system Xetra.
The board of directors will include up to 12 members will equal
representation from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb said the link with Nasdaq should come early next year,
after the LSE and Deutsche Borse make their connection.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
