<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4264 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CHINA-TRADE-TEXAS-HNS     05-03 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHITE HOUSE TO LOBBY TEXAS DEMOCRATS ON CHINA TRADE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GARY MARTIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Commerce Secretary William Daley is headed to Texas
Friday to urge congressional Democrats to rebuff organized labor
and vote to normalize trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Daley is scheduled to be in Houston, McAllen and San Antonio as
the battle over the China trade bill heats up in the House of
Representatives, making it one of the most contentious votes since
the North American Free Trade Agreement in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite some optimistic press accounts, this is going to be a
tough vote,'' Daley told business leaders attending the Information
Technology Association of America's 5th annual policy summit on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to approve the bill granting China
permanent trade relations.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders and the Clinton administration have banded
together to push the bill through the House, where it is expected
to face stiff opposition when it comes to the floor for a vote on
May 22.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt, D-Mo., has announced
his opposition, citing human rights abuses by the Chinese
government and the denial of religious freedom to its people.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the U.S. Commission on International
Religious Freedom, a bipartisan and multifaith organization, urged
Congress to reject permanent trading privileges with China, joining
environmentalists and labor organizations in opposition to the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO President John Sweeney said China ``continues to
flagrantly violate the human rights and religious freedoms of its
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley told business leaders that opening up China to
American-made goods will give the U.S. government more leverage on
human and religious rights issues, in addition to boosting sales of
U.S. exports.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the United States has a $69 billion trade deficit
with China, ``because our market is open, and theirs is not.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, China will become the second largest market for
personal computers. Daley said the Asian country continues to
expand wireless communication. ``It is like they add a new Baby
Bell every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles A. Gonzalez, D-Texas, said Texas companies such as
SBC Telecommunications Inc. would prosper by normalizing trade
relations with China, possibly creating more jobs in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think in terms of SBC,'' said Gonzalez, who represents
the San Antonio area where SBC is based. He is being lobbied by
union leaders trying to reverse his position and oppose the trade
bill.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to soothe ruffled feathers, Gonzalez has asked
Daley to meet with San Antonio labor leaders Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Daley will meet with business leaders at McAllen
Country Club in the Rio Grande Valley on the request of Rep. Ruben
Hinojosa, a Democrat from Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   Hinojosa remains undecided despite a trip to China last week
with Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   Hinojosa has assembled Rio Grande Valley elected officials,
business leaders and professors with the University of Texas Pan
American in Edinburg for the meeting with Daley, who is expected to
announce an initiative that could boost high-technology development
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Daley will be joined by Mayor Lee Brown in Houston where he is
scheduled to speak to the Asia Society at a noon luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade is always a tough vote for Democrats,'' said Debra
Silimeo, a Commerce Department spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   In South Texas, only Rep. Ciro Rodriguez, a Democrat from San
Antonio, has come out in opposition to the trade measure, which
would grant permanent trade privileges to China as it enters the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   China has agreed to open its markets to enter the WTO, but
American businesses and farmers will benefit only if Congress
approves permanent normal trading relations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Noting his agricultural district, Rodriguez said he is
``concerned that American businesses will be subject to a flood of
price-busting Chinese imports.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez noted that China is among the largest exporters of
livestock, corn, cotton and peanuts, products that would compete
against those grown in Wilson and Atascosa counties, as well as
those in the Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that American businesses will be subject to a
flood of price-busting Chinese imports,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not hastily grant a permanent contract to China,
without first ensuring the security of our small entrepreneurs. We
can't afford it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rep. Solomon Ortiz, a Democrat from Corpus Christi,
is leaning in favor of the trade measure after taking a tour of
China with private business groups involved with the Port of Corpus
Christi.
</P>
</TEXT>
