<HEADLINE>
NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE ADVISORY
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special Features. For
purchase information, see end of text.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following is a menu for New America News Service stories
that are for release Fri., April 28, 2000, or anytime thereafter:
</P>
<P>
   PLEASE NOTE: THE FOLLOWING ARTICLE MOVED EARLIER TODAY.
</P>
<P>
   FORWARD MARCH IN THE PARADE FOR GAY CIVIL RIGHTS. This weekend,
hundreds of thousands of gay, lesbian, bisexual and transgender
people will arrive in the nation's capital for the Millennium March
for Equality, a three-day celebration and civil-rights rally.
``It's history in the making,'' writes columnist Chuck Colbert, who
says the governor of Vermont's recent signing of the same-sex civil
union bill will spotlight a featured weekend event _ a mass wedding
of same-sex couples that will take place at the Lincoln Memorial.
(slugged: BC-NEW-AMERICA-MILLENNIUM-MARCH-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   WIRED GENERATION: HISPANICS ONLINE. Polls indicate that
Hispanics are at home in the online market. A recent Hispanic
Business/Zogby International poll found that almost one-half (49
percent) of Hispanics have made an online purchase in the last
three months, compared to 34.7 percent of Anglos, 31.3 percent of
African Americans and 14.9 percent of Asians. Find out why
Hispanics are more likely to spend larger amounts of money and time
on the Web compared to other groups. (slugged:
BC-NEW-AMERICA-HISPANICS-ONLINE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   HOW SOON WE FORGET GREATNESS. ``The people of America are
usually pretty fastidious about celebrating the dates of important
historical happenings,'' writes columnist Tim Giago. One such event
occurred in South Dakota 10 years ago, but one would never know it
happened. In 1990, Gov. George Mickelson (R-S.D.) spearheaded the
effort to pass a proclamation making 1990 ``The Year of
Reconciliation'' _ a year in which Native Americans and whites come
together to resolve their differences. Mickelson also got the
state's legislators to pass a bill making Oct. 12 _ Columbus Day in
the rest of America _ Native American Day in South Dakota. Now,
nearly nothing is reported to commemorate this historic event.
``Perhaps 1990 was not the year, and perhaps the races were not
ready to come to the table as friends,'' Giago writes. And racism
between whites and Indians continues to grow. (slugged:
BC-NEW-AMERICA-TRIBUTE-TO-GOV-MICKELSON-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   WE SEE NO EVIDENCE, BUT STILL HE WAITS. Imagine being in your
home eating breakfast with your family, when U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service authorities charge in, handcuff you in front
of your wife and children and drag you off to an unspecified
location _ all without charging you with a crime. Such an arrest
occurred in Tampa on May 19, 1997. The victim: Palestinian refugee
Mazen Al-Najjar, then a 40-year-old professor at the University of
South Florida in Tampa. The ``crime'': ``secret evidence'' that
allegedly connects him with Palestine Islamic Jihad, a notorious
terrorist organization in the Middle East. This is his story, as
reported by columnist Bill Maxwell.
</P>
