<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV17-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV17  
 (FOR USE WEDNESDAY, MAY 17, 2000, AND THEREAFTER)  
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: MAPLE YOGURT DIP FOR STRAWBERRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by 20-MINUTE-MENUS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Giving new ideas to cooks for using strawberries is a rite of
spring. Certain recipes come immediately to mind, like strawberry
short cake. And if I could think of a way to serve strawberry
shortcake in the context of low-calorie dishes, believe me I would.
</P>
<P>
   Of course you could reduce the fat by using angel food cake
instead of biscuits. You could use yogurt instead of whipped cream.
But would this be shortcake? Better to have small pieces of the
real thing once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime you don't want to miss strawberries, and if you
are picking them yourself from your own garden or a nearby farm
there isn't much you have to do to them after they are washed. When
you tire of that here are a number of other suggestions that take
very little effort and provide great rewards.
</P>
<P>
   When picking or buying strawberries choose those with the least
amount of white at the stem, preferably none at all. The white is a
sign of an unripe berry.
</P>
<P>
   Next to eating them out of hand, strawberries can be sliced and
topped just before sitting down for dinner with orange liqueur.
Such a mixture is even better over lemon sorbet.
</P>
<P>
   The maple yogurt dip for strawberries is excellent with peaches
and berries. The sweet ricotta looks handsome when mixed with cut
up peaches and spooned into a tall slender glasses. The raspberry
puree is not only handsome but delicious with blueberries.
</P>
<P>
   MAPLE YOGURT DIP FOR STRAWBERRIES
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plain nonfat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated orange rind
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon grated lime rind
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 quart strawberries, sweetened with sugar, if necessary, up to
2 tablespoons
</P>
<P>
   1. Mix all the ingredients until well blended and chill.
</P>
<P>
   2. Wash berries, trim and slice; mix with sugar if berries need
to be sweetened.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Plain nonfat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   Orange
</P>
<P>
   Maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   Sugar
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   Lime
</P>
<P>
   1 quart strawberries
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 115 calories, less than 1/2
gram fat; no saturated fat, 1 milligram cholesterol, 45 milligrams
sodium, 5 grams protein, 25 grams carbohydrate, 3.5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SWEET RICOTTA
</P>
<P>
   2 cups skim milk ricotta
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoon milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Grand Marnier
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely diced candied ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 quarts strawberries, sweetened with sugar if necessary _
perhaps 1 or 2 tablespoons.
</P>
<P>
   1. Mix together the ricotta, milk, Grand Marnier and ginger
until well blended. Add more milk if necessary for desired
consistency to top berries. Use immediately or chill, up to one
day, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   2. Wash, dry and trim berries. Slice thinly. Add sugar, if
necessary, to sweeten berries. Refrigerate up to a day or use
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Milk
</P>
<P>
   Grand Marnier or other orange liqueur
</P>
<P>
   Sugar
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   Skim milk ricotta
</P>
<P>
   Candied ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 quarts strawberries
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 170 calories, 7 grams fat, 4
grams saturated fat, 25 milligrams cholesterol, 105 milligrams
sodium, 10 grams protein, 15 grams carbohydrate, 3.4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   RASPBERRY PUREE
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pint raspberries
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberries
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash and dry raspberries; puree in food processor or blender.
Mix with 2 tablespoons sugar and chill a few hours if desired.
</P>
<P>
   2. Wash, trim and quarter strawberries and mix with lime juice.
Chill if desired.
</P>
<P>
   3. To serve, top the strawberries with the raspberry puree.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pint raspberries
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberries
</P>
<P>
   Lime
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 115 calories, 16 grams fat, 1
gram fat, no saturated fat, no cholesterol, 2 milligrams sodium,
less than 2 grams protein, 30 grams carbohydrate, 7.6 grams fiber.
</P>
