<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCHANGE-MERGER-1STD-WRITETHRU-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ ENTERS ALLIANCE WITH LONDON, GERMAN EXCHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, updates throughout)  
 By KEVIN MAX   
 TheStreet.com   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nasdaq market made a large stride Wednesday in the direction
of building a global unified trading place after entering an
alliance with the London and Frankfurt exchanges to provide the
single European source for high-growth stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks from Frankfurt's Deutsche Boerse and
blue-chips on the London Stock Exchange will trade on a new
exchange. The headquarters will be in London with operations in
Frankfurt and include the aspirations of the fast-growing Nasdaq
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The new exchange, to be called the iX, will open at 9 p.m New
York time after operations are under way. The iX will allow
Europeans to trade Nasdaq stocks by day and Americans to trade tech
stocks listed only on the German exchange and blue-chip stocks on
the London exchange by night. The new market will account for 81
percent of Europe's growth market.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the European exchanges will own 50% of the new entity,
according to a statement from the London exchange. Don Cruikshank,
LSE's chief executive, will become the chairman of iX. His German
counterpart, Werner Seifert, will become the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The London-Frankfurt agreement is subject to approval by British
and German regulators, and by stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   The merger brings to a climax two years of fitful efforts by the
London and Frankfurt exchanges to combine.
</P>
<P>
   The combination spurs a shift toward around-the-clock trading,
and rivals the New York Stock Exchange, which has been reluctant to
accommodate Nasdaq stocks among its own issues.
</P>
<P>
   The iX market, however, will move quickly to capitalize on the
stalemate between the top two U.S. markets and cross-list Nasdaq
issues on the new exchange, Cruikshank told CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   The volume and liquidity on the new exchange will dwarf that of
the NYSE, and could force the Big Board to reconsider its position
as an isolated market while the Nasdaq is opening new markets
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq currently trades more than twice the number of shares
a day that the NYSE does.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the NYSE said: ``We're continuing to talk to
everyone.'' But he declined to comment on any initiatives in
Europe. ``Our chairman has talked about creating an alliance in the
Americas, including Central, South and North America,'' he
continued.
</P>
<P>
   Also, more companies coming public in initial public offering
are boosting the growth rate of the Nasdaq while the NYSE brought
in a third less new companies in 1999 than the previous year.
Notably, NYSE's income has been contracting while the growth rate
of Nasdaq and its European partners has been growing.
</P>
<P>
   Executives behind the new exchange are also talking with
representatives from the Milan and Madrid exchanges about joining
the iX, according to a statement from the LSE.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Zarb, chief executive officer of Nasdaq, in a
teleconference from London, said, ``We have no preconditions as to
how far this can go, and will go, with respect to the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the IPO engine of choice for Europe,'' Zarb said.
</P>
<P>
   In the teleconference, Zarb would not answer a question as to
whether the NYSE will eventually be brought into the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Under current conditions, individual investors in the U.S.
currently have to either find a brokerage firm with access to
European markets, or take the less-direct route of buying a mutual
fund to own shares of Frankfurt- and London-listed stocks. European
investors face the same obstacles when investing in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Under the alliance, U.S. investors will be able to trade these
in the same way that they can now trade (CSCO:Nasdaq) or Amazon
(AMXN:Nasdaq). European investors will have local access all of the
companies listed on Nasdaq as well.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the deal will eventually hold all European
companies listed on the U.S. exchange to the American accounting
and financial data reporting standards, providing investors with
more information about the companies.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert said in a statement that all market participants will
benefit from lower spreads due to higher liquidity. He added that
smaller trading firms will benefit from the trading system's remote
access and larger retail investors will have a wider choice of
products to trade.
</P>
<P>
   The new European exchange, to be headquartered in London but
operated in Frankfurt, will use the German trading system Xetra.
The board of directors will include up to 12 members will equal
representation from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb said the link with Nasdaq should come early next year,
after the LSE and Deutsche Borse make their connection.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
