<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIBLE BELONGS TO ALL, WRITER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA AND MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For seven years, Amy Dockser Marcus was a foreign correspondent
based in Israel writing stories from one of the world's most
strife-torn regions.
</P>
<P>
   And few things stirred more passion than debates touching on the
Bible. In Israel, as Marcus quickly discovered, the Bible often is
used to divide people _ Israelis from non-Israelis to be sure, but
also Israelis from each other.
</P>
<P>
   There were instances when Israel's conservative religious
parties threatened to bring down the ruling government because of
controversies involving the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Her concern over what she perceived to be a near monopoly of
religious opinion is one reason Marcus wrote a recently released
book, ``The View from Nebo: How Archaeology is Rewriting the Bible
and Reshaping the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted people to believe that the Bible belonged to them,''
said Marcus, who covered the Middle East for The Wall Street
Journal from 1991 to 1998 and is now a senior writer at Money
Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like the idea that people might have to apologize for
using the Bible in a way that was not popular,'' added Marcus. ``I
feel the Bible is filled with fabulous stories and it is an
incredible heritage. But it doesn't belong to one people. It
belongs to everyone. I felt that the right to read the Bible and
see what you want in it and interpret it the way you want is
something worth fighting for.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaving together science, politics, history, and Biblical
scholarship, Marcus analyzes what insights modern archeology can
provide on some of the stories of the Old Testament. In some cases,
contemporary science buttresses what the Old Testament chronicles
and in other instances disputes the biblical record.
</P>
<P>
   And in a land where competing biblical claims have been the
cause of so much bloodshed, Marcus also wanted to underscore the
evidence archeology provides suggesting that the people living in
the biblical period had more things in common than is generally
believed.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Marcus notes, it wasn't just the Israelites who did
not eat pork, but all the different people who populated the region
during ancient times.
</P>
<P>
   ``What seems to emerge from the archeological record is that
there was a lot of common ground between Israel and her neighbors
in artistic tradition, commercial trade back and forth, and
religious practices,'' Marcus said. ``I thought if people could get
more exposure to this other history, this fuller history, knowing
that there was a lot of cultural exchange, it would give them a
different perspective on how the Bible is used in a contemporary
political context and what the potential might be for that.''
</P>
<P>
   While archeological digs in the Middle East have been occurring
for more than a century, Marcus says recent technological
advancements have made it possible for researchers to more
accurately assess historical evidence _ and not always in ways that
please biblical defenders.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Exodus story, one of the central moments in the
story of the Jewish people commemorated every year during Passover,
has come under scrutiny because of what archeologists have found.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence found in Egypt suggests that there might have been no
Israelites kept as slaves during the period coinciding with the
Exodus saga. The belief passed on through generations that it was
Israelite slaves who built the pyramids has been strongly
challenged by scientists who say sites unearthed around the
pyramids shows they were not built by slaves but by skilled
crafstmen and laborers compensated for their work, Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, she points out, there is no evidence that the Jews spent
40 years wandering in the desert as the Bible describes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say that it could have been a small group of
Israeli slaves that escaped and it became a part of our national
myth just like the pilgrims and the Mayflower are part of our
national myth,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   The point, according to Marcus, is not what is true or not true
in the Bible. ``The fact is that these biblical stories are an
ancient tradition that has kept together as a group for thousands
of years,'' she said. ``That's what's important.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Marcus said, the authors of the Bible did not mean it to
become a fossilized document.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost from the moment the Bible was written down, people were
trying to change it,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bible writers believed it was a living document. So
archeologists and even we who read the Bible who have our own
interpretation are part of an ancient tradition of reinterpreting
the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holiday of the Week
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Question of the Week
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My question is about Mormons and their no-caffeine,
no-alcohol rule. Are they allowed decaffeinated beverages? What
about food cooked with wine? And how come Donny and Marie Osmond on
their show eat chocolate, which contains caffeine?
</P>
<P>
   - J.B.P., Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Mormons, officially known as The Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints, do not avoid caffeine in all its forms, but are
supposed to avoid coffee and tea.
</P>
<P>
   The Mormon dietary restrictions stem from the Word of Wisdom, a
health code written in 1833 by church founder Joseph Smith. That
code bars the consumption of tobacco, ``wine or strong drink,''
which is understood to mean liquor, and ``hot drink,'' which is
understood to mean coffee or tea. Many Mormons also avoid the
consumption of caffeinated colas.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sue Schmidt, regional public affairs director for
the church, observant Mormons do not drink decaffeinated coffee or
tea. However, she said, there is no prohibition against food cooked
with small amounts of alcohol, or against chocolate, which contains
caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Events of the Week
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two major conferences over the next 10 days will examine the
changing role of women in the world of faith. Both conferences are
open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard Divinity School, conferees will examine how the
rising number of women in ministry are transforming religious
institutions. ``Claiming Power, Authority, and Passion'' runs from
Monday through Wednesday. ($50, 617-496-2943).
</P>
<P>
   At Hebrew College, conferees will examine the changing roles of
women within Christianity, Islam, and Judaism. ``Women, Traditions,
and Change'' runs May 7 and 8. ($50, 617-278-4974).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Spiritual Life welcomes questions about religion and
suggestions for stories by mail to Religion News, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378, or by e-mail to religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
