<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNALISM IN JEOPARDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the more memorable letters that have fluttered into this
corner's mailbox was a handwritten note perhaps a quarter-century
back, a real ink-on-paper-none-of-your-cheezy-ballpoints-here
Palmer Penmanship missive from the late speaker of the US House,
John W. McCormack.
</P>
<P>
   I forget just what column sparked his writing, but what stands
out was the generalization from this shrewd old politician who'd
seen a lot of the wicked ways in which the world works: ``The
fabric of civilization is very thin,'' he cautioned, ``and easily
rent, so all in public life, press as well as politics, had best
tread warily, and don't push the poor too hard.'' That sober
warning recurs to me often, most recently this week on the occasion
of the convening of the 50th annual conclave of the International
Press Institute in Boston, where 500 publishers, poobahs, editors,
and assorted spear carriers.
</P>
<P>
   At speeches and panels much was made of the fluidity of
post-Cold War geography, the oppositional centrifugal and
centripetal forces spun off by globalization, and the evolving
roles of the news media in an era of disorienting technological
change.
</P>
<P>
   What is obvious to bosses of the planet's media and to
politicians whose agendas they frame, advance, retard, or condemn
is the interlocking nature of government and media. What's less
obvious to the great masses of news consumers is the parlous nature
of root-out-the-secrets journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The IPI keeps track of the relentless repression of journalists
in many of the world's countries, some as prosperous as Ireland,
some as poor as the most barren African outback. In just the past
10 years, 458 reporters, editors, or news technicians have been
murdered in the course of their work _ almost as many victims over
a decade as total delegates in the hall at one of the Press
Institute's plenary sessions.
</P>
<P>
   If your idea of a journalist is some ``hammy blowhard'' (Tom
Shales's un-toppable description of a certain ABC ``personality'')
spouting banalties with practiced self-assurance, you might want to
broaden the definition to include some of the 65 journalists and 21
support staff who were killed on duty last year alone or the 87
working reporters imprisoned last year or the 118 confined the year
before. They are paying the dues for all of us who pontificate
profitably from the safety of journalistic sinecures. In this
country, the opinion makers worry more about their 401(k) plans
than the sudden and unwelcome appearance in the driver's side
window of an AK-47 pointed by a trigger-happy teenager.
</P>
<P>
   With media bosses from all over the world dipping into canapes
and cocktails after weighty words from the likes of Vice President
Gore, Henry Kissinger, Tom Brokaw, and the rest, there was no
shortage of shop talk about the journalist job to be done in the
age of AIDS and HIV, famine and ethnic cleansing, the Internet and
environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
   The important things can never get done without ground being
prepared by sustained media coverage of a high order of accuracy
and reliability. Nothing will get set right without the commitment,
funding, and leadership that can be marshaled only by explanation
and debate in the media.
</P>
<P>
   The map is blotched in places by the blood spilt in precincts
where the papers and broadcast outlets are in the hands of despotic
regimes or proprietors. The Russian election was a case study in
the character assassination of rivals to the favored candidate. In
the late, lamented Yugoslavia we have seen a decade's worth of
death and destruction fomented, in large measure, by villainous
propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   A former colleague of mine at Oxford's Reuter Foundation told of
how Bosnia fell into the jaws of the dogs of war when prominent
journalists succumbed to the temptation to savage rival ethnic
groups, to become ``a soldier with a typewriter . . . a soldier
with a microphone.''
</P>
<P>
   China's saber-rattling over Taiwan, nuclear-tipped braggadocio
in Pakistan and India, the impotence of some African regimes in
confronting AIDS, the plundering of the Southern Hemisphere's rain
forests, all these high-risk behaviors flourish in the absence or
weakness of journalism.
</P>
<P>
   When the news editor of his family newspaper in Colombia,
Francisco Santos of Bogota's El Tiempo, is driven out of the
country by repeated threats on his life, that tells me, if not
Santos, that his country is not ready for prime-time US aid. The
overlapping drug and guerrilla warfare raging there for 36 years
left seven Colombian journalists killed last year alone, 24
kidnapped, and 15 forced to flee for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, our problem is too much influence, not too
little. We have a terrible problem with credibility. We careen from
the stupefying to the soporific with the flip of a page, remote, or
mouse. And our audiences keep tuning out. You can track the decline
of serious TV network news from abroad as a mirror image graph of
the wild popularity of sadistic and degrading professional
wrestling, a tale of less bread and more circuses, please.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
