<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOOM OFF THE ROSES FOR TRAINER BAFFERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Things are quieter around trainer Bob
Baffert's barn than they have been during previous Kentucky Derby
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Baffert earned the limelight by saddling Silver Charm
to victory in the Derby at 4-1. The following year, having become
the darling of the media, he won the Rose Run again, as Real Quiet
scored at 8-1. Last year, he sent out the entry of Excellent
Meeting and General Challenge, which was favored at 9-2. However,
both had troubled trips and wound up off the board.
</P>
<P>
   This time, with only long shot Captain Steve, Baffert is on the
edge of the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the love?'' said Baffert, ever quick with a quip, when
he saw a smaller-than-usual media contingent approach Tuesday
morning, after Captain Steve worked 5 furlongs in :59 2/5 over the
Churchill Downs strip.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert then turned serious and put matters into perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Captain Steve is getting the treatment he should be
getting,'' he said. ``But he's got a chance. I've put him in
position to win the race, but he's got to get it done. Fusaichi
Pegasus is so talented, he can make a mistake and still get there.
Captain Steve has to get over the track without a straw in his
path. He just needs a lot of luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get him any more prepared. I feel good about it. I
can sleep at night. But we still have to worry about the draw.
That's the magic pill.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve, a son of Fly So Free, out of a Vice Regent mare,
was a relatively modest yearling, costing $70,000. By contract,
Fusaichi Pegusus is a $4 million yearling. Captain Steve has raced
three times this year, and been third each time. But he has one big
thing in his favor: He likes this track.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Captain Steve won the Kentucky Jockey Club at
Churchill, and he preceded Tuesday's eye-catching move with two
other superior workouts, going 4 furlongs in :47 1/5 over a muddy
surface April 17, the best of 28 horses who worked that distance
that day, and zipping 5 panels in :59 4/5 April 22. Also, Captain
Steve, who has raced with blinkers in his last eight starts, worked
without them Tuesday and will race without them in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work went great,'' said Baffert. ``It was the last major
hurdle. This is the workout that tips you off. He's still doing
great. He's more relaxed; he's much better with no blinkers. He was
getting hot behind the gate with blinkers on. Now, we'll let him
look around. I don't know if he's good enough to win, but he's fit
and ready, and he'll have no trouble with a mile and one-quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 15-1. There are some nice horses here, horses who have
accomplished more. He's earned over $900,000 but he hasn't won this
year. This is the first Derby I've been involved in where there is
so much depth. Before, there were two or three horses to worry
about. This field has talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Captain Steve is different from Silver Charm. Silver Charm was
a gritty, gutsy horse. He liked to duke it out. Captain Steve is
more like Real Quiet, a green horse who is finding his best stride.
Whether he's as good as either of them, it's hard to say. But he's
won as much money as they had at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Robby Albarado, a fixture in Kentucky racing, will ride Captain
Steve, who is owned by Mike Pegram. Pegram is the laidback
fast-food magnate (he owns 18 McDonald's franchises in the Seattle
area) who also owned Real Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike is a relaxed guy,'' said Baffert. ``He doesn't worry
about what I do with these horses. It's hard enough to worry about
the horses without having to worry about the owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was time for more humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media makes the favorites in the Derby, and a lot of them
are false,'' Baffert said. ``You guys are bad handicappers. My
greatest fear in life used to be not having good horses. Now, it's
the media.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
