<SLUG> BC-WOM-FOOTBALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S FIRST AND 10 FOR WOMEN'S PROFESSIONAL FOOTBALL LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans have embraced the idea of women playing soccer;
they've gotten used to women playing basketball; they've warmed up
to the sight of women playing ice hockey.
</P>
<P>
   But women playing football, wearing pads and tackling each
other? The sport doesn't make it in the NCAA, and women only
grudgingly are allowed to play on some Pop Warner and high school
teams. Flag football is acceptable for the fair sex, and so is
rugby, but tackle football? Give me a break, the naysayers cry.
</P>
<P>
   For the past year, though, enough men and women have ignored
that cry to plow ahead and form a national Women's Professional
Football League.
</P>
<P>
   This past winter the league had a trial run of six games, with
two teams in the Midwest and a team put together by women in New
York. The trial seemed to work; the league now has 14 teams,
including the New England Storm. Tryouts begin later this month,
team camps open in September, and the season starts Oct. 14, with
games every Saturday until the championship game on Feb. 4. The
all-star game will be Feb. 17 in Miami's Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   One of the organizers of the WPFL used to play for the Minnesota
Vikings and the San Diego Chargers, another promotes minor league
football, and a coach of one of the teams used to play for the Jets
and the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Did someone ask if these women are serious?
</P>
<P>
   The stories of commitment include women who work the sport into
their schedules as doctors, lawyers, police officers, and
housewives.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Brook, 42, left her husband and two children every week
last fall to drive six hours from Rochester to Long Island to train
with the Sharks. Kim Ketchum, who turned 18 last August, said
goodbye to her home in San Diego to fly to Minneapolis to play with
the Minnesota Vixens. Jennifer Blum, a first-year student at
Western New England School of Law in Springfield, Mass., spent her
first semester driving to Long Island every weekend to train with
the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the others, Blum doesn't rant about Title IX, or
moan about the lack of opportunity for women in sports as her
motivation for doing this. In fact, she's simplistic about her
desire to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole life I always wanted to be a football player,'' Blum
said.
</P>
<P>
   This was her chance.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Korpacz, a lawyer from Providence, R.I., didn't play in
the fledgling league last year, but is now one of the general
managers as head of the New England Storm. She has one friend as
her assistant and another as the team's graphic designer. They've
decided on the team's logo, and the uniform colors (``red, white,
and blue, like the Patriots''), but Korpacz is still on the lookout
for a field, and is interviewing potential coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Korpacz said she thinks contact football is a natural
progression for women who play flag football, the club sport in
which tearing off a flag substitutes for tackling. It should also
attract women who play rugby, do martial arts, or run track, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another level of sports that women can go to to
display their talents, and I have a feeling it will fill the
void,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who play in my flag football league, you don't know
exactly why you want to play, but you know that I'm good at this,
I'm good at catching the ball, handling the ball, running, doing
plays,'' she said. ``So the next logical thing would be to try out
for the league.''
</P>
<P>
   And Korpacz said she's prepared for the cynics who will wonder
why women want to don helmets and wear pads like the men do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had one negative comment yet, but bring on the
questions,'' she said. ``If people have questions or want to
trivialize it, that's fine; they have their reasons. But I think
the time is now, and women should be given a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter Turner, one of the league's founders, had a couple of
reasons to create the WPFL. One is his 15 years of experience with
World Wide Sports, a Minnesota-based organization that promotes
minor league football and college all-star games. The other is his
16-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago she would have had no choice,'' Turner said.
``Now she can be a doctor, lawyer, or a football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe in her spare time she can be a football player,
since the league will pay the women only $100 a game, although the
league will pay for uniforms and travel expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets will range from $5 to $20, and Turner said he hopes to
get between 3,000 and 5,000 people at a game. Each franchise will
have five games, and is expected to sell 1,000 season tickets by
Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But he's optimistic based on the more than 300 women who showed
up for tryouts last fall, and on the ensuing exposure the league
got, with games in Chicago, Minneapolis, Miami, and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phones have been ringing off the hook,'' he said,
acknowledging that curiosity is part of the attraction. ``We know
there's a lot of novelty in it, but we'll capitalize on that. We
feel if people will come to one game, they'll come back for more.''
</P>
<P>
   John Turner, who for eight years played with the Minnesota
Vikings and coached the Minnesota Vixens, is the league's
commissioner. Former Jets player Bobby Jackson coached the New York
Sharks (the collection of flag football players who wanted to
challenge the WFPL), and former Jets and Giants player Lou Piccone
will coach the Rochester Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the women had clashes with the boys when they were
growing up when they tried to horn in on ``their sport.'' The
controversy either inspired them or turned them off of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Blum, 26, said she was such a good soccer player that when she
was 9, a coach asked her to play on the boys' team. But the head of
the league protested, a lawsuit followed (her father is a lawyer),
and Blum lost her desire for soccer even though she won the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is very powerful, but society is very powerful, too,''
said Blum, who got harassing phone calls from men. ``Hey, it was
just soccer, but it ceased to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   She went on to play softball and basketball in high school, and
tried out for the Silver Bullets baseball team. She didn't make it,
so started playing flag football.
</P>
<P>
   Ketchum, a defensive lineman who is 5 feet 6 inches and weighs
190 pounds, grew up playing Pop Warner and high school football in
Oceanside, Calif. It was her grandfather who alerted her of tryouts
for the WPFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wasn't really a tomboy,'' said Ketchum. ``I did have
Barbie dolls and Cabbage Patch kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Korpacz, sounds as if she's working almost as hard on the Storm
as she does with the law firm she started last summer.
</P>
<P>
   She'll announce tryout dates and places on the team's Web site
(www.newenglandstorm.com) on May 15, then invite 80 women to
training camp on Sept. 2, and eventually cut the roster to 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to start somewhere, and if it works it's great, and
if it doesn't work, well, I was still a part of it,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
