<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4302 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES     05-03 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PETERS TAKES THE READER BY STORM IN `THUNDER IN THE SKY' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOBBIE HESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picking up the latest Elizabeth Peters mystery, featuring
archaeologists Amelia Peabody and her husband, Radcliffe Emerson,
is like hearing from old friends and learning of their latest
adventures. And as always, it is pure delight.
</P>
<P>
   In ``He Shall Thunder in the Sky'' (William Morrow, $25, 400
pages), the Emerson clan has returned to Egypt even though war has
broken out in Europe. Emerson is put in charge of the excavations
at the Pyramids at Giza because the German who has supervised the
site for years has been barred from returning to Egypt until the
war is over. The Emersons' son, Ramses, has refused to join the
British army, and he's treated like a coward by most of the Britons
who live in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   Their beloved nephew David has been deported to India because of
his support of the Egyptian nationalist cause. David's wife, Lia,
remains in Britain, awaiting the birth of their first child.
</P>
<P>
   Nefret, the Emersons' beautiful ward, works at a hospital for
women and tries to regain Ramses' trust and love, which she fears
she has lost forever. The Emersons' despicable nephew Percy is, of
course, one of the most respected members of the British general
staff in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   Working hard to maintain his pacifist image, Ramses actually is
impersonating the nationalist leader el Wardini and trying to
discover who is smuggling weapons to the nationalists. Emerson
uncovers an incredible statue that Peabody realizes had to have
been planted by their archenemy, the master criminal Sethos. As
each member of the Emerson family is hiding secrets from the
others, the dangers can only increase for all of them. Sins of the
past only add to their perils.
</P>
<P>
   ``He Shall Thunder in the Sky,'' the 12th in the series,
resolves many unanswered questions from previous books. Fans will
find it hard to put down (if you haven't read this series, begin at
the beginning when Emerson and Peabody first meet). Using witty
dialogue and deft plot devices, Peters instills her protagonists
with strength, high moral character and a deep sense of family.
They may not tell each other ``I love you,'' but each knows how
much he or she is cherished. That adds to the charm that has made
this series so much fun.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I Say Good-Bye.'' By Mary Higgins Clark. Simon &AMP;
Schuster. $26. 332 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Higgins Clark is the undisputed queen of the cozy, the
mystery subgenre ``defined by its light tone and element of fun.''
Her legions of fans won't be disappointed by ``Before I Say
Good-Bye.''
</P>
<P>
   Nell McDermott is a newspaper columnist; granddaughter of
Cornelius ``Mac'' McDermott, one of New York's most beloved former
congressman; and the wife of architect Adam Cauliff, who opposes
her decision to run for her grandfather's House seat.
</P>
<P>
   Nell and Adam quarrel over her decision, and he storms out of
the condominium. Later, his assistant, Winifred Johnson, shows up
at the couple's home to pick up his jacket and briefcase. Nell
senses that something very bad is going to happen. That evening,
during a routine business meeting on his yacht in New York harbor,
an explosion kills Adam and three colleagues _ Johnson, builder Sam
Krause and construction foreman Jimmy Ryan. Peter Lang, a prominent
real estate broker, missed the meeting due to a traffic accident.
</P>
<P>
   Nell is devastated. Encouraged by her Aunt Gert, Nell visits a
medium, who gives her a message from Adam saying not to trust Lang.
Investigators find that the explosion was caused by a bomb. Mac
learns Adam was involved in some shady business practices. Ryan's
wife finds $50,000 hidden in her husband's work room, takes the
money to Nell and asks her to find out where it came from. That
investigation will put Nell in great peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I Say Good-Bye'' is a fast read, with interesting
characters and a strong plot. At first, I didn't think the medium
stuff worked, but the ending won't work without it. Higgins once
again strikes gold.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lion's Game.'' By Nelson DeMille. Warner Books.$26.95. 677
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson DeMille's latest thriller would have been a sure-fire
winner if it had been just 200 pages shorter.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Anti-Terrorist Task Force is waiting for the arrival of
Trans-Continental Flight 175 from Paris. On board is Asad Khalil, a
Libyan terrorist known as the Lion, who is wanted by most Western
governments because of his widespread terrorist activities. About
two hours out of New York, the control tower loses contact with
Flight 175, which remains on course.
</P>
<P>
   When the plane finally lands, crash crews are waiting. When the
plane is boarded, everyone is dead, and the Lion is not among them.
</P>
<P>
   Thus begins a massive hunt for the Lion, led by agents John
Corey and Kate Mayfield. Everyone who comes in contact with the
Lion dies. And it soon becomes apparent that Lion's mission will
wreak havoc across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lion's Game'' is overwritten, which is too bad because
DeMille has a really good plot going. The protagonists are a little
too glib, but the Lion really is a well-drawn character.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4303 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-03 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WRONG OATH FOR THE BOY SCOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Boy Scouts of America is a private club, then Central
Park is Augusta National, the subway is Steinbrenner's skybox,
school lunch is Lutece, and the Lincoln Memorial is Studio 54.
These incongruities have not stopped the Scouts from coveting what
country clubs, luxury boxes, elite restaurants, exclusive beach
resorts, and chic dance clubs share in common: Maitre 'ds. Guards.
Bouncers.
</P>
<P>
   The Scouts want it all. They want to bathe their club in red,
white, and blue strobe lights even as they scrutinize the line
trying to get in, flexing their biceps, cracking their knuckles,
and scowling at unwanted guests. They want to be all-American yet
do not want all Americans. They pledge to ``respect and defend the
rights of all people'' yet have obviously amended their oath to
say, ``I will do my best to do my duty to God and my country . . .
to keep myself physically strong, mentally awake, and morally
straight in order to jack up queer Scouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Boy Scouts of America argued before the Supreme
Court that it has the right to exclude homosexuals. The case
concerns the expulsion a decade ago of James Dale, an Eagle Scout
assistant scoutmaster, from his troop in Monmouth County, N.J.,
after the troop saw an article about him being gay. Dale was a
co-president of a gay rights group at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Supreme Court said the expulsion was wrong
because the scouts are a public accommodation covered by state
antidiscrimination laws. The Boy Scouts of America says it is a
private club that can do what it wants.
</P>
<P>
   To be clear, not every scout troop feels as driven to expunge
gay Scouts and Scoutmasters. Asked what would happen to a Dale in
Boston, Brock Bigsby, executive of the Boston Minuteman Council,
said: ``I can't picture that it would play out the same way. Based
on what I know from the news, we wouldn't have taken any action. We
don't inquire. Frankly, it doesn't even enter into the equation. I
would suspect pretty much that our scouting membership represents a
cross-section of the society as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   But the national organization is so pigheaded it makes you want
to just say, fine, go ahead, be a private club. But then, don't
take money from all the charities that would be nailed to the wall
if they, too, discriminated that way.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, for instance, the 1999 donor list includes the United
Way, Fleet, BankBoston, American Express, Hilton and Marriott
hotels, the Globe, BU, MIT, Northeastern, law firms, labor unions,
and law enforcement agencies, restaurants, real estate and credit
card firms, law enforcement agencies, and telecommunications,
energy and high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   If the Boy Scouts of America say it is a private club, it should
renounce its dependency on the public. In New Jersey, more than 600
public school and law enforcement agencies have ties to the scouts.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 5 million Boy Scouts. Two thirds of Boy Scout
troops are in churches, and two-thirds of the churches that sponsor
units disapprove of homosexuality enough to support the Scouts
against Dale (Mormons, United Methodists, Missouri Synod Lutherans,
and the National Catholic Committee on Scouting).
</P>
<P>
   Church affiliation or not, no one disputes the vast interaction
the scouts have with the public. Despite the dominance of churches,
the American Association of School Administrators says there are
425,000 boys in 12,000 troops in public schools. Law enforcement
and fire departments sponsor 7,000 troops with 132,847 members. The
2001 national Boy Scout Jamboree, which will bring together 37,000
people, will be held on US Army land in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Scouting benefits from government for things as unspoken as
having ponds stocked for fishing trips. More than 90 percent of
police precinct houses in New York City support Explorer scouts.
Half of Newark's schools have scout troops. A brief filed by
several cities on behalf of Dale said, ``Municipal sponsorship is
the result of a conscious decision by the Boy Scouts to solicit
municipalities as their partners in scouting.''
</P>
<P>
   All this suggests we can end this matter very quickly. Give the
Boy Scouts a choice. If they want to remain an all-American club,
drop the suit, reinstate Dale, and follow the scout admonition to
``respect those with ideas and customs that are different from his
own.''
</P>
<P>
   Should the scouts persist in living under a rock, companies,
universities, public schools, and police and fire departments
should rethink their support of the scouts. No one wants it to come
to this, given what the scouts do for a child's sense of
accomplishment and for communities across America.
</P>
<P>
   But neither do sensible people want to be part of a youth group
that teaches reverence on one hand and revulsion on the other. The
scouts would not be what they are without access to public spaces,
places, and institutions. They cannot be allowed, at their own
homophobic convenience, to become the Straight Country Club, Hetero
Head, or the Discrimination Disco. We love scouts for their
bravery. We will love them less as bouncers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
