<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4307 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-GOODWIN-ART-BO     05-03 1447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-GOODWIN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 NEIL GOODWIN SEEKS A FATHER LOST TO THE SIERRA MADRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ When Neil Goodwin was in his early 20s,
helping his mother prepare a book on Apache culture that his father
had been working on before he died, he came across an old scrapbook
containing his father's field notes. ``I remember her saying,
`Here's the dairy of the Mexico trip,' '' the trip Grenville
Goodwin had taken into the Sierra Madre in the 1930s. ``As I read
it, I realized that when he wrote it, he was about the same age as
I was,'' Goodwin said. ``And my first thought was that I wished I
could do this thing, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Goodwin was barely four months old when his father died in
1940, cutting short a pioneering career studying Apache life and
culture in southwestern mountain strongholds. Now, having
established himself as a documentary filmmaker, the 60-year-old
Goodwin has brought his father's studies to completion with the
publication of ``Apache Diaries.'' In the book, Grenville Goodwin's
field notes are interspersed with entries from a journal Neil
Goodwin kept as he retraced his father's trail into the Mexican
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   In preparing the field notes for publication, Goodwin embarked
on a quest to understand the father he never knew. Even now, he
admits to being ``intrigued and puzzled.'' While the parallel
journeys recorded in ``Apache Diaries'' have ``taken me to an
understanding of what his life was,'' said Goodwin, ``I know I will
never know what he was entirely like.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts Grenville Goodwin was an enigmatic figure, as
mysterious as the people to whose study he devoted his life.
``Grennie,'' as his son calls him, was the child of a prominent
Hartford family who as a teenager was stricken with tuberculosis
and sent to school in the Southwest ``to rough it and recover,''
his son writes. Except for a few brief visits, he would never go
back East.
</P>
<P>
   From an Indian policeman he meets in 1927, the elder Goodwin
first hears about elusive bands of Apaches living ``in a primitive
condition'' across the border in isolated camps in the Sierra
Madre, a detail that becomes the first entry in his field notes.
Two years later, he hears that these Sierra Madre Apaches have
ambushed a Mexican family, killing the wife and abducting a young
boy.
</P>
<P>
   As Goodwin reconstructs his father's reaction to this event, he
writes that if the raiders ``represent a pre-reservation form of
culture, they would be living history, a `lost people,' a
once-in-a-lifetime opportunity for an ethnographer of the 1930s. A
heady thought.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, ``Grennie'' Goodwin spent the remaining 10 years of
his life in and around the Apache reservations _ and getting as
close as possible to the ``pre-reservation'' Apaches in the
mountains, recording everything in neat, precise handwriting in his
notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with all this,'' said Goodwin. ``There were
artifacts he had collected, and a kind of oral history from my
mother.'' His parents had met at a family wedding, and over the
next seven years, Goodwin said, ``I think they probably talked a
lot about the things he was doing, and he must have been a very
romantic figure to her.'' To their families' displeasure, they
eloped, drove across the country, and were married in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His father's field notes appear as pages from a college blue
book pasted into a scrapbook, the penmanship neat and regular,
perhaps a second draft of notes jotted down during the day and
rewritten by the campfire at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fairly dry,'' Goodwin said of the writing, ``but it was
clear this was something he was very excited about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got talking with an Apache Police here,'' begins an entry in
August 1930 at the Fort Apache Reservation in Arizona. ``He said
that sometimes in summer some of Geronimo's people come up from Old
Mexico and run horses off the reservation. These had been seen in
the summer of 1929 by an Apache, a friend of his, but were wild and
would not stop to talk. He only saw them from a distance, but they
appeared to be dressed in modern clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to imagine,'' Neil Goodwin writes in his own journal,
``what it must have been like to hear from an Apache that
`Geronimo's people' have been up from Old Mexico as recently as one
year ago. It must have had an electrifying effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Several months after the initial entry, Grenville Goodwin was in
Douglas, Arizona, and met with the local police chief. ``It would
be almost impossible to come in contact with these Apaches, he
says, they being so wild. But there would be a chance to see their
camps, etc. The country should be studied as there are many ruins
in the locality. However it would not be safe for one to go
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Very shortly, he found a guide to accompany him and headed into
Mexico. While he never encountered the elusive ``Geronimo's
people,'' he often came upon one of their encampments and would
find signs that they had been there very recently, perhaps a day or
two before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often,'' said Goodwin, ``there were indications that they were
not far away, maybe even observing him.''
</P>
<P>
   But for its dryness, the notes of that trip ``open the door to
the rest of his life, his life at the reservation,'' said Goodwin.
``He had a passion for witnessing. His whole technique was to sit
day after day, at first not taking notes, just listening.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, Goodwin said, ``didn't want to be seen as a prying
anthropologist so he got a job at a trading post. To the Indians,
he was just the young guy behind the counter, but after a while, he
started asking questions and writing down people's life stories.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was not for another dozen years after he first saw his
father's journal that Goodwin got back to it _ after graduation
from Yale and Yale's School of Architecture, several years working
as an architect, and then making his first nature film, ``Following
the Tundra Wolf.'' Goodwin is now president of the Cambridge-based
Peace River Films, which has produced documentaries on cultural,
historical, and environmental subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin made the first of several trips to his father's
territory in 1976. ``I took the diary,'' he said, ``and followed it
like a treasure map.''
</P>
<P>
   While searching out locations his father had visited and even
meeting some of the people he had interviewed, Goodwin was
sometimes accompanied by his wife, Margot, and by his own son,
Seth. The more Goodwin learned, the more one great mystery loomed _
the underlying facts surrounding his father's death at age 37 (the
official cause was a brain tumor).
</P>
<P>
   For over a year Grenville Goodwin had been suffering severe
headaches, at one point telling his wife that it is ``as if the top
of my head is coming off.'' A tumor was not diagnosed until shortly
after Neil Goodwin's birth. Surgery at first seemed successful, but
his condition worsened and he died in July 1940.
</P>
<P>
   As he talked to Apaches who had known his father, Goodwin began
to pick up hints that Grenville Goodwin's death might have come
about because he knew too much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At first,'' he said, ``I was offended by that. But I knew that
he had been very interested in their religious beliefs, especially
that there is a supernatural power that is with you all the time
and that your own well-being is dependent on this power and your
relation to it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Apaches believe there is another side to that power, Goodwin
said. ``If you learn it, but are not powerful enough to use it, it
will turn on you and harm you.''
</P>
<P>
   He then began reading his father's notes from the period after
that coincides with ``The Apache Diaries'' and ``found references
to conversations he had with Apaches who would say things like,
`This is too dangerous, we can't talk about it now.' '' Often, he
would be told that he would have to wait until winter to talk about
it, because then all the supernatural beings would be asleep,
``hibernating like the animals so they couldn't hear you talking
about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin is now working on these later notes for a series of
articles on his father for the Journal of the Southwest. These days
he tries to imagine his father as a living person. ``I often wonder
if he would have wanted me to bother to try and understand him,''
he writes.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Goodwin muses, his father might say: ``Don't look
for me. I'm not there, not real. Only the Apaches are real.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
