<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4308 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-03 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALMOST LAST, BUT WITH A FINISHING KICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virtually every aspect of my life is governed by the magazine
Runner's World. I eat whatever they tell me to eat;
flatulence-inducing Balance bars? Yum! I buy the wildly overpriced
Pearl Izumi micro-mesh gear that is so essential for my
6-mile-per-hour slogs through suburban streets. I am thinking of
moving into a king-sized ``hypoxic tent'' advertised in RW, to
boost ``my red blood cell production and VO/2 max,'' whatever that
means. How I have come this far without it, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   So when Runner's World published its first ``Beginning Racing
Guide'' for tyro sloggers, I thought _ why not? ``The camaraderie
during a race _ especially a first race _ can be poignant,'' RW
claims. ``It's been known to reduce dyed-in-the-wool-stoics to
tears.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend pointed out that, as a columnist, I could avail myself
of the Breslin Option. Jimmy Breslin wrote a hilarious column in
the fall of 1979, averring that he had spent the previous year ``in
the privacy of Queens,'' training for the New York Marathon.
Beautifully written (``The sparkling early morning fall air forced
its way into my lungs, the effect far more intoxicating than
brandy''), delightfully entertaining _ the column was complete
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Bad career move, Alex. He's Jimmy Breslin, you're not. You'll
have to run the race.
</P>
<P>
   The task, in a nutshell, was to raise my endurance to the 3-mile
level, so that I could finish a 5-kilometer race. Runner's World
had a 10-week scheme for doing this, which I followed, more or
less. I definitely spent the three days preceding the race
``tapering,'' which is RW-speak for sitting on my can.
</P>
<P>
   So on Sunday morning, I wolfed down the recommended high-carb,
low-fat breakfast, started ``hydrating,'' _ RW-speak for drinking
water _ and pointed my car toward bucolic Groton, for that town's
Ninth Annual Road Race. Perusing the course description, I couldn't
help noticing the half-mile long hill following mile two. That's
funny, I had specifically asked about _ oh, never mind. It was a
gorgeous day; I had my micro-mesh singlet, my race number, and
access to free Balance bars _ we're off!
</P>
<P>
   Duffers like me were advised to start at the very rear of the
750-person pack. Nonetheless, people kept passing me. The fact is,
I run quite slowly. (Have I told you that I have asthma?) First all
the parents pushing their kids in those creepy ``all-terrain
jogging strollers'' rushed past me. Then all the grade schoolers
passed me. The guy with the dog passed me. Where are the people on
crutches, or the Prosthetic Division? I kept wondering. Shouldn't
they be passing me, too?
</P>
<P>
   During mile one, I made a vow: No one would walk the course
faster than I would run it. So I spent the first half of the race
slogging past the power walkers who had somehow gotten out ahead of
me. (Have I told you that I have an unusually high body-mass index
of 26.2?) I hit the 2-mile mark at 23 minutes and then turned up
the Big Hill. This hill was quite gentle, but it did turn quite a
number of runners into walkers. I'm good on hills; it's a
personality thing. I did manage to crawl past a dozen or so racers.
</P>
<P>
   As the course wound back toward the finish line, I asked a
spectator if there was less than half a mile left to run. He said
yes, so I stupidly decided to accelerate, or ``kick,'' the last few
hundred yards. What can I say? Jim Ryun was a boyhood hero. This is
about the last thing Runner's World would recommend for a
first-time runner, and explains my difficulty in walking this week.
</P>
<P>
   My time was execrable (Have I told you about the hip
replacement? _ just kidding) and I finished 701st. Do you think I
pulled a Breslin? As they say in New York, you can look it up. Now
I look forward to returning to my life of casual dissipation _
full-time ``tapering,'' as it were _ and then doing the whole thing
all over again.
</P>
<P>
   You can check my time under ``State Results'' on the Web site
www.coolrunning.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
