u s BC-HKN-DIPIETRO-BOS &LR;      05-03 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DIPIETRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETMINDER DIPIETRO IS CLOSING THE BOOKS AT BU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ricky DiPietro may be sitting on more than a million
bucks, but Tuesday the star Boston University netminder sounded
like something less than a phenom headed for a fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I'm relieved, really,'' said DiPietro, reached
at his dorm by telephone. ``It's all kind of sad, to tell you the
truth _ sad that I have to leave such a good program and such a
great bunch of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 18 years old, DiPietro on Monday signed the form that
essentially declared him a professional _ a classification that
will become official June 24 when the NHL holds its annual entry
draft in Calgary. A star freshman this past season for the
Terriers, DiPietro decided to accelerate his career and opt not to
wait for the June 2001 draft. By declaring early, at age 18 rather
than 19, he is forced to surrender his remaining three years of
college eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what a lot of people say,'' said DiPietro, who grew up
in Winthrop, hometown of another BU hockey star, 1980 Olympian Mike
Eruzione. ``They say, `It's the money, the money, the money _ take
it and run.' But that's not the issue, and it hasn't been the issue
here from the get-go. It's about my dream to play in the NHL, and
after talking to a lot of people, it just seems to me that this
year's entry draft will be the quickest and most efficient way to
get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreams are for the dreaming, of course, and DiPietro could be
the next Boston-area teenager to step directly into an NHL net. But
such quantum leaps are rare for less-than-twentysomethings.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Barrasso, still on the job as recently as 10 days ago with
the Ottawa Senators, was only 18 years old when he became a regular
starter for the Buffalo Sabres in the fall of '83. Barrasso, the
No. 5 pick in the '83 entry draft, went directly from Acton-Boxboro
High School to NHL stardom, named the league's Rookie of the Year
in '84.
</P>
<P>
   The forgotten Jim Carey, ex- of Catholic Memorial, turned pro
after two years at the University of Wisconsin and was playing
regularly for the Washington Capitals at age 19 after an AHL primer
in Portland, Maine. The following spring, in '96, he won the Vezina
Trophy. Less than a year later, he was dealt to Boston, his NHL
career all but finished.
</P>
<P>
   North Easton's Jim Craig, also a BU alum and member of the US
gold-medal squad in Lake Placid, played two seasons on Comm. Ave.
prior the Olympics and turned pro at 22. His career totaled 30
games.
</P>
<P>
   If DiPietro makes it to The Show, he likely won't get there
until he has played in the minor leagues for at least a year or
two. That's the conventional wisdom, the standard nurturing process
for even the best NHL netminders. For instance, Patrick Roy made it
to the Canadiens at age 20, but only after three years of major
Junior A netminding. Martin Brodeur became the Devils' regular at
age 21, but only after three years of Junior A and a full season in
the AHL.
</P>
<P>
   Can DiPietro find a shortcut? Of course he can. But he will
still be an 18-year-old when he reports to his first NHL training
camp, and the overwhelming odds, the conventional wisdom, even the
Cliff Notes of Cage Success suggest that his route will be, at
best, circuitous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it take me two years? Hopefully not,'' said DiPietro, who
went an impressive 18-5-5 with the Terriers in '99-00, with a
sparkling .913 save percentage and a 2.45 goals-against mark. ``I
think that will depend on how I approach the situation. If I
produce, then hey, it's a business, and I'll get my chance.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, his declaration signed, the game DiPietro has been
playing all his life stopped being a game and became his chosen
career path. Soon after the draft, he will sign a rookie contract,
a mandatory three-year deal, with base pay of $1,075,000 per
season, more than half of which will be guaranteed. His agent, Jay
Fee of Woolf &AMP; Associates, likely will seek a deal similar to that
of Roberto Luongo, the Islander phenom-in-waiting, who was the
fourth pick overall in the '97 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Luongo has yet to, shall we say, grow into the job, but his deal
made him eligible to earn an extra $2.4 million in bonuses _above
and beyond his $925,000 in base pay _ the first year of his
contract. Widely considered to be the hottest goalie prospect since
Luongo, DiPietro could get a three-year deal that, with incentives,
weighs in at around $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   In DiPietro's wake, BU must find another goaltender to work the
'00-01 season with junior returnee Jason Tapp. Head coach Jack
Parker no doubt was working the phones Tuesday, along with his top
recruiter, Mike Bavis, sifting through names of prospects. As of
Monday, they were plus a full scholarship but minus a franchise
goalie. And May is beyond late on the recruiting calendar _ it's OT
and then some.
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro, with about another 10 days remaining in his college
life, didn't scratch out his name Monday afternoon, just hours
before the NHL deadline to opt in as an ``underage,'' and take off
down Comm. Ave. in Mardi Gras spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, there was no celebration, not at all,'' he said, still
sounding subdued some 24 hours later. ``Why? Because it was just
such a tough decision. I was torn. I know it's supposed to be
exciting, and a new beginning and everything. But more than
anything, I feel sad I have to leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
