<HEADER>
A4314 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EXAMINER-PUBLISHER-HN     05-03 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-PUBLISHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEWSPAPER REMOVES PUBLISHER AMID FALLOUT OF TRIAL TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZACHARY COILE and PETER HARTLAUB  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Hearst Corp., owner of the San Francisco
Examiner, placed the newspaper's publisher on an indefinite leave
of absence after he testified that he had offered Mayor Willie
Brown favorable editorials in exchange for the mayor's support of
Hearst's plan to buy the San Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for the New York-based Hearst also called for an
immediate internal review into whether the newspaper's editorial
pages had been compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy O. White, who previously was publisher of Hearst's Times
Union in Albany, N.Y., testified Monday that the proposed purchase
of the Chronicle raised questions about the newspaper's credibility
with its readers and caused a furor in the newsrooms of the
afternoon Examiner and the morning Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people read a newspaper's editorial opinion pages, they
are entitled to believe that the newspaper, whatever the opinion
is, has based the opinion on facts and philosophy and a considered
look at the situation and not based on something that will help the
news organization financially,'' said James Risser, a two-time
Pulitzer Prize winner with the Des Moines (Iowa) Register who now
directs Stanford University's Knight journalism fellowships. ``To
the extent that they can't believe that, then the credibility of
the newspaper suffers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst and Examiner officials vehemently denied that White had
pressured staffers to change editorials or news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   And Brown strongly defended the publisher, expressing shock at
Hearst's decision to put White on leave. The mayor said he did not
recall White's ever offering favorable treatment in the Examiner's
editorial pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the Examiner has been an incredibly nasty newspaper
to me,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   George B. Irish, president of the Hearst Newspapers, will take
over publishing responsibilities while the matter is investigated.
Examiner Executive Editor Phil Bronstein will remain in charge of
newsroom operations.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members of the Examiner, who packed into a conference room
to hear Bronstein announce the news Tuesday afternoon, said they
felt some relief that the company was taking swift action to
address remarks seen as undermining the newspaper's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Bronstein insisted that the integrity of the news staff was not
in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have is absolute knowledge that our news pages have
never been compromised,'' he said. ``I think our coverage of Willie
Brown is only one example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the newspaper's staff of 200 reporters, editors and
photographers said they were sympathetic to White, who has been
well-liked since he took over as publisher in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim White, on more than one occasion, expressed complete
support and encouragement for some of the toughest stories that the
Examiner's investigative team had done on the Brown administration
during the election,'' said reporter Chuck Finnie.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Mr. White said may have left the Hearst Corporation
little choice in the short term but to take the action it took,''
he said. ``But in the long term, at the end of the review, I expect
they will determine that nothing improper was done or even
contemplated.''
</P>
<P>
   White declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   His controversial statements came Monday on the first day of the
trial in an antitrust suit brought by San Francisco developer Clint
Reilly. Reilly is asking U.S. District Judge Vaughn R. Walker to
bar Hearst from buying the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly contends that Hearst's plan to buy the Chronicle for $660
million and sell the Examiner to the publishers of the free
Independent newspaper will effectively end newspaper competition in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   White testified Monday that he had made the offer of editorial
support at a lunch with Brown on Sept. 1, 1999, at the height of
the mayor's re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's lawyer, Joseph M. Alioto, quizzed White about an e-mail
he sent Irish reporting on the lunch. In the e-mail, White wrote he
had suggested to the mayor it would be difficult to ``support him
and cooperate with him when he was seeming to go out of his way to
make our lives difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Alioto asked White whether he was ``doing a little
horse-trading'' _ Examiner editorial page support in return for the
mayor's backing on Hearst's bid for the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   Later Monday, in a statement released by Hearst officials, White
backed away from his testimony. ``I was tired and confused by the
question,'' White said in the statement. ``The implication of my
answer that the pages of the Examiner can be influenced, under any
circumstances, is absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Alioto contended in court Tuesday that Hearst executives had
known the substance of White's testimony for months, because White
gave similar sworn statements to the Department of Justice, which
was reviewing the proposed purchase. A Hearst company spokesman
declined to comment on the allegation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Media specialists said that even if there was no quid-pro-quo in
the Examiner's editorial pages, the newspaper's credibility had
still been damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Readers who care about this kind of thing would still tend to
be alarmed that the publisher might say this, offer this to a
politician or have it in his mind to do this,'' Risser said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tom Rosenstiel, director for the Project for Excellence in
Journalism at the Columbia School of Journalism, said Hearst's
quick action to put White on leave and review the matter might help
the newspaper deal with doubts about its credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``How you deal with the crisis is more important than how the
crisis happened,'' Rosenstiel said. ``Nobody expects perfection out
of any business, and nobody expects perfection out of the news
business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
