</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIVIDE AND CONQUER?: MINI-MICROSOFTS COULD BE BILL'S BEST
REVENGE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GATES-ROCKEFELLER-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Take heart, Bill Gates. American courts do not much
like breaking up successful companies, but when they do, the
results are not always dire. Think of Exxon, Mobil, Amoco, Chevron;
those companies are among the fragments of Standard Oil, broken up
in 1911. In the subsequent decade, the value of Standard Oil's
divided assets rose fivefold. John D. Rockefeller, lucky man, thus
made more money in retirement than during his working life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MR. LIVINGSTONE, I PRESUME?: LONDON GETS `LOONY' NEW MAYOR &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LONDON-`RED'-MAYOR-ECONOMIST-500&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Revenge is a dish best eaten cold. But this is
ridiculous. A full 14 years after Margaret Thatcher abolished the
Greater London Council, thinking she had consigned its leader to
history, ``Red'' Ken Livingstone is poised to take his place again
as the public face of London. Much to the chagrin of Prime Minister
Tony Blair, Livingstone is expected to become London's first-ever
directly elected mayor, the closest thing that Britain has had to
an American-style big-city boss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 225-word optional trim at 500; 975 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFRICA'S TWIN SCOURGES: AIDS AND MALARIA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALING-AFRICA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ In the rich world, AIDS, though still incurable,
seldom nowadays means imminent death, and malaria kills hardly
anyone. In the poor world, however, AIDS kills about 2.5 million
people a year and malaria another 2 million, perhaps more. Most of
the deaths are in Africa, and they are increasing in number. Alas,
they would be attacked with far greater energy and effectiveness if
most of their victims lived not in Africa but in Europe or
America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JUST HOW `COMPASSIONATE' IS GEORGE W.? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSH-BLEEDING-HEART-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Just how compassionate can a Republican get before
he has to leave the GOP and join Vegans for Global Justice? George
W. Bush seems bent on finding out. One moment he is holding a
get-to-know-you meeting with a bunch of gay Republicans. The next
he is holding forth on education or the environment or some other
squishy-squashy crowd-pleaser. It is enough to make a red-blooded
conservative choke on his spotted-oil drumstick. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary and Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 175-word trim at 850; 1,075 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELIAN GONZALEZ: MOVED, BUT STILL A PAWN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELIAN-SAGA-LIMBO-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A screaming boy, policemen pointing guns,
Cuban-Americans burning flags. The Elian Gonzalez affair reached a
new crescendo with the armed removal of the six-year-old from the
home of his Miami relatives. So, now that Elian has been reunited
with his father in Maryland, you might expect a speedy conclusion
to the affair, right? Don't count on it. With Cuban exiles still
smarting from a mixture of tear gas, pepper spray and public
humiliation, lawyers for the boy's Miami relatives are already
planning to erect new legal obstacles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (850 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SYRIA'S SURPRISING CYBER-REVOLUTION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CYBER-SYRIA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAMASCUS _ The future has finally arrived in ancient Damascus.
At a fairground once used to tout the output of state-owned
factories, veiled women and mustachioed men skitter from pavilion
to pavilion, ogling the latest DVD players, comparing new makes of
mobile phones and trying their hands at surfing the Web. What might
sound standard elsewhere is revolutionary in Syria, whose
authoritarian regime has steadfastly skirted the information
superhighway. Until now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Technology Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REBORN WARSAW IS BUSINESS MECCA OF CENTRAL, EASTERN EUROPE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WARSAW-BIZ-BOOM-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WARSAW _ The capital of Poland is stupendously ugly. Almost
every building is less than 50 years old: the entire city was
virtually wiped off the face of the earth in the Second World War,
leaving 600,000 Poles dead. But Warsaw has been largely reborn.
Chicago-sized skyscrapers punching skyward along John Paul Avenue
confirm Warsaw's place as the undisputed business capital of
Central and Eastern Europe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Business Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (525 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW WILL THE CHECHEN WAR END? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHECHNYA-SCENARIO-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW_ If this is victory, what would a stalemate look like?
Even in winter, when Chechen fighters were at their most vulnerable
_ cold, hungry and visible through the bare trees _ the Russian
forces, which outnumber them at least tenfold, failed to destroy
them. Now spring is making conditions in the mountains more
favorable for the Chechens. The war drags on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICO'S PRESIDENTIAL RACE GETS `MUY CALIENTE' AFTER ALL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRI-NO-SHOO-IN-MEXICO-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The vote is not until July 2, but as the campaign
for Mexico's presidential election got under way in earnest this
week, two things confirmed that it will not be like any other in
the country's history. What once looked like a walkover for the
ruling PRI party, which has held power since the 1920s, has turned
into a hotly contested fight after all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,050 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELIAN'S THE STAR OF CASTRO'S POLITICAL THEATRE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CUBA-`ELIAN-EFFECT'-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Now that Elian Gonzalez has been reunited with his
father _ in keeping with the main aim of the huge protest rallies
orchestrated by Fidel Castro over the past five months _ political
life in communist Cuba might be expected to return to a rather dull
normality. Yet that looks unlikely. Castro's declared ``truce''
with the U.S. government lasted only a day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S BARBARA (NOT BHAVANA) CALLING: INDIA'S BOOMING CALL
CENTERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DELHI-CALLCENTERS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DELHI _ The death of distance is throwing up a lot of new
opportunities for India. Indians are animating movies and
transcribing foreigners' medical records without consumers in the
West being any the wiser. Telephone agents handle everything from
late credit-card payments to complaints about software. You'll be
hearing from Barbara (not Bhavana), even though she may be calling
you at midnight her time from a cubicle in Delhi. Her familiarity
with baseball may surprise you. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CARIBBEAN TOURISM: TROUBLE IN PARADISE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `GO-AWAY'-CARIBBEAN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BARBADOS _ There's trouble in paradise. On Good Friday, on
Tobago's most popular beach, a 41-year-old man got into an argument
with a security guard about access to a private beach. He was shot
dead. It was a painful illustration of the political difficulties
that are aggravating the Caribbean tourism industry's many woes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Business and Travel Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (975 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOREOVER &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THOUSANDS OF ANTIQUITIES DOOMED BY TURKISH DAM. DOES ANYONE
CARE? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DAM-SHAME-TURKEY-ECONOMIST-575&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GAZIANTEP, TURKEY _ Countless archaeological treasures _
irreplaceable treasures _ will be buried under the waters of the
Euphrates River when the newly completed Birecik Dam starts filling
up on April 29. ``We are about to witness a great tragedy,'' says a
distressed Dr. Catherine Abadie Reynal, a French archaeologist who
has been digging there since 1996. ``A second Ephesus is about to
be lost. And no one seems to have lifted a finger to stop it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORS: Note APRIL 29 reference, 4th graf) &QL;
</P>
