<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, May 4, 2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-VIEQUES _ VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ The latest
developments from the island of Vieques, where protesters await
federal action to remove them from the Navy bombing range.
Developing. (MWilliams, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move in (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-MAYOR _ LONDON _ On Thursday, London is to elect its
first real mayor. The jockeying has been under way for months.
Sometimes comical, oftentimes tough. Developing. (Roughton, Cox
News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   LATAM-COVERDELL _ Q and A with Sen. Paul Coverdell on his new
emphasis on Latin America and his policy proposals. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CRIM-OBIT _ ATLANTA _ Alonzo Crim, 72, the first black school
superintendent of a major Southern city, died Wednesday in a car
accident. Crim was Atlanta's school superintendent from 1973 to
1987 and was credited with raising attendance to more than 92
percent and increasing the graduation rate to more than 70 percent.
He received his doctorate in education from Harvard and had
honorary doctorates from Princeton, Harvard, Tuskegee University
and Columbia University. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CRIM-PROFILE _ ATLANTA _ A look at the life of Alonzo Crim. We
focus on Crim's early life, his education at the University of
Chicago and Harvard and his role as a barrier-breaker in education
in the South. Under Crim --who was picked in 1973 by a mandate
specifying a black superintendent -- attendance rates and
graduation rates improved. His tenure was marred, though, by a
declining enrollment and low test score levels which some say was a
reflection of more educated, affluent families moving to the
suburbs. (Cumming, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ALAMIN _ ATLANTA _ Paul Howard is expected to announce today
(Thursday) that he will seek the death penalty against Jamil
Abdullah Al-Amin. The announcement will likely come at Al-Amin's
first appearance hearing in Fulton Superior Court. If the death
penalty is sought, the case will be re-assigned to a judge. It
would not go to a judge who already has a capital case, as several
do. Stephanie Manis, the current judge, could get it back.
(Warner/Davis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   GA-FLAG _ ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes is planning to appoint a
commission to make recommendations about removing the Confederate
emblem from Georgia's state flag. The commission would study
potential economic impacts if a boycott were declared here, as it
has been in South Carolina, and the panel would make the case that
the Confederate symbol was added to the flag in 1956 as a protest
against school desegregation. African American lawmakers say
they're close to having enough votes in the House to change the
flag's design, and if Barnes gets behind the effort, it would
succeed. (Judd, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   KENT _ An interview with Chuck Fassinger, the ranking National
Guard officer at the time on the 30th anniversary of the Kent State
shooting. Fassinger now lives in Miami-Dade. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach
Post). 55. WITH MUG.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   FED-SCORECARD _ WASHINGTON _ Many federal agencies are given low
marks for their annual reports to taxpayers in a grading by the
Meratus Center at George Mason University. According to the study,
many agencies failed to give comprensible reports to the public on
what they're doing. (Malone, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ With Al Gore intimating that he could tap a
Republican as a vice presidential candidate, where are the
differences between him and George W. Bush? (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m. EDT.
</P>
