<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4341 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     05-03 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING THAT TESTOSTERONE BOOST  
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first tube of testosterone gel is scheduled to appear on the
market this summer and I, for one, can hardly wait.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, I can become a hairy, macho, studly,
hormone-spewing guy simply by smearing some goo on my body the same
way I would sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, there is the small matter of getting a doctor to
prescribe the stuff, called AndroGel, and there's a blood test, and
I think I saw something in the fine print about prostate tumors,
but I think it's clear that the rewards will outweigh the risks,
especially for testosterone-deficient guys like me.
</P>
<P>
   I can foresee many areas in which testosterone gel will improve
my quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   Take driving, for instance. My wife says that I drive like an
``old man,'' which I think is a rather unkind way of saying that I
am cautious. Personally, I do not think that driving 45 mph in the
left lane of the Interstate is a sign of feebleness; I prefer to
think of it as setting a positive example for the younger
generation.
</P>
<P>
   But never mind. Once AndroGel hits the streets, the ``old man''
who followed at a respectful distance and always used his turn
signals will be replaced by a snarling, aggressive maniac whose
idea of a fun weekend is running over pedestrians while yelling
into a cell phone. In other words, I will become like other
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturer suggests that you apply AndroGel by rubbing it
into hairless skin, so I plan on smearing the stuff on my chest. It
will take some practice unbuttoning my shirt and rubbing the goo
into my chest while performing a 70-mph U-turn across six lanes of
traffic on U.S. 41 at rush hour, but I trust that my
testosterone-in-a-tube will give me the confidence I need to pull
off the maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the matter of hobbies. When I was a kid, my
hobbies were chess and astronomy, two of the most
testosterone-deficient activities a young person could pursue.
Later, in my 20s, presumably at the peak of my
testosterone-producing years, I took up golf. I think you can see
why I have been waiting so long for something like AndroGel to come
along.
</P>
<P>
   Testosterone supplements have been available for some time, but
there are drawbacks. Injecting the hormone risks side effects such
as liver problems, blood thickening, acne and breast development.
Plus, I've never cared much for needles.
</P>
<P>
   There is a testosterone patch, but it works best if applied
directly to the scrotum. Plus, it's suggested that you heat the
area first with a hair dryer. This is a bigger sacrifice than I'm
willing to make for visible biceps and sideburns.
</P>
<P>
   The gel, on the other hand, appears to be relatively safe and
easy to use aside from the fact that you're supposed to slather it
on several times a day. There could be some embarrassing moments,
say at staff meetings or in a fancy restaurant, where I forget
where I am and rip off my shirt so that I can apply a fresh coating
of AndroGel.
</P>
<P>
   But a few embarrassing moments seem a small price to pay for a
new, testosterone-laden lifestyle, a lifestyle where chess and
astronomy have no place and where I grind my golf clubs into spears
for shark-fishing expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   And if daily applications of AndroGel help make my dry skin go
away, then so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
