<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, May 4:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-BRITAIN-MARKETS (London) _ Europe's two biggest stock
markets, London and Frankfurt, agreed on Wednesday to merge in the
first step towards creating a pan-European exchange which should
drive down the cost of trading. The London Stock Exchange and
Frankfurt's Deutsche Boerse also announced a tie-up with the
technology-laden U.S. Nasdaq market, offering up the prospect of an
eventual global market-place for stocks. The merged entity will be
called iX _ standing for International Exchanges _ and will command
53 percent of the traded volume in European equities and 81 percent
of the European market for high-growth shares. (Summary from wires)
By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-EXCHANGE (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Germany's stock exchange
has quietly amassed clout through acquisitions, new technology and
a readiness to start up new ventures. Much of the credit goes to
its chief executive, Werner G. Seifert, a devoted gourmet and jazz
pianist who was an outsider when he arrived at the exchange in
Frankfurt 1994. For starters, he is Swiss rather than German. Now
50 years old, he had been a partner in Germany at McKinsey &AMP; Co.,
the management consulting firm. And while he had little experience
in the nuts and bolts of securities trading, he had a strong sense
that technology would transform the markets and erode national
boundaries _ particularly in Europe. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ (Undated) _ What the alliance with the merged
London-Frankfurt exchange means for the Nasdaq market. By Alex
Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   BESTFOODS-UNILEVER (Undated) _ Unilever, saying it would not
rule out a hostile bid, says Bestfoods, the maker of Hellmann's
mayonnaise, Skippy peanut butter, has until the of the day on
Thursday to discuss its $18.4 billion bid. By Constance L. Hays.
(With reporting from London by Andrew Ross Sorkin.)
</P>
<P>
   EURO (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The euro falls below $0.90. The
currency has lost more than 20 percent of its value against most
major currencies since its launch in January, 1999. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were sharply lower in early trading.
At 11:20 a.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was down 1.68
percent, the S&AMP;P 500 was down 2.01 percent and the Nasdaq composite
index down 3.32 percent. European markets were also lower: London
down 2.02 percent and Frankfurt down 2.51 percent. Hong Kong closed
down 1.52 percent. The Tokyo market is closed for the Golden Week
of holidays. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE-AWARDS (New York) _ The national magazine awards to be
announced. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly Economic Scene column. By J.
Bradford DeLong. (J. Bradford DeLong is a professor of economics at
the University of California at Berkeley and co-editor of The
Journal of Economic Perspectives.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (Dateline to kum) _ Developments in the
seizure and reported slaying of U.N. peacekeepers by rebels in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   PANAM103-TRIAL (Camp Zeist, the Netherlands) _ Two Libyans plead
innocent, accuse Palestinians as trial opens in 1988 bombing of Pan
Am Flight 103. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-TRIALS (Tehran) _ Story on trial of people who have
confessed to shooting reformist editor _ they say he was corrupt
and anti-Islam. Also, two more Jews are said to confess at the spy
trial. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   EASTEUROPE-BIRTHS (Prague, Czech Republic) _ A United Nations
study finds that the birth rate is plunging in Eastern Europe. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANTIROCKET-LASER (Undated) _ In the first practical
application of a revived program to use lasers for missle defense,
the U.S. Army plans to shoot down a Katyusha rocket at the White
Sands Testing Range this month. If the system, which was developed
in collaboration with Israel, is proved successful, it will be
deployed on the Israel-Lebanon border, according to U.S. military
officials. By James Glanz. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BIOTECH-FOODS (Undated) _ The Food and Drug Administration's
new policy on biotech foods, which requires formal review of
gene-altered crops and sets standards for labeling, appears
unlikely to bring wholesale changes to supermarket shelves. By Iver
Peterson. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-LAPTOP (Washington) _ State Department security measures
in the wake of the missing laptop computer with national security
files on it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-PRIMARIES (Washington) _ The Republican plan to stretch
out the primary season raises a host of practical questions about
what such a calendar would mean to campaigns. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   DELAY-PAC (Washington) _ Democrats file suit charging that a
political action committee formed by Representative Tom DeLay
violates campaign finance laws. The DeLay group was set up under
section 527 of internal revenue code, a loophole that allows
unlimited political fund-raising and spending with virtually no
disclosure. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-SOCSEC (Atlantic City) _ Al Gore talks about Social
Security. He is particularly harsh about Bush on the issue. By
James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCHOOLS (Owensboro, Ky.) _ Bill Clinton begins his
fabulous schools tour. The two-day, four-city tour promoting
education reform begins with a visit to an elementary school in
Owensboro. Stops are also planned in Davenport, Iowa; St. Paul,
Minn.; and Columbus, Ohio. By Abby Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   PACIFIC-ATOLL (Los Angeles) _ In a bid to preserve one of the
most pristine places left in the tropical Pacific, the Nature
Conservancy has agreed to buy Palmyra atoll, a spectacular cluster
of uninhabited coral islets 1,052 miles south of Hawaii, from the
Honolulu family that has owned it for 80 years, with plans to
create a nature preserve for marine and climate research and
limited, ecologically sensitive tourism. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-BASE (Vieques, Puerto Rico) _ Developments in the
protests on Vieques, the Navy test firing range. By Jon Nordheimer.
</P>
<P>
   SF-PAPERS (Undated) _ Developments in fight over the San
Francisco Examiner and Chronicle. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
