<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4369 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-BOOKS-WALKING-SFCHRON     05-03 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-WALKING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THINKING ON HER FEET: Rebecca Solnit wrote a book about walking
_  while on the move  
 (Eds. Art is being sent to NYT photo clients.)  
 By SAM WHITING  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Walkers always have time to think, but they
don't always think about walking. Not the way Rebecca Solnit does _
from a scholarly viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about all the great thinkers who thought while they
walked, Solnit has come in from her own walks to write
``Wanderlust: A History of Walking,'' (Viking; $24.95.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an interesting project because there are no authorities
on walking as such. There are just authorities on bits and pieces
of a picture that hadn't been assembled before,'' Solnit says in an
interview conducted entirely while walking two or three miles South
of Market.
</P>
<P>
   Snaking through the alleys to avoid the clangor of construction
and traffic, she categorizes this as a ``conversational stroll,''
not a walk. Solnit doesn't really consider it walking unless a pace
of 3 miles per hour is maintained, which is too fast to do anything
besides think and dodge cars.
</P>
<P>
   To discuss her book it would make more sense to drive to some
quiet place, such as the Marin Headlands, and take a walk there.
But Solnit is not that kind of walker. If she wants to walk in the
Marin Headlands, she'd prefer to walk there first, all the way over
Lyon Street from her small apartment in the Western Addition, then
past Crissy Field and across the Golden Gate Bridge. Her most
productive walks start at her door _ walking for transportation, as
opposed to walking for aerobic workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk wherever my errands take me,'' says Solnit, who has
found that 3 mph is the speed at which her feet and mind work most
efficiently. An essayist, she had to walk three books out of her
system before she could focus on walking.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought the official version of what walking is are
these piously uplifting walks in rural places in which very little
happens,'' she says while making a hard right from Bonifacio Street
onto Lapu Lapu.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I started to pursue the subject more deeply I realized that
walking was this wonderful meandering path through everything I was
already interested in _ gender politics, public space and urban
life, demonstrations and parades and marches. The relationship
between walking and thinking and between the mind and the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Solnit uses first-person narrative in ``Wanderlust,'' but in the
interest of full disclosure she did not do all the types of walking
she wrote about. She did not do any streetwalking, and she did not
walk up Mount Everest. But she did walk 16 miles on a pilgrimage in
the high New Mexico desert, and she did walk in the rain around her
ancestral home in Ireland. She also walked through London, Paris
and Las Vegas, and all over San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Walking was the easy part. The hard part was reading everything
there is about walking, from theories of bipedalism to great quotes
from people in all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely everybody has a walking anecdote,'' says Solnit,
who found enough of these to amount to 30,000 words, enough for a
second book. Instead, she strung these quotes together like an
electronic message sign along the bottom of each of the 291 pages.
There are some clever observations by famous walkers, but the most
clever may be her own succinct explanation on Page 5:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thinking is generally thought of as doing nothing in a
production-oriented society, and doing nothing is hard to do. It's
best done by disguising it as doing something, and the something
closest to doing nothing is walking.''
</P>
<P>
   By that definition Solnit has spent half her 38 years doing
nothing, starting when she was a child in Novato. Her family's
subdivision backed onto open space. There was a fence, ``but
private property isn't of much concern to a little kid,'' she says.
She walked to school, but that stopped after junior high. Not
because she stopped walking but because she stopped going to
school, avoiding high school altogether in the
alternative-education 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I sort of ran away to Paris when I was 17,'' she says.
She thinks that through and decides ``ran away'' is too strong a
term. ``My parents were busy getting divorced, so nobody was really
trying to stop me. I didn't really have to run. I sort of walked
away.''
</P>
<P>
   While walking around Paris she learned that ``you don't have to
go inside the museums to have things worth looking at,'' she says.
Back home, she got her bachelor's degree at San Francisco State and
her master's at the University of California at Berkeley Graduate
School of Journalism before she got her driver's license, at age
23.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a hurry when I was young. I didn't slow down until
later,'' says Solnit, who just won a Guggenheim Fellowship for a
book she'll start after finishing ``Hollow City,'' a study of the
effects of gentrification on the neighborhoods of San Francisco
that she's walked for 20 years. The grant, around $35,000, will
allow her to ``join the lower middle class,'' she says, but her
feet will still be on the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me being in a car or on an airplane is like being in
limbo. It's this dead zone between two places. But to walk you're
some place that's already interesting. You're not just between
places. Things are happening,'' she says while raising a hand in a
``stop'' gesture to oncoming motorists as she jaywalks across
Second Street.
</P>
<P>
   Though Solnit can be militant, she isn't a power walker. Her
equipment consists of street clothes and a pair of Clark's high-top
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you have feet and a place to go and a little bit of
free time,'' she says, ``you're pretty equipped as far as I'm
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
