<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., MAY 21, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My basement windows are slightly below ground level on the
outside and the builder installed curved ``window well'' soil
retainers around the outside of each window.
</P>
<P>
   These are partly below ground at the bottom and project up about
five or six inches above the ground around the window. There is
just soil at the bottom of this window well, and this soil is only
an inch or two below the level of the window.
</P>
<P>
   My problem is that in a heavy rain, water accumulates in the
bottom of this ``well'' and some of this seeps in under the window
and runs down on the inside of the basement wall.
</P>
<P>
   What can I do to solve this problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: Dig out the soil inside the window well to a depth of about
10 inches, or until you are almost at the bottom of the well
enclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Apply silicone caulking to the joint where the metal (or
plastic) meets the foundation wall, then fill the space you just
dug out with gravel or small stones.
</P>
<P>
   Pour in gravel until its height is about one inch below the
bottom of the window.
</P>
<P>
   Finish by making certain the ground around the outside of this
window well slopes away from the house foundation on all sides to
help it shed water more effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am building a wall unit of plywood and want it to fit flat
against an existing wall when finished. However, the wall it will
fit against is slightly irregular and there is a baseboard at the
bottom that I want to leave in place.
</P>
<P>
   How can I trim the edge of the plywood panel that will form the
side of the unit so its contour will exactly match the contour of
the wall and baseboard and thus make the unit fit snugly against
the existing wall?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hold the plywood panel temporarily in place so its edge is up
against the wall where you want it to fit.
</P>
<P>
   Now take an ordinary pencil compass and scribe the back edge of
the plywood to exactly match the face of the wall and its baseboard
molding.
</P>
<P>
   You do this by holding the panel so its edge just touches the
front of the baseboard at the bottom, then measure the space
between the edge of the panel and the wall in several places to
make certain the edge of the panel is standing parallel to the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Set the legs of the compass a little wider apart than this
distance, then hold the metal point of the compass against the wall
as you slide the pencil leg over the face of the plywood.
</P>
<P>
   The pencil will then trace the outline of the wall and baseboard
onto the face of the plywood, which you can then cut accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Rusty nail heads are showing through the paint on the outdoor
siding on my house.
</P>
<P>
   I used a metal primer on these rust marks before repainting last
year, but some rust stains still show through.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a more permanent solution I can take to cover up these
rust stains without having to pull all the old nails out?
</P>
<P>
   A: Start by scraping and sanding all the exposed nail heads to
remove as much of the rust at possible.
</P>
<P>
   Then apply a liquid rust converter to each head and after this
dries, use a nail set to drive the nail head in about a quarter
inch below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Fill each hole with an exterior grade wood putty or wood
patching compound, then finish by touching up with matching paint.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My very old house has a brick foundation and some years ago a
layer of plaster was troweled on over the bricks on the inside.
</P>
<P>
   Moisture is apparently seeping up into the bricks from the
ground and this is causing the plaster to crumble and flake off in
places, although the basement is dry.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have any idea as to how we can correct this problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: The problem may be insoluble because the plaster should never
have been applied directly to the bricks originally.
</P>
<P>
   Short of removing all the plaster, you may be able to improve
matters by doing what you can to improve drainage on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   The ground should slope away from the foundation on all sides
and the gutter's downspouts should be connected to underground
plastic drainage pipes that will carry the water at least 10 feet
away.
</P>
<P>
   It would also help to apply a waterproofing paint or sealer to
the exposed brick on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``WINDOW WELL LINER'' goes with this
column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Filling bottom of basement window well with gravel will
help to insure proper drainage during a heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
