<HEADER>
A4390 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-MAYOR-0504-CO     05-03 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MAYOR-0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POPULIST CANDIDATE , BLAIR NEMESIS, LOOKS LIKE SHOO-IN FOR
LONDON MAYOR
 &HT;    (EDs: Contains optional trim.)
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A loner known with both fondness and derision as ``Red
Ken'' almost certainly will become this ancient and influential
city's first elected mayor when voters head to the polls Thursday
to cast their historic votes.
</P>
<P>
   Barring an upset that would stun analysts and bankrupt England's
bookies, Ken Livingstone will become the leader of the largest
single electorate in Britain and one of most visible politicians in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Livingstone almost certainly will be a thorn in
the side of Prime Minister Tony Blair, who staged a spectacularly
unsuccessful campaign to keep Livingstone from becoming mayor.
</P>
<P>
   An unreconstructed leftist with a fondness for uttering somewhat
shocking statements, Livingstone is everything the prim and careful
centrist Blair detests.
</P>
<P>
   After Blair succeeded in blocking his nomination by the Labor
Party, Livingstone decided to run as an independent. Consequently,
he was acrimoniously banished from the party.
</P>
<P>
   Londoners responded sympathetically to the 55-year-old
Livingstone, who was seen as a maverick refusing to bow to the
national government.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Blair's handpicked candidate, Frank Dobson,
summoned little more than a yawn. Pre-election polls suggest
Dobson, formerly a dutiful bureaucrat, will finish more than 30
percentage points behind Livingstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vote for Frank Dobson will be bad to derisory,'' said
Patrick Dunleavy, the political analyst credited for designing the
American-style election process.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone is expected to win a commanding 51 percent of the
vote, while none from his opponents _ a field that also includes
Conservative Steve Norris and Liberal Democrat Susan Kramer _ is
expected to top 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was Blair who prepared the way for Livingstone _
a paunchy, middle-aged populist. As part of his push to
decentralize government, the prime minister advocated energetically
for a directly elected mayor for London.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to overstate the importance of this new role on the
British political stage. While London's mayor may seem of similar
standing to a mayor of a big American city, it is really much more.
</P>
<P>
   London is the dominant cultural and economic center for Britain,
while even a city such as New York is dwarfed by the rest of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the prime minister, who holds office because he is head
of the party in power and directly represents only his
parliamentary district, the mayor will have the clear legitimacy of
speaking for more than 5 million voters.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   While Livingstone is loved by Londoners, many regret that the
city has been unable to produce a more illustrious candidate. Early
on, the ballot had more sex appeal with author Jeffrey Archer and
former actress Glenda Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   But both fell aside. Jackson failed to get enough Labor Party
support. Archer dropped out last fall amid a scandal that suggested
he lied in a libel lawsuit he won against two newspapers that
reported he had a tryst with a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Livingstone promises to add color to a city
that often seems overwhelmingly gray. For the last few weeks, he
has been cruising London in a purple open-topped bus wise-cracking
into a megaphone to amused crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone has made headlines by asserting that the
international financial system has killed more people than Adolf
Hitler. He has said that the now controversial World Trade
Organization will be unwelcome in his London unless demonstrators
have time to stock up rubbish to throw at its members.
</P>
<P>
   He also has said that the leaders of the International Monetary
Fund deserve to ``die painfully in their beds.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts don't know quite what to make of Livingstone.
``Left-wing populists are very rare in Britain,'' said Tony
Travers, a political scientist at the London School of Economics.
``But Livingstone is a loner and a left-wing populist. And he's a
politician who, as an individual can win a very big election. This
is rarer still.''
</P>
<P>
   If Blair and his followers regard Livingstone as an embarrassing
eccentric uncle, the Conservative Party considers him a
communist-coddling loony who will threaten the city's reputation as
the center of European finance.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives say Livingstone believes in higher taxes,
supporting rioters, persecuting motorists and legalizing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   His lack of popularity on the right is unsurprising. Livingstone
came to fame during the 1980s by throwing rocks at Conservative
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Then head of the Greater London Council, Livingstone used his
office to rail against Thatcher's government. He once hung a banner
from his offices across the Thames from Parliament displaying the
number of London jobs lost to Thatcher's campaign to trim
government and cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Thatcher abolished the council, the last central
government in this city of more than 7 million. Since then, the
city has been governed by the national government and a variety of
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts think that Livingstone might be too busy with
potholes, horrific traffic and a burgeoning crime rate to be a
similar annoyance to Blair.
</P>
<P>
   He will oversee a budget of about US$6 billion, and will be
responsible for two major institutions: the Underground subway
system and the London police.
</P>
<P>
   He will have the expectations and responsibilities of an
American-style mayor with none of the structure in place to deal
with it. And he will have very limited powers to raise more money
to address the city's urgent needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question is will Ken Livingstone be the kind of mayor
who is able to take that kind of active role,'' Travers said. ``On
that the jury is very much out.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.london.gov.uk
</P>
<P>
   http://www.poptel.org.uk/ken-livingstone
</P>
<P>
   http://www.frank-dobson.org.uk
</P>
<P>
   http://www.norrisforlondon.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.susankramer.org.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
