<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUBBLE AND SQUEAK'S NO TOIL AND TROUBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kathy Housewright, Hurst, Texas, writes looking for a recipe for
bubble and squeak. This is a great way to use leftover mashed
potatoes. It was a big dish during the Depression because it was
economical and filling. The dish gets its name from the noises it
makes while cooking.
</P>
<P>
   An e-mail sender would like the recipe for coconut pie using
Bisquick. A quick search on the Internet pulled up the version
we're running.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the spirit of Cinco de Mayo, here's the recipe for the
tortilla soup served at Luby's.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BUBBLE AND SQUEAK
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cooked mashed potatoes
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cooked cabbage, chopped into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Combine potatoes and cabbage and season well with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in large skillet and add vegetables. Saute over medium
heat, pressing the vegetables down so they form the shape of a flat
cake. When one side is well browned, turn and cook on the other
side.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to hot serving plate and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 252 calories, 15 grams fat, 29
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 17 milligrams cholesterol,
436 milligrams sodium, 54 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Great British Cooking'' by Jane Garmey (HarperPerennial,
$15)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   IMPOSSIBLE COCONUT PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 stick butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded coconut
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Bisquick
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients in blender. Blend on low for 30 seconds.
Pour into ungreased 10-inch pie plate. Bake at 350 degrees for 50
minutes. The pie makes it own crust as it bakes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 324 calories, 19 grams fat, 30
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 173 milligrams cholesterol,
293 milligrams sodium, 54 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   LUBY'S TORTILLA SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4 corn tortillas cut into 1-by-3-inch strips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound lean ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   6 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   14 1/2-ounce can whole peeled tomatoes, undrained, chopped
</P>
<P>
   12-ounce can cream-style corn
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups (6 ounces) shredded American cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 small clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped cilantro, optional
</P>
<P>
   In small skillet, heat about 1/2 inch of vegetable oil. Add half
the tortilla strips and cook until crisp. Drain on paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   In small skillet, brown ground beef with onion. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   In large saucepan or Dutch oven, combine broth, tomatoes, corn,
cheese, cumin, salt, pepper and garlic. Bring to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, mix cornstarch and water until cornstarch is
dissolved. Gradually add to boiling soup, stirring constantly.
Reduce heat and simmer 10 minutes. Remove from heat. Stir in ground
beef mixture and uncooked tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Ladle into bowls. Garnish with fried tortillas and, if desired,
cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 284 calories, 16 grams fat, 21
grams carbohydrates, 14 grams protein, 44 milligrams cholesterol,
1,528 milligrams sodium, 51 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
