<HEADER>
A4410 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     05-03 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPTING TREATS FROM SOUTH OF THE BORDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is one thing I really, really don't need added to my daily
menu _ a new line of snack cakes and sweet breads.
</P>
<P>
   I am already locked in a life's battle with cookies and cakes. I
shouldn't eat them, but they pull at me with a gravitational force
that could suck the moon right into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   The tug of a new line is just too compelling to control,
especially when the snacks are displayed in the middle of a grocery
store, stacked on a table with plenty of room to park your cart and
ogle.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I found this weekend at the Carnival grocery store
at 28th Street and North Main in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The product line isn't exactly new; it is only new to most of us
who live north of the border with Mexico. Those who have lived in
Mexico know it very well.
</P>
<P>
   They know that Gansitos are little chocolate-covered sponge
cakes with a cream filling and a shot of strawberry puree in the
middle. They know that Submarinos vainilla are just like Hostess
Twinkies with a hint more vanilla and a bit more density in the
cake. We need more Twinkies.
</P>
<P>
   Pinguinos are chocolate cupcakes with a harder, more sugary
icing than our more familiar brands.
</P>
<P>
   The labels on the Marinela-brand goodies show they are
``Products of Mexico,'' but they are distributed by ``BBU General
Offices Fort Worth, Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Bimbo Bakeries USA, owner of the Mrs Baird's brand that
Texans are more acquainted with.
</P>
<P>
   Bimbo, which bought out Mrs Baird's a couple of years ago, has
been slowly bringing up its Hispanic brands and introducing them in
the Texas market. Aside from the Marinela cookies and snack cakes,
there are also the Tia Rosa-brand tortillas and Bimbo-brand bread
and sweets.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Bimbo label _ always accompanied by a smiling Teddy
bear _ you can buy mini poundcakes called Panquecitos, or crispy,
cinnamon funnellike cakes called Bimbunuelos, or the more familiar
sweet rolls called Conchas.
</P>
<P>
   The Bimbo bread has even made it to local shelves. I haven't
tried it, but those who have say it is slightly sweeter than the
Mrs Baird's brand.
</P>
<P>
   Bimbo Bakeries USA is the U.S. subsidiary of Grupo Bimbo,
Mexico's largest food producer and the world's third-largest baking
company. Company officials intend to follow the Hispanic migration
into the United States, taking advantage of their familiarity with
the Bimbo brand, as well as spreading the products into other
cultural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our idea is to follow Hispanic consumers _ our customers _ to
offer them the products they already know wherever they live,''
said Juan Muldoon, president of Bimbo Bakeries USA. ``Our brands _
Bimbo, Marinela, Tia Rosa _ are household names in Mexico and Latin
America, names that most Hispanics grew up with.''
</P>
<P>
   Muldoon also said Bimbo's vision is to become one of the United
States' baking leaders as well.
</P>
<P>
   All of the company's Hispanic products aren't in every grocery
store in the Fort Worth market, but there is a little in each. I
found the Tia Rosa tortillas at Albertson's, the Tia Rosa corn
chips at Tom Thumb.
</P>
<P>
   It was only at Carnival _ a Minyard's-owned store designed for
the Hispanic market _ that I found the entire line.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Bimbo has the incentive to grow in
this area. Here is the statistical profile it has come up with as
it follows its Hispanic consumers:
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics represent over 11 percent of the U.S. population _
more than the entire population of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics are younger than the average population and have
larger families.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics are 66 percent more likely to live in households with
children under 18.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1998 and 2010, the Hispanic population will increase by
nearly 12 million _ an astounding 39 percent growth rate vs. 7
percent for non-Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics spend more on food at home than non-Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   The Bimbo, Tia Rosa, and Marinela brands were once shipped to
this market from Mexico, but now, with the success of these brands
in the United States, Bimbo has begun producing the products
locally.
</P>
<P>
   You can ship the ``pan dulce'' from Monterey, but its fresher if
it's done in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
