<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COMMUTE-WORKPLACE-ART     05-03 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMUTE-WORKPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY ARE THESE COMMUTERS SMILING? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JULIA LAWLOR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terry Murray feels most alive when he is on the move _ which is
why he spent five years making the two-hour one-way hike to and
from his job as an engineering manager at Bio-Rad Laboratories in
Cambridge, Mass. It wasn't until he strapped on a pair of in-line
skates and headed out the door one morning last year, though, that
his commute became really interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a warrior on my way to work,'' said Murray, who
cuts a striking figure in black stretch pants, fluorescent
green-and-yellow top and helmet with red blinking lights fore and
aft. It takes him 40 minutes to skate 10 miles from his home in
Winchester to his workplace, past woods, lakes, streams and throngs
of trenchcoat-clad 9-to-5ers waiting forlornly at the train
station. For fun, he plows through puddles, throwing up a wake
behind him, or jumps over recyclable containers left on sidewalks.
``Every commute is like a day of skiing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mention the word ``commute,'' and most people make a face. And
no wonder. An overwhelming majority of Americans drive to work, and
according to a study of 68 urban areas by the Texas Transportation
Institute in 1997, they spent an average of 45 hours a year sitting
in traffic, up from 16 hours in 1982. Los Angeles had the highest
average, at 82 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Users of mass transportation, though smaller in number, tell
horror stories of delayed trains and overcrowded subway platforms.
Yet, a breed of worker is flourishing that actually likes the daily
commute. Some simply sit back and enjoy the ride; others have
figured out ways to make the ride more interesting, and still
others _ like Murray _ have switched from cars or trains to more
exotic forms of transport. The common theme is to try, somehow, to
make one of life's great frustrations one of the day's great
rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Skinner, a travel consultant in New York City, is a
traditionalist who has commuted by train since 1959. Her favorite
commute, she says, began on ``the day Elvis died'' in 1977 when she
first took the 8:03 a.m. Metro-North train from New Canaan, Conn.,
to Grand Central Station. ``Everybody knows everybody,'' said
Skinner, who recently got a cake for her 70th birthday from the
train's engineer and conductor. ``In the morning, it's like a
kaffeeklatsch.''
</P>
<P>
   In the '60s and '70s, she rode the 6:10 p.m. ``party train''
home and luxuriated in the smoky bar car, where bartenders hired
three-piece combos on holidays. Every Christmas, Skinner dressed up
as Santa and handed out gifts. Though she has since switched to the
more sedate 5:05 p.m. train, she still considers the ride a high
point of her day.
</P>
<P>
   The three-piece combos are long gone, but long-running card
games and bar cars endure as institutions on the Metro-North line.
Two years ago, Tom Skinner (no relation to Jacqueline), executive
producer for Touchscreen Media Group, an Internet company based in
New York, started the Web site www.barcar.com to give commuters a
way to keep in touch once they left the train. Contributors post
jokes and photos and comment on just about everything. One popular
section, named ``The Blue Lagoon'' after a blue disinfectant used
to clean the toilets, invites visitors to submit opinions of the
train's restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   New Canaan bar-car riders have posted their own Web page on the
site, decorate their bar car with lights each Christmas, are
fiercely loyal to their bartender, Vinnie, and tend to be a little
cliquish. ``If someone new walks in, they have to tell one good
joke that offends at least one person, or sing their alma mater,''
said Linda Hinckley, an advertising account supervisor and regular
on the 6:05 p.m. bar car to New Canaan. ``The more timid
personalities tend to turn around and leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, a regular on the West Port line for 20 years, typically
stands at the end of his bar car with a can of beer and a bag of
peanuts, chatting with old friends. ``It's the only social life I
have during the week,'' he said. ``I see people on the train
sitting with their laptops playing solitaire, and I feel pity for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even fighting highway traffic can be enjoyable _ if you have
company. Derrick Mitchell, a San Diego city employee, organized a
van pool with seven other commuters not long ago and says the
hour's drive into the city now slips by almost unnoticed. ``We are
literally laughing all the time,'' he said. ``Wednesday is doughnut
day. On the way home, sometimes we go to a truckers' stop called
Messy's Burger for hamburgers. At Christmas, we all get together
with our spouses and go out to dinner. When someone is having a
personal problem with a child or a spouse or a job, we support
them. We are very close _ like family.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Brown, the owner of a restaurant in Cherry Hill, N.J., also
found a way to ease the angst of fighting his state's notorious
traffic jams. Five years ago, he began taking his son, Jordan, with
him and dropping him off at a day-care center near the restaurant.
``He demonstrates his karate moves for me, and we sing Motown
songs,'' Brown said. ``It's our best time together.''
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers take extreme measures to relieve ennui. On a crawl
along 25 miles of California Highway 17, Emil Gallant of Soquel
said he and a friend used to ``take pictures of people doing stupid
stuff while they were driving _ like putting on makeup, eating
breakfast, talking on cell phones, reading books.'' They would post
the photos on a Web site they entitled ``The Highway 17 Page of
Shame.'' Gallant has since found a job closer to home and zips over
country roads to his new workplace on his Triumph motorcycle. ``I
love it,'' he gloated.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Head loves riding two-wheelers, too. Head, a postal worker
in Carrollton, Ga., gave up her Chevrolet Suburban for a bicycle
when gasoline hit $1.44 a gallon. Now, her 30-minute ride to work
past flowering dogwood and apple trees, a lake, a river and all
kinds of wildlife ``has turned into more of a pleasure than a
protest for me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best part of the day. The kids aren't bothering me,
and the telephone isn't ringing.''
</P>
<P>
   If she thinks her commute is serene, she ought to meet Pat Doud,
general manager of the Scuttlebutt Brewing Co. in Everett, Wash. He
paddles a kayak across Puget Sound from his home in Marysville.
Though the ride takes up to an hour, versus 15 minutes by car, it
gives him an unhindered view of the Cascade and Olympic mountains,
bald eagles, seals, osprey, blue herons and spectacular sunsets on
the way home.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, ``it's a great upper-shoulder and arm workout,'' Doud
said. ``I bring an extra set of clothes, and when I get to work I
hose off with one of the brewery hoses _ a quick cold shower.
Invigorating.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
