<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Atlantic City, N.J.) _ Firing early salvos on
what likely will be a key front in the presidential battle, Vice
President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush offer competing plans for
the future of Social Security, with Bush proposing private
investment accounts and Gore advocating a version of the
traditional, government-oriented approach. By BENNETT ROTH and R.G.
RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DELAY-LAWSUIT (Washington) _ Democratic Party leaders sue House
Majority Whip Tom DeLay, accusing him of extortion and
money-laundering connected with his extensive campaign fund-raising
activities. The civil lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court under
federal racketeering statutes, alleges that DeLay helped set up
several tax-exempt conservative groups under the direction of
former aides and close political associates to raise money. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ The Clinton administration sends four
Cabinet members to persuade Congress to approve permanent trading
rules with China. The administration officials dismiss criticisms
that the current annual review of trade status with China helps
prevent Beijing's human rights abuses. By AUSTIN ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BONFIRE (College Station, Texas) _ In the wake of a
critical report on the cause of Texas A&AMP;M University's deadly
bonfire collapse, a former engineering professor suggests calling
off the event this year. The 1999 accidents killed 12 students. By
JOHN WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   WEATHER-SATELLITE (Undated)_ With the start of the Atlantic
hurricane season less than a month away, NASA launches a $220
million satellite to give the National Weather Service an important
new surveillance tool. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   OYSTER-BAR (Undated) _ An international research team, including
two geologists from the University of Texas at Austin, has
unearthed ancient stone tools in Africa that may help solve the
mystery of the geographic origins and adaptation of modern human.
The findings push back by 10,000 years the date for the earliest
evidence of shellfish consumption by humans. By TODD ACKERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   OLD-MURDER (Houston) _ A 46-year-old diesel mechanic is
sentenced to 40 years in prison for a 1980 murder following an
investigation by a special unit of the Sheriff's Department that
reopened the 20-year-old case. The mechanic had moved to California
and raised a family. By STEVE BREWER.
</P>
