<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES INCREASINGLY TURN TO CORPORATE JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE SHARKEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   We fly higher and faster,'' said Bill Wagner, a pilot. ``We can
get from Des Moines, Iowa, to Washington, D.C., in about two hours
with no delays. And we've never lost a piece of luggage.''
</P>
<P>
   But hold on before inquiring where to book your next business
trip on this astonishing airline. Wagner flies an executive jet for
the Townsend Engineering Co. of Des Moines, one of more than 11,000
American companies that own corporate aircraft. To take a business
trip on Townsend's Cessna Citation X, an eight-passenger mid-size
executive jet, or its six-passenger Piper Cheyenne propeller plane,
you generally have to be an employee or a customer of the company,
which manufactures processing machines for domestic and foreign
meat packers.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate-jet business has abandoned the defensive crouch it
went into for years after the shareholder revulsion generated by
the celebrated business excesses of the mid- to late 1980s, when
legendary corporate Champagne Charlies like F. Ross Johnson of RJR
Nabisco presided imperially over fleets of expensive jets that
could be dispatched on a whim, say to fetch a pet.
</P>
<P>
   The business has come back at full throttle, thanks to a booming
economy, a reaction against the delays and frustrations of
commercial airlines, and a pronounced change in attitudes as
corporate managers justify the expense of a company plane as a
business tool. It is seen as a productive way to transport not only
top executives, but also the middle-management teams that are
increasingly spanning out on ever-wider business trips.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate jet is ``very expensive _ so they'd better provide
a return on that investment of significant value or you cannot
realistically own one,'' said Ted Townsend, the president of
Townsend Engineering. Some big companies, like Wal-Mart Stores,
operate big fleets of aircraft for a variety of business reasons,
but even smaller operations like Townsend Engineering use planes
for functions besides transportation, including things like
shipping spare parts to outlying areas.
</P>
<P>
   Though he admits to fervently loving his jet, Townsend says that
its value is strictly practical for a company like his, a machinery
maker whose sales and service staffs have to be quick-footed,
wide-ranging and happy on the job. ``With our location in the
central part of the country, we can go anyplace in the United
States and still come home for dinner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of companies owning jets and other turbine-engine
aircraft increased more than fivefold over the last 30 years, to
more 11,000 by 1998, according to the National Business Aviation
Association. American companies now operate about 6,200 jets; 5,100
turbo-prop planes; and 5,000 helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   But the climb wasn't steady. After a steep ascent through the
1970s, sales of business aircraft flattened in the late 1980s. In
1992, manufacturers delivered 348 new business jets and
turbo-props, according to the General Aviation Manufacturers
Association. Last year, the number was 778.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long haul to change the corporate jet's image as a toy
for pampered executives, industry experts say. ``To a certain
extent, the community brought this upon itself many years ago when
they emphasized the tremendous comfort, luxury and special
privilege of a company airplane,'' said Jack Olcott, the president
of the National Business Aviation Association, a trade group that
represents corporate aircraft owners. ``The excesses of the '80s
were really only very limited examples, but they received
tremendous media attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Even corporations with big corporate fleets depend heavily on
commercial aviation for most of their business travel, he noted.
``The enlightened company uses the airlines when appropriate, and
business aviation when appropriate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fastest-growing areas in business aviation is in
companies that operate corporate jets for charter and for use by
clients who purchase fractional shares of a plane or a group of
planes, allowing them to have an aircraft available when they want
it. The number of companies with fractional-ownership deals
doubled, to 1,125, from 1997 to 1998, according to the business
aviation trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the corporate jet back, but it's getting bigger.
Boeing Co. is now marketing its new Boeing Business Jet, which has
an 807-square-foot interior _ about twice the space of other
top-line corporate jets. The plane costs about $38 million, with
another $8 to $12 million for accessories and other options. So
far, Boeing has orders for 56 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Kelley, a spokesman for the Boeing Business Jet division,
described the plane as ``basically a hybrid 737,'' with
modifications, including bigger fuel tanks that give it a flying
range of about 6,200 miles, similar to the Gulfstream V and twice
the range of the Boeing 737 aircraft used domestically by many
commercial airlines. The appeal of having a ``global presence''
accounts for the longer range, Kelley said. The size reflects a
demand for flying more people, including management teams, and
equipping them to work in flight with ``all the things you would
have in a normal office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley and other Boeing executives recently returned from a
40-day barnstorming trip on one of the new planes through Europe
and the Middle East. Negative public attitudes toward business
aircraft remain especially entrenched in Europe, where ``if you
have a private jet, you don't talk about it,'' Kelley said, adding:
``We're trying to convert people's thinking into seeing it as a
business tool, rather than it being an excessive perquisite for the
CEO, the royal barge kind of image.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley said the trip was productive. ``I flew 150 hours, 48,000
miles, in 40 days,'' he said. ``I wouldn't want to even think about
doing that on commercial flights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
