<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN DEMOCRATS ARE PART OF PHILADELPHIA'S WELCOME WAGON FOR GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANCIS X. CLINES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ As he prepares for the Republican national
convention this summer, David Cohen, an urbane political insider
and civic factotum worthy of the Medicis, is willing to risk the
ultimate rhetorical jabbing at his beloved city.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't have low expectations of Philadelphia; they had
no expectations of Philadelphia,'' Cohen, co-chairman of the city's
convention host committee, said in his 52nd-floor law office
overlooking a city that undeniably gleamed with the stuff of
renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought of Philadelphia: old city, falling apart, dirty,
unsafe,'' said the advocate, recalling two catastrophic mayoral
images that long beset this place. ``You know, Frank Rizzo lining
up African-Americans on North Broad Street with a billy club in his
cummerbund; Wilson Goode dropping a bomb on his own city.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen beamed down upon the turnaround in that image across the
last decade, an exuberant rebirth confirmed by the Republicans'
choice of this Democratic bastion above eight other contenders as
precisely the attractive, entertaining city they need.
</P>
<P>
   Basic hospitality and civic elbow grease is at the heart of the
turnaround. The city, long a modern conventioneer's backwater, has
succeeded at the breakneck task of building 4,500 new downtown
hotel rooms in the past four years. Philadelphia thereby more than
doubled its goal and finally ascended to the heavyweight class by
being able to offer the 20,000 rooms that the convention industry
requires for a city to be rated a prime destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge opportunity for the city,'' said former Mayor
Edward Rendell, still a popular politician here for conceiving the
fast-forward construction plan four years ago when virtually no one
believed Philadelphia could pull it off. Invincibly excited at the
possibilities of his city, Rendell has since become the new
Democratic national chairman in charge of defeating the
Republicans' ticket. Far from feeling conflicted, he promises to be
dancing discreetly in the streets when the Republicans pack into
town July 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the Republicans a tremendous first-class experience,
but I'll be around to respond to the content of the convention as
the loyal opposition, pointing out the hyperbole,'' he happily
promised. ``I might even wear an elephant necktie one day out of
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphians know Rendell would have donned a clown suit if
that is what it took to win a presidential convention, the city's
first in 52 years. In 1948, Philadelphia had all three, including
the Progressives. But hotel space gradually became the main
shortcoming in a city well noted for its stock of fine restaurants
and peerless settings of American history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Philadelphia is right on the cusp of being one of the
premier destination cities in America and this convention will put
us over,'' predicted Cohen, celebrating the Republican flood of
45,000 political and media visitors to a city that did not have a
modern convention center until seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It now has two, and James DiPaula, the Republicans' convention
manager who is known as Chip, is delighted to be using both plus
the city's trove of historic and cultural treasures _ from the
Liberty Bell to the Museum of Art's ``Rocky'' steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had fine local support in past conventions, but nothing
like what this city is showing us,'' said DiPaula, citing the host
committee's creation of a shuttle bus system that will operate 15
hours a day on 21 routes among 95 hotels as free transportation. In
contrast, Republicans at the 1996 convention in San Diego had to
pay $60 each for a shuttle system that operated only 8 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 residents anxious to show off their city have
volunteered as unpaid guides, drivers and greeters for a convention
that so far is an affair of symbiosis, not partisanship. Mayor John
Street, the city's ranking Democrat, garnered more than 7,500 new
local jobs alone from the new hotel space. He, in turn, is working
on new municipal contracts to make sure city workers stay aboard
the hospitality wagon.
</P>
<P>
   As Republican major domo, DiPaula savors the 6,600 miles of
fiber optic cable and the studio-quality television lighting that
blankets the city's First Union Center. This is the three-year-old
sports arena and convention hall in south Philadelphia, three miles
from downtown, where delegates will hold their sessions and flash
their campaign message to the world.
</P>
<P>
   With the Internet looming large this year for both major party
conventions, DiPaula is preparing enough electronics to serve not
just the estimated 25-million-member broadcast audience, but a more
participatory audience of another 25 million on the Web. The
convention will have extensive rows of ``Internet Alley'' space for
Web reporters and ``streaming video'' computer broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``A former speaker once said all politics is local,'' DiPaula
noted, quoting the late Tip O'Neill. ``No more: All politics is
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, politics is both and no one knows that better than
former Mayor Rendell, who worked closely with Republican Gov. Tom
Ridge to win the convention. It was the governor who urged
Republicans to ``go into some nontraditional constituencies'' and
broaden their convention image.
</P>
<P>
   Peripheral delegate meetings will be held at the downtown
convention center on Market Street, which embraces the
spectacularly refurbished Reading railroad terminal shed. The
center was built in conjunction with the Marriott convention hotel,
the badly needed keystone to the city's recovery that came close to
failing when, Cohen recounts, banks lost faith in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Marriott chain finally had to finance the hotel with its own
cash, all the while predicting it would be the city's last new
hotel, Cohen loves to note. ``Well, Marriott has since built three
more,'' he adds with an airy smile that exemplifies the city's mood
right now in awaiting the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great moment for Ed, but perhaps an awkward one,
too,'' said Cohen, who for eight years was Rendell's most trusted
adviser, providing Panza practicality for the Quixote impulses of
Rendell. But the expansive Rendell, who many expect to run next for
governor, says no problem, he will somehow manage to survive a week
that includes Philadelphia's biggest opportunity for free media
since the signing of the Declaration of Independence. About 15,000
news workers are expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could not buy this,'' said Cohen, anticipating the
hundreds of foreign and heartland television crews who, even more
than the network anchors, will broadcast the images of a renewed
city. ``It's a once-in-a-generation opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, it will be back to donkey neckties and uninhibited
partisan hyperbole for Rendell in Los Angeles, where the Democrats
convene on Aug. 14. For his city, if not his party, the former
mayor is hoping that the Republicans disprove the notion that
Democrats just naturally throw better parties. ``But the
Republicans spend more money,'' he always emphasizes, ever the
Philadelphian.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
