<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PARENT'S VIEW OF 16, THE YEAR OF COMPETING FURIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Lessons Column) 
 By HUBERT B. HERRING    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was 16 once. My mother, in the midst of tearing her hair out,
used to mutter, ``When you have a 16-year-old, you'll understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, suddenly I do, and I'm starting to.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, though, that being 16 isn't what it used to be. As
I've quickly come to realize, it's worse. I'd love to be able to
harrumph to my son, ``Why, in my day ... '' and then reel off the
horrors of coming of age in the early '60s. But once I told him I
grew up without a VCR (``You're kidding!'') or had to learn to
drive a stick shift (``What's that?''), I would have to admit that
the pressures now are far greater.
</P>
<P>
   For those out of the teen-age loop, 16 might seem just another
number on the steady climb from 0 to 21. But just look at the
pressures that our society, in its infinite mischief, has conspired
to load onto children _ or are they young adults? or what? _ in the
year following their 16th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Educational pressure is surely the worst. It used to be that we
wandered into the College Boards without much thought, looked at a
few colleges and sent in our applications. But these days, high
school juniors _ who are typically 16 _ often go to tutors or
special classes for the tests. My wife and I tried to resist this,
thinking of such prepping as a gimmick, a low-cal short cut, but
since most students do it, the playing field would be tilted
distinctly against our son without it. We succumbed, and off he
went each week to two different tutors, one for English, one for
math _ preparing to submit himself to the College Boards ordeal not
once but twice this spring.
</P>
<P>
   This time-consuming process came just as high-pressure
advanced-placement exams loomed, along with _ in his case _ Regents
and International Baccalaureate exams. That last program, as I
understand it, gets students both to learn more rigorously and to
approach learning in a new way _ noble goals indeed. It's still
fairly rare in this country, but I was glad to hear at least one
college admissions officer speak of it with respect. Innovative as
it is, it adds yet another round of exams and another layer of
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the day-to-day classroom, it has been drilled into
these students that solid junior-year grades are vital for getting
into a good college, and they feel this pressure daily, test by
test, paper by paper. To top it off, many sports-minded teen-agers
have hit the varsity level _ for our son, it's tennis _ and the
endless practices and bus trips gobble a big slice of time. Since
such activities are essential for college admission, what parent
will say no?
</P>
<P>
   Even as all this is happening, guidance counselors are telling
students they really need to start getting a sense of what the
college scene is all about. So we, like many other parents,
dutifully tried to find little pockets of time this spring to
squeeze in college visits _ to a chorus of ``No, the SAT's are that
weekend'' or ``That's the prom'' or ``I've got to work that weekend
to get money to buy clothes.'' Or, perhaps, the day came and he was
simply exhausted. (Do these people ever sleep?)
</P>
<P>
   We did manage to visit several colleges this spring, but were
flying a little blind until we knew our son's SAT scores _ and thus
which colleges would be realistic choices.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's tuition. A generation ago, a middle-class family
could probably just write the check; now, unless there's a new
dot-com or some old money in the family, that's unlikely. So, like
many other parents of college-bound students, we've had to give our
son a crash course in matters financial: there's this much money,
and beyond that you have to play a part in making the numbers add
up, whether through scholarships, loans, of opting for a less
expensive school.
</P>
<P>
   And in a cruel quirk of timing, all this often coincides with a
host of extracurricular pressures, notably that liberating,
get-out-of-my-way-world moment: getting a driver's license. One
moment they're children, suffering the indignity of having bald,
badly dressed parents chauffeur them around; the next they're
full-fledged members of an on-the-go society.
</P>
<P>
   A driver's license, in turn, expands the social possibilities
exponentially, and these, in turn, create a dire need for cash,
which means an intense desire to earn money even as all the other
distractions mount.
</P>
<P>
   Any one of these pressures could be heavy going; when they all
converge in the spring of junior year _ well, it makes my head
spin, and I'm mainly just watching in awe from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   But I wonder: Does it put too much stress on students and
parents alike to have childhood rattle over so many bumps
simultaneously? Can any tinkering be done to spread these pressures
out?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
