<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4431 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CRIM-PROFILE0504-COX     05-03 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIM-PROFILE0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crim: An optimist during turbulent time of transition
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At the news of his death today, Alonzo Crim was
remembered as the courtly, optimistic superintendent who brought
Atlanta schools through tumultuous years of desegregation and white
flight, and managed to teach the city something about civility in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``His genuine belief in community, which included all sorts of
conditions of people, was a key factor in his ability to draw
people who may think they disagree into some sort of consensus,''
recalled Charles V. Willie, an emeritus professor at Harvard
University's Graduate School of Education, of which Crim was one of
the most honored doctoral graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Crim came to Atlanta in 1973 to be the superintendent specified
in a desegregation compromise that avoided massive cross-town
busing, but required an African-American superintendent and a
balance among blacks and whites in administration.
</P>
<P>
   The late Benjamin E. Mays, school board president at the time,
took on as a personal mission seeing that Crim succeeded, said
Willie, whose 1984 book ``School Desegregation Plans That Work''
includes a chapter by Crim on Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Mays and Crim developed a mentor-protege relationship, Willie
said. ``Never has there been such a warm and intimate interaction
between a superintendent and a president of a school board. They
taught the system, as well as the students, something about the
fundamental concept of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   During Crim's 15 years as head of Atlanta schools, he oversaw
the transition of a predominantly white system to a predominantly
black system and withstood questions of academic decline. He put
the best face on things, highlighting student awards and
achievement. Critics accused him of hiding academic problems in
order to project an upbeat image.
</P>
<P>
   But history will see him as a great leader during a crucial time
for Atlanta, said Joe Martin, a board member during most of Crim's
years as superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a white businessman who often clashed with Crim, said
Crim was always professional and courtly. He handled the criticism
and political pressure of the period, Martin said, noting that Crim
often joked about his diminutive stature by saying that he had been
6-foot-8 when he first came to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saw his job as restoring confidence and showing that black
leadership could get the job done,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said he was a pioneer, in the truest sense of being in a
position no one had ever been in for Atlanta. ``He not only
survived, but distinguished himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Willie both said that Crim will be seen in the light
of history as an important figure for Atlanta and the history of
school desegregation. ``I'm totally shocked,'' said Sara Lawrence
Lightfoot, a Harvard University professor who researched Crim for
her book ``The Good High School.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of him as an extremely thoughtful, elegant, quietly
charismatic gentleman, always a gentleman,'' said Lightfoot. ``But
with some very progressive values, a commitment to all children,
particularly those children who are typically disenfranchised from
American education.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
