<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEDERAL AGENCIES GET LOW SCORES ON 'PERFORMANCE REPORTS'
 &HT;    220&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If federal agencies were private corporations,
nearly all of them would be in trouble with government regulators
for issuing annual reports that are hard to obtain, difficult to
understand and lacking in measures on how well they deliver
services, says a study released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a scorecard for 24 top federal agencies, the Mercatus Center
at George Mason University flunked the majority of their
performance reports, which were issued for the first time last
March as part of the Government Performance and Results Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agency reports should mirror standards required in the reports
of Fortune 500 companies, which suffer severe penalties if they
fail to report accurately and ethically to their shareholders,''
the academic review said.
</P>
<P>
   The report's authors said they made no attempt to gauge the
actual success of government operations, only to analyze the
quality of the information they provide the public.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Governmental Affairs Committee Chairman Fred Thompson,
R-Tenn., said the ranking of reports did not indicate which
agencies best fulfill their missions.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he said he was concerned about the agencies with the
lowest-rated reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not doing a very good job, then you don't want
people to know what you're doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Only three agencies scored high marks for their reports. They
included the U.S. Agency for International Development (which has
since been merged with the State Department) and the departments of
Transportation and Veterans Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The rest had scores of only 37 to 21 out of a possible 60
points. The National Science Foundation came in last and was
criticized for its lack of candor. Instead of acknowledging any
failures, the NSF report used only the categories of ``successful''
or ``marginally effective,'' the Mercatus study noted.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Commerce fared almost as poorly, scoring only
22 points. Not only was its report hard to find, but it was almost
unreadable, the study said. ``Slim chance that many people will
read its 180 pages laden with undefined acronyms, technical jargon,
and poorly designed tables,'' the reviewers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department's report was also among the bottom
three. ``USDA appears to consider its results disappointing but
offers no explanation of why,'' said the study.
</P>
<P>
   The review team was led by Jerry Ellig, a research fellow at the
center who previously served as an economist for the Joint Economic
Committee of Congress and research director for the conservative
group, Citizens for a Sound Economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercatus Center, which describes itself as having a
pro-small business, libertarian orientation, was established by
George Mason University and is partially supported by private
donations to the George Mason University Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.mercatus.org
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
