<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FISH AND GAME COMMISSION GETS A RAW DEAL UNDER DAVIS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gov. Gray Davis has appointed the most qualified
candidate to the California Fish and Game Commission. That is,
qualified for lining up at the public trough as one of the
governor's buddies.
</P>
<P>
   The troubled commission, which had only one of five members show
up for a monthly meeting this year, opened April with three
vacancies. That has been somewhat alleviated by Richard Theriot,
who agreed to stay on after his term expired and a replacement
could be named.
</P>
<P>
   The Fish and Game Commission is one of California's most
powerful small boards. It serves above and independently of the
Department of Fish and Game and its $208 million budget and sets
state policy for fish and wildlife management, endangered species,
introduction of exotic species and administration of state lands.
Almost as a sidelight, it sets all seasons, limits and methods of
take for sportfishing and hunting and several highly-contested
commercial fishing seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Getting appointed to the commission by the governor is
considered a dream job for a candidate who had prepared with a
lifetime of work within the conservation or wildlife management
fields.
</P>
<P>
   Since Davis was elected governor, there was a 17-month wait for
his first appointment to the commission, which can define a
governor's conservation ethic. After this long wait, and apparent
search for the right candidate, Davis appointed Michael Flores, who
comes complete with only his political dues having been paid. Here
is the Flores bio provided by the governor's office:
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Flores was named Governor Gray Davis' Secretary of
foreign Affairs in May 1999. Secretary Flores facilitates Governor
Davis' international relations and acts specifically as his liaison
for California-Mexico affairs. Mr. Flores also has administrative
responsibility for the Governor's office and regional offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secretary Flores is responsible for orchestrating the
Governor's trips abroad as well as receiving foreign dignitaries in
California. He carries out functions akin to the diplomatic corps
on behalf of the Governor; working directly with embassies and
foreign officials to ensure closer social, economic and political
ties between California and its international partners. Secretary
Flores has played an integral role in the planning and
implementation of various events including the Governor's visits to
Mexico, the visits of the Irish and Mexican Presidents to
California, and the Governor's Business Development Mission to
Europe and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to his appointment in the Governor's office in January
1999, Mr. Flores served as Lieutenant Governor Davis' Chief of
Staff. He also represented Lieutenant Governor Davis on the
California World Trade Commission, the State Lands Commission and
the State Job Training Coordinating Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Flores was appointed by former State Treasurers Kathleen
Brown and Matt Fong to serve as Chief Information Security Officer
and Special Assistant to the Chief of Staff. In this position, Mr.
Flores supervised adherence to the policies and procedures
protecting the information assets of the State Treasurer's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 1986 to 1991, Mr. Flores was an Associate Consultant for
the Senate Democratic Caucus. His largest accomplishment in this
role was the drafting of legislation to protect terminally ill
patients' insurance claims. He also composed editorial op-eds,
conducted research, and analyzed proposed legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Flores is deeply concerned with issues of juvenile crime.
Prior to his political involvement, he dedicated sixteen years of
state service to the California Department of Corrections, the
California Youth Authority, and the Department of Justice, among
other state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Flores, a native of Sacramento, received his degree in
psychology from California State University, Sacramento and
attended the graduate school of clinical psychology at Morehead
State University in Kentucky.''
</P>
<P>
   You waited 17 months for this?
</P>
</TEXT>
