<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CINCINNATI TAKES STOCK OF A LAUGHINGSTOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Cross one of the bridges that spans the Ohio River
and connects Kentucky to Ohio, and you will arrive in downtown
Cincinnati, in view of a large construction site with huge cranes,
slabs of concrete and busy workers blending like bees. It is a
jungle down there. Paul Brown Stadium _ the Bengals' new $318
million home _ is nearly complete.
</P>
<P>
   Now to stick a blast of dynamite into the Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   This is a franchise that has not produced a winning record in
the past nine seasons and went 3-13 and 4-12 the past two years.
During that span the Bengals have employed three coaches (Sam
Wyche, Dave Shula and Bruce Coslet), a slew of quarterbacks, a ton
of unsuccessful draft picks, devastating injuries and controversy
followed by more controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Bengals trudged to an 0-4 start and began
thinking about next year. The team president, Mike Brown, said
then: ``It has been our worst nightmare, worse than imagined. We've
got to go with the young guys; it makes not sense to go in the
direction we're going in.''
</P>
<P>
   After the season, the Bengals let quarterback Jeff Blake flee to
New Orleans and Blake offered this parting shot: ``I've felt the
losing aura. I've been on a team where as soon as you walk in the
facility you can smell it.'' The Bengals are about to rid
themselves of receiver Carl Pickens, who said of Coslet: ``Bruce
has never had a winning record here or anywhere else so why would
you bring him back?''
</P>
<P>
   Controversy, frustration, futility, embarrassment. Losing.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is lost on the current cast of Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have happened here,'' Coslet said. ``There has been a
lot of the `Here we go again' syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Bengals used their second-round pick to draft a
spiffy cornerback, Charles Fisher, from West Virginia. After a
dozen or so plays in their season-opening game, he was out for the
year because of a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``And from the sidelines last year,'' Fisher said, ``I could see
the problems. A lot of breakdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackle Rod Jones said, ``When you're in the NFL,
you've got to be proud of where you're at because the opportunities
are few.'' That does not keep the Bengals from being jokes and
fodder for their peers. They have been called the Black Hole of the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals also have a reputation for being thrifty, which has
resulted in protracted contract holdouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my third year here, and we've been a team that once
one or two things kind of negative happen, everybody on the team
lets that take over.'' linebacker Brian Simmons said. ``Once that
happens, you are already defeated.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the quarterback for this season, the man they hope will
return the Bengals' home field to the Jungle is Akili Smith. The
third player selected in the draft a year ago, Smith talks as if he
has been here for 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at this town and this team, and I see a lot of people
in a box,'' said Smith, who played at Oregon and grew up in San
Diego. ``I see a lot of people struggling to get out of that box to
explore more. Everybody walking through that door must know that we
can't have another season like last year. We'd get behind in so
many games by 10 points or more in the first quarter and guys would
start hanging their heads and basically give up. We're talking
about releasing some demons. The Bengals have been haunted by
demons for the last 10 or 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Bengals have been in two Super Bowls (1982 and
1989) and though both losses were to San Francisco, at least the
Bengals have been there. (There are a handful of National Football
League franchises that have never had a whiff of the Super Bowl.)
Their fans came early and stayed late and their stadium became
known as the Jungle, a frolicking place where running back Ickey
Woods did his shuffle and where quarterback Boomer Esiason made his
mark.
</P>
<P>
   Many trace the origin of the Bengals' struggles to the death in
1991 of their founder, Paul Brown. As the Bengals opened minicamp
last week, Coslet pondered what has gone wrong for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through quarterbacks here like it was nobody's
business; I've never had the same starter two years in a row,'' he
said. ``There has been no continuity in the offensive line.
Injuries have hurt us. This is not sour grapes. And it hurts you if
you dwell on it, so I have selective memory. You look at Ray Rhodes
fired in Green Bay for going 8-8 in the first year of a five-year
contract and I go 4-12 in my third year and I'm back. But it's no
surprise to me. As a player and coach, I've been a Bengal off and
on for 24 years. There is a sense of loyalty here. I've done the
best with what I've had to work with. We've got better players now.
We like our draft picks. Our offensive line returns intact for the
first time. We've got strong linebacking. Our special teams hurt us
and we've improved there. Akili will be the most important single
player on our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Real problems, though, remain. Pickens is in limbo; he will
probably be released. Ki-Jana Carter recently suffered another
setback, another knee injury, and the oft-injured running back
hopes to return when training camp opens. Running back Corey
Dillion is a contract holdout, but Brown believes he will be
signed.
</P>
<P>
   The draft produced Peter Warrick, the Florida State receiver,
with the fourth pick over all. Many scouts rated Warrick the best
player in the draft. That is Smith, a No. 3 pick, throwing to
Warrick, a No. 4. That could be a signature connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter came into minicamp this week and showed a lot of
exceptional things,'' Smith said. ``His quickness, his elusiveness.
I threw one up there and I was impressed with the way he went up
and got it. That was something I didn't know he could do. Don't
forget about Darnay Scott and some of our other guys. We've got
receivers. We've got runners and blockers. Our defense is better.
There is great hope here.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick said: ``I know how to play this game. I'm ready to play
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And he will, immediately, as a starter. Coslet said that maybe
the rest of the Bengals can learn what it takes to be champion from
Warrick, who was dominant at the collegiate level in leading
Florida State to the national championship last year. Coslet
believes that Smith has that edge, too, that feel and style of a
champion. Smith is being given the ball and the team. Run it.
</P>
<P>
   Smith played in seven games and started four last season before
missing the last eight games with a toe injury. After the Bengals'
0-4 start, he made his first start against the Cleveland Browns and
won. Smith has been in Cincinnati since Feb. 14 working with Ken
Anderson, the team's offensive coordinator. Smith said he will be
there for most of the off-season. ``I'm not going anywhere for a
while,'' he said. ``Basically, they are putting the franchise in my
hands. I'm excited but I also know there is pressure that comes
with being given the ball. I'm going through this locker room every
day trying get people on board and help get the ones out of here
who don't want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has made changes. Bigger planes for travel. Breakfast is
now served to the players and a PlayStation game for them to enjoy
is available near the locker room. The new stadium and new practice
fields are adjacent. So the Bengals now have some of it little
things that several NFL teams have long offered.
</P>
<P>
   But, receiver Tim McGee said: ``You can sleep in silk pajamas,
but that doesn't guarantee you go out and create havoc on the
field. It's about leadership and accountability. We're going to get
behind Akili and build that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
