<HEADER>
A4446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WELFARE-ECONSCENE-NYT     05-03 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: EARNED-INCOME TAX CREDIT IS A RARE WELFARE-REFORM
SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   J. Bradford DeLong is a professor of economics at the University of
California at Berkeley and co-editor of The Journal of Economic
Perspective  
 By J. BRADFORD DeLONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1990s began with a burst of intellectual and political
energy in support of genuine welfare reform. By the beginning of
the decade mainstream political opinion had finally coalesced
around the idea that the welfare system based on Aid to Families
with Dependent Children _ cash payments to nonworking single
mothers _ was a failure. Welfare recipients remained very poor, the
incentives the system gave them were horrible, and the lessons
implicitly taught about responsibility and opportunity were
destructive.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed better, according to the consensus of opinion makers,
to make a big push to shift people from welfare to work. The idea
was to bolster the wages of low-skilled workers, to provide
training programs so that long-term AFDC recipients could build
enough skills to escape the system and to offer job-search
assistance so that they could find employers who would pay for
those skills. Such an extensive welfare overhaul would be more
expensive for the government than would simple cash grants to
nonworking single mothers, but to many liberals and conservatives,
it seemed worth the price.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 welfare reform of Newt Gingrich, Bob Dole and Bill
Clinton, however, largely dropped the ball. Instead of making a big
push on training and job searching, it basically gave each state a
blank check _ roughly equal to the money the federal government had
formerly spent on welfare _ to spend as it saw fit. A few states
have used their money to do remarkable and innovative things. But a
lot more have paid lip-service to the goal of reform, and used
large chunks of the federal money for programs that the state
budget used to pay for, reducing rather than increasing the total
amount of money spent to help the poor.
</P>
<P>
   True, the number of people on welfare has dropped significantly.
But in spite of a booming economy, the incomes of the poor have not
risen significantly. Very little money has been spent on building
skills. Little has been devoted to providing assistance in finding
jobs. No one knows but everyone fears what will happen to America's
single-parent poor when the boom ends and the next recession
begins.
</P>
<P>
   One piece of the original welfare reform program, however, was
quietly put into place in 1993, as part of President Clinton's
deficit-reduction program. And unlike the 1996 law, it may prove to
be the most enduring and effective anti-poverty instrument the
federal government has ever devised.
</P>
<P>
   The instrument is the earned-income tax credit. In 1993 the
government significantly expanded the already-existing program so
that it now gives a family with two children a 40-cent payment from
the IRS for every dollar of income earned up to $9,500. A part-time
$8-an-hour job thus becomes, after taxes, an $11.20 an hour job for
the working poor.
</P>
<P>
   The tax credit means that a two-child family with a full-time
minimum-wage worker is lifted _ just barely _ above the poverty
line. Two economists at the Economic Policy Institute (epinet.org),
Max Sawicky and Robert Cherry have found that more than five of six
families eligible for the tax credit actually collect it, and that
the credit manages to push more families above the poverty line
than any other government program.
</P>
<P>
   Is the earned-income tax credit perfect? No. But, like
democracy, it is better than any of the alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   There are three standard criticisms of the program: It is a
subsidy to low-wage employers, and low-wage employers should be
discouraged; it penalizes working-class two-earner families; and it
is overly bureaucratic and complicated.
</P>
<P>
   The first criticism seems completely wide of the mark. If we
want to raise the wages of the working poor, we want to see a lot
of employers competing to hire them. To provide subsidies to
employers of low-wage labor is to raise their numbers and so
increase the bargaining power of low-wage workers in the labor
market.
</P>
<P>
   The second criticism has a point. As the income of a two-child
family increases from $12,500, to $30,850, it gradually loses its
$3,816 tax credit. When this reduction is combined with the 15.3
percent Social Security wage tax paid by both employee and employer
and the payment of income tax at a 15 percent rate, the burden on
American families earning $28,000 ends up with them paying the
highest marginal federal tax rates of anyone.
</P>
<P>
   An easy way to make the earned-income tax credit a better
program would be to reduce the speed with which the credit is
phased-out as income rises. But that takes money. Politicians are
almost always more excited about seeing their signature on some new
initiative than about improving effective but existing programs.
Moreover, the political leaders who made the credit their signature
initiative _ former Sens. Russell Long and Lloyd Bentsen in
particular _ are mostly long gone from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And the third criticism has a point as well. The earned-income
tax credit is a social insurance program administered by the IRS,
an agency whose core mission does not involve lifting the incomes
of the working poor. Moreover, the tax credit's details are
unnecessarily complex: the family as defined by the earned-income
tax credit is not necessarily the family as defined by the rest of
the tax code, and the income concept that determines whether you
qualify for the program is not necessarily the income that appears
anywhere else on your tax form.
</P>
<P>
   But this flaw could be overcome with relatively modest changes.
Cherry and Sawicky have made a proposal to fix it by simplifying
the tax credit and combining it with other child-centered tax
provisions into a universal unified child credit.
</P>
<P>
   Most important of all, even if nothing is done to improve the
program right away, the validity of these criticisms should not
blot out the tax credit's broad success: $32 billion a year
channeled to 15 million working poor and lower-middle class
families to increase their real wages and make work pay.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder whether the training and skill-building and job-search
components of the original 1990s welfare reform dream would now be
regarded as equal successes, had they been undertaken, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1626EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
