<HEADER>
A4450 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a BC-CPT-WEBHOG-ADS-SFCHRO     05-03 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEBHOG-ADS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLE MODEM ADS IRRITATING EXCITEATHOME  
 BY TODD WALLACK  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pacific Bell claims that some people find its new ``Web Hog''
television ads so funny that they're asking for copies on
videotape.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is laughing at ExciteAtHome, the country's largest
provider of cable modems, which claims the ads are misleading. The
Redwood City-based company sent a letter to Pac Bell last week
threatening to sue unless it pulls the ads.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, designed to promote Pac Bell's speedy Internet service
over phone lines, focus on an idyllic neighborhood where residents
start signing up for superfast Internet service over cable TV
lines, like the type offered by ExciteAtHome.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the service works great, the ads report. But as more
people sign up _ all using shared TV lines _ the cable modem
service slows to a crawl, and the once friendly neighbors turn on
one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Web hog!'' a group of kids yell at a middle-aged neighbor
working on his lawn. ``No. You're the Web hog!'' he shouts back.
One neighbor pours water into a neighbor's car. Others paint
garages and trucks with words like ``Log off'' and ``Web hog.'' The
ads end with the tag line: ``Get Pacific Bell DSL. Always fast.
Never shared.''
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell points out that its service uses telephone lines, which
run separately from each home to a nearby switching office. But
ExciteAtHome uses cable television lines, which are all connected,
much like a party line.
</P>
<P>
   But cable proponents say they can easily split a cable network _
called a node _ into smaller pieces as more users sign up.
</P>
<P>
   And even with DSL, once telephone lines reach the central
switching office, e-mail and other Internet traffic are all merged
together, just like cable.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Pacific Bell's own service agreement warns: ``Pacific
Bell ... operates on shared resources. Excessive use or abuse of
these shared network resources by one customer may have a negative
impact on all other customers.''
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome spokeswoman Allison Bowman said, ``We believe that
the ads are misleading to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, ExciteAtHome quietly fired off a letter to Pacific
Bell President Bill Blase, demanding the telephone company yank the
ad, according to people familiar with the matter. In the letter,
signed by ExciteAtHome executive Byron Smith, ExciteAtHome said it
``may consider legal action'' if Pac Bell didn't pull or change the
ads. (Pac Bell hadn't received the letter as of yesterday, the
company said.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ExciteAtHome executives are exploring lodging a
complaint with a group like the National Advertising Division, the
arm of the Better Business Bureau that helps sift through false
advertising complaints, one person said. Spokeswoman Melissa Walia
said she couldn't comment on either action.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Pac Bell says ExciteAtHome is just thin-skinned
because the ads zero in on a key problem with cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're upset because it's effective,'' said Pac Bell
spokesman John Britton.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the bottom line is that both services are similar.
PC World magazine couldn't find any major differences in speed in
its tests, according to this month's issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality, it is more or less the same,'' said Yankee Group
analyst Fritz McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome admits there have occasionally been slowdowns in
some neighborhoods, such as in Fremont, but says such problems are
rare.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Calic, president of Fremont's cable modem group, said he
thinks the ads are largely ``accurate, but not the whole story.''
He added, though, that he thought the ads are ``very, very funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell has also had its own service problems. At least twice
in recent months, the company has acknowledged that e-mail has been
backed up for hours or days because its mail computers were
swamped.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear, though, how a judge would rule if the dispute
actually wound up in court.
</P>
<P>
   First, ExciteAtHome would have to prove that the ads are false.
But that depends on how you interpret the ad. Pac Bell claims the
ads just focus on the neighborhood level where DSL runs over
separate phone lines, but cable doesn't. ExciteAtHome claims the ad
misleads people into thinking DSL offers a direct connection to Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those cases where it is not a straightforward
inquiry,'' said Andrew Schau, a New York lawyer who has handled
false advertising cases. He said the case would turn on how viewers
interpret the ads.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pac Bell says the ads have been running in San
Francisco, Los Angeles and San Diego since March. SBC
Communications, Pac Bell's parent company, also started running the
ads in Texas and Missouri last month. ``It's not a case where we
will just run it a couple times,'' said Beth Kachellek, SBC's
executive director for advertising.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at toddsfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &LR;
</P>
