 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Office 2000 shows Microsoft's prowess
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While I do not expect to lose any sleep wondering what
will become of Microsoft, I will say this for Bill and his Merry
Men and Women: They have given us some pretty fine software.
</P>
<P>
   Looking over Office 2000, and the portions of it that I use
regularly, it is undoubtedly the best collection of the standard
programs available today.
</P>
<P>
   Take FrontPage, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   I've been through most of the Web creation programs on the
market. The really simple ones are capable of creating only really
simple Web sites _ usually the one-page kind your children might
wish to set up. A couple of pictures, ``Hi! I'm Eric! I Love The
X-Files!'' _ that sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   The more complicated ones are, in my experience, a very mixed
bag. I put up a fairly complicated site using Symantec's Virtual
Page, and it was a chore. Strange things occurred _ like huge gaps
between one line of text and the other _ for reasons I could never
determine.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all _ and this is not all the fault of Virtual Page, by
any means _ the site looked entirely different depending on which
browser you used to examine it. It usually looked better in
Microsoft Internet Explorer. As a result, after years of resisting
attempts to shove Explorer down my throat, I began using it
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   When Office 2000 arrived, I pulled all the elements of my site
into FrontPage and worked on picture alignment, so difficult in
Virtual Page that I just about gave up using pictures.
</P>
<P>
   It looks a lot better now, although there are still some
discrepancies between browsers. That, I fear, is unavoidable. But
FrontPage is, as far as I'm concerned, head and shoulders above the
rest of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Word will certainly remain my high-powered writing program, too
_ although I must admit that WordPad meets 98 percent of the
requirements I'm ever likely to have. Most people who write, I
believe, do not make huge demands on a writing program. (I'm trying
to avoid the accursed phrase ``word processor'' here. Food may need
processing; words do not.)
</P>
<P>
   After all, what is there beyond cut and paste, paste and drag,
find and replace, spellcheck and undo? Well, it's fun to play with
fonts once in a while, put things in italics and look at print
preview to make sure you got it all on one page, but the rest of a
huge program like Word is used primarily by secretaries, and people
like professors and researchers who must write formal papers for
publication.
</P>
<P>
   The big thing in Word 2000 seems to be foreign languages. You
can set it up to write in a huge number of languages and to
translate between them, too. And, with a nod to those writers with
special needs, when you choose New under the File menu, you can
find a vast array of choices in addition to good old Blank Page.
</P>
<P>
   Writing a report? You can choose among Contemporary Report,
Elegant Report and Professional Report. I have no idea what you
must do if you want an elegant, contemporary, professional report
all in one.
</P>
<P>
   There's a legal pleading wizard to help you through the
construction of a legal pleading. Unfortunately, no simple begging
wizard.
</P>
<P>
   So I suppose there's still room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
