 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Grip it and rip it
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Nyko's Viper PSX ($30; www.nyko.com) is the slickest, most
functional, coolest, highest-tech video game controller on the
market. Any PlayStation gamer without it is underpowered. It comes
in sexy translucent colors, has an auto-fire turbo mode _ useful
for scrolling shooters _ and can function in digital or analog
modes even with games that shouldn't. The only real drawback is
that the cord is a little short and forces one to sit about a foot
closer to the electromagnetic wash of that big screen TV in the
living room. That can't be good for the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK, MA, NO WIRES
</P>
<P>
   If your Sony PlayStation controller wires are weaving a tangled
web, try MadCatz's new wireless Dual Force controllers ($40;
www.madcatz.com). These little marvels are easy to set up and a
blast to use. Plug the receiver into the controller port on your
PlayStation and you're good to go. They look and function just like
Sony's Dual Shock controllers but can be configured to function as
a TV remote, allowing you to channel-surf while the game is loading
or to mute the volume when the phone rings. MadCatz's Dual Force
controllers feel good, look cool and function perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
