</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY0502-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Based on test version, Windows Millennium's a winner
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A few weeks ago, I sat down at my computer to install
still another new version of Windows. This is the version that will
be released later this year to replace Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   As I sat there and listened to the hard disk spin and whir, I
realized I was in danger of feeling nostalgic about a computer
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mind getting misty-eyed over a sunset or walks on the
beach in Oregon, but I hadn't planned to turn into the kind of guy
who gets warm and tingly over Windows. Truth is, back when I
installed the first version of Windows ever, it was little more
than a poorly done rip-off of the Macintosh operating system. It
would have had to improve greatly to aspire to bad.
</P>
<P>
   But by now I've used all the versions, including Windows 2000,
which is aimed at the business market and was released this year.
Over the years, Windows has gotten better. And the latest version,
Millennium Edition (which ends up with the too-cute nickname of
ME), is the best Windows yet, at least on first impression. Don't
rush to the store yet. It's still a beta, or test, release, but _
to start with a highly technical evaluation _ it works real good.
</P>
<P>
   I installed the test edition of Millennium on my home PC. If
that machine was a human it would need a good therapist. So many
programs have been installed and removed, so many internal changes
have been made, that it crashes more often than the stock market
has lately. So I did not have high hopes when I installed Windows
ME.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that my Frankenstein of a computer has run
flawlessly since that moment. It hasn't frozen or crashed since.
</P>
<P>
   Now _ before I get carried away _ some disclaimers: For
starters, it's impossible to really judge something as complex as a
new edition of Windows after trying it for just a few weeks on a
single computer. And it is possible that a fresh installation of
any operating system would have made things better. But there are
some solid reasons why this new Windows should be more reliable.
</P>
<P>
   For one, Windows ME is not a radical departure from Windows 98.
That's good, not bad. Since much of the computer code stayed the
same, programmers were able to refine the way Windows works without
injecting a lot of new programs. For another, this new Windows
incorporates a technology called SFP, System File Protection. This
technology prevents new applications from mistakenly overwriting
old system files _ a fairly common problem _ and that keeps the
system more stable, according to Microsoft. For once, my computer
agrees with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Another noticeable advance is the speed with which Windows ME
loads and closes down. That may not seem like a big thing, but in
this instant world, most of us have grown to expect that kind of
response from microwaves, TVs and other gadgets. The reason for
this is technical _ Microsoft got rid of some of the old code used
in DOS operating systems that had hung around past its time _ but
you'll see the difference that has made and like it.
</P>
<P>
   The last item I'll mention may be the most important. Anyone who
has tried to use the interactive help features in Windows 98 will
appreciate this. The suggestions offered for fixing a problem were
often more complicated than the problem itself and could only be
understood by people so technically savvy that they didn't need the
help in the first place. The new interactive help truly does guide
you through fixing many common problems and doesn't start off with
the assumption that you are an honors graduate from MIT.
</P>
<P>
   Windows isn't perfect. But this new version is the most
worthwhile upgrade I've seen in a while. It's especially impressive
that I'm making this judgment based on a beta version of the
program, so _ with any luck at all _ the final shrink-wrap version
that you'll find in stores will be even better.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-01-00 1117EDT &QL;
</P>
