<HEADLINE>
NEW BIZ-TO-BIZ MARKETPLACES ARE TURNING TO OLD HANDS FOR HELP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask Michael Rothschild, the 47-year-old chief executive of
Maxager and he'll diplomatically answer that many of his young,
techie programmers are ``interesting looking.''
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to selling Maxager's product, software that
helps industrial companies determine what to bid during Internet
auctions, Rothschild sends out a sales force that's a lot closer to
his age _ people he has recruited from the basic industries that
Maxager serves.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his potential customers are themselves middle age and,
while eager to buy or sell industrial goods on the Internet, they
are afraid, Rothschild explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid with the nose ring and crazy hair may do well in our
research labs, but he's not going to allay those fears on the
manufacturing floor.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the new economy rendering obsolete the old pros of
the old economy.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more business-to-business electronic marketplaces
crowd onto the Internet, the selling of goods and services may
often seem to have turned into a youngster's game _ a forum in
which techno-entrepreneurs in their 20s and early 30s are running
the show. And in fact, that perception is pretty accurate when it
comes to writing the software, designing the Web pages and
otherwise building the backbone of those electronic services.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, though, the young entrepreneurs are recognizing
that, in the same way that their parents often have trouble
comprehending exactly what it is that they do for a living, so do
many of their prospective customers.
</P>
<P>
   And that is particularly true in the so-called b-to-b segment of
the e-commerce world, where the suppliers and purchasing folks that
make up the customer base are often less conversant with HTML and
URL's than they are with the old-economy talk of ``RFQ's'' and
``SKU's'' (Those last two abbreviations refer to ``request for
quotations'' and ``stock-keeping units,'' if any Web-heads ask; and
if they do, the defense rests its case).
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the b-to-b dot-coms are scouring the steel mills, the
auto parts companies and other basic industries, looking for people
who can talk the talk that will persuade the target customers to
switch their main transactional mode from the handshake to the
mouse click.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 30-year-old who understands the technology is an important
part of the success equation, but it takes a grizzled industry
veteran to persuade corporate buyers to change their entrenched
habits,'' said Andreas W. Eversbusch, the 39-year-old chief
operating officer for EDS CoNext, an electronic corporate
purchasing service owned by Electronic Data Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the ``grizzled veterans'' don't have to be all that
grizzled to qualify as a Mr. or Ms. Outside for an e-commerce
company. By age 32, Diana L. Wright had clocked 10 years in sales
for industrial stalwarts like Honeywell and General Electric before
becoming director of industrial supplies in February for
EqualFooting.com, an online marketplace for industrial supplies and
construction equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as a prospective supplier realizes I have similar
experiences, our conversation goes up to a higher level,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   How does she like being on the dot-com side of the digital
divide? ``I didn't take a pay cut to come here, but I would have,''
she said. ``Things are so rigid in the corporate environment, and
so stimulating here.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Diana Wrights of the world are not always easy to find.
Signing on with an e-business is by definition riskier than
sticking it out with a Fortune 500 company. Recent gyrations in
technology stocks have made compensation packages that rely heavily
on stock options _ the dot-com dangling carrot _ seem even more
risky than they did a month or so ago.
</P>
<P>
   And, Wright's enthusiasm notwithstanding, the culture shock can
be a job killer. Thomas V. Colella, a recruiter at Korn/Ferry
International, recently recruited a paper industry executive with
30 years' experience to work at a fledgling electronic paper
exchange. The man quit after six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just hated working with kids who knew nothing about running
a business,'' Colella said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Colella and other recruiters say there are many industry
who willingly heed the Internet's siren call.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who've been with an organization for 25 years leave a
chunk of money on the table, but they make the move because they
want equity and because they're bored,'' said Christopher C.
Nadherny, a recruiter at Spencer Stuart who recently placed ``a
lifer at Dow Chemical'' into the presidency of an online chemicals
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The old-economy transplants bring more than a fluency in
industrial jargon; they bring an inside track to their former
companies, which are often the kinds of customers over which
e-commers salivate.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shirley, a former Federal Express executive who is now
senior vice president for sales for the online printing service
NowDocs.com, helped NowDocs get a $30,000 contract _ its largest
single job yet _ to print and deliver training manuals for FedEx.
Similarly, Michael S. Oswald, NowDocs' staff lawyer, who had
previously worked for a software company called Acuity, has brought
in so many law firms as customers that ``Rob says he's our best
source of leads,'' said Brad Adamske, 36, NowDocs' founder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I hadn't thought of recruiting people from industry
for sales leads, but I'm sure thinking about it now,'' Adamske
said.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, NowDocs hired Tamara Johnson, a saleswoman from Xerox,
figuring she could bring entree to that company as well as to other
customers that were tired of doing their own printing. And Adamske
is wooing a salesman who he hopes will help persuade his soon-to-be
former employer to invest in NowDocs.
</P>
<P>
   After those recruited from the industrial ranks help land
clients, they can serve as translators, explaining to their dot-com
bosses how to keep old-economy customers happy.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the three founders of EqualFooting, all of whom
are tech types and thus used to working at Internet speed, had been
giving prospective buyers only four hours to respond to a
supplier's price offer. Wright persuaded them to change that to 24
hours. ``They just didn't realize that buyers are out in the field,
not tied to a desk or a phone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also persuaded the company to run a promotion in which
buyers could win free safety gloves and goggles for buying specific
amounts. Why? She knew from her own experience that extra safety
equipment always comes in handy.
</P>
<P>
   EqualFooting.com plans to set up a financing service on its Web
site soon, and the company is already looking for someone familiar
with making small-business loans to run it, according to Aaron
Martin, 30, who is one of the EqualFooting founders.
</P>
<P>
   Martin extols the value of recruiting from the old economy. He
noted that it was the people recruited from industry on his staff
who persuaded him to run pictures next to every item on his Web
page, rather than expect customers to click for a photograph. And,
at their suggestion, Martin has put industry types on his telephone
help desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier to train them on how to answer tech
questions,'' he said, ``than to teach them about industrial
supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-30-00 1648EDT &QL;
</P>
