<HEADLINE>
GROUP STARTING WORK ON NEW CYBERSPACE DOMAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Armed with a formal but vague go-ahead from one of
its advisory panels, the Internet's international oversight body
has begun writing a plan for new suffixes that would be added to
ones like .com, .net and .org in network addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The work follows a recent report from one of the group's
committees recommending that the Internet addressing system be
expanded.
</P>
<P>
   The report proposed that the group, Internet Corp. for Assigned
Names and Numbers, or ICANN, consider creating four different types
of of address suffixes, known as domains. The four new domains
would include those that are open to anyone, others that are for
specialized businesses, some for noncommercial interests and others
for personal use.
</P>
<P>
   But the report, issued on April 20, avoided many tough
questions, leaving it to ICANN's staff to make recommendations to
the board on what the new domains should be called (e.g., .per or
.shop), how many should be added, and when.
</P>
<P>
   The report also gave no guidance on how to protect trademark
holders from a new round of speculative buying of their famous
words by so-called cybersquatters, although that issue is still
being studied by ICANN members. One industry proposal would give
trademark holders an opportunity to register their names before
those words were opened to the public for registration.
</P>
<P>
   ICANN's president, Michael M. Roberts, said the staff would try
to answer the implementation questions in a report that he hoped to
release for public comment within a month. A final decision by
ICANN on how to proceed is expected at the board's next public
meeting in Yokohama, Japan, in July. It is unclear whether that
decision will include a go-ahead for introducing new domains.
</P>
<P>
   Seizing on the lack of consensus or guidance from the different
business and noncommercial interest groups that were involved in
writing the report, Network Solutions _ the company that operates
the worldwide registry for .com, .net and .org _ has proposed that
only two domains be added initially, .shop and .banc.
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions has also proposed that the new registries be
run by industry organizations rather than by individual companies.
Network Solutions was the sole registrar of addresses for the .com,
.net and .org domains, until the Clinton administration set up
ICANN in 1998 to break up that monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions still controls a large part of the
registration business. Last week the company reported that it had
registered 2 million new domains in the first quarter of this year,
more than one-third of the total number of domain names registered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-30-00 1714EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
