<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-THIRDPARTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SAY IT MAY BE TOO LATE TO DISMANTLE MICROSOFT 
 BY JOHN MARKOFF  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the government's proposal to break up
Microsoft and set new ground rules for its business practices, the
beneficiaries are supposed to include other software companies _
especially the little guys.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, reaction to the government's proposed helping hand
seems muted, or outright skeptical, among software developers _ the
primarily small and mid-sized companies that create a variety of
products that make computers work faster or more easily, or that
act as tools used by other programmers.
</P>
<P>
   Why so little rejoicing?
</P>
<P>
   Some developers view the plan the Justice Department and 17
states filed last Friday as too backward looking, aimed at a
personal computer software industry the Internet is already passing
by. And some of these same developers and others predict Microsoft,
even split in two, will remain too mighty a force to counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is the ocean,'' said Mark Eppley, a veteran software
industry executive who is president at Laplink Inc., a maker of
software that enables users to synchronize the files on their
desktop and portable computers. ``Even if you divide it into
Pacific and Atlantic oceans, I still have to swim in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eppley's company is an example of one that has been able to
continue to compete, even though Microsoft offers a similar utility
program called ``the briefcase'' as a free part of the Windows 98
and 2000 operating systems. Laplink, based in Bothell, Wash., has
been able to survive by offering more features than are available
through Microsoft's briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   Eppley noted that Laplink, like most other companies in the
software business, was now moving its products rapidly to Internet
versions. And he said he hoped that Microsoft would not develop its
own Internet formats for storing and retrieving files _ because
unified or divided, Microsoft would present a formidable
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at some other small companies still focused on the
traditional personal computer software business said they did not
see how a Microsoft breakup would create new possibilities for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not obvious where the opportunity would occur if a
breakup were to occur,'' Lawrence A. Zulch, chief executive officer
of the Dantz Development Corp., a company in Orinda, Calif., whose
software is used for making back-up copies of personal computer
data and files. ``We don't see a logical fracture line that
wouldn't turn into a dominant company that would overtake the other
one and create a new Microsoft. So it's not clear how it would help
the personal computer industry and, therefore, us.''
</P>
<P>
   By proposing to separate Microsoft's Windows operating system
business from its Office applications software business, the
government hopes to unleash personal computer makers to pursue new
business strategies and relationships that Microsoft has opposed.
The government would also be counting on the breakup to re-ignite
the kind of brushfire of innovation in the personal computer
software industry that flourished in the early days of the PC in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1990s, Microsoft had pretty well won the war for
operating systems _ the software that controls the basic operations
of a computer. But before Microsoft's Office suite of desktop
personal computer applications became the de facto industry
standard, the industry was awash with small and medium-size
software publishing firms developing hundreds of different kinds of
competing application programs. These applications ranged from word
processors, databases and spreadsheets to programs used for
enabling PC's to communicate and utility programs for helping PC's
work better.
</P>
<P>
   But since the mid-'90s, with Office dominating applications, new
investment in the software industry has largely flowed instead to
products for the Internet. The traditional software industry has
languished, with even name-brand products like Wordperfect changing
corporate owners, while many other companies merged or went out of
business and the survivors scrambled for niches that gave some
shelter from competition's risks.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, many _ though not all _ industry executives who
discussed the government's plan for Microsoft said they were
skeptical that slicing off Microsoft's application business would
create a meaningful resurgence in applications software. Besides
predicting that the spun-off company would continue to dominate PC
applications, many executives argued that there were simply no
longer enough opportunities for growth in the traditional
applications field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking Office and Windows apart doesn't seem to prepare for
the future,'' said William Gurley, a venture capitalist at
Benchmark Capital in Menlo Park, Calif. ``The majority of new
innovation and spending isn't going into desktop. It feels like
that game is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some industry executives who have battled Microsoft for
years said they could now envision new designs for software
products that might not have been viable in a Microsoft-dominated
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be selling packaged software the way we did in the
1980s,'' said Mitchell D. Kapor. He was founder of the Lotus
Development Corp., a company that was once a leader in spreadsheets
and other applications. But after the Microsoft Office onslaught,
Lotus sought refuge by selling itself to IBM in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's worthwhile conducting some experiments in new kinds
of application architectures,'' said Kapor, who is now an investor
and venture capitalist. ``If the applications aren't linked to the
operating system, there are some real possibilities for
innovation.'' But he declined to be specific, for competitive
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Some other software designers said that it would be almost
impossible to predict the consequences of the splitting of
Microsoft _ and that unintended consequences might surprise the
industry and the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't know what these things will do; it's hard to
debug remedies,'' said Daniel S. Bricklin, who was co-inventor of
the software spreadsheet and is now co-founder of the Trellix Corp.
Trellix, based in Concord, Mass., publishes an application software
program that helps users create documents suited for reading on the
World Wide Web, rather than being printed out.
</P>
<P>
   One example of an unintended consequence of the government's
antitrust case may already be taking place, in the view of Hal
Varian, an economist who is dean of the School of Information
Management &AMP; Systems at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Varian said that the Justice Department is hoping that a newly
spun-off applications company will make a copy of Microsoft Office
available for use with the Linux operating system, which many
Microsoft denigrators hope will be a viable alternative to Windows.
``But because of Microsoft's monopoly,'' he said, ``Sun
Microsystems recently began giving away a free copy of Star Office
for Linux.''
</P>
<P>
   By offering its own free alternative to Microsoft Office, Varian
said, Sun may discourage any new Microsoft spin-off from trying to
compete in the Linux market. That, presumably, would not be the
kind of competitive response the government would hope for with a
Microsoft breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, several executives in the Linux community said they hoped
that a Microsoft spinoff would create versions of its applications
for Linux, making the free operating system much more attractive to
nontechnical computer users. So far, Linux has tended to be an
operating system only a geek could love.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Microsoft shows up on Linux, everything would change; it
would be a big enabler for Linux,'' said Michael Boiche, co-founder
and chief executive of Eazel, a company designing software intended
to make Linux easier to use.
</P>
<P>
   One formerly competitive sector of the computer industry that
appears to have been overlooked by the government proposal is
programming languages, a field that Microsoft also dominates.
</P>
<P>
   Programming languages like C, C++, Basic and Java are used by
software developers to build desktop computer applications like
word processors and Web browsers. But they are also used for
creating network applications like Web-searching programs that
reside on network server computers and are queried by multiple
people using individual Web-browser programs.
</P>
<P>
   Development tools are any variety of software programs that help
software programmers do their jobs. And just as in automotive
repair, it matters whether a mechanic's tools are based on the
metric system or gauged in fractions of inches, so do programming
languages govern the basis for software tools.
</P>
<P>
   The government proposal would place Microsoft's development
tools business within the new applications company. But several
executives said that not enough attention had been paid to the
importance of programming languages in giving Microsoft a
commercial and technical advantage. Microsoft's Visual Basic
program is but one of several of the company's development tools
that help it dominate this part of the software world.
</P>
<P>
   Software developers say that Microsoft's vast influence in
programming languages not only gives the company special advantages
in developing applications; it also tends to bind outside
developers to Microsoft's operating systems and applications
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tools business doesn't seem important to people, but it's
really very important,'' said one industry executive, who spoke on
condition that he not be identified. ``If there is no vibrant tools
business than there is no applications business.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-30-00 1806EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
