<SLUG> BC-CPT-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY ANALYSTS THINK EXPENSIVE PORTAL DEALS DESERVE MORE SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV:  Photo NYT8  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last two years, Web portals, the jumping-off sites for
many Internet surfers, have grabbed a piece of the e-commerce pie
by offering retailers prime real estate on their sites. In
exchange, the portals receive stratospheric tenancy fees.
</P>
<P>
   Sites like Yahoo, AOL, MSN, Excite, Lycos, AltaVista and Go
flourished, as retailers fought for top billing within the portals'
shopping categories. In the frenzy of dot-com investment last year,
those deals cost merchants like Drugstore.com, Pets.com and Value
America between $2 million and $5 million for every portal they
signed with.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the spending made sense. Portal deals not only
provided direct access to customers, but more important, they
virtually guaranteed a pre-initial public offering buzz, as
evidence that an electronic merchant was a major force within its
retail segment.
</P>
<P>
   But since e-tailers have become Wall Street's personae non
gratae, they have had to begin thinking of marketing budgets as
something that must actually serve the purpose of attracting
customers _ not investors. And so portal deals have been the second
line item on the budget, after TV ads, to come under the microscope
of e-tailing executives no longer willing to pay hundreds of
dollars to acquire each customer.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and e-commerce executives predict that the new scrutiny
will affect all the portals, most drastically those ranking below
the big three, AOL, Yahoo and MSN.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's re-evaluating the wisdom of portal deals,'' said
Jonathan Gaw, research manager at IDC, a technology research firm.
``One reason is, we have more to re-evaluate. Three years ago,
people were pulling numbers out of the air, trying to figure out
how the deals would perform. Now we have some data.''
</P>
<P>
   And some of the data is not pretty. Jim Rose, chief executive of
MobShop (www.mobshop.com), a Web site that lets groups of customers
bid on items in hopes of getting a bulk discount, said he had tried
a partnership deal with Excite(at)Home last year. That agreement,
for an undisclosed amount, entailed putting MobShop links on
various parts of the site.
</P>
<P>
   Rose said that the company calculated the number of Excite
visitors who actually bought from MobShop, then divided that number
into the overall price charged by Excite(at)Home. After discovering
a customer acquisition cost of more than $1,000, MobShop promptly
pulled out of the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can go to another site like washingtonpost.com, and it
drops to $20,'' Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year's standard tactic among the portals,'' he said,
``was to take a category with maybe six competitors, then create
three premium tenant slots for them and let them bid up the value
until it ultimately got absurd. Now, there's not going to be as
many e-tailers left to bid, and there aren't many who really want
to, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Rose said, ``e-tailers will say, `Here's how much
we're willing to pay for customers. If you can guarantee that,
fine.'''
</P>
<P>
   Arno Harris, vice president of business development for
WineShopper.com, an Internet-only wine store, said he looked into
tenancy deals with all of the portals last year, but signed none
because they were ``economically not viable.'' The fees would
inflate his company's customer acquisition costs, he said, ``and
customer acquisition cost is the Rosetta stone of this whole
model.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he planned to approach the portals again in coming
months in hopes of finding what he called the silver lining of the
recent shakeout among dot-com retailers _ more flexible bargaining
environments. ``We're seeing more interest now among the portals in
coming to more reasonable terms,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But to hear the portals tell it, Harris and other Internet
merchants may not find many bargains. An executive at the At Home
Corp., for one, said e-tailers had renewed their tenancy deals at
rates comparable with last year's. Jon Skinner, Excite(at)Home's
senior vice president for sales, said he expected the site's
tenancy fees to remain stable. He disputed the notion that
retailers were holding out for lower fees but said they wanted
better performance. Excite(at)Home is controlled by AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner said Excite(at)Home was developing different models for
delivering customers to tenants. One strategy is to put more
shopping links into editorial areas on the site _ so-called
contextual commerce. For example, Skinner said that instead of
simply displaying a jewelry store on the site's shopping channel,
the site's producers could create an editorial page about choosing
engagement rings, and put links to the featured jeweler near the
text.
</P>
<P>
   James F. McCann, chief executive of 1-800-Flowers.com, said
performance was the watchword of the moment. McCann said that of
the company's half-dozen portal deals, ``the only ones we'll renew
are the ones that pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the company had signed a four-year $37 million
deal last fall to be the exclusive floral tenant for AOL. ``We're
happy with that,'' he said, ``because AOL really gets commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   On AOL, McCann said, he pays less than $30 to acquire each new
customer, which is in line with his company's expectations and well
below the industry average of $80 to $100.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the portals with the most visitors, AOL, Yahoo and
MSN, had fared best recently in attracting new tenants. And
according to James Kinsella, vice president for sales and marketing
at MSN, part of Microsoft, perhaps two e-tailers had dropped out of
tenancy deals because the bottom had fallen out of their stock.
Otherwise, he said, ``we've seen an upturn in the last month,'' as
media managers closed their ad budgets for the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   J. Michael Kelly, chief financial officer of America Online,
said his company, too, had avoided fallout from the financial woes
of e-tailers. That, he said, was partly because AOL screened its
potential tenants for financial soundness before signing deals, and
partly because the number of purely dot-com tenants on the site was
not significant compared with the Web extensions of traditional
retailers, like Sears.com.
</P>
<P>
   Such a weighting, some analysts predict, will insulate the
top-tier portals from the e-tailer shakeout. ``The top portals have
only a 20 or 25 percent exposure to dot-coms in terms of their
tenancies,'' said Rob Martin, an analyst with Friedman Billings
Ramsay, an investment firm. ``But as you go down the food chain, to
Lycos, Go and the others, dot-coms become a larger percentage.''
</P>
<P>
   Such portals, Martin said, ``will definitely run into issues
when the dot-coms start to run out of cash, and there definitely
will be a shakeout among the portals as the dot-coms shake out.''
</P>
<P>
   Speeding that shakeout could be the tendency of some e-tailers
to shy away from anything that is seen as second-tier.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper Evans, director of business development for Boo.com, a
Web retailer of sporting goods, said her company had shunned deals
with the top portals because they were too expensive. But instead
of settling for more-affordable deals among the second tier, she
said, the company simply looked for partnerships that relied on
marketing techniques that were more narrowly focused, like creating
a network of affiliates that refer prospective customers to
Boo.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what you get from a deal with one of the top three or
four sites is P.R. value, so you're taken seriously as a player,''
she said. ``You lose that with the other sites.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McCann of 1-800-Flowers questioned the assumption
by some of the portal executives that traditional retailers would,
in fact, continue to prop up the demand _ and thus the costs _ for
portal deals. ``Traditional retailers aren't so dumb and crazy that
they can just blindly give portals a bag of money,'' he said. ``And
they have different capital constraints: they have to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-30-00 1853EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
