<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4472 &Cx1f; ttx-z
u a BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-     05-03 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS GIG MAY NOT LAST AS LONG AS YOU HOPE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY  
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I am well past 65, but my husband and I took
enough courses to find our way around a computer. We should have
bought one with more memory. However, we are stuck, since money is
scarce when you live on Social Security. Don't tell us to go buy a
new computer! We have a 1.5-gigabyte hard drive, and I have filled
1.25 GB of that. I found that I can compress the drive and get more
storage. How will this affect the info I have in the machine?
</P>
<P>
   _ Senior Citizen
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SENIOR: If there was one thing I could rip out of Windows
and beat Bill Gates over the head with, it would be that stupid
disk-compression software. Years ago, I thought using it would be a
great way to avoid spending money to update my computer. And it
worked right up until it murdered my data.
</P>
<P>
   Software like Microsoft's DriveSpace compresses everything on
your hard drive into one big file that looks like just another
drive. When you run a program off that compressed image, the
software unpacks it, restoring it to its original size.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, if the program that keeps track of where all the
compressed stuff is gets hammered, you've got no way to get to your
files.
</P>
<P>
   With the price of hard drives dropping faster than the value of
my dot-com portfolio, I think you ought to add a second drive or
maybe just replace the first. You could probably get a 10-gig or
better installed for under 200 bucks. I know that's still a lot on
a fixed income, but it beats losing everything to some software
hocus-pocus.
</P>
<P>
   Find a local clone maker to do the work. You're more likely to
guilt him into cutting you a break than you would be with a
superstore clerk.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I tried your suggestions about running the
Msconfig program to eliminate things running in the background and
increased my resources from something like 63 percent to 80 percent
by deactivating three or four files. How does one know which
programs can be deactivated without causing major problems?
</P>
<P>
   _ Resourceful
</P>
<P>
   DEAR RES: It's fairly simple. If you take things out one at a
time, then do a restart and if nothing works right, you took out
the wrong deal. Trust me, most of the stuff running in the
background you can live without. Sure, your scanner may not scan
when you press the button, but you can always put that particular
program back in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Msconfig, for all of you thoughtful readers who took time to
write in and call me a bonehead, is available only if you have
Windows 98, reason enough to upgrade. Another thing that makes it
worthwhile is ScanRegistry. Every time you start up, it checks the
Registry and makes a backup.
</P>
<P>
   In the unlikely event you goober things so badly with Msconfig
that Windows won't even start, bring the computer up in DOS mode,
type in ``Scanreg/restore'' and press Enter to revert to a
previous, working Registry file. Don't type the quotes. Did I
really have to say that? Sigh.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Why is it that when I try something that you
suggest on my computer, I can never get the desired results?
</P>
<P>
   _ Dissatisfied Customer
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DISS: Must be your fault.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, software evolves. If I tell you how to do something
and don't specifically mention a version, you should assume I'm
using the latest. I thought everybody knew that.
</P>
<P>
   (If Dr. Emilio Bombay really keeps that up-to-date with his
software, why did he turn in this column in longhand? Complain to
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. In the nonvirtual world, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst,
editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-28-00 1404EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
