<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADDING A CENTRAL VACUUM SYSTEM TO YOUR HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A central vacuum system is a convenience, especially in large
homes, because it eliminates the need to drag a vacuum cleaner from
room to room or up and down the stairs. The heart of the system is
the power unit, which produces the suction for vacuuming. It
consists of the motor and dust-collection canister, and is usually
located in the basement, attic or garage. Because the unit remains
in a fixed location and need not be carried about, it utilizes a
larger, more powerful motor than portable ones.
</P>
<P>
   A trunk line with branches runs from the power unit to strategic
locations throughout the house. At the end of each line is an inlet
valve with a spring- loaded closure gate and a power switch.
Plugging the vacuum hose into an inlet valve will activate the
unit.
</P>
<P>
   If your home doesn't have a central vacuum system, you can have
one installed, or if you are reasonably handy, you can do it
yourself. These units cost anywhere from $500 to $1,500, depending
on the quality of construction, the size of the motor, the amount
of pipe needed and the extra features included in the kit.
</P>
<P>
   The skills required for installation are basic ones, and you
will only need a few common tools. However, in order to run the
trunk lines through the walls, you will have to drill large holes
(about 2 1/4 inches in diameter) through the floor plate. This task
can be made easier if you rent a right-angle drill and a hole saw
at a tool-rental store.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty of the installation will depend on the size,
shape and construction of your house. It will be easier to run a
vacuum line around a house with a simple floor plan and only one
level. A two-story house may require a main trunk line and a large
number of branch lines to adequately service all the areas. It is
also easier to run lines through a house with an unfinished
basement or attic.
</P>
<P>
   The first step, then, is to look at the house plan and determine
the best place for the power unit; it should be near an electrical
outlet in the garage, basement or attic. Next, plot locations for
the inlet valves. Keep in mind that you do not have to put a valve
in every room. Most central vacuum systems come with a 30-foot
hose. This is usually long enough to vacuum a room, then work into
the hallway and into an adjacent room without having to reconnect
the hose. The trick is to position the valves so they service
overlapping cleaning zones.
</P>
<P>
   When locating an inlet valve, consider that interior walls may
have obstructions, like plumbing and electrical lines. To avoid
these roadblocks, choose walls that do not have outlets or
switches. Stay away from ceiling or floor vents since there is apt
to be ductwork that feeds them.
</P>
<P>
   After establishing the location for the power unit and inlet
valves, outline the best route to connect them with trunk and
branch lines. Check your plan carefully before you start cutting
into the walls. It's a good idea to show the plan to the vacuum
dealer when you buy your unit. He may be able to offer advice on
installation.
</P>
<P>
   Begin the installation by mounting the power unit. If you place
it in the basement or garage, you will probably want to mount it on
a wall. In the attic, it's best to secure it to the floor joists.
Next, install the inlet valves. They should be mounted at the same
height as the electrical outlets. Trace the outline of the mounting
bracket on the wall. Cut around the outline with a drywall saw to
make a rectangular hole. Use the angle saw to cut a round hole in
the floor plate directly below the inlet-valve hole.
</P>
<P>
   You will have to run a low-voltage electrical line from the
power unit to the activator switch on the valve. An easy way to run
this wire is to tape it to a length of PVC pipe, then push the pipe
through the wall cavity to the inlet valve.
</P>
<P>
   Connect the low-voltage wire to the activator switch connection
on the back of the bracket. Attach a 90-degree elbow to the back of
mounting bracket. Push the assembled unit through the hole, being
careful not to dislodge the wire from the valve, and secure the
valve by screwing the bracket to the wallboard (the necessary
screws should be provided in the vacuum kit).
</P>
<P>
   The trunk lines are usually made of standard PVC plumbing pipe.
The pipe cannot be bent, so straight lengths are combined with
elbow and T-fittings to make right angles. All the pieces must be
bonded together with solvent cement to keep them from pulling
apart.
</P>
</TEXT>
