<HEADER>
A4476 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SMART-MEDICINE-NY     05-03 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SMART-MEDICINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS GADGETS SHRINK, THEY MAY WIND UP IN SURPRISING PLACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The standard advice may be ``take two aspirin and call me in the
morning.'' But it soon may become ``take these tablets, and they
will call me in the morning'' _ and in the afternoon and evening.
</P>
<P>
   That is what some researchers are predicting for the
fast-growing field of embedded computing _ a futuristic place of
microscopic medical devices packaged in grains of medicine as small
as grains of sand.
</P>
<P>
   Within the decade, some researchers say, patients will swallow
these tiny grains, and down will go microscopic sensors,
microscopic processors and microscopic radio transceivers, all part
of a delivery and communications network. The devices will, for
instance, track a medical condition and release drugs to treat it
while constantly sending wireless data transmissions on the
patient's physiological responses to a portable server in the home.
The data will then be sent via the Internet to the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   This medicine will be more than smart _ it will be downright
voluble. But it is only one practical application expected to come
out of a future wave of embedded devices in wireless networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such applications are nearer to happening than even educated
observers might think,'' said Gaetano Borriello, a professor in the
department of computer science and engineering at the University of
Washington in Seattle. He is a co-author of the article ``Embedded
Computation Meets the World-Wide Web,'' which appears in a special
section on embedded computing and the Internet in the May issue of
Communications of the Association for Computing Machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Embedded devices are already all around us. ``Ninety-eight
percent of all processors we have on the planet are not in desktop
systems,'' Borriello said in an interview. ``They are, in fact, in
cars, on factory floors, in homes.'' For example, he said, a dozen
or so processors are found in an older car, a hundred or more in a
newer one. These embedded devices are task-specific computers, he
explained, ``so tailored that you don't think of them as computers
_ for instance, the computer that controls your anti-lock brakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the future, embedded devices will become even smaller and
communicate wirelessly, as well as through wires, forming a
universe of ubiquitous networked computing, said Borriello and many
other researchers writing in the special issue. And one of the many
applications of such networks would be for monitoring, medical and
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Estrin, a co-editor of the journal's special section and
a professor of computer science at the University of Southern
California at Los Angeles, said: ``It's much more serious than
whether your coffeepot is smart enough to talk to your
refrigerator. This is the next dimension in scaling up the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrin said there would soon be numberless small devices used as
controls and monitors in fields as varied as agriculture and
environmental sensing, with nary a human in the loop.
</P>
<P>
   In medicine, embedded computers that will one day monitor blood
sugar or oxygen levels in the bloodstream with unprecedented
precision may be liberating, but they will also be quite nosy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might want a program to keep track of my habits,'' Borriello
said, ``but I might not necessarily want my physician to know when
I've been a bad boy. I can imagine programs you buy along with a
set of sensors you could wear so that information stays home
instead of going directly to the physician.'' Patients might wear
sensors in a belt or wristband and transfer information wirelessly
to a home computer. ``You could buy a health-o-meter program that
would tell you how you were doing in the same way cars have
diagnostics that tell them when to get serviced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Borriello and his co-author, Roy Want, a principal
scientist and former manager at the embedded systems area in the
Computer Science Laboratory at Xerox PARC, in Palo Alto, Calif.,
pointed to the profound issues of security and privacy that were
bound to be raised by the networking of embedded computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have to build these systems so that they have the
capability for users to determine who sees the data,'' Borriello
said. ``Right now we don't have that, and it's going to be a key
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   G.J. Pottie, an associate professor in the electrical
engineering department at the University of California at Los
Angeles and an expert in low-power wireless sensing, is one of the
researchers working on the wireless integrated network sensors that
will one day provide distributed network and Internet access for
controls, processors and sensors embedded in equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Such networks need to be self-organizing, Pottie said. ``We want
the whole network to come up on its own without people having to
configure any part of it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Borriello said one trend that would hasten the development of
networks of embedded devices was the falling cost of wireless
communications. The wireless chips that translate digital signals
into radio waves and back again, called transceivers, are now
comparable in cost with a microcontroller. Industry consortiums are
in the process of design standards for the wireless networking of
embedded devices.
</P>
<P>
   Want and Borriello both said that many challenges remained
before the interconnection of embedded processors became a reality.
One pressing issue will be the concern about privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But predictable advances in chip fabrication, in
microelectromechanical devices and in radio and sensor design are
going to lead us inevitably into the world of ubiquitous
computing,'' Borriello said. ``The major issues to solve are in
software architecture, which lags far behind the hardware.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
