<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   How Pixels Add Up To a Good Picture
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to buy a digital camera, but I find
advertisements with terms like megapixels and resolutions
confusing. What kind will take decent pictures?
</P>
<P>
   A. With the prices of digital cameras dropping to more
comfortable levels and the picture quality getting better, digital
photography has become more popular.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of digital cameras, a pixel is the smallest unit of
data in the image. Like building blocks, a bunch of pixels all
grouped together will create something larger: the image itself.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``resolution'' refers to the sharpness of the picture
the camera produces and how clear that image appears.
</P>
<P>
   A camera with a lower resolution number, like 640 pixels by 480
lines (often referred to as just 640 x 480 in advertisements),
produces a total of 307,200 pixels to display each picture.
</P>
<P>
   Megapixel cameras, which use more than a million pixels to
create the image, have a higher resolution.
</P>
<P>
   A camera with a resolution of 1,800 pixels by 1,200 lines can
produce images containing 2.16 million pixels. The resulting
pictures are much sharper than those taken by a lower-resolution
camera because the picture is made up of more pixels.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule of thumb, the higher the resolution of the camera, the
higher the price tag.
</P>
<P>
   Adjustable lenses and storage capacity (how many digital
pictures the camera's memory will hold at one time) are two other
factors that can affect the price.
</P>
<P>
   But prices for cameras in the middle of the resolution spectrum
have fallen, and it is possible to buy cameras with resolutions of
1,280 x 960 and 1,440 x 1,080 for about $300 to $400.
</P>
<P>
   The type of camera that would be best for your needs depends on
what type of pictures you plan to take and what you plan to do with
them.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to take photos that will look good if you print them
out at a traditional photo-lab size, like 4 inches by 5 inches, a
midrange camera with a 1,280-by-960 resolution should do the job.
The resolution of the printer that you are using, be it a regular
all-purpose printer or a photo printer, will also affect the
overall picture quality.
</P>
<P>
   If you want good-looking 8-by-10 pictures, you will probably
want a higher-resolution camera. If you just want a camera to take
quick photographs to put up on a Web site or to attach to e-mail, a
lower-resolution camera may be all that you need.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am getting a new computer, and I know I can transfer all of
my data from the old PC to the new one with an Ethernet cable. But
is there a way to transfer my programs, Explorer favorites and
system configurations so I don't have to kill a day getting
everything on the new machine the way I want it?
</P>
<P>
   A. A number of utility programs on the market will help you with
this problem. They will generally let you transfer your old system
settings onto the new PC in a relatively painless manner, although
the software will probably need a small dose of hands-on help from
you to get everything in place.
</P>
<P>
   Programs like PC Transplant Pro by Altiris and Desktop DNA by
Miramar Systems are expensive (about $250) and are aimed more at
computer professionals maintaining an office full of machines than
at the average home user upgrading the family hardware every few
years. But these programs give you a lot of control over what you
want to transfer, leaving behind the files you don't want or need.
</P>
<P>
   More in the price range of the typical home user is Aloha Bob's
PC-Relocator, which costs around $50 and can be ordered from the
www.alohabob.com site.
</P>
<P>
   The program doesn't let you pick what you want to transfer,
though; it simply moves everything. Your browser favorites,
programs, settings and other important files should show up in the
right place to work properly on the new machine.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(at)nytimes.com or mail to Questions, Circuits, The
New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St., New York, NY 10036-3959. This
column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
