<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4482 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-VIEQUES-HONEYMOON-050     05-03 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-HONEYMOON-0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BAD TIMING? NEWLYWEDS FIND UNEXPECTED GUESTS ON ISLAND
HONEYMOON: PROTESTERS, NAVY WARSHIPS
 &HT;    With Photo of the Bartels.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ Bob Bartels wanted to surprise his
bride-to-be with a honeymoon she'd never forget: a week of sun and
sand on a little-known Caribbean gem where deserted beaches are
lapped by azure waters.
</P>
<P>
   He surprised her, all right, but Wednesday he was wondering if a
contingent of U.S. Marines and a couple of Navy warships might
crash the party.
</P>
<P>
   Married on Sunday in Montgomery, Ala., the couple arrived on
Vieques Monday, just as a showdown between the U.S. government and
protestors camped out on a Navy bombing range appeared imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out when we got to the San Juan airport,'' said
Bartels' bride, Andrea, 28. ``He showed me a newspaper and I said,
'Oh my God, we're going to a war zone.'''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the couple found Vieques to be all Bartels promised:
quaint, laid-back, stunningly beautiful and filled with friendly
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just adds a little bit of excitement in addition to the
basic honeymoon,'' Bob Bartels said, as the couple stopped to see a
clump of protestors gathered outside the main gate to the bombing
range. ``We'll keep the newspaper clippings and have a little more
to remember it by.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartels _ formerly a public relations executive with Fitzgerald
and Co. in Atlanta, and now an employee of the Public Utility
Commission of Texas in Austin _ booked the honeymoon months ago. He
had visited Vieques once, and fell in love with the tiny island,
where horses and cows sometimes graze along the narrow roads that
wind through the hilly countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a hidden treasure,'' he said. ``Let everybody else
go to Jamaica and St. Thomas. We've got the beach to ourselves
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartels, 30, had heard about the long-simmering controversy over
the bombing range, and grew a little worried as the wedding drew
near and news reports said the conflict was heating up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just before the wedding, a friend told me he had seen news
about Vieques on CNN,'' he said. ``That got me a little worried, so
I made a few calls and decided it shouldn't be too much of a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he told both sets of parents to keep them from
worrying, he kept the trip a secret from Andrea.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept dropping hints about it,'' she said. ``I kept thinking
there might be a hurricane or a problem with the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, there have been no signs of federal agents or U.S.
Marines, although a couple of giant Navy ships have been patrolling
the waters off Vieques and military helicopters sometimes beat
through the otherwise clear Caribbean sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really won't affect us,'' Bartels said. ``We're still
having a great time. The beaches are still beautiful and the
weather is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1655EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4483 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-03 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WATERFRONT LIFE BACK WITH A SPLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After Barry Bonds' home run splashed down in the
San Francisco Bay, my wife said, ``That's it. San Francisco is a
world-class city. New York doesn't have anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we were among the lucky 40,930 who saw the first homer
leave Pac Bell Park for a dip in the Bay. And, no, my wife does not
ordinarily use the words ``world-class city.'' Usually, when
someone says their city is world-class, you know it's
Sunbelt-class.
</P>
<P>
   But not San Francisco. We have an urban ballpark with yachts
docked around it. Across the street are restaurants as good as New
York's, and condos with rents as high as New York's and just as
little room to park or drive.
</P>
<P>
   New York isn't as exciting as San Francisco right now, though.
When a home run leaves Shea or Yankee Stadium, it may hit a beer,
but it won't hit salt water.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the home run that caused my wife's
uncharacteristic effusion _ and she was effusive, objecting that
baseball officials didn't give us the equivalent of a whole inning
to cheer Bonds and his shot into salt water.
</P>
<P>
   We stood and cheered as long as we could, all us fans, for a
nearly perfect game in a nearly perfect park. Let Barry be Barry.
Who cares about the arrogance? That game was worth the price of
admission to San Francisco, all $120,000 down and $4,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   OK, San Francisco has totally unreal prices for property. But
lots of other things about San Francisco are unreal, and always
have been. Now we have the surreal dot-com economy.
</P>
<P>
   The heartening part of being at the ballpark for Barry's brine
ball was that you could still sense the saltiness of San
Franciscans, despite the wealth and slickness of the new ballpark
district of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The guy behind me may have been using a cell phone, but he was
calling someone at home to ask if a mutual friend was at the park _
he thought he spotted the guy across the field. See, cell phones
can bring us together, as well as divide.
</P>
<P>
   A young fellow in front of me wore a hat with some obscure
dot-com logo, but he was filling out a scorecard, and when Mets
manager Bobby Valentine was hit on the shin by a foul ball, the
dot-commer yelled, ``Don't rub it, Bobby.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a fan. And so was the working-class woman in front of me,
who brought her two kids and pumped her 2-year-old's arms to the
ballpark music. She economized by bringing her own snacks, but when
she ordered $12 worth of Cokes (not all that much Coke), she tipped
the waitress two bucks and the delivery man another buck.
</P>
<P>
   You can always tell the working people by the way they tip.
Here's hoping our civic leaders find some way to keep them from
being driven to Yuba City.
</P>
<P>
   People in the stands razzed Rickey Henderson and Mike Piazza,
the way good San Francisco fans are supposed to. The fans seemed
awe-struck by the amenities of Pac Bell Park, as if they had been
cowed by years of abuse by Candlestick Park.
</P>
<P>
   On the way back from the park on the streetcar, everyone treated
each other with the greatest of respect. There was banter about
sardines and the Japanese subway system, but no prickliness,
N-Judah rage or much resentment of the Municipal Railway.
</P>
<P>
   Muni is trying, and not doing such a bad job, considering the
system needs fleets of cars going in two directions from
Embarcadero Station at rush hour. Even the traffic didn't look that
horrible, at least to someone who wasn't in it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the dire predictions, the people of the Bay Area
have risen to the very special occasion of going out to the
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   As we Muni sardines passed along the waterfront with our noses
jammed involuntarily against the windows, we stared at the fancy
restaurants and workout rooms filled with beautiful bodies on
treadmills.
</P>
<P>
   When I made a crack about people going out at night to run in a
window, the craggy and work-worn baseball fan in front of me said,
``If I looked that good, I'd run in a window, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy had every right to be resentful of San Francisco's new
class of buffed and stock-optioned young people, but he was
generous and humorous about them. It was so damn San Francisco of
him.
</P>
<P>
   Resenting the rich is a great game in this country where
everyone wants to be rich. The game gets very confusing in San
Francisco, a socialite-ruled, near-socialist city that sits atop
entrepreneurial Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Another old game in San Francisco is resenting newcomers. Again,
the game is confusing because newcomers sweep into town every
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five years ago, the hippies arrived in search of peace
and love in a world where material things besides a good stereo
wouldn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Now the dot-com kids are arriving in search of the hottest Web
innovation, the coolest restaurant and enough material success that
they can retire and find peace and love at age 35.
</P>
<P>
   You know what? We can rail against them in the abstract, or rage
against their SUVs and Beemers when they're sealed inside them. But
still, they're San Franciscans, and at the ballpark or on Muni the
usual rules of respect apply.
</P>
<P>
   Funny how one horsehide ball hitting fuel-slicked water can make
you feel so good. I honestly thought it was going to be just a
gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   When my wife and I got back downtown, cars parked on the street
were lightly sprinkled with drops of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they got splashed by that ball,'' my wife said.
</P>
<P>
   No, she wasn't on drugs, just $6 beers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1655EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
