<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, May 4. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (Dateline to kum) _ Seven U.N. soldiers have
been killed in clashes with rebels in Sierra Leone and about 50
have been captured, a U.N. spokeswoman said on Wednesday. (Summary
from wires)
</P>
<P>
   PANAM103-TRIAL (Camp Zeist, Netherlands) _ Nearly 12 years after
a jumbo jet blew up in the skies of Scotland, raining bodies and
flaming debris down on the village of Lockerbie, the trial of two
men accused of that terrorist act begins Wednesday. By Donald G.
McNeill Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-MADCOW (Buellas, France) _ The number of cases of mad cow
disease discovered in France has been climbing steadily. The totals
are still miniscule compared to Britain, which has reported 178,000
cases of the deadly degenerative brain disease since 1986, and
endured a ban on its beef by European nations. But what is alarming
in France is that the numbers are going up, given that preventive
measures were put into place in 1991 and then even stricter ones
were ordered in 1996. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-BRITAIN-MARKETS (London) _ The London and Frankfurt
stock exchanges announced plans for a full merger and an alliance
with New York's tech-heavy Nasdaq exchange on Wednesday, seeking to
build a pan-European trading heavyweight and a 24-hour global
market in new economy stocks _ both unthinkable only a few years
ago. The combined exchange will be Europe's biggest by far. The
announcement offered the most dramatic evidence to date of a
sea-change in European markets, driven by a clamor among investors
for cheaper trading, a challenge from Internet-based and electronic
trading systems and an increasing trend to treat Europe as a single
investment arena following the introduction of the euro. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The Dow Jones industrial average plunged
more than 300 points Wednesday as interest-rate worries weighed on
the market and investors punished companies that warned of slowing
earnings growth. Weakness in blue-chip stocks spread to the broader
market, sending the Nasdaq composite down nearly 200 points.
(Summary from wires) By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AUTISM (Undated) _ Children who become autistic or mentally
retarded during the first few years of life may have abnormally
high levels of four brain chemicals that can be detected the day
they are born with a blood test, scientists reported. Since each of
these chemicals plays a major role in constructing animal brains,
the finding supports what many experts believe may be the root
cause of both autism and mental retardation: faulty wiring present
from birth. By Sandra Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANTIROCKET-LASER (Undated) _ The Israeli Defense Ministry
formally announced Wednesday that it would deploy an advanced laser
system along the northern border that would be capable of shooting
down guerilla rockets after Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon this
summer. Dan Weinreich, a Defense Ministry spokesman, said that the
$250 million system is in the final stages of testing in the United
States and Israel. Designed and built by a California defense
contractor, TRW, for Israel and the U.S. Army, the powerful laser
and its tracking system was successfully tested against stationary
targets last week at the White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico,
said Lt. Gen. John Costello, commander of the Army Space and
Missile Defense Command. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-THERAPY (Undated) _ Researchers at St. Elizabeth's
Medical Center in Boston failed to report the death of a patient
during gene therapy experiments there and may have contributed to
the growth of cancer in another patient, an event also not properly
reported, according the Food and Drug Administration investigators.
By Philip J. Hilts.
</P>
</TEXT>
