<HEADER>
A4497 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ROAD-SAFETY04-COX     05-03 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROAD-SAFETY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS URGED TO WARN TRAVELERS OF ROAD DANGERS ABROAD
 &HT;    By ANGEL WILSON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Road accidents will become the third greatest
health burden worldwide within 20 years, members of Congress were
told Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   About 1 million people worldwide die annually from road deaths.
Of these, nearly 80 percent occur in developing countries. Road
accidents are the leading cause of death and serious injury to
healthy Americans traveling abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla., hosted the Association
for Safe International Road Travel's ``Day on the Hill'' to urge
survivors of international motor accidents to speak to lawmakers.
The goal, Wexler said, is to convince Congress that the United
States must warn its citizens of dangerous traffic conditions
overseas and actively work with developing countries to improve
road and traffic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Ross, former technical director and road safety adviser of
the Global Road Safety Partnership, said that by 2020 road
accidents will become the third greatest health burden, knocking
HIV/AIDS down to around number 10 or 11.
</P>
<P>
   Ross urged the U.S. government to become active members of the
fight against such tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a superpower, it is an obligation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank, which conducted a study concerning the amount of
money involved in road accidents, has also gotten involved in the
fight. According to the study, the global economy loses $500
billion annually to road accidents. In cooperation with several
other governments and private sector organizations, the Bank
created the Global Road Safety Partnership, whose goal is to
improve road safety worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Road safety is an issue of immense human proportions, it's an
issue of economic proportions, it's an issue of social proportions,
and it's an issue of equity. Road safety is an issue that very much
affects poor people,'' said James D. Wolfensohm, president of the
World Bank Group.
</P>
<P>
   Wexler circulated a letter to Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright urging the State Department to expand the information it
compiles on traffic accidents worldwide and to make it more readily
available to international travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Such information would highlight road conditions, traffic
customs _ such as which countries drive on the left side of the
road and which don't require use of headlights at night _ and
statistics on which countries have the highest international
traffic death rates.
</P>
<P>
   Wexler and his wife, Laurie, have a personal interest in the
issue. The son of their daughter Rachel's fourth-grade teacher was
killed, along with 22 other passengers, in a bus accident in Turkey
five years ago Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since that time, the teacher, Rochelle Sobel founded the
Association for Safe International Road Travel, which educates
Americans on international road and traffic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   On the web: Association for Safe International Road Travel:
www.asirt.org/
</P>
<P>
   Angel Wilson's e-mail address is angelw(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
