<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4508 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NURSES0504-COX     05-03 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSES0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nurses celebrate fifty years of friendship
 &HT;    By Kim Folstad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The mementos smell a little musty. The
yearbook is starting to yellow, and some of the pictures pasted to
the scrapbook pages are curling at the corners.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The memories are still fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years have gone by since their graduation from Good
Samaritan Hospital's School of Nursing, but the women of the Class
of 1950 are still close, and the history they share remains dear.
</P>
<P>
   Kay Clark Wheat was the funny one. Still is. Jean Acuff was the
best student. They called Gloria Gaines Foster ``Speedy'' because
she was always in a hurry. Nancy Haddock, who became an operating
room nurse, was nicknamed ``Fearless.''
</P>
<P>
   They were all bright and brave and caring. That's why they chose
nursing ... or it chose them.
</P>
<P>
   For three years, the 15 women lived together, worked together,
played together. ``It was like a big family, really,'' Wheat says.
</P>
<P>
   And so, like family, they all make the effort to get together
every few years. In five decades, they've held 15 reunions.
</P>
<P>
   This year's reunion was special, though: The class marked its
golden anniversary. Thirteen of the 14 surviving graduates were in
West Palm Beach recently for the celebration, and a luncheon was
held at the Good Samaritan Medical Center. They used the time to do
a little catching up and a lot of reminiscing about their days at
the school.
</P>
<P>
   The nurses _ retired now _ still make faces about the
green-and-white-striped seersucker uniforms they had to wear for
their first six months of training. They roll their eyes about the
old curfew, too: 8:30 p.m. the first year, 10 p.m. the second, and
finally a bearable 11:30 that senior year at Good Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Those who were especially daring would try to sneak out anyway,
with a raincoat over their pajamas. But ``Mother White,'' house
mother at Dodge Hall, the lodge where the nursing students lived on
the hospital campus, made it tough. Getting in was sometimes
easier: A gal could always look for engineer Jim Thompson, who
might be willing to prop a ladder up to the second-floor fire
escape.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, the students were under the watchful eye of John
Wymer, who began his 34-year tenure as hospital administrator when
the Class of 1950 was starting its first year of training. ``He
took care of us,'' says Louise Dorothy Muller, a West Palm Beach
native who came from New Jersey for the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   The nurses liked and admired Wymer so much, they made him an
honorary member of their class. And he tells the best stories of
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no air-conditioning,'' Wymer says. ``The season then
was about three months long. Then we had to sweat out a half-empty
hospital.'' But the nurses found ways to keep cool: During the day,
they'd walk to the beach. At night, there were the ``submarine
races.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the girls from Good Sam managed to get their share of
attention around town.
</P>
<P>
   Wymer also will tell you that this is a special group of women,
and the training they received 50 years ago at Good Samaritan _
before the big, new medical center dwarfed the old hospital behind
it _ were top-notch even by today's standards.
</P>
<P>
   The school, which opened in 1923 and closed in 1961, offered a
three-year nursing education that was more hands-on than other
programs. It included off-campus instruction for tuberculosis
nursing in Orlando, psychiatric nursing in Chattahoochee and a
month at the Palm Beach Crippled Children's Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got theory in junior college. We got practical on-the-job
training,'' says Marylou Garner Rogers Smith, who later became the
first director of nurses for the Martin County Public Health Unit.
</P>
<P>
   At the hospital, the student nurses were assigned patients and
worked the wards in crisp white uniforms, white shoes and white
caps.
</P>
<P>
   About those caps: Each nursing school's has a unique style _ the
difference is in the fold. The women in the class of 1950 had their
``capping ceremony'' after six months of probation, and they still
remember how special they felt that day.
</P>
<P>
   Few nurses wear their caps anymore, of course. Times have
changed, and so has the dress code at most hospitals. ``It took me
a long time to break down,'' says Wheat, who spent most of her
career at Good Samaritan. ``To me, that gave me _ this is kind of
corny _ that was my dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   The cap isn't the only thing that's changed over the years, and
the changes haven't always been for the better, Wymer and the
nurses say. Things have gone from ``high touch to high tech,'' and
they worry about what's been lost. ``This is the age of
specialty,'' says Haddock. ``Then, there weren't the specialties _
pediatrics, the ICU, the ER.'' Good Samaritan didn't have an
intensive care unit. ``So no matter how traumatized the patients
were, we took care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The interest and care the nurses gave their first patients is
evident in the photographs they've included in their yearbook and
scrapbooks. Along with shots of the beach and their dorm rooms,
there are photos of them cuddling babies in the hospital nursery
and swimming with patients from the Crippled Children's Clinic.
Notes from former patients thank them for their kind words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, the patient came first,'' Wheat says. ``Now, the
paperwork comes first. That's the reason I retired.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, they all say they encourage both women and men to follow
in their footsteps. And each puts her money where her mouth is,
donating generously to the John F. Wymer Jr. Endowed Professorship
in Nursing at Florida Atlantic University.
</P>
<P>
   They also say _ and this is perhaps the most significant sign
that the school did a good job preparing them for a challenging
career _ they'd do it all again. Nursing isn't an easy profession,
it isn't financially rewarding, and few find fame. But it has its
own rewards, the women of the Class of 1950 agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love each other,'' Foster says. ``And we loved what we were
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   So together they celebrated 50 years of friendship _ and three
unforgettable years of learning that sent them on their way.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4512 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NURSES-DATES0504-COX     05-03 0317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSES-DATES0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Important dates in the history of nursing education
 &HT;    Compiled by Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   1836 _ Theodor Fliedner reinstitutes the Order of Deaconesses
and opens a small hospital and training school in Kaiserwerth,
Germany, where Florence Nightingale, ``The founder of Modern
Nursing,'' receives her training.
</P>
<P>
   1872 _ Women's Hospital, Philadelphia, and New England Hospital
for Women and Children, Boston, open training schools for nurses.
</P>
<P>
   1873 _ Linda Richards graduates from New England Hospital for
Women and Children school of nursing and becomes known as America's
first trained nurse.
</P>
<P>
   1879 _ Mary Eliza Mahoney graduates from New England Hospital
for Women and Children school of nursing and becomes known as
America's first trained African-American nurse.
</P>
<P>
   1885 _ Clara Weeks Shaw publishes the first textbook written by
an American nurse titled ``Textbook of nursing for the use of
training schools, families and private students.''
</P>
<P>
   1894 _ The University of Texas establishes a school of nursing
as a regular division in its medical department.
</P>
<P>
   1907 _ Mary Adelaide Nutting joins Teachers College, Columbia
University, New York, and becomes the first professor of nursing in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   1908 _ National Association of Colored Graduate Nurses is
established.
</P>
<P>
   1917 _ National League of Nursing Education publishes its first
``Standard curriculum for schools of nursing.''
</P>
<P>
   1952 _ Associate degree education for nursing begins in an
experimental project at Teachers College, Columbia University, New
York, by Mildred Montag.
</P>
<P>
   1953 _ National Student Nurses Association is established.
</P>
<P>
   1973 _ American Nurses Association starts certification programs
for nurses in specialty areas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
