<P>
   GERMANY-BRITAIN-MARKETS (London) _ The London and Frankfurt
stock exchanges announced plans for a full merger and an alliance
with New York's tech-heavy Nasdaq exchange on Wednesday, seeking to
build a pan-European trading heavyweight and a 24-hour global
market in new economy stocks _ both unthinkable only a few years
ago. The combined exchange will be Europe's biggest by far. The
announcement offered the most dramatic evidence to date of a
sea-change in European markets, driven by a clamor among investors
for cheaper trading, a challenge from Internet-based and electronic
trading systems and an increasing trend to treat Europe as a single
investment arena following the introduction of the euro. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The Dow Jones industrial average plunged
more than 300 points Wednesday as interest-rate worries weighed on
the market and investors punished companies that warned of slowing
earnings growth. Weakness in blue-chip stocks spread to the broader
market, sending the Nasdaq composite down nearly 200 points.
(Summary from wires) By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
