<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4516 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-BROKERS-EBAY-NYT &LR;      05-03 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BROKERS-EBAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROKERS FIND A NICHE ESCORTING NOVICES INTO THE WORLD OF EBAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By KAREN J. BANNAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Liz Parella had a big problem. She needed to sell a Baldwin baby
grand piano that was taking up too much space in her New York City
apartment. She got in touch with an antiques dealer, but the dealer
offered her only $1,000, far less than what she thought the piano
was worth.
</P>
<P>
   By chance, Parella, a secretary at a financial management firm,
saw a magazine advertisement for an eBay broker service. Although
she knew about online auctions, at that point she had never used
the Internet. On a whim, she decided to give the broker a call and
subsequently entered the online auction market by proxy.
</P>
<P>
   As the term implies, eBay brokers photograph, list, sell and
ship auction items for people who cannot do it themselves or do not
want to. Some people, like Parella, say they do not have the online
know-how needed to list an item for sale. Others just want to avoid
what they consider to be the hassle of posting, selling and
shipping items.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Temkin, the eBay broker who sold Parella's piano, said: ``I
got the idea from observing that a lot of people I knew were
interested in selling things online but just didn't have the time.
We live in a very service-driven society. I've been a booker at
Ford Models; I've sold real estate. I've always been involved in
customer service. This is just another way of using my talents.''
</P>
<P>
   Temkin, a full-time eBay broker in New York, charges a flat-rate
listing fee of $10 and a 25 percent commission on each item's sale
price (with no extra charge for eBay's fees). The listing fee is
nonrefundable even if an item does not sell, and that happens
frequently, especially with items that have high reserve prices,
the lowest prices sellers say they will take.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike antiques dealers or secondhand-goods dealers, Temkin does
not set prices. She lets customers decide how much they want for
each item. If they do not know, she will help them find reputable
appraisers.
</P>
<P>
   Temkin, who said she was doing very well with her business,
specializes in expensive items like jewelry and art. She will not
accept items like $5 Beanie Babies or $50 home furnishings. ``By
the time someone pays my commission and listing fee, it would cost
them more than if they just gave it away to charity,'' Temkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike and Cheryl DeWolfe, brokers in Victoria, British Columbia,
also limit the types of items they list. They specialize in store
liquidations and collectibles and have sold board games,
knickknacks and figurines on eBay for clients, most of whom find
them through word-of-mouth. Mike DeWolfe also runs a Web
development service.
</P>
<P>
   The DeWolfes have expanded their eBay business to include buyer
services. A customer, usually a collector, can hire them to find a
specific item and purchase it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife goes online for a customer _ she can usually get an
item cheaper online for a collector than she can if she buys it
locally, even with our commission,'' DeWolfe said. The DeWolfes'
commission is 50 percent of the seller's profit on an item. They
spend 30 to 35 hours each week scrutinizing eBay's millions of
listings and buying and selling items for customers.
</P>
<P>
   The DeWolfes also cater to clients with items too inexpensive
for them to list. They offer such customers coaching and computer
templates that make it easy to post items on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Brokering is more of a sideline for Steve Eaton, the owner of
the Hotlink Cyber Cafe in Romeo, Mich. Eaton, who advertises his
service in the local newspaper, and his store manager, Amber Mills,
sell items like wall hangings, Pokemon cards and computer equipment
for customers. Most of their customers are, like Parella was,
people who have never been online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers can come in, bring their item, and we take care of
everything,'' Eaton said. ``We scan or photograph the item, take
care of the posting and bidding process and handle the payment and
shipping.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the commission and listing fees, which are much higher
than the 1.25 percent to 5 percent commission and listing fee of 25
cents to $2 that eBay charges, most eBay broker users come out
ahead, compared with what they would pay an offline consignment
shop.
</P>
<P>
   Most consignment stores charge a commission of 30 percent to 50
percent, based on each item's sale price. Most will not take large
items, like the piano that Parella sold. And upscale auction
houses, like Christie's and Sotheby's, will not bother with
inexpensive items.
</P>
<P>
   Although eBay brokers are starting to be seen across the
country, their services are not available directly through eBay,
said Matt Bannick, the company's vice president for product and
community. Instead, eBay will integrate a question-and-answer
service offered by Keen.com into the eBay site so users can help
others. Under a three-year agreement announced on Tuesday, eBay
users will be able to pay a fee for answers to questions about how
to list and buy items.
</P>
<P>
   Bannick said eBay's community boards also offered help. ``People
can post questions, and other users post responses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Parella is pleased with her experiences with an eBay
broker. Two weeks after the antiques dealer offered her $1,000, her
piano sold for just under $4,000 on eBay. Since listing her piano,
Parella has used Temkin's service six additional times to list two
Japanese woodblock prints, two handbags, a necklace and a bracelet.
Although only four of her seven items sold, Parella said she would
use the eBay broker service again.
</P>
<P>
   ``For items that she wouldn't be interested in selling, we might
do it ourselves,'' Parella said. ``But using someone like Liz, who
is extremely professional and kept us from having to deal with
e-mail and all the bother, is a real time saver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful to sell things and get rid of stuff. Downsizing
is great when you're not just throwing things away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1710EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
