<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4519 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SHEEP-SHEARERS0504-CO     05-03 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEEP-SHEARERS0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shear agony
 &HT;    By Marija B. Vader
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ It's spring: sheepshearing time in the
Rockies' verdant valleys.
</P>
<P>
   At Oscar Wyatt's Morapos Ranch, nestled in an oxbow of the White
River between Meeker and Rangely, sheepshearing takes on an
international flavor.
</P>
<P>
   For one week each year a flock of international shearers,
including many New Zealanders, clips the wool of some 7,000 sheep
here to prepare the animals for lambing season and summertime
mountain grazing.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign voices seem incongruous in the bucolic setting _
placid rolling hills, stretching for miles to the base of rugged
peaks, even a quaint, red log house for the ranch manager.
</P>
<P>
   On the sheepshearing platform, there is no idle chatter.
</P>
<P>
   Bent at the waist, New Zealander Jimmy Clark seems to work a
dance with each sheep, moving his electric hand shearer quickly,
but gently and gracefully, over the animal from head to hoof, while
a perpetual drop of perspiration poises indeterminately at the tip
of his nose.
</P>
<P>
   During the time a nearby boom box blasts Led Zeppelin's
``Stairway to Heaven,'' Clark sheds two sheep of their fleece.
</P>
<P>
   The shearers enjoy loud music with a heavy beat, perhaps to
drown out the interminable drone of the electric shears. Sheep
after sheep after sheep, 12 shearers work in a nonstop, no-nonsense
methodical, mechanical manner.
</P>
<P>
   These guys aren't the big, bulky men one might think they'd be
from the hard physical work of manhandling that many sheep. They're
tall but wiry, strong but slender, and constantly bent at the
waist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything hurts when you learn to shear _ your hands, back,
legs, arms, but you get fit to it,'' says New Zealander Stuart
Caldwell, 36 and in his 12th year shearing on the international
circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have three years of pain, then you get over it,'' agrees
Keith Oliver, at age 48 the oldest in the crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disease, shearing,'' Caldwell adds with his thick Kiwi
accent. ``Once you get it, you're hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lifestyle's good. It's hard sometimes to put the finger on
it, but you always meet new people all over the world,'' Caldwell
says. ``It keeps us alive. No one's getting rich. We keep coming
back, we've got to.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it makes the beer taste better afterwards,'' he adds,
grinning. ``We do play fairly well, too. We go into town _ there's
always something to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   But while working, the quick shearers take only a few brief
moments to clip the fleece from the beast, nudge it off the
shearing platform, then reach for yet another sheep from a chute
that feeds the shearing wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the shears slip, clipping a bit of skin, leaving a red
bloody streak on the white wool.
</P>
<P>
   Some sheep appear dazed as they leap off the platform, as if
asking, ``What just happened to me?''
</P>
<P>
   Others scamper off to huddle with their sheep pals, bleating.
</P>
<P>
   Shearers are paid by the piece _ $1.50 per fleece, while the
backup crew of fleece handlers and the press operator split 21
cents per fleece.
</P>
<P>
   That's good money, especially when quick shearers clip up to 250
sheep a day.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell bought a house last month in his hometown of Piopio, on
the north island, but he hasn't moved in yet because he was
shearing sheep in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   His girlfriend lives in England, the group's next stop on the
shearing world tour.
</P>
<P>
   From there, he'll venture on to Wales, Australia, and then to
his new home, where the shearing season lasts through the Northern
Hemisphere's winter.
</P>
<P>
   The shearers realize the limitations of the physical work and
say that's one deterrent to attracting young people to the line of
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do it forever. There's not enough money in it and
it's hard physical work,'' Oliver says. ``If something better comes
along, you hang up your handpiece and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   To greener pastures.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
