<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4521 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SOLDIER-GAME-NYT &LR;      05-03 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SOLDIER-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN PUSHING THE ENVELOPE FOR CREATIVE VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (Editors: product notes at end of article)  
 By PETER OLAFSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Soldier of Fortune'' does not simply push the envelope for
computer-game violence. It seals the envelope, stamps it and posts
it, then empties a clip into the mailbox for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   In fundamentals, this new first-person shooter developed by
Raven Software doesn't appear significantly different from similar
games on the market. Cast as a mercenary on the trail of stolen
nuclear warheads, the player explores a hostile three-dimensional
environment through 26 game levels spread over 10 missions, lays
waste to a host of enemies and uses an array of weapons and
supplies to clear a path.
</P>
<P>
   The twist: You can inflict wounds with unprecedented
specificity. In most shooters, every hit to an enemy does the same
amount of damage, regardless of its location on that enemy's body.
(For instance, in Nova Logic's recent Special Forces shooter,
``Delta Force 2,'' you can kill enemies as effectively by shooting
them in the foot as in the head.)
</P>
<P>
   However, 1998 releases like ``Sin,'' ``Vigilance'' and ``Tom
Clancy's Rainbow Six'' introduced the concept of ``one shot, one
kill'' _ with wounds to the head instantly fatal _ and ``Soldier of
Fortune'' extends this conceit to the rest of the virtual body. An
enhanced version of Id Software's ``Quake II'' game engine allows
the player to hit 26 zones on the polygonal enemy bodies, with
results that range from the disturbing to the practical.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with all the violence options enabled, I shot off
enemies' legs in the opening level in the New York subways. I shot
off arms aboard a speeding freight train in southern Africa. I left
chests and groins spattered with blood in the Kosovo sewers. (When
enemies fell forward, I could see the exit wounds.) In an Iraqi
marketplace, guts poked out of the hole I had drilled in an enemy's
midsection. In Siberia, I liberated some heads from their bodies
and reduced others to something resembling partially eaten apples.
</P>
<P>
   And when I finished a level, I was provided with a checklist of
carnage performed, including ``throat shots,'' ``head shots'' and,
ahem, ``nether region shots.'' These are unusual things for a
computer game to be adding up.
</P>
<P>
   Does the game go too far? Initially, I would have said yes. How
many ways should you really see an enemy's head explode? (``Soldier
of Fortune'' is not suited for children. Parents and the squeamish
will be grateful for a password-protected filter that allows users
to disable five violent elements in the full-violence version. A
``tactical low-violence'' version is also available in which the
filter is permanently enabled.)
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out that once you've seen one screaming soldier
with his leg shot off, you've seen them all. The effects are
shocking the first few times around, and then they begin to recede
into the body of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there is something to be said for a game that offers
enduring evidence of the player's passage through the game world.
Details like bullet holes and bloodstains on walls helped make
``Duke Nukem 3D'' a huge hit in the mid-'90s, and it might be
argued that ``Soldier of Fortune'' represents the next bloody
footstep in this trend.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment of violence isn't the only creative twist. Soldier
takes a novel approach to saved games. Saves are snapshots of the
player's position, which enable one to resume play from a given
point at a later time. Most three-dimensional shooters allow saves
at any point during the game _ a strategy that allows players to
finish games more easily, but one that, when abused, can squeeze
the fun out of a game by sacrificing its challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Soldier gears the number of saves allowed within a game level to
the difficulty level selected at the start of a new game _ from
unlimited at the Effortless level to five at the Medium level to
none at the Unfair level. At the harder levels, this turns saving
from a simple reflex into a strategic decision. Can you finish the
rest of an unseen level with the available saves?  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Soldier also takes a step toward addressing reduced capacity
in injured enemies. In most games, enemies simply pound away at the
player until they are killed, regardless of the level of damage
they have taken. Soldier of Fortune interrupts this cycle. A shot
to the leg may leave a live enemy hopping on one foot, and the
hopping means that at least for the moment, the enemy isn't
shooting at the player. You can also force enemies to drop their
weapons and surrender or flee the field. The game in which enemies
and the player lose proficiency as they take damage still awaits
us, but in the meantime, it's agreeable to find other ways to
resolve combat.
</P>
<P>
   Gore finds its justification only in what it adds to game play,
and when the novelty of blood-spouting necks wore off, I found
myself wishing this advanced damage model had served as inspiration
for other elements of the game. The creators seem so taken with the
depictions of violence that they have neglected the fear and dread
that the carnage should inspire in its victims and perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   Enemies with such diverse vulnerabilities should be smart enough
to better protect their nether regions _ they are little more than
the usual bunch of dumb bunnies _ and engagements should be smaller
and more tactical. After all, when you are going up against an army
of enemies who are all blazing away at you, you don't have time to
try for critical hits. All you can do is survive.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps these shortcomings are a sign that although the
developer has surely pushed the envelope, it hasn't finished
addressing it.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCT NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``Soldier of Fortune''; published by Activision; $45.99; Windows
95, 98 and NT 4.0-SP5; for mature players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
