<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4522 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     05-03 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOULD A BREAKUP MATTER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Proposed Final Judgment in the case of the United States vs.
Microsoft Corp. is on the Internet at
www.usdoj.gov/atr/cases/ms(underscore)index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Less than a decade ago the preceding sentence would have
indicated that the reporter had fallen asleep in mid-sentence and
smashed his forehead onto the keyboard. Today, however, we
instantly recognize the gibberish as a World Wide Web address.
</P>
<P>
   As if you haven't already read or heard enough about the
proposal to cleave Microsoft, you can follow the link and view the
document in one of three formats: in Hypertext Markup Language
(HTML), which requires a standard Web browser; in Adobe's Portable
Document Format (PDF), which requires a free program called Acrobat
Reader; or as a WordPerfect document (WPD), which requires any word
processing program that can read WordPerfect files. Besides the
government's petulance in not making the document available in the
popular Microsoft Word's .doc format, what do you notice?
</P>
<P>
   The operating system does not matter. HTML is the common
language of the Web, and it is operating system-agnostic. Adobe
Reader can handle 13 different operating systems, including
Windows, Macintosh, OS/2, Unix and Linux, and 14 different
languages.
</P>
<P>
   The operating system is just the dial tone that you need to make
a call to the Internet. Just as any phone company can provide the
dial tone for a telephone these days, any company _ not just
Microsoft _ can provide the operating system for an
Internet-connected device.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Windows is not a requirement to use the
Internet. And that worries Microsoft far more than the dubious
proposal made last week by the Justice Department and 17 states to
break up the company into two companies. One would be based on
operating systems, and the other would be based on a gaggle of
applications that include Microsoft Office, Internet Explorer, the
MSN network and the Microsoft Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is moving so fast that by the time this legal mess is
resolved, consumers may not even notice or care whether Microsoft
is one company, two, or 57. The Internet, not the desktop computer,
is becoming the center of power. Consumers will routinely tap into
the Internet not just from personal computers, but from a variety
of devices, including smart phones, handheld computers, Internet
appliances, Web pads, television sets, ATM machines and automobile
dashboards.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has no monopoly in this world of Internet-enabled
devices, and almost no chance of creating a monopoly even if it
ultimately wins its court case. When people decide to go online to
read the latest headlines, check their e-mail or trade stocks,
chances are that they do not pause to consider their operating
systems. They may think ``AOL'' or ``WebTV'' or even ``browser,''
but when it comes down to it, I suspect that most people do not
care whether their Internet access devices are powered by Windows,
Linux, BeOS, America Online, Sprint, DoCoMo, Palm OS, Java, Odwalla
juice or hamsters on a treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   Macintosh users are a special case. They care passionately about
the Mac OS and would rewire their own bodies to run on Mac OS X if
such a thing were possible. But for most other people, the
operating system is about as significant in their daily lives as
the plumbing system.
</P>
<P>
   In no way is this argument intended to diminish the findings
that Microsoft violated federal and state antitrust laws through
its predatory behavior, which in turn was fostered by its Windows
monopoly. A lot of people lost jobs and money when Microsoft
unfairly bullied rival companies out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it suggest that personal computers are on the wane. PC
sales have never been more robust, in fact. Microsoft still puts
its plumbing in more than 90 percent of all new desktops and
laptops. When the PC first emerged as an alternative to big,
expensive mainframe computers, I compared it to the small mammals
that eventually inherited the world from the dinosaurs. Is the PC
now itself a dinosaur? No way. But insects outnumber even the
mammals, and cell phones outsell desktop computers by a big margin.
In several countries, cell phones outsell even regular phones.
Phones that surf the Web and handle e-mail are just around the
corner, and Microsoft has the wrong number.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a lot of conjecture about what impact the
proposed breakup of Microsoft would have on people who use personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   First, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson is under no obligation to
accept the proposed remedy. He may decide that disintegrating
Microsoft is a fundamentally dumb idea, given that the integration
of new features into software, and the integration of one piece of
software with another, is the goal of every other company in the
industry. He may decide instead to fine Microsoft several bazillion
dollars for making annoying software. (If I were judge, I'd fine
them a billion dollars just for trying to foist Microsoft Bob on an
unsuspecting public. And I'd fine them another billion for that
silly ``Where Do You Want to Go Today?'' marketing tag.)
</P>
<P>
   Second, Microsoft will appeal whatever remedy the judge
proposes, with all the legal firepower at its disposal. A higher
court could reverse Jackson's ruling. Meanwhile, a breakup order
would be stayed until all appeals are concluded, which could take a
couple of years. If you think it takes a long time for Windows 98
to boot up and shut down, just wait until you see the Windows
appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   Third, the appeals could extend well past the election of a new
administration, and a new attorney general might be more inclined
to settle the case instead of pursuing a breakup, even though the
state cases could remain active.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say the chances of Microsoft being broken up are zero,''
said Mark Anderson, author of the influential Strategic News
Service newsletter (www.stratnews.com), which has an admirable
track record for technology forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's president, Steven Ballmer, vows that the company
will never be broken up. In a letter published in newspaper ads
earlier this week, Ballmer wrote that the proposed remedy would
``send a signal that companies in America that are `too' successful
will be punished harshly _ a signal that will be welcomed by
foreign competitors seeking to overtake America's global leadership
in technology.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a half-century after General Motors made the
same arrogant argument, Microsoft is saying that what's good for
Microsoft is good for America.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Japanese carmakers clobbered General Motors in the
1970s and 1980s, not because GM was hamstrung by unreasonable
government regulations, but because it failed to react to the
changing market caused by the demand for smaller, less expensive
and more fuel-efficient cars. Today you may be driving a car made
by a company you had never heard of a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The software market is now in a corresponding upheaval because
of the rising demand for access to the Internet through small,
inexpensive devices. A few years from now, you may be connecting to
the Internet using software from companies that you don't hear much
about today.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, the dial tone was always provided by AT&AMP;T. Today
there is so much competition that obnoxious calls from phone
companies are as much a part of the dinner hour as family
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1987, there was an opportunity for companies
besides Microsoft to dominate the market for personal computer
operating systems. Apple's Mac OS was at its peak, and IBM's OS/2
was superior to Windows in many ways. But both Apple and IBM
blundered, and Microsoft seized power.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's monopoly on personal computer operating systems
seems bulletproof, even in the unlikely event that the government
succeeds in its plan to give the software giant a lobotomy,
separating the left-brain lobe (operating systems) from the
right-brain lobe (applications). But even without the surgery,
Microsoft is in no way assured of dominating the Internet era in
the same way it has dominated the PC era.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
