<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4524 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-CHINA-TRADE-HNS &LR;      05-03 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHITE HOUSE PRESSES CONGRESS ON CHINA TRADE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in the ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Clinton administration heavyweights went to Capitol
Hill Wednesday to pressure a divided House to approve permanent
trading rules for China.
</P>
<P>
   The secretaries of the Treasury, Agriculture and Commerce and
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky, who negotiated the
trade deal with the Chinese, told the House Ways and Means
Committee that normalizing trade with China would reap economic and
political advantages for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky said to deny permanent trade relations ``would be to
severely damage American trade interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be to set back the cause of reform in China. It would
be to risk, without cause, a fundamental deterioration in the U.S.
relationship with China.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade legislation is one of the last major policy
initiatives of the Clinton administration, which is lobbying
feverishly for House approval. A vote is scheduled for the week of
May 22.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official acknowledged Wednesday that the
administration is 15 to 20 votes shy of the 218 needed for passage.
The Senate is expected to approve it.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1979, Congress has annually reviewed America's trading
status with China and granted Beijing the same privileges as most
other trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has selectively reduced tariffs on some products,
China has maintained high tariffs to protect its domestic
industries.
</P>
<P>
   But Beijing has agreed to lower tariffs for all nations with
which it has a permanent trade agreement in order to gain admission
to the World Trade Organization (WTO), which oversees trade among
its member states. China's acceptance into the WTO is almost
assured, and it is expected to have permanent trade deals with
every other member nation.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement negotiated by Barshefsky would reduce China's
tariffs on U.S. goods significantly while Chinese goods would
continue to flow into the United States under the same favorable
tariffs as before.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress does not approve the permanent agreement, China
would be able to continue charging high tariffs on American goods
while other nations would benefit from lower tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``To forgo that opportunity (for low tariffs) would be to
inappropriately disadvantage American producers,'' Treasury
Secretary Lawrence Summers told the House panel. ``At a time when
it is a matter of great economic importance that we promote our
exports, this type of market-opening agreement is very much in the
national interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said American farmers would
benefit from normalized trade ties with China. He recalled a trip
he had made to China in January where he saw in a supermarket
fruits from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese people really like what we are selling them,'' he
said. ``There will be a dramatic potential market there'' for
American goods.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House faces strong opposition from some of its
traditional Democratic allies, including organized labor and
environmental groups. They fear lax labor and environmental
standards will give Chinese producers advantages over American
companies and cost jobs in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The two highest-ranking Democrats in the House, Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt of Missouri and the minority whip, David Bonior of
Michigan, are also against the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, noted that giving
support to the bill ``is not easy for my Democratic colleagues when
their two top leaders are opposed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the bill argue that the annual review of trade
relations with China gives the United States leverage to demand
that Beijing improve its treatment of political and religious
dissidents. But the administration officials dismissed that
criticism, noting that China's abuses have continued despite yearly
reviews. They said opening China's markets would open China to U.S.
values as well.
</P>
<P>
   The annual review ``doesn't really accomplish, I believe, what
needs to be accomplished to see effective and sustained reform in
China,'' Barshefsky said. ``The cementing of a reformist element in
China, which is what (permanent trade) will do will provide far
greater leverage than an annual process.''
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Secretary William Daley responded to critics who say
China won't live up to the agreement by announcing a department
initiative that will begin immediately. It will monitor trade with
China and teach American businesses about their trading rights.
</P>
<P>
   China's ``track record, frankly, has been mixed,'' Daley said.
But he added that the Chinese ``do want to join the WTO and follow
the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1729EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0215 </DOCNO>
