<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, May 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sultry air will combine with slow-moving low pressure to promote
thundershowers with areas of heavy rain from eastern parts of Texas
and Oklahoma to the southern parts of the Mississippi and Ohio
Valleys. Local flooding will occur, especially where the ground has
been saturated by recent rain. Farther east, scattered afternoon
thunderstorms will form in the increasingly humid air from the
Tennessee Valley to the southern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Northeast will begin a protracted warm spell as
breezes from the southwest circulate around a sprawling
high-pressure system. Late Thursday, scattered thundershowers will
erupt from the eastern Ohio Valley to the interior Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Heat will build beneath sunny skies from the western Plains to
the northern Mississippi Valley. Afternoon readings near 90 degrees
will be common.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: MICROBURST
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane reconnaissance aircraft, which usually flies
unscathed into the most powerful storms on earth, was damaged by
high winds late Monday while on the ground in Galveston, Texas. The
violent gusts were caused by a microburst, a channel of
fast-sinking air less than 2 miles in diameter. As falling
raindrops evaporate far above the ground, the surrounding chilled
air plunges to earth. Like water running from a tap and striking
the sink below, the downward-rushing air spreads out on impact,
sometimes reaching speeds of more than 150 mph.
</P>
</TEXT>
