<HEADER>
A4540 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IRAN-TRIALS-2TAKES-NY     05-03 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-TRIALS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN IRANIAN COURT, ACCUSED ASSASSINS CALL VICTIM AN ENEMY OF ISLAM 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ In a packed courtroom covered with flowery
carpets, two smiling young men told a judge Wednesday that they had
decided to shoot one of the country's leading reformers because
they believed that he was corrupt and an enemy of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, in which eight men are charged in the attempted
assassination of the reformer, Saeed Hajjarian, an editor and
political strategist close to President Mohammad Khatami, has
mesmerized this city.
</P>
<P>
   Hajjarian's plight is the most vivid illustration of the
setbacks suffered recently by Iran's reformers. The bearded young
men who say they attacked him out of religious zeal are seen as an
ominous reminder of the violence that lurks under the surface of
Iran's political turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, in a courtroom in the southern city of Shiraz,
two of the 13 Jewish men charged with spying for Israel confessed
Wednesday to charges of espionage, according to their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The admissions do not prove the government's case, the lawyers
said, because no evidence has been presented to show that the men
disclosed classified information. In all, three of the accused men
_ all of those brought to trial so far in two days of closed
hearings _ have now said they spied for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   They and most of their co-defendants have been in prison for 15
months but were able to consult with lawyers only three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both trials are being heard in Revolutionary Courts, the branch
of Iran's legal system that deals with political and moral
offenses, drug trafficking and crimes involving national security.
In those courts, the judge investigates, brings charges, prosecutes
and renders a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The Hajjarian trial is being held in open court attended by
several hundred people, with a large yellow banner reading ``The
Judiciary Is the Axis of the Islamic System'' stretched across one
corner. The spy case is taking place with only the defendants and
their lawyers present, despite the protests of family members and
human rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   But both proceedings have focused unusual attention, in Iran and
outside, on the quality of justice that victims and defendants
receive.
</P>
<P>
   Hajjarian was shot once in the face on March 12 by a man who
fled on the type of high-powered motorcycle reserved for members of
Iran's security forces.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, security officials said that ``rogue elements''
within their ranks had assassinated democracy advocates. No one has
yet gone on trial for those killings. One security official who was
arrested died in prison while awaiting trial. The authorities said
he had committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The two defendants who have testified so far in the Hajjarian
case maintained that they were not part of any official group and
knew each other only through a neighborhood vigilante squad that
had assigned itself the job of attacking those they believed to be
un-Islamic.
</P>
<P>
   They said they had been encouraged to shoot Hajjarian by a third
associate who had convinced them that the reformer was an enemy of
religion. Hajjarian was released from the hospital late Tuesday, in
a wheelchair and with a bullet still in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting raised alarms in Iran about the effect of recent
statements of several leading conservative clerics and members of
the Revolutionary Guard Corps, which is controlled by the clergy.
In speeches and communiques, the hard-liners have justified
violence against anyone who opposes the Islamic system of
government and have labeled many reformers as anti-Islam.
</P>
<P>
   In the present charged atmosphere, in which the reformers who
won a sweeping victory in first-round voting for Parliament in
February have been arrested and jailed for insulting Islam, such
talk is dangerous, reform leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement quoted Wednesday by the official Iranian press
agency, Mohammad Reza Khatami, the president's brother and leader
of the reform coalition that swept the polls, said those advocating
violence in the name of religion harm Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advocates of violence under the current situation present a
tarnished image of Islam,'' he said, adding that ``Islam, with such
friends, needs no other foes.''
</P>
<P>
   Support for that view was not on display when two of the eight
men charged in the Hajjarian shooting took the stand Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Saeed Asgar, 20, the confessed gunman, said in the first session
of the trial last week that he believed he was performing his
``religious duties'' by shooting Hajjarian.
</P>
<P>
   In the second session Wednesday, he said he had not even known
what Hajjarian looked like and had needed a signal from one of his
friends to point him out on a crowded street outside the Tehran
city hall. On that signal, Asgar told the court, he walked up to
his victim and fired once, then rode away on a waiting motorcycle
driven by an accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   Some distance away, he removed the extra pair of pants he was
wearing _ so as not to be recognized by witnesses, he explained. He
then went to a movie theater and later paid his water bill at a
local bank before heading home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really want to kill him,'' Asgar said. ``The
agreement between us was to beat him up.'' He added that he did not
know why the plan was changed.
</P>
<P>
   A second man, Mohsen Majidi, said he had provided the motorcycle
and the gun in for the shooting. He said a third friend, who has
not yet testified, urged the attack on Hajjarian. ``He came to my
place and criticized him as a symbol of vice and said he was doing
stuff against the Islamic system,'' Majidi told the court.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The casual attitude of the defendants appeared to puzzle even
the Revolutionary Court judge, who ordered psychiatric evaluations
earlier this week of the eight defendants. The examination, a
doctor told the court, found them all sane and responsible for
their actions.
</P>
<P>
   The attitude of the defendants in the espionage trial in Shiraz
has also puzzled many observers, including their lawyers, human
rights activists and foreign diplomats monitoring the intensely
watched trial.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, after the first closed hearing, Hamid Tefileen, a
shoe store clerk who is the accused ringleader of the spy network,
confessed to spying first in Revolutionary Court and then in an
interview on state television. He said he has visited Israel, where
his mother and two of his siblings live, and in 1994 received
``training'' from Israel's secret service, an assertion that Israel
has denied.
</P>
<P>
   Tefileen was brought from the courtroom to meet with reporters
Wednesday and again proclaimed his guilt, saying he was motivated
by money and a misplaced enthusiasm for ``the promised land.'' Two
other men, Ramin Nematizadeh and Shahrokh Paknahad, joined him in
admitting to espionage.
</P>
<P>
   But the lead defense lawyer in the case expressed skepticism at
the confessions, which he said are not admissible under Iranian law
because they came from suspects who have spent a year or more in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accused may have been sick and tired of his condition and
may be willing to say anything to get his ordeal over with one way
or another,'' said the lawyer, Esmail Nosari.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers also rebutted the Revolutionary Court judge's charge
that the Jews have committed espionage under the law, saying the
defendants had no access to classified information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4542 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-03 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MONEY DOESN'T GROW ON TREES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Despite the fiscal woes of the San Francisco
Health Department, we are supposed to be as flush as a city as we
have been in history.
</P>
<P>
   But we can't find enough money to keep the city's modest tree
planting program operating at its current level?
</P>
<P>
   In the big picture of a $4 billion budget, we are not talking
about a lot of acorns here. We are talking about $1 million, the
amount that the Department of Public Works has been spending each
year to plant and maintain city trees and to fund the Sheriff's
Department's excellent Tree Corps program.
</P>
<P>
   Begun in 1985, Tree Corps is one of those ideas that is so
commonsensical, it's genius.
</P>
<P>
   Women and men who are about to be paroled from the county jail
are trained and employed as arborists. Working with the nonprofit
Friends of the Urban Forest and Public Works, the inmates earn
taxable income by planting and nurturing trees throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   For many of these people, their paychecks are the first
legitimate money they've earned in decades. For almost all of them,
the actual work is the very first time in their lives that they
have plugged into the natural world and literally connected to the
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   As several of them told the San Francisco Board of Supervisors
last week, the Tree Corps changed their lives in ways they never
dreamed could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't just grow trees, we grow people,'' said an ex-convict
named George Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as former San Quentin inmate Rumaldo Centeno told me a few
years ago: ``When I see things growing, I think, `Look what I am
doing. I'm growing this living thing.' The trees I plant, maybe I'm
not going to be here for my grandchildren, but they will be here,
the trees will be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, when voters approved a 20-year, half-cent sales tax
to pay for street improvements and transit projects, the
Transportation Authority has handled that tax money. Tree planting
and maintenance was allocated $10 million out of the projected
20-year total.
</P>
<P>
   Given the slow-growing nature of trees, the Department of Public
Works decided wisely to pour the tree resources into planting right
away. The only problem: Now, the $10 million has been spent.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Public Works has been reluctant to ask the
Transportation Authority for the usual $1 million tree budget.
Among other pressing needs, the department must raise $5 million
for its share of a matching federal grant bridge repair project.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Michael Yaki, however, thinks the trees should come
first _ at least for one more year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be only a stop-gap measure, but it will give us time
to figure out some long-range funding for the city's trees,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   With the support of Milton Marks III, executive director of
Friends of the Urban Forest, Yaki has asked his fellow board
members to urge Public Works to request the customary $1 million
for trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the realities of state and federal funding, money for
bridges almost does grow on trees, but money for trees doesn't,''
said Yaki.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (the supervisors) can't tell DPW how to spend its money,
but we do approve their budget requests. An extra million for trees
is available in the Transportation Authority tax money. If that
money is allocated for something instead of trees, that project
might have some difficulty getting passed by the board.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm with Yaki.
</P>
<P>
   As lovely as San Francisco is, we could plant $5 million worth
of trees each year and still not have enough. Even though Friends
of the Urban Forest has put in thousands of saplings in 700
projects in every city neighborhood, there are still scores of
blocks with nothing green and leafy growing on them.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen producing, trees are a direct and immediate contributor
to the quality of urban life. They are also an investment in the
future face of a city.
</P>
<P>
   When you include an element as personally transforming as the
sheriff's Tree Corps, trees become an investment in the health of
an entire citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
