<HEADLINE>
BUBBA DOG ISN'T MAN'S BEST FRIEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bubba Dog is a wheat beer made in San Antonio. Because we are
Americans and live in Texas, this is one of those things we wish we
could recommend, but we can't.
</P>
<P>
   The beer is not horrible, but there isn't anything distinguished
about it. It is amber with a yeasty aroma. And it's unpasteurized
and unfiltered, which means there is some sediment. At $12 a
six-pack, you can easily do better.
</P>
<P>
   Bubba Dog doesn't have much head, but there's much about it that
is very wrong-headed.
</P>
<P>
   First, one wonders about the marketing plan. With a name like
Bubba Dog, it would seem the folks at Yellow Rose Brewery are
trying to appeal to your good ol' boy with a pickup, a gun rack,
and a dawg or three in back.
</P>
<P>
   Now the trouble here is that guys in this group _ of which I am
a charter member _ do not buy beer that costs $12 a six-pack. (I do
only because the newspaper pays for it.)
</P>
<P>
   While we are stereotyping here, let us also point out that your
effete, $40 dollar haircut, Lexus-driving gent for whom a $12
beverage is slumming, isn't about to buy something called Bubba
Dog.
</P>
<P>
   Second, and more important, the label includes an offensive yarn
about ``Bubba Dog, a forgotten hero of the Alamo,'' who survived
the battle despite being shot and kicked by a Mexican soldier.
</P>
<P>
   The label goes on: ``Today Texans often recall `Remember the
Alamo,' but if you listen more closely, you will hear the haunting
ring of the last words passed man-to-man amongst the Alamo martyrs
_ `Remember the Bubba Dog.'''
</P>
<P>
   This, friends, is a shameless trivialization of the Alamo and
those who died there, in a feeble attempt to sell beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It offends me and I ain't even a Texan,'' said Maj. Tom Bob
Rocket (USMC) retired, who hails from a far-off flat land called
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did some advertising goober from New York City think this up?
This is demeaning to Texans and Mexicans, and being from San
Antonio they ought to know better than to say something that
dishonors the Alamo ... and to say a Mexican kicked a dog. What
kind of person kicks a dog? No fighting man would kick a dog. Not
even a Communist would kick a dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is offensive to the memory of the Alamo, to war heroes
everywhere and even to dogs,'' said the Maj.
</P>
<P>
   Bubba Dog does not deserve a rating.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul Bourgeois is beer critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
