A4549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PACIFIC-ATOLL-NYT     05-03 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACIFIC-ATOLL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATURE CONSERVANCY AGREES TO BUY PRISTINE ATOLL IN THE PACIFIC 
BY TODD S. PURDUM 
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a bid to preserve one of the most pristine
places left in the tropical Pacific, the Nature Conservancy has
agreed to buy Palmyra atoll, a spectacular cluster of uninhabited
coral islets 1,052 miles south of Hawaii, from the Honolulu family
that has owned it for nearly 80 years, with plans to create a
nature preserve for marine and climate research and limited,
ecologically sensitive tourism.
</P>
<P>
   The precise purchase price was not disclosed, but Nature
Conservancy officials say they must raise $37 million to buy the
atoll, establish operations and an endowment, making it the
nonprofit conservancy's single most expensive acquisition in its
49-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Palmyra has five times as many coral species as the Florida
Keys, and three times as many as Hawaii, and is home to the world's
largest land invertebrate, the rare coconut crab, and a population
of red-footed booby birds second only to that of the Galapagos
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the last marine wilderness area left in the U.S.
tropics,'' said Chuck Cook, the conservancy's project director for
Palmyra. ``The fact that there are no human pressures to speak of
is unique and the opportunity to protect this pristine reef is
fantastic. It is one of the few nesting areas for seabirds in a
450,000-square-mile area.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservancy has already raised about $10 million, and hopes
to raise another $8 million by selling part of the area to the
Interior Department for use as a federal fish and wildlife refuge.
With 15 feet of rain a year, yet as much sunshine as Hawaii,
Palmyra is a rare, ``wet'' atoll able to sustain life and
vegetation, including one of the last remaining undisturbed stands
of Pisonia grandis beach forest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Palmyra has been a stopping point for Pacific
yachtsmen, a U.S. Navy supply base in World War II, and the site of
a proposed nuclear waste dump, an unsuccessful coconut plantation
and various development schemes that never got off the ground. Two
years ago it attracted the attention of Microsoft founder Bill
Gates, who considered buying it as his own private getaway.
</P>
<P>
   But it is perhaps most famous as the scene of a 1974 murder in
which a married couple were killed and their boat stolen by fellow
yachters whose own craft was sinking. The case became the subject
of a best-selling thriller, ``And the Sea Will Tell,'' by Vincent
Bugliosi, the lawyer who won an acquittal for one of the
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Palmyra, situated about 300 miles north of the equator and two
hours by jet from Honolulu, was named by an American ship captain,
whose vessel, the Palmyra, blew ashore in a storm in 1802. In 1816,
a Spanish pirate ship, the Esperanza, loaded with plunder from
Incan temples, was wrecked on the atoll's coral reefs. In 1862, two
New Zealanders who had married Hawaiian women obtained a deed to
the atoll from King Kamehameha V, but when Hawaii was annexed to
the United States in 1898, Palmyra was specifically excluded, and
in 1922, a family of Honolulu roofing contractors, the
Fullard-Leos, bought the atoll for $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1938, the Fullard-Leo family embarked on a
long-running feud with the Navy, which built an airstrip on the
atoll and used it as a base in World War II. Ultimately, the
Fullard-Leos took their successful fight for title all the way to
the U.S. Supreme Court, and when Hawaii became a state in 1959,
Palmyra was again excluded.
</P>
<P>
   But three surviving Fullard-Leo brothers who control the
property, Leslie, Ainsley and Dudley, are now all in their 80s or
90s and repeated efforts to develop the property have either failed
or been rejected by the family as too disruptive to the atoll's
pristine ecology. The Nature Conservancy has been negotiating to
buy the parcel, which includes 680 acres of land and 15,512 acres
of reefs, for more than two years, at a price well below the $47
million the family initially sought, with the family taking a tax
deduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potential buyers all had plans for much larger developments
than the family was comfortable with,'' said Peter Savio, the
Honolulu real estate agent who represented the Fullard-Leos and who
himself had made an unsuccessful stab at developing the island as a
resort. ``The family is very happy at the sale to the Nature
Conservancy. It's the kind of use they've always looked for.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservancy has until the first quarter of next year to
raise the needed funds. The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service
identified Palmyra last year as its No. 1 land purchase priority,
and $8 million in federal funds have already been appropriated to
help defray the cost, subject to the conservancy's ability to
acquire the atoll.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said the conservancy is now in the process of building a
small tent camp and improving the overgrown runway, with the
expectation of eventually teaming up with a tour operator that
could allow 30 to 40 people at a time to visit the atoll for scuba
diving, snorkeling and catch-and-release bonefishing, at a cost of
$3,000 to $4,000 a week.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``eco-tourism is not our primary objective;
preserving these robust and abundant habitats is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
