<SLUG> BC-EURO-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EURO DROPS TO NEW LOWS, AND NO ONE IS EXACTLY SURE WHY 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The euro fell to new lows against the
dollar and other major currencies Wednesday, settling below 90
cents for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of the euro _ which at Wednesday's late price in New
York of 89.61 cents is more than 23 percent below its value when it
was introduced in January 1999 _ has become a source of
embarrassment to European political leaders and of bewilderment to
currency traders.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the common currency's recent steep decline
remain murky. The most obvious source of pressure continues to be
the strength of the U.S. economy, which is growing faster than
those in Europe and has been a magnet for capital from around the
world. Moreover, the dollar's value has been pushed up by
expectations that the Federal Reserve will continue to raise
interest rates _ a step that ordinarily increases the exchange rate
of a currency.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts note that the euro has also been losing ground to
other currencies. It has fallen further against the Japanese yen
than against the dollar, and fallen as well against the British
pound and Swiss franc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the strength of the dollar explains everything
that is going on,'' said Joachim Scheide, an economist at the
Institute of World Economics in Kiel, Germany. ``This is a problem
of euro weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   By most measures, economic growth and optimism in the 11-nation
euro zone are stronger than they have been in years. Growth is
expected to exceed 3 percent in 2000, price rises are lower than in
the United States, exports are booming, and even unemployment _ in
the last few years Europe's intractable problem _ is declining
markedly.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, currency traders have begun talking about
``panic sales'' of euros in recent days. One reason is that
international fund managers had been betting on a strong increase
in the euro. When the currency defied their expectations and
declined further, many institutions were caught with low-value
euros that they are now selling every time the rate creeps up a
bit.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It probably did not help the single currency that the European
Commission and European Central Bank recommended that Greece,
rejected for entry into the monetary union two years ago, should
now be allowed to join. But analysts said the decision on Greece
probably had little real effect, as most considered it a foregone
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, some specialists have begun to blame the
European Central Bank and European political leaders for making the
problem worse. When the euro was introduced, central bank officials
indicated that they had little interest in the day-to-day movements
of exchange rates, but were concerned about signs of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, central bankers have changed their position and
made it clear that they are now worried that the euro's weakness
could ignite inflation by pushing up the prices of imported goods.
</P>
<P>
   That was the main reason that European Central Bank gave last
week when it raised its benchmark short-term interest rate to 3.75
percent from 3.5 percent _ a move that did not stop the euro from
sinking immediately afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Noyer, vice president of the European Central Bank,
said in a speech Wednesday that the euro's slide ``puts pressure on
price stability,'' and most analysts expect more rate increases in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   But most of Europe's central bankers remain convinced that
intervening in markets to prop up the euro would be fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very doubtful whether intervention can be successful
against the market trend,'' said Ernst Welteke, president of
Germany's central bank, in remarks carried by Bloomberg News. ``If
one looks, for example, at current U.S. interests,'' Welteke added,
``it's unlikely that concerted intervention is even possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
