<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-AGING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RIPE OLD AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A combination of research breakthroughs and the odometer flip of
the year 2000 has helped put a spotlight on the subject of aging
and on those among us _ the country's estimated 70,000 centenarians
_ who have weathered it most successfully. The beneficiaries of
good genes and this century's remarkable progress in sanitation,
vaccination, nutrition, and disease treatment, their ranks should
expand to about 1 million by the year 2050.
</P>
<P>
   As a seminar on the subject held at the Massachusetts
Biotechnology Council in Cambridge this week demonstrated, skilled
scientists are at work both to make that projection come true and
to ensure that those who live so long will continue to have their
faculties, including vision. Good health and an occupied, active
mind go hand in hand, as last year's ``Living to 100'' study of New
England centenarians by Dr. Thomas Perls and Dr. Rachel Hitt
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of aging moved into the headlines last week, when
researchers in Worcester said they had managed to clone calves
whose cells gave evidence of being younger than their original
cow's. Because the cells of Dolly, the cloned sheep, had shown
evidence of being as old as Dolly's original ewe's, some scientists
had worried that the dream of using cloned human tissues to replace
or repair diseased organs might not come true. But other scientists
dispute the evidence of ``oldness'' in Dolly's cells and question
whether it really ever portended a shortened lifespan.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there is another tip for human beings who are
eager to live a long time but not anxious to be patched with cloned
heart tissue of uncertain shelf life: Cut calories by 25-30
percent. Experiments with several species _ from worms to yeast to
mice, with primate trials under way _ show it to be a surefire way
to extend lifespan substantially.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers, including Massachusetts Institute of Technology's
Leonard Guarente, are trying to figure out just why this is so. If
he and others can track down the biochemistry behind it, there may
be a pill someday that can get the same results for human beings,
changing forever our notions of ``old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
