<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SHOWTRIALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN'S SHOW TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hardliners in Iran who are trying 13 Iranian Jews on charges
of spying for Israel are repeating an all-too-familiar lesson about
the distinction between revolutionary justice and the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   In a state based on a genuine rule of law, innocent citizens are
not accused of preposterous crimes in order to make a political
point. But that is what has happened to the accused Jews in the
city of Shiraz.
</P>
<P>
   The principal evidence against them is that some have traveled
to Israel to visit relatives _ a journey that is against the law of
Iran's Islamic Republic. Thus they have the forbidden stamp of the
Jewish state in their passports. Of course, a real spy who knew
that traveling to Israel was a cause for suspicion would hardly
allow himself to be found with an Israeli entry stamp in his
passport.
</P>
<P>
   Another arrow pointing to some of the accused is that they
exchanged e-mail with relatives in Israel and the United States.
The Iranian laws against such innocuous activity are not merely bad
laws; they are tell-tale signs of a repressive, paranoid regime.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants are being tried in a Revolutionary Court in which
one man serves as judge, investigator, prosecutor, and jury. Human
rights groups, diplomats, reporters, and Jewish groups have been
denied access to the courtroom. The reason given is the familiar
excuse of ``national security.'' In reality, these show trials are
held in secret to veil the hardliners' travesty of a fair trial by
a real court.
</P>
<P>
   The plainly coerced confession from three suspect who had no
access to any state secrets represents a shameless effort by
hardliners to justify their persecution of the 13 citizens. Because
Iranian reformers backing President Mohammad Khatami are also
facing revolutionary judges for their political activities and
writings, nobody from the reformist camp has felt secure enough to
come to the defense of the railroaded Jews.
</P>
<P>
   If the democratic powers are serious about human rights and the
rule of law, they will make it plain to Iran's hardliners that they
will have to pay a high price for any injustice done to the 13
scapegoated Jews of Shiraz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
