<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sweet rice dish goes with the grain
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quittis Taylor of Ellenwood, Ga., remembered an easy dessert
called Glorified Rice she and her children enjoyed more than 30
years ago. Filled with Minute Rice, pineapple and whipped cream, it
was a lost recipe she hoped to regain to make for her
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   After striking out with the makers of Minute Rice, she asked us
and we asked you. Among several responses was this one from Dorothy
Deakins of Lithonia, Ga., who thanked Taylor for reminding her of
the long-forgotten recipe.
</P>
<P>
   This one contains a sliced banana, while others call for a
chopped apple or 1/4 cup of chopped pecans. We expect you could
glorify it most any way you like.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Glorified Rice
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: at least 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   1 (8 3/4-ounce) can crushed pineapple, syrup drained and
reserved
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Minute Rice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups miniature marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe banana, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy (whipping) cream, beaten to hold soft peaks
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped maraschino cherries
</P>
<P>
   In a small pan, bring pineapple syrup and enough water to make 1
cup to a boil. Add rice and salt. Remove from heat and let stand 5
minutes or until rice is done. Place in large mixing bowl. Add
pineapple and lemon juice. Set aside to cool, about 45 minutes, or
refrigerate until cool.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in marshmallows and banana slices.
</P>
<P>
   Fold whipped cream and cherries into cooled rice-pineapple
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Chill thoroughly, at least 1 hour, before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 198 calories, 2 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 26), 35 grams carbohydrates, 21 milligrams
cholesterol, 159 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Request
</P>
<P>
   If you have a favorite recipe for cooking dried pinto beans,
Kathie Cooney wants it. She and a friend have one that cooks the
beans all day, but they are wondering about spices and whether to
include ham or a hambone.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
