<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's one stale argument: The big loaf
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While on vacation at Jekyll Island last fall, I fell into a
conversation about the single life with sisters Ethel Colquitt and
Kathleen Fink of Barnesville.
</P>
<P>
   It seems whether you're 30-something or 80-something, some
things are harder to do alone _ flip a mattress, put up a Christmas
tree and use a whole loaf of bread before it goes stale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't they just make a smaller loaf of bread?'' Ethel
wondered.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Why can't they? I must throw out half a loaf every week.
With the number of one- and two-person households approaching 50
percent, it's curious the bread industry has failed to offer
smaller loaves. Even families find that with so many different
breads _ buns, dinner rolls, white, wheat _ some always goes to
waste.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy a pint of milk or a gallon; a half-dozen eggs or
whole. Why not a half loaf of bread?
</P>
<P>
   An attempt to get an answer from the bread industry proved as
challenging as following a bread crumb trail through a midnight
forest. I was directed from expert to association to institute.
Matt Hall, spokesman for Earthgrains in St. Louis, which produces
Colonial and Earthgrains breads, finally offered an explanation.
It's cheaper to have one size for bread pans, wrappers and storage
racks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of people say they want a smaller loaf, but since we
can't sell one for half the price, there wouldn't be a market for
it,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not so sure. I admit to raising an eyebrow when I saw that a
half loaf at Harry's in a Hurry wasn't half-price. But I bought it
anyway. (Harry's makes its own bread, so it has more packaging
flexibility.)
</P>
<P>
   It seems that as long as flour is plentiful and folks will buy
the big loaves, the industry figures why bother? Never mind that
multitudes of loaves go to waste on grocery shelves and countless
partial loaves go to waste in people's homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we'd like to see consumers do is urge their
grocers to work out a system with local food banks so all the
unbought bread doesn't go to waste,'' said Bill Bolling, executive
director of the Atlanta Community Food Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Then we need to adopt a more European attitude at home and treat
stale bread as a pantry item (it keeps best in the freezer). For
ideas, pick up Carole Lalli's new cookbook, ``Yesterday's Bread''
(HarperPerennial, $12.95). She recommends making bread crumbs for
coatings and stuffings or for thickening soups like gazpacho. Stale
bread also makes a base for sweet or savory bread puddings.
</P>
<P>
   Or follow Lalli's recipe for this salad _ an Italian specialty
that is delicious with vine-ripened tomatoes, which you can buy in
grocery stores now. This summer, enjoy it with locally grown
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   italian panzanella salad
</P>
<P>
   Tear stale bread into chunks and soak in water (2 cups for 1/2
pound of bread) and 1/8 cup red wine vinegar. Thinly slice an onion
and chop 1 pound of tomatoes and 2 stalks celery. Then tear up 1/2
cup basil leaves. Drain the bread and squeeze out as much
water/vinegar as you can. Toss with the other ingredients, cover
and chill for 30 minutes. Remove, let stand 10 minutes, drizzle
with olive oil and season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
