<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Funny things happened on way to Rome
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, the glory that was Kirk Douglas in ``Spartacus.'' The
grandeur that was Charlton Heston in ``Ben-Hur.'' It's been a
couple of decades since we've seen a really good Roman Empire
flick, but ``Gladiator,'' opening Friday in metro Atlanta, revives
the genre with panache. And, even better, with Russell Crowe as our
hero.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few video suggestions to remind you that, sometimes,
there's no place like Rome:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Robe'' (1953): The first movie made in CinemaScope, it
was also the movie that was supposed to make Richard Burton a huge
Hollywood star (ironically that would happen thanks to another
Roman epic, ``Cleopatra'' and a huge Hollywood star named Elizabeth
Taylor). Anyway, Burton plays Marcellus, a Roman tribune who wins
Christ's robe in a dice game, falls in love with Jean Simmons and
is converted to Christianity by his slave, Victor Mature, who
spends a lot of the movie looking devoutly ... well ... up.
</P>
<P>
   The picture looks a little '50s-square these days, but in its
time it was considered a serious and intelligent attempt to deal
with the nature of faith. Burton gave it his all, including
thoughtful interviews in which he told reporters, ``Playing
Marcellus is like playing Hamlet.'' Still, he ended up back in
London with his big break a decade away.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Demetrius and the Gladiators'' (1954): In this sequel to
``The Robe,'' Mature moves center stage as does the wonderfully
decadent Jay Robinson who, as the insane Emperor Caligula,
initiates a search for the robe, thinking it has the power to grant
him immortality. That lands Mature in the gladiator's arena, where
he catches the eye of beautiful and duplicitous Susan Hayward.
Mature, wearing skimpy red trunks (possibly what caught Hayward's
eye), single-handedly defeats four tigers and keeps looking ...
well ... up. You can look for a very new-to-movies Anne Bancroft in
the tiny role of a vestal virgin.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Barabbas'' (1962): Anthony Quinn gives one of his classic
brute/saint performances as the thief who was freed instead of
Christ. The movie imagines what happened to him after the mob
chanted, ``Give us Barabbas.'' Ultimately, he ends up as a
gladiator, being tormented by a truly memorable Jack Palance, who
gives one of his classic demented villain performances as a
gleefully sadistic charioteer.
</P>
<P>
   Director Richard Fleischer recalls in his autobiography that,
among the 9,000 extras filling the Colosseum (actually, an arena in
Verona doubling for the Colosseum), he spotted a stunning
18-year-old and told his cameraman to gets lots of reaction
close-ups of her. As it turned out, Palance noticed her as well and
they moved in together. Her name was Sharon Tate.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Fall of the Roman Empire'' (1964): This should make for
very interesting viewing vis-a-vis ``Gladiator'' since the plots
are oddly similar. Both begin shortly before the death of Emperor
Marcus Aurelius (Alec Guinness) and both depict a rivalry between
the emperor's son, Commodus (Christopher Plummer) and a fictitious
general (Stephen Boyd) who is, supposedly, the emperor's handpicked
successor.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Anthony Mann, the movie was mostly praised for its
incredibly lavish sets (the reconstruction of the Roman Forum is
rumored to be the largest film set ever built.) Guiness wrote in
his memoirs that he enjoyed working with Mann and was smitten with
Sophia Loren (she plays Plummer's sister) but could never bring
himself to watch more than 20 minutes of the finished film. Of
course, he was never all that fond of ``Star Wars'' either.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Cleopatra'' (1963): Because, like Mount Everest, it's there.
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : For more about movies and ancient Rome:
www.capitolium.org/eng/ludi/cinema.htm
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
