r l BC-MOTHERSDAY04-COX     05-03 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHERSDAY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beyond breakfast in bed
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since President Woodrow Wilson proclaimed the second Sunday
in May as Mother's Day, moms have been royally gifted with elegant
brunches, bunches of flowers and trinkets of all kind.
</P>
<P>
   For one of mom's treats May 14, why not serve her breakfast in
bed? You don't have to search a mall or the Internet for this
hassle-free, old-fashioned gift. In fact, you don't even have to
leave home. Most ingredients can be found in the kitchen. You will
want to add a few neat touches, including the perfect flower, the
right card and mom's favorite drink. And dad might be pressed into
service if the tots are too tiny.
</P>
<P>
   In her book, ``Breakfast in Bed,'' (HarperCollins, $19.95),
author Jesse Ziff Cool writes, ``Serving breakfast in bed is
creating a special day out of one that would otherwise be like any
other.'' On the mouthwatering pages, you can learn how to wow mom
with such indulgences as banana pancakes, a smoked salmon omelet or
fresh berries with creme fraiche.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, however, many moms would be just as happy with a
bagel and cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   To create our breakfast in bed scenario, we combined easy (fruit
and croissant) with elegant (damask and china). For starters, our
brushed metal bed ($399) was made up with a set of Tuck's white
cotton sheets ($119) and topped by Area's plush duvet cover ($110)
done in pastel squares and backed by fluffy pillows ($29-$44). All
available at Innovations furniture store on Monroe Drive in
Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Mom can wear her satinlike, short floral-print nightgown by
Jones New York and matching short robe ($68) on many mornings after
Mother's Day. Available at Rich's.
</P>
<P>
   No breakfast in bed is complete without an ivory breakfast tray
($168) elegantly appointed with a damask place mat ($11) and
matching napkin ($10). Other touches: a metal flower attached to a
votive candleholder ($23) and a real-looking ``faux cup of
cappuccino'' ($33) so mom won't spill any in bed. All from
Lassiter's in Phipps Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, to hold the breakfast goodies, a china plate from
Villeroy &AMP; Boch ($16) at Rich's.
</P>
<P>
   P O I N T A N D C L I C K F O R G R E A T G I F T S
</P>
<P>
   If your mom cringes at the thought of crumbs on her sheets, pass
on giving her breakfast in bed. Instead, buy her gift on the
Internet. Click on the following sites and never leave your home or
office:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.RedEnvelope.com:
</P>
<P>
   Gifts for living well and loving life _ a tea sampler ($65);
rose petal soap in jar ($45); salad-making kit ($65).
</P>
