<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, May 4 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (Dateline to kum) _ The United Nations has
made an emergency appeal for more troops to aid a peacekeeping
mission under widespread attack in Sierra Leone, United Nations
officials and diplomats said Wednesday. The United States, which
has largely shied away from African peacekeeping since a debacle in
Somalia in 1993, is also being asked to help, as a once promising
African country plunges again into violence. American officials
have been taking part in meetings at United Nations headquarters in
New York. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   PANAM103-TRIAL (Camp Zeist, Netherlands) _ Nearly 12 years after
a jumbo jet blew up in the skies of Scotland, raining bodies and
flaming debris down on the village of Lockerbie, the trial of two
men accused of that terrorist act begins Wednesday. By Donald G.
McNeill Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CARDINAL-OCONNOR (New York) _ Cardinal John O'Connor, the
Roman Catholic bishop of New York, is reportedly near death.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DADS (New York) _ How the foster care system in New York City
periodically fails to tell the father of a child who is about to be
taken away from his or her mother. By Nina Bernstein. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   GUNMAKERS-STRATEGY (Undated) _ Faced with lawsuits by 31 cities
and counties, the nation's gun companies have broken off settlement
negotiations, deciding to take their chances on sympathetic state
judges or victory by Republican presidential candidate George W.
Bush in November. This defiance by the gun industry dashes the
hopes of the White House and state governments that a recent deal
with Smith &AMP; Wesson would lead other major gun companies to fall in
line. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-BRITAIN-MARKETS (London) _ The London and Frankfurt
stock exchanges announced plans for a full merger and an alliance
with New York's tech-heavy Nasdaq exchange on Wednesday, seeking to
build a pan-European trading heavyweight and a 24-hour global
market in new economy stocks _ both unthinkable only a few years
ago. The combined exchange will be Europe's biggest by far. The
announcement offered the most dramatic evidence to date of a
sea-change in European markets, driven by a clamor among investors
for cheaper trading, a challenge from Internet-based and electronic
trading systems and an increasing trend to treat Europe as a single
investment arena following the introduction of the euro. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
