<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOCKERBIE-FAMILIES (Zeist, Netherlands) _ Families confront
bombing suspects for first time _ and say they wouldn't look them
in the eye. By Kevin Cullen. 1350 words.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-ECONOMY (Johannesburg) _ President Robert Mugabe's
willingness to thumb his nose at the world is beginning to affect
South Africa's economy. By Kurt Shillinger. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-BIGDIG (Washington) -- Raising the prospect of Boston's
financially struggling ``Big Dig'' project ultimately costing as
much as $20 billion, Senator John McCain says he wants legislation
that would bar Congress from approving another dime for the
project. By Bob Hohler. 900 words. (w and a coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-CARDINAL (New York) _ Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York
says the Cardinal O'Connor, ailing since brain surgery last summer,
is near death. By Fred Kaplan. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EMC-ANNUAL (Undated) _ Chief executive, Michael Ruettgers,
predicts EMC will become one of the world's 10 most valuable
companies by 2010 as the Internet continues to drive demand for
information services. By Ross Kerber. 400 words.
</P>
<P>
   ALTAVISTA-RAGING (Undated) _ AltaVista announces a makeover,
including the rollout of a new stripped-down search engine called
Raging Search for true search enthusiasts. By Alex Pham. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ (Boston) _ Red Sox star pitcher Pedro
Martinez says he'll appeal a five-game suspension handed to him by
Major Leage Baseball for plunking Roberto Alomar of the Cleveland
Indians. During the appeal, he'll still be allowed to pitch. By
Gordon Edes. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   RUN-KHANNOUCHI (Undated) _ Khalid Khannouchi announces at an
emotional news conference that injuries have crushed his plans to
compete in the US Olympic Marathon Trials Sunday. He will not be
able to run for the United States at the Olympics in Sydney. By
Barbara Huebner. 700 words.
</P>
