<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4583 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-COOKING-NOBOOK0504-CO     05-03 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKING-NOBOOK0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let kitchen freedom ring
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Pam Anderson is every bit the contemporary
Everywoman.
</P>
<P>
   She's 42, married to an Episcopal minister and a mother of two
teen-age daughters who are, typically, involved in everything from
sports to the school play.
</P>
<P>
   She works, every day. And she fixes dinner, too, just the way
most of you do _ opening up the refrigerator at 6 p.m. and looking
to see what's there.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson manages dinner, often within 15 minutes, without
relying on boxed mixes or home delivery.
</P>
<P>
   She has done what she thinks every home cook should do: Learn a
handful of solid techniques and put the cookbooks back on the
shelf.
</P>
<P>
   That applies even to her newest book, ``How to Cook Without a
Book'' (Broadway, $25).
</P>
<P>
   ``Learn the techniques and you're free of cookbooks,'' she says.
``You've got your `Get Out of Jail Card.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cooks may recognize Anderson as the former executive editor of
Cook's Illustrated magazine, the no-ad publication that focuses on
the definitive ways to do everything from making home fries to
baking brownies. She went on to author ``The Perfect Recipe,
Getting It Right Every Time,'' which has more than 100,000 copies
in print.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two books reflect the two sides of me,'' she says.
``Everyone wants the recipe for the perfect Thanksgiving turkey,
for the perfect lemon meringue pie, for the cheesecake without
cracks _but on the other side, you gotta get dinner on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   As a food writer, Anderson has a room full of cookbooks, which
she uses for research. But she rarely turns to them for daily
living. The most recent time was for a millennium party when she
was looking for inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Daily cooking is easy because she has internalized _ make that
memorized _ a bank of quick, reliable techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to free people from the tyranny of recipes,'' she says.
``There may be millions of recipes, but there are only a handful of
cooking techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense she is taking a cue from her grandmother and mother,
who cooked every day but didn't own a cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   Today's cooks have ample books and ingredients from around the
world, but less time to use them. The pressures of daily life
convinced her ``we didn't need more recipes; we needed to learn to
cook without them.''
</P>
<P>
   She starts each chapter of the book with a little rhyme.
</P>
<P>
   The one for simple tomato sauce _ which takes less time to make
than it does for the pasta to cook _ starts out this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heat fat and garlic, then cook it for two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Add canned tomatoes and simmer for a few.''
</P>
<P>
   The prose may not be memorable but her formulas are. To learn to
make a tomato sauce without a recipe, she advises, always use the
same pot. ``Measure the amount of oil specified, then tilt the pan.
Notice what that amount of oil looks like. Now put away the
measuring cups and spoons because the rest is simple _ a couple of
garlic cloves, a 28-ounce can of crushed tomatoes and a little
chopped parsley if you have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her book covers everything from hearty soups to desserts, but
the strongest chapters focus on the main course. The chapter on
sautes _''If You've Made One Saute You've Made Them All'' _ can
permanently expand the repertoire of most cooks.
</P>
<P>
   A part of that chapter is a section on making quick pan sauces,
of which she says she's most proud. Recipes for pan sauces usually
call for time-consuming rituals: cooking some shallots for flavor,
then reducing wine, then reducing broth or cream. Often cream or
butter is used in large quantities.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time the sauce is done the meat is cold,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She dispensed with the shallots and cut the quantity of liquids
so they would reduce quickly. And she combined them all rather than
waiting for first the wine and then the broth to boil down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically throw everything in a 1-cup measuring cup,'' she
says. ``At the end I whisk in 1 tablespoon butter, for four people.
It flavors the meat, and it's not too fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Some weekday cooks might be tempted to skip the sauce, but as
Anderson says, ``It helps people get through chicken breast
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says that if she had to pick one technique to pass on
to her daughters, who like many vegetarian teens won't eat red
meat, it would be the short-cut technique for pasta with
vegetables. Firm vegetables such as broccoli, carrots, snow peas
and asparagus cook right along with the pasta, saving one dirty
pan. Garlic or onions are cooked in oil in another pan. That's it,
except for the addition of some cheese. Different herbs vary the
taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got a pound of vegetables and a pound of pasta you
don't need a recipe,''she says and that's the formula she works
with.
</P>
<P>
   She offers variations. If the vegetables are tender ones such as
bell peppers, mushrooms and squash, they get cooked in the oil
instead of with the pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the viewpoint of purists _and she has worn that
mantle before _ she says you don't really have to cook pasta in a
gigantic pot of water that takes forever to come to a boil. As an
added bonus, the pasta water becomes more flavorful and thickened
by pasta starch, and she makes use of that by incorporating a
half-cup of the pasta water into the flavorings to make the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The short cuts trim enough time that the family may still be
eating salad when the pasta is done. But sitting in the water for a
couple minutes won't really hurt it either, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Relax and enjoy your salad. After all you're fixing dinner for
the family, not the boss.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
