<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4589 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NOBOOK-RECIPES0504-CO     05-03 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOBOOK-RECIPES0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cookbook author's technique is long on shortcuts
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ KPam Anderson, author of ``How to Cook Without a
Book,'' says she takes shortcuts whenever she can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rarely have much more than 30 minutes for weeknight dinner
preparation,'' she says. But her shortcuts are those of a
thoughtful cook.
</P>
<P>
   She cuts the backbone out of a whole chicken and flattens it,
shaving a half-hour from the roasting time. As a bonus, it will be
easier to rub some seasonings under the skin. Although it takes a
bit more than 30 minutes to cook, all but five minutes of that is
roasting time when the cook is free to do something else.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson defies the rules for cooking pasta, using less water,
which can take forever to come to a boil in a big pot. One
serendipitous recipe for orzo was an accident that developed by a
daughter's breakfast-time request for orzo for her school lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson found that when orzo cooks in less water, the pasta
absorbs almost all the liquid and turns out like risotto. It's the
only way she cooks orzo now, and it's a 10-minute dish.
</P>
<P>
   The chicken and the orzo plus a salad make for a fine weekday
meal. You might even serve it to weekend company.
</P>
<P>
   NO-HASSLE ROAST CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 3- to 3 1/2-pound chicken,
</P>
<P>
   backbone removed, rinsed and
</P>
<P>
   patted dry
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil or
</P>
<P>
   softened butter
</P>
<P>
   Open up the bird and flatten it with your hand. Adjust oven rack
to lower-middle position and heat oven to 450 degrees. Place the
butterflied chicken on a foil-lined 18-by-12-inch shallow roasting
pan or jellyroll pan. Lift the skin and season under skin with salt
and pepper. Pat skin back in place and drizzle with oil or rub with
butter.
</P>
<P>
   Roast chicken until it is golden brown and its juices run clear,
about 40 minutes. Let stand 5 minutes, then cut into 2
breast-and-wing pieces and 2 leg-and-thigh pieces.
</P>
<P>
   _ Variation: For roast chicken with Dijon and fresh bread
crumbs, remove chicken from oven after 25 minutes. Pour off and
reserve pan drippings. Brush chicken with 1/4 cup Dijon mustard,
then sprinkle with 1 cup fresh bread crumbs. Drizzle reserved pan
drippings over bread crumbs. Return chicken to oven and roast until
crumbs are golden brown and juices run clear, 10 to 15 minutes
longer.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE ORZO
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound orzo (1 1/3 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil or butter
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Optional flavorings
</P>
<P>
   Bring 1 quart of water to a boil in a large saucepan. Add salt
and the orzo; boil until orzo is tender and has absorbed the
cooking liquid, 8 to 9 minutes. Stir in the oil or butter, cheese,
pepper and optional flavorings.
</P>
<P>
   Optional flavorings:
</P>
<P>
   _ For a less rich-tasting side dish, eliminate the cheese and
add 1 1/2 teaspoons zest and 1/2 teaspoon juice from a lemon, plus
2 tablespoons minced fresh parsley.
</P>
<P>
   _ Add 2 tablespoons minced fresh basil and 2 tablespoons toasted
pine nuts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Add 3 canned tomatoes, chopped and drained, 8 Kalamata olives,
pitted and chopped and 1/4 cup crumbled feta cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's favorite way of cooking vegetables is a combination
technique called steam/sauteed. The vegetables steam in a little
bit of water that has some oil added to it. By the time the
vegetables are tender the water has evaporated and the vegetables
sizzle in the residual fat, intensifying their flavor. It works
perfectly for everything from asparagus and broccoli florets to
green beans and cabbage.
</P>
<P>
   Here's her basic recipe. Optional seasonings such as sliced
onion, minced garlic or dried herbs should be cooked along with the
vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   STEAM/SAUTEED VEGETABLES
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil, vegetable oil, butter or bacon fat
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 pound prepared vegetables
</P>
<P>
   Ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Bring the water, fat, salt and vegetable to a boil in a large,
deep skillet. Cover and steam over medium high heat until the
vegetables are brightly colored and just tender, depending on size.
Remove the lid and continue to cook until the liquid evaporates, 1
to 2 minutes longer, adding optional fresh herbs or flavorings if
desired. Saute to intensify the flavors, 1 to 2 minutes longer. Add
pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
