<HEADER>
A4594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WYO-SCHOOLS-COMPUTERS     05-03 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WYO-SCHOOLS-COMPUTERS-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WYOMING'S INTERNET EXPERIMENT: ONE TEACHER, ONE PUPIL, ONE
COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time
rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAYCEE, Wyo. _ The day began as it always does in Mrs.
Wetherbee's third-grade class at Willow Creek Elementary School,
and it proceeded routinely, from the pledge of allegiance through
reading, writing exercises, math, science, geography and phys ed.
</P>
<P>
   If Diamond Forbes seemed to enjoy almost every minute of her
six-hour day, who could blame her? As Mrs. Wetherbee's only pupil,
she had the teacher all to herself, making Willow Creek a fanciful
symbol of the ultimate in American public education, one-on-one
instruction.
</P>
<P>
   But if the class size is an accident of Wyoming's sparse
population, the iMac computer Diamond uses every day for current
events, research and sending e-mail messages to her friends
represents the ultimate in careful planning.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most states, Wyoming has not taken a big bite of
America's booming economy. Faced with sluggish job growth and a
steady exodus of college graduates to other states, state officials
focused on Internet access in the classroom as a critical component
in equalizing educational opportunities and developing job skills.
As a result, Wyoming this academic year became the first state to
wire all its public schools _ even those as small and remote as
Willow Creek, here in central Wyoming. And there are quite a few
others that are just as small: Among Wyoming's 234 elementary
schools, 19 have fewer than 10 students this year. The state
average is about eight students for every computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child in Wyoming now has the opportunity to develop to
his or her own potential,'' Gov. Jim Geringer, who began the push
for statewide Internet access in schools more than five years ago,
said in an interview. ``By finding a way to touch every school, the
next great leader from business or government could come from that
one place.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Wyoming's rugged terrain and the isolation of many
schools, it has been an ambitious and expensive project, $25
million for the first five years. But in financing the connections,
state leaders recognized a desperate need to keep Wyoming children
competitive or watch the state's economy fade and the population
continue to slip, as it has since 1996, to the current level of
479,602, fewest of any state in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature approved for every school not only
Internet access but also a two-way interactive video system that
maximizes teacher skills by allowing, for example, a Russian
language instructor to address students in his own classroom as
well as those at distant locations at the same time. So far, all of
the state's high schools have been connected to the video system,
with the middle and elementary schools to follow.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of technologies, Geringer said, also
demonstrates how businesses seeking to expand or relocate in
Wyoming could take advantage of a skilled but far-flung workforce.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine a school that would benefit from the
wonders of telecommunications more than Willow Creek, a one-room,
cinder-block school 22 miles off the nearest interstate along a
winding gravel road that cars share with cows and sheep. The
antelope and llamas apparently know enough to keep their distance.
The school mailing address is Kaycee, a town of 400 that is 20
miles away. The nearest city is Casper, more than 80 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   In planning for the academic year, Kathy Wetherbee was expecting
to teach three pupils, Diamond, who is 9, plus two younger
children. But the parents of the other children decided at the last
minute to send them to kindergarten in Kaycee, leaving the iMac to
Diamond, who has found it immensely helpful on her two big projects
this year _ one on the Basque region of Spain, the other on
Scotland. Wednesday, she searched the Internet to see if there had
been any recent sightings of the Loch Ness monster. She found
nothing new, only pictures from the 1930s, which she had seen
before. ``There she is,'' Diamond said, assuring Mrs. Wetherbee
that the monster is female. ``That's why they call her `Nessy.'''
</P>
<P>
   For Diamond, whose mother, Gloria, moved to the area from Casper
last year to marry a local rancher, Skip Forbes, the Internet has
become an invaluable tool. The computer she uses at home is not
linked to a telephone line. ``I learn a lot of card games there,''
she said. But it is clear from her time on the iMac that she has
mastered more than that, navigating the World Wide Web with speed,
dexterity and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   As part of each day, Mrs. Wetherbee requires her to consult the
Casper Tribune's Web site to chart daily weather conditions and
read at least one story. Diamond found the weather information
easily and was drawn to a story about the ABC television dispute
with Time Warner that included a photograph of the ABC studio in
Times Square. Mrs. Wetherbee told her that millions of people live
in New York City, compared with fewer than a half-million in all of
Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond looked puzzled. ``That doesn't make sense,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wetherbee, 54, a veteran elementary school teacher who
plans to retire after this year, said she volunteered to work at
Willow Creek this year, attracted by the remote location _ she
earns an extra $55 a month in what the state calls ``isolation
pay'' _ the class size and the living conditions. Adjoining the
classroom is, effectively, a one-bedroom apartment that includes a
small kitchen, living room and bathroom. Grazing cows and deer
sometimes wander past the huge satellite dishes that serve the
computer and Mrs. Wetherbee's television to peek inside her
windows.
</P>
<P>
   She lives at the school during the week and travels to Casper on
weekends to stay with friends, shop and buy food for the week
ahead. After school ends in June, she said she plans to move to
Modesto, Calif., to live with her sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it has been a gift to be here, and I think it goes both
ways,'' she said of working with Diamond. ``I needed some space
after the typical teaching situation. It was not as much fun
anymore, teaching to test. Everything had become so structured. But
this is a dream. For the first time in my life, I am not managing
children's behavior. I'm truly teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   And Diamond, Mrs. Wetherbee added, has vastly improved her
learning skills this year, especially in reading, which she regards
as her favorite subject ``after recess.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Diamond will have a new teacher at Willow Creek and,
in all likelihood, several classmates, a change that Mrs. Wetherbee
said would enhance Diamond's social skills and improve her
confidence, which is considerable already. Without classmates, she
sees friends and cousins on occasion but spends most of her free
time with her horse, Smokey, and five dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Guiding the cursor across the iMac screen in search of the Loch
Ness monster, Diamond said she would prefer that Mrs. Wetherbee
return in the fall. But even with a new teacher she will still have
her old iMac even if she has to share it.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Diamond doesn't look at it this way, but with the
computer, she has not just been stuck in the little world of a
ranching community,'' Mrs. Wetherbee said. ``The Internet gives her
the opportunity to see a world she doesn't see at home. I think
that's a real blessing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
