<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4599 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-LATAM-COVERDELL0504-C     05-03 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATAM-COVERDELL0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coverdell proposes alliance of hemisphere's democracies
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.), director of the Peace
Corps in the Bush administration and a former member of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, recently outlined a new strategy for
dealing with Latin America. In aconversation with Washington
correspondent Ken Foskett, the senator, who also serves as an
advisor to the presidential campaign of Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
described his ``Democratic Doctrine of the Americas.'' Excerpts
from that conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the doctrine for the Americas and why did you feel
the need to develop it?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's founded on the platform that democracy or liberty is
fragile and never permanent, and it requires a constant vigil.
</P>
<P>
   In our hemisphere, a large number of the democracies are very
new, so they are even more fragile. And I believe that what was
achieved in the '80s with regards to becoming a democratic
hemisphere _ except for one country, Cuba _ really called on the
'90s to become good stewards of that. It's kind of like a garden
just coming up. You've got to be particularly careful in watching
and protecting.
</P>
<P>
   And I don't think we did that. We sort of accepted the fact
that, well, here are all these new democratic republics and then
kind of went off to do other things.
</P>
<P>
   I use this ``Doctrine of the Americas'' as an idea that I hope
will flourish, where all the countries become observant of anything
that undermines the democratic nature of our hemisphere. That could
be a security threat, like narcotics. It could be the lack of civil
institutions, civil law enforcement or judiciary that leave people
unprotected or leaves human rights violations going unaccounted
for. Or the total breakdown of constitutional law. All of these are
very visible today throughout the hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How would you rate the Clinton administration's policies
toward Latin America?
</P>
<P>
   A: Poor. I think the United States hasn't historically as been
attentive to its back yard as it should be. Basically, the
narcotics struggle has languished.
</P>
<P>
   I think that trade policy since NAFTA has been nonexistent. So,
for example, you have Mexico signing a trade agreement with the
European Union a couple of weeks ago. I think the Reagan-Bush years
were, conversely, very attentive.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Given the evidence of fraud in the Peruvian elections, what
should the United States do?
</P>
<P>
   A: The whole democratic hemisphere _ not just the United States
_ needs to exert pressure and sanctions if there is open flouting
of constitutional law.
</P>
<P>
   You do have to accept that, right at the moment, these are
assertions. They seem to be fairly well founded, but they are
assertions. I think the hemisphere should make clear that there
will be consequences. It may be sanctions. It may be trade. It may
be assistance and aid. It may be just that being a partner in the
hemisphere has diminished if you have a country that won't adhere
to the basic premises of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   I think the situation in Peru began to diminish itself when
(President Alberto) Fujimori basically overturned the two-term
limit on the presidency. If he had moved on at that point, he would
probably be one of the larger figures in this hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In Haiti, the administration ousted a dictator and restored
the elected president to power. You have been critical of U.S.
policy there. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because it has accomplished nothing. It's almost sound bite
foreign policy. We send in thousands of troops, impose the
government order as we see it, and leave.
</P>
<P>
   Two billion dollars has been invested in Haiti. And you can go
to any hearing on (Capitol) Hill, and the common denominator is
that the Haitians are worse off today than they were before we
interceded, as bad as that situation was. There is no government
now.
</P>
<P>
   And if you were going to make the investment you made, you would
want to make sure that it flowered, that it bloomed. And that takes
a real conscious effort of long-term engagement, and you just don't
ever hear the administration ever refer to it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A 30-year embargo against Cuba has failed to bring democracy
to that country. What is the best way, in your view, to bring
democracy to Cuba?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is a huge debate up here as to whether (sanctions) have
worked or not. Clearly, Castro is in charge of the government so
somebody might say, ``It hasn't worked.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Castro's influence in the hemisphere has
become very, very limited. And so the embargo and the closing off
of the country could be said to have worked.
</P>
<P>
   The political reality is that the policy, which is greatly
shaped by Cuban-Americans, is not going to change in the short
term. There will be modifications in terms of food-related products
and health-related products and the ability of families to send aid
to their families still in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes people forget that in Castro we have an individual who
does consider the United States an adversary, a hostile force. We
have an individual who would send MiGs out to shoot down private
aircraft or would ram a boat of refugees with women and children
and certify that everyone one of them was drowned. This is an
unusually evil and hostile force, and I think that drives a lot of
the policy here.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How confident are you that the doctrine you've outlined would
be a part of the foreign policy of a Bush administration?
</P>
<P>
   A: I can't say. I was taken with the fact that Robert Zoellick,
who was at the State Department at the time I was director of the
Peace Corps under his father's administration, is a part of (George
W. Bush's) foreign policy team. And he recently gave a speech in
Florida with regard to the lack of attention in the hemisphere. And
if you read the two documents _ and neither one of us talked to the
other about it _ they are extremely alike.
</P>
<P>
   It would be my intention to make the argument to the new
administration that the hemisphere does require an almost command
focus and considerable attention.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
