<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BEIRUT-MALE-DANCER-AR     05-03 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEIRUT-MALE-DANCER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIRUT'S RISING STAR: A MALE BELLY DANCER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Lebanon Journal) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT20 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ It is nearing 2 a.m. when a cloud of blue
smoke rises from the stage. Bands of turquoise lights flit through
the murk as the music switches abruptly from the normal fare of
Latin salsa to the lugubrious melody of an old Arabic song.
</P>
<P>
   Out slithers a tall broad-shouldered man, his eyes rimmed with
black powder. He does a little shoulder shimmy and teasingly flicks
one hip audience-ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please welcome,'' shouts the emcee from somewhere in the
shadows beyond the spectacle, ``the one and only Mousbah!''
</P>
<P>
   It is belly dancing night in the Amor y Libertad nightclub in
north Beirut. And Mousbah Baalbaki, quite possibly the only male
belly dancer performing regularly in public in the Arab world, is
about to tweak tradition to the delight of his adoring fans and the
discomfort of many others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can shake his body and get money,'' said Baalbaki, in
an interview before his show. ``But to me dancing is an art.''
</P>
<P>
   What Baalbaki, who is 28, does is not a transvestite show or a
striptease. It is more like ``Saturday Night Fever'' meets ``The
Thousand and One Nights.'' Sinuous and seductive, dressed one
recent Friday night in a gauzy black caftan over a Bedouin-style
white robe, he undulates on stage with a faraway look in his eyes
and a bodyguard close at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wasn't an artist, he would have been arrested long
ago,'' said Michel Elefteriades, the nightclub owner and Baalbaki's
promoter.
</P>
<P>
   He offered a simple explanation for his interest in representing
a male belly dancer in a country that, for all its worldly glitz,
still has a generous streak of religious conservatism and
criminalizes homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always looking to shock,'' said Elefteriades.
</P>
<P>
   That is not always an easy task.
</P>
<P>
   Beirut is a paradoxical town, with European designer boutiques
interspersed among the sniper-shattered buildings from the 15-year
civil war and Shiite Muslim militants hobnobbing with urbane
Christians and Sunni Muslims in the halls of power.
</P>
<P>
   But Baalbaki's public gyrations seem a step beyond the pale even
for Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real taboo,'' the dancer confided. ``In our culture,
people look down even on women who dance professionally, so they
look down on me even more. Every weekend I struggle with the
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of the men in the Amor y Libertad seemed to squirm
and concentrate resolutely on their drinks when Baalbaki took the
stage. Their dates did not seem discomfited at all. Although
Baalbaki does not like it _ he is there, he explained, to be
watched, not to be a background novelty act _ quite a few young
women lost themselves in their own versions of belly dancing as he
performed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can dance to any kind of music,'' he said, ``but with an
Arabic song, it comes from my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   And his abs, among other body parts.
</P>
<P>
   There is a long tradition of male teachers of belly dancing in
Arab countries. But men who perform the flirtatious movements, at
least in mixed company, are rare.
</P>
<P>
   And not only rare but bogus, in the view of Fifi Abdo, the
leading lady of Egyptian belly dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man belly dancing?'' she exclaimed in a telephone interview
from Cairo. ``They can do the folk dances, but it's impossible for
a man to dance real belly dancing. The phrase itself describes the
part from the hips to the waist and a man lacks the energy there
that a woman has. They can perform, but they can't belly dance.''
</P>
<P>
   An Egyptian man who had undergone a sex change operation danced
onstage for a while in Cairo a few years ago, causing a major stir
before he disappeared from public view. One Istanbul nightclub
offers a male belly dancing show.
</P>
<P>
   But whether people are ready for it yet is an unanswered
question.
</P>
<P>
   Baalbaki has not told his parents that he belly dances, much
less that he does it in public. And Elefteriades' own father, who
is a theatrical promoter, has expressed profound reservations about
his son's association with a male belly dancer.
</P>
<P>
   This annoys Elefteriades, who considers himself a warrior in a
larger fight against social conservatism. ``I don't think it makes
sense that men in a lot of countries like Greece dance to their own
music,'' he said, ``while the Arabs only clap their hands while
women dance.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants to make Baalbaki a big star _ that is how he put it _
and is preparing a music video for distribution on Arab satellite
stations that shows his client dancing but without the usual makeup
and flamboyant costume. He is weighing the pros and cons of
allowing Baalbaki to accept an invitation to a talk show on a
Lebanese television station.
</P>
<P>
   The world outside Beirut also beckons. ``I think there's a real
interest in Orientalism,'' Elefteriades said. ``There's always a
flavor that's popular and now it's the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   Baalbaki was just another club kid dancing his nights away in
Beirut's many bars, discovered him and signed him to a seven-year
contract that prohibits him from free-lance dancing and from
gaining weight.
</P>
<P>
   He did not have formal training, picking up his moves instead
from watching Egyptian movies of the 1940s and 1950s, which always
featured a voluptuous belly dancer as the centerpiece. He can be
mesmerized by his favorite, the late Takiya Karyoka, whose dancing
is still considered to have set the modern standard.
</P>
<P>
   Baalbaki is handling the celebrity of his nascent stardom _ the
squealing young women who haunt his dressing room, for example _
pretty easily. ``All my life, I've enjoyed being a celebrity,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is the taunts and the hostility _ even a few thrown objects _
that bother him. So he is keeping his day job as the fashion editor
of a glossy Lebanese magazine and tries to maintain a regal
indifference to the occasional insults.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he walks, no matter what people say, it doesn't touch
him,'' said Elefteriades in admiration. Then he quoted a line from
the Lebanese-American philosopher and poet Khalil Gibran to explain
what he meant: ``The dogs bark, but the caravan moves on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
