<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4609 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-ECONOMY-BOS &LR;      05-03 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC CONSEQUENCES SEEN IN MUGABE INTRANSIGENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ A day after Commonwealth member nations condemned
the escalating violence in Zimbabwe this week, President Robert
Mugabe publicly spurned his critics and refused to halt
government-sponsored attacks against white farmers and his
political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, South Africa's currency, the rand, dropped three
cents against the US dollar. That might not sound like much, but
the swiftness of the reaction, economic analysts say, indicates how
much Zimbabwe's crisis has rattled its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble comes at a time when southern African countries are
becoming increasingly reliant on each other, developing stronger
trading links and integerated transportation systems. But with the
unrest in Zimbabwe, investors are hedging across the region. Banks
are withholding credit. And companies are shutting down plants.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the rand, southern Africa's strongest and most stable
currency, hit record lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation continues to melt down,'' said Kevin Wakeford,
chief executive of the South African Chamber of Commerce. ``Trading
conditions are abnormal. Credit guarantees, foreign exchange
reserves, risk cover _ all that is absent. It is very difficult for
importers and exporters alike, and it is evident that the situation
is having a serious impact on our currency.''
</P>
<P>
   Already facing its worst economic crisis in at least a decade,
Zimbabwe plunged further into chaos in February as veterans of the
1970s war for independence began invading white-owned commercial
farms, the backbone of the economy. In the past 10 weeks, nearly
1,000 farms have come under violent attack.
</P>
<P>
   Many farmers lost their soy crops and have been blocked from
planting winter wheat. When trading opened last week on the annual
tobacco harvest, which accounts for 30 percent of Zimbabwe's annual
exports, barely a third of the normal yield wa on auction.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture represents for about 40 percent of Zimbabwe's total
annual output and is critical to Zimbabwe's foreign exchange
reserves, now too low to cover the debt owed by any one of the
state-owned utility companies. The country can't afford diesel
fuel, and banks, carrying about $158 million in farm debts, risk
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Regional leaders and Western donors offered Mugabe a generous
bailout in recent weeks. Britain promised $57 million and offered
to unfreeze earlier pledges to finance land reform, on condition
that Mugabe end the farm invasions and begin organizing the
upcoming parliamentary elections. South Africa lobbied the
International Monetary Fund to provide about $123 million to prop
up Zimbabwe's bankrupt electricity company, on similar conditions.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Mugabe has refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let no one ever think that we will call upon the war veterans
to withdraw,'' Mugabe said Wednesday, reacting to the
Commonwealth's expression of ``deep concerns'' over Zimbabwe's
rising instability. Britain responded by slapping its former colony
with an arms embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to keep their doors open, Zimbabwe's bankers warned
Tuesday that the country's arrears on debt payments had risen to
$350 million and that it risks defaulting on its entire $4.5
billion foreign debt. Zimbabwe's stock market, meanwhile, is
trading at a five-month low.
</P>
<P>
   Casting a wary eye northward, South Africa's Standard Chartered
Bank said Zimbabwe's economic decline has triggered profit warnings
from companies with operations in Zimbabwe. In its week bulletin
last week, the bank raised worries about a crisis in foreign
investor confidence in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere has this been clearer than in South Africa,'' the bank
warned. ``Despite good fundamentals, sound fiscal policy, and
growth that is expected to accelerate over the coming years, the
rand has been caught up in the `Zimbabwean contagion.' '' Shaken
both by the decline in the euro, Europe's common currency, and
Zimbabwe's woes, the rand slid close to seven to the dollar
Wednesday on currency exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe's crisis is particularly worrisome for South Africa,
which counts its northern neighbor as its largest African trading
partner. The two countries have entwined banking and industrial
sectors. Underscoring their concern, senior South African business,
financial, and agriculture leaders flew to Harare this week for
consultations on limiting the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Several South African manufacturers and construction firms have
suspended new investment in Zimbabwe in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political acts and behavior are undermining fundamental
capitalist values like the rule of law and property rights,''
Wakeford said. ``Our greatest fear is an implosion of Zimbabwe's
economy before the elections.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
