<HEADER>
A4613 &Cx1f; tab-z
u i BC-GATES-PHILANTHROPY-SH     05-03 2306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATES-PHILANTHROPY-SHORT-VERSION-CENTERPIECE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO GIVE AWAY $21.8 BILLION
</HEADLINE>
  (For immediate release.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following article from The New York Times
Magazine is for use by clients of the ``Centerpiece'' package.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. This article has been
double-filed into the ``a'' general news and ``i'' international
news files. 
 By JEAN STROUSE 
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Before Bill Gates began giving money away, people complained
that he was a miser.
 &HT;    Now that he is giving money away, they complain that: he's doing
it too late, isn't giving enough; that the projects he is financing
are too conservative, too liberal, too big, too small, too safe,
too risky, too conventional, too splashy.
 &HT;    Or they say he's only doing it to avoid taxes, or to expand
Microsoft's markets, or, especially, to improve his image in light
of the government's antitrust suit.
 &HT;    But in January, the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation edged past
Britain's Wellcome Trust to become the largest in the world, with
assets of $21.8 billion. Even the greatest philanthropists of the
past did not give away as much in real dollars over their entire
lifetimes as Gates has at the age of 44.
 &HT;    Gates has always said that he will give away most of his fortune
before he dies. He plans to make sure his children are well taken
care of but doesn't want to leave them the burden of tremendous
wealth.
 &HT;    He probably has decades of earning and giving ahead. In
February, Patty Stonesifer, president of the foundation, said that
Gates thought it had reached about the right size for the time
being.
 &HT;    Gates has delegated the running of the foundation to Stonesifer,
a friend and former Microsoft executive, and to his father, William
H. Gates Jr., a 73-year-old retired attorney _ although he and his
wife, Melinda, are actively involved.
 &HT;    The foundation is already having a major impact _ not only on
specific projects in the fields of education and health but also on
other wealthy individuals, on the American conversation about
philanthropy and on public policy.
 &HT;    The aspects of his philanthropical work that Gates seems most
excited about have to do with redressing tremendous inequities in
global health. According to the World Health Organization, less
than 10 percent of the world's medical research financing is
directed at the health problems that afflict 90 percent of its
people.
 &HT;    Pharmaceutical companies don't make drugs for people who can't
afford them. And millions of children in poor countries die every
year from diseases that could be prevented by existing vaccines.
The Gates Foundation recently pledged $750 million to help buy and
distribute those medications in developing countries through a new
group called Global Alliance for Vaccines and Immunization.
 &HT;    ``We're in this unbelievable era where you could argue, what's
the most amazing thing taking place?'' Gates says, leaning forward
in his chair at his Redmond office one morning in February. ``Is it
software technology stuff and the Internet and new forms of
communication? Or is it the revolution in biology?''
 &HT;    At the World Economic Forum at Davos, Switzerland, in January,
Gates was disappointed to find not everyone as galvanized as he is
by the combination of biotechnological innovation, widespread
social disparities and hugely difficult problems that might be
solved by the intervention of enormous resources and armies of
intelligent people. He sat on a panel that officially inaugurated
the global vaccine alliance with Gro Harlem Brundtland of WHO,
Carol Bellamy of UNICEF, James Wolfensohn of the World Bank,
Joaquim Chissano, the president of Mozambique, and Raymond
Gilmartin of Merck (pharmaceuticals).
 &HT;    It was, Gates said in his office a month later, a colossal bore:
``We're talking about saving three million lives a year here....
but that was one of the least inspirational, least informative
panels I've seen.''
 &HT;    The Gates Foundation is underwriting projects in Ghana, Gambia
and South Africa, focusing on childhood immunization, family
planning, cervical cancer, malaria, the reduction of maternal and
infant mortality and AIDS.
 &HT;    The foundation generally channels grants through existing
organizations, seeking to identify good projects that are already
under way and to find new models and strategies that work. The most
difficult problem, however, for potentially lifesaving
interventions is getting medications and services to the people who
need them.
 &HT;    The foundation's health financing will help improve people's
access to existing and newly developing medical technologies, and
support people who are finding innovative ways to approach public
health problems and promote major social change.
 &HT;    Lynette Denny, for example, is a gynecological oncologist
working with women in impoverished squatter villages and townships
near Cape Town. Most of the women have never seen a gynecologist,
much less had a Pap test. Cervical cancer is the leading cause of
cancer death among women in developing countries, but it can
effectively be prevented by early detection.
 &HT;    Because Pap smears are complicated to administer and expensive
to analyze, Denny's work led her and several colleagues to devise a
simple new screening test for cervical cancer. In early January,
the Journal of the American Medical Association published a study
showing that the new test detects the precursors of cervical cancer
at least as well as the Pap test does. Denny works with the
Alliance for the Prevention of Cervical Cancer, which received a
$50 million grant over five years from the Gates Foundation in
1999.
 &HT;    The Gates Foundation has a lean, informal structure. Last year,
when Gates decided to combine two smaller charitable funds into one
and increase the endowment, he chose not to enlarge the foursome in
charge of ultimate decisions _ himself, his wife, his father (CEO),
and Stonesifer (president) _ and not to appoint a board.
 &HT;    Gates set up the first foundation in 1994, the year he married
Melinda. And, by all accounts Melinda has played a significant role
in directing more of her husband's attention to the world outside
Microsoft.
 &HT;    The foundation's senior adviser for global health is William
Foege, a widely revered epidemiologist and former head of the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention who was part of the
international team that eradicated smallpox.
 &HT;    Stonesifer and Gates' father serve as co-chairpersons of the
foundation, and Gates and his wife set the overall direction and
priorities for their giving. The foundation receives more than
3,000 proposals a month, and the senior officers, with some staff
help, select lists of projects and submit them to Melinda and Bill,
who read and talk about the proposals and personally approve every
grant over $1 million.
 &HT;    Bill writes questions and comments all over the lists _
sometimes saying simply yes (to a request for $40 million) or no,
or ``tell me more about respiratory diseases,'' or ``why this
country?'' or ``if this does well what's the next step?'' His
negative response isn't always final: ``When I say no,'' he says
with a grin, ``somebody usually comes back with, `Did you really
mean to say no on this one?'''
 &HT;    Melinda is more closely involved than her husband in the
day-to-day operations of the organization. ``Melinda has a strong
interest in children and early childhood,'' says Stonesifer. ``Bill
is very interested in medical interventions and new tools, in
figuring out what is possible with new scientific technology. And
they are both passionate about how those areas can work together.''
 &HT;    Since foundations are required by law annually to give away 5
percent of their assets, the directors of this $21.8 billion fund
now have to dispense more than $1 billion a year _ not an easy
thing to do well. They insist on careful monitoring and evaluation
to assure that the money is not wasted or mismanaged. They take a
long-term, strategic view of what their grants can do.
 &HT;    So far, though, Gates' domestic U.S. programs have drawn more
critical fire than the work in international health.
 &HT;    Last September the foundation announced that it was pledging $1
billion over 20 years to scholarships for minority students _ for
full-time college programs and graduate study in engineering, math,
science, education or library science, to be administered by the
United Negro College Fund.
 &HT;    In October, the conservative Weekly Standard ran an article
called ``Bill Gates, Minority Leader: A Billion Dollars Is a
Terrible Thing to Waste.'' The argument: that the program should
not be race-based and is an attempt to circumvent recent
anti-affirmative-action rulings in states including Texas,
California and Washington.
 &HT;    Gates looks back with some amusement at his belated realization
that access to information technology might not be the answer to
the world's most serious problems. Microsoft was donating computers
to poor communities in Africa in the mid-'90s. But he says it was
toward the end of 1998 that he realized _ partly through working
with Foege and Gordon Perkin, the foundation's director of global
health, and partly through his own reading _ how little
international attention was being paid to some of the world's most
urgent medical problems and how much of a difference his
large-scale resources could make.
 &HT;    WHO estimates that malaria kills about 2 million people a year,
nearly half of them children in sub-Saharan Africa, infects about
200 million more and poses a risk to 2.3 billion _ more than a
third of the world's population.
 &HT;    Yet since most victims are poor, there has been no financial
incentive to develop a malaria vaccine. According to The Economist,
the amount of money spent on malaria vaccine research worldwide in
1996 was about $60 million. In June 1999 the Gates Foundation set
up a $50 million Malaria Vaccine Initiative.
 &HT;    ``With one grant,'' says Gates, ``we became the biggest private
funder of malaria research.''
 &HT;    The research fund creates what economists call a ``push''
mechanism, providing the means for scientists to conduct studies
that would not otherwise be economically feasible. Through its $750
million gift to the Global Alliance for Vaccines and Immunization,
it also gives pharmaceutical companies a ``pull'' incentive _
essentially saying, ``If you develop a vaccine, we'll buy and
distribute it.'' Still, scientists think it will take at least 10
years to find a vaccine against the extremely complex malaria
virus.
 &HT;    The foundation is also applying the ``pull'' mechanism to the
less glamorous but no less urgent problem of getting existing,
relatively cheap childhood vaccines against measles, whooping
cough, tetanus, polio and diphtheria to developing countries. The
$750 million fund will buy and distribute those basic drugs, along
with new ones against yellow fever, hepatitis B and Haemophilus
influenza type B.
 &HT;    One of the most ambitious of the Gates-financed projects is the
New York-based International AIDS Vaccine Initiative. Founded by an
intense, 43-year-old physician named Seth Berkley, the initiative
identifies promising AIDS vaccine candidates, then brokers deals
with drug manufacturers and developing countries to fast-track the
candidates into clinical trials.
 &HT;    More than 33 million people are infected with HIV worldwide,
about 70 percent of them in sub-Saharan Africa, where AIDS is
expected to kill more people in the coming decade than died in all
the wars of the 20th century. Pharmaceutical companies are not
about to spend enormous amounts of money developing a vaccine that
is needed primarily by people who can't afford it. But if the
International AIDS Vaccine Initiative supplies the research money,
a drug company would have no major costs to recoup. In exchange for
its financing, the initiative expects the company to provide the
vaccine at low cost in developing countries or forfeit the rights
to the technology.
 &HT;    In the fall of 1998, the initiative announced two novel vaccine
approaches for Kenya and South Africa and started preparations for
clinical trials. Early in 1999 the Gates Foundation provided a
five-year, $25 million grant for the effort.
 &HT;    Dr. David Ho, the director of the Aaron Diamond AIDS Research
Center, an affiliate of Rockefeller University, says, ``Vaccines
are the biggest thing in AIDS research today.''
 &HT;    Ho, who came up with the concept of the triple-combination drug
therapy that has significantly slowed AIDS in the United States and
Europe, thinks the freedom Gates has to provide substantial
financing more quickly than the National Institutes of Health is
essential.
 &HT;    Wouldn't it be interesting, he reflects, ``if Bill Gates were
remembered in the future more for his philanthropy than for his
work with computers?''
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Jean Strouse 
