<HEADLINE>
ALTAVISTA LAUNCHES SIMPLIFIED SEARCH SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AltaVista Co., the Internet search engine developed from Digital
Equipment Corp.'s research labs, launched a new Web site Wednesday
in an effort to fend off rivals chipping away at the company's
market share.
</P>
<P>
   The new site, named Raging Search, is a radically simplified
version of AltaVista's main Web site. That orginal site has
struggled over the years to win over notoriously fickle Web users
by adding a plethora of features, such as stock quotes, weather
reports, e-mail, news, and shopping, in addition to its signature
search service.
</P>
<P>
   While those features drew more people to AltaVista's Web site,
they also distracted from its search engine. As a result, AltaVista
lost some of its core following to newcomers such as Google.com and
Northern Light, whose simpler sites feature only searching tools.
</P>
<P>
   Raging Search is AltaVista's attempt to recapture what it calls
``search enthusiasts,'' such as professional researchers,
librarians and students. Raging Search will operate alongside
AltaVista's main site, which will continue to have a menu of
services and compete with portal companies such as Yahoo! and Lycos
for casual Web surfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're focusing on reinforcing the core foundational strength
of AltaVista, which is our search service,'' said Rod Schrock,
chief executive of the Palo Alto, Calif., company. ``For the first
time, we're segmenting the market. Our new, pure Web search site
will be the fastest, most unobstructed path to Web pages.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny Sullivan, editor of SearchEngineWatch.com based in
Britian, said AltaVista's move represented the first time a search
engine has launched a completely new site to cater to hard core
users and opinion makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No established search engine has ever gone that route
before,'' Sullivan said. ``Ultimately, this may give them a way to
keep their loyal audience, while allowing them to tinker with their
main site.''
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista's search engines respond to 40 million queries a day
worldwide, giving them a 35 percent market share of the total
search queries on the Internet, according to company data.
</P>
<P>
   But when measured by the volume of traffic it garners, AltaVista
captures just 17 percent of Web surfers who visit search sites,
according to Media Metrix. Yahoo! captures a commanding 63.5
percent, while Lycos has 38.5 percent (combined totals exceed 100
percent because people tend to visit more than one site to do a
single search).
</P>
<P>
   Greg Memo, senior vice president at AltaVista, said the
discrepancy lies in the fact that Media Metrix does not count
traffic outside of the United States, where AltaVista gets over
half of its queries.
</P>
<P>
   Schrock said the launch of Raging Search was not scheduled to
coincide with AltaVista's pending initial public stock offering.
The company announced several weeks ago that it has postponed its
IPO until the recent stock market turmoil settles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting for the market to come back,'' Schrock said
Wednesday. But he gave no indication of when the company might
proceed with its IPO.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista has yet to make a profit since its inception in 1995.
It is jointly owned by CMGI, a venture capital firm in Andover, and
Compaq Computer, which acquired Digital Equipment in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
