<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4624 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-NOW-AGAIN-LADN &LR;      05-03 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOW-AGAIN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCOMMON GROUNDS
</HEADLINE>
  Career styles differ but the goals are the same for `Now and Again'
stars 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `tonight' refers to Fri., May 5.) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a photo shoot featuring TV performers expected to be the
film stars of tomorrow for a glossy magazine, a photo assistant
squeezes the air out of some oversized beach toys that surround a
figure-eight-shaped pool, while a hotel employee runs a wet mop
around the outside of the pool to no discernible effect. Just a few
minutes ago, Eric Close, who stars on ``Now and Again'' as Michael
Wiseman, a middle-age former insurance salesman reborn as a lean,
dreamy governmental crime-fighting machine, was helping start an
exodus of young, beautiful and fully clothed young actors into that
pool.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he sits calmly (and dryly) in the hotel bar, which sports a
chic '60s retro look, the kind of place George Jetson would come to
drown his sorrows. Close, however, orders nothing stronger than an
iced tea, and explains that the photo shoot is important because it
should help his feature film career, which, he makes clear, is very
important to him.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks later, Margaret Colin, who has a solid movie
background _ she was on hand to witness the world being saved in
``Independence Day'' _ and currently plays Wiseman's ``widowed''
wife, Lisa, sits in an elegant dining room and makes it clear that
doing a movie over the summer would be OK, but she's not going to
knock herself out worrying about such things.
</P>
<P>
   Opposites attract: Together, the ambitious Close and the more
career-casual Colin form television's most unique couple suffering
through unrequited passion. In the show's set-up, Michael was a
frumpy guy (played by John Goodman) killed by a speeding subway
train at the beginning of the season only to reawaken with his
brain in the body of a much younger and hunkier man. Not a bad deal
_ except that, to perform the secret government work required of
him, he's not supposed to contact his wife ever again. (Obviously,
that rule has been broken at length over the season, but Michael
has never revealed to Lisa his true identity.)
</P>
<P>
   Upon its debut last September, ``Now and Again'' was hailed as a
roundly entertaining genre-buster _ the year's best (and not just
because it was the only) romantic action-adventure comedy. Still,
the hot buzz hasn't quite lasted; as we near the time that the
networks will announce their upcoming fall schedules, ``Now and
Again'' is what is called ``on the bubble,'' meaning it could
either be picked up for a second season _ or that Michael Wiseman
could die a second death. The series offers up its season finale
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the bubble _ that's a new phrase for me!'' says Colin,
laughing. She then offers an argument why the show should return:
``We did better there than CBS has done since 'Beauty and the
Beast,' which was a long time ago. And what else do they have
that's going to do as well in that time slot as we have? It's not
the most flowery way to look at our show, but I heard someone
thinking that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Close blames, with good reason, the Friday time slot _ the show
is designed to appeal to the sort of audience that is likely out on
a Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even 'The Practice' was languishing on Saturday night, and
when it was moved _ boom. We need a chance to build the show _
we're at a place where we're about ready to pop,'' he says, and
helpfully offers a suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday at 10, right after 'Everybody Loves Raymond,' would be
great,'' he says. ``Right now, they have 'Family Law,' which is a
real serious drama, and since you have all these comedies (earlier
on the schedule), I think it'd be nice to go into a dramedy. I know
Glenn (Gordon Caron, the series' creator) would love to be on
Mondays at 10, too. But I'm not in the executives' office, I've
just got to do my job. Everything about this show makes it a
winner. The only thing it's missing at this point is, it's in a
tough time slot.''
</P>
<P>
   One factor working against ``Now and Again'' is its adventure
quotient results in budget-busting sequences. Close, who previously
starred in the adventure series ``Dark Skies'' and ``The
Magnificent Seven,'' says, ``Somehow, I keep getting on these
huge-budget shows, and if they're not doing the numbers that the
advertisers are looking for, it's hard to justify keeping it on the
air. This show is grabbing the demographic they want _ it's a fun,
young, hip show. The advertisers like the show, and that'll make a
difference in the life of the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Colin jokingly offers a money-saving solution: ``I say, you want
to save some money, do a blackout episode. We'll walk around with
candles and flashlights saying, 'Look, he's flying through the
air!'''
</P>
<P>
   When Close and Colin got the script for the pilot, there was no
way they could guess the series' direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glenn used to describe the episodes in terms of this musical
or that musical, then he ran out of references,'' Colin recalls.
``It was 'Damn Yankees' a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was definitely curious to know where it was going to go _ I
talked to Glenn, and he assured me that he wasn't going to do your
basic superhero show, that he was going to take it in different
directions and surprise people,'' Close says. ``I think what
happens in the first season is, you get a sense of what people like
and don't like, what they want to see more of and what they want to
see less of.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's episode will bring back the Eggman _ the enigmatic
terrorist who opened the series by killing passengers in a Tokyo
subway, only to disappear a couple of episodes later. ``I think
people have been longing to see that, to see Michael go out on
missions, and we're gonna start using his abilities on the job he
was designed for. We're setting the groundwork for where the show's
going to go, but I hope the show never gets married to one
direction. What'll make it exciting and creative is mixing it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Colin says, ``We'll be put together again in some big
end-of-the-world plight that's worth it for him to risk revealing
himself. But it's like the 'Fugitive' _ he can't really tell who he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Colin buys that the show's premise can't offer flights
of fancy that would allow Michael and Lisa fleeting moments of
passion. ``Glenn's opened up this huge sci-fi ball of wax _ take
romance there. We have to spend more time developing romantic and
sexual tension so that people can root for us. Ninety percent of
the time, when I'm in the same room with the man, I'm yelling at
him.''
</P>
<P>
   She suggests cribbing the gizmo from the movie ``Men in Black''
that erases memories: ``How wickedly tickling for them to hook up
and then to remove it from their consciousness,'' Colin suggests.
``Since you've already introduced the sci-fi element, use it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Close observes, ``I think they're doing a
good job of not letting Margaret's character not stagnate in one
place. They're letting her move on and grow _ she definitely
doesn't play the pathetic widow. They can focus stories on her
life, too, and eventually, they'll be able just to weave back and
forth just occasionally to remind the audience of who they are to
each other without overkilling it. But it's a difficult thing to do
_ you don't want to wear that out, the whole relationship between
the two of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Colin, for her part, thinks more could be done. ``Everything I
suggest, Glenn gives to another character. So I no longer suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric is a charming, enthusiastic young man with a lot of
playfulness in him,'' she continues, ``but what we have yet to
explore in this show is her seeing someone beyond his years in that
man. He knows what music she likes, but that's not enough to knock
her over. Glenn has to step up and write that.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The show: ``Now and Again.'' &QL; 
What: The Eggman is back in the season finale. &QL; 
The stars: Eric Close, Margaret Colin. &QL; 
Where: CBS. &QL; 
When: 9 tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
