A4625 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DELAY-PAC-510&AMP;ADD-NYT     05-03 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAY-PAC-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS ACCUSE DELAY OF RACKETEERING IN GOP FUND-RAISING EFFORTS
</HEADLINE>
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a federal lawsuit filed Wednesday, congressional
Democrats accused Rep. Tom DeLay, the House Majority Whip, of
engaging in extortion, racketeering and money laundering in his
aggressive fund raising for Republican candidates and causes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, said that the suit was filed in
an effort to stop ``massive illegal conduct'' by DeLay, R-Texas,
who has raised millions of dollars for the Republican party through
a variety of committees.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is the third attempt in the past year by Democrats
to corral DeLay's fund-raising empire that some critics and
admirers have come to call ``DeLay, Inc.'' Democrats last year
complained to the Justice Department and the Federal Election
Commission about DeLay's tactics, without immediate result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. DeLay is unfortunately conducting these activities under
the color of his office,'' Kennedy said at a press conference
Wednesday, ``He seeks through the use of systematic extortion to
coerce the contribution of millions of dollars to Republicans and
to intimidate those inclined to support Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   In reply, DeLay declared himself ``saddened and disappointed''
that Democrats would tarnish the dignity of the House ``by
resorting to ugly, unfounded, politically motivated charges for
their own political gains.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Baron, a spokesman for DeLay, said that the charges
were baseless and DeLay would vigorously contest them, if they are
not quickly dismissed by the court. ``This is a tactic designed to
limit Republican fund raising. That's all this is,'' Baron said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit attempts to apply the federal Racketeer Influenced
and Corrupt Organizations Act, known by the acronym RICO, to
DeLay's fund-raising activities through a variety of linked
committees.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is drawn chiefly from news reports over the past
year that detail DeLay's forceful efforts to persuade corporate
lobbyists to donate large sums to a number of political action
committees controlled by DeLay and his associates.
</P>
<P>
   Robert F. Bauer, the Democratic lawyer who drew up the
complaint, said he believed it was the first time that the
racketeering statute had been applied in a political fund-raising
case, although the conservative legal watchdog group Judicial Watch
cited the law in one of its complaints against the Clinton-Gore
re-election committee of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said that the law can be applied against any form of
bribery or extortion by an organized group. He also said that
federal money-laundering laws govern political as well as criminal
activities.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kenneth A. Gross, a former chief of enforcement at the
Federal Election Commission, said the attempt to apply the
racketeering law to political fund raising was creative but legally
questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that Mr. DeLay is an aggressive
fund-raiser,'' Gross said, ``but to allege that he's crossed the
line into racketeering as a legal matter is a real stretch.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gross speculated that the Democrats were hoping to use the
lawsuit to engage in extensive pre-trial discovery, allowing them
to pore through the records of DeLay's various fund-raising
committees.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit names several DeLay-related committees as part of a
scheme to extort and launder illegal political funds, but focuses
on the Republican Majority Issues Committee, a group that plans to
spend $25 million on voter turnout and issue advertising in the
fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The group is organized under a provision of the Internal Revenue
Code known as section 527 that allows it to raise and spend
unlimited amounts of money with no disclosure, as long as it does
not advocate the election or defeat of individual candidates. The
Democrats contend that such activities amount to illegal money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Gallant, chairman of the Republican Majority Issues
Committee, said that the lawsuit was a threat to the group's
free-speech rights and an effort by Democratic ``hacks'' to stifle
independent political groups. He said that liberal groups, such as
the Sierra Club, were also taking advantage of the section 527
loophole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
