u i BC-SRILANKA-UNREST-NYT &LR;      05-03 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SRILANKA-UNREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBATTLED SRI LANKA TRIES TO BLUNT TAMIL REBEL OFFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The Sri Lankan cabinet took emergency steps
Wednesday night to divert money to the war effort at the northern
tip of this island nation, where government forces are battling
Tamil rebels _ and the rebels are winning.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, a guerrilla group that is
notorious for its suicide bombers, Wednesday lobbed mortar fire
into a strategic military base on Sri Lanka's northern peninsula in
the latest phase of a powerful offensive. They are trying to
reclaim Jaffna, the city at the heart of the Tamil ethnic
minority's culture, which the rebels lost to government forces five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers, designated a terrorist outfit by the United States,
have delivered humiliating defeats to the army on their recent
march toward Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
   They routed the government on April 22 at the Elephant Pass army
base, which is on a slender spit of land connecting the rest of the
island to the Jaffna Peninsula, and forced as many as 17,000 troops
to retreat to the north.
</P>
<P>
   And they proceeded to overrun the Pallai army base this weekend,
moving another step closer to Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task was to inflict casualties and get back to fight
another day,'' Brig. Palithi Fernando, spokesman for the Sri Lankan
military, said Wednesday in a telephone interview. ``We're fighting
a defensive battle.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Tigers pounded the Kilali military base on the
coast, just 23 miles east of Jaffna, with sporadic mortar fire, the
brigadier said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently fearing that more than 30,000 government soldiers
could be trapped on the Jaffna peninsula _ at the mercy of the
merciless Tigers _ Sri Lanka's foreign minister, Lakshman
Kadirgamar, came to Delhi on Wednesday to meet with India's prime
minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee, and said a request to India for
help in evacuating the troops could be in the works.
</P>
<P>
   But after their meeting, India's foreign minister, Jaswant
Singh, ruled out any such military assistance. ``The evacuation of
Sri Lankan troops is not India's responsibility,'' he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The fall of Jaffna _ which some military analysts believe could
come within weeks _ would be a tremendous political blow to the
recently re-elected president, Chandrika Kumaratunga. Her party
faces parliamentary elections by August.
</P>
<P>
   Kumaratunga, who was wounded in a December attack by a Tiger
suicide bomber, was first elected president in 1994 on a peace
platform, but began a major military campaign against the rebels in
1995 after talks broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Her greatest military triumph was the government's recapture in
Dec. 1995 of Jaffna, which had been the Tigers' capital for five
years and the stronghold for the rebels' unofficial mini-state on
the Jaffna Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the rebels advancing, a cabinet meeting led by the
president suspended all non-essential development work for three
months and said it would divert the money saved to the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers have been battling since 1983 for a separate
homeland, called Tamil Eelam, for their ethnic group, which they
feel has been mistreated by the majority Sinhalese. More than
60,000 people have died in the conflict. And despite an expensive
government military buildup in recent years, the Tigers appear to
be stronger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, casualties on both sides have mounted, as
have hardships for civilians living in Sri Lanka's predominantly
Tamil north.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando said 500 government troops have died since the attack
on Elephant Pass. He estimated that 1,000 Tiger rebels have been
killed. And each side has about 1,500 wounded, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from the warfront in the north are heavily dependent on
information handed out by the government and the rebels.
Journalists in Sri Lanka said there has been no phone contact with
Jaffna since the rebels blew up a telecommunications tower there in
late March. The government is not allowing reporters into the
north.
</P>
<P>
   Relief agency officials said the plight of the 350,000 people
living in the largely Tamil-controlled Wanni area just south of the
Jaffna peninsula has been deteriorating. There is no electricity to
run the hospitals and generators are running low on fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Since April, the government has blocked the International
Committee of the Red Cross and Doctors without Borders from
transporting many medicines and supplies to hospitals and clinics
in the area, saying it feared the rebels would use the supplies,
officials of those agencies said.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Trujillo, the head of mission for Doctors without
Borders' French chapter, said the government has not allowed the
relief agency to deliver antibiotics, syringes, IV fluids, gastric
tubes and many other items.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're turning people away from the hospitals because we have
nothing to treat them with,'' he said. ``And the situation doesn't
look like it's going to improve. On the contrary, the procedures
are getting more complex. Several authorizations, stamps and
signatures are required before we can send in one antibiotic.''
</P>
<P>
   The 150-bed hospital in the village of Mallavi, operated by
Doctors without Borders, Holland, had no medicines to treat more
than 2,000 patients in the last two weeks of April. Among those
turned away were 223 who had malaria, 62 asthmatics, 32 psychiatric
patients and 37 with heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the Geneva convention, we treat those who arrive in
civilian clothes and without arms,'' said Isabel Simpson, head of
mission for Doctors without Borders, Holland. ``We do not have
Tiger cadres in uniform coming to the hospital.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
