<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4632 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-AFRICA-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      05-03 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I DREAMED OF AFRICA' IS A SNOOZER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You may fall asleep at ``I Dreamed of Africa.'' Episodic in the
extreme and indifferently acted, this truth- based account of the
life of Italian environmentalist Kuki Gallmann is astonishingly
bereft of dramatic momentum. Interesting characters might have made
an excusable substitute, or something more than superficial
insights into man's relationship to nature, but it was not to be.
</P>
<P>
   Director Hugh Hudson fails to muster even the false sense of
passion that tricked so many people into believing that his
Oscar-winning ``Chariots of Fire'' had something to say.
Unfortunately, ``I Dreamed of Africa'' does _ Gallmann's source
autobiography tells of a connection to the harsh, beautiful land
that even profound tragedy cannot sever _ but you'd never know it
from this film, even though Basinger's droning voiceover narration
keeps trying to tell you so.
</P>
<P>
   Set vaguely in the 1970s, film opens with well-off, if husband-
abandoned, young mom Kuki surviving a terrible auto accident on the
road home to Venice. The car's driver, Paolo Gallmann (Swiss actor
Vincent Perez), lost his girlfriend in the tragedy, but soon he and
Kuki are bonding, then married, then off to follow his dream life
in Kenya with her young son Emanuele (Liam Aiken as a child,
Garrett Strommen as a teen-ager) in tow.
</P>
<P>
   The Gallmanns set up a cattle ranch near the Great Rift Valley,
and Kuki spends the rest of the movie adjusting. And adjusting. The
trials she faces over the years, though undoubtedly true, seem pat:
devastating storms, elephants in the vegetable patch, the
occasional lion attack, ivory poachers, loving-but-adventurous
hubby always away on safari, kid develops unhealthy interest in
snakes ...
</P>
<P>
   All the while, we're treated to magnificent photography of
unspoiled land and freeborn animals _ just like you can see every
night on Animal Planet, and probably do right before nodding off.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, the film stirs up continuous negative
comparisons to ``Out of Africa,'' which was something of a
tranquilizer itself. But at least that overpraised Oscar-winner had
the words of a real writer, Isak Dinesen, spoken with a perfect
Danish accent by Meryl Streep. Gallmann's alternately obvious and
overpoeticized prose mark her as a diarist by comparison _ and we
can only be thankful that Basinger's flat readings from it weren't
burdened with an accent attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Although another thing you constantly wonder about as
``Dreamed'' loops along is what this American-sounding woman is
doing amidst this community of otherwise thoroughly European
expatriates. As to other ethnic matters, the usual contingent of
helpful African servants uniformly share the usual Hollywood lack
of discernible personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, it's never asked why Paolo gets so upset at the
occasional, subsistence elephant poacher while he spends half the
movie presumably shooting up all the game he can find. For that
matter, isn't it just the weeist bit ironic, if not downright
hypocritical, for cattle ranchers to fancy themselves champions of
wildlife preservation?
</P>
<P>
   At its most successful, ``I Dreamed of Africa'' does depict a
beautiful, senses-filling place that anyone would seriously
consider pulling up stakes and moving to given the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But then, who doesn't love Venice? &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The film: ``I Dreamed of Africa'' PG-13 (Sex, nudity, violence,
language). &QL; 
The stars: Kim Basinger, Vincent Perez, Liam Aiken, Garrett
Strommen, Eva Marie Saint. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Hugh Hudson. Written by Paula Milne
and Susan Shilliday, based on Kuki Gallmann's book. Produced by
Stanley R. Jaffe and Allyn Stewart. Released by Columbia Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 52 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
