<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4638 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOREA-DMZ-ART-975(2TA     05-03 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-DMZ-ART-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND KOREAN SUMMIT MEETING: MILLION TROOPS IN A STANDOFF
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANMUNJOM, Korea _ For U.S. and South Korean soldiers stationed
in the demilitarized zone that divides the two Koreas, days begin
with a blast of martial music and Communist propaganda blaring from
gigantic loudspeakers that North Korea has erected just across the
heavily fortified border.
</P>
<P>
   The monotonous diatribe, which urges ``one and all to join the
workers' paradise,'' is often broken by jarring explosions that
send the soldiers scrambling to determine whether North Korean
troops or wild animals are invading nearby minefields. More often
than not, the intruders are mule deer. But sometimes they are North
Korean infiltrators who incite deadly gun battles.
</P>
<P>
   This is the front line of the tense demilitarized zone, a
fiercely armed no man's land of barbed wire and big guns, where
well over a million opposing troops are locked in a highly
combustible standoff in a place that President Clinton once called
the ``scariest'' on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   As the leaders of the two Koreas prepare for their first summit
meeting since their countries went to war 50 years ago, the
soldiers whose sole mission is to defend against a North Korean
attack say the danger of another all-out conflict remains high.
</P>
<P>
   ``With such a heavy concentration of manpower and weapons
located in this relatively small area, there is great potential for
fighting to break out at any time,'' said Lt. Kwon Byung Su of an
elite South Korean front-line unit on border patrol.
</P>
<P>
   A half-million South Korean soldiers guard the border, backed up
by 36,000 U.S. service members and some of the most advanced
military hardware available. Their assignment is widely considered
one of the most difficult military postings, because the hard-line
North Korean government, which has amassed a million troops along
the border, seems determined to reunify the peninsula by force.
</P>
<P>
   The demilitarized zone, a 150-mile-long three-mile-wide stretch
of rolling hills, craggy mountains and farmland, was formed by the
1953 armistice. The village of Panmunjom, which straddles the
demarcation line that runs down the middle of the zone, was
destroyed by tank fire in the war. But it now serves as the site of
truce talks. The northern and southern borders of the zone are
lined with high fences crowned with barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   Although most clashes in the zone resemble a game of a cat and
mouse and are nothing more than saber rattling, they sometimes turn
deadly. More than 1,000 South Koreans, 50 Americans and numerous
North Koreans have died in skirmishes along the border since the
armistice officially ended the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most notorious incident involved the ax killings of
two U. S. soldiers by a gang of North Koreans in 1976 in a dispute
over tree pruning. In a gun battle in 1992, three North Korean
soldiers were killed and two South Korean soldiers were wounded
after the North Koreans had crossed into the southern part of the
demilitarized zone. Last year, a naval skirmish resulted in the
sinking of a North Korean boat and the deaths of at least 20 North
Korean sailors.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the threat posed by North Korea, the United States
recently distributed 14,000 gas masks to dependents of U.S.
soldiers and embassy workers in South Korea. That is because
military intelligence officers have determined that North Korea has
thousands of tons of chemical and biological weapons that the
officers predict could be used in storming the border and taking
Seoul, the South Korean capital, 30 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Some soldiers said they hoped that the anniversary of the start
of the Korean War, which began on June 25, 1950, would remind the
world that the conflict had not been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people don't know very much about the Korean War,
and they take freedom for granted, or they just don't realize the
costs,'' said Phillip McNeal, 21, an Army specialist from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In his two years on the line, Chung Eup, 24, a South Korean
lieutenant, has never encountered a North Korean soldier. But he
said that possibility was always in the back of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's stressful, but we think it's every Korean man's duty
to serve his country here,'' Chung said as he inspected fences for
signs of infiltration.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials said one of every 100 South Korean soldiers
have had at least one encounter with a North Korean counterpart in
his mandatory service of two years and two months. Many encounters
occur on special patrols beyond the southern boundary. Soldiers
told of tense, almost surreal, encounters with North Korean troops
in grassy fields of the demilitarized zone late at night.
</P>
<P>
   In those situations, the soldiers said the opposing troops often
confronted each other face to face, arms drawn, in a stare down.
Usually the soldiers back away from one another and continue on
their ways. In one case fraught with symbolism, the soldiers
exchanged cigarettes before moving on. Not all such encounters end
so amicably, and there have been numerous casualties in late-night
gunfights that were not made public.
</P>
<P>
   Although North Korea has publicly sought to improve its
diplomatic relations in recent months, senior U.S. and South Korean
military officials said Pyongyang had also been busy beefing up its
military, acquiring advanced weaponry and conducting rigorous
exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``North Korea remains the major threat to stability and security
in northeast Asia and is the country most likely to involve the
United States in a large-scale war,'' Gen. Thomas A. Schwartz,
commander of the U.S. forces in South Korea, testified to the
Senate in March.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing that, a spokesman for the South Korean Defense Ministry
said that although his agency supported the summit meeting,
scheduled for June 12 to June 14 in Pyongyang, it still considered
North Korea ``a very dangerous and aggressive enemy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, as North Korea suffered a devastating
recession and severe shortages of food and fuel, its ability to
attack the South with conventional armed forces was widely thought
to have declined. But South Korean and U.S. military officials now
say that despite economic woes and widespread famine, North Korea
has replaced much of its obsolete weaponry, and its troops are well
prepared to go to battle.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Schwartz said that over the last year, North
Korea had done more to arrest a decline in readiness among its
troops and to improve its military capability than in the last five
years combined. The general said North Korea had greatly improved
its ground forces, including the deployment of large numbers of
long-range multiple-rocket launchers and self-propelled guns near
the demilitarized zone.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz said North Korea had installed anti-tank barriers;
taken new combat positions along major routes between Pyongyang,
its capital, and the border; strengthened its coastal defenses;
procured fighter aircraft; and taken steps to increase its missile
range.
</P>
<P>
   There is some growing concern in the South Korean military that
new draftees have a weakened sense of North Korea as an enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have noticed that some younger troops don't have the same
contempt for North Korean troops as past generations,'' said Kwon,
a public affairs officer. ``They know that we are enemies. But they
also realize that we are same people. It's not like we are Iran and
Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Myong Won, 22, a recruit who had just finished basic
training and was about to begin his first tour on the front line,
said: ``We will fight to defend ourselves. But we really don't
consider them enemies. Especially with the summit talks, there is
the possibility of reunification.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwon said that with a little ideological training and field
experience, he expected Kim would eventually see things
differently. ``Nothing has changed,'' Kwon said. ``We teach our
soldiers to shoot to kill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
