<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-KHANNOUCHI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KHANNOUCHI SAYS INJURY WILL BAR HIM FROM TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fighting back tears, new citizen Khalid Khannouchi announced at
an emotional news conference Wednesday that injuries have crushed
his plans to compete in the US Olympic Marathon Trials on Sunday,
meaning he will not be able to run the marathon for the United
States at the Olympics in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad,'' said a heartbroken Khannouchi, 28, in a
teleconference call. ``I feel ashamed of myself, but this is
reality. It doesn't look right. People worked very hard to make my
dream come true and my body doesn't want to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that I'm a citizen I'm so happy with it, but I know it is
going to be tremendous pressure on me,'' he said. ``It's my turn to
keep my promises.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Moroccan-born Khannouchi, who has lived in the
United States since 1993, achieved his longtime dream of becoming
an American citizen in time for the trials. But Wednesday morning,
after a final consultation with his physiotherapist, Khannouchi
finally acknowledged that the rest of his dream, to win a gold
medal for the United States, would have to be deferred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better not to risk anything and think about the future,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi said he will turn his focus to trying for a berth on
the US Olympic 10,000-meter team at the US track trials in July,
despite not having run a track race since 1995, and believes he can
run under 27 minutes. The American record, set by Mark Nenow in
1986, is 27:20:56.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say if he's healthy, he's on the 10K team,'' said Mark
Coogan, the 1996 Olympic marathoner who will be seeking to repeat
on Sunday. His closest competition would likely be Bob Kennedy, who
is expected to move up from the 5000 and last year ran 27:38.37 for
the fifth-best US time ever.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Khannouchi would be only an outside medal threat in
Sydney, with Haile Gebrselassie (26:22.75) a heavy favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad for Khalid, because I know how much he wanted to run
in the marathon trials,'' said Coogan. ``It's too bad all the
citizen stuff took so long to come through.''
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi acknowledged that, had he known he would become a
citizen in time for the trials, he would not have run London, where
he earned $22,500 for his third-place finish on top of an
undisclosed appearance fee likely in the neighborhood of $250,000.
``I feel sorry,'' he said. ``I didn't want to take a chance'' on
saying no to London and then not becoming a citizen by the May 4
deadline, either.
</P>
<P>
   On March 1, Khannouchi stumbled on a training run and severely
sprained his left ankle. After 10 days of rest it healed well
enough for the world-record holder (2 hours, 5 minutes and 42
seconds) to finish a respectable third in the London Marathon on
April 18 in 2:08:38, but by then he had also developed what
physiotherapist Gerard Hartmann termed ``a slight niggle'' in his
right hamstring from compensating for the bad ankle. The
combination put more than his Olympic bid in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was adamant'' about running, said Hartmann from Limerick,
Ireland, where he lives. ``I advised Khalid not to. We're
protecting Khalid from doing more damage so he can continue his
career.'' Recovery, he said, should take four-to-six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Although Khannouchi held out some hope for what he called a
miracle (``Maybe something can happen, I don't know''), there seems
little. Under USA Track &AMP; Field rules for the marathon, an athlete
must complete the trials to be eligible for the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not envision any scenario'' under which an exception
would be made, said Danny Grimes, chairman of USA Track &AMP; Field's
long-distance running committee.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the top three finishers in the trials make the
team, but that assumes each has run the Olympic ``A'' standard ,
which last year was tightened to 2:14, since Jan. 1, 1999. Without
Khannouchi in the race, only two Americans _ David Morris of
Missoula, Mont. (2:09:32) and Joe LeMay of Danbury, Conn. (2:13:55)
_ have met the standard coming into the race.
</P>
<P>
   With temperatures in the 80s expected, the winner of Sunday's
race in Pittsburgh could well finish in over 2:14. Unless that
winner is either Morris or LeMay, the United States would then be
able to send only one marathoner to Sydney, as happened to the
women when Christine Clark won the Trials in Columbia, S.C., on an
unseasonably warm day in February in 2:33:31, short of the 2:34
``A'' standard. Each country is allowed to send one athlete under
the more-lenient ``B'' standard, but if a ``B'' goes the country
cannot send any ``A'' athletes.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, Morris or LeMay won but the third-place finisher
failed to break 2:14, they would both go and one spot would
theoretically be left open. But because the US rules specify that
athletes can be chosen for the team only in order of finish at the
trials, Khannouchi would be shut out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chance is one in a million, maybe less,'' said Grimes, of
changing the rule. ``It would be completely unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it appears Khannouchi's first chance to compete in a
marathon for the United States will be the 2001 World Championships
in Edmonton. ``That's going to be the goal,'' he said. ``This time
I hope my body won't betray me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
