<HEADLINE>
BAIN CAPITAL INVESTING $50M IN CAROLINA INTERNET UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bain Capital Inc. is investing $50 million in the
Internet unit of Carolina Power &AMP; Light Co. and gaining a
controlling position in the utility's two-year-old subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Bain Capital will take a 65 percent stake in Interpath
Communications Inc. and will control the company's board. Raleigh,
N.C.-based Carolina Power will invest $50 million and keep a 35
percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Interpath is an ``application service provider,'' or ASP, which
essentially rents software and data services to big companies via
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Power said the deal was ``designed to unlock the value
of Interpath,'' which has not been reflected in its stock price.
The utility's shares fell $2.0625 to $33.8125 Wednesday. Investors
had been expecting Interpath to go public or to be sold outright.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Carolina Power separated Interpath's Web
services and its fiber-optic network. The utility keeps the
fiberoptics and plans to merge them with a 3,000-mile
telecommunications network of a company it is acquiring, Florida
Progress Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Carolina Power will retain 50 employees of Interpath and a
10 percent interest in BellSouth's cell phone business.
</P>
<P>
   William Cavanaugh, the utility's chief executive, said in a
prepared statement that ``Both of the agreements announced today
are important steps towards unlocking, maximizing and returning to
shareholders the value of our Interpath subsidiary.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bain Capital, which manages $7 billion and invests mainly in
private companies for its clients, the goal is to increase
Interpath's sales outside its core Southeastern market and to
become a top ASP player.
</P>
<P>
   The field is wide open, said Bill Martorelli, an analyst with
Hurwitz Group in Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an evolving thing,'' Martorelli said. ``They've had some
turmoil. Now they've got a huge cash infusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil included the departure of Interpath's CEO, Chris
Darby, in February. Now chief executive of (at)Stake Inc., an
Internet security company, he declined to be interviewed about
Interpath.
</P>
<P>
   Darby is said to have overseen revenue growth at Interpath to
$78 million, from $3 million, in two years and an increase in
employment to 650. There are now 450 workers, the company said
Wednesday, plus the 50 staying with Carolina Power.
</P>
<P>
   Interpath's interim CEO, Michael Fox, said the company's clients
include Ericsson Telephone and First Union Mortgage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
