<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AIRLINES-LIVETV0504-C     05-03 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-LIVETV0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surfing the skies Live TV, Internet access on the horizon for
fliers
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Air travelers of the not-too-distant future could
spend their idle time aloft the same way many spend it at home:
surfing TV channels or Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   Two small carriers that began flying this winter, JetBlue and
Legend Airlines, are pioneering real-time broadcast television on
small video screens at every seat.
</P>
<P>
   JetBlue and Legend passengers can use armrest controls to peruse
two dozen cable channels, ranging from CNNfn and ESPN to the
Discovery Channel and A&AMP;E. The system is made by Live TV, a
2-year-old venture of Harris Corp., and Sextant In-flight Systems.
It uses DirecTV programming beamed to a special antenna on the
plane.
</P>
<P>
   Legend, an all-first-class carrier based in Dallas, provides the
TV for free. JetBlue, a discounter flying out of New York's Kennedy
Airport, will charge $5 following an introductory free period for
the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   How soon the concept might spread to the mass market is unclear,
although industry consultant Rich Salter, of Irvine, Calif.,
believes it's a matter of when rather than if.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has reached the point of breaking through, and it will
proliferate over the next several years,'' Salter said.
</P>
<P>
   Major airlines offer taped programs and movies but have been
leery of the cost and maintenance issues of adding broadcast TV,
especially at every seat. Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines had a pilot
project in 1996 involving DirecTV broadcasts of sports events that
were shown on overhead consoles in one plane. Delta then dropped
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines, one of the 10 major U.S. carriers, plans to
field test a more advanced system like JetBlue's later this year.
And carriers are gradually having seatback video screens installed
in larger planes for movies and taped shows anyway, making the
addition of live TV a simpler and cheaper proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If live TV ever takes hold at a major carrier, the others are
going to have to take a very hard look at it,'' predicted Rob
Brookler of the World Airline Entertainment Association, a trade
group for carriers and manufacturers of in-flight entertainment
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, systems for in-flight Internet access may appear on a
mass scale sooner than broadcast TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at satellite TV, but right now we're more
interested in bringing the Internet into the cabin because it's
what our business customers tell us they want,'' said United
Airlines spokesman Matt Triaca.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, a traveler with a laptop and an urgent need to log on
can do so via an airphone jack, but the connection can be poor and
a 5-minute session costs close to $20.
</P>
<P>
   Several manufacturers are working on systems to provide cheaper,
better-quality access.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Wireless Services, for instance, will launch a system
dubbed ``ePlane'' later this year. Using ground-to-air or satellite
transmissions to a receiving device on the plane, it would upload
Internet content to an on-board server capable of storing more than
1 million web pages. Passengers with laptops could access the
content, which would be periodically refreshed during flight, and
send or retrieve web-based e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Giant jet-maker Boeing Co. last month announced Connexion, a
joint venture with several partners to develop a new Internet
access system for airliners. The company believes Connexion could
be installed on one-third of the world's jetliners over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually it's expected that passengers will have live,
real-time Internet access while in the air, and that video,
satellite TV and Internet systems will all be integrated.
</P>
<P>
   Delta recently announced plans for wireless Internet connections
in its airport gate areas and Crown Room lounges. A spokesman said
the airline also is exploring in-flight Internet access but added
it's too early to predict how soon it will be able to offer the
service.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said Delta also is staying abreast of further
developments in in-flight broadcast TV, but that Internet access is
a higher priority at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some airlines are eager about live TV and others are on the
fence or unconvinced that the benefit of another perk outweighs the
cost,'' said Brookler. That cost stems from installation expenses _
estimated at $1 million or more per plane _ as well as from
maintenance requirements and even added weight, which cuts fuel
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   But those obstacles have been eroded in recent years with the
development of smaller, lighter and more reliable electronics. And
as more manufacturers enter the field big airlines will be able to
cut volume discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Brookler said live TV is easier to operate for airlines than
taped content and gives passengers more control over their
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to store, change and maintain a library of
content,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean the days of reading a pulp novel, chatting with a
seatmate or staring out the window to contemplate the cosmos will
be gone forever as passengers zone out on TV and the Web?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a segment of the public that wants to get
away from all these things, especially when they are traveling,''
said Brookler. ``The option of reading a book or looking out the
window will always be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
