u i BC-LOCKERBIE-FAMILIES-BO     05-03 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKERBIE-FAMILIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES FACE ACCUSED PAN AM BOMBERS FOR FIRST TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Arabic spellings for defendants are from the indictments.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZEIST, Netherlands _ Exactly 4,211 days after her daughter,
Sarah, was blown out of the sky along with 258 other people flying
on Pan Am Flight 103, Elizabeth Philipps finally came face to face
with the two men who allegedly planted the bomb that did it.
</P>
<P>
   From her seat in the spectators gallery Wednesday, Philipps, a
former publishing executive who used to live in Massachusetts,
stared through the bulletproof glass that separated her from the
alleged terrorists on the opening day of their trial here.
</P>
<P>
   Just 25 feet away, Abdelbaset Ali Mohmed Al Megrahi and Al Amin
Khalifa Fhimah waved to their families, who sat across the aisle
from Philipps. The two men took no notice of her.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Susannah Buchanan Philipps was a 20-year-old student at
Syracuse University and one of 23 New Englanders on board Pan Am
Flight 103 when it exploded 31,000 feet above Lockerbie, Scotland,
on Dec. 21, 1988. In addition to the 259 passengers and crew who
perished, 11 Lockerbie residents were killed when debris from the
airliner crashed to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Philipps intends to make eye contact with the
suspects, and says she won't give up until she does. They took her
middle child, she said, her sweet, smart, beautiful Sarah, and in
doing so they took a piece of her she can never replace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a certain voodoo thing working, so I'm going to keep
staring at them,'' Philipps said, smiling sadly on a day when
prosecutors called the first of more than 1,000 expected witnesses
in a trial that will last at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other few dozen relatives of victims who attended
Wednesday, Elizabeth Philipps said it is imperative that she bears
witness. She plans to spend the next three weeks here. She is
telephoning back reports to her husband Ervin and elder son Andrew
in Chapel Hill, N.C., where the family moved in 1992, and to her
younger son, Fritz, a doctor at Boston University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your child is murdered, you go to the murder trial,'' she
said. ``There aren't any graduations, no birthdays, no weddings, no
grandchildren. All I have is this trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Philipps got choked up but quickly regained her
composure.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, lawyers for the two suspects entered not guilty
pleas on their behalf and formally notified the three Scottish
judges hearing the case that the defense will blame the bombing on
Palestinian terrorists. The defense also formally indicated it
would implicate at least two men who are scheduled to testify for
the prosecution, Mohamed Abo Talb, a convicted terrorist who bombed
a synagogue in Copenhagen, and Parviz Taheri, who appears to be an
Iranian national but about whom no other information was available.
</P>
<P>
   The first witnesses to take the stand were British air-traffic
controllers who charted the path of Pan Am Flight 103 after it
departed London's Heathrow airport on its way to John F. Kennedy
Airport in New York. In a poignant moment, one of them recalled how
he and the pilot of the doomed aircraft wished each other a good
night, the last contact with the airliner before it disappeared
from the radar screens.
</P>
<P>
   More chilling was a video recording of a radar screen, showing
the jet's green image break up into three pieces, and the testimony
of a British Airways pilot who from his jet miles away saw the
fiery fuselage of Pan Am Flight 103 plummet to earth like ``a gas
flare burning off.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most dramatic moment was when the suspects, who
prosecutors allege were Libyan intelligence agents bent on
vengeance against the United States, walked into the courtroom. It
was the first time that any relatives of the victims had seen them
in person.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing shasiyas, traditional Libyan hats that look like pillbox
berets, and shiny abayas, traditional Libyan robes, the two
suspects smiled broadly at their families but betrayed no emotion
when a clerk read the indictment against them.
</P>
<P>
   The reading, which took almost 20 minutes, was a chronology of
the alleged movements of the two suspects as they planted the bomb
in Malta, where they worked for Libyan Arab Airlines. The dry
recitation failed to capture the visceral pain felt by the
relatives of some of the 189 Americans, 44 Britons, and people from
20 other countries who were on board Pan Am Flight 103.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the clerk paused briefly and added, ``and did murder
them,'' was there a hint of the human carnage that is at the heart
of the case. Elizabeth Philipps nodded almost imperceptibly.
Sitting next to her, Ann McLaughlin of Jamestown, R.I., whose son
Bernard Joseph was killed, glanced briefly at the suspects. The two
men, who were listening to an Arabic translation of the charges,
were impassive.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the relatives complained that the suspects had been
dressed up to appear meek, almost like Muslim clerics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was well staged, them in their religious garb,'' said Maddy
Shapiro of Stamford, Conn., whose 21-year-old daughter Amy was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been dressed up to look like priests,'' said Philipps,
adding in a sarcastic voice, ``They look so pious in their
beautiful robes. How could people who look like that buy the
electronic timers needed to blow up an airplane?''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Philipps said, the sometimes tedious testimony
will be a welcome diversion from the emotions flooding her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect this trial to be drenched in procedure, and that can
be a good break at times,'' she said during a recess called when
the system broadcasting translations of the proceedings broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Philipps said she felt no strong emotion, certainly not the rage
she feared, as she stared at the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emotion comes in waves,'' she said. ``I'm almost as angry
at the airline employees who put the unaccompanied luggage carrying
the bomb on the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the suspects, she said, ``It's their job to put
bombs on planes. But it's the job of people who work for the
airlines and airport security to make sure that doesn't happen. I
worry about whether we'll ever get the truth about why those people
didn't do their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The relatives complained about the choice of United Nations
observers attending the trial. Philipps and other relatives,
including Kathleen and Jack Flynn of Montville, N.J., whose
20-year-old son John Patrick was killed, said too many of the
observers are Arab and African.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way those people are impartial,'' said Jack Flynn,
shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   Across the aisle, Megrahi's 16-year-old daughter Ghada stood
with her 15-year-old brother, Khalid, and said the two Libyan
families are as anxious as the victims' relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a kerchief on her head in keeping with Muslim tradition,
she said, ``It hurts, but I know my father is innocent,'' before a
burly Libyan man, who would not identify himself, shepherded them
away.
</P>
<P>
   Philipps said she bore no ill will toward the suspects'
families. ``I'm very sympathetic to the relatives,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers will argue that the airliner was downed by
members of the Palestinian Popular Struggle Front, which was led by
Talb, or the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine. Talb's
group was suspected at first, before American and British
prosecutors zeroed in on the Libyans.
</P>
<P>
   But Philipps, as she glared at the men who would not return her
stare, was convinced she was looking at the terrorists who killed
her daughter and 269 other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I know it's a cornerstone of democracy and the
civilized world, I'm having trouble with the doctrine of the
presumption of innocence,'' she said. ``I have no doubt they did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   She does have doubts in the convoluted legal process in a
society that affords far more rights and protections to the accused
than the suspects' own country affords its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   When the testimony got tedious, or when defense lawyers started
talking about the rights of their clients, Elizabeth Philipps took
out a small, framed photograph of her daughter which she keeps in
her pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about you, Sarah,'' she said, almost in a whisper.
``This is all about you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
