<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINT-JULEPS-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLASSIC COCKTAIL: DERBY DAY CALLS FOR A MINT JULEP
</HEADLINE>
  By ALLISON BALLARD    
Morning Star, Wilmington, N.C. 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To muddle, or not to muddle? A dash of mint syrup or just
straight bourbon with a sprinkle of powdered sugar?
</P>
<P>
   These are the questions facing those getting ready to celebrate
the 126th Kentucky Derby on Saturday in the most traditional way _
while drinking a mint julep. The problem is that there are almost
as many recipes for the cocktail as there are horses in the race.
That is quite a feat for a drink with only a few ingredients _
bourbon, sugar and mint. There are strong versions not for the
faint of heart, and there are fruity versions to please the
pickiest palates.
</P>
<P>
   The julep is believed to be derived from an Arabic drink called
a julab, made of water and rose petals. When the beverage came to
the Mediterranean, mint became the herb of choice.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the beverage was first imbibed in
Virginia, according to the Encyclopedia of Southern Culture. But
different regions had different versions. In New England, it was
made with rum. In Louisiana, the choice was brandy. Eventually, the
julep came to be associated only with bourbon. The frosty drink was
served on hot, humid mornings in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Mint juleps were served at Churchill Downs not long after the
first derby in 1875. But it did not become the official drink until
1939. Now, more than 80,000 are served each Derby Day.
</P>
<P>
   There are just a few basic ways to prepare the cocktail. All of
the recipes, though, recommend serving the beverage in the classic
mint julep cup. It is a small, straight-sided vessel of pewter or
silver that turns frosty. Make sure the cups are approved for food,
and not decorative, use. And in a pinch, just use a glass.
</P>
<P>
   All of the recipes suggest packing finely crushed ice into the
cup and pouring Kentucky bourbon on top. The difference comes with
the cocktail's other two ingredients _ the mint and the sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Spirited debates have ensued over the use of the muddle, a
small, rounded stick that crushes the herbs, fruits and peels. Some
prefer to muddle because it releases aromatic essences. Others
maintain that muddling makes a julep too bitter, and they object
strenuously to the sight of crushed leaves and stems in the bottom
of the cup.
</P>
<P>
   For a strong mint julep, simply make a drink with straight
bourbon. Sprinkle a little powdered sugar over the top and garnish
with a sprig of mint. Other mint juleps are basically either
muddled or made with a mint syrup. Epicurious.com lists several
recipes. Here is the basic version:
</P>
<P>
   THE MUDDLED MINT JULEP
</P>
<P>
   Crushed ice
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon superfine sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces bourbon
</P>
<P>
   Fill glass with crushed ice. In a small glass, muddle the leaves
from two mint sprigs with sugar and a dash of club soda or water.
Add bourbon, stir and strain into glass. Stir again with a
long-handled spoon until the glass frosts. Serves 1.
</P>
<P>
   From House &AMP; Garden's Drink Guide
</P>
<P>
   (The Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4659 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IPI-JOURNALISTS-BOS &LR;      05-03 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPI-JOURNALISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNALISTS HONORED FOR SACRIFICES WORLDWIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Reporters and publishers of all colors and continents,
survivors of torture, imprisonment, and assassination attempts by
authoritarian regimes around the world, were honored Wednesday at
Faneuil Hall as heroes of the international struggle for free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   The awards by the Vienna-based International Press Institute
were timed to coincide with World Press Freedom Day, and with the
conclusion of a four-day conference in Boston marking the
institute's 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Some honorees came in Savile Row suits, some in traditional
African dress. Some could not attend because they were not allowed
to travel, others because attempts on their lives had succeeded.
But certain common traits _ especially uncommon courage _ ran
through all their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bravery in a democracy is very different from bravery in other
countries,'' said retired Washington Post publisher Katharine
Graham, the only honoree from the United States. ``I am in awe of
journalists from around the world who have suffered'' severe
political repression and physical abuse. ``I do not belong in that
pantheon.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Graham is one of the few US newspeople ever threatened
from the highest levels of government, a distinction she won for
publishing documents that showed the government was lying to the
public about the origins and progress of the Vietnam War, then
giving her editors and reporters strong backing for the Watergate
investigation, which toppled President Richard M. Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most famous threats of that contentious period, US
Attorney General John Mitchell told a Post reporter that ``Katie
Graham is going to get her tit caught in a big fat wringer'' for
pursuing the Watergate case.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Graham said, many of the other journalists honored
Wednesday distinguished themselves in lands where ``horrific
dangers are, alas, almost routine.''
</P>
<P>
   Faraj Sarkuhi, a critic first of the Shah of Iran and later of
the Islamic fundamentalists who succeeded him, was persecuted on
and off for 30 years, culminating in his being kidnapped in the
Tehran airport and tortured for 48 days _ after which he was
charged with spying for a foreign power. His case illustrated the
relationship, cited by many speakers, between press freedom and
freedom generally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just like this Jewish thing,'' Sarkuhi said after the
ceremony, referring to the apparent show trials of 13 Iranian Jews,
some of whom are confessing to charges of spying for Israel.
``First they torture you, then they threaten to torture your son,''
he said. ``I confessed also.''
</P>
<P>
   Some cases, like Sarkuhi's, attracted international attention.
Others, like that of Indo-Canadian Times founder Tara Singh Hayer,
who was shot to death in his home in British Columbia in November
1998, received little previous attention.
</P>
<P>
   Some are still in progress: Gao Yu could not accept her award
because she is under house arrest in China; Raul Rivero was denied
an exit visa from Cuba; Nizar Nayyouf is believed near death in a
Syrian prison.
</P>
<P>
   Others have happy outcomes, such as the case of Kemal Kurspahic,
who was editor of the leading newspaper in Bosnia during the
horrific siege of Sarajevo. Operating from a bomb shelter, under
frequent shelling, Kurspahic and his multi-ethnic staff never
missed an edition, despite shortages of electricity, ink, and
newsprint. He now is writing a book on journalism in the Balkan
wars.
</P>
<P>
   Also in observance of World Press Freedom Day, the New
York-based Committee for the Protection of Journalists Wednesday
published its annual listing of the 10 worst offenders among
officials and governments that abuse the media.
</P>
<P>
   Foday Sankoh, whose Revolutionary United Front targeted
journalists during the civil war in Sierra Leone, topped the list,
followed by Iran's Ayatollah Ali Khamenei and Yugoslavia's Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Khamenei, the supreme leader of Iran, has fostered a reaction
against reformists in which 16 publications were closed in the past
week.
</P>
<P>
   Others on the list were: President Nursultan Nazarbayev of
Kazakhstan; President Jose Eduardo dos Santos of Angola; President
Alberto Fujimori of Peru; Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad of
Malaysia; President Zine el Abdine Ben Ali of Tunisia; President
Jiang Zemin of China; and President Fidel Castro of Cuba.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4661 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0504-COX     05-03 2227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Politics . . . racketeering: how big a
stretch?
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   House Democrats filed suit under civil anti-racketeering laws
today against House Majority Whip Tom DeLay (R-Texas), alleging he
oversees an organization that extorts campaign contributions and
evades federal disclosure requirements. Rep. Patrick Kennedy of
Rhode Island, who chairs the Democratic campaign committee, said
DeLay stands atop an unprecedented operation, ``hammering
contributors for money, threatening to punish those who decline and
setting up a shadow party structure outside public view and our
laws.'' Several of DeLay's aides greeted reporters arriving for the
press conference where the suit was announced and handed them
written statements accusing Democrats of ``resorting to ugly,
unfounded, politically motivated charges.''
</P>
<P>
   LIKE THAT SECRET PLAN TO END THE VIETNAM WAR?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore accused George W. Bush today of making a ``smug
assumption'' that he can win the presidency without detailing his
plans for Social Security. ``It is responsible to make the strength
and solvency of Social Security a major national priority. And it
is responsible to tell the American people exactly how you propose
to do it,'' Gore told the New Jersey AFL-CIO. But Gore barely
mentioned the administration's push to open trade with China, an
effort opposed by labor groups. Bush plans to outline next week the
principles by which he would work to protect Social Security. Aides
say he'll not release a detailed plan, though Bush has said he
supports letting retirees invest a portion of their Social Security
benefits in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYING THE CARD CARD
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Card, transportation secretary under President Bush, has
been picked by George W. Bush to head his operations at this
summer's Republican National Convention in Philadelphia. Two weeks
ago, the candidate reached back into his father's Cabinet and
picked former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney to head his vice
presidential selection committee. Said Card, 52, today: ``Governor
Bush and I are the same age, and I am a passionate supporter of
Governor Bush's initiatives and his leadership, and that is
independent of the tremendous and absolute respect I have for his
dad.''
</P>
<P>
   INFLATION IN THE FUND-RAISING BIZ
</P>
<P>
   Raising the bar for political giving, the Democrats are asking
their biggest donors to come up with a half-million dollars each
for the party's barbecue-and-jeans gala set for May 24. Those who
deliver are being promised a sweet political reward: a private
dinner the night before with President Clinton. The Democrats' new
asking price doubles the $250,000 mark that was the standard for
both parties the past few years, including the recent Republican
fund-raising gala with George W. Bush that raised a record $21.3
million. ``They just keep trying to jack up the limits,'' said
Larry Makinson, head of the Center for Responsive Politics, a
private group that studies political money. ``How long until they
have the million-dollar club? This really shows you there is no end
to the appetite for money.''
</P>
<P>
   THAT WAS NO LADY, THAT WAS MY _
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan fired back at Hillary Clinton, accusing her of
acting less than first-ladylike after her scathing attack on his
candidacy. Clinton accused Buchanan last week of ``hateful
rhetoric'' and ruled out sharing an Independence Party ticket this
fall with him. Buchanan told the New York Daily News: ``I don't
think that kind of inflammatory language comports with being a
first lady. I think the first lady ought to always try to be a lady
even if she falls short. She certainly did in this case. It's a bit
arrogant, especially when you consider that Mrs. Clinton herself is
currently under criminal investigation for possible perjury and
obstruction of justice.'' Plus, she's too liberal, Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S ALWAYS GOOD TO HAVE A PLAN B
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton told Ladies' Home Journal in its June issue that
if she loses her Senate race, ``I'll probably be connected with a
foundation or academic institution in some way.'' She added that
she'd remain active on political issues that matter to her: ``I'll
support the same issues: raising the minimum wage, expanding the
earned income tax credit for poor working people, and putting more
teachers into the classroom to lower class size in our public
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   EX-RENO AIDE QUESTIONED GORE'S HONESTY
</P>
<P>
   The former head of the Justice Department's campaign finance
task force told a Senate panel that in a memo to Attorney General
Janet Reno, he had questioned Al Gore's truthfulness in answering
investigators' questions about fund-raising phone calls Gore made
in 1996. Charles LaBella said he had wanted a more aggressive,
independent probe of allegations ranging from technology transfers
to China to Gore's fund-raising calls _ a stance at odds with Reno,
his boss at the time. LaBella told the senators that he didn't
believe Reno was protecting anyone, but that he disagreed with her
refusal to appoint an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   NUMERICAL SPARRING IN FISCAL BATTLE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is fighting back against Al Gore's accusations
that his fiscal proposals are risky, saying that the growth in the
economy over the past six months means there will be enough money
to accommodate his spending and tax cut proposals comfortably.
Bush's advisers released a new analysis of his budget plans after
Gore asserted that Bush's large tax cut proposal and plan to push
for a portion of Social Security payroll taxes to be put into
private investment accounts would return the nation to the era of
deficits. Using new economic data, Bush's campaign now says that,
excluding Social Security, there will be a federal surplus of $647
billion from 2002 through 2006. That's $61 billion more than they
had previously projected.
</P>
<P>
   GORE TAPS WHITE HOUSE TALENT POOL
</P>
<P>
   Top White House talent employed by the taxpayers is helping Al
Gore write his campaign speeches, work up attacks against George W.
Bush's budget, and develop everything from crime-fighting proposals
to health and education reforms. Gene Sperling, head of President
Clinton's National Economic Council, and Bruce Reed, chief White
House domestic policy adviser, and scores of lower-level aides are
lending their expertise _ legally, the Gore campaign asserts _ on
their own free time.
</P>
<P>
   But good-government watchdogs wince at the overlap. ``These guys
are dropping any pretense of a separation between campaign and
government. The problem here is of perception, and the average
American does not expect his or her taxpayer money to go toward Al
Gore's campaign,'' said Charles Lewis, head of the Center for
Public Integrity.
</P>
<P>
   NRA KEEPING ITS TOP GUN
</P>
<P>
   Charlton Heston will be allowed to run for an unprecedented
third term as president of the National Rifle Association at the
group's annual convention later this month. NRA spokesman Bill
Powers said today that the gun lobby's bylaws are being amended.
Traditionally, NRA officers have been elected twice to one-year
terms. Heston and the NRA have had a high profile since Congress
began considering gun legislation after a rash of school shootings
across the nation. The NRA has vehemently lobbied against any new
restrictions on gun owners' rights. Heston also recently appeared
in a series of political ads that critics say portrayed President
Clinton as a liar during the recent fight over the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNOR BATTLE SET IN CAROLINA . . .
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of winning their parties' nominations in North
Carolina, Republican Richard Vinroot and Democrat Mike Easley
indicated that education will be a key issue as they battle to
succeed popular Gov. Jim Hunt. Both candidates won handily,
avoiding runoffs in crowded fields. Vinroot, an ex-Charlotte mayor,
beat state Rep. Leo Daughtry 45-37 percent. Easley, the state
attorney general, turned back Lt. Gov. Dennis Wicker 59-36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND IN INDIANA, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Indiana Rep. David McIntosh won the GOP nomination
to challenge first-term Democratic Gov. Frank O'Bannon. McIntosh
won 72 percent of the vote, beating John Price, a lawyer who toured
the state in a red school bus and drew 28 percent for his travels.
O'Bannon had no opposition. Ex-radio talker Mike Pence defeated a
crowded field to win the GOP nomination for McIntosh's House seat.
Lawyer Robert Rock won the Democratic nomination. Sen. Richard
Lugar (R-Ind.) faced no primary opposition. In the fall, he'll go
up against Democratic lawyer David Johnson, an adviser to O'Bannon.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT THE HECK, A FEW MORE DELEGATES CAN'T HURT
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and Al Gore already have won the necessary number
of delegates, and they've piled on even more. In North Carolina,
Bush drew 79 percent, John McCain 11 percent and Alan Keyes 8
percent. Gore had 70 percent and Bill Bradley 19 percent. In
Indiana, Gore drew 75 percent and Bradley 22 percent. Lyndon
LaRouche had 3 percent. Bush drew 81 percent to McCain's 19
percent. And in Washington, D.C., Gore drew 96 percent of the
Democrats, and Bush beat McCain 75-25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S THAT KNOCKING?
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giulilani can knock on the door of New York's Conservative
Party, as he announced he would do, but the party is not ready to
let him in. ``As I've said all along, he cannot be on the party's
ballot if he is also supported by the Liberal Party and if he
supports partial-birth abortion,'' Conservative Party chairman
Michael Long told the Washington Times. Giuliani has enjoyed the
Liberals' support and ballot position during his two terms as New
York City mayor.
</P>
<P>
   LONG ANGER ON LONG ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmingly Republican Nassau County, on Long Island, stunned
the New York political establishment last November, when an
electorate that was angry over the fiscal crisis, tax increases and
a series of government scandals ended decades of one-party rule in
the county and gave the Democrats a 10-to-9 majority in its
legislative branch for the first time in 80 years. Four months
later, the death of Barbara Johnson left chamber tied 9-to-9.
Tuesday, voters were still plenty angry, as Craig Johnson, 29, won
a special election to succeed his mother. Johnson defeated
Republican Linda Green and Benjamin Zwirn, an ex-Democrat who ran
on the Green Party line.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE ARE THOSE CHARRED BITS OF ZEPPELIN?
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, New York Governor George Pataki said, ``I
would think it's more likely that the Hindenburg would come back
together than I would step down as governor and become senator.''
But now, he is refusing to rule out entering the Senate race if
Rudy Guiliani is forced to drop out because of his prostate cancer.
Pataki stressed, though, that he expected the mayor to remain in
the race, and beyond that, he said, ``I'm not going to speculate.''
</P>
<P>
   WALKING THE STRAIGHT AND NARRAL?
</P>
<P>
   An abortion rights group is launching its campaign to elect Al
Gore with an ad focused on the president's power to influence the
issue through the Supreme Court. The ad by the National Abortion
Rights and Reproductive Action League begins today in the
Washington area. ``George W. Bush would nominate Supreme Court
justices who would overturn Roe v. Wade,'' the announcer says. ``He
even supports a constitutional amendment to outlaw abortion.'' Bush
spokesman Ari Fleischer would not comment on the ad's overall
message, saying only that Bush ``will appoint justices to the court
who will strictly interpret the Constitution, and he will seek to
bring people together on areas where there is agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   AND HE'LL HEAR THE ANGELS SINGING
</P>
<P>
   Trailing in the all-important money chase and statewide polls in
the California Senate race, Republican Rep. Tom Campbell still
believes he can beat two-term Democratic incumbent Dianne
Feinstein. His own polling shows a close race this fall, and ``it's
a good year for Republicans, I win,'' he told reporters in
Washington. He said his last poll prior to the primary put him at
42 percent against Feinstein's 48 percent. ``That's really good,''
he said. Campbell's dream scenario? Al Gore selects Feinstein to be
his running mate. ``That is a gift from heaven if it occurs,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   IN MONTANA, THE ISSUE: PRESCRIPTION DRUG COST
</P>
<P>
   Brian Schweitzer, a Democratic farmer trying to unseat
Republican Sen. Conrad Burns in Montana, has campaigned hard on the
high price of prescription drugs and the burden it puts on the
uninsured elderly. Schweitzer has taken retirees to Canada to
highlight the lower cost of drugs there, and battled with a drug
industry lobbying coalition called Citizens for Better Medicare.
The Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, now believing
Schweitzer has a chance to help retake the Senate, has produced a
television spot urging voters to ``call the big drug companies and
tell them to get out of the way of Brian Schweitzer's fair prices
drug plan.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
