<SLUG> BC-BOTTLE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPIN THE BOTTLE': CRUELTY OF CHILDHOOD RETURNS TO HAUNT ADULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Spin the Bottle'' takes place in and around a creaky, isolated
lakefront house somewhere in the wilds of Vermont. Four childhood
friends, now in their late 20s, have been summoned to this lonely
spot by another old acquaintance, a mysterious fellow named Jonah
(Holter Graham), whom none of them have seen in more than a decade
and who suffered hurt and humiliation at their thoughtless young
hands.
</P>
<P>
   You may think you know where this is going, and nothing would
make me happier than to report that Jonah responds to this ``Friday
the 13th''-style setup by dispatching his erstwhile tormenters, one
by one, using the most gruesome cinematic means at his disposal.
But instead Jonah takes his revenge by setting in motion a series
of cat-and-mouse sexual mind games designed to humiliate his
guests, who are in the neighborhood for a wedding, and to expose
their hang-ups and hypocrisies. The movie would have been shorter,
more entertaining and a richer source of insight into human
psychology if he had simply cut them into pieces with a chain saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spin the Bottle,'' which was completed in 1997 and is now, for
some reason, playing at the Two Boots Pioneer Theater, is certainly
gruesome (though not graphic) but hardly cinematic. The Vermont
wilderness is pretty enough, and the moon looks lonesome shining
through the trees, but the director, Jamie Yerkes, has nothing much
to do besides watch people talk. What they say, thanks to a script
by Amy Sohn, a novelist and former sex columnist for The New York
Press, consists of exchanges like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll believe enough for the both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The road to ultimate human tranquillity is not paved with the
hands of good girlfriends.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonah and his pals are meant to be, I guess, a sampling of the
jaded, overprivileged generation now facing the complications of
adulthood. Ted (Mitchell Riggs) is engaged to Bev (Kim Winter),
though he is plagued with doubts about his commitment to monogamy
and his law school career. Alex (Jessica Faller), the ensemble's
designated slut, exploits these doubts by flirting shamelessly with
Ted, while Rachel (Heather Goldenhersh), the one with low
self-esteem, whines about the man who dumped her.
</P>
<P>
   Into this nest of seething insecurity comes Jonah, who we know
to be a dangerous, ambiguous sexual dynamo because he wears a
sheepskin vest with no shirt underneath and has pierced ears and
nose.
</P>
<P>
   The film turns, as you may have surmised, on a midnight game of
spin the bottle, after which Jonah has sex with two visitors. I
won't reveal which ones, because you couldn't possibly care. The
poor actors arch their brows and enunciate their lame witticisms as
if they were performing Noel Coward, or else rage and parry as if
auditioning for an imported-beer commercial loosely based on
``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' Perhaps the characters are
meant to remind you of people you know, but if that's the case,
they are people you would do everything in your power to avoid, on
screen or off.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SPIN THE BOTTLE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jamie Yerkes; written by Amy Sohn; director of
photography, Harlan Bosmajian; produced by Yerkes and Kris
Hornsher; released by CineBlast! Productions.
</P>
<P>
   With: Mitchell Riggs (Ted), Kim Winter (Bev), Jessica Faller
(Alex), Heather Goldenhersh (Rachel) and Holter Graham (Jonah).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 86 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
