<HEADER>
A4666 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PANAM103-TRIAL-2TAKES     05-03 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAM103-TRIAL-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL BEGINS FOR 2 LIBYANS ACCUSED IN PAN AM 103 BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands _ Nearly 12 years after a jumbo jet blew
up in the skies of Scotland, raining bodies and flaming debris on
the village of Lockerbie, the trial of two Libyans accused of
planting a bomb on the plane got underway Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is unusual in many ways: with 270 victims, it is the
largest mass murder trial in British history, the first time a
patch of Scottish soil has been created overseas to allow such an
event, and the first Scottish murder trial to use judges instead of
a jury.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the first time a trial in what is nominally Britain
has attracted the massive attention usually associated with the
American courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many senses, this trial is unique,'' said John P. Grant,
who leads a team of law professors from the University of Glasgow
studying the trial and helping journalists with the vagaries of
Scottish law. ``It may become the longest trial in British history.
It certainly will be the most expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York-bound Pan Am Flight 103 blew up at about 7:03 p.m.
on Dec. 21, 1988, just after crossing the Solway Firth in Scotland
at 31,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The trial culminates years of struggle among nations, involving
outrage at the crime; a detective investigation spanning the globe,
the isolation of Libya and United Nations sanctions that Libya has
claimed cost it $33 billion, and years of diplomatic maneuvering
that ultimately allowed the suspects to be brought to trial while
Libya's dictator, Col. Moammar Gadhafi, could still claim that he
never handed them over to Libya's enemies.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For all the ballyhoo, the trial got underway quite simply
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under Scottish law, neither prosecution nor defense make opening
statements. So after some preliminary motions had been agreed on,
the indictment had been read and the defense had notified the
prosecution of part of its plans, Judge Ranald Iain Sutherland
looked up and said: ``My Lord Advocate?''
</P>
<P>
   And the lead prosecutor, Colin Boyd, began: ``M'Lord, the first
witness for the Crown is No. 1 on the witness list, Richard James
Dawson.''
</P>
<P>
   After some sound system screeching was fixed _ by a court ruling
that witnesses would be allowed to testify while seated, which
somehow hushed the microphone feedback _ Dawson, a 52-year-old air
traffic controller, began describing the air routes around Heathrow
Airport, from which Pan Am Flight 103 took off shortly before it
exploded.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution has a list of more than 1,000 witnesses, and the
trial of Abdelbaset Ali Mohmed Al Megrahi and Al Amin Khalifa
Fhimah is expected to last a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment lays out a lengthy description of the plot of
which the two are accused. Both are said to have been members of
the Libyan Intelligence Services _ Megrahi the head of security for
Libyan Arab Airlines and Fhimah the airline's station manager in
Malta _ and to have acted in their intelligence roles.
</P>
<P>
   The plot as described stretched from a special forces base in
Libya where bomb timers were said to have been tested to the
offices of front companies named Mebo in Switzerland and Medtours
in Czechoslovakia, and to a Holiday Inn in Malta and Libyan
government offices in Czechoslovakia and Germany. Like the outline
of a Frederick Forsyth novel, it makes sketchy references to
purchases of electronic detonators, travel under false passports
and the carrying out of an unexplained intelligence operation in
Chad, but the core of it is this:
</P>
<P>
   The two men are accused of stealing airline luggage tags at Luqa
Airport in Malta in December 1988, then bringing to Malta a
suitcase and a Toshiba RTSF-16 ``Bombeat'' boom box packed with
plastic explosive and a timer. They bought clothing and an umbrella
in Malta, the prosecution contends, packed them around the bomb,
put them in the suitcase and checked it aboard Air Malta KM180
tagged so that it would go through Frankfurt, London and on to New
York on Pan Am 103.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The list of the dead, part of the indictment, reads like a grim
trip past the headstones of a cemetery. It is alphabetical, so the
name of Brittany Leigh Williams, aged 2 months, of the 516th
Engineer Company Army Post Office, New York, is found between those
of her parents, Bonnie Leigh and Eric Jon, of the same address. All
in all, 259 crew and passenger members and 11 residents of
Lockerbie, two of them aged 10, are on it.
</P>
<P>
   Although it began blandly, Wednesday's trial did have a dramatic
moment in mid-afternoon when Alan John Topp, the last controller to
talk to the pilot, described losing contact with the flight. Its
number had disappeared from his radar screen he was monitoring, he
said, as court television screens showed a tape of the screen he
had been looking at.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost the height readout,'' he testified, explaining the
tape as if he were back at his desk that night. ``That could be a
glitch. Now we've lost everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one big bright square response,'' he continued, referring
to a radar signal response, ``is actually several big lights close
together. That would be _ well, I don't want to say.''
</P>
<P>
   After a court break, he returned to describe how he had
repeatedly tried to radio the plane _ 7 attempts in the next 8
minutes, two calls to a nearby KLM flight asking them to contact
the Pan Am plane, a call to a controller in charge of a lower
altitude and one in charge of over-ocean flights, trying to find
out if they could see Pan Am 103 or had its pilot and co-pilot on
their frequencies.
</P>
<P>
   At about 7:11, he said, he tried to wave his supervisor over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, ``I've got a problem.''`` he recounted.
</P>
<P>
   His boss, he said, replied: ``Not now. I'm trying to get through
to the Dumfries and Galloway police.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, ``What about?'' Topp went on. ``He said, ``The big
fire on the ground.'' He didn't say explosion, but it was in my
area -- it was at that point the penny dropped, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And what,'' asked the prosecutor, ``was the penny?``
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `It's the Clipper 103.'''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Less dramatic, but possibly more important, was a 14-line
document read out before testimony began. It was the defense's
notice to the prosecution that it planned to blame the crime on a
Syrian-backed Palestinian group.
</P>
<P>
   Under Scottish law, the defense must state at the opening of a
trial if it plans to mount certain defenses. They include insanity,
self-defense, coercion, ``automatism'' _ a notion akin to temporary
insanity _ and ``incrimination'' _ a claim that someone else did it
and you will produce evidence against him.
</P>
<P>
   McCourts, the firm defending Megrahi, filed notice that it would
offer an incrimination defense that would blame members of the
Palestinian Popular Struggle Front, possibly including two of the
prosecution's witnesses and six other men, ``all present
whereabouts unknown.'' The defense said they were ``all formerly
directors of the Miska Bakery, Malta'' and members of the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
