<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4668 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PANAM103-TRIAL-2NDTAK     05-03 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAM103-TRIAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands: General Command.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Before the indictment naming the Libyans was announced in 1991,
much attention had focused on Iranians, Syrians and Palestinians as
suspects, and one theory had been that the Pan Am bombing was
revenge not for the U.S. bombing raid on Tripoli in 1986 that
supposedly killed one of Gadhafi's children, but for the shooting
down of an Iranian airliner by the USS
</P>
<P>
   Vincennes in 1988. Under those scenarios, the Iranians were said
to have ``subcontracted'' their revenge, like a Mafia hit, to
Syrians and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The defense asked few questions Wednesday, but focused on how
long the plane was at 31,000 feet before it exploded, how far the
debris blew and whether the plane was definitely in Scottish
airspace, not English.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish law contains other provisions foreign to Americans.
Normally, serious crimes are tried before 15 jurors, and only 8
votes are needed to convict.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the defense had argued that it could not get a
fair trial with a jury because of advance publicity and anti-Libyan
feeling. The prosecution agreed that it would be unfair to have
Scottish jurors away from home for as much as 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, three judges are hearing the case; a fourth sits on
the bench in case one becomes ill. Two of three are needed to
convict.
</P>
<P>
   Three verdicts are available: guilty, not guilty, or not proven.
A not-proven verdict ``leaves a question mark over the head of the
accused, but it's an acquittal,'' said Jim Murdoch, a former
defense lawyer who now teaches at the University of Glasgow law
school. ``As they're leaving the court, a cloud is over their head
_ but they are leaving the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone found ``not proven'' cannot be tried again on the same
charge.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 Scottish police officers, some with submachine
guns, are guarding the prison compound, which has a 20-foot-high
concrete wall. Including construction costs on this former NATO air
base, the trial is expected to cost up to $200 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the outside, the courthouse looks like the gymnasium of a
prosperous suburban high school. Inside, it looks as if Rumpole of
the Bailey was being filmed in the computer center.
</P>
<P>
   The four judges, each seated before his own monitor that
displays evidence, provide nearly the only color in the court: the
snow white chests of their robes are dotted with square red
crosses, and they sit beneath the mace of the court's authority and
the lion-and-unicorn-flanked Royal Arms of Scotland, with the motto
``Nemo me impune lacessit,'' which court aides translate as ``Nane
dare meddle wi' me.''
</P>
<P>
   Six wall-mounted video cameras sweep the court; the signal is
beamed into a media center nearby that housed about 200 reporters
Wednesday. It also goes to New York, London and Dumfries, where the
families of the victims are allowed to follow the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is not otherwise broadcast; Scottish courts forbid it.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists are not supposed to talk to victims' families in the
sealed-off court gallery, but many family members, who have filed
their own civil lawsuits, want to chat, and the police have not
intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Snide comparisons to the O.J. Simpson trial are made regularly
by Scottish court officials, and reporters have been told to assume
that neither prosecutors nor defense lawyers will speak to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Scottish judges don't do press conferences,'' warned a
court press aide. ``So don't ask.''
</P>
</TEXT>
