<HEADER>
A4673 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NC-GOV-630&AMP;ADD-NYT     05-03 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-GOV-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTTERY PROPOSAL EMERGES AS KEY ISSUE IN N.C. GUBERNATORIAL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ind.)   By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The results of Tuesday's primary elections for
governor in North Carolina set up a fall campaign between
candidates with starkly different views, particularly on the
critical issue of education.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic nominee, Attorney General Mike Easley, is likely
to campaign on his plan for a state lottery that would finance a
reduction in class sizes in lower grades. Democrats who defeated
Republican governors in Alabama and South Carolina in 1998 used
their support for the lottery to great effect, and polls show the
idea of a lottery is popular in North Carolina as well.
</P>
<P>
   Easley's Republican opponent, Richard Vinroot, the former mayor
of Charlotte, opposes a lottery for North Carolina, though he would
support a referendum on the issue. As an alternative to a lottery,
Vinroot supports a system of vouchers intended to give parents
greater choice in selecting schools.
</P>
<P>
   Voter turn-out was low in both primaries. Easley, 50, and
Vinroot, 59, won easily despite spirited challenges from
well-financed opponents. With 97 percent of precincts reporting,
Easley was leading Lt. Gov. Dennis Wicker 59 percent to 36 percent.
Vinroot took 45 percent of the vote while his closest competitor,
state Rep. Leo Daughtry, won 37 percent. Candidates must win at
least 40 percent to avoid a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Easley and Vinroot will compete to succeed Gov. Jim Hunt, who
has held the office for four of the last six terms. He was barred
from seeking another term.
</P>
<P>
   Political scientists in North Carolina were struck that the two
victors on Tuesday won without the support of their parties'
grass-roots political machines. In the Democratic race, Wicker was
the clear preference of his party's traditional loyalists,
including organizations of teachers, trial lawyers and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, Daughtry, as the former House majority
leader, was supported by dozens of state legislators and their
local political organizations. And some Christian conservatives
groups, including the Christian Coalition, questioned Vinroot's
commitment to the anti-abortion cause.
</P>
<P>
   Although Vinroot now says he opposes abortion except in cases of
rape, incest and danger to the life of the mother, he and his wife
once made small contributions to Planned Parenthood. He says he did
not realize at the time that the group performed abortions at its
clinics.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it did not matter much that Easley and Vinroot were
not the favorites of their respective party organizations. Both ran
aggressive television advertising campaigns, and they did not
suffer for making fewer public appearances than their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old-style politics may not work as well as it used to,
meaning going county to county and shaking hands with a lot of
people,'' said Thad Beyle, a political scientist at the University
of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. ``The new politics of raising
money and paying for your media and looking good on TV worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley, a former prosecutor who is considered a moderate, made
it clear in his victory speech on Tuesday night that he would make
education a centerpiece of his campaign against Vinroot. ``To those
who seek to dismantle public education by risky schemes of
vouchers, let me be clear,'' he said. ``I will fight you every step
of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinroot, who ran as more of a conservative this year than in his
unsuccessful 1996 gubernatorial primary race, asserted that Easley
``won by promising to spend more of your money.'' Vinroot has taken
a pledge against raising taxes, but Beyle and other political
observers predicted that the state's deepening fiscal problems and
the dynamics of the campaign would force him to move toward the
center and reconsider his position on taxes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The presidential race is also expected to have a significant
impact on the fall campaign. Republicans are counting on a strong
showing by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, their presumptive nominee,
to pull Vinroot to victory. Bush is heavily favored to win North
Carolina, but the size of a Bush victory could be crucial to
Vinroot's chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George Bush is a really strong candidate, if he's winning
at the level of Reagan in '84 or Nixon in '72, Easley can hang it
up,'' said Ted Arrington, the chairman of the political science
department at the University of North Carolina at Charlotte. ``If
George is more like his father or Bob Dole, there's a good chance
that Mike Easley will be our next governor.''
</P>
<P>
   In Indiana on Tuesday, Rep. David McIntosh won the Republican
nomination for governor. He will challenge the Democratic
incumbent, Frank O'Bannon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
