<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TAVERNER-MUSIC-ART-NY     05-03 1447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAVERNER-MUSIC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMERSED IN ANCIENT MUSICAL TRADITIONS, SEEKING TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT20,22 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Taverner sat near the window of his East Side
hotel room, calmly if unsmilingly cooperating as a photographer
tried to frame him in the afternoon light. Tall and thin, with long
blond locks that cascade onto his shoulders and a deep tan acquired
in Greece, where he spends much of his time, the recently knighted
English composer gazed into the lens without decipherable emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look like someone from another century,'' the photographer
remarked between shots. And in a way that's exactly what Taverner
would like to be.
</P>
<P>
   He is, on the one hand, a composer whose serene sacred works
have won him an enormous popular following in recent years. Yet in
his view Western civilization generally, and its music in
particular, have been heading in the wrong direction at least since
the Renaissance, possibly longer. He has been trying to put things
right. It's not that he has rejected the last four centuries of
musical evolution: his work would not be mistaken for anything
other than modern post-atonal music. But since his conversion to
the Russian Orthodox faith 23 years ago, he has sought musical and
philosophical roots in ancient musical traditions ranging from
Byzantine chants to Indian ragas to American Indian music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has taken me years to really understand what tradition
is,'' he said, ``and to explain it to anyone else is difficult.
People call it different things. In Islam, the Sufis call it `the
eye of the heart.' St. Augustine defined it as `the intellective
organ of the heart.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different way of thinking about writing music. I used
to fret over manuscripts and think, `What am I going to do?' Now
it's a question of going very quiet, emptying my mind of
preconceived ideas and seeing what happens. It's not so much a
question of finding my voice as finding the voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Taverner is to conduct a retrospective of his works at the
Church of St. Ignatius Loyolain Manhattan Thursday night at 8. The
performers include the Tallis Scholars; the Flux Ensemble; the
Juilliard Brass Ensemble; Patricia Rozario, a soprano who has
recorded several of his vocal works; and Paul McCartney, who has
known Taverner since 1970, when the Beatles' Apple Records label
released two albums of his music. Taverner is to narrate ``In the
Month of Athyr,'' a setting of a poem by the Greek poet Constantine
Cavafy. The concert will be broadcast live by WNYC (93.9 FM) as
well as on its Web site, www.wnyc.org.
</P>
<P>
   Taverner's appearances in New York have been rare. He attended
the New York premiere of his popular cello concerto, ``The
Protecting Veil,'' in 1993. But when the Greek Orthodox
Archdiocesan Cathedral of the Holy Trinity presented an
all-Taverner concert last year, the composer said that his doctor
prohibited him from trans-Atlantic travel because of his health.
His presence is not a sign that his health has improved; this time
the invitation came with a ticket for the Concorde, which cut his
travel time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have doesn't get better,'' said the 56-year-old
composer, who is married and has two children. ``It's called Marfan
syndrome, and it attacks the main valve to the heart, it attacks
the eyes, it attacks the mind _ there isn't much it doesn't attack.
And the big danger of Marfan is that you can suffer a rupture at
any time, and you go quickly. So I suppose I live with the thought
of death very much in front of me, and this may well have a bearing
on the way I think generally.''
</P>
<P>
   It does not, however, explain his fascination with religion,
which predates the discovery about 14 years ago that he has the
congenital disease. The interest in religion, he said, began when
he was 12 and heard a broadcast of Stravinsky's ``Canticum Sacrum''
from the Basilica of St. Mark's in Venice. Several of his early
works, like ``The Whale'' (1968), which is about the biblical story
of Jonah, the ``Celtic'' Requiem (1969) and the a cappella ``Nomine
Jesu'' (1970), have sacred underpinnings.
</P>
<P>
   But he composed those works in his comparatively secular
mid-20s, a time when he was celebrated as a hot newcomer on the
London compositional scene. He had recently completed studies at
the Royal Academy of Music and had started on a conducting career
that included a performance of Verdi's ``Trovatore'' at Covent
Garden when he was 24. By the early 1970s, though, he had begun
searching for a sense of religious stability. An interest in
Russian and Greek Orthodox icons, which he encountered at an
exhibition of religious art in London, led him to explore the
church's theology, and he formally converted in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   This was not, at first, good for his composing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I joined the Orthodox Church,'' he said, ``the archbishop
asked me to make a setting of the liturgy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very clever of him, because first of all, it helped me
get to know the liturgy really well. But it brought me up against a
real compositional crisis because the congregation came up and
said, `You don't know anything about the sacred tone systems' and,
`This is just your own fabricated music.' I began thinking that
maybe they're right, maybe everything I'd done up till then was a
complete waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That brought me headlong into the whole concept of tradition.
I stopped composing, and I listened to Indian music, Persian music,
all music from the Middle East. I listened to American Indian
music. I listened to any music that was based on traditional ideas.
That's when I started to question what on earth happened to this
Western civilization and why the sacred seems to have been pushed
out gradually by the domination of the ego.''
</P>
<P>
   His study of ancient, durable musical forms led him to develop a
style that, it turned out, was perfectly suited to a part of the
new-music world that was taking shape in the mid-1980s. Like the
music of Arvo Part, Giya Kancheli and others of the Eastern
European mystical school, his works tend to be slow-moving and
intense, and in an eclectic, accessible language. Recordings of
works like ``The Protecting Veil'' sold plentifully.
</P>
<P>
   Because he no longer sees a point in writing entirely secular
music, his instrumental works, which include several concertos and
three string quartets, have what he calls a metaphysical subtext.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't important for listeners to know what these subtexts
are,'' he said. ``Only I have to know. I have to have in mind what
the text would be if the work had one. But people can make of it
what they want. When `The Protecting Veil' had its premiere, one
letter that touched me the most was from a young girl who asked if
in that piece I was protecting unfashionable values like truth and
beauty. Well, the protecting veil is associated with a feast in the
Orthodox Church, but if people hear something else, that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, his music is vocal or choral, and although the
texts are not always overtly religious _ he has set poetry of
William Blake and Sappho, for example _ his music tends to cast
them in devotional light. That, it turns out, is not always easy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the works on the program Thursday night, ``A New
Beginning,'' was commissioned for a performance at the Millennium
Dome in London during the final moments of 1999. The text was
composed by committee and includes a list of wishes for the future
_ ``Respect for the earth, peace in the world, forgiveness of past
wrongs, a new start.'' At first glance, Taverner found it too
platitudinous and vague to set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked: `Who is this addressed to? Couldn't I at least put an
Oh Lord at the end of each one?''' he said. ``Well, they didn't
want to offend atheists, but in the end they agreed that for
musical purposes it might be best. Anyway, by the time it got to
midnight, everyone was so drunk and there was such a ludicrous
party mood that the piece had very little effect. So I regard the
performance here as the world premiere.''
</P>
<P>
   What, a visitor wondered, do those in the Orthodox Church who
disliked his early liturgical setting think of his current work? Do
they think he has learned to write sacred music?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I think so,'' he said with a quiet laugh. ``But I'm very
grateful to them for being so miserable and mean. Because of that,
I've found a completely angstless way of writing music. And the
music really does appear to spring from somewhere else. I can't
tell you where _ I just don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
