<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4679 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-COLUMN0504-COX     05-03 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Candidates mixing up a political melting pot
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For a sense of how blurred distinctions have become in
the century's first political campaign, consider these items from
the past week or so:
</P>
<P>
   Chatting with reporters aboard Air Force Two, Vice President Al
Gore said his instinct in choosing a running mate was to ``build
consensus'' and reach out to someone different than himself. It
wasn't likely, he cautioned, but he wouldn't even rule out choosing
a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George Bush campaigned in Ohio with four sympathetic
Democrats from the Texas Legislature. Then he met with Democratic
Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, who shares some of his views on
privatization, before announcing his Social Security plan. Gore has
attacked this as a ``secret plan'' to wreck the Social Security
system.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Gore met Sunday with Sen. John McCain to talk
about campaign finance reform. McCain has publicly blasted Gore on
both Social Security and campaign finance reform, but he gave the
vice president 20 minutes of his time, and he still hasn't arranged
a meeting with Bush. (Gore-McCain? Bush-Kerrey? The ticket
possibilities are endless, once you allow interleague play.)
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no big surprise, all this considered, that in
a poll released last week by the Joan Shorenstein Center on the
Press, Politics and Public Policy, voters knew less about where
Bush and Gore stand on the issues than they did two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   And get this: Lawyers from Kenneth Starr's law firm, Kirk and
Ellis, have contributed more than $32,000 to Hillary Clinton's New
York Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, surely, the time will come when Bush and Gore will begin
to sharpen the edges a little and define themselves, so the voters
can again remember which is from Texas and which is from Tennessee.
The great battle at this point is for the loosely affiliated
middle, and neither party has done much to activate its base,
unless fund-raisers count as pep rallies.
</P>
<P>
   But when the parties nominate two presidential candidates more
like each other than any of the rivals they faced in their own
party's primaries _ boomer sons of politicians, centrist
Southerners _ a degree of fuzziness is inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   ``At their heart, these are not partisan issues,'' Gore said in
Atlanta on Tuesday, in a policy speech on crime. The same could be
said of several core issues in this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Gore proceeded to blast Bush, but even the way the
candidates attack each other avoids making a point of any
fundamental differences.
</P>
<P>
   Gore accuses Bush of not doing enough as governor about crime,
education, or whatever. Bush likes to accuse Gore of copying him:
``Gore Travels to Texas to Embrace Bush's Education Reforms,'' was
the headline on Bush's Web site Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As opposed to some of the phony line-drawing of recent
campaigns, the ooziness of this one may not be such a bad thing.
The danger is that without partisan differences to define the
debate, the argument will grow increasingly personal.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a certain risk for both candidates that in sounding
so much like the other, voters start hankering for someone who
doesn't. But to judge by Pat Buchanan's lack of headway, that
hasn't happened yet. So far, the voters like what their candidate
is saying _ if they can just remember which one it is.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
