<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4682 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-MCCAIN-BIGDIG-BOS &LR;      05-03 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-BIGDIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN WOULD SEEK TO CAP `BIG DIG' APPROPRIATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Raising the prospect that Boston's ``Big Dig''
highway renovation project could ultimately cost $20 billion,
Senator John McCain says he is ready to push legislation to bar
Congress from approving another dime for the project.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, an Arizona Republican who wields enormous power over the
project as chairman of the Senate Committee on Commerce, Science
and Transportation, cited estimates of the Big Dig's final price
that have spiraled from $2.6 billion in 1985 to $13.6 billion last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that kind of trend continues, we're talking about $20
billion, and that kind of overrun is unbelievable,'' McCain said
during a hearing on the Big Dig's financial crisis. ``I think the
taxpayers deserve a law that says at some point this has to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has approved about $8.5 billion in federal funds for
the project, of which $5 billion has been spent. The remainder of
the cost is paid by the state.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who blasted federal highway authorities, Big Dig
officials, and private contractors for their ``complete and utter
failure'' in handling numerous aspects of the budget debacle, said
he would consider seeking the spending cap despite assurances from
state officials that Massachusetts will seek no additional federal
aid for the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our problem, and we're going to fix it,'' the Big Dig's
new chief, Andrew Natsios, told McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry, a senior Democrat on the committee, said
during the hearing that the Massachusetts congressional delegation
also has pledged to request no more federal money for the Big Dig,
the nation's most costly public works project.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry noted that congressional leaders, who have given numerous
signs that they have lost all patience with the venture's
exorbitant cost increases, would likely kill any effort to seek
additional dollars in any case.
</P>
<P>
   ``In effect there is a cap already because no one in the US
Congress is going to vote for giving us more money ever again,''
Kerry said. ``Maybe the Massachusetts delegation might, but we are
going to be roundly beaten.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet McCain, during an exchange with US Transportation Secretary
Rodney E. Slater, underscored his intention to consider a law to
prevent additional federal spending on the Big Dig. When Slater
appeared to balk at a cap, saying, ``At the end of the day, we may
do that,'' McCain snapped back, ``At the beginning of the day, we
may do it with an amendment to an appropriations bill.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain later left open the possibility that he would settle for
a written agreement, which Slater, Kerry, and Natsios appeared to
favor, rather than a new law.
</P>
<P>
   McCain called the hearing in response to a scathing federal task
force report last month that said former Big Dig officials had
intentionally concealed the cost overruns from federal oversight
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which included 34 recommendations to restore the
project's integrity, prompted Governor Paul Cellucci to fire the
project's former chief, James J. Kerasiotes, and join state
legislative leaders in trying to craft a massive bailout plan.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the report followed more than two dozen reviews by
federal agencies and the state auditor that were ``routinely
ignored'' before the budget crisis became public.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among McCain's complaints was the failure of Big Dig
officials to require private contractors to pay financial penalties
for any role they may have played in the budget overruns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be some penalty,'' McCain told Matthew Wiley,
project manager for the Big Dig's prime management contractors,
Bechtel and Parsons Brinckerhoff. ``I don't know many places in the
world that would submit or accept this kind of performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiley defended the joint venture's performance, saying the
contractors properly responded to factors that drove up the Big
Dig's costs, primarily the project's wider scope. ``We have done a
good job of managing that project,'' Wiley said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kenneth Mead, the US Transportation Department's
inspector general, criticized the Bechtel/Parsons Brinckerhoff team
for not informing his office of the unexpected cost increases as
Kerasiotes and his staff allegedly withheld them from federal
highway officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed that I didn't hear anything from Bechtel
about these costs increases,'' Mead said during the hearing. ``With
600 people, I would assume that some of them must have had a clue
about where some of the costs were going.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiley said the contractors expressed concern last year to the
Big Dig's state officials and were told that the overrun was offset
in part by nearly $1 billion in credits from the project's
insurance program.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general and federal task force later ruled that
Big Dig officials had improperly used the insurance funds as budget
offsets. The insurance funds, which should have been returned to
the federal government, were used to invest in Disney stock, bonds
and other securities, Mead said.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Kerry, Richard Thomas, senior vice
president of the Big Dig's insurer, American International Group,
said the funds at issue had grown unusually large because the
insurance company has paid claims totaling less than 20 percent of
the premiums the Big Dig has paid.
</P>
<P>
   When the inspector general first criticized the Big Dig's
insurance program, Kerasiotes and a top aide, Patrick Moynihan,
vehemently disputed the findings. McCain cited a letter that
Moynihan sent Mead last year, saying the findings were the product
of ``a backward-looking management technique that is unworkable and
shows a fundamental lack of understanding how a multimillion-dollar
megaproject needs to be managed.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said of the letter: ``It's a degree of arrogance I don't
think I've experienced before.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Senator Bob Smith, a New Hampshire Republican who
serves on the panel, said he also is investigating the Big Dig as
chairman of the Committee on the Environment and Public Works. ``I
urge the secretary of transportation and other members of Congress
to join me in ensuring that no federal funds above the existing
formula are spent on these cost overrurns,'' Smith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4683 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DSL-BLUES-ART-2ND     05-03 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DSL-BLUES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the public. '' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The greatest source of annoyance is the level of customer
support or, as many companies now label it, customer care.
</P>
<P>
   Phone companies and other DSL service providers need hundreds of
customer service representatives to handle the flood of inquiries
and service and repair requests, so they are retraining and hiring
workers. Along with the shortage of trained personnel has come a
lack of efficiency and, some say, a lack of competence.
</P>
<P>
   Some frustrated DSL subscribers have even taken to logging the
number of fruitless hours they spend on the phone with customer
support employees.
</P>
<P>
   Hipps said he had racked up 65 hours, acquainting himself with
every aspect of U S West's customer support hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   James Williams, a police officer in Philadelphia, is all too
familiar with Bell Atlantic's customer support. Williams said he
had encountered three serious problems since he first got his DSL
service three months ago. With each problem, he said, he talked to
a minimum of five people.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Williams became something of a DSL expert. He
tosses around DSL jargon as if he invented it. Terms like DSlam
(digital subscriber line access multiplexer, the equipment that
sends data into a bigger data pipe), CO (central office, the place
where the switching equipment resides) and throughput (transmission
speed) trip off his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams, who prefers to do his Web surfing before dawn,
would gladly have traded all that knowledge for a cure for his
strangest problem. At least twice a week at 4:30 ``on the dot,'' he
said, his service went down. ``I took that as my cue to go to
bed,'' he said. Williams was assured that the service was not being
taken down for routine maintenance. The problem has been fixed, but
its cause remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Trying times call for creative measures.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic has taken to dispatching technicians to customers'
homes. ``If all the basic things we do can't help us nail it down,
we'll send someone out with a laptop,'' Mendelsohn said. By using
the company's computer instead of the customer's, the technician
can determine whether the problem is with a setting in the
customer's computer or with the DSL service.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to have technicians come to the house _ until it
begins to look as though they may never leave.
</P>
<P>
   Klarquist, marketing director for a market research firm in San
Francisco, ordered DSL service from Pacific Bell, which is owned by
SBC, at the end of March. The installer arrived at 4:30 one
afternoon and stayed until 9 p.m. trying to get her service up and
running. ``It worked for about 5 or 10 seconds, then it didn't work
at all,'' she said. That went on all evening. ``Every time
something came up, he said, `Gee, I've never seen that before.'''
</P>
<P>
   Klarquist said she had considered offering him a beer but
thought better of it. ``I thought that would probably really mess
him up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several days passed and she still had no service. She devoted
hours to calling the customer support line. Then she came home one
day to find that all telephone service to her house had been
obliterated, and she was forced to make all calls from her cell
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, her phone service was restored, and when a
friend stopped by for a visit, she asked him to take a look at her
DSL setup. ``He said, `I think I can figure this out,' and within
20 minutes it was up and running, she recalled. As it turned out, a
Web browser setting needed to be changed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, finally, Klarquist has DSL service, ``but no thanks to
Pacific Bell,'' she said. ``Now every time I see a PacBell Internet
commercial, I feel like drop-kicking my television.''
</P>
<P>
   The frustration runs both ways, of course. ``We've seen, as you
can imagine, everything under the sun,'' said Mendelsohn, of Bell
Atlantic. ``People who've moved jacks and plugged into the wrong
line, and customers installing other software. All of that fouls up
communication.''
</P>
<P>
   To cope with the explosion in demand, SBC, Bell Atlantic and
other companies are moving toward having customers do their own
installations _ the DSL provider simply sends customers the
hardware and software they need to do it themselves. Eighty-five
percent of Bell Atlantic's DSL customers handle their own
installations, and SBC plans to start offering the option by May. U
S West has offered customer installation since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Another solution being considered by Bell Atlantic and others is
remote diagnoses of customers' computer setups. That is, each
support technician, with the customer's permission, is given remote
access to the customer's computer to check settings and other
potential causes of a snag.
</P>
<P>
   And one novel approach to the shortage of customer service
technicians is to let technicians work from home. Telocity, a
broadband provider in Cupertino, Calif., that uses DSL, has hired
100 part-time customer support employees in the Chicago area.
Instead of requiring them to work in large call centers, the
company routes calls to the employees' homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They provide the computer, two phone lines and a quiet
professional environment,'' said Jim Rohrer, Telocity's customer
care officer. ``No barking dogs and no children in the
background.''
</P>
<P>
   Rohrer said he was convinced that this approach would attract a
higher caliber of employee. ``We're getting college-degreed folks
who would never come to work at a call center,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the learning curve remains steep, and for some customers, it
is already too late. Earlier this month, Ajit Tharaken, a
programmer in Manhattan, canceled his DSL service from Bell
Atlantic after two months of spotty connections and ordered service
from a competing DSL carrier. ``When I canceled, they did not ask
me for my reasons for canceling,'' Tharaken said. ``I do not think
they care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4684 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-VIEQUES-HONEYMOON-050     05-03 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-HONEYMOON-0504-1STLD-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 3rd graf, adds the couple's individual hometowns in
Alabama
 &HT;    BAD TIMING? NEWLYWEDS FIND UNEXPECTED GUESTS ON ISLAND
HONEYMOON: PROTESTERS, NAVY WARSHIPS
 &HT;    With Photo of the Bartels available.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ Bob Bartels wanted to surprise his
bride-to-be with a honeymoon she'd never forget: a week of sun and
sand on a little-known Caribbean gem where deserted beaches are
lapped by azure waters.
</P>
<P>
   He surprised her, all right, but Wednesday he was wondering if a
contingent of U.S. Marines and a couple of Navy warships might
crash the party.
</P>
<P>
   Married on Sunday in Montgomery, Ala., the couple (botrh
Alabamians, he's from Auburn, she's from Dothan) arrived on Vieques
Monday, just as a showdown between the U.S. government and
protestors camped out on a Navy bombing range appeared imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out when we got to the San Juan airport,'' said
Bartels' bride, Andrea, 28. ``He showed me a newspaper and I said,
'Oh my God, we're going to a war zone.'''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the couple found Vieques to be all Bartels promised:
quaint, laid-back, stunningly beautiful and filled with friendly
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just adds a little bit of excitement in addition to the
basic honeymoon,'' Bob Bartels said, as the couple stopped to see a
clump of protestors gathered outside the main gate to the bombing
range. ``We'll keep the newspaper clippings and have a little more
to remember it by.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartels _ formerly a public relations executive with Fitzgerald
and Co. in Atlanta, and now an employee of the Public Utility
Commission of Texas in Austin _ booked the honeymoon months ago. He
had visited Vieques once, and fell in love with the tiny island,
where horses and cows sometimes graze along the narrow roads that
wind through the hilly countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a hidden treasure,'' he said. ``Let everybody else
go to Jamaica and St. Thomas. We've got the beach to ourselves
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartels, 30, had heard about the long-simmering controversy over
the bombing range, and grew a little worried as the wedding drew
near and news reports said the conflict was heating up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just before the wedding, a friend told me he had seen news
about Vieques on CNN,'' he said. ``That got me a little worried, so
I made a few calls and decided it shouldn't be too much of a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he told both sets of parents to keep them from
worrying, he kept the trip a secret from Andrea.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept dropping hints about it,'' she said. ``I kept thinking
there might be a hurricane or a problem with the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, there have been no signs of federal agents or U.S.
Marines, although a couple of giant Navy ships have been patrolling
the waters off Vieques and military helicopters sometimes beat
through the otherwise clear Caribbean sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really won't affect us,'' Bartels said. ``We're still
having a great time. The beaches are still beautiful and the
weather is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
