<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4685 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-VIEQUES-HONEYMOON-050     05-03 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-HONEYMOON-0504-1STLD-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 3rd graf, adds the couple's individual hometowns in
Alabama
 &HT;    BAD TIMING? NEWLYWEDS FIND UNEXPECTED GUESTS ON ISLAND
HONEYMOON: PROTESTERS, NAVY WARSHIPS
 &HT;    With Photo of the Bartels available.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ Bob Bartels wanted to surprise his
bride-to-be with a honeymoon she'd never forget: a week of sun and
sand on a little-known Caribbean gem where deserted beaches are
lapped by azure waters.
</P>
<P>
   He surprised her, all right, but Wednesday he was wondering if a
contingent of U.S. Marines and a couple of Navy warships might
crash the party.
</P>
<P>
   Married on Sunday in Montgomery, Ala., the couple (botrh
Alabamians, he's from Auburn, she's from Dothan) arrived on Vieques
Monday, just as a showdown between the U.S. government and
protestors camped out on a Navy bombing range appeared imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out when we got to the San Juan airport,'' said
Bartels' bride, Andrea, 28. ``He showed me a newspaper and I said,
'Oh my God, we're going to a war zone.'''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the couple found Vieques to be all Bartels promised:
quaint, laid-back, stunningly beautiful and filled with friendly
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just adds a little bit of excitement in addition to the
basic honeymoon,'' Bob Bartels said, as the couple stopped to see a
clump of protestors gathered outside the main gate to the bombing
range. ``We'll keep the newspaper clippings and have a little more
to remember it by.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartels _ formerly a public relations executive with Fitzgerald
and Co. in Atlanta, and now an employee of the Public Utility
Commission of Texas in Austin _ booked the honeymoon months ago. He
had visited Vieques once, and fell in love with the tiny island,
where horses and cows sometimes graze along the narrow roads that
wind through the hilly countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a hidden treasure,'' he said. ``Let everybody else
go to Jamaica and St. Thomas. We've got the beach to ourselves
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartels, 30, had heard about the long-simmering controversy over
the bombing range, and grew a little worried as the wedding drew
near and news reports said the conflict was heating up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just before the wedding, a friend told me he had seen news
about Vieques on CNN,'' he said. ``That got me a little worried, so
I made a few calls and decided it shouldn't be too much of a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he told both sets of parents to keep them from
worrying, he kept the trip a secret from Andrea.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept dropping hints about it,'' she said. ``I kept thinking
there might be a hurricane or a problem with the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, there have been no signs of federal agents or U.S.
Marines, although a couple of giant Navy ships have been patrolling
the waters off Vieques and military helicopters sometimes beat
through the otherwise clear Caribbean sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really won't affect us,'' Bartels said. ``We're still
having a great time. The beaches are still beautiful and the
weather is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
