<SLUG> BC-EMC-ANNUAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMC CHIEF HAS HIGH EXPECTATIONS FOR COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing demand for data storage devices could make EMC Corp. one
of the world's 10 most highly valued companies by 2010, EMC's chief
executive, Michael Ruettgers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   EMC announced a two-for-one stock split, its sixth split since
1992. The record date for the new stock split will be May 19 and
the distribution date June 2.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year, EMC's shares have more than doubled on
increased sales of the heavy-duty computer disk-drive assemblies
and software it produces for corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   Prime customers have been airlines and banks, though EMC has
begun marketing itself as an Internet infrastructure provider as
well. Last week in New York, it rolled out a new line of storage
devices. Wednesday, speaking in Southborough, Mass., after the
company's annual meeting, Ruettgers said the increasing importance
of data for communications and e-commerce applications would
continue to drive up EMC's market valuation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to agree that (a spot in) the top ten is likely,'' he
said, perhaps by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in EMC fell $2.75 in New York Stock Exchange trading
Wednesday to close at $136.25. That left EMC's market
capitalization _ its number of shares times its price per share _
at $142 billion, the 16th largest in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The most highly valued company is General Electric Co., with a
market cap of $514 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ruettgers' forecast came as the Hopkinton, Mass. company has
increased its lead over competitors like IBM and Compaq Computer
Corp. in key data-storage market segments. Those companies are
seeking to recapture share, partly by offering equipment at lower
prices.
</P>
<P>
   EMC's meeting was held in an empty manufacturing hall acquired
when EMC purchased Data General Corp. for about $1 billion in stock
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting drew about 2,000 shareholders, including many small
investors invited by the company as it tries to broaden its
ownership. Institutions now hold about 75 percent of the company,
down from 80 percent a year ago, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle facing the company, Ruettgers said, will be
to find, hire and train about 6,000 skilled employees EMC plans to
hire this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ruettgers said the company will continue its acquisitions,
buying software companies or companies that provide remote-storage
services. EMC also plans to increase overseas sales to 50 percent
of total revenue by 2003, from 40 percent today, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
