<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-BIGDIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN WOULD SEEK TO CAP `BIG DIG' APPROPRIATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Raising the prospect that Boston's ``Big Dig''
highway renovation project could ultimately cost $20 billion,
Senator John McCain says he is ready to push legislation to bar
Congress from approving another dime for the project.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, an Arizona Republican who wields enormous power over the
project as chairman of the Senate Committee on Commerce, Science
and Transportation, cited estimates of the Big Dig's final price
that have spiraled from $2.6 billion in 1985 to $13.6 billion last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that kind of trend continues, we're talking about $20
billion, and that kind of overrun is unbelievable,'' McCain said
during a hearing on the Big Dig's financial crisis. ``I think the
taxpayers deserve a law that says at some point this has to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has approved about $8.5 billion in federal funds for
the project, of which $5 billion has been spent. The remainder of
the cost is paid by the state.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who blasted federal highway authorities, Big Dig
officials, and private contractors for their ``complete and utter
failure'' in handling numerous aspects of the budget debacle, said
he would consider seeking the spending cap despite assurances from
state officials that Massachusetts will seek no additional federal
aid for the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our problem, and we're going to fix it,'' the Big Dig's
new chief, Andrew Natsios, told McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry, a senior Democrat on the committee, said
during the hearing that the Massachusetts congressional delegation
also has pledged to request no more federal money for the Big Dig,
the nation's most costly public works project.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry noted that congressional leaders, who have given numerous
signs that they have lost all patience with the venture's
exorbitant cost increases, would likely kill any effort to seek
additional dollars in any case.
</P>
<P>
   ``In effect there is a cap already because no one in the US
Congress is going to vote for giving us more money ever again,''
Kerry said. ``Maybe the Massachusetts delegation might, but we are
going to be roundly beaten.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet McCain, during an exchange with US Transportation Secretary
Rodney E. Slater, underscored his intention to consider a law to
prevent additional federal spending on the Big Dig. When Slater
appeared to balk at a cap, saying, ``At the end of the day, we may
do that,'' McCain snapped back, ``At the beginning of the day, we
may do it with an amendment to an appropriations bill.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain later left open the possibility that he would settle for
a written agreement, which Slater, Kerry, and Natsios appeared to
favor, rather than a new law.
</P>
<P>
   McCain called the hearing in response to a scathing federal task
force report last month that said former Big Dig officials had
intentionally concealed the cost overruns from federal oversight
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which included 34 recommendations to restore the
project's integrity, prompted Governor Paul Cellucci to fire the
project's former chief, James J. Kerasiotes, and join state
legislative leaders in trying to craft a massive bailout plan.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the report followed more than two dozen reviews by
federal agencies and the state auditor that were ``routinely
ignored'' before the budget crisis became public.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among McCain's complaints was the failure of Big Dig
officials to require private contractors to pay financial penalties
for any role they may have played in the budget overruns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be some penalty,'' McCain told Matthew Wiley,
project manager for the Big Dig's prime management contractors,
Bechtel and Parsons Brinckerhoff. ``I don't know many places in the
world that would submit or accept this kind of performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiley defended the joint venture's performance, saying the
contractors properly responded to factors that drove up the Big
Dig's costs, primarily the project's wider scope. ``We have done a
good job of managing that project,'' Wiley said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kenneth Mead, the US Transportation Department's
inspector general, criticized the Bechtel/Parsons Brinckerhoff team
for not informing his office of the unexpected cost increases as
Kerasiotes and his staff allegedly withheld them from federal
highway officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed that I didn't hear anything from Bechtel
about these costs increases,'' Mead said during the hearing. ``With
600 people, I would assume that some of them must have had a clue
about where some of the costs were going.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiley said the contractors expressed concern last year to the
Big Dig's state officials and were told that the overrun was offset
in part by nearly $1 billion in credits from the project's
insurance program.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general and federal task force later ruled that
Big Dig officials had improperly used the insurance funds as budget
offsets. The insurance funds, which should have been returned to
the federal government, were used to invest in Disney stock, bonds
and other securities, Mead said.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Kerry, Richard Thomas, senior vice
president of the Big Dig's insurer, American International Group,
said the funds at issue had grown unusually large because the
insurance company has paid claims totaling less than 20 percent of
the premiums the Big Dig has paid.
</P>
<P>
   When the inspector general first criticized the Big Dig's
insurance program, Kerasiotes and a top aide, Patrick Moynihan,
vehemently disputed the findings. McCain cited a letter that
Moynihan sent Mead last year, saying the findings were the product
of ``a backward-looking management technique that is unworkable and
shows a fundamental lack of understanding how a multimillion-dollar
megaproject needs to be managed.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said of the letter: ``It's a degree of arrogance I don't
think I've experienced before.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Senator Bob Smith, a New Hampshire Republican who
serves on the panel, said he also is investigating the Big Dig as
chairman of the Committee on the Environment and Public Works. ``I
urge the secretary of transportation and other members of Congress
to join me in ensuring that no federal funds above the existing
formula are spent on these cost overrurns,'' Smith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
