<HEADER>
A4690 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-QUILTER-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      05-03 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUILTER-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACE WORK
</HEADLINE>
  Ex-Marine finds calm in hobby 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Optional fact box below) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It doesn't take much to recognize someone who has been bitten by
the quilting bug. Hazel Wetts sees such a person in Ollie Norman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people golf and some people bowl,'' says Wetts,
co-chairwoman of the Quilting in the Valley 2000 show this weekend
at Cal State Northridge. ``Ollie quilts.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed he does.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, a 73-year-old former U.S. Marine and the only man in the
175-member Valley Quiltmakers Guild, has completed 20 queen- or
king- sized quilts in three years. The talented and prolific North
Hollywood resident calls the activity an ideal form of relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'll be sewing at 3 in the afternoon until 3 a.m.
the next morning,'' says Norman. ``I don't care to watch TV. There
ain't much worth watching anyway. I can turn the radio on to some
music and sew all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   One look inside Norman's home and you know he's not lying.
</P>
<P>
   First, there are the completed quilts _ big, bright colorful
pieces exemplifying techniques Norman rattles off: ``stack and
whack,'' ``double wedding rings'' and ``square-in-a-square.'' Then,
there are the scraps and pieces _ some kept in an empty pizza box _
that will one day be stitched together with other pieces to become
a quilt. Norman also uses these pieces for informational patches on
the backs of finished works, which describe the quilt's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a quilt, you should always have a record of that
quilt,'' says Norman with a laugh. ``All of mine do.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are the full bolts of fabric, crammed onto the
shelves in the tiny room where Norman does his sewing. Norman's
collection comes from quilt shops both existing and defunct. He
gets his materials from anyplace handy. Once he cut a slice off an
old abandoned couch he discovered in a parking lot near Los Angeles
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Norman plans to work at the quilt show this weekend. He'll also
have at least one of his works displayed. He might have had more,
but a ruptured appendix sent him to the hospital for 11 days and an
on-the-mend Norman is still not at full-stitching strength. Once he
has fully recuperated, he'll get to work on making drapes for his
home.
</P>
<P>
   You might say the Tennessee-born and -bred Norman has sewing in
his blood. His mother sewed, and he learned as a child by observing
his two older sisters. When he joined the Marines, a sewing machine
was his ticket to some spare cash, since he could ``cut out a shirt
and sew chevrons on it like nobody's business.''
</P>
<P>
   But quilting is a relatively new hobby. He started three years
ago after buying his granddaughter a sewing machine and some books
in an effort to try to get her interested in the hobby.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did she take to the craft, she turned Norman on to it
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Hey, Gramps, you ought to try it. It's good
therapy,''' recalled Norman. ``It's !ital!very good therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, and if Norman's output is any indication, he is
one of the most calm and sane people alive. Norman is never without
a project under construction or completed. He gives most of his
quilts away, to family members _ including one to his mother who
celebrates her 101st birthday in July _ friends, and even
strangers. Norman says he gave one woman a quilt simply because he
felt she needed one.
</P>
<P>
   Wetts says Norman is one of the guild's less talkative members,
though he is a fixture at their monthly meetings. His productivity
isn't unusual, says Wetts, although most of the guild members tend
to work on slightly smaller projects _ baby blankets and wall
hangings, instead of bedspreads.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got talent,'' Wetts says of Norman, ``and we all
appreciate his quilts.''
</P>
<P>
   And Norman appreciates the guild. The quilters have been nothing
but concerned and sympathetic since his hospital stay, and Norman
has developed a particular friendship with the guild's oldest
member, 92-year-old Libby Landerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just one of the most beautiful groups of people I ever
met in my entire life,'' Norman says. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
What: Quilting in the Valley 2000 presented by the San Fernando
Valley Quilt Association and the Valley Quiltmakers Guild. The
event features more than 150 quilts on display as well as a doll
display, a fashion show, a vendor mall and a quilt auction. &QL; 
Where: California State University, Northridge, Student Union,
18111 Nordhoff St., Northridge. Park in Lot C off Zelzah Avenue. &QL; 
When: 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. today, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Sunday. &QL; 
Tickets: $5 donation. &QL; 
Info: (323) 874-1557 or (818) 886-4021. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
