<HEADLINE>
NEW GADGETS AND SITES: PORTABLE FAX AND COPIER; JEFFERSON'S PAPERS
ONLINE; VIDEO GLASSES; TUPPERWARE ONLINE AND CORBIS ADDS MORE
IMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an age when gadgets let e-mail and the Web follow people
virtually everywhere, a portable fax machine and photocopier seems
like a quaint idea. But Dave Faulkner, product manager for Thomson
Multimedia, says business travelers are still addicted to paper. By
his calculations, at least, it's a costly habit. ``Most hotel
chains throughout the U.S. charge quite a bit of money to make
photocopies or send faxes,'' he said. ``It's a premium service.''
</P>
<P>
   The RCA Docuport, made by Thomson, is a way for business
travelers to bring the fax and photocopier along for the trip, and
it adds a scanner for good measure. With a thickness of just 1\
inches when folded and a length of 12 inches, the device should fit
into most briefcases or laptop cases. It contains a rechargeable
battery and also runs from standard wall outlets.
</P>
<P>
   The $299 portable office, however, does have some compromises.
At two and a half pages a minute, it is not the world's fastest
copier, and a maximum resolution of 400 dots per inch does not make
it the sharpest. To avoid in-flight disasters involving leaking ink
or toner cartridges, the Docuport uses special (and more expensive)
thermal imaging paper. But Faulkner says the current generation of
thermal paper is not as glossy as the older type, is substantially
thicker, doesn't curl and will go five years without fading.
</P>
<P>
   PAPERS OF JEFFERSON CAN BE VIEWED ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   The Library of Congress is marking its bicentennial in part by
honoring Thomas Jefferson. Congress bought Jefferson's collection
of 6,487 books after the British burned the first Library of
Congress in 1814. (About two-thirds of Jefferson's books went up in
flames during another fire in 1851.)
</P>
<P>
   As one of its Jefferson projects, the Library has posted online
images of all its Jefferson papers, about 83,000 items, at
memory.loc.gov/ammem/mtjhtml/mtjhome.html.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said the library had the largest and most
comprehensive collection of Jefferson's papers. They are divided
into nine groups, including financial statements and drafts of the
Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   The legibility of the aging, handwritten documents ``varies
substantially,'' the library notes.
</P>
<P>
   The images can be downloaded, and some have modern text
transcriptions.
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO GAME GLASSES BLINK FOR YOU  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inveterate video game players now crave the kind of hard-edged
realism you can find only by sitting in your parents' basement,
staring at a monitor. Elsa Technologies has tried to introduce
another dimension into the video game experience with the 3-D
Revelator. The glasses use LCD shutters that open and close over
alternating eyes 120 times per second. That creates the mental
effect of seeing the video image from two angles. (If you look at
the 3-D image without using the glasses, it will appear slightly
out of register.)
</P>
<P>
   The 3-D Revelator works only with games that use the DirectX
platform. The glasses also require an nVidia graphics card and a
monitor that refreshes at least 100 times each second. The company
sells two models of the Revelator, a pair with wires that sells for
$55 and a wireless version, useful for when you get dizzy and fall
out of your chair, for $75. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUYING TUPPERWARE ONLINE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do you covet a Tupperware Egg-ceptional Server set (``a stylish
server for deviled eggs and more'') but can't bear the thought of
sitting through an actual Tupperware party to buy one? Tupperware
now has a Web buying option. With a new service called
My.Tupperware.com, you can do business with your neighborhood
Tupperware representative while keeping your evenings free.
</P>
<P>
   At the company's new site, 75,000 U.S. sales representatives can
create personal home pages using preformatted designs. Besides
listing Tupperware parties and Tupperware bingos, the personal
pages can include Tupperware testimonials and recipes. If users
click through from the personal home pages to shop on Tupperware's
corporate e-commerce site, the sales representative receives the
usual 20 percent commission on everything they buy.
</P>
<P>
   Tupperware is not giving up on its usual sales method. ``We're
not looking to replace the party with anything else,'' said
Christine Hanneman, the company's vice president for financial
relations and treasury. ``We're looking to enhance it.''  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   CORBIS' ARCHIVE OF IMAGES WILL ADD CHRISTIE'S IMAGES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Corbis, the image archive company owned by Bill Gates,
Microsoft's chairman, is adding to its collection yet again. The
company announced Thursday that it planned to put online thousands
of digital images owned by Christie's, the art auction house.
</P>
<P>
   The Christie's images include all the works that have been sold
through the auction house in the last 20 years: more than 500,000
transparencies, ranging from Asian and African art to Old Master
paintings, and from modern and contemporary art to Hollywood
memorabilia. The non-exclusive licensing arrangement between the
two firms will provide Corbis' customers with a selection of those
images via www.corbis.com.
</P>
<P>
   Corbis, based in Seattle, already owns and licenses 65 million
images, including the Bettman Archive. Last June, the company
acquired Sygma, one of the world's largest news photography
agencies. Nonexclusive licensing agreements like the one announced
Thursday with Christie's already exist with the Ansel Adams
Publishing Rights Trust, the National Gallery of London and the
Hermitage in St. Petersburg. To date, Corbis has put some 2.1
million images online, which it sells to publishers and consumers
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
