<HEADER>
A4695 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-STARS-TE     05-03 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO HITCHCOCK TIRADES AFTER STARS' GAME 3 LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ To even remotely understand Ken Hitchcock,
and most of us are in that remote category, you first have to try
and understand Hitchisms. Take yesterday, as the Stars' coach was
describing the Game 3 loss to the Sharkies from the evening before.
</P>
<P>
   ``In desperate areas, they were a little stronger than we
were,'' he said, calmly, with an emphasis on calmly.
</P>
<P>
   Translation:
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the coach was mostly satisfied with his team's effort
and performance, much more so by the way, than the Game 2 win by
the Stars on Reunion ice.
</P>
<P>
   See there. Hitchcock doesn't just go off on his tirades, and go
off on his team, without what he considers valid reasons. The
definition of ``valid,'' however, has been and will be a continuing
debate between players and head coach.
</P>
<P>
   It is OK for the Stars to lose a game _ that's a game, not the
series _ because the other team got something special going and
deserved to win. The Sharks' ``something special'' on Tuesday night
applied to the feisty Owen Nolan, who raised his right hand and
once again repeated the Playoff Oath of Hockey:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am injured, but I am not hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being ``out for the series'' with various ailments,
Nolan's inspirational play, along with his toughness and his
game-winning goal, kept San Jose alive. The Sharks are down two
games to one as the wait for tomorrow night's Game 4 continues.
</P>
<P>
   The other reason San Jose rescued hope on Tuesday evening was
Steve Shields, who frankly played bigger and better in goal than
his resume indicates.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Stars still have this conference semifinals
series right where they want it, and the only thing which could
change that would be a home-ice loss. The best player, by far, is
still Mike Modano, who also appears to be emerging as the league's
best player in the postseason. The best goalie, by far, is still
Eddie Belfour. And frankly, if there's any lingering negative
attached to the Game 3 loss, it's that the Stars felt jilted by
referees Don Van Massenhoven and Mark Faucette.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the second-period penalty situation for the Stars did
appear a tad fishy. And Mike Ricci's goal, tying the game for San
Jose, did come after Ricci let his hair down on Belfour in the
crease. A two-man advantage for the Sharks was nearly out of time
when Ricci hacked Belfour and then tipped in a shot from the point.
That one steamed the Stars, and Hitchcock still had to do some
tongue biting yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty that set up the five-on-three for the Sharks came on
a well-done ``dive'' by Shields to draw a goalie-interference
whistle against Blake Sloan. Whatever works, huh?
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Stars were whistled for five penalties in the second
period, and wore down physically because kill units were on the ice
so much. In fact, it was almost 10 consecutive minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into \Rthe officiating\S because I've got
to have a summer vacation, and I don't want to be paying fines for
what I might say,'' said Hitchcock, who has never been a candidate
for the Lindy Ruff Whine Award among NHL coaches. Because of this,
those of us who thought the Stars were simply outplayed in Game 3
felt obligated to lend an ear.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Hitchcock referred to the second-period penalty binge as
a ``bizarre case,'' while also refusing to criticize his team for
undisciplined or retaliation tactics. ``If those had been involved,
which they weren't, you can take a stand on that,'' Hitchcock said.
``But the best way to say it is we played hard in the second
period, they played hard, and we got caught.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had dominated in the first period in all areas, and
had a 1-0 lead after the opening 20 minutes. ``The idea was to come
out and build immediately on that, but there was no opportunity
because we had to kill penalties for the first 10 minutes,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   There had also been a first-period scene when Bryan Marchment
performed his speciality _ a cheap-shot hit, this time on Stars
rookie Roman Lyashenko. Marchment drew a penalty, but the power
play for Dallas was nullified as Scott Thornton skated hard at
Marchment after the whistle, and belted him with a high stick. ``I
didn't mind that at all,'' said Hitchcock, who usually does. `'It
was part of the game at that particular moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The grumbling over Van Massenhoven and Faucette was amplified
because those two had worked Game 3 in Edmonton, and the Stars,
despite a poor early effort in that one, had many of the same
complaints as Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But let's be honest. None of this stuff really matters,
particularly since Shields had far more to do with the Sharks'
winning than whistle-happy refs. And even with a loss, if the
referees are all the Stars have to gripe about, then their on-ice
game was basically where it needed to be, and in this series' long
run, that's all that's necessary to move on to the next round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
