<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4698 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-OLD-MURDER-HNS &LR;      05-03 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-MURDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE AFTER 20 YEARS FOR WOMAN'S MURDERER IN HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE BREWER 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A murderous impulse on a Houston freeway almost 20
years killed a divorced mother of two. On Wednesday, justice caught
up to her killer.
</P>
<P>
   Francis F. Pelkey, 46, remained expressionless as he was
sentenced to 40 years in prison for the Aug. 13, 1980, murder of
Nell Johnson, a 36-year-old hospital inspector whose bizarre
shooting remained unsolved while her children grew up waiting for a
day in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally,'' said an emotional Doug Johnson, 28, who was 8 when
his mother died. ``It's a lot easier to breathe now.''
</P>
<P>
   His sister, Laura, now 31, shared her brother's bittersweet
feelings about Pelkey's sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he's finally being held accountable for his
actions,'' she said. ``It helps with some closure, I think. But we
still miss her.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelkey's sentence will keep him in prison for at least 13 years
before he's eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
   Pelkey, a diesel mechanic with no criminal record, was the prime
suspect in the murder 20 years ago. But the case was thin and he
wasn't charged.
</P>
<P>
   Pelkey eventually left Houston. About 16 years ago, he and his
wife and their three children moved to Sacramento, Calif., where he
bought a $130,000 house with a pool and lived a law-abiding,
church-going life.
</P>
<P>
   But that came crashing down in April 1999 when a grand jury
indicted him for murder, following the work of the Harris County
Sheriff's Department ``cold case squad'' and two detectives who
thought Pelkey had gotten away with murder for too long.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran homicide detectives Harry Fikaris and Roger Wedgeworth
were assigned to the special squad in May 1998, when a reduction in
the crime rate allowed more time for fresh looks at old cases.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's was one of the first cases they examined.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some hope that new DNA evidence could be found, it
wasn't, and the detectives were left with the evidence they had
before _ Pelkey's odd statement to police after Johnson's
bullet-riddled body was found five miles from her car in a wooded
area in north Harris County.
</P>
<P>
   But the detectives found what they needed in the statement and,
because of a change in evidence rules on the admissibility of such
statements, they took the case to prosecutor Steve Baldassano.
</P>
<P>
   According to testimony and evidence, the day after Johnson's
body was found, Pelkey called police and told them an intricate
story about an encounter with her.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was on his way to work early on Aug. 13, 1980, when
he stopped to help her fix a flat on Interstate 45. He said he got
back into his van to leave and that his vehicle wouldn't start.
</P>
<P>
   Pelkey said he honked his horn to stop Johnson from driving off
and that she gave him a ride to his home so he could get his tools.
He said they returned to his van on the side of the busy freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Pelkey claimed he was fixing his van and that Johnson was
sitting inside of it when two armed robbers approached. One of the
robbers, he said, reached inside the van, got Pelkey's own
.22-caliber pistol and shot Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Pelkey told police the killers then took his cap and shirt and
that one of them drove off in his van with Johnson's body and his
gun, while the other held him at gunpoint in their truck.
</P>
<P>
   He said the other killer returned, without Johnson, and returned
his cap, shirt and gun to him.
</P>
<P>
   Pelkey contended the robbers then threatened to kill him if he
talked, and they left in their truck.
</P>
<P>
   And just as authorities had 20 years ago, Baldassano and the
detectives thought Pelkey's story was ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   But going over old interviews, Fikaris and Wedgeworth found
there was part of Pelkey's statement that wasn't included in the
official reports.
</P>
<P>
   When police in 1980 had expressed disbelief at Pelkey's story,
he said: ``I'll tell you what really happened.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Pelkey's wife, Sharon, shut him up and he talked
no further. Years later, when he was arrested in California, he
refused to talk and so did his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Pelkey declined to talk to the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   But the detectives and Baldassano had what they needed.
</P>
<P>
   In Pelkey's statement, he admits to going home after the
mysterious robbers left so he could clean his clothes, his van and
his gun.
</P>
<P>
   His description of a gunman matched his own appearance, even
down to the color of the pants he was wearing, something Baldassano
said must have been concocted so Pelkey could cover being seen with
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   And no one saw the truck the alleged robbers were driving. The
only vehicles spotted were Pelkey's and Johnson's.
</P>
<P>
   Throw into the mix two more things _ Pelkey said Johnson was
about to drive off after he fixed her flat. But when her car was
found the hood was up. Baldassano said it was unlikely Johnson was
going to drive off with her hood raised.
</P>
<P>
   Pelkey also mentioned honking at Johnson. But Baldassano
wondered how that horn could work since Pelkey had said he was
working on his van's failing battery.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the bite mark on Pelkey's left arm that was visible
when he was questioned in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   An expert testified at trial that the bite appeared to be
consistent with a human bite made by someone whose mouth was the
same shape as Johnson's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's got to live free for 20 years,'' Fikaris said
Wednesday. ``He got to raise his family, but there's no doubt in my
mind, or Roger's mind, that he absolutely did this.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite arguments by defense attorney Don Rogers that the
state's case was weak and lacked physical evidence, jurors thought
the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   But the question remained _ why would a married father on his
way to work, who never had been in trouble with the law, kill a
woman for no reason?
</P>
<P>
   Baldassano told jurors no one will ever know.
</P>
<P>
   But he theorized that Pelkey had made a sexual advance on
Johnson in his van.
</P>
<P>
   She fought and bit him, Pelkey got mad, and things spiraled out
of control, said Baldassano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think things just got out of control in incremental steps
and he just sort of overreacted,'' Baldassano said. ``I think this
was a crime of opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Jim Wallace said the case sends a message
to criminals who think they've gotten away with something.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said the saying, ``Justice delayed is justice denied''
doesn't apply in this case because Pelkey was caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice has now been achieved for Nell Johnson,'' said
Wallace, who added that criminals who are free should now shudder
when they hear a knock on the door, whether it's the next day or
the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Wedgeworth agreed and now he and his partner say this case will
drive them as they dig into more unsolved murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw Nell Johnson's family stand shoulder-to-shoulder and
watch the cuffs be put on (Pelkey),'' Wedgeworth said. ``They had
waited for that and that picture will stay in my mind always.
That's going to motivate me.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
