<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4700 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GERMANY-EXCHANGE-ART-     05-03 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-EXCHANGE-ART-665(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DEUTSCHE BORSE AND ITS CHIEF ARE CALLING THE SHOTS IN EXCHANGE
MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (with GERMANY-BRITAIN-MARKETS)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The remark would normally provoke little
notice. But coming from Werner G. Seifert, chief executive of
Germany's stock exchange, it was startling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason why we have to be headquartered in
Frankfurt,'' Seifert mused at a dinner in late January. ``I could
imagine myself living in London. Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Seifert announced that he will indeed be moving to
London. In a stunning coup, Deutsche Borse confirmed that it will
merge with the London Stock Exchange and that Seifert will be chief
executive of the new company.
</P>
<P>
   It is the most dramatic step yet toward creating a pan-European
securities market, uniting Europe's two biggest exchanges into a
single corporation that would be nearly twice as big as the next
contender_ the recently announced merger of the Paris, Amsterdam
and Brussels exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   In also announcing an alliance with Nasdaq, the new exchange
could become the European anchor for a global system available 24
hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   But the most remarkable aspect of the deal may be the extent to
which Seifert and his once-sleepy stock exchange are calling the
shots. Even now, the London Stock Exchange is nearly twice as big
as the Frankfurt bourse in terms of stock trading and London's
financial district is by far Europe's biggest center for investment
banking and trading.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that a Frankfurt executive might suddenly be in charge
would until very recently have seemed absurd. Frankfurt is city of
bankers more than traders, a quiet burg compared to London with its
thousands of brokers, traders, analysts, dealmakers, information
merchants and back-office workers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Seifert has turned the old order upside-down. Not only will
he be chief executive of the new exchange, to be called iX (short
for international exchanges and pronounced eye-ex''), but London
will give up its own electronic trading system in favor of
Frankfurt's XETRA system.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this new clout stems from Seifert, an iconoclastic
management consultant who is also a passionate jazz musician and
gourmet.
</P>
<P>
   More than any of his counterparts in London or Paris, according
to executives at big financial institutions, Seifert redefined the
basic mission of an exchange and then charged ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main difference that has given Deutsche Borse its power
has been the strength of its management,'' said a senior executive
at a large financial institution. ``The other exchange executives
have been slow to make changes, wedded to doing things by consensus
and avoiding conflicts. Seifert has had a clear idea of what he
wanted, and he went after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Seifert merged Frankfurt's market for futures and
options with that of its Swiss competitor to form Eurex. Last year,
Eurex became the world's biggest derivatives market, eclipsing not
only London's LIFFE but also the Chicago Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert also oversaw the launch of Frankfurt's Neue Markt, a
three-year-old exchange for younger technology companies like those
traded on NASDAQ. Until then, new companies had little chance of
going public in Germany or in most other European countries.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many European exchanges have their own ``new markets.''
But none has grown as explosively as Frankfurt's, which now handles
80 percent of such trading in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Seifert built up XETRA, the Deutsche
Borse's electronic trading system. . Besides running Germany's own
exchanges, XETRA runs Vienna's stock exchange and is being adapted
for exchanges in Helsinki and Dublin. The Chicago Board of Trade is
launching a collaborative electronic platform with Deutsche Borse
that will be based on XETRA as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business isn't really trading in stocks or bonds,''
Seifert, 50, remarked recently. ``Our fundamental business is
building systems, loading systems and operating systems.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thanks in large part to Deutsche Borse's stake in Eurex,
Deutsche Borse earned 124 million euros ($112 million) last year on
revenues of 643 million euros (about $585 million). London, by
contrast, had profits of $41.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the talks say Seifert's ambitions have sometimes
angered rivals. When negotiations with the London officials
surfaced several weeks ago, Seifert was demanding that the
shareholders in Deutsche Borse _ which are mainly Germany's big
banks _ get 60 percent of the merged company.
</P>
<P>
   The specter of an outright takeover angered many members of the
London exchange and Seifert backpeddled. About one week ago, the
two sides agreed to a 50-50 merger by keeping Deutsche Borse's
clearing and settlement business out of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   But all exchanges have been facing a common reality: a mounting
unwillingness among big financial institutions to tolerate the high
costs that arise from trading over fragmented national exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges have negotiated over alliances for years, but the
talks always broke down amid disputes over control and over which
system would be scrapped and which would become a common platform.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert was among the first to become impatient with the
meandering negotiations. With backing from Deutsche Bank, the
biggest shareholder in Deutsche Borse, Seifert shocked other
European exchanges by negotiating a two-way alliance with the
London Stock Exchange two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   News of that alliance outraged many of Seifert's counterparts,
particularly in Paris. In the months that followed, most of the
other exchanges announced their intentions to grudgingly join up
with the Anglo-German plan.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But those talks floundered as well, with the players unable to
agree on a common technology much less on a serious merger. Even
London and Frankfurt failed to agree on much beyond ``ground
rules'' for how a combined system could work.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the pressure from financial institutions was rising.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a number of the biggest institutions, including
Goldman Sachs, JP Morgan and Deutsche Bank, began investing in an
alternative electronic exchange called Tradepoint Financial
Network. Based in London, Tradepoint plans to list about 230
European stocks beginning in July.
</P>
<P>
   In another challenge, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter teamed up with
OM Gruppen AB of Sweden, which runs the Swedish stock exchange, to
develop an system called Jiway for trading about 6,000 European and
American stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Jiway is scheduled to start up in September.
</P>
<P>
   Still stung by what they viewed as Seifert's high-handed and
seemingly secretive attempts to cut his own deal with London,
exchange executives in Paris viewed him more as a rival than as a
potential ally.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several months, the Frankfurt and Paris stock
exchanges competed in proposing mergers with London. The logic was
straightforward: with markets moving toward pan-European trading,
supremacy would go to the exchange with the highest trading volume.
London, despite sluggishness in some areas, had far more volume
than any other European exchange.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of March, executives in London apparently decided
their best bet lay with Seifert. In response, the Paris, Amsterdam
and Brussels exchanges preemptively announced their own plan to
merge and form a single exchange called Euronext.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement in London sets the stage for a new
competition. But industry analysts caution that neither Seifert's
iX nor Euronext will complete their merger for months and it will
take even longer before they move their operations onto the same
trading system.
</P>
<P>
   Because different exchanges measure their trading volumes in
different ways, it is difficult to make direct comparisons. But
measured by the market capitalization of their listed stocks, the
London and Frankfurt stock exchanges have a combined value of about
$4.1 trillion _ nearly double the combined valuation of the
Euronext partners.
</P>
<P>
   If Seifert can truly unite the systems of London and Frankfurt,
the sheer size of the combined entity should give it trading
efficiencies that make it easy to draw business away from his
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert continues to push for new partners. He disclosed
Wednesday that he is already in talks with the Milan and Madrid
stock exchanges. Somewhat disingenously, he also insisted that he
was open to deeper collaboration with Euronext.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are open for all reasonable steps in the future and this
includes constructive discussions with Euronext and any other
exchange as long as it serves our customers,'' Seifert said in
London.
</P>
<P>
   But if the last three years have proven anything, it is that
announcing deals is much easier than actually carrying them off.
Even an Anglophile like Seifert may find it takes some time before
he can make a permanent move to London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
