<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEREST RATES MOVE UPWARD AS FED CITES WAGE GAINS
</HEADLINE>
  By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Interest rates shot higher Wednesday after the
Federal Reserve reported that wages are rising across the country
and investors wondered if that news would make the central bank
more aggressive in its effort to slow economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The report on economic conditions in Federal Reserve districts
around the country said that ``there were more frequent reports of
intensifying wage pressures as shortages of workers persisted in
all districts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed report also said economic growth was moderate to strong
across the country. That assessment was re-enforced by the report
that factory orders jumped a higher-than-expected 2.2 percent in
March.
</P>
<P>
   The new information on inflationary pressures comes after the
report of a surprisingly sharp jump in consumer prices, excluding
food and energy, in March and an increase in total worker
compensation in the first quarter. Together they have increased
speculation that the Federal Reserve may decide to raise its
short-term interest rate target by a half of a percentage point
when policy-makers meet May 16.
</P>
<P>
   William C.J. McDonough, the president of the Federal Reserve
Bank of New York, noted the rise in inflation in March in a speech
Wednesday and said ``we have to keep especially alert now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Treasury market, the investor concern was reflected in a
jump in the yield on the two-year note, which is sensitive to
expected policy moves by the Federal Reserve. The yield rose to
6.74 percent, from 6.68 percent Tuesday, and is the highest it has
been in five years. The price, which moves in the opposite
direction, fell 5/32, to 99 9/32.
</P>
<P>
   This was a sharp rise in the two-year yield given the fact that
the Treasury announced Wednesday that it will reduce its issuance
of two-year notes as part of its program to cut government
borrowing as the budget surplus grows. Such a cut in issuance
normally sparks buying.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the Treasury's 10-year note rose to 6.39 percent,
from 6.30 percent on Tuesday. The price fell 21/32, to 100 26/32.
The yield on the 30-year bond climbed to 6.11 percent from 6.01
percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Until now most forecasters thought the Fed would raise its
interest rate target just a quarter of a point, which would be the
sixth such move since June. That would bring the federal funds
rate, the overnight rate on loans between banks to 6.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Hoffman, chief economist at PNC Financial in Pittsburgh,
said if Fed policy-makers were meeting today, ``knowing what they
know today, they would probably go half a percentage point.''
</P>
<P>
   William Dudley, chief economist at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., didn't
want to predict the size of the next Fed move. But he did say that
the current strength of the economy and the new signs of
inflationary pressure will force the Fed to push interest rates
higher than he had thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to stake my reputation on predicting the May
move,'' he said. ``But I want to stress that the Fed has a lot more
work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday he raised his forecast for how high the Fed will have
to push the federal funds rate. Dudley is now predicting that it
will be up to 7 percent by the end of the year, a quarter of a
point higher, and at 7.5 percent in 12 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
