<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4705 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-GERMANY-BRITAIN-MARKE     05-03 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-BRITAIN-MARKETS-ART-420(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON AND FRANKFURT EXCHANGES PLAN TO MERGE AND LINK WITH NASDAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GERMANY-EXCHANGE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The London and Frankfurt stock exchanges on Wednesday
announced plans for a full merger and an alliance with New York's
technology-heavy Nasdaq stock market. The exchanges are hoping to
build a pan-European trading heavyweight and a 24-hour global
market in new-economy stocks _ both unthinkable only a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The combined exchange would be Europe's biggest by far and the
world's fourth largest.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement offered the most significant evidence to date
of a sea change in European markets. The shift has been driven by a
clamor among investors for less-expensive trading, a challenge from
Internet-based and electronic trading systems and a perception of
Europe as a single investment arena since the introduction of a
unified currency _ the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The development also showed how far Frankfurt has progressed in
its challenge to London as Europe's prime financial center.
</P>
<P>
   Just six weeks after the exchanges in Paris, Amsterdam and
Brussels announced a rival European combination called Euronext,
the London Stock Exchange and the Deutsche Borse said their merged
company_ called iX, for International Exchanges _ would have its
administrative headquarters in London and would carve European
markets into two parts. Blue-chip stocks would be listed in London,
while a combined market in high-growth technology stocks linked to
the Nasdaq would be run from Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   The Eurex market for derivatives _ complex financial contracts
based on stocks, bonds commodities and currencies _ _ would
continue to be run from Germany as part of the combined exchange,
effectively aiming to isolate London's LIFFE futures and options
market, which is not part of the alliances announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Zarb, the chief executive of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, the parent of Nasdaq, told a news conference
Wednesday that the opening of a Nasdaq subsidiary in Tokyo next
month would enable investors to connect with both European and U.S.
markets, offering ``a 24-hour clock for the high-growth
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   `'The markets will follow the sun for the biggest companies,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq alliance will bring together London's techMARK and
Germany's Neuer Markt as the core of a new high tech exchange.
Nasdaq and iX are to be equal shareholders in that venture, which
will be incorporated in London and operated from Frankfurt. Zarb
indicated that the deal had pre-empted Nasdaq's plans to set up a
separate European trading system.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The negotiations on a Frankfurt-London tie-up have been
progressing for almost two years since an alliance was first mooted
as the core of a proposed pan-European exchange. That has now
crystallized into the competing iX and Euronext markets. While the
Paris-dominated Euronext market will trade stocks valued at some
$2.2 trillion, iX will group equities with a combined value of $4.3
trillion.
</P>
<P>
   By way of contrast, the New York Stock Exchange trades shares
valued at $11.2 trillion, while NASDAQ`S equities are valued at
$6.3 trillion, and Tokyo's are about $4.5 trillion, according to
the International Federation of Stock Exchanges. In Europe, the new
exchange would clearly dominate, particularly since, it said
Wednesday, smaller bourses in Milan and Madrid, also want to join
the combination.
</P>
<P>
   Without those two exchanges, iX said it will control 53 per cent
of all European equity trading, 81 per cent of the market in
high-growth stocks and 56 per cent of the European derivatives
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first step to an integrated pan-European market,''
said Don Cruickshank, the newly-appointed chairman of the London
Stock Exchange, who will be chairman of iX. Cruickshank is expected
to hold talks with both LIFFE and Euronext on expanding the
Frankfurt-London axis.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Denton, a spokeswoman for LIFFE said the exchange would
not reject an approach from iX out of hand but felt its own
technology gave it a strong position. ``We do not see ourselves in
terms of being marginalized and left out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Euronext shrugged off the new combination, saying it proved ``we
took the right decision,'' according to Olivier Lefebvre, president
of Brussels Exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Werner Seifert, the chief executive of Deutsche Borse AG which
owns the Frankfurt exchange, will be the chairman of iX, ousting
Gavin Casey, chief executive of the London exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will be owned 50-50 by the London and Frankfurt
exchanges, and will eventually use Germany's Xetra technology for
all cash transactions. Participants said the merger will be
completed by the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``What belongs together finally comes together,'' Seifert said.
``London is the largest cash market in Europe and we bring in the
largest derivatives market worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   The management line-up reflects both the national sensitivities
underlying the merger and the increasing muscle of Frankfurt at the
heart of the 11-nation euro-zone, of which Britain is not a member.
</P>
<P>
   With 200 years of history behind it, coupled with its role as
the biggest of Europe's stock markets and its reputation as
Europe's financial capital, London would once have regarded itself
automatically as the senior partner. But Frankfurt's fast-growing
and technologically-advanced exchange earns more as a business than
the London Stock Exchange, boosting its ambitions to displace
London as Europe's financial hub.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this transaction a blow to the ambitions of finance center
Germany? The answer is: no,'' said Rolf Breuer, the chairman of
Deutsche Borse, who is also chief executive of Deutsche Bank.
Indeed, some British bankers said the merger represented a German
take-over because of the use of German technology and the
appointment of Mr Seifert as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly bad for London and good for Frankfurt,'' said
a senior investment banker, who spoke in return for anonymity.
``What's most notable is that high growth and new companies will be
listed in Frankfurt. So Frankfurt is going to become the new
economy center of Europe and London will be all old economy.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the differing ownership structures of the London
and Frankfurt exchanges meant that shareholdings in the merged
company would be heavily weighted towards the big German banks that
dominate the Deutsche Borse. Ownership of the London Stock Exchange
is shared by over 290 members who voted earlier this year to
demutualize, while ownership of the Deutsche Borse is much more
restricted. Seifert said the iX exchange's long-term goal was to go
public with an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Others said the move was inevitable considering the changing
profile of the market-place.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Marks, executive chairman of Merrill Lynch Europe,
Middle East and Africa called the merger and tie-in with the Nasdaq
exchange ``a significant step forward in the creation of a broader,
deeper, more liquid marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The investors have moved on and they want one stock market to
reflect that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the German and British governments welcomed the deal and
the European Union said the merger was unlikely to encounter
regulatory hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   The participants made their announcement Wednesday with more
emphasis on grand visions than detail. It remained unclear, for
instance, precisely when and at what cost Germany's Xetra
technology would be rolled out for British investors, or what
savings would accrue to investors. Seifert said the conversion
should be possible some time in the first six months of 2001.
London traders work on the SETS system and `'people are going to
face conversion costs that have not been spelled out,'' said one
trader.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the number of possible layoffs was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's position outside the euro-zone also meant that
London-listed blue-chips, including such giants as BP Amoco and
DaimlerChrysler, would be quoted in both euros and sterling. Some
bankers expressed concerns about the likely costs of clearing and
settlement in the merged market.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Borse owns 50 per cent of the Luxembourg-based
Clearstream settlement system, which is not included in the merger.
Clearstream said Wednesday that it was in talks with CrestCo
Limited of Britain. Both companies will provide settlement services
to the merged exchange, but a Clearstream spokesman said a merger
between them was ``quite a long way down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the impetus for the deal came from the rapid pace of
events beyond the control of traditional bourses, notably the
proliferation of smaller and more nimble electronic trading systems
such as Tradepoint in Britain. Tradepoint, which is supported by
big U.S. and European banks, plans to launch a pan-European trading
system in July and says it will offer investors lower costs.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge presented by such organizations emerged anew
Wednesday when Breuer, the Deutsche Bank chief executive, was asked
whether his organization would withdraw from Tradepoint in favor of
iX. His answer was less than a ringing endorsement for the merged
exchanges. ``Both systems have still to show whether they'll
perform,'' he said. `'So let's wait and see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
