<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-SATELLITE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SATELLITE IN ORBIT FOR HURRICANE SEASON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ A $220 million satellite hurtled into Earth orbit
early Wednesday, giving the National Weather Service a new
surveillance tool for the upcoming hurricane season.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th Geostationary Operational Environmental Satellite, or
GOES-11, soared from Cape Canaveral Air Force Station, Fla., at
3:07 a.m. EDT, aboard a commercial Atlas IIA rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Following 90 days of maneuvers to raise its orbital altitude and
for instrument checkouts, the spacecraft is slated to become a
ready backup for one of two similar, but aging sentries that now
monitor tropical and severe storm development over the U.S.
Atlantic and Pacific coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane season for the Atlantic and Gulf coasts begins June 1.
</P>
<P>
   The urgency of Wednesday's launch was apparent last Friday when
NASA decided to postpone liftoff of the shuttle Atlantis until May
18 in order to proceed with the GOES-11 launching.
</P>
<P>
   The GOES launch is more than a year behind schedule. The mission
was slowed by problems last May with a rocket engine in an advanced
Delta commercial rocket. The Atlas IIA is powered by a similar
engine.
</P>
<P>
   The GOES-8 weather satellite launched in April 1994 is
monitoring tropical storm development over the Atlantic. Though
functioning, the spacecraft has surpassed its five-year design
life.
</P>
<P>
   The GOES-10 spacecraft launched in April 1997 is monitoring
Pacific storm development.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday's launch, both were backed up by the GOES-9
satellite launched in May 1995. But that spacecraft has lost the
use of its principal Earth-imaging system because of a problem with
the satellite's electronic control system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's vitally important we have a continuity of data or we may
find ourselves impaired in our capability to forecast,'' said
NOAA's William Proenza, southern region director for the National
Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   The imagery furnished by the GOES satellite series is a staple
of television weather broadcasts. In addition to monitoring
hurricane development, the GOES spacecraft are used
around-the-clock to warn of tornado and flash flood development.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
