<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4719 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KENT0504-COX     05-03 1598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENT0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-commander speaks for the guard
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In Charles Fassinger's corner office near Miami
International Airport, walls are covered with plaques and
certificates chronicling his long career in the military and the
national guard. Fassinger said he was most moved by one that reads,
``To a squadron commander who took more than his share of blame and
less than his share of credit. We remember. We were there.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, Fassinger was the highest-ranking Ohio
National Guard officer at a place called Kent State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had anybody in a long, long time, say, 'You dirty
bastard-murderer-killer,' '' Fassinger says.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges the 13 seconds of violence at 12:24 p.m. on May
4, 1970 that sparked outrage across a divided nation. He doesn't
sugarcoat the fact that guardsmen fired more than 60 bullets,
striking 13 people and killing four: He says it was a tragedy for
everyone. But he also believes that for decades the men who opened
fire that day have been unfairly characterized as murderous goons
who leaped from their trucks ready to get them some hippies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt somebody had to talk for the guard. I felt as
commander, that was my job. And I continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   He's recited the points many times so he's very clear on them:
The idea of guardsmen deliberately opening fire without provocation
``is absolutely crazy.'' There was no conspiracy. Most protestors
were not combative, but some were. The guardsmen were in danger,
and if they weren't, they believed they were. And no one gave an
order to fire.
</P>
<P>
   He knows people feel differently. Alan Canfora, shot in the
hand, recently responded to a reporter's e-mail about Fassinger by
calling him a ``ghoulish bastard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't like me much,'' Fassinger said. ``He's one of those
you can't talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Fassinger got a Christmas card in the mail.
It had been signed ``Allison Krause,'' the name of one of the four
dead students.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, he's received notes from people
complaining about the guard being lousy shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes me just as sick to my stomach: 'You should have
given them better training. They should have got more.' ``
</P>
<P>
   He said he took heat at the 20th anniversary in 1990 when he
said it was wrong that the guard was there at all; he says he meant
it was a tragedy that things escalated to that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did armed anybody, whether police, guard or army, find
themselves in a position where they had to face unarmed civilians,
students or anything else? That circumstance made everybody a
loser. Everyone took that that the Guard shouldn't have been there.
They should have been there. They would be there today if the same
thing happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassinger was there when a grand jury indicted two guardsmen,
then when charges were dismissed. He was there when eight of the 27
guardsmen who fired were criminally charged with violating the
civil rights of the dead and injured, then when a federal judge
threw the case out. He was there when Canfora and another injured
student sued the National Guard, the college and the governor;
Canfora won $15,000 and the other $22,500 in a settlement. By 1978,
the wounded and families of the dead would receive a total of
$675,000 from the state of Ohio and a signed acknowledgment by Gov.
James Rhodes and the 27 guardsmen that the shootings should not
have occurred. Fassinger knows a presidential commission called the
shootings ``unnecessary, unwarranted and inexcusable.'' He says no
one interviewed him.
</P>
<P>
   Fassinger, for years an executive of a suburban Cleveland
welding supply dealership and a board member of the trade group
American Welding Society, was invited in 1991 to come to Miami to
work for the associations. The children were grown and Florida's
sunshine was enticing, so he came, buying the home of former
Baltimore Orioles manager Earl Weaver near Pro Player Stadium in
northern Miami-Dade County. He's now its associate executive
director. He'll be 70 in August and enjoys being able to come to
work in casual slacks and shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Four days after his 16th birthday, in 1946, Fassinger lied about
his age and enlisted in the Ohio National Guard. He saw action in
Korea. And while his National Guard unit was never called, it was
eligible to go to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not have strong personal feelings about Vietnam one way
or the other, frankly,'' Fassinger said. ``The protestors, as a
group, they certainly had a right to protest.''
</P>
<P>
   While many protestors did so peacefully, by the beginning of
May, troublemakers _ Fassinger believes they constituted a tiny
minority of Vietnam opponents _ had trashed the tiny college town
of Kent, Ohio, about 40 miles southeast of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students were breaking windows, building bonfires, threatening
merchants,'' Fassinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Fassinger's unit of about 500 guardsmen was pulled from policing
a Teamsters strike in northeast Ohio and sent, along with several
other units, to Kent State. In all, about 700 converged on the
college town. Protestors had burned the ROTC building the night of
May 2. ``I don't know that I anticipated something bad happening,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The first few days, he said, the issue was Vietnam. Once troops
arrived, ``It was the guard. 'Guard off campus.' ''
</P>
<P>
   On the night of May 3 and the morning of May 4, Fassinger said,
authorities responding to bomb threats had searched dorm rooms and
found weapons; he said that bolsters his contention that guardsmen
who fired feared for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   By the afternoon of May 4, 2,000 to 3,000 students had gathered
for a noon rally that the university had banned. The guard ordered
them to disperse, then fired tear gas. Guardsmen said they were
greeted by deafening shouts and chants and some said they were
struck by rocks and other objects.
</P>
<P>
   ``When does it go from a crowd to a mob? That was the first time
I ever saw it happen. This was a mob.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Fassinger says, he heard a single shot from the ranks of
the guard. Then a pause. Then more shots.
</P>
<P>
   Guardsmen later said they fired because they heard others fire,
were surrounded on three sides by protestors, and were being
advanced upon. In some news articles, however, guardsmen who didn't
want to be identified were quoted as saying they fired
indiscriminately, then agreed on a version of events that would
justify the shooting; Fassinger says he never heard that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what was in the mind of the guys that pulled the
trigger,'' Fassinger said. ``I know what they said. I know what I
saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassinger said no one could have heard an order to fire had one
been given.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't hear anything,'' Fassinger said. ``People were
yelling. They (guardsmen) were wearing gas masks. We literally
reached over and grabbed them by the shoulder and yelled ``cease
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pure instinct. By the time I turned around, and we're talking
seconds, it appeared that the students at that point were reacting
to the firing of bullets, were leaving the area, were falling to
the ground and there didn't appear to be any further threat.''
</P>
<P>
   He says guardsmen stopped shooting ``instantaneously. Which
makes this panic thing difficult. If they'd panicked they'd have
kept shooting. Only a few fired all the rounds in their clip. A few
just fired once or twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Within moments, Fassinger said, he had the guardsmen line up and
march back down the hill. ``There was no running. No panic.'' He
said he tried to relax the guardsmen, told them to put weapons down
and said, 'You will not fire until specifically told to do so by
me.' `` Officers called for ambulances. Some students wouldn't let
them pass. An armored personnel carrier was needed to get the
ambulance crews in. ``Kids were shouting, 'Murderers. Kill the
guard.' I thought it would go totally out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   By that night, guardsmen knew people had died; ``We had one guy
who'd had a panic attack. One had a heart attack.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Thursday before all the guardsmen left Kent. Fassinger
was the last to go. He'd been so busy and so exhausted that it was
not until he got home that the immensity of the shootings sunk in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were characterized as murderers, killers, kid
killers, that sort of thing, and that was hard to take,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The passage of years allows for a lot of hindsight, spin and
myth-making. Some historians call the incident a turning point in
the nation's commitment to the war in Vietnam, saying most
Americans lost their stomach for the war after learning that
American soldiers had killed their own people. Fassinger doesn't
necessarily agree, noting the war lasted another five years, but
concedes that ``it was another incident that led people to where
they were going.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassinger believes bloodshed could have been avoided had his
troops been armed with the same equipment today's riot police use:
full body armor, face shields, riot batons, water cannon. ``My guys
and me were there in old army fatigues, World War II gas masks and
an M-1 rifle.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he was bothered when a memorial placed at the campus
didn't mention the guardsmen and they weren't invited.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guards were victims. The system was a victim. The citizens
were victims. There were lots of victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassinger said he doesn't stay in touch with fellow guardsmen.
And, no, they've never had a reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you do that?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
