A4723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-METAL-POPLIFE-TEAMS-N     05-03 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METAL-POPLIFE-TEAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT ON THE STREET, CYBER AND OTHERWISE
</HEADLINE>
   (With METAL-POPLIFE-ART) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brett Vapnek sits at the computer in his Beverly Hills office,
zooming in on a map of the United States filled with clusters of
black dots. Each dot represents a ZIP code inhabited by a youth
volunteer for the Streetwise Concepts and Culture street team, a
fan volunteer network that assembled over the Internet for
grass-roots promotion for new rock bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can zero in on the broadcast range for K-Rock, click a
button to send an e-mail, and get hundreds of kids to call the
station and request `Spiders' by System of a Down,'' Vapnek, the
company's vice president, explained.
</P>
<P>
   Look outside any new rock show, and chances are there will be a
couple of Streetwise kids toting cardboard boxes full of cassettes
of Slipknot, Papa Roach, Taproot or another band that Streetwise
represents. A slightly more sophisticated version of rap's street
promotion teams, Streetwise sends its volunteers tapes, stickers
and flyers to give to their friends or hand out in the street to
generate excitement about a band.
</P>
<P>
   The street team concept began for David Benveniste when he was
managing System of a Down. Benveniste, whom most people call Beno,
would hang out in Internet chat rooms and give teen-agers his home
phone number. When they called, Beno would play them System of a
Down's demo tape over the phone, then make a copy, wrap it in
Kleenex, and send it to the lucky or confused teen. Eventually, he
insisted that System's record label, Columbia, make him 30,000
advance cassettes; Streetwise began when the album's initial sales
surprised not just Columbia but the band itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I start at the bottom and work up,'' Beno said. ``I inject the
streets. There's no price you can put on word of mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   For Streetwise members, there is another benefit. ``Everybody's
always grateful when I give them free tapes,'' said Julian Trevino,
a college freshman, who was distributing Ultraspank cassettes
outside the San Antonio concert by Slipknot, a band that Trevino,
by the way, discovered when someone gave him a Streetwise cassette
sampler of the band.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
