A4726 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ALAMIN0504-COX     05-03 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMIN0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State expected to seek death penalty at Al-Amin's murder trial
 &HT;    By Jack Warner and Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The state will formally advise Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin
Thursday that it will seek his death in the killing of a Fulton
County sheriff's deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin gets his first hearing on the charges at 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Paul Howard refused to confirm in advance that
he will seek the death penalty against the former H. Rap Brown. But
prosecutors in Georgia invariably ask for the death penalty in
cases of suspected cop killers.
</P>
<P>
   David Kinchen, older brother of slain Deputy Ricky Kinchen,
confirmed late Wednesday, after members of the family met with
Howard, that the state will announce it is seeking the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the family concurs with Howard's decision,
David Kinchen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family is deeply religious, especially my mother, and while
there are some reservations and we are asking God to forgive us, we
want the death penalty,'' he said, speaking slowly and
deliberately.
</P>
<P>
   Kinchen, his mother, Erma Kinchen Brooks, two sisters and Ricky
Kinchen's widow, Sharese, spent about an hour talking to Howard at
his office Wednesday. ``More than anything, we want the right
person brought to trial,'' David Kinchen said. ``We were satisfied
pretty much by the facts the district attorney presented that Mr.
Al-Amin shot and killed my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Thomas Robinson is expected to act
for the state today, but Howard's spokesman, Erik Friedly,
indicated that Howard is considering joining the prosecution team
for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Little else but the death penalty announcement is expected to
happen at today's hearing before Fulton Superior Court Judge
Stephanie B. Manis. Al-Amin will not enter a plea.
</P>
<P>
   The one-time Black Panther is accused of killing Kinchen and
wounding Deputy Aldranon English when they tried to serve him with
a bench warrant on minor charges from Cobb County the night of
March 16.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin, the imam of a West End mosque, was arrested six days
later in White Hall, Ala. He waived extradition, was returned to
Atlanta April 21 and lodged in the Cobb County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
