<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PERSONALS: British Calendar Pin-Ups Storm America
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Four of the ladies of Rylstone, England, who raised more than a
half-million dollars for cancer research by selling the English
version of their nude calendar, were in the United States this week
to preside over the introduction of an 18-month American version
(Workman; $10.95).
</P>
<P>
   The Yorkshirewomen _ all middle-aged members of the Rylstone and
District Women's Institute _ began work on the project after
 &UR; Angela Baker &LR; 's husband,  &UR; John &LR; , died of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
(Profits from American sales of the calendar will be split between
the British Leukemia Research Fund and the Leukemia and Lymphoma
Society of the United States.) Their husbands didn't think they'd
really do it; their children were mostly grown. ``We'd got past the
stage of being embarrassed,'' said  &UR; Beryl &LR; 
 &UR; Mumford &LR; . ``It's a waste of time being embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lynda Logan &LR; 's photographer husband,  &UR; Terry &LR; , agreed that the
models would wear bathrobes while being posed; he'd set up the
camera then leave the room, whereupon the robes would drop and
Lynda would snap the picture. This unwieldy scheme lasted for three
shots, after which all agreed to drop their clothes and get on with
it.
</P>
<P>
   There was a general level of agreement on standards. ``We knew
we wouldn't have bottoms in,'' said  &UR; Tricia Stewart &LR; , ``but we
didn't mind some nipples showing.'' ( &UR; Rosie O'Donnell &LR; 's producers
apparently didn't agree; the ladies said the nipples had been
airbrushed from pictures shown when they were Rosie's guests last
week.)
</P>
<P>
   The ladies were surrounded by media from day one, which was the
announcement of the project at the sole pub in Rylstone, one of
their sponsors.  &UR; Glenda Jackson &LR;  sent her congratulations the next
day. The phones haven't stopped ringing since then, they say; in
addition to the American calendar, they've signed a movie deal with
a British company linked to Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there have been copycats. ``There have been some
terrible calendars,'' said Stewart, ``mainly men. There have been
fishermen and caravaners and people in mobile homes, and then the
butchers, `putting the beef back in Britain.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmmmm,'' said Mumford, ``the cricketers weren't bad.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Speaking of good deeds and clothing, or lack of it:
 &UR; Andrew Grimstad &LR; , secretary of the San Francisco Education Fund and
teacher at James Lick Middle School, hands out free ties to
students to wear to graduation, but he's out of them this year. If
you can contribute a newish tie, send it to  &UR; Andrew Grimstad &LR; , c/o
San Francisco Education Fund, 47 Kearny St., San Francisco, CA
94108.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WORDS AND MUSIC &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Soprano  &UR; Sylvia McNair &LR;  is touring the country singing music
written by  &UR; John Corigliano &LR;  to go with words of  &UR; Bob Dylan &LR;  songs,
including ``Mr. Tambourine Man'' and ``Blowin' in the Wind.''
Corigliano told Rolling Stone that he had never heard the original
songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends of mine found it bewildering, because they were so
used to the other versions. The point is, if a wonderful poem is
reset, it will have validity,'' said the composer.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Persuasions' 21st album, ``Frankly A Cappella, The
Persuasions Sing Zappa,'' includes 16 works by the late  &UR; Frank &LR; 
 &UR; Zappa &LR; . In 1969, Zappa signed the group to his label, Straight,
which produced their first album, ``A Cappella.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bad enough that motorists talk on cell phones;  &UR; Anne Hruska &LR; 
has seen two bicyclists in traffic with one hand on the handlebars,
the other holding a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Elliot Cahn &LR; , the lawyer who manages the Vacaville, Calif.,
band Papa Roach _ described as a ``hard dark band in the Limp
Bizkit vein'' _ and got them a deal with DreamWorks records, is a
former member of Sha-Na-Na.
</P>
<P>
   _ Preaching last weekend in Greensboro, N.C., disgraced
televangelist  &UR; Jim Bakker &LR;  spoke for 90 minutes on the evils of
talking too much.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Patti Itano &LR;  forwards a page from Trial magazine that
describes the arrest of a would-be robber in Biloxi, Miss. ``The
man called a casino and ordered employees to deliver $100,000 to
his home address within two hours or he would arrive at the casino
with guns blazing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the fun of being an actress is that you don't have to
do it all yourself, you know? Your publicist helps you; designers
give you free clothes to wear and borrow. Someone does your hair
and makeup. So it's like you're not alone and adrift.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Heather Graham &LR;  on the satisfactions of her career, in Allure
magazine
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4731 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     05-03 0788
