A4734 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CRIM-OBIT0504-COX     05-03 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIM-OBIT0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Educator's death shakes community
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming and Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Alonzo A. Crim was an outsider who brought calm and
academic focus to Atlanta's public schools during the 15 years that
followed the tumultuous desegregation agreement of 1973.
</P>
<P>
   As the city's first African-American school superintendent, he
set out to settle the political waters. Over the years, his focus
turned on educating the city's children, especially its poorest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this city yet knows what an impact Dr. Crim had
on the school system per se in resolving the racial difficulties
that desegregation had imposed,'' said Ozell Sutton, a U.S. Justice
Department official in Atlanta who worked with Crim to implement
the desegregation settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Crim, 71, was killed in a three-car accident early Wednesday,
about three blocks from the high school named for him after he
retired as superintendent in 1988. The flags at Crim High School
and at Atlanta's other 96 schools flew at half-staff out of respect
for the courtly, Harvard-educated Chicago native who guided the
system through difficult years.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Crim was driving in the wrong direction in a
reversible lane about 12:20 a.m. when he swerved to avoid hitting a
car, then collided with another. He died about an hour later at
Grady Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Fortier, 25, swerved to avoid hitting Crim, police said, but
Crim's black and white 1985 Mercedes Benz sideswiped her 1997 Ford
Taurus. Fortier's arms and legs were injured, but she was able to
get out of her vehicle and attempted to give Crim mouth-to-mouth
resuscitation after his car collided into a 1999 Volkswagen Passat
driven by Francis Treadway. Neither Treadway nor Fortier was
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Crim's death hit many Atlantans hard.
</P>
<P>
   Friends recalled how active he had remained in the cause of
education. In the days before he died, he was teaching Georgia
State University graduate students, helping find a facility for a
summer mentoring program and serving on the board of Cities in
Schools, an alternative program for would-be dropouts that he
helped start in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew him well said Crim was still grieving the loss of
Gwendolyn, his wife of 50 years, who died just two months ago. One
Hundred Black Men of Atlanta, a service organization in which Crim
was active, called a news conference to express their sadness and
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave us the confidence to know that we can make a
difference in the life of a child,'' said Terrell Slayton,
Georgia's assistant secretary of state and a 100 Black Men member.
``And to that, I say. 'Thank you, Lonzo Crim.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
