<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR INDEXES DECLINE BY MORE THAN 2 PERCENT ON RATE ANXIETIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices skidded Wednesday as investors absorbed
more troubling data on the rapid growth of the economy and braced
for more such disappointment Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The major market gauges fell more than 2 percent. The Dow Jones
industrial average lost ground for the fifth time in six sessions,
falling 250.99 points, or 2.34 percent, to 10,480.13. The Nasdaq
composite dropped 78.14 points, or 2.06 percent, to 3,707.31, while
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was off 31.19 points, or 2.16
percent, to 1,415.10.
</P>
<P>
   The worrisome evidence of economic strength showed up in a
government report that factory orders in March were higher than
expected, in a Federal Reserve survey showing ``intensifying wage
pressures'' and in comments by a top central bank official, William
McDonough, on economic imbalances and strains. Productivity figures
are to be released Thursday, and a crucial report on the labor
market is due Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Such data is seen as increasing the amount by which the Fed, at
a meeting on May 16, is likely to raise interest rates, for the
sixth time since last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's tremendous anxiety around the rate hike,'' said John
Peluso, a senior trader at Lehman Brothers. ``The market is more
and more perceiving a 50-basis-point rise coming down the pike.''
Almost nobody expects the Fed to leave rates alone, and those still
expecting a rise limited to 25 points, or one-quarter percentage
point, are now a clear minority.
</P>
<P>
   Another drag on the market Wednesday was a downgrading of
Wal-Mart and other retail shares by Goldman, Sachs, which said that
the national shopping spree was winding down as retailers faced
cost pressures. Wal-Mart, the biggest chain, sagged 4 3/16, to 53
7/16, and Sears, Roebuck fell 2|, to 36 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   If the Fed should misjudge the needed credit restraint, others
said, the economy could move quickly from too much growth to too
little.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy's extremely leveraged to the wealth effect,'' said
Timothy M. Ghriskey, senior portfolio manager at the Dreyfus Corp.
``If we see the stock market slow down, we think consumer spending
dries up pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   And stock values have shriveled, with the Nasdaq composite and
the Dow industrials each down 8.9 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   While a few food and beverage stocks resisted the latest
downturn _ Coca-Cola rose 2\, to 48{, the only Dow component to
gain as much as a point _ drugs and other so-called defensive
stocks mostly succumbed to moderate selling pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Technology was hit hard, with Novell down 6 15/16, to 10|, after
reporting poor earnings; Hewlett-Packard down 5 9/16, to 132{;
Cisco Systems down 1 15/16, to 66 1/16; and AT&AMP;T, downgraded by
PaineWebber, slumping for a second day. AT&AMP;T fell 2 3/16, to 39},
while its newly marketed wireless unit fell 13/16, to 31 7/16,
after reaching 36 on Monday. Microsoft, however, edged up 11/16, to
70 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, skidding 5 5/16, to 88 1/16, suffered from a
Lehman Brothers recommendation to switch from it to Ford, which
lost 7/16, to 52 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods, object of a bid late Tuesday by Unilever, jumped 10
11/16, to 61\. Disney fell 1\, to 41\, but reported
better-than-expected earnings for its second quarter after the
close of normal trading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
