<HEADER>
A4736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-03 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORWAY: 80,000 STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   More than 80,000 workers went on strike, disrupting
construction, printing, freight hauling, maritime transport, hotels
and restaurants, and sparking hoarding of consumer goods by people
fearing an extended walkout. The strike was called after members of
Norway's main umbrella trade union turned down wage and benefit
offers negotiated by their leaders with the employers' association.
No new talks are set.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: POLICE ADMIT GUILT
</P>
<P>
   London's police force admitted in the High Court that some
officers acted unlawfully when they confiscated flags and banners
and otherwise blocked pro-Tibet demonstrators protesting a visit
last October by President Jiang Zemin of China. The Free Tibet
Campaign accused them of particularly heavy-handed tactics as Jiang
rode in a carriage with Queen Elizabeth to Buckingham Palace. The
Tibet group agreed to accept the police admissions and drop its
legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   SWEDEN: DISCO TRIAL BEGINS
</P>
<P>
   Four men went on trial in Gothenburg on charges of setting a
fire in October 1998 that killed 63 young partygoers in an
overcrowded disco frequented by Eastern European immigrants.
Prosecutors said the Iranian-born men, ages 19 to 21, acted because
they were angry at having to pay $4.50 admission. They are charged
with deliberately setting a fire to cause injury or death, an act
punishable by up to eight years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: SLAVIC REUNION
</P>
<P>
   President-elect Vladimir Putin met with the leaders of Ukraine
and Belarus at a World War II battleground in western Russia, the
first time the three have met since the breakup of the Soviet
Union. Putin underscored the nations' Slavic heritage and
inaugurated a memorial to the Battle of Kursk, a huge tank battle.
``We are one family,'' Putin said. ``We have common historic roots,
a common fate, history, culture.'' But there are many divisions
among the three: Ukraine, for instance, is determined to stay
independent.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: PRI FINED
</P>
<P>
   Based on evidence that President Ernesto Zedillo's party, known
as the PRI, illegally siphoned at least $2.5 million from the
treasury of the northern state of Nuevo Leon, the autonomous
government agency that organizes elections in Nuevo Leon fined the
party $5 million. The PRI said it would appeal the decision.
Several party officials still face criminal prosecution in the
case. The state has been governed by the opposition National Action
Party since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: PEASANT PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   A protester was reported to have been killed in a clash with the
police after the Rural Landless Workers Movement, a radical peasant
group, occupied government buildings in more than a dozen states,
demanding that the government accelerate the distribution of land
to the poor and provide more credit to farmworkers.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: 3 HELD IN SHARIF CASE
</P>
<P>
   The police have arrested three activists from the Muttahida
Qaumi Movement in the March 10 slaying of Iqbal Raad, a lawyer who
had been representing the ousted Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in his
hijacking case. The movement's leaders immediately declared that
the charges were false.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: NEW SHAS CASE
</P>
<P>
   Aryeh Deri, the former leader of the Shas political party, who
was convicted last year of corruption for personally profiting from
his government jobs, went on trial in a separate case. He is
charged with ensuring that his party profited from his positions as
interior minister and deputy interior minister by directing money
to Shas institutions through local city governments. Deri pleaded
not guilty, although he does not dispute many of the facts, only
their interpretation as a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: U.S. ROLE GROWS
</P>
<P>
   American peace envoys began ratcheting up their involvement in
the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks as they directly took part in
final-status talks in Israel for the first time. In the Red Sea
city of Eilat, Dennis Ross, the lead envoy, said the two sides were
entering a ``new and intensive'' phase of deliberations that should
indicate, over the next six to eight weeks, whether a framework
agreement is possible.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: CALL FOR HELP
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing the need for urgent decisions, President Joaquim
Chissano presented a plan to international donors in Rome for
rebuilding his country, which was hit by devastating floods this
year. He appealed for $450 million to get the country back on its
feet. ``This help is required now and not tomorrow,'' he said. ``So
we appeal for generosity and urgency.''
</P>
</TEXT>
