u s BC-RAC-DERBY-NYT &LR;      05-03 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DERBY PICK IS ASSIGNED POST NO. 16 IN FIELD OF 20 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ A full field of 20 horses was entered Thursday
in the 126th Kentucky Derby on Saturday, with Fusaichi Pegasus
starting from the 16th stall in the outside auxiliary gate and
ranked as the 9-5 favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should keep him out of trouble,'' said Neil Drysdale, who
trains the star for the Japanese venture capitalist Fusai
Sekiguchi. ``The other spots give you a long time to stand in the
gate. So, why wait?''
</P>
<P>
   The second choice, The Deputy, trained by Jenine Sahadi, will
start from the 11th slot at 4-1. D. Wayne Lukas, who has won the
Derby four times, selected three positions near the outside: No. 13
for Commendable, No. 17 for Exchange Rate and No. 18 for High
Yield, winner of the Fountain of Youth Stakes and the Blue Grass
and the third choice for the Derby at 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   Outside post positions were favored for several of the most
highly rated horses in the Derby as part of an evolving strategy
for the mile-and-a-quarter race, since maximum fields of 20 tend to
create traffic jams near the rail that often determine the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the inside or rail position has produced the most
winners, 12 in all; the outside slots, the fewest. But even with
two starting gates in use, 14 horses starting in the main gate and
six in the auxiliary, trainers tend now to favor the less cluttered
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the last five runnings of the Derby have been won by
horses who started in the auxiliary gate. Last year, Charismatic
broke from the 16th slot and Menifee, who finished second, started
from No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time we won it,'' Lukas said, ``we had to agonize over
the draw. But we found that, more important than where you start,
is which horses start next to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Irwin, one of the owners of The Deputy, agreed. He
reported that once Fusaichi Pegasus had drawn the 16th spot, the
people directing strategy for The Deputy changed their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about taking No. 17,'' Irwin said, ``but instead of
getting next to a keg of dynamite. we decided to go inside of him
and took No. 11.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Pletcher, making his first appearance as a trainer in the
Derby, entered all four of his candidates and spread his post
positions this way: No. 6 for the undefeated speed horse Trippi,
No. 10 for More Than Ready, No. 14 for Graeme Hall and No. 15 for
Impeachment. He, too, admitted that some strategy had prompted his
picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``More Than Ready won't have to stand in the gate too long,'' he
said, ``and Graeme Hall has extra space because he's at the end of
the main gate and there's more room between that spot and the
auxiliary gate.''
</P>
<P>
   The draw was conducted in two tiers: First, an order of
selection was established by lot. Then, according to the order of
selection, post positions were chosen. The first pick went to Bob
Baffert, who has won the Derby twice in the last three years but
who has become a kind of lonesome man this year. He selected the
No. 8 stall in the center of the pack for his horse, Captain Steve,
who was made the fifth choice at early odds of 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   Pletcher, with his team of four starters, is a former assistant
to Lukas, who saddled five horses in the 1996 Derby and who won
with Charismatic last year. When Lukas was asked if he had any
advice for his onetime pupil, he replied with a straight face: ``I
told him it was a big job, and he should scratch three.''
</P>
<P>
   The full field meant there was no room for Unshaded, who won the
Lexington Stakes but was never nominated for the Kentucky Derby,
His trainer, Carl Nafzger, has been training the colt at Churchill
Downs in case the owner, James Tafel, was willing to put up the
supplemental fee of $150,000 to enter his horse, and if the field
fell short of the maximum of 20 horses, all of whom would get
preference. But when Ronton was confirmed as a starter, Unshaded
was blocked out.
</P>
<P>
   Another candidate who dropped out of the Derby was Harlan
Traveler, third in the Lexington and third in the Swale. The
decision was left to the colt's trainer, Ray Lawrence Jr., who
decided Wednesday morning that Harlan Traveler simply didn't have
enough seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm behind the 8-ball with him,'' Lawrence acknowledged. ``I
just don't have enough into him. This race is plenty tough if
you've got all your ducks lined up. But when you're trying to play
catch-up, it's just about impossible. I look at this race and I see
five or six horses I know we can't beat right now, so what are we
running for?''
</P>
<P>
   Harlan Traveler's defection opened a slot for Curule, a second
runner for the Godolphin stable from the Middle East, who will join
China Visit among the 20 starters. Curule has raced only four
times, all four in Dubai, with one victory. But the trainer, Saeed
bin Suroor, who saddled Worldly Manner in the Derby (seventh last
year), expressed satisfaction with both colts' workouts.
</P>
<P>
   China Visit held his final workout Wednesday morning, going five
furlongs in 1:01 2/5. Curule arrived Tuesday, cantered this morning
and will gallop up to the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The invaders are a continuing part of the strategy of Sheik
Mohammed al-Maktoum of Dubai to extend his racing empire
internationally.
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES
</P>
<P>
   The rider on China Visit will be Frankie Dettori, while the
jockey on Curule will be Marlon St. Julien. According to the
Churchill Downs records, St. Julien will be the first
African-American rider in the Derby since Henry King in 1921. St.
Julien comes from Louisiana, made his reputation at Texas tracks
and recently has had two smashing seasons at Keeneland. In the
early years of the Kentucky Derby, black jockeys predominated,
winning 15 of the first 28 runnings. And 13 of the 15 horses in the
inaugural Derby in 1875 were ridden by black jockeys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
