<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4739 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FAMILY-REUNION-THEATE     05-03 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-REUNION-THEATER-$ADV07-2takes-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WINTRY MUSIC OF T.S. ELIOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 7)  
 By BENEDICT NIGHTINGALE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ T.S. Eliot's ``Family Reunion'' has risen greatly in
critical esteem since it flopped like unleavened dough in the West
End 60-odd years ago. Many now regard the poet's story of the
English lord impelled by updated Furies to atone for his wife's
dark death as the nearest to a theatrical masterpiece Eliot ever
wrote. Even the more skeptical would probably agree that the play
is interesting as an experimental attempt to restore verse to
British drama, or at least as an indirect insight into its author's
own awful marriage.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers will doubtless make up their own minds when the
Royal Shakespeare Company's revival of the play opens at the
Brooklyn Academy of Music on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet an influential essay published in 1950 shows how close ``The
Family Reunion'' came to joining the bric-a-brac of history in the
theatrical junkyard. According to this, the play lacks dramatic
development. Its overabrupt conclusion comes ``after an
interminable amount of preparation.'' The mix of the mythic and
modern is awkward. The author tries to update ``The Oresteia,''
suggesting that the House of Monchensey is a British House of
Atreus poisoned to its roots by sins both recent and long ago, but
fails either to stick closely to Aeschylus or to venture far enough
away from him _ and so remains marooned in an artistic no man's
land.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, an attempt to transform the aunts and uncles in Lord
Monchensey's drawing room into a Greek chorus is woefully
unsuccessful. The Furies pursuing this troubled aristocrat are a
disaster, since in practice they look like uninvited guests from a
fancy dress ball or a swarming football team or a Disney cartoon or
half-visible shrubbery outside the window. And it's hard for the
audience to sympathize with a hero who renounces his mother, his
house and his heritage for the spiritual life, when he is plainly
an ``insufferable prig.''
</P>
<P>
   Why should we still listen to this contemptuous and possibly
contemptible diatribe? Well, because the critic with the long sword
was T.S. Eliot himself. He believed he had learned much about
stagecraft from the failure of ``The Family Reunion.'' Others might
say he had lost his nerve, had begun to prove it by writing the
fascinating but far less ambitious ``Cocktail Party'' and was about
to destroy the credibility of a renaissance of poetic drama in
Britain with a flimsy comedy called ``The Confidential Clerk.''
Subtler or slyer critics might add that ``The Family Reunion'' was
too close to the psychological bone for the self-effacing Eliot's
liking.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Monchensey returns to his ancestral home at least as
dejected as Eliot himself was in 1936, when he began to write ``The
Family Reunion.'' He has, he believes, been as guilty of
wife-murder as Orestes was of matricide. He has killed Lady
Monchensey by pushing her off an ocean liner. This naturally shocks
his family, who assume he is hallucinating, but the death itself is
a relief to all. The poor woman was a bitter if fragile neurotic,
jealous of her husband's friends and relations: ``A restless,
shivering painted shadow'' who wanted to bring Harry ``down to her
own level.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, she was very like Vivien Haigh-Wood, the
Englishwoman the 27-year-old Eliot dismayed his parents by marrying
in 1915. To the virginal young American newly arrived in Britain
she seemed glamorous and exciting, but beneath her surface vivacity
she was deeply troubled. To read Peter Ackroyd's biography of the
poet, ``T.S. Eliot,'' is like reading doctors' notes. Vivien
variously suffered from neuralgia, menstrual cramps, fainting fits,
malnutrition, ``catarrh of the intestines,'' septic influenza,
paralysis, hysteria, manic depression, panic attacks, paranoia and
obsessional behavior, meaning she constantly washed her hands. She
made Eliot as unhappy as he clearly made her.
</P>
<P>
   Tranquilizing drugs, mainly morphine and ether, seem to have
harmed rather than helped. Vivien became a possessive wife who
enjoyed embarrassing Eliot before his friends and encouraged him to
reject many of them. Conrad Aiken had a dinner with the two of them
at which, looking like a ``shivering, shuddering'' scarecrow, she
traded hate-filled tirades with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   When Edith Sitwell met her by chance in the street, Vivien
responded to her greeting with, ``No, no, you have mistaken me
again for that terrible woman who is so like me and is always
getting me into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   She told Virginia Woolf she kept hornets under her bed and then
accused her of having an affair with Eliot. She was rumored to
carry a knife in her handbag.
</P>
<P>
   It could not go on indefinitely, and it didn't. Vivien never
accepted that Eliot had left her, but he did just that when he took
a professorship at Harvard for the year 1932-33, asked his lawyers
to send her a Deed of Separation while he was in America and
refused to have anything to do with her after his return.
</P>
<P>
   There is little clear information about her later activities,
though it is known that she saw her husband's play ``Murder in the
Cathedral'' seven times in 1936 and was committed to a London
mental hospital in 1938. When Eliot heard she had died there in
1947, he buried his head in his hands, crying: ``Oh, God! Oh,
God!''
</P>
<P>
   Eliot said that the character in ``The Family Reunion'' most
like him was Harry's Uncle Charles, a genial Mayfair
man-about-town; but that is surely disingenuous or self-deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   There is doubtless substance in the skeptical portrait of the
poet, and the more sympathetic one of Vivien, that Michael Hastings
painted in his 1984 play and 1994 screenplay ``Tom and Viv.'' What
must it have been like to be married to such a man?
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s and '30s Eliot was more like the ``insufferable
prig'' himself, a remote, intellectually disdainful figure, who was
consumed with guilt at the antipathy he felt for his impossible
wife and who found a grim consolation for his misery in religion.
Eliot did not ``push'' Vivien into any sea, but then neither did
Harry, not literally. Harry probably watched as his wife went over
the rails, Eliot as she went off them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
