<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SAYS BUSH HAS `SECRET PLAN' TO PRIVATIZE SOCIAL SECURITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. _ Democratic presidential contender Al Gore
Wednesday accused George W. Bush and his advisers of hatching ``a
secret plan'' to privatize Social Security that would ruin the
retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president used an address before a New Jersey labor
group to underscore his differences with his Republican rival over
how to deal with Social Security's long-term solvency.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security, the tax-funded retirement and disability plan
established in the 1930s, is emerging as a key issue in this year's
presidential battle, with both sides staking out unambiguously
distinct positions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants to extend the life of Social Security, by pumping
more money into the system from the projected federal budget
surplus and savings from a reduced national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has embraced the concept of letting people invest in the
markets a portion of the payroll taxes now earmarked for Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   In his address Wednesday at this seaside gambling resort, Gore
was most critical of the Texas governor's intentions to keep all
but a general outline of his proposal out of public view before the
November election.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just smiles and goes on with the smug assumption that there
is no need to share with you the details of what he wants to do,''
Gore told members of the state AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   Gore repeatedly referred to Bush's Social Security proposal as
his ``secret plan'' _ evoking memories of Richard Nixon promising
voters during his 1968 presidential campaign that he had a ``secret
plan'' to end the war in Vietnam. Nixon won the election but lost
the war in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also touched on other issues, including his
support of legislation opposed by labor unions that would ease
trade with China.
</P>
<P>
   Gore acknowledged he differed with labor leaders on the China
bill, but said he believed it would increase American jobs. While
some in the audience said they disagreed with Gore on trade, they
were still supporting him, citing his other pro-labor stands and
their dislike of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president revamped his speech to stress Social Security
after news stories appeared this week reporting that Bush advisers
say the governor intends to step up his support of private
retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides have said, however, that the governor won't provide
details of how such a complicated plan would work until after the
November election. Bush has said he could better bring Democrats
and Republicans together on the issue after he was elected.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Reuters News Service Wednesday, Bush said,
``the fundamental issue is to convince both Republicans and
Democrats that now is the time to reform the system, that there's a
need for reform and that I am the president who will be willing to
spend the capital to get something done.'' He said that if elected
he would make private Social Security accounts one of his top
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Gore attacked such privatization plans as too risky, saying they
could destroy Social Security by allowing people to withdraw money
needed to pay benefits. With Bush's proposed large tax cut
siphoning off most of the surplus, Gore argued, there would not be
enough federal funds to make up any shortfalls in the retirement
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Social Security may be 65 years old this year, we're not
ready to retire it, no matter what George W. Bush and his advisers
say,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Karen Hughes attacked Gore's opposition
to private Social Security funds, saying that the vice president
has not been opposed to investing his own money in the markets.
Citing his financial disclosure forms, the campaign said that Gore
owns between $250,000 and $500,000 in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Aaron, a Social Security expert at the Brookings
Institution who opposes Social Security privatization, said Bush is
being politically smart by not revealing details of his plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were in Bush's shoes I would do just what he was doing.
If I were in Gore's shoes I wouldn't let him get away with it,''
Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that a detailed plan would raise numerous questions,
such as who would bear the most risk if the markets did not perform
as expected and how high administrative costs would be.
</P>
<P>
   The Brookings expert said the risk for Bush if he remains vague
is that Gore likely will continue doing what he did before the
labor group _ citing the various plans proposed by Bush's advisers
as examples of the governor's thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said Gore's strategy will be, ``You won't tell the
American public what your plan is. I'll tell the American public
what your plan is and it isn't very attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of those Bush advisers whom Gore singled out for
favoring Social Security privatization, Lawrence Lindsey, told
reporters this week that major changes must be made to the system
to ensure its long-term viability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kind of strengthening of the Social Security system must
be done, and Vice President Gore maintaining that the present
system is fine and if it ain't broke, don't fix it _ I really don't
know what planet he is on,'' Lindsey said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4741 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FAMILY-REUNION-THEATE     05-03 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-REUNION-THEATER-$ADV07-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
LONDON: went off them.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Creative cause and effect are always hard to pin down, but
nobody could claim that ``The Family Reunion'' is the work of a
contented man. The Furies are eventually revealed as the Eumenides,
or kindly ones, as they are in Aeschylus' ``Oresteia.'' But they
still require Harry to live a life of ascetic self-sacrifice. The
play's verse is as bleak as that of ``Burnt Norton,'' which Eliot
wrote in 1935 and eventually integrated into his book of poems
``Four Quartets.'' You can feel the dread in phrases like ``the
sobbing in the chimney, the evil in the dark closet''; ``the wind's
talk in the dry holly-tree''; ``the unspoken voice of sorrow in the
ancient bedroom at 3 o'clock in the morning.'' You can also hear
the poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot was not the only major writer who tried to help the
English theater recover its long-lost poetic prowess _ Shelley and
Browning had similar hopes _ but with him it became an obsession.
Again and again he argued that ``the human soul, in intense
emotion, strives to express itself in verse.'' Again and again he
debated ways of making colloquial dialogue and contemporary
conflict as poetic as they had been in the Jacobean era. As late as
1950 he was declaring that there were emotional and spiritual
aspects to life, ``which prose drama was wholly inadequate to
express.''
</P>
<P>
   But if we discount ``The Rock,'' a pageant about the building of
a church, Eliot's first serious attempt at verse drama was, by his
own admission, a ``dead end.'' ``Murder in the Cathedral'' remains
a memorable account of the martyrdom of Thomas a Becket; but it was
designed for special performance in Canterbury Cathedral and aimed
at those serious people who, as Eliot said, go to festivals and
``expect to have to put up with poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   What he wanted was to bring depth to the drawing rooms where
successful West End plays were invariably set and ask audiences to
listen to poetry ``from people dressed like ourselves, living in
houses and apartments like ours, and using telephones and motor
cars and radio sets.''
</P>
<P>
   With this aim in mind, he endlessly revised ``The Family
Reunion.'' According to Michael Redgrave, who played Harry after
Eliot rejected John Gielgud as ``not religious enough to understand
the character's motivation,'' the author sat uneasily aloof at
rehearsals but was always ready to adjust the text. He must, then,
have been shaken by the reviews that followed the play's opening in
March 1939. Virtually all the London critics found the play
literary, slow and abstruse, and they were hardly more sympathetic
when it received its first major revival in 1955, even though Peter
Brook was the director and Paul Scofield played Harry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Family Reunion'' fared no better in postwar Manhattan,
where it was staged first at the Cherry Lane Theater in 1947, then
on Broadway in 1958. Reviewing the second production in The New
York Times, Brooks Atkinson praised Lillian Gish for endowing the
wisest of Harry's aunts with spiritual strength but thought the
play ``a wordy drama about uninteresting people engaged in a
struggle that they are not eager to explain.'' The irony is that
well before this revival Eliot had come to agree with him.
</P>
<P>
   A bolder dramatist might have reacted to criticism by drawing on
his unique strengths and increasing his poetry's intensity. Eliot
did the opposite. ``The Cocktail Party,'' which appeared in 1949,
also involves a spiritual loner who rejects the humdrum world for
the religious life. She is far more sympathetic, humbler and warmer
than Harry, perhaps partly because Eliot had himself been thawed by
a second, much happier marriage. But the language has lost much of
its originality. In his own words, he had put the verse on such ``a
very thin diet'' that it was ``an open question whether there is
any poetry in the play at all.''
</P>
<P>
   His last two plays, which appeared in 1953 and 1958, not only
confirm that view but justify those who felt that, far from
transforming the West End, he had let the West End transform him.
He had chosen to tailor three-piece dramas in conventional gray
flannel. ``The Confidential Clerk,'' a comedy about a young man
with a religious vocation, was dismissed by one critic as ``a
repertory of West End gestures,'' and ``The Elder Statesman,'' in
which a politician confronts his past sins, was damned by another,
with a sneering reference to the father of drawing-room drama. It
was, wrote Kenneth Tynan, ``Pinero on stilts.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrival in London of John Osborne's ``Look Back in Anger''
in 1956 and the kitchen-sink drama that followed did even more
damage to Eliot's crusade. Christopher Fry, Ronald Duncan and
others who had helped him pioneer a poetic revival in Britain also
fell victim to the vogue for social realism. Yet that, in turn,
came to seem imaginatively limiting, and in 1979 Michael Elliott
staged a production of ``The Family Reunion'' in London that was
surprisingly well received. Reviewers who no longer demanded
consistency of style or tone seemed exhilarated by the
inventiveness of Eliot's language and chilled by Furies transmuted
into towering ghosts in white cowls.
</P>
<P>
   That was, as it happened, also the first time I had seen ``The
Family Reunion'' onstage, and I recall wishing to dig Eliot up and
give his skeleton a shaking. How could he have been so intimidated
by the conventional drama of his day? Yes, Harry is a bit of a
prig, but to a critic half-deadened by endless insular plays about
the British class system, Eliot's insistence that the man has a
soul to discover seemed infinitely refreshing. And, yes, some of
the verse was flat, but much of it resonated with that strange
wintry music that made him perhaps the greatest of 20th-century
poets. It was as if Eliot were telling the dramatists of his day
and mine that there were possibilities, spiritual and verbal, they
had never even contemplated.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers will, as I say, make up their own minds about Adrian
Noble's revival at BAM. (It is being accompanied by ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream'' and Schiller's ``Don Carlos.'') But most of the
British critics now find the play's oddities more than digestible.
``The RSC has struck gold,'' declared John Gross in The Sunday
Telegraph, adding that even when ``The Family Reunion'' becomes
elusive or off-putting, it is ``curiously compelling _ you succumb
to its spell.''
</P>
<P>
   John Peter in The Sunday Times wrote, ``A tense, gaunt,
uncluttered production of Eliot's greatest play.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five years after his death, Eliot the
dramatist-who-might-have-been has gained posthumous recognition.
Ours is an era that no longer winces at choruses on the patterned
carpet or Furies behind the leather armchair or echoes of the
``Four Quartets'' beside the drinks cupboard. We don't shrink from
stylized language, whether it has been written by Aeschylus,
Shakespeare, Synge, Beckett or Pinter. We tend to think that the
argument about the need for a poetic drama misses the point by
confusing poetry with verse.
</P>
<P>
   Prose can be poetic, and poetry prosaic. Given the right
director and actors, can't ``The Oresteia,'' ``The Family
Reunion,'' ``Waiting for Godot,'' ``The Homecoming'' and ``American
Buffalo'' achieve the kind of elusive magic that Eliot had in mind?
Why not?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
