<HEADER>
A4745 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-CARDINAL-OCONNOR-A     05-03 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CARDINAL-OCONNOR-ART-385&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL O'CONNOR, NEW YORK'S ARCHBISHOP, IS NEAR DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cardinal John O'Connor, the Roman Catholic archbishop
of New York, who underwent surgery for a brain tumor last August,
was near death Wednesday, after his health sharply declined in
recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters on the steps of the cardinal's Madison
Avenue residence Wednesday, Joseph Zwilling, the spokesman for the
archdiocese, said ``the cardinal is at the hour of his death.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of the cardinal's grave condition spread quickly through
the city and the archdiocese as speculation over his possible
successor as archbishop once again intensified. This week, the name
of Bishop Edward Michael Egan of Bridgeport, Conn., flew to the top
of a list of candidates that has included William F. Murphy, an
auxiliary bishop of Boston; Edwin O'Brien, who heads the
archdiocese for the military services; Henry J. Mansell, the bishop
of Buffalo, N.Y.; and Justin F. Rigali, the archbishop of St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of an archbishop, however, is a secret process
that rests in the hands of the Vatican, and appointments often come
as a surprise to those in the church who though they were in the
know.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, spiritual leader of 2.4 million Catholics in the New
York area, has waged a largely private battle through brain surgery
followed by radiation, disappearing from public view over the last
10 weeks as his illness, which he declined to call cancer, claimed
the last of his vitality.
</P>
<P>
   Zwilling said Wednesday that the cardinal ``is not communicating
at this point.'' The spokesman declined to say whether O'Connor,
whose wry humor had guests chuckling through a fund-raiser on his
80th birthday in January, had been administered last rites
Wednesday, technically known as ``the sacrament of the sick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know precisely when he will die,'' Zwilling said,
``but I think it is clear that he is, in Catholic terms, at the
hour of his death.'' He was referring to the ``Hail Mary,'' a
prayer in which Catholics implore the Virgin Mary to ``pray for us
at the hour of our death.''
</P>
<P>
   Zwilling said the cardinal was not in any pain, and that his
sister and other family members were at his side, as were the
priests who live with him and a few close friends.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the Catholic Center's 22-story tower on First Avenue _ the
central nervous system of a vast diocese that spans Manhattan, the
Bronx and Staten Island, along with seven counties north of the
city _ a somber mood prevailed. Employees, who had long taken to
beginning meetings with prayers for the Cardinal's health, realized
his condition had worsened when a cabinet session planned for
Tuesday morning was canceled without warning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Gerald Walsh, who had served as the cardinal's
secretary for more than two years, said his colleagues at the
Catholic Center considered the Cardinal's downturn as ``sad, but
expected.'' After watching O'Connor, who once was not expected to
survive much beyond his birthday, struggle these many weeks, those
closest to him felt relieved that he would no longer suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh noted that O'Connor's column had not appeared in Catholic
Week, the newspaper of the archdiocese and a favorite platform of
the cardinal, for six weeks. Even those Catholics and other New
Yorkers who do not attend church knew that he had not attended mass
at St. Patrick's for 10 weeks, and was forced to skip Easter mass
because of his weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Though reporters had gathered outside the cardinal's residence
for word of his condition, at St. Patrick's Cathedral, tourists
strolled through the aisle and offered their prayers as on any
normal day, apparently unaware that the cardinal was nearing the
end of his life around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   At the Roman Catholic Church of Our Savior at 38th Street and
Park Avenue, several worshipers arrived in the late afternoon to
say prayers for the cardinal, as word spread of his deteriorating
condition. ``He unified a lot of people in Manhattan, as far as
attending mass and bringing people together,'' said Susan
Hagelthorn, who said she nevertheless left the church because she
did not ``appreciate his disdain for homosexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his surgery, O'Connor, who had served in the military for
26 years before coming to New York, appeared intermittently in his
offices on the top floor of the Catholic Center, frequently work
from home instead. A long-time insomniac, the Cardinal would
frequently read or work through the night, leaving the resulting
assignments piled outside the doors of the priests and bishops who
lived with him.
</P>
<P>
   But over the months, maintaining a normal life became
increasingly difficult. O'Connor's usually trim figure grew bloated
from the steroids he was prescribed for his illness, and in
November, he was forced back into the hospital, weak and
dehydrated.
</P>
<P>
   At his 80th birthday party, the cardinal joked about being the
first archbishop of New York not to die in office, and said he
could pretend, but would not, enjoy seeing another take his place.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with Church tradition, Pope John Paul II had received
O'Connor's resignation five years earlier, but had put off naming a
successor at the time. Most thought he would do so this January.
Allowing O'Connor, who is considered a favorite of the pope, to
remain beyond his 80th birthday in such a key post was considered
wildly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   As the weeks following O'Connor's 80th birthday spun into
months, however, church watchers realized the Pope would do his
best to allow the Cardinal to end his days while still in office,
as a reflection of his affection and esteem for the cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, O'Connor's friends and family kept a round the clock
vigil, with only two or three at a time standing by the Cardinal in
his spare bedroom. Saying he wanted to respect the cardinal's
privacy, Zwilling would not say whether prayers were going on for
the cardinal in his residence.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh noted that ``sacraments for the sick,'' as the last rites
are now called, were given to O'Connor when he was admitted to
Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Centers for surgery last August,
and may have been periodically administered in the months since
then. Zwilling declined to say whether the sacraments had been
given again to O'Connor as he now approaches death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2116EDT &QL; 
