<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4746 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-INDEPENDENT-TV-ART-$A     05-03 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDEPENDENT-TV-ART-$ADV07-1,110&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON TV, A LOSS OF INDEPENDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 7) 
(ART ADV: NYT Photo 7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For more than two decades, Robert Greenwald, a
prolific television producer, has owned the films he made, which
gave him the leverage to do such Emmy Award-winning shows as ``The
Burning Bed'' and ``A Woman of Independent Means.'' But now
Greenwald, and every other producer of films and series, is under
powerful pressure to yield to the networks and allow them to own
more and more of their shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the money,'' Greenwald said. ``We all get paid
well. It's about the fact that a show you own is your viewpoint,
your vision. All that is dissipated when you're a hired hand. You
can have the most brilliant people in the world running networks,
but it's almost a scientific impossibility for bureaucracies to be
inventive and edgy. They cannot. It's their nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Until five years ago, federal regulations prevented broadcast
networks from creating and owning shows, which left the job to
independent production companies and studios like Warner Brothers,
Fox, Sony and Universal. The thinking was that the networks were so
powerful they could lock out projects by independent producers. But
in 1995 the Federal Communications Commission lifted the
20-year-old restriction, freeing the networks to aggressively seek
financial stakes in and ownership of films, dramatic series and
sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, what does this mean to viewers? Is the
television landscape, already littered with derivative shows, even
more compromised if independent producers are unable to get
provocative programs on the air? Or are the complaints just a
Hollywood shell game _ one group of rich people getting richer at
the expense of another group of rich people? Put another way, was
television better 10 years ago than it is today?
</P>
<P>
   The clearest proof of where the television networks are heading
will be evident in New York during the week of May 15. That is when
the networks, in their lavish annual presentations to advertisers,
will announce their fall schedules. Most of the new comedy and
dramatic series will be owned entirely by the networks, or made in
partnership with producers. Inevitably _ and despite the denials of
network executives _ some shows will be selected simply because
they are home-grown. Cynics may recall that in recent years NBC
green-lighted such in-house shows as ``Union Square,'' ``Conrad
Bloom'' and ``The Mike O'Malley Show.'' Each of them died without a
trace, and one can only wonder what shows failed to make it to the
air because of the decision to put on those three.
</P>
<P>
   The decline of independent producers is a reflection not only of
increased network ownership of shows but, far more important, of
the ascendancy of conglomerates like Disney and Viacom, General
Electric and News Corp., who own the networks. The result is that
network executives have also lost considerable independence,
further hampering creative programming.
</P>
<P>
   Two or more decades ago, television was presided over by figures
like Grant Tinker, Fred Silverman and Brandon Tartikoff, who held
top jobs at NBC, and Barry Diller, a onetime ABC programming
executive and the former chairman of Fox. Whatever their flaws,
these men were more independent than their counterparts today. At
Disney-owned ABC, for example, Lloyd Braun and Stuart Bloomberg,
the two talented executives who run the entertainment division,
work under the formidable shadow of Michael Eisner, the chairman of
the Walt Disney Co. and a former ABC executive himself. The fact
that Eisner weighs in on program decisions is an open secret _ and
doing so is his prerogative. (Not long ago, he went so far as to
personally call Peter Berg, the creator of ``Wonderland,'' to give
him script advice. The show failed anyway.) Rupert Murdoch, the
chairman of News Corp., and executives at General Electric and Time
Warner are less intrusive than Eisner, but their voices are heard
at Fox and NBC and WB.
</P>
<P>
   As corporate owners study the bottom line, the mood is bleak.
The days are over when a show is allowed to struggle and find an
audience, as NBC did with ``Seinfeld'' in 1990. This month, ABC
canceled ``Wonderland,'' a drama set in a mental hospital, after
only two shows, and NBC dropped the DreamWorks police comedy,
``Battery Park,'' after just four outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no free lunch anymore,'' said Tom Werner, who with his
partners, Marcy Carsey and Caryn Mandabach, created ``The Cosby
Show,'' ``Roseanne'' and other gold mines. The four pilots his
company is now producing are being done in partnership with
networks, partly out of necessity, he said. Making 22 episodes of a
series can lead to a deficit as high as $15 million before the show
is sold to syndication. Partners are needed to defray the costs.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, CBS and NBC have their own in-house production units
and seek out (or demand) partnerships with producers as well. Fox
and ABC rely heavily _ although not exclusively _ on shows produced
by 20th Century Fox and Disney. Is there any question that networks
favor their own shows? It is a subtle issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, it's a factor that gets in the way,'' said
Amy Lippman, the co-creator of Fox's ``Party of Five.'' ``When
networks have material that comes from a studio they own, it can't
help but weigh in the decision about what gets on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Lippman said that ``Party of Five,'' admittedly in its sixth
year, was shifted out of its choice Wednesday night time slot to
make room for a Fox-produced comedy, ``Get Real.'' ``Party'' is
produced by Columbia-TriStar. ```Party of Five' suffered,'' said
Lippman, whose show went off the air this season.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Levitan, the creator of NBC's ``Just Shoot Me,'' told a
similar story about ``Will and Grace,'' which is produced in part
by NBC Studios. ``NBC smelled a hit in `Will and Grace,''' he said,
``and poured all their resources and advertising into that show,
giving it a great time period, the `Just Shoot Me' time period,''
meaning Tuesday night at 9. ``It's just that they're favoring their
own show. It's not like they're doing something wrong. It's not
like, `How dare they do that?''' (The fact that ``Shoot Me'' is in
its fifth year surely figured in the decision.)
</P>
<P>
   Another writer-producer, Marshall Herskovitz, said that he and
his partner, Edward Zwick, the creators of ``Thirtysomething,''
went out of their way to make a deal with Disney knowing it would
give them a leg up with their series ``Once and Again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a deal with Disney knowing they would be the main
supplier of ABC,'' Herskovitz said. ``What we felt was, at best,
there was a statistical advantage in being with an in-house
production company. By that I mean that, at some odd moment, when a
decision is to be made about a show, and all the factors are equal,
it would be of some benefit for a network to favor its own show.''
(ABC recently renewed ``Once and Again'' for another season.)
</P>
<P>
   How this affects creative quality is difficult to assess.
Network executives are hardly hacks. Aware that audiences are
shrinking in favor of cable and the Internet, they are plainly
struggling to come up with shows that are intelligent (NBC's ``West
Wing''), funny (Fox's ``Malcolm in the Middle''), adult (ABC's
``Once and Again'') and even a bit risky (NBC's ``Will and
Grace''). And they insist that the demise of the independent
producer _ and the rise of producing partnerships _ has not altered
the creative landscape.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4747 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-INDEPENDENT-TV-ART-2N     05-03 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDEPENDENT-TV-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: creative landscape.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fact that a producer is affiliated with a studio or a
network doesn't mean that half of their brain died,'' said Braun of
ABC. ``Producers are better served by being with a network or a
studio because the business is so economically challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   Braun denied that ABC goes out of its way to select Disney
properties. ``Certainly we'll be as aggressive as possible in
building up our studios,'' he said. ``But our mantra is to develop
and put the best possible shows on the air, regardless of the
source.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Leslie Moonves, the president of CBS Television,
dismissed the notion that series and films have been diminished.
``You think the creative aesthetic of David Kelley has changed one
iota because he's under the Fox banner? Of course not.''
</P>
<P>
   An unfair example, perhaps. Hugely successful creator-producers
like Kelley (``The Practice,'' ``Ally McBeal'') and Steven Bochco
(``N.Y.P.D. Blue''), whose companies are now aligned with studios,
are given creative carte blanche. Most independent producers are
under seige.
</P>
<P>
   Television was once dominated by powerhouse producers like
Norman Lear, Aaron Spelling, Witt-Thomas-Harris, Carsey-Werner,
Lorimar and others. By all accounts, some of the shows they made _
``Soap,'' ``All in the Family,'' ``Benson,'' ``Maude,'' ``Golden
Girls'' _ would probably not pass muster today. The lead characters
would not fit snugly into the prized youth market: they are too
old, too ethnic, too female. ``Try doing a show today like `Golden
Girls,' about three older women,'' said one top network executive.
``Good luck!''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those producers, like Carsey-Werner-Mandabach and
Spelling, still work in television, but their number has dwindled.
When this reporter called Michael Jaffe, a well-known producer, and
said he was doing an article about independent television
producers, Jaffe replied, with some hyperbole: ``You're doing a
short story. There are only two of us left.'' Jaffe said there were
probably only 10 producers making films for television, in contrast
to 30 or 40 in the 80's.
</P>
<P>
   But a handful of powerful producers has entered the field _
Basic Entertainment (formerly Brillstein-Grey), Regency Television
and the Robert Greenblatt-David Janollari studio, among them.
Artists Television Group, a newcomer, has made 12 pilots for the
new season. All of which suggests that, despite the changes wrought
by the F.C.C. decision, there is money to be made, creative work to
be found.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, producers are turning to the flourishing cable
networks, where, as Variety reported last week, wealthy corporate
parents like Time Warner and Viacom are willing to pay the costs of
series and films. (A one-hour series on basic cable can cost about
$1.3 million an episode, only slightly less than the $1.5 million
price of a broadcast show; a two-hour cable film can cost $7
million to $10 million.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We embraced the new world,'' said Jaffe, whose company made
more than a half-dozen films for cable last year. ``The
partnerships are somewhat complicated because it's all new
business. We're paving the landscape as we go.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, said Gail Berman, president of Regency Television,
the producer of Fox's successful sitcom ``Malcolm in the Middle,''
whether or not studios own series and films is not the issue. ``The
audience doesn't know, doesn't care about vertical integration,''
Berman said. The issue, she said, is a straightforward one. Without
better programming, the viewers won't be there. ``They'll just flip
the channel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4748 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-U.N.-ART     05-03 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-U.N.-ART-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBELS IN SIERRA LEONE KILL 7 U.N. PEACEKEEPERS, TAKE OTHERS
HOSTAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A United Nations attempt to take charge of security in the West
African country of Sierra Leone has exploded in violence, with
rebels killing seven peacekeepers, all Kenyans, and taking hostage
at least 49 other peacekeepers and civilians, U.N. officials said
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels of the Revolutionary United Front, who made a grisly name
for themselves by chopping limbs off thousands of civilians during
an eight-year civil war that ended last year, detained members of
the U.N. mission after a series of confrontations in central and
north-eastern parts of the country on Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The violence _ the worst for U.N. peacekeepers since 10 Belgians
were killed in Rwanda in 1994 _ is by far the most serious
breakdown of a chronically troubled peace agreement brokered last
year by the United Nations between the government of Sierra Leone
and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels' leader, Foday Sankoh, who became a government
minister after last year's peace deal, has consistently refused to
honor his promises to pacify his forces and allow U.N.s
peacekeepers to move freely in rebel territory.
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeeping troops responded on Wednesday to the rebel attack
by surrounding Sankoh's house in the capital, Freetown. A U.S.
official in Freetown said by telephone he had received a statement
from Sankoh, saying that if hostages were being held by the
Revolutionary United Front, they should be released. Sankoh also
called for dialogue and free movement about the country for U.N.
forces.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. spokesman in New York said that the rebel leader's house
was surrounded because ``the U.N. wants to make sure it can remain
in contact with Mr. Sankoh at this time of crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't formally been arrested for anything. However it
would be dishonest to say he can just pack up and leave,'' said the
spokesman, Farhan Haq.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council demanded the release of the captured
troops and said Sankoh should order his followers to stop the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said it had no plans to rescue the
peacekeepers who have been taken hostage, but a senior State
Department official said the United States is ``looking into the
availability'' of using C-140 cargo aircraft to fly Jordanian,
Bangladeshi and Indian troops into Sierra Leone. The officials
said, however, that these troops are not yet ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released in New York, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan called the attacks ``outrageous and criminal,'' and a
``flagrant violation'' of the July peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington an administration official said on Wednesday that
the United States was looking at ways to see if Mr. Sankoh could be
charged with war crimes. The peace deal Sankoh negotiated last year
exempted him and his forces from prosecution for possible war
crimes committed during the civil war. But the State Department has
said it has credible information that atrocities have been
committed by Sonkoh's forces since the agreement was signed.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations made an urgent appeal Tuesday night for more
troops to reinforce the 8,500 peacekeepers, mostly Nigerians,
Kenyans and Indians, who have been deployed there. Members of the
Security Council were asked to transport, presumably in an
emergency airlift, 3,000 more peacekeepers to Sierra Leone from
Jordan, Bangladesh and India.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations authorized 11,000 troops for the mission in
Sierra Leone, but their deployment has been delayed because of
lagging troop contributions from member nations.
</P>
<P>
   The nationalities of the detainees were not immediately
released. In one of the areas where the attacks occurred, Kailahun,
the troops are mostly Indian; in the other area of attacks, the
troops are mostly Kenyan.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. spokeswoman said the number of dead was based on
preliminary reports and could change.
</P>
<P>
   The worse single attack on U.N. peacekeepers was the death of 24
Pakistani troops in 1993 in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   (START OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The killings and detentions provoked strong condemnations from
the Security Council, Annan and the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation in Sierra Leone is unacceptable to the United
Nations and should be unacceptable to all the member states,'' said
Richard C. Holbrooke, the American representative to the United
Nations, who was in Brussels and on his way with other Security
Council members to assess another shaky African truce, in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Violence in Sierra Leone seems likely to raise more questions
about the United Nations' plan to send a force of about 5,500 to
Congo, made up of monitors, peacekeeping troops and a large support
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Influential members of Congress have been objecting to paying
the American share of the Congo operation, even though no U.S.
troops are being considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't turn away from crises like these,'' Holbrooke said,
referring both to Sierra Leone and Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said on Wednesday that the violence in Sierra Leone could
discourage Western countries from taking part in further
peacekeeping operations on the continent. He pointed out that
countries were reluctant to intervene in the genocide in Rwanda
after casualties in Somalia in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``And after Sierra Leone, I think there's going to be very
little encouragement for any of them to get involved in operations
in Africa,'' said Annan.
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing sense at the United Nations that Sankoh will
have to be declared a war criminal sooner or later, although in the
absence of an international criminal court _ a body the United
States opposes _ there is no mechanism for capturing or trying him,
even though he may now be under effective house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems as if Foday Sankoh is trying to derail the peace
process,'' Maj. Gen. Vijay Kumar Jetley, the Indian officer who
commands the U.N. force in Sierra Leone, said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The attacks on U.N. peacekeepers occurred on Monday and Tuesday
in two north-central towns, Makeni and Magburaka, and in Kailahun
in eastern Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials say that 21 of the captives, including three
military observers policing a much-violated cease-fire, were taken
in the Makeni-Magburaka area. Another 28 captives in Kailahun
include two U.N. civilian employees and four members of a
helicopter crew.
</P>
<P>
   One of the peacekeepers' major tasks is to get the rebels,
Sankoh's troops and others, to give up their weapons so that the
country can hold a national election in 2001. There were reports
Tuesday that at least one attack from Sankoh's Revolutionary United
Front followed the defection of some of his soldiers to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   When peacekeepers refused to turn them over, they came under
attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
