<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT REBUKES DIPLOMATS FOR SECURITY SLIPS
</HEADLINE>
 By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a fierce speech transmitted around the world,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright Wednesday told U.S. diplomats
that protecting the nation's secrets was at the core of their
mission and warned that enemies abounded even in a post-cold-war
world.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who said she was furious over both the disappearance
of a laptop computer packed with classified information and other
recent security lapses at the State Department, summoned more than
800 staff members to the department's auditorium to hear her
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   The speech was broadcast live on the department's internal
television network and beamed by satellite to U.S.missions in
dozens of countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care how skilled you are as a diplomat, how brilliant
you may be at meetings, or how creative you are as an
administrator,'' Albright said in stern tones reminiscent of her
days as a Georgetown University professor, ``if you are not
professional about security, you are a failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may have seen reports indicating that I am furious about
these incidents,'' she said. ``Well, I am, and I hope you are,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said it was the first time a secretary had held a
department-wide meeting on security. It came as Albright's aides
were exploring new measures to protect classified materials and
guard against espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Albright was embarrassed by the laptop incident,
which she learned about through newspaper articles more than two
months after the computer was reported missing to State Department
security officers by the Bureau of Intelligence and Research.
</P>
<P>
   The computer's disappearance, which is being investigated by the
FBI, was just a month after federal agents found an electronic
listening device in a department conference room. A Russian
diplomat was expelled after the discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers have criticized the breaches. Albright is
scheduled to testify Thursday before the House Select Committee on
Intelligence. The chairman of the House Committee on International
Relations, Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., has invited her to a panel
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who last week announced an overhaul of department
security, transferred two officials from Intelligence and Research
and stripped that office of its ability to police itself,
complained Wednesday that she had met resistance from a diplomatic
culture that played down the importance of security.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomats privately acknowledged that they were
occasionally cavalier about security. Many said their public
profiles required a steady stream of foreign visitors and contacts,
unlike many of their colleagues at the Pentagon or the intelligence
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   A diplomat said the department in recent years had ordered a
halt to nightly office-by-office security checks by Marines _ a
training maneuver for Marines bound for overseas posts _ because
they turned up so many violations, creating a morass of paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody cares about security within the department,'' said the
diplomat, who has served three decades at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   An interagency group that includes members of the FBI, the CIA
and the Secret Service is preparing recommendations to improve the
department's security. Among the options being considered are
closing off two entrances and streets adjacent to the department's
headquarters, increasing camera surveillance throughout the
facility and limiting the number of electronic building passes,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the end of the Cold War, Albright said, the threats to
U.S. interests are more varied and less predictable than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spy novelists may be having trouble thinking up plots,'' she
said. ``But our nation still has enemies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
