<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4750 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ABT-DANCE-$ADV07-NYT &LR;      05-03 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABT-DANCE-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSING THE 'SWAN LAKE' TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 7) 
 By IRIS FANGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the turn of the millennium, American Ballet
Theater moved into overdrive on its new production of ``Swan
Lake.'' Mounting a classic as big as this one, with a price tag to
match, involved every resource the company could muster. Work days
turned into nights for Kevin McKenzie, Ballet Theater's artistic
director and ballet master, the dancers and coaching staff and the
technical crews, not to mention the efforts of the development
office, which raised $1.4 million to assure the splendor of the
spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   The production will have its New York premiere at the
Metropolitan Opera House on May 19. ``Swan Lake'' is expected to be
the blockbuster of the company's 60th-anniversary season, which
opens with a gala performance tomorrow night and runs through July
1.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie describes ``Swan Lake'' as the quintessential ballet,
the one that defines the standards of the company, tests its
dancers and ennobles the spirit of the viewer. ``It rings so true
of human nature, of man's inconsistency, of the victimizing of
women, so full of big truths,'' he says. ``The key point is about
not being able to marry one's ideals to one's realities.''
</P>
<P>
   These issues came to life on stage in St. Petersburg in 1895
when Marius Petipa and Lev Ivanov created the choreography for the
``Swan Lake'' that has come down to us, joined to Tchaikovsky's
glorious score (the first, butchered staging of the score was in
1877). McKenzie has based his production on theirs, but combined
his own ideas with the familiar story about the Prince who falls in
love with a Swan Queen in the power of the wicked sorcerer von
Rothbart.
</P>
<P>
   Late one March afternoon, McKenzie stood watching a rehearsal of
the prologue he has added to ``Swan Lake'' while two two-man teams
double cast as von Rothbart refined a fancy twisting of the body
around an arm. In rethinking the scenario, McKenzie needed to
introduce up front his notion of presenting the evil sorcerer as a
split personality, with two dancers trading places as the character
throughout the ballet. It was not hard to picture the moment of
theatrical magic he intends with von Rothbart's transformation from
devil to suave courtier. Off in a corner, three of the principal
dancers cast as the Swan Queen at different performances _ Paloma
Herrera, Julie Kent and Susan Jaffe _ waited for the cue to walk
unknowingly into von Rothbart's trap.
</P>
<P>
   A prologue that explains the Swan Queen's enchantment in a
long-ago and faraway era before the familiar story unfolds is
another of the innovations McKenzie has brought to this ``Swan
Lake.'' Still another is condensing the ballet into two acts,
posing a challenge for the set and costume designer, Zack Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swan Lake'' takes place in four distinct locales, requiring
the shifting of backdrops and platforms from the palace garden, to
the lakeside, to the palace ballroom and back to a different
perspective of the lake. Brown solved the problem of only one
intermission by using a traveling curtain, with silhouetted trees,
to bring in the lakeside clearing, plus a transparent back wall for
the palace and a ballroom platform that breaks in half for the
final act. Before the ballet's premiere at the Kennedy Center in
Washington last month, Ballet Theater's technical crew spent a week
in one of the theaters on the campus of the State University of New
York in Purchase to devise the intricate backstage choreography for
the rapid set changes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Barbara Matera's costume shop on the fifth floor
above the company's studios at 890 Broadway was buzzing with 85
workers constructing the more than 300 costumes required for the
multiple casting of roles. In one corner, three women did nothing
but hand beading and embroidery. Another worker bent over the
colored ribbon she was threading into fabric for the vests to be
worn by the Neapolitan dancers for about three minutes of stage
time. Forty-four swan tutus had to be hand pleated of tulle to look
like feathers.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Horowitz, Ballet Theater's wardrobe supervisor for the
last 19 years, planned a strategy as complicated as a military
maneuver for the quick costume changes. The women of the corps de
ballet will have only a few minutes to shed their Act I peasant
costumes for tutus. During Act III, the corps members, dressed in
court costumes, must melt off the stage a few at a time to climb
back into tutus and point shoes. Horowitz had already measured the
dancers' feet for 140 pairs of leather boots that complement the
court and peasant costumes and sent the men's measurements to
Portland, Ore., and the women's to Russia, where the boots were
made.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who have seen a production of ``Swan Lake'' _ its
viewers since 1895 must number in the millions because the work is
a staple of repertories the world over _ retain, above all else,
the image of the Swan Queen, with her quivering arms, long, arched
neck and demeanor of doom. Behind her, sister swan maidens dance in
perfect symmetry to complete the moonlit vision that has remained
in collective memory.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie can be forgiven for having a viewpoint that differs
from the shared opinion that the ballet belongs to the Swan Queen.
The fate of Prince Siegfried has been his to ponder since 1980,
when he made his debut in the role, a year after he joined Ballet
Theater as a dancer. He believes the focus of the ballet is the
Prince. ``In my mind, the Swan's story is done,'' McKenzie says,
ending a 12-hour day at the studio by talking about his work on the
ballet. ``The story happens to Siegfried, not the Swan. He can't
marry his ideal to reality. That is the tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   In radically shortening Act IV, McKenzie brings the story to a
quick conclusion. ``Prince Siegfried's rite of passage is that he
realizes he owes it to her to join her in death,'' he says. ``Her
rite of passage is that she realizes she can forgive him for his
betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   A full-length production of ``Swan Lake,'' choreographed after
Petipa and Ivanov by David Blair of the Royal Ballet, has been in
the ABT repertory since 1967, briefly replaced by Mikhail
Baryshnikov's production in 1988. However, Baryshnikov took the
rights to his ballet with him when he left the company in 1989.
Ballet Theater reverted to Blair's ballet in 1993 when McKenzie
first staged ``Swan Lake.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie was a teen-age ballet student in Washington when he saw
excerpts from ``Swan Lake'' on a Bolshoi Ballet program. A year
later he attended a Ballet Theater performance and saw his first
full-length ``Swan Lake.'' In subsequent years, the company became
an annual visitor to Washington at the Kennedy Center. McKenzie
went regularly to the performances. ``I grew up seeing all those
wonderful casts,'' he says. ``I was obviously very thrilled when my
time came to do the ballet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Swan Lake'' has been a constant in the company's history since
1940, when the Act II lakeside scene was presented in its opening
season. Lucia Chase, a founder of Ballet Theater, its director with
Oliver Smith from 1945 to 1980 and its financial fairy godmother,
had dreamed of a full-length ``Swan Lake'' to replace the one-act
version. But there wasn't enough money or dancers until 1967, when
an enlarged company presented Blair's complete version. With its
premiere, the first of the evening-length classics that ABT would
produce, ``Ballet Theatre acquired the confident assurance that it
could rank itself among the half-dozen major ballet companies of
the world,'' according to Charles Payne in his detailed history,
``American Ballet Theatre,'' published by Knopf in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
