<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4756 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-GUNMAKERS-STRATEGY-2T     05-03 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNMAKERS-STRATEGY-2TAKES(945)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAKERS, BETTING ON A BUSH VICTORY, END SETTLEMENT TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Pa., Ohio, La., Calif., Fla.)  By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faced with lawsuits by 31 cities and counties, the nation's gun
companies have broken off settlement negotiations, deciding to take
their chances that state judges will prove sympathetic or that
victory in November will go to the apparent Republican presidential
nominee, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   This defiance by the gun industry dashes the hopes of the White
House and state and local governments that a recent deal with Smith
&AMP; Wesson to change some of its marketing and manufacturing
practices might lead other major gun companies to fall in line.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, people on both sides of the litigation say, the gun
companies, believing that the November elections will be crucial to
their future, are holding off any further settlement talks at least
until they see whether Bush wins the presidency and the Republicans
maintain control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, the companies hope that Bush, who as governor of
Texas has been a staunch defender of the industry and of gun
owners, will help dampen the growing public sentiment for
additional gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, their hope is that Bush as president would help
push through Congress a bill outlawing municipal suits against
them. As governor, Bush got just such a law through the state
Legislature with the help of the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Even if those hopes are unrealized, the companies calculate,
Bush would at least stop the kind of pressure the Clinton
administration has put on them through Andrew Cuomo, the secretary
of housing and urban development, to settle the suits.
</P>
<P>
   Although the suits vary from city to city, they generally accuse
the industry of failing to incorporate enough safety features in
handguns and of distributing them in ways that make it easy for
criminals and juveniles to buy them. The suits collectively seek
millions of dollars to reimburse the municipalities for their costs
related to gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Delfay, president of the National Shooting Sports
Foundation, the industry's trade organization, said he believed
that as president Bush would work to pass a law protecting gun
makers from such municipal suits, ``based on his actions as
governor of Texas,'' where he signed not only similar legislation
but also a tort-reform measure curbing lawsuits against
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Delfay said, the gun companies are encouraged by
the names being mentioned for the Republican vice-presidential
nomination, particularly Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, who
recently signed into law a measure prohibiting cities in his state
from suing the firearms industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is looking toward the election as a watershed
event on this issue,'' Delfay said. ``If Bush wins, we could be
going in a whole new direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Januzzo, vice president and general counsel of one gun
maker, Glock Inc., acknowledged that settlement negotiations had
come to a halt and that the industry was hoping for sympathy from a
Bush administration. Januzzo said that the negotiations had
``degenerated into terrorism'' with escalating demands by the
plaintiffs and that he no longer trusted their lawyers or Cuomo. He
said the industry viewed Bush as ``anti-lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this can happen to us,'' Januzzo said, ``who's next? If the
lawyers are successful with the gun industry, you can be sure they
will be out there claiming they have done more than anyone to
change society since the Supreme Court in civil rights days.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry describes the suits, and the negotiations that
resulted from them, as an effort by its opponents to win through
the courts the kind of controls they could not get enacted in state
legislatures or Congress. The companies maintain that a federal law
not only barring future suits but also voiding those already filed
would withstand challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's camp has been noncommittal about whether he would back
the kind of legislation the gun makers are seeking. Scott
McClellan, a Bush spokesman, declined to rule out the possibility,
saying simply, ``He has not addressed that at the federal level.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a reflection of their more aggressive posture, seven of
the largest handgun makers sued 16 of their municipal adversaries
last week, and added New York state and Connecticut. The suit,
filed in U.S. District Court in Atlanta, asks that the defendants
be forced to abandon new policies favorable to Smith &AMP; Wesson in
handgun purchases for their police.
</P>
<P>
   The companies contend that those policies, a result of the
recent deal with Smith &AMP; Wesson, brokered by Cuomo, are an illegal
effort to regulate interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   One big risk in the gun makers' November strategy, of course, is
that Bush could lose. In that case, the industry's best hope would
lie in favorable treatment by judges. So far, in the six cases in
which the courts have ruled on the industry's requests for summary
dismissal, judges have thrown out three, involving Bridgeport,
Conn., Cincinnati and Miami. In the other three cases, involving
Atlanta, Cleveland and New Orleans, the suits have been allowed to
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   One senior gun industry executive said a factor behind the
companies' election-related strategy was that the NRA ``has been
telling everyone not to do anything till November, that this
administration is history, so don't deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, who has met privately with a number of firearms industry
executives in an effort to bring more of them into the Smith &AMP;
Wesson settlement, said the gun makers had been telling him as well
that they were counting on Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are waiting to see who wins in November,'' Cuomo said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Short of enacting federal legislation, a Bush administration and
a Republican-controlled Congress could achieve the same ends
through other means. One way would be to tie federal block grants
to cities for law enforcement to a condition that any city
accepting the money not sue the gun companies. Federal
law-enforcement aid to cities and states has typically been through
block grants, often with conditions attached. The Clinton
administration, for example, has prided itself on providing money
for the hiring of 100,000 police officers, who, under the program,
were required to be assigned to community policing.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawsuits are now moving through the courts, and many of
the cities believe they will hit pay dirt in the discovery process,
finding material that will weaken the gun companies' position in
the same way that documents about nicotine addiction helped force
tobacco companies to settle lawsuits with various states. Two of
the cases, in Cleveland and Atlanta, have just moved into the
discovery phase, in which the two sides can examine previously
confidential material relevant to the claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an industry that has never been investigated by
Congress, whose executives have never been put under oath,'' said
David Kairys, a professor at Temple University Law School who is an
adviser to many of the cities. ``I think they have a lot to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Some small gun companies say they are already feeling enormous
financial pressure from having to defend themselves against the
suits.
</P>
<P>
   The head of a California handgun company estimated that he was
paying $50,000 to $100,000 a month in lawyer fees. ``We are a small
company,'' the executive said. ``We're going to go broke.''
</P>
<P>
   But aside from Smith &AMP; Wesson, the larger companies appear to
have decided to try to wait it out, at least until November.
Januzzo, of Glock, said he thought the firearms manufacturers could
persuade the courts to dismiss about half to two thirds of the
suits before trial, making the costs manageable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
