<HEADER>
A4758 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-KHANNOUCHI-NYT &LR;      05-03 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-KHANNOUCHI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KHANNOUCHI'S EXIT LEAVES BLAME FOR ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His legs overruling his heart a day after he became
an American citizen, Khalid Khannouchi announced Wednesday that he
was too injured to compete in the Olympic marathon trials on Sunday
in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the few smart decisions made in an immigration
case that has included bad advice from lawyers, miscalculation by
his agent-wife, grandstanding by politicians and abandonment of the
runner by the shoe company he endorses.
</P>
<P>
   Ankle and hamstring injuries aggravated at the London Marathon
on April 16 threatened the longevity of Khannouchi's career, his
trainer, Gerard Hartmann, said Wednesday. It should never have come
to this. If his pursuit of citizenship had been conducted as
professionally as his racing, Khannouchi would not have had to run
the London Marathon, his American dream would not have become an
athletic nightmare and American chances for a marathon gold medal
at the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia, would not have
been reduced to zero.
</P>
<P>
   At least, after a day, the Moroccan-born Khannouchi was enough
of an American not to let outside pressures force him to run a race
that would have been dangerous for his career, one that involves a
classic immigrant story of working his way from dishwasher to
world-record holder in six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very sorry,'' Khannouchi said, tears welling in his
eyes at a Manhattan news conference, a day after being sworn in as
a U.S. citizen. ``I feel bad for the people that really worked hard
on the case. I'm looking toward the case realistically. I don't
want to be pushed and make some bad mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough bad mistakes have already been made. The first was not
listening to Craig Masback, the CEO of track and field's national
governing body, who told the Khannouchis in the fall of 1998 that
legislative pursuit of citizenship would be fruitless. In recent
memory, not a single athlete has ever received expedited
citizenship through a private bill in Congress. Why would
Khannouchi be any different, Masback advised.
</P>
<P>
   Masback recommended the use of a naturalization provision,
normally used by the military, that grants citizenship to spouses
of American citizens working abroad for American companies. The
French soccer player David Regis had used this provision to become
a U.S. citizen for the 1998 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sandra Khannouchi, Khalid's agent and wife, listened to
lawyers who suggested they pursue expedited citizenship with the
New York congressional help of Rep. Sue Kelly and Sen. Charles E.
Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was bad advice,'' Sandra Khannouchi, who lives with her
husband in Ossining, N.Y., said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The matter devolved into a political fight between Schumer's
office and the Immigration and Naturalization Service. Schumer's
office blamed the INS for temporarily freezing Khannouchi's case
when the agent who interviewed him was charged with bribery in
another case. The INS charged that Schumer was handling the case
for political gain, and that, even if the case had not been frozen,
Khannouchi would not have been eligible through conventional means
to apply for citizenship until September 2000, weeks before the
Oct. 1 Olympic marathon and too late to have competed in the
Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Khannouchi said she was hesitant to ask anyone for a job
overseas, not wanting special treatment for her husband. But having
an international job for a year or so would have been far more
legitimate than the flimsy job she took in Madrid, Spain, in March
with a San Diego-based company called Elite Racing. That move was
desperately calculated to gain citizenship for Khalid Khannouchi.
</P>
<P>
   New Balance, the shoe company that Khannouchi endorses, declined
to provide a job for Sandra Khannouchi, saying that the spousal
immigration provision seemed a contrivance and a loophole. In fact,
it is not a loophole, and it need not be a contrivance. If New
Balance objected to a job, fine. But the company should have at
least pointed Khannouchi toward helpful legal advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't feel it was appropriate for us to step in and get
involved,'' said James Tompkins, the president of New Balance.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Khannouchi is the company's most accomplished and
visible runner. Instead, New Balance engaged in the hypocrisy of
hosting Wednesday's news conference at one of its stores, wanting
publicity without responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi is not without fault. He did not tell his
Houston-based lawyer, Harry Gee, that he was running the London
Marathon. He ran with a prior ankle injury. ``It's certainly
contradictory, running in London and the desire to run in the
Olympic trials,'' Gee said.
</P>
<P>
   Gee got involved in March after reading of the case in a
magazine. Two months later, Khannouchi has his citizenship but no
chance to run in the Olympic marathon, a missed opportunity for
which many must accept blame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
