<HEADER>
A4761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-RUN-GA-NOTRACK0504-CO     05-03 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-GA-NOTRACK0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coaches: Short season is costing state's kids
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA, Ga. _ When it comes to track and field in Georgia, the
state isn't short on talent. But to many coaches, it's short on
time.
</P>
<P>
   The girls' state championship track meet gets under way today in
Albany, the final chapter in a season that high school coaches and
college recruiters say ends too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of coaches would like to see the state track meet be the
second and third week (of May) instead of the first and second,''
Brookwood coach Tomy Sitton said. ``You pick up the better part of
the spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches and recruiters contend that the way Georgia's track
season is scheduled isn't conducive to fully developing a talent
base that some say compares favorably with any other state in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia is one of the top five states in track,'' South
Carolina head track coach Curtis Frye said. ``It has as good (as)
or better athletes than anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But few Georgia names are among the national lists of track and
field's elite high school performers, who mostly hail from
California and Texas. On the latest DyeStat high school track Web
site rankings, only two girls and two girls relay teams from
Georgia have cracked the top 10 nationally in the 24 events posted.
Three boys and one boys relay team are in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the results in sprints, jumps and hurdles and
compare (Georgia kids) with kids in other parts of the country,
you'll see that in Georgia, the performances are somewhat behind,''
Georgia Tech women's track coach Alan Drosky said. ``That doesn't
mean these kids aren't as good _ there are a lot of talented kids.
... They just don't develop in high school to the level of other
kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple answer is, have the season be longer. Move state
meets back a little later.''
</P>
<P>
   Girls track teams began practicing Jan. 31, with their first
meets on Feb. 21. Since teams have to schedule 10 meets, excluding
region and state meets, most are done during March, one of
Georgia's coolest and rainiest months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost a flip of a coin if its going to be 20 degrees or
60 degrees some days,'' Sitton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Track is definitely a warm-weather sport,'' Pope coach Bill
Sheskey said. ``It hurts to run hurdles when it's cold outside. You
can't pole vault in cold weather. You're slower, you don't jump as
high. The effects are pretty obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   On the most recent Georgia track field honor roll, most of the
state's top outdoor performances have come in the latter part of
the season. Of the 15 events posted on the Georgia track and field
honor roll, 11 of the top girls' performances came after April 1 _
and three were posted on March 28. Nine of the top boys'
performances came in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``In April, we get some good weather the last two weeks and the
kids are finally starting to perform,'' Southwest DeKalb coach
Napoleon Cobb said. ``But in a week or two, it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   While Cobb would like to see the track season extended two more
weeks, Sitton and Westminster boys coach Joe Tribble feel an extra
week in May would suffice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, seven to 10 days, that could make a difference,''
Tribble said. ``You'd have better weather and better training
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Change isn't likely to happen anytime soon. Georgia High School
Association executive director Tommy Guillebeau said no one has
proven to his satisfaction that an extended season would lead to
improved performances or more scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would consider a move, Guillebeau said, ``Why? Is it
going to make a real difference? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Our info shows that some schools will be dismissing
in the middle of May next year. We try to get everything we can
while school's still in session.''
</P>
<P>
   Including spring football, which some coaches blame for the
shortened season in spring sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same in North Carolina, Florida, here,'' Frye said.
``They've got to get enough time in before school lets out for
football. They cut the (track) season short.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillebeau said spring football has no impact on other spring
sports. The GHSA allows two weeks for spring football and this
year, it is scheduled from May 1-12. The boys' state meet is May
12-13 in Jefferson this season. No matter the reason, most coaches
would like to see a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my real regrets during my career is that the kids in
Georgia's season is so short,'' Cobb said. ``Rarely are our kids
able to post the best times. They don't reach their peak. They
don't get a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
