<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4764 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LANCASTER-FILM-$ADV07     05-03 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANCASTER-FILM-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURT LANCASTER'S BRAWNY MELANCHOLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 7)  
 By RICK MARIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In many ways, Burt Lancaster is the antithesis of the modern
leading man. Today's young actors build themselves the bodies of
athletes. He was an athlete who built himself into an actor. They
come from the schools of soft knocks (Harvard, Yale). He graduated
from De Witt Clinton High School, in New York City's Hell's
Kitchen. They went to the circus. He was in the circus.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster was both of his time _ a golden-age Movie Star _ and
way ahead of it. As an independent producer, he helped sabotage the
studio system that made him, at one time, the highest-paid actor in
the world. And yet, when he died, in 1994, at the age of 80, there
was no funeral or memorial service. That was his choice. But there
wasn't much in the way of public epitaph, either.
</P>
<P>
   In the final episode of ``Seinfeld,'' Kramer looks up into the
sky and says with even more than his usual brio: ``There's
something in the air. I can feel it!'' To which Jerry snidely
retorts, ``You know you're turning into Burt Lancaster?'' The man
who inspired such awe and trembling had become a punch line.
</P>
<P>
   A decade after his last appearance on the screen, attention is
being paid. Kate Buford's new biography, ``Burt Lancaster: An
American Life'' (Knopf), wants to reclaim relevancy for its
protagonist in all kinds of ways: as actor, indie producer,
possible bisexual. More straightforward proof of Lancaster's
lifetime achievement, as they say on the awards shows, is on view
at the Walter Reade Theater through May 18, in the Film Society of
Lincoln Center's retrospective, ``American Dreamer: Burt
Lancaster.'' Both the biography and filmography are overdue
tributes to what Vincent Canby once called `` Lancaster's
remarkable _ though not often remarked about _ career.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Lancaster's remarkable body and equally energetic mind
did him the disservice of lasting too long. His cap-toothed
charisma and immaculate diction seemed square once mumbling method
men like James Dean and Marlon Brando changed the game. After his
years as a prime specimen of hunkus Americanus _ Pauline Kael's
cutting coinage _ the movies didn't quite know what to do with him,
nor he with them. The nadir on this score may have been his
unfortunate foray into the disaster genre, ``Airport'' (1970),
justifiably spoofed in ``Airplane!''
</P>
<P>
   But he had an impressively long run, documented in the Film
Society's series, from his debut in ``The Killers'' (1946) and the
even more noir follow-up, ``Criss Cross'' (1947), the swashbuckling
of ``The Crimson Pirate'' (1952), ``From Here to Eternity'' (1953),
the Indians-and-cowboy reversal ``Apache'' (1954) and the double
whammy of ``Sweet Smell of Success'' and ``Gunfight at OK Corral''
(both 1957), then ``Elmer Gantry'' (1960), which won him his first
and only Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   The '60s and '70s _ Lancaster's middle period _ were less
sure-footed. The cerebral ``Birdman of Alcatraz'' (1962) gave way
to ill-advised experiments with facial hair and neckwear. A bid for
so-called international stardom was bracketed by two pictures
directed by Luchino Visconti, ``The Leopard'' (1963) and ``The
Conversation Piece'' (1974). Out of these years came many would-be
classics and one true one, ``The Swimmer'' (1968), an underrated
adaptation of John Cheever's short story of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   Late Lancaster started with ``Atlantic City'' (1980) and peaked
with ``Local Hero'' (1983). These lion-in-winter years are how many
younger moviegoers first got a load of him: a big, white-haired,
wild-eyed geezer or, as Buford more kindly suggests, ``like a
famous uncle who was once a great athlete.'' But as Buford so
extensively demonstrates, he was much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth of five children, Burton Stephen Lancaster was born
in 1913. His father worked at the post office, sang Irish songs and
took the kids to the zoo and Coney Island. His mother went from
black-Irish beauty to 250-pound terror. They lived on the second
floor of a narrow brownstone in East Harlem. After high school,
young Burt joined the circus with his gym buddy and lifelong crony,
Nick Cravat. Lancaster was good, not great, on the horizontal bar,
carneys later recalled. A marriage in 1935 to a female acrobat also
ended in 1935. World War II beckoned, and the USO. When the war
ended, he went West and made ``The Killers,'' Richard Siodmak's
hard-boiled elaboration on Ernest Hemingway's story about a
washed-up boxer with a price on his head.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Picture met with really great reception and seems pretty close
to what we dreamed about,'' the producer, Mark Hellinger, cabled
him after the first press screening. ``I'm afraid you're destined
to be a big star, you poor guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Picture was also the ideal Lancaster showpiece. It played to his
two sides: explosive physicality and melancholy. Three sides if you
count mixing it up with Ava Gardner. (Jackie Bone, Lancaster's
companion for many years, once described watching him on a golf
course, in repose, and thinking, ``there is one unhappy man.'') In
``Criss Cross'' he was again a good guy doomed to a bad end, if a
little too commanding and charismatic a presence to convincingly
play a loser. As Lancaster strides through an early scene in the
movie, the bartender mistakes him for a G-man liquor inspector, a
``checker.'' Disappointed, a female barfly gives Lancaster a
surprised once-over, purring, ``Swell looking, nicely built man
like that, a checker!''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-1 build would remain nice, lovingly preserved and on
display for many years to come. Hard to believe the lean, and very
mean, warrior hero of ``Apache'' was being played by a 40-year-old
man. In the new Technicolor print at Lincoln Center, the contrast
between his greasepaint Indian skin and blazing blue eyes almost
looks like a special effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burt Lancaster is 52,'' Cheever wrote in a letter when ``The
Swimmer'' went into production in 1967. ``Lithe, comely and
somewhat disfigured by surgical incisions and he looks both young
and old, masterful and tearful.'' Lancaster could barely swim when
he took the part of Ned Merrill, a Connecticut suburbanite with an
unspoken secret who swims home through his neighbors' pools as the
weather _ and neighbors _ get colder and darker. But he trained
scrupulously (as he had for ``Jim Thorpe: All-American''), hiring
the coach of the UCLA men's water polo team because he didn't want
to ``insult'' real smimmers in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   He never tried to disown the action-man stuff but was always
eager to play against type, on the screen and off. By 1947, he
already had his own production company, Norma Productions (named
after his second wife). Work with the producer Harold Hecht led to
a new entity, Hecht-Lancaster. Their partnership contributed to the
seismic power shift from the studios to the actors or, more
accurately, their agents. Lancaster's agent was the godfather
himself, MCA's Lew Wasserman. With Wasserman advising and wetting
his beak, Hecht and Lancaster made serious, sometimes political
films in black and white while living large in offices decorated
with El Grecos and adjustable waterfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Their big-screen version of Paddy Chayefsky's television drama
``Marty'' swept the 1956 Oscars _ the same year Lancaster starred
in ``Trapeze,'' a sentimental ode to the big top co-starring Tony
Curtis. The two movies might as well have been made on different
planets.
</P>
<P>
   These two stars had worked together before: Curtis had an
uncredited bit part as a gigolo in ``Criss Cross.'' But the
collaboration people remember is ``Sweet Smell of Success,''
produced by Hecht-Hill-Lancaster. (James Hill, a writer, producer
and world-class hanger-on, made the company a troika.) Too
gimlet-eyed for moviegoers and many critics when it came out,
``Sweet Smell'' ruthlessly unmasked the unholy alliance between
journalism and publicity at a time when people did not speak of
such things. We're still in that time, come to think of it.
</P>
<P>
   The principal characters are J.J. Hunsecker, an all-powerful
columnist modeled on Walter Winchell, and Sidney Falco, the
ambitious press agent in the great man's thrall. Lancaster is in
full cerebral mode as Hunsecker, physically almost inert, while
Curtis dances around him. In many of the most famous scenes, he is
sitting down, staring up through glasses smeared with vaseline to
further fog the windows to a darkened soul. Based on a novella by
Ernest Lehmann, a former press agent who had been one of Winchell's
gofers, the screenplay was taken to the next level of crackling
cynicism by Clifford Odets. Odets, in full ``Barton Fink'' mode,
was on his last legs career-wise but still able to dash off on-set
rewrites like Falco's ``the cat's in the bag and the bag's in the
river.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost every line in the movie seems memorable, either because
of the words or their delivery. Hunsecker's exultation, ``I love
this dirty town.'' Falco announcing, ``From now on the best of
everything is good enough for me,'' and, to his naive secretary:
``This is life. Get used to it.'' Originally, the partners had
thought of Orson Welles for Hunsecker until Lancaster said, ``What
about me?'' It wasn't a stretch. He had already become a maniacal
control freak, with a reputation as ``one of the rudest individuals
in Hollywood,'' Look magazine reported in 1953. He womanized _ and
manized, if we are to believe the rumors. His mean streak could
reduce huge stars to tears. He supposedly made his friend and
fellow ex-acrobat Kirk Douglas cry by making fun of the lifts in
his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Mackendrick, imported from England to direct ``Sweet
Smell,'' bore the brunt of Lancaster's rages. One choice incident
that Mackendrick relates in Buford's book:
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been drinking a little. Burt started shouting at me _ and
he's scary. Then he came at me across the room with that
coiled-spring animal energy, like a panther, and vaulted over a
sofa in one of the most graceful movements I've ever seen, [as if)
to attack me. I stood up and said, `No, Burt,' and he stopped. That
took every atom of performance possible. The reason I had the
strength was that just as he came across the sofa I thought, `He's
beautiful!'''
</P>
<P>
   It was a turning point. ```Sweet Smell of Success' destroyed us
all,'' Mackendrick said near the end of his life. Lancaster was
never quite that beautiful or powerful again, even though he had
yet to turn down the unprecedented offer of $1 million for
``Ben-Hur'' and was still three years away from his Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Malle got a taste of Bad Burt two decades later when he
cast him as the broken-down old gangster in ``Atlantic City.'' But
this time, Burt was in no position to be hurdling furniture. In
1980, Lancaster was 63, and his big, broad style could not have
been more out of style. Early requests by Malle to tone down line
readings drew tantrums. ``OK, we'll do it the way the little
froggie wants it, and then we'll do it the way it should be done,''
Lancaster railed on the set one day, in front of the director. To
his credit, he realized Malle was right, modulated his performance
and was nominated for an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   How sad that the Buford biography has to play the sex card to
validate Lancaster's currency _ as if bisexuality makes him modern.
The naked rear-view still from ``The Swimmer'' seems like a fairly
obvious and cheesy plea for publicity. You want current?. Watch the
movies. There is no sadder statement about suburbia than ``The
Swimmer,'' no inmate in HBO's ``Oz'' as complex as the Birdman, and
no villain more hep than J.J. Hunsecker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
