<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY MICROSOFT EXECUTIVE FINDS HIS `OTHER LIFE' MORE ALLURING 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nathan P. Myhrvold, the chief technology officer of Microsoft
Corp., announced his departure on Wednesday, joining a wave of
executives and senior engineers who have left the company in the
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Myhrvold's exit, however, is not a big surprise. He had been on
a leave of absence since last July, and many industry analysts had
predicted it would become permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure,'' Myhrvold said on Wednesday. ``But, of course,
there is always the possibility that when a guy takes a year off
he'll find that other life more attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   For Myhrvold, 40, the other life has included digging for
dinosaurs in eastern Montana as part of a five-year expedition he
helped finance.
</P>
<P>
   Myhrvold joined Microsoft in 1986 and has held many positions,
but was always a close adviser to Bill Gates, the chairman,
suggesting new ideas and new directions for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Myhrvold brought to that task a wide-ranging intellect and
breadth of interests. He did post-doctoral research in cosmology at
Cambridge University under the physicist Stephen Hawking. He has
written articles for Nature, The New Yorker and Vanity Fair on
everything from paleontology to the pleasures of owning a private
jet. He is an accomplished chef, having studied at French cooking
schools.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Myhrvold founded Microsoft Research, a unit that now
has a worldwide staff of 500 researchers. Critics say Microsoft has
little to show for its investment so far, but the company says work
from the research group can be found inside its operating systems,
database, Internet media and electronic-book software.
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming chief technology officer in 1996, Myhrvold was
the group executive in charge of Microsoft's online and new media
efforts. But Microsoft eventually pulled back from trying to be a
media company as it failed to make any real progress against
America Online. In early 1999, after a management reorganization,
Myhrvold was no longer a member of the executive team that reported
directly to Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Myhrvold has founded a company called Intellectual Ventures and
has invested in an Internet company and a couple of biotechnology
start-ups. He will continue as a part-time adviser to Gates, who
said Myhrvold's contributions over the years had been ``critical''
to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Myhrvold's departure, Microsoft announced on
Wednesday that Rick Rashid has been named senior vice president for
Microsoft Research. Rashid joined Microsoft in 1991 from Carnegie
Mellon University and has been largely responsible for building the
research group up to its current size.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Ling, a former researcher at IBM's Watson Labs, who came to
Microsoft in 1992, was named vice president for research.
</P>
</TEXT>
