<HEADER>
A4770 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      05-03 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURN DOWN TURNOVER COSTS BY GIVING EMPLOYEES MORE OPPORTUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How ya gonna keep 'em on the farm?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe by letting them work a different field.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that complain mightily about high staff turnover rates
may have their own human resource policies to blame. They make it
too difficult for employees to explore job opportunities within the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Some organizations have rules designed to prevent managers from
one division or department from raiding talented employees from
another operating unit. They don't let managers solicit
applications from someone else's domain.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, these rules also say employees can't apply to other
units without alerting their current managers.
</P>
<P>
   Such rules are reasonable in that they lessen the chance of
nasty turf battles and blindsided staffing disruptions. But there's
a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The real effect sometimes is that excellent employees choose to
look outside the company for new opportunities rather than travel
the time-consuming and politically dangerous route to an in-house
job change.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, some employees stay in jobs they've outgrown or don't
like because they fear the political repercussions of internal
change. They lose out on new challenges, plus the possibility of a
better raise than they'd get by staying put. The company loses,
too, when a good job candidate gives up.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the worst cases, current managers are allowed to veto or
hold up job transfers for months on the grounds that their
operations would be hurt by the departure. What happens then?
All-around disgruntlement.
</P>
<P>
   With staff turnover consistently ranking as a top corporate
human resource problem, it's time to demolish barriers to in-house
transfers. The very rules designed to reduce staff disruption may
be causing more disruption than they prevent.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, the U.S. workplace is becoming a ``free agent''
economy. Workers today, especially younger, techno-savvy workers,
are changing jobs _ and will change jobs _ far more frequently than
the World War II or baby boom generations. They leave when they're
unchallenged or bored in their current work assignments.
</P>
<P>
   If providing an interesting and variable career path to a good
worker isn't enough reason to facilitate interdepartmental
transfers, then maybe money talks. It costs companies a lot more to
hire and train people from outside than it does to accommodate
in-house changes.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the 1990s, the typical U.S. corporate worker
received a 4 percent annual raise. The surer way to a bigger raise
was to change jobs, but reluctance to lose tenure and benefits kept
many workers from testing the job market. In-house transfers let
workers retain tenure and prospect for better pay or opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing: Because companies usually have to pay more to
lure new hires on board than they pay to current workers in the
same positions, that pay disparity breeds morale problems with
existing staff.
</P>
<P>
   When employees can test their marketability through in-house
transfers, they sample the free-agent action without abandoning
their employer _ and that's profitable for all concerned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4772 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CENSUS-RETURNS-ART-NY     05-03 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-RETURNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONGER RESPONSE BY MINORITIES HELPS IMPROVE CENSUS REPLY RATE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif., Idaho, Minn., Wis., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Helped by a surprisingly strong response from
Hispanics and other minorities, the Census Bureau has halted a long
slide in response rates and received answers from nearly two-thirds
of the households that got a census form in the mail this year.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary figures from the agency show that despite widespread
complaints about its questionnaires, especially the long form
received by a sixth of all households, 65.9 percent of all
households replied as of April 30. Census officials estimate that
the final response rate may be as high as 67 percent, compared with
a mail-back rate of 65 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Though small, the improvement over 1990 represents the reversal
of a three-decade decline in the proportion of American households
that have returned the questionnaire. In 1970, 83 percent of
households receiving the forms responded; in 1980, 75 percent did
so. And the improvement occurs as other indices of civic
engagement, like voting and volunteer work, have been in steep
declines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure some of this mobilization to get people to fill out
their forms was about how you help your communities,'' Kenneth
Prewitt, the census director, said. ``That's a positive sign when
you get people to take responsibility for their communities. It's a
foundation to try to do something about the cynicism and
indifference that we all complain about.''
</P>
<P>
   The new figures provide powerful evidence of the effectiveness
of a vigorous advertising campaign the agency mounted to persuade a
jaded and skeptical public to fill out the forms. The campaign has
aimed heavily at minority groups and focused heavily on the
advantages of increasing census tallies, which are used to steer
many federal programs to local communities.
</P>
<P>
   Polling data indicate that households that were heavily exposed
to the bureau's marketing effort were much more likely to send back
the form, even though these same households were more prone to
consider the questions an invasion of their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   As has always been the case, neighborhoods and states whose
residents tended to be overwhelmingly white still had a higher
response rate than those areas with more members of minority
groups.
</P>
<P>
   But census data show that areas where the majority of households
are black held their own and that census tracts where Hispanic
residents are the majority or where no ethnic or racial group is
more than 50 percent sharply improved their performance over 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, census bureau figures indicate that the biggest declines
in participation occurred in areas whose residents were largely
white or Asian American.
</P>
<P>
   For example, California, a state where racial and ethnic
minorities make up nearly half of the population, posted the
biggest growth in the response rate, rising to 68 percent this
year, compared to 65 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But Minnesota, Wisconsin, Iowa and Idaho _ which have relatively
few minorities _ all saw sharp declines in the number of households
that returned census questionnaires.
</P>
<P>
   ``To oversimply things, in terms of response rates, whites
performed slightly less well than they did in 1990; Hispanics and
blacks out-performed their 1990 experience,'' said Steve Jost, the
Census Bureau's associate director for communications.
</P>
<P>
   The high rates of response is a welcome relief to census
officials, whose original projections anticipated a response rate
of 61 percent. The 5 percentage points of higher response will save
the bureau millions of dollars in labor costs because it will need
fewer census takers to visit the homes of residents who did not
mail back their forms. Census takers have already begun making
those visits.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials cautioned that the results were based on a
compilation of the mail that the bureau has received back. Those
forms have not yet been read to determine if they were fully
completed. Any household that did not complete its form will still
be visited by a census taker.
</P>
<P>
   The performance should quiet some of the bureau's critics, who
have expressed concerns about its ability to carry out the census.
But it will do little if anything to quell the debate about the use
of statistical sampling methods to correct for a potential
undercount.
</P>
<P>
   Information on response rates among states comes from publicly
available data listed on the Census Bureau's World Wide Web site
(www.census.gov). Data on the response from different ethnic and
racial groups come from bureau's internal analysis of returns from
the country's more than 61,000 census tracts _ neighborhoods each
containing roughly 4,000 residents _ that was provided to The New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau officials emphasized that some figures were
preliminary and subject to change, though they added that they
doubted that any changes would alter the overall conclusions very
much.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the improvement is due to the determined effort to
increase the response rate in California. Early in the planning
process, census officials estimated that 58 percent of the
households in the state that received a form would mail it back.
But state officials mounted a major campaign that included
appropriating $24 million to raise the response rate.
</P>
<P>
   By April 4 _ the latest date for detailed figures _ the response
rate for California was 68 percent, more than 1.4 million
households than original estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just delighted,'' said Linda Gage, the state's official
demographer. ``Only 12 states had better mail response rates than
we did and only Massachusetts, which is much smaller, exceed our
improvement in mail response rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau officials did not offer any theories for the
racial and ethnic differences in response rates. But a polling
company in Menlo Park, Calif., that was hired by a number of
foundations to assess the bureau's outreach efforts has produced
data indicating that the bureau's marketing and advertising
campaign resonated much more strongly among minorities than it did
with whites.
</P>
<P>
   The polling company, InterSurvey, found that 31 percent of the
black and 33 percent of the Hispanic households it surveyed said
they had ``high levels'' of exposure to the bureau's campaign,
compared with 16 percent of white households.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Noting their success at reversing a major trend, census
officials have grumbled that the White House has failed to express
appreciation for their achievement.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, in a slightly veiled reference to the White
House as well as congressional leaders, Prewitt said that
``national leaders'' had missed the opportunity to use the census
to engage the public in a discussion of its rights and
responsibilities and to trumpet a government program that had
accomplished what it set out to do.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn B. Maloney of Manhattan, who is the ranking
Democrat on the House Subcommittee on the Census, said that
President Clinton ought to extend more credit to the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole administration should be proud of the good work that
the Census Bureau has done,'' Maloney said. ``They should say so,
and I hope they will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
