u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      05-03 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major Market Gauges Drop On Interest Rates Concerns
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices fell after the government reported that factory
orders in March were higher than expected and a Federal Reserve
survey showed intensifying wage pressures. Both reports increased
anxiety about the Fed's May 16 meeting, at which it is expected to
raise interest rates for the sixth time since June. The Dow Jones
industrial average fell 250.99 points, or 2.3 percent, to
10,480.13. The Nasdaq composite index dropped 78.14 points, or 2.1
percent, to 3,707.31, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
was off 31.19 points, or 2.2 percent, to 1,415.10. The yield on the
two-year note rose to 6.74 percent and is the highest it has been
in 5 years. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond jumped to 6.11
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another Microsoft Executive Quits
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Myhrvold, the chief technology officer of Microsoft,
announced that he will leave the software company. He had been on a
leave of absence from Microsoft since last July, and many analysts
predicted it would become permanent. ``I wasn't sure,'' he said.
``But, of course, there is always the possibility that when a guy
takes a year off he'll find that other life more attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's Top Banks in Merger Talks
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's largest financial group, Banacci, has begun merger
talks with Bancomer, the country's second-largest financial group.
The entity that would result if the merger were successful would be
Latin America's largest, with nearly $60 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch Daughter to Leave BSkyB
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old daughter of Rupert Murdoch, Elisabeth Murdoch,
is quitting the company her father controls, British Sky
Broadcasting, at the end of June to start a media venture of her
own in London. Her departure may signal the end of a rivalry
between her and her two brothers, Lachlan and James, to succeed
their father as chairman of News Corp., which owns 40 percent of
BSkyB, which is Europe's No. 2 pay television concern.
</P>
<P>
   Disney Profits Exceed Expectations
</P>
<P>
   Profits rose 66 percent at Walt Disney Co. on higher advertising
sales at ABC. Net income jumped to $161 million, or 8 cents a
share, from adjusted earnings of $97 million, or 5 cents a share,
in the period a year earlier. Excluding Go.com, Disney earned 18
cents a share; analysts had expected 14 cents. Still, its shares
fell $1.25, to $41.25. Revenue rose 14 percent to $6.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Metallica Pursues Napster
</P>
<P>
   Fight Representatives of the heavy-metal band Metallica went to
the headquarters of Napster with 13 boxes of papers said to list
more than 300,000 computer users who recently had downloaded
Metallica music without the band's permission. Napster said it
would review the papers and take steps to disable those users
Metallica identified if the claims had been properly submitted.
</P>
<P>
   New Bottle, New Ads for Lipton
</P>
<P>
   Lipton's Iced Tea, seeking to shore up its eroding market share,
will soon have a new bottle and a new campaign, its first major
advertising effort for the brand in four years. The strategy is to
differentiate Lipton's Iced Tea, which has a 9.5 percent share of
sales of all ready-to-drink bottled and canned teas, from its main
competitor, Snapple, which has a 14.6 percent share.
</P>
<P>
   Magazine Industry Honors Itself
</P>
<P>
   In a rough year for the magazine industry, the tone at the
National Magazine Awards presentation could have been one of
uncertainty. Instead, the ceremony, which held a few surprises,
sounded more like an evening of stand-up comedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
