<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-COMEDY-865&AMP;ADD-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR AND JOKING ON THE LATE-NIGHT CAMPAIGN TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 7) 
 By PETER MARKS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes, even the professionals have to avert their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could barely watch it,'' Vance DeGeneres, a veteran comedy
writer and performer on Comedy Central's ``Daily Show,'' said of
the incident on ``Late Show with David Letterman.'' ``It was almost
like watching those films where they're clubbing the baby seal to
death.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``it'' was, perhaps, the most uncomfortable moment of
political humor of the television season. After weeks of goading by
Letterman, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas agreed to appear by
satellite on his show, an encounter that was, by most assessments,
a disaster for the Republican presidential candidate. Bush,
hampered by the split-second time delay and projecting an air of
being led on a forced march, offered one lame quip after another,
including a pun about Letterman's recent heart operation so
strained that it left the host staring, mortified, into the camera.
</P>
<P>
   The episode was instructive not only about how truly dangerous a
tete-a-tete with a witty talk-show host can be, but also about how
much clout television comedy wields in the shaping of political
perceptions. In a recent survey by the Pew Research Center for the
People and the Press, roughly one in 10 Americans said they
routinely gleaned information about the presidential race from
late-night talk shows like the ones presided over by Letterman and
Jay Leno; nearly as many said that they regularly obtained
political news from other shows, like ``Saturday Night Live'' and
``Politically Incorrect,'' ``The Daily Show'' and ``Mad TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The proportion of viewers admitting that they get their politics
from television comedy may not be overwhelming. But considering
that the 1996 presidential election was decided by a mere eight
percentage points, what each and every consumer of comedy on
television takes away from the experience can be highly
significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to believe that,'' said Dick Blasucci, the executive
producer of ``Mad TV,'' Fox's Saturday night comedy show. ``Look:
what killed Dan Quayle was the beating up by Jay Leno and others.
I'm not saying they were taking sides, but I do think that kind of
stuff leaves an impression.''
</P>
<P>
   Having a serious impact on real events is, of course, the last
thing on the minds of most of the writers and performers of
political satire on television. ``I just want the politicians and
the people who watch our show to know that this is a place where
the buck honestly stops,'' said Bill Maher, the no-nonsense host of
``Politically Incorrect,'' ABC's free-wheeling after-hours
talkfest. Still, as the Bush appearance on ``Letterman''
illustrates, political comedy relies ever more intensively on the
willing (and in some instances unwitting) participation of actual
officeholders and officeseekers.
</P>
<P>
   That is attributable, at least in part, to the blurring of the
line between politics and entertainment, a boundary that has been
fading since the psychedelic days of ``Rowan and Martin's
Laugh-In,'' on which, in 1968, a dour politician by the name of
Richard M. Nixon, in a startling cameo, uttered the show's stock
phrase, ``Sock it to me?'' into the camera. If self-mockery once
seemed a bit of an indignity for politicians, nowadays they jump at
the chance to make 'em laugh. Members of Congress appear as
panelists along with country singers, rappers and actors on
``Politically Incorrect.'' Former presidential candidates _ even
former presidents _ show up at benefits as agreeable sidekicks to
their ``Saturday Night Live'' impersonators.
</P>
<P>
   C-Span has gotten into the act, broadcasting an annual evening
of stand-up comedy from Washington, in which reporters like Walter
Shapiro of USA Today and lawmakers like Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut perform their 10 minutes of shtick. And in what may
just be the slyest marriage of politics and comedy on television,
``The Daily Show,'' the satirical four-nights-a-week news and talk
show with the comedian Jon Stewart as host, has hired the former
Sen. Bob Dole as a commentator. ( Dole declined an interview
request.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Daily Show,'' with its deadpan reports from a comic corral
of field correspondents and sidelong glances at the day's
headlines, has developed a reputation for offering some of the
shrewdest political foolery on the small screen. ``We had a blast
working with them,'' said Todd Harris, who served as press
secretary for the New Hampshire primary campaign of Sen. John
McCain, to which ``The Daily Show'' attached one of its performers,
Steve Carell, for a mock news piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the piece came out, we had a tape of it on board the
Straight Talk Express,'' Harris said, ``and every couple of weeks
or so Senator McCain stopped everything and said, `Let's watch the
``Comedy Central'' tape!'''
</P>
<P>
   The segment followed Carell's exploits as he tried vainly to get
a seat on McCain's bus, a conceit that was inherently funny: McCain
had become instantly legendary for the generous access he provided
to the press. ``So there was a very humorous irony there,'' Harris
said, ``but there was also a deeper irony in the fact that we were
a serious presidential campaign, allowing them to partake of this
irony.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
