<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4778 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-POLITICAL-COMEDY-$ADV     05-03 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-COMEDY-$ADV07-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: this irony.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was just the sort of piece that ``The Daily Show,'' and its
ongoing ``Indecision 2000'' election coverage, revels in. For the
past 16 months, the program's anchor desk has been manned by
Stewart. (Before that, it was the perch of Craig Kilborn, whose
talk show now follows Letterman's on CBS.) Stewart, along with
Madeleine Smithberg, the executive producer, oversees a staff of 60
writers, producers and technicians who work out of the show's
headquarters on a desolate midtown Manhattan side street a block
from the West Side Highway. The 30-minute program is a kind of
comic cocktail of reality and parody. ``We are a fake news
organization,'' Stewart said, ``but we feel the ups and downs that
real news organizations feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart sets a benign tone with political guests. There is a
compassionate quality to his interviews that reflects a higher
level of affection for politics than that displayed in the cranky
irreverence of Letterman or the jokey, disconnected chatter of
Leno. ``I believe if these people come on our show, they should
have the respect they're owed by virtue of the office they're in,''
Stewart said. ``I want them to feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, in fact, has gained a following in political circles
for its hipness and sense of fun. ``He is so fast, if he were a
shortstop, he would pick up everything,'' Rep. Dennis Kucinich,
D-Ohio, said of Stewart. ``And he realizes that he is prospecting
in very rich territory.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Politically Incorrect,'' Maher's style is decidedly less
ingratiating: he puts everyone on the hot seat. ``Not that I insult
the movie stars, but my show lives on the premise that I never pull
a punch,'' he said. As a result, he says, some potential political
guests remain leery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan Quayle was booked on our show recently and then pulled
out,'' Maher said, adding that he was told that ``something I
said'' about the former vice president had upset his handlers and
that ``they wanted me to apologize.'' Maher declined.
</P>
<P>
   He is aware, though, that his blunt style has power. Asked, for
instance, if he had invited Bush on his show, Maher laughed at the
improbability of such an appearance. ``I've been so hard on him,''
he said. (He added that he was not a fan of Vice President Al Gore,
either.)
</P>
<P>
   It may be just as well that Bush steers clear of the program,
given his performance on ``Letterman,'' a show that has become a
kind of political proving ground. Gerard Mulligan, a longtime staff
writer, said that Letterman ``discovered inadvertently'' just how
gravely candidates respond to his comic denunciations. For weeks,
he complained on the air about Hillary Rodham Clinton's refusal to
appear on the show after announcing her campaign for the Senate
seat from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `The road to the Senate goes through this chair,' a
spur-of-the-moment thing,'' Mulligan recalled. Soon enough, Clinton
was seated opposite Letterman and submitting to a pop civics test
about New York, in which the host quizzed her on the name of the
state tree and bird.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of how important a sense of humor on camera has
become to political discourse that candidates feel real pressure to
perform. As Clinton all but said to Letterman, her appearance on
his show was as obligatory a part of her race as a whistle-stop
tour of the Western tier. The tacit and attractive acknowledgment
to voters in such a booking is that a candidate is serious about
running but not so serious about themselves. ``You have to prove
you're a good sport,'' Mulligan said.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of a political personality able to give as good as he
gets was what appealed to ``Daily Show'' honchos about signing on
Dole, who has been called on for commentary on the program's
expanded, hourlong coverage of pivotal campaign events. On the
campaign trail, Dole's barbs sometimes came across as a little too
sharp, but they are welcomed by Stewart and company. His hiring
brings the phenomenon full circle: the politician as television
entertainer about the political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory on Dole,'' Smithberg said, ``is that he's like the
lawyer who is secretly a musician. Law is the job. And there are
these other muscles he always wanted to flex.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
