<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-CBS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL REGULATORS APPROVE VIACOM'S MERGER DEAL WITH CBS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif., Ill., Md., Texas) By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal officials Wednesday approved the largest
broadcast merger in history _ Viacom Inc.'s $30 billion acquisition
of CBS _ just a day after two other media giants resolved a dispute
that was, in large part, a byproduct of consolidation in the
broadcasting and cable industry.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the Federal Communications Commission to approve
a merger that will give Viacom control of 35 percent of the
broadcasting market represents the high-water mark of a Clinton
administration policy of promoting consolidation in a number of
industries as a way of encouraging competition. It was immediately
hailed by top executives of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Sumner M. Redstone, the chairman and chief executive of Viacom,
said that the acquisition would be completed on Thursday morning
and that CBS' ticker symbol would never again be trading on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has really worked perfectly,'' an ebullient Redstone said
in an interview Wednesday afternoon. ``We basically got everything
we had wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration's policy of permitting consolidation in the
telecommunications industry will be on display again later this
month, when the FCC is expected to approve a staff recommendation
to permit AT&AMP;T to complete its acquisition of MediaOne, giving it
control of more than a third of the cable industry. Many experts
expect that the Justice Department, which is reviewing that deal
for antitrust issues, will also approve it.
</P>
<P>
   The policy is rooted in the notion that a few corporate
behemoths battling over control of the market can be both more
efficient and more competitive than any regulation and control from
bureaucrats in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think big is per se bad,'' said Joel I. Klein, the
assistant attorney general in charge of the Justice Department's
antitrust division. ``We analyze mergers in terms of relevant
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   But such mergers do not always come without a price. The policy
helped both the Walt Disney Co., ABC's parent company, and Time
Warner grow into formidable broadcasting and distribution companies
in recent years. But this week, some 3.5 million customers of Time
Warner cable television lost their ABC signal for almost two days
as the two companies wrangled over retransmission agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation has created bottlenecks that have made it
easier for one company to block the access of another. Moreover,
government officials and industry analysts say negotiations between
Time Warner and ABC had grown more strained following Time Warner's
announcement that it intended to merge with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after approving the merger of Viacom and CBS, the FCC
ruled that Time Warner had violated a regulation that prohibits a
company from removing a network's signal during the sweeps rating
month and said it would consider what penalty to impose. The fine
will be symbolic, as the agency can only penalize the company
$7,500 for each violation each day.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer groups say the larger lesson from this week's
events is that further consolidation of the cable and broadcast
industries will lead to similar disputes and blackouts, as the
survivors struggle to control both the content and distribution of
what appears on television and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of dominant players in telecommunications and
other industries dwindle, some regulators are also beginning to
question how much further the government should go in approving
large pending deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite often the best consumer competition comes from big
companies fiercely competing against each other,'' said Robert
Pitofsky, chairman of the Federal Trade Commission. ``But in some
sectors of the economy, we are running out of big companies.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky declined to discuss his agency's review of the proposed
merger of America Online with Time Warner. But other government
officials said Wednesday that Time Warner's decision to remove ABC
this week from its cable systems had undermined the companies'
repeated pronouncements when the merger was announced that they
would never attempt to shut out others from using their enormous
Internet and cable backbone.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In approving Viacom's acquisition of CBS, the regulators gave
the companies a year to come into compliance with a rule that
prohibits a television network from having an ownership interest in
a second network. Viacom holds an interest in the fledgling UPN,
and some experts predict that the agency may relax the dual network
rule over the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom will also have a year to meet the national television
ownership cap, which prohibits a company from controlling more than
35 percent of the broadcast market. The combined reach of CBS and
Viacom is now more than 41 percent. As part of the regulatory
order, the companies will have six months to sell some radio and
television stations in the Los Angeles, Chicago, Baltimore,
Sacramento and Dallas-Fort Worth areas.
</P>
<P>
   But those divestitures are relatively small pieces of the deal,
which involves the transfer of 38 television stations and more than
160 radio stations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With a few exceptions, regulators during the Clinton years have
signed off on big mergers, many of which would have been
unimaginable a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In merger law, the Clinton administration has a great deal in
common with the Reagan and Bush years,'' said John Shepard Wiley
Jr., a law professor at the University of California at Los
Angeles. ``The analysis has become bipartisan.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in the 1960s, the Justice Department successfully
blocked one deal that would have resulted in a grocery store merger
that would have resulted in a company controlling 7.5 percent of
the industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
