<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNORTHODOX MOVE BY DRYSDALE PUTS FAVORITE OUTSIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ An unorthodox choice by trainer Neil Drysdale
means Kentucky Derby favorite Fusaichi Pegasus will break from post
position 16 in Saturday's 20-horse race.
</P>
<P>
   A blind draw gave Fusaichi Pegasus' braintrust the 12th pick in
the ``draft'' Churchill Downs has instituted in recent years to
make the post-selection process more telegenic. When it came time
to decide, posts 1, 2, 11, 12 and 16-20 were available. Most
horsemen would have gone with 11 or 12 _ neither far inside, at the
risk of being boxed in, nor far outside, in danger of losing
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale hung the placard in Fusaichi Pegasus' owner's colors on
No.16.
</P>
<P>
   Derby horses enter the gate two at a time _ post 1 and 11, then
2 and 12, and so on. Drysdale said he hoped to avoid having
Fusaichi Pegasus wait for too many horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out in the clear and hopefully can stay out of trouble,''
explained Drysdale, the newly elected Racing Hall of Famer known
for offbeat approaches. ``He's a good gate horse, but I didn't want
him to be standing in the gate for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision allowed Santa Anita Derby winner The Deputy's
connections, choosing 15th, to slip into a comfortable post 11.
They considered that a lucky break.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he (Drysdale) is telling us is that he's concerned about
it (Fusaichi Pegasus' behavior), even though he's said all week he
isn't,'' said Jeff Siegel, the Southern California handicapper who
is a part-owner of The Deputy. ``One reason we chose the 11 hole is
that we didn't want to be next to his antics.''
</P>
<P>
   Churchill morning-line maker Mike Battaglia pegged Fusaichi
Pegasus as a 9-5 favorite, with The Deputy next at 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   As offbeat as Drysdale's selection was, post 16 has produced
winners Thunder Gulch (1995) and Charismatic (1999). Three of the
past five Derby winners came from the auxiliary starting gate _
posts 15 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve landed the first pick in a blind draw and trainer
Bob Baffert chose post 8. War Chant, Drysdale's other Derby horse,
went second, and jockey Jerry Bailey chose post 9.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Grass Stakes winner High Yield (post 18) will start
farthest outside of any contender.
</P>
<P>
   The odd horse out when the field was trimmed to 20 was Unshaded.
The $150,000 that owner Jim Tafel put up to make the Lexington
Stakes winner a supplemental nominee was refunded. Dubai-based
Curule got in when Harlan Traveler wasn't entered.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTIFUL: Churchill Downs announced a Derby-day forecast of
scattered thunderstorms and a high of 85 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   FRANKEL'S COLT WORKS: Aptitude went half a mile in :47 1/5 in
what probably was the week's last workout by a major Derby horse.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, trainer Bobby Frankel has Robbie Albarado ride Aptitude
in workouts, although he's the jockey for Bob Baffert-trained
Captain Steve. Frankel said he has confidence in Albarado and uses
him in Kentucky races.
</P>
<P>
   Albarado said the workout ``didn't take anything out of him
(Aptitude). He's a consistent finisher. He's definitely going to be
a threat. (But) I'm not going to ride (Captain Steve) any
different.''
</P>
<P>
   HAPPY TALK: Cot Campbell, whose Dogwood Stable has Trippi and
Impeachment, on long-range planning: ``I've heard people say
they'll skip the Derby and have a better horse in the fall. Well,
we might all be dead in the fall.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
