<SLUG> BC-OYSTER-BAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OYSTER BAR THAT GOES BACK 125,000 YEARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TODD ACKERMAN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) A team of scientists has discovered the earliest
example of an oyster bar: a fossil reef on Africa's Red Coast where
early man dined on clams, crabs, oysters and scallops.
</P>
<P>
   The unearthing of small stone blades and hand-sized stones with
sharpened edges pushes back to roughly 125,000 years ago the first
documentation of ancestral humans adapting to a marine environment
and a new food source. The earliest example of shellfish
consumption had been thought to be 10,000 years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important discovery because it is the oldest
documentation in the world of marine resources and a major new
adaptive strategy,'' said Richard T. Buffler, a University of Texas
professor of geological sciences and senior research scientist at
the UT Institute for Geophysics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also points up the importance of coastal environments as
previously overlooked study sites.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery, reported in this week's journal Nature, suggests
that early humans were essentially forced out of their native
habitat in the interior of Africa because a change in climate dried
up the lakes and rivers they relied on for food, said Buffler.
</P>
<P>
   It also suggests that man may have eventually left Africa along
the Red Sea rather than going up the Nile River valley, as is
traditionally assumed.
</P>
<P>
   As such, it supports the ``out of Africa'' theory _ the view
accepted by most scientists _ that humans evolved from a common
ancestor in Africa 100,000 to 200,000 years ago. A competing theory
is that modern humans evolved semi-independently in Africa, Europe
and Asia 100,000 to 40,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The once-submerged barrier reef in which the tools were
embedded, about seven miles long and 15 to 40 feet above current
sea level, was located near the village of Abdur, Eritrea, on the
Gulf of Zula in northeast Africa. The team found evidence of the
tools during an unrelated 1997 African trip, then came back two
years later to do the research.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers also found fossils of large land mammals such as
elephants, rhinos and hippos. The ancient humans may have trapped
the animals against the sea and butchered them there, the
scientists speculated.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists found no evidence of who made the tools likely
used to remove shellfish from boulders and to crack or pry open
shells.
</P>
<P>
   The age of the stone tools was estimated by radioactive dating
of fossil corals found closest to them. Though some isolated
specimens of hand axes have been found on other marine terraces in
Eritrea and the Egyptian coast, none had been found embedded in
rock, allowing it to be dated.
</P>
<P>
   Buffler said the team is soliciting funds for a hoped-for
research trip back to the site next winter. Such a team would
include archaeologists and paleontologists as well as geologists.
</P>
<P>
   Berhane Negassi Ghebretensae, a University of Texas graduate
student from Eritrea, also participated in the project.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
