<HEADLINE>
SAMMY GLICK'S LONG RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 7) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Budd Schulberg dreamed up Sammy Glick _ the
ultimate Hollywood wheeler-dealer, ``a little ferret of a kid,
sharp and quick'' _ back in the 1930s, he meant his novel, ``What
Makes Sammy Run?,'' to be seen in part as a cautionary tale. Back
then, Sammy Glick was the villain of the piece, the awful example
of what might happen if you let individualism and free enterprise
run away with you. Yes, Sammy was a product of his environment
(``in the midst of a war that was selfish, ruthless and cruel,
Sammy was proving himself the fittest, the fiercest and the
fastest'') and perhaps readers did pity him, a bit. But they
definitely did not want to be him.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the 1970s did Schulberg notice the beginnings of a
``180-degree turn in our national attitude toward Sammy.'' By 1989,
when he wrote an afterword to a new paperback edition of the novel,
the author noted that Sammy's rap was being heard much differently
by the young faces he saw in the college classes he addressed.
``The book I had written as an angry expose of Sammy Glick was
becoming a character reference,'' Schulberg wrote. He remembered
one student telling him how much he admired Sammy Glick's ruthless
rise to the top. ``He put out his hand, the hand that would soon be
knifing friends and colleagues in the back,'' Schulberg wrote. ``As
I took it hesitantly, I asked myself, What have I done?''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Schulberg said, the 11 years between writing that
afterword and today have been even more disheartening. Back then,
the young Sammy Glicks he encountered would acknowledge that, yes,
of course, they understood the irony of admiring a character as
despicable as Sammy. ``But today, I don't think they'd even be
aware of it,'' Schulberg said in a recent interview. ``This new
generation has absolutely no consideration of such matters. It's
another world. They appear to feel that any kind of moral brakes on
what you do seem old-fashioned or out of date or even nonexistent.
I don't think they even think about it. I don't think they even
worry about it. I think, in a sense, they see themselves as super
Sammys.''
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Glick is merely the most vivid and persistent example of
what has become over the last 75 years one of the stock characters
in American popular culture _ the Hollywood wheeler-dealer. The
history of this character extends back to the earliest days of the
movie business right through Sammy and up to the current, digital
era. Though not as ubiquitous as such other stock types as the
rugged loner, the wacky dame or the wronged man seeking vengeance,
like them, this feral Hollywood character keeps popping up through
the decades, wearing different hats to reflect different moral
attitudes but always recognizably the same: ruthless, power-hungry,
egomaniacal and hedonistic.
</P>
<P>
   But while America's attitude toward its other stock types has
remained fairly consistent, its relationship to this Hollywood
figure has gone through a transformation over the years, telling us
something not only about America's moral fluctuation but also about
the way Hollywood views itself. It can hardly be coincidence that
the Hollywood wheeler-dealer has become, in many versions, almost
endearingly amoral at just the moment when Hollywood itself has
become more corporate-minded than at any time in its history. To
corporate nine-to-fivers in their fluorescent cubicles who came
West with dreams of wild parties and wide-open-town millions, this
figure takes on a romantic tinge _ Sammy Glick, cunning operator,
betrayer extraordinaire, the quickest rat in the maze. If only!
</P>
<P>
   ``The dramatic transformation of Sammy Glick from the anti-hero
of the '40s to the role-model hero for the yuppies of the '80s is a
painful reminder of the moral breakdown we are suffering, without
even seeming to realize that suffering is involved,'' Schulberg
wrote in his 1989 afterword.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
