<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4787 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MOGUL-IMAGE-FILMS-2ND     05-03 1454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOGUL-IMAGE-FILMS-2NDTAKE-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: 1989 afterword.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The myth did not begin with Sammy Glick, of course. In the
beginning, the public image of the movie mogul was that of a recent
immigrant, probably Jewish, with the scent of the Lower East Side
clinging to him and a background in the garment industry and the
burgeoning world of the nickelodeons. As Robert Sklar, author of
``Movie-Made America,'' describes it, many ``regarded the rise of
the storefront-theater managers to fabulous wealth and power with a
mixture of awe and amusement.'' Their contempt was revealed in the
name they created to describe the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The term `movie mogul' came into use around 1915, nicely
describing the immigrant producers in the eyes of the public _ part
splendid emperors, part barbarian invaders,'' Sklar wrote. ``Their
foreignness, their alleged ignorance, were the subjects of a
thousand jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the silent era, the older generation was drifting
away and a younger breed of moguls _ slicker, more assimilated _
was taking their place. It was in this context that the archetype
of the Hollywood wheeler-dealer was born.
</P>
<P>
   Initially a tragic figure (Monroe Stahr in F. Scott Fitzgerald's
``The Last Tycoon''), he became almost a benevolent despot (the
carping studio chiefs in ``Sullivan's Travels,'' Adolphe Menjou in
``A Star in Born'') before mutating into the villainous Sammy Glick
and then into scoundrels of a marginally more sympathetic stripe,
whose duplicity was mitigated by their passion for moviemaking
(Kirk Douglas in the 1952 movie ``The Bad and the Beautiful'').
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to his editor at Collier's magazine in 1939,
Fitzgerald described why he created Monroe Stahr, a fictional
version of Irving Thalberg, the legendary MGM producer of the late
'20s and early '30s. ``Thalberg has always fascinated me,''
Fitzgerald wrote. ``His peculiar charm, his extraordinary good
looks, his bountiful success, the tragic end of his great
adventure. I have chosen him for my hero (this has been in my mind
for three years) because he is one of the half-dozen men I have
known who were built on the grand scale.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Monroe Stahr's aspirations _ to greatness, to power, to
artistic purity _ that made his fall so tragic. But of those three
aspirations, the only one that could be applied to Sammy Glick was
an aspiration, indeed a lust, for power. What the two men have in
common, though, is a complete lack of the kind of credentials that
might be required to achieve success in mainstream society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though Stahr's education was founded on nothing more than a
night school course in stenography, he had a long time ago run
ahead through trackless wastes of perception into fields where very
few men were able to follow him,'' Fitzgerald wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Glick's education was founded on even less than this; his
gift was for bluff and betrayal. He fashioned himself a
screenwriter but could hardly write his name. He stole other
people's ideas, without a backward glance.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s and 1980s, he had evolved into a more satiric, even
absurd figure (Ron Silver in the 1982 movie ``Best Friends,''
wearing a mask of laid-backness to smooth out his essential
monomania; Michael Lerner in the Coen Brothers' 1991 film ``Barton
Fink,'' Steve Martin as the ersatz Joel Silver action-flick
producer in Lawrence Kasdan's 1991 movie ``Grand Canyon'').
</P>
<P>
   Only in the 1990s did he reach his full flowering as a kind of
paranoid sadist, albeit an attractive one (Tim Robbins in the 1992
movie ``The Player,'' Kevin Spacey in the 1994 film ``Swimming With
Sharks'').
</P>
<P>
   When Fox's short-lived television series ``Action!,'' bombed out
last year, its self-consciously profane and gleefully malevolent
portrait of the Hollywood producer Peter Dragon (Jay Mohr) was
deemed too insider and too nasty for mass tastes. In a review of
the series in The New York Times, Caryn James described Mohr's
character as ``a producer who understands that his grand success
exists in direct proportion to his ruthlessness. He seems to come
by his savage attitude naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Hollywood wheeler-dealer archetype had finally gone
too far? Don't bet on it. He's still out there, hiding in the
bushes, just as savage and seductive as always.
</P>
<P>
   One of the new Internet sites dedicated to games and streaming
video for the 12-to-24-year-old set, www.thethreshhold.com, has a
regular animated series called ``The Producer'' that puts a kind of
sophomoric, ``South Park'' spin on the Hollywood sub-genre. It's
antihero is Lester Spaxman, president of the fictional Spaxmedia.
``So driven by his vision and passion to make spectacular films,
Lester is constantly blind to those he plows over on his path to
success,'' says the on-line character description. ``Lester lives
according to a twisted set of morals, specifically tailored for
survival in Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   A computer game called ``Hollywood Mogul'' promises players a
chance to ``go inside the dream factory and run your own movie
studio.'' You become studio head, are responsible for the release
of 100 feature films. If you win, you get immense wealth and an
Academy Award. ``All you need to immerse yourself in the simulated
world of Hollywood Mogul is a love for movies,'' says promotional
materials for the game. ``Of course, it doesn't hurt if you're
capable of being completely power-hungry and ruthless as you wield
an obscene amount of power over other people's lives (which is
always fun).''
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood wheeler-dealer has also played another cultural
role: capitalism's nadir, the example of what can happen when
ruthlessness and self-interest are carried too far. Two recent
biographies of modern-day moguls (``The Operator: David Geffen
Builds, Buys and Sells the New Hollywood'' by Tom King and ``The
Keys to the Kingdom: How Michael Eisner Lost His Grip'' by Kim
Masters) are finger-wagging examples. Tsk, tsk, those awful moguls.
They lie! They cheat! They think only of themselves! But they hang
out with really cool famous people.
</P>
<P>
   When the director Bruce Beresford (the 1989 movie ``Driving
Daisy,'' among many others) decided to stage a version of
``Rigoletto'' for the Los Angeles Opera this season, he and his
creative crew began noodling around ideas for something that
wouldn't be just another version of Verdi's tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that there was nothing quite so much like a ducal
court in medieval Italy as the world of a major Hollywood mogul,''
Beresford said.
</P>
<P>
   In the production that was presented last month at the Dorothy
Chandler Pavilion, the Duke of Mantua became Duke Mantua, a
Hollywood big shot with a sprawling estate in Bel-Air. Rigoletto
was transformed from a conniving fool into a conniving agent. And
the members of the ducal court were yes-men and hangers-on for the
hedonistic, self-absorbed Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really eerie, it fit so perfectly,'' Beresford said.
</P>
<P>
   Is Hollywood really more ruthless and predatory than any other
lucrative business? No, although it likes to think that it is.
``Hollywood is a jungle and the smaller animals have to run for
their lives,'' Schulberg wrote in 1941. Many of the hustlers trying
to break into the movie game would puff with pride at such a
description of the world in which they live. After all, if I'm
surviving, I must be a big animal.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Hollywood has become a more comfortable nest for this
American archetype because of the history and composition of the
place, its mixture of glamour and otherness. It reflects America,
but it's not really a part of it. Hollywood is seen as a place that
rewards ruthlessness and betrayal, where glib patter goes farther
than solid credentials.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to imagine simply walking into a Wall Street
investment bank or a Seattle high-tech company without any training
or track record and somehow weaseling your way to the top. But any
slob can do it in Hollywood, or so the myth goes. It's an illusion
that still draws them to Southern California by the Titanic-load.
</P>
<P>
   Nebbishes from any walk of life _ convinced that, given half a
chance, they could act or write or hustle as competently as anyone
_ are free to fantasize about playing out their own Sammy Glick
melodrama. All they have to do is brush up on the local lingo, buy
a lot of black clothes and jettison their moral compass, just for
the time being.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message of Hollywood wheeler-dealer stereotype. The
only difference between mogul and you is that they are willing to
do what it takes. That's why they're in the back of the limousine
with their cleavage pets and you're stuck in tunnel traffic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
