<HEADER>
A4788 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MOGUL-IMAGE-FILMS-3RD     05-03 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOGUL-IMAGE-FILMS-3RDTAKE-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: tunnel traffic.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In some eyes, it's the ultimate capitalist fantasy. No rules,
not even basic decency, except as a ruse. It's capitalism turned
topsy-turvy, wrenched of any boundaries, regulatory or moral, like
some Southern California version of Moscow after the collapse of
the Soviet Union. And even those who don't embrace the macho code
of get-'em-before-they-get-you, who despise people like that, can
still indulge in the fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   NBC broadcast a two-part adaptation of ``What Makes Sammy Run?''
back in 1960. Not long after, Steve Lawrence starred in a Broadway
musical version. But thus far, there has never been a movie
adaptation of the book that, to most people, speaks most directly
to the heart of this mythical Hollywood of back-stabbing hustlers
and unalloyed selfishness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been on the front burner and the back burner many times
over the years,'' Schulberg said. ``At the moment, it's somewhere
in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Brothers, which currently controls the rights to the
novel, is in talks with someone _ Schulberg said he can't say who
it is _ to finally make a Sammy Glick movie. ``They're trying to
make a deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, however, it is only by happenstance that this
wheeler-dealer figure has come to be associated with Hollywood.
Schulberg, who was the son of a prominent Hollywood producer and
grew up in that world, said he never intended to suggest that the
rules in Hollywood were any different than those on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's been unfair to Hollywood,'' Schulberg said. ``I
never meant to suggest that it was a purely Hollywood syndrome.
Sammy Glicks can and do operate in the stock market, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Why then, do we persist in having this Hollywood type emerge,
again and again?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Hollywood has always been kind of a magnet in terms
of being sexier and in the public eye,'' he said. ``It's always
easier to hang this type of attitude on a Hollywood wheeler-dealer
than on some wheeler-dealer who is just wheeling and dealing in
some more ordinary job. Here, he's with the stars. It's just
sexier.''
</P>
<P>
   The strange irony, though, is that just as the Hollywood
wheeler-dealer archetype has mutated into this dark hero of
hedonistic free-enterprise, the real-life Hollywood executives are
moving inexorably toward buttoned-down corporate America _ not that
refined boardrooms don't have their own forms of cold-blooded
ruthlessness, where proper pedigree is less important than raw
business talent. Sammy Glicks still exist in Hollywood. But as the
movie studios are being swallowed by larger corporate entities,
becoming little more than departments within divisions of
mega-media empires, the real executives tend more toward business
school models than Sammy's school of hard knocks.
</P>
<P>
   This shift may account for part of the durability of the
stereotype _ to many who came to Los Angeles hoping for the
free-wheeling capitalism of the Glick myth only to find a corporate
world of marketing meetings and company canteens, the Hollywood
wheeler-dealer becomes a kind of romantic figure, a gleefully dark
self-image, embraced all the more fervently. Undoubtedly, that is
one reason that the archetype is kept alive in movies and
television series and related entertainment vehicles. It's the Hyde
that so many Jekylls search for in their midnight dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I suppose that Hollywood is becoming more corporate, I am
sure it is,'' Beresford said. ``But there are still a lot of Sammy
Glicks out there. You know there are. I meet them every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
