<SLUG> BC-GORE-SOCSEC-2TAKES(1210)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JABS FLY IN PRESIDENTIAL RING OVER SOCIAL SECURITY'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO with FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an sharp exchange that gave the presidential
campaign the intensity of a day in late October, Vice President Al
Gore accused Gov. George W. Bush on Wednesday of devising a
``secret plan'' that could bankrupt the Social Security system.
Hours later, Bush tartly questioned the vice president's honesty
and predicted that Gore's attacking style would soon backfire.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing a theme he has repeated often in recent days, Gore used
a speech to union officials in New Jersey to assert that Bush, the
likely Republican nominee, was quietly developing a ``risky'' plan
to allow individual investment accounts in Social Security that
would jeopardize millions of taxpayers' savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does the Bush plan propose to deal with the bankruptcy of
Social Security that his privatization scheme would cause?'' Gore
told a gathering of AFL-CIO officials in Atlantic City, N.J. ``He
doesn't even bother to provide an answer. He just smiles and goes
on with the smug assumption that there's no need to share with you
the details of what he wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Gore's cascade of attacks, Bush spent much of a
plane flight Wednesday afternoon from Austin, Texas, to Palm
Springs, Calif., telling reporters that the vice president had
flatly misrepresented his record on a host of issues ranging from
the Texas budget to his positions on China and Russia to his
crime-fighting policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone running for the highest office of the land should
stick to the facts,'' Bush said. ``I think it is a pattern to say
things, to stretch the truth. He's the man who said he invented the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Gore's aggressive campaigning might work as well
against him as it did against former Sen. Bill Bradley during the
Democratic primaries, Bush said he planned to respond faster and
more forcefully than Bradley did. ``It's not going to work here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, rather than being aggrieved by his opponent's attacks,
Bush seemed somewhat amused by the constant salvos from the vice
president, suggesting that Gore's strategy was self-defeating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty soon, it's going to have a corrosive effect on his
campaign if he's not telling the truth,'' Bush said of Gore during
the 78-minute airborne news conference. ``The fact that he relies
on facts _ says things that are not factual _ are going to
undermine his campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The more outrageous he gets, the more outrageous
allegations he makes against me, the more skeptical people will
become.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides disagree. Privately, they contend that the slashing
strategy they employed during the primaries will work again in the
general election, provided they avoid the appearance of attacking
Bush personally. They have done that, they argue, by focusing on
issues like Social Security, tax cuts, health care and gun-control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primaries showed that voters believe that vigorously
debating your opponent on issues is considered fair play,'' said
one adviser to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also used his Atlantic City speech to discuss his own
proposal for keeping the Social Security system solvent. Under that
plan, he would use the system's surplus to pay down the national
debt, which in turn would reduce the federal government's interest
payments. Those savings would then be put back into the Social
Security trust fund, keeping the system solvent for an additional
13 years or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will devote all interest from debt reduction to shore up
social security,'' Gore said. ``I think it is wrong to cut
benefits, raise the retirement age or risk your retirement savings
in a game of stock market roulette.''
</P>
<P>
   But that description amounted to one brief passage in a
35-minute speech that was devoted mainly to attacking Bush on a
variety of fronts, particularly Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal floated by Bush's aides in recent days,
taxpayers would be allowed to invest a small part of their Social
Security payroll taxes in the stocks or bond. Bush's aides argue
that such a plan would help taxpayers take advantage of the stock
market's historic growth.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore asserted Wednesday that the plan would make the system
vulnerable to huge market fluctuations that could hurt millions of
retirees. And as he has repeatedly done in recent days, he
suggested that Bush was charting a course that was ``reckless'' and
``irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Social Security is more than a government program,'' he
said. ``It is a solemn compact between the generations.'' Bush, he
added, ``Seems to believe differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore asserted that Bush had ``left the door wide open'' to
raising the retirement age for Social Security as a means of
bolstering the system. That approach, he argued, would be harmful
to people who do strenuous manual labor and physically cannot
postpone retirement. And he accused Bush of wanting to cut Social
Security spending to pay for a tax cut that Gore argues would favor
the rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the waitress who's carrying a heavy tray, what
about the longshoreman, what about the steel worker and the auto
workers?'' he asked. ``When they get to the current retirement age,
they don't want to be told that in order to finance some risky tax
scheme for the wealthy, they are going to have to keep on working
until they are 70 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides acknowledge that he has not ruled out raising the
retirement age. But they note that he has not formulated a detailed
plan yet, only the general principles for one. Those include not
increasing Social Security taxes, not cutting benefits and setting
aside the Social Security surplus in a ``lockbox'' to make sure it
is used only on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bush's lack of a detailed plan that caused Gore to accuse
the Texas governor of devising a ``secret plan'' Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to spring it on you after the election,'' Gore said.
``Well, I think he may be underestimating the capacity of the
American people to figure out for ourselves what the details of his
secret plan would mean for each and every American.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Gore's barbs were meant to rattle Bush, they failed.
Indeed, what was extraordinary about Wednesday's exchange was the
almost delighted mood that Bush brought to his end of it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was on his way to California for several days of
campaigning, including a fund-raiser in Palm Springs on Wednesday
night for the Republican Party that was expected to bring in about
$1 million.
</P>
<P>
   On the flight, Bush revealed a few more glimmers than usual of
his obvious distaste for what he seems to see as Gore's desperation
to be president. Usually, Bush does a more thorough job of pulling
his punches when he is asked what he thinks about Gore as a person.
</P>
<P>
   After a reporter told Bush that Gore, whose first grandchild was
born on the Fourth of July, sometimes says to Hispanic audiences
that he hopes his second grandchild will be born on Cinco de Mayo,
Bush muttered, ``Totally pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point, talking about his own desire for the
presidency, Bush said: ``I'm willing to work for it. What I'm not
willing to do is sell my soul to become the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Gore would do that, Bush arched an eyebrow and said,
``That's for you all to figure out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not used the word ``lied,'' and when reporters did, he
corrected them, coyly repeating again and again that he was simply
setting the record straight and expressing his ``disappointment''
in Gore's behavior. But he did use the words disappointment or
disappointed at least half a dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president said I've never submitted a budget as
governor of Texas'' said Bush, reciting the comments by Gore that
he deemed untruthful. ``He talked about recidivism rates that were
totally inaccurate numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said I called China and Russia enemies'' Bush added. ``Have
I ever referred to China and Russia as enemies?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush shook his head and veered toward what he clearly intended
to be a kind of emotional and moral high ground. ``I just am
disappointed and I think Americans will be disappointed when they
find out the truth,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
