<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROWE QUITS AS NETS' PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Rowe resigned as president of the Nets on Wednesday and
accepted a reassignment to the project the franchise hopes will
result in a state-of-the-art arena in Newark for the 2003-4 season.
Rowe, the Nets' president since 1995, will serve in a currently
unspecified position with Newark Sports and Entertainment, a
subsidiary of YankeeNets, on which Rowe is a board member.
</P>
<P>
   According to YankeeNets officials, Rowe would have been fired if
he had not resigned. Officials spent the last several days trying
to persuade Rowe to continue working with the organization in a new
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   With the firing of Coach Don Casey last week, General Manager
John Nash is the only remaining member of the Nets' basketball
operations triumvirate. The club's first priority is to hire a
director of basketball operations, who will then decide on Nash's
future and lead the search for a new head coach. The director may
also serve as the Nets' president if he has a strong background in
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank Michael Rowe for his dedication and loyalty to
the Nets organization,'' said Harvey Schiller, the chairman and
chief executive officer of YankeeNets. ``We are fortunate to be
able to harness Michael's experience with the Nets and his
expertise with arena management to help us with one of our most
important goals: to build a new arena for the Nets and Devils in
Newark.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiller will assist Lewis Katz, the chairman of the Nets'
operating board, in the search for new front-office personnel. In
the meantime, Finn Wentworth, the president of YankeeNets, has been
designated as the Nets' acting president.
</P>
<P>
   Before taking over the Nets' presidency, Rowe had distinguished
himself in arena management as an executive with the Meadowlands
Sports Complex. But while the Nets' enjoyed off-the-court successes
in the front office during his tenure as president, he struggled
with the basketball side of the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met Ray Chambers two and a half years ago,'' Rowe
said, referring to the Nets' philanthropic and civic-minded owner,
``he told me one of the main reasons he was purchasing the team was
to build a new arena for the Nets in Newark. I am happy to join him
in making that dream come true.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
