<HEADER>
A4795 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BEETHOVEN-MUSIC-$ADV0     05-03 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEETHOVEN-MUSIC-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING A HERO'S WELCOME TO ANY CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 7) 
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When in the course of human events, musicians feel impelled to
declare to the world and to themselves the highest ideals of which
the individual and humanity are capable, the composer to whom they
are most apt to turn is Beethoven.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, at the ceremony at which Wagner laid the foundation stone
for his Festspielhaus at Bayreuth in 1872, what he presented was
not his own Music of the Future but Beethoven's Ninth Symphony. In
1955, 10 years after suffering a direct hit in an Allied air raid,
the rebuilt Vienna State Opera opened with ``Fidelio.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vienna Philharmonic and the chorus of the Vienna Singverein
under the baton of Simon Rattle strike a self-consciously epochal
note with their live broadcast on Austrian radio of a concert from
the quarry in Mauthausen, the concentration camp where, by the tens
of thousands, victims of the Nazis were enslaved and worked to
death. The musicians are playing for Mauthausen survivors, their
families and the public: ``a declaration of humanity on a site of
horror,'' says Clemens Hellsberg, the orchestra's president; a
gesture of ``remembrance, repentance and homage,'' in Sir Simon's
words.
</P>
<P>
   They are playing the Ninth Symphony, perpetuating a pattern that
shows no sign of fading. When Kurt Masur and the New York
Philharmonic rang in the millennium last year, the choice of the
Ninth was not so much obvious as inevitable. It was equally so when
Leonard Bernstein celebrated the reunification of Germany at the
Berlin Wall in 1989. On that occasion, by Bernstein's wish, the
clarion call ``Freude'' (``joy'') in the choral finale was replaced
by ``Freiheit'' (``freedom''), perhaps a less daring liberty than
it seems. Bernstein dreamed of revisiting the score on Mount Scopus
once peace had come to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness,'' ``liberte,
egalite, fraternite'': like many another artist, not to mention
ordinary citizens of every stripe, Beethoven felt the fire in the
ringing catchwords of revolution. But he alone, by virtually
universal consent, found the means to make music play out the
passions those revolutionary ideals enshrine. The Ninth Symphony's
``Ode to Joy,'' cresting in a vision of a universal brotherhood and
a benign father beyond the stars, is one cardinal example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fidelio'' is another, on many counts: for Leonore's courage in
her quest for Florestan, her husband, who languishes in the
clutches of a tyrant; for Florestan's moral majesty at the brink of
despair; for the heartbreaking nobility of the chorus of others
also unjustly imprisoned, breathing free in the sun for a stolen
hour.
</P>
<P>
   But Beethoven could make his music convey such ``stories'' of
struggle and triumph even in the absence of text or an overt
program, notably in his Symphony No. 3 (the ``Eroica,'' or
``Heroic''). Scott Burnham's book ``Beethoven Hero,'' published in
1995, examines in illuminating detail precisely this phenomenon and
its consequences for the reception of Beethoven's music.
</P>
<P>
   By Burnham's count, the ``heroic'' style dominates in only two
of the composer's nine symphonies, two of his 32 piano sonatas, one
of his five piano concertos and several of his overtures. Yet its
powerful halo effect has raised Beethoven's music _ indeed, his
very name _ to the level of symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes him the perfect figurehead for a series of six free
concerts by the Orion String Quartet, presented by the Chamber
Music Society of Lincoln Center at Alice Tully Hall beginning on
May 12. Under the title Beethoven 2000, the series includes all 16
of the composer's string quartets. As Beethoven the keyboard
virtuoso often did at charity fund-raisers in Vienna, the players
are waiving their fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played all the quartets before but never as a cycle,''
said Steven Tenenbom, the Orion violist. ``We've been working
toward this all our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Described by the society as a gift to New York, Beethoven 2000
honors six nonprofit organizations in the five boroughs that in
various ways devote their resources to engaging children with the
arts. At each concert, one honoree is showcased in a short film
clip or video and receives up to 200 tickets to use for
fund-raising, incentives or whatever purpose it thinks best. Funds
from grants by Credit Lyonnais and other sponsors will be
distributed to institutions as well, but recognition, not dollars,
is the heart of the exercise.
</P>
<P>
   A handsome gesture, certainly, but where, exactly, is the
connection? ``Beethoven came first,'' said Timothy Eddy, the Orion
cellist. As quartet in residence with the Chamber Music Society, he
and his colleagues took their dream project to Jacqueline Taylor,
the society's executive director, and David Shifrin, the artistic
director, who at once began thinking of added dimensions that would
lift the cycle above obligatory chamber music routine.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the project, Taylor offered her own rationale:
``All around us great organizations are doing their part to give
meaningful opportunities to young people to experience life's
brighter side through the remarkable world of the arts in all of
its forms. Without their work, our work would not be possible, and
our city would not be the extraordinary place that it is. We wanted
to take the time to say `thank you' to a few of these special
organizations, invite them into our home and salute them for their
achievements in the best way we know how _ with music.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenenbom elaborated on the specific choice of composer:
``Beethoven reaches to express the struggle between man and the
universe, between man and his own soul. He's universal, and he's
visceral. That's a good choice for this kind of project. The
organizations we're celebrating are changing lives out there,
saving lives.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
