<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ SUSPENDED FOR 5 GAMES FOR HIT BATTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes Rule sidebar)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Red Sox ace Pedro Martinez, who was dogged early in his
career with the reputation of being a headhunter, is appealing the
five-game suspension he was given by Major League Baseball
Wednesday for hitting Roberto Alomar of the Cleveland Indians with
a pitch during the eighth inning of Boston's 2-1 win Sunday over
the Indians in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland pitcher Charles Nagy, who hit Jose Offerman of the Red
Sox with a pitch in the top of the eighth inning, was fined an
undisclosed amount but received no suspension from Frank Robinson,
the vice president of on-field operations for Major League
Baseball. Last week, in the aftermath of a brawl between the
Detroit Tigers and Chicago White Sox, Robinson handed out 16
suspensions, totaling 82 games, and nine fines
</P>
<P>
   With the appeal pending, Martinez will make his next scheduled
start, Saturday afternoon in Fenway Park against the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays. A likely scenario -- Jimy Williams' involuntary smile
seemed to confirm as much when asked about it -- is that Martinez
will drop his appeal after pitching Saturday, accept the
suspension, and pitch again May 12 in Baltimore. In essence, the
suspension would not cause him to miss a start, but push it back a
day.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez would not comment on the suspension Wednesday. He spoke
briefly with Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette in the clubhouse
about two hours before the night's game, shortly before the
suspension was announced publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Pedro is doing the right thing, appealing the
suspension,'' Duquette said. ``We'll have to see how the appeal
comes out. We hope the length of suspension is diminished by going
through the appeal process.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Duquette, Martinez was suspended because he hit
Alomar after both managers and pitchers had been warned after Nagy
hit Offerman in the top of the eighth. But Duquette suggested that
the umpires should have ejected Nagy, rather than issuing a
warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro was doing his job,'' Duquette said. ``The team's
position on the issue is that the umpires must do a better job of
administering rule 8.02 (d) more effectively, by throwing out the
first pitcher who illegally hits an opposing batter, who in this
case was Charles Nagy . ... It's clear Nagy was throwing at
Offerman. Obviously, that's why Nagy was fined.''
</P>
<P>
   Nagy hit Offerman leading off the eighth after an incident in
the previous inning, when Martinez knocked down Einar Diaz of the
Indians with a head-high fastball. The Indians maintain that
Martinez was deliberately throwing at Diaz because he already had
two doubles in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro was clearly pitching inside to Einar Diaz,'' Duquette
said. ``He had pulled two balls into the left-field corner. so he
pitched inside with the purpose of getting him out. Their response
was to hit our player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Umpires must take control of the situation so that the
unwritten rule within baseball (of retaliating when a player is hit
by a pitch) isn't adhered to by players.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was on the West Coast and did not answer repeated
telephone calls. But Red Sox outfielder Carl Everett was critical
of the decision by the former Hall of Fame outfielder, who this
year was placed in charge of on-field disciplinary actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to have their opinion on the way baseball
should be played,'' Everett said. ``To me, just let it be played.
The person who wrote this decision, he played in times where if you
hit a player, we're going to hit your player. Now he's making an
example just because of the stink that came out this year about the
inside part of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Nagy) hit (Offerman) on purpose, so Nagy has to get
suspended, too. So you know that's garbage. They're just trying to
make an example.''
</P>
<P>
   The suspension is the second of his career for Martinez, who was
given an eight-game suspension in 1996 by National League president
Leonard Coleman after charging the mound when Mike Williams of the
Philadelphia Phillies threw two pitches behind him. Williams, who
was suspended six games, said he was retaliating for Martinez
hitting Gregg Jefferies in the elbow in a pitch. Jefferies is in
Boston with the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Martinez's first year as a starting pitcher for the
Montreal Expos, he hit six batters in his first five starts. In his
23 starts that season, there were 12 ejections and three fights,
including the game in which he had a perfect game for 7 1/3 innings
in Cincinnati, then hit Reggie Sanders with a pitch, apparently
provoking Sanders to charge the mound.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Martinez was warned three times by umpires, but there
has been no other disciplinary action against the Sox pitcher. Last
September, he was angrily attacked verbally by then-Baltimore
manager Ray Miller after he hit Brady Anderson of the Orioles with
a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Two Sox players, outfielder Darren Lewis and pitcher Rheal
Cormier, were suspended three games apiece after an April 23 brawl
in which benches cleared twice. Lewis charged Indians pitcher Jaret
Wright after being hit by a pitch, and Cormier hit Jim Thome of the
Indians with a pitch. Wright was suspended five games.
</P>
<P>
   Sox manager Williams was measured in his reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what I say, I don't know if there's a right way
to do this,'' he said. ``There's always going to be a controversial
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't going to be the last one, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought Martinez's past reputation might have
factored into Robinson's decision, Williams said: ``I would like in
my mind not to think it comes into play, but I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams could not recall an occasion in which players were
suspended after batters were hit by pitches without a fight
ensuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this going to set a precedent, something like this, when
there's no fight?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(sidebar) &QL; 
THE RULE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rule 8.02 (d) _ Intentionally pitch at the batter:
</P>
<P>
   If, in the umpire's judgment, such a violation occurs, the
umpire may elect either to:
</P>
<P>
   1. Expel the pitcher, or the manager and the pitcher, from the
game, or
</P>
<P>
   2. May warn the pitcher and the manager of both teams that
another such pitch will result in the immediate expulsion of that
pitcher (or a replacement) and the manager.
</P>
<P>
   After the rule, there is this from the Case Book of the Official
Playing Rules Committee:
</P>
<P>
   To pitch at a batter's head is unsportsmanlike and highly
dangerous. It should be _ and is _ condemned by everybody. Umpires
should act without hesitation in enforcement of this rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
