<HEADLINE>
THOMPSON FEELS NO PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Rangers pitcher Justin Thompson threw for
15 minutes in the bullpen before yesterday's game without any pain
in his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson will throw lightly today and then have a full-speed
session in the bullpen tomorrow. That will determine if he's ready
to return to the minors on a medical rehabilitation assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything went fine,'' Thompson said. ``I threw all my
pitches. I was a little tentative but ... it was a positive step. I
feel better than yesterday when I didn't know what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has made three starts on rehab, but his progress came
to a halt Sunday when he felt pain in the shoulder throwing in the
bullpen. \Nsubheds:Helling delayed one day Rick Helling has been
pushed back one day in the rotation to allow a left-hander _
probably Doug Davis _ to start against the Oakland Athletics on
Sunday. Helling, who normally pitches on four days' rest, will
pitch Monday against the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to neutralize some of Oakland's hitters,''
manager Johnny Oates said. ``Seattle has a more balanced lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-handers Darren Oliver and Kenny Rogers are scheduled to
pitch the first two games of the series against the Athletics, who
have a lineup dominated by left-handed hitters. Davis or Matt
Perisho, who is also being considered for the start, would replace
Mark Clark in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is the leading candidate because he has made four starts
at Triple-A Oklahoma.  &QL; 
Reviewing Helling
</P>
<P>
   A few statistics on Rick Helling after Tuesday's 8-1 victory
against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Helling has thrown 681 pitches in his six starts, an average of
113.5 per game. Both numbers, going into last night's games, are
the second-highest in the American League, behind Baltimore's Mike
Mussina, who has thrown 693 pitches in six starts. Kenny Rogers has
thrown 660 pitches, fifth-most in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Helling led the American League by allowing 41 home
runs. He has allowed just two in six starts this year, covering
381/3 innings. Only two pitchers _ Oakland's Omar Olivares and Gil
Heredia _ have allowed less per innings pitched.
</P>
<P>
   Helling has allowed a .234 slugging percentage, third-lowest in
the league, and a .299 on-base percentage, ninth-lowest in the
league.  &QL; 
Sele sighting
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are likely to face former teammate Aaron Sele on
Wednesday during their three-game series against the Seattle
Mariners. Sele is scheduled to pitch Friday for the Mariners, which
would put him in line to start on Wednesday against the Rangers.
Sele pitched the past two seasons for the Rangers before signing
with the Mariners in the off-season.  &QL; 
Rodriguez bashing
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Ivan Rodriguez went into last night's game with 10 home
runs, tied for second in the American League. He said he doesn't
think the proliferation of home runs has anything to do with the
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitters are getting stronger, bigger,'' Rodriguez said. ``I
think the ball is the same, you still need to hit it in the perfect
spot to make it go. The hitters are just working harder, more
weight and doing more exercises.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez set a career-high with 35 home runs last year and
wants to go beyond that this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always put it in my mind to have better numbers than the
year before,'' Rodriguez said.  &QL; 
Minor-league news
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers signed former major-league infielder Scott
Livingstone to a minor-league contract and assigned him to Triple-A
Oklahoma. He has a career major-league average of .281 in 673
games, mainly with the Detroit Tigers and San Diego Padres. He has
played third base regularly in the major leagues and gives the
Rangers depth behind Mike Lamb and Tom Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa pitcher Joaquin Benoit, one of the Rangers' top
minor-league prospects, has been put on the disabled list because
of shoulder stiffness.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Sierra was 0-for-4 in his first game with the Oklahoma
RedHawks.
nn
</P>
