<SLUG> BC-GUARE-THEATER-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CAPTAIN REWRITE' ON DRAGGING THE PAST INTO THE PRESENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 7) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Guare's play ``Gardenia'' begins in 1875 with
Joshua Hickman sitting on the beach at Nantucket and reading from
Walt Whitman's poem ``On the Beach at Night Alone'': ``A vast
similitude interlocks all.''
</P>
<P>
   That quotation about the interconnectedness of humanity is the
central theme of the 1982 ``Gardenia'' and of the untitled cycle of
plays of which it is a part. Whitman's line, though unspoken, was
also at the heart of ``Six Degrees of Separation,'' Guare's 1990
play about the idea that ``everybody on this planet is separated by
only six other people.'' In the world of Guare, a vast similitude
interlocks all.
</P>
<P>
   After years of revising that earlier cycle, he has reordered it
into two plays under the collective title ``Lydie Breeze'' now in
previews, the production opens on May 15 at the New York Theater
Workshop. Tickets are being sold only to both plays, which can be
seen on consecutive nights or the same weekend day. They are titled
``Lydie Breeze, Part 1: Bulfinch's Mythology'' (formerly
``Gardenia'') and ``Lydie Breeze, Part 2: The Sacredness of the
Next Task.''
</P>
<P>
   The cycle, moving from the Civil War to the beginning of the
20th century, deals with American idealism and its decline through
history. ``It's about what happens to our dreams,'' Guare said
recently, ``what happens to the best part of ourselves and how we
manage to adapt to a world that's constantly changing.'' In the
plays, the characters are trying to invent a utopia in this case a
variation of Brook Farm.
</P>
<P>
   One common misconception about Guare is that plays like ``The
House of Blue Leaves'' and ``Bosoms and Neglect'' are
autobiographical but that ``Lydie Breeze'' is largely historical.
Yet all his plays are personal, deriving from his own life and that
of his family, both in the present and the past.
</P>
<P>
   The Guares immigrated to the United States from Ireland in the
1840s during the potato famine. On the maternal side of Guare's
family, the Gradys, also Irish, had come over earlier in the
century. His great-grandfather, who fought in the Civil War, was
named Joshua Hickman, and there are also Lydies and Breezes in his
genealogy. Since these relatives lived before his time, he has had
to reimagine them, while remaining as true as he can to the real
people behind the fictionalized characters.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if any chronicles of his family had been written, he
laughed and said: ``Written? They weren't even oral. Nobody spoke
to each other.'' From overheard conversations, memories and
intimations, he has created his own chronicle, sometimes merging
relatives. On one level, the plays deal with ``violence and
betrayal, things that happened in my family,'' he said. ``My
parents were very detached from their families and very pained by
them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he loved 19th-century novels, in particular those
by Balzac, George Eliot and Wilkie Collins, and his objective was
to write a dramatic equivalent, a richly textured narrative. That
approach, he said, ``made the family history accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   For him, ``Lydie Breeze'' is an attempt ``to drag that past into
the present, and to make some sense of those dark parts of your
life that you're not responsible for _ the inflicted shadows.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the revised cycle was supposed to be the cornerstone
of the Guare season at the Signature Theater, but when the
production proved to be too expensive, Guare rushed a new play,
``Lake Hollywood,'' into production in its stead. ``Lake
Hollywood'' has since been rewritten and was staged in February at
the Guthrie Theater Lab in Minneapolis. That play, too, had an
earlier existence, as a one-act play that Guare wrote 40 years ago
and expanded much later.
</P>
<P>
   After Elizabeth Marvel played Blanche in ``A Streetcar Named
Desire'' at the New York Theater Workshop last year, the artistic
director, James C. Nicola, invited her to look through manuscripts
and choose another project. She chose the ``Lydie Breeze'' plays
and, following a reading in January, Nicola decided to go ahead
with a production. Marvel portrays the title character. At the
playwright's request, the director is Itamar Kubovy, who staged
``Lake Hollywood'' at the Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   The major change, Guare said, was that, in contrast to the
original version, the plays are being performed in chronological
order with the same cast and at a single theater.
</P>
<P>
   His revisions include excerpted passages from ``Women and
Water,'' a third play in the cycle that was presented in 1985 at
the Arena Stage in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Guare is, he admitted, a compulsive rewriter. Thirty years ago,
when ``The House of Blue Leaves'' opened at the Truck and Warehouse
Theater (the predecessor of the New York Theater Workshop, on East
Fourth Street in the East Village), he was presented with a shirt
that read ``Captain Rewrite.'' When he is not redoing his own work,
he is sometimes called in to doctor musicals. This season, he did
some brushwork on the book for the revival of ``Kiss Me, Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching a rehearsal of ``Lydie Breeze'' and hearing that line,
``a vast similitude interlocks all,'' he began thinking about its
application to his life and his work. ``We ricochet around,'' he
said, ``and we don't realize the connections until later.'' He
remembered that his father believed strongly in ``this connective
tissue.'' One day, his father ``broke all rules'' and passed on to
his son the secret Masonic handshake as if it were a legacy. In
times of urgency, he suggested, that secret could unlock doors.
</P>
<P>
   In Guare's family, his uncle Billy Grady occupied a lofty
position, though he was, by his nephew's estimation, ``a monstrous
man.'' For many years he was a casting director for MGM, credited
with discovering James Stewart and other stars and also for his
talent report on Fred Astaire (``balding, can't act, can't sing,
can dance a little''). Uncle Billy, who was the model for the
Hollywood director in ``The House of Blue Leaves,'' always held out
the illusion that he would discover some member of the Guare
family.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he was discovered, Guare said, ``I can tell you
exactly.'' After graduating from the Yale School of Drama, he was
offered a job as an intern at Universal Studios in Hollywood.
Pleased that his nephew had not come to him asking for work, Uncle
Billy offered him a better position as a trainee at MGM.
</P>
<P>
   While he was in California, Guare visited his Aunt Louise, a
member of the Guare side of the family, in San Francisco. He told
her he was planning to accept Uncle Billy's offer. She said:
``Didn't you want to be a playwright? Isn't that why you went to
Yale?'' He explained that he did, but that he was desperately in
need of money and after working for a time in Hollywood he would
return to New York to write plays. Aunt Louise said she had planned
to leave him something in her will: ``But I'll make a deal with
you. If you give up that job at MGM, and go back to New York and
become a playwright, I'll give you the money now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was terrified,'' Guare said. ``She had taken away all my
excuses.'' Accepting the challenge, he returned to New York. His
first week, he walked down Cornelia Street in Greenwich Village and
noticed that the Caffe Cino was presenting the early work of
Lanford Wilson and other writers. He realized that ``something new
was happening in the theater.'' He lived off his aunt's beneficence
for three years, and was even able to finance a trip to Europe.
During this time he wrote several plays, including his
breakthrough, ``The House of Blue Leaves'' _ and he became a
playwright.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who discovered me?'' he asked. ``It was my Aunt Louise.'' In
her honor, one of his two pet pugs is named Louise and the leading
character in ``Six Degrees'' is named Louisa.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to write many more plays, the musical ``Two Gentlemen
of Verona'' and several films, including ``Atlantic City.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
