<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4799 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-GUARE-THEATER-$ADV07-     05-03 0339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUARE-THEATER-$ADV07-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK:``Atlantic City.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Along with revising ``Lydie Breeze,'' he has been working on the
book for a Broadway musical version of the movie ``Sweet Smell of
Success'' (with music by Marvin Hamlisch and lyrics by Craig
Carnelia).
</P>
<P>
   His new play, ``Chaucer in Rome,'' is scheduled for Lincoln
Center Theater next season. It takes place at the American Academy
in Rome (which is headed by his wife, Adele Chatfield-Taylor). In
keeping with his favorite themes, the play is, he said, ``about an
artist who is no longer able to work in the way he wanted to
work.'' It was inspired by the story of the painter Chuck Close,
who was paralyzed by a stroke and had to ``reinvent himself and
created a new vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   Guare is also involved in a new film project, based on the lives
of Sara and Gerald Murphy, the models for the characters in
``Tender Is the Night.'' Rereading the F. Scott Fitzgerald novel,
he said, he realized that it was ``about people who create an oasis
for other people to live in.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, he makes voluminous notes in pocket-size notebooks _
106 so far _ about events in his life and ideas for plays. He works
every day, writing his plays in longhand and then transferring them
to a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, in talking about his writing, Guare said:
``Everything deals with what you're afraid of: same old fears. They
find new names, new costumes.'' What was he afraid of today? He
paused and then, the perpetual Captain Rewrite, answered, ``Not
finishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Through Guare's plays, even those that deal with physical and
emotional mayhem, there is a current of affirmation. Now 62, he
continues to greet the day with anticipation rather than
apprehension. ``When I was a kid,'' he said, ``I had such enormous
dreams _ to be a writer, to marry someone wonderful, to live in New
York, to work in the theater _ and reality has outdone my dreams on
every level.'' He added, ``The theater's my utopia.'' And he hasn't
even had to use the secret handshake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
