<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4802 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX     05-03 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOWDEN SIGNING SHORES UP COWBOYS' WEAK LINK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Since the start of the off-season, the Cowboys have
made moves to upgrade areas of their team where they lost players
or anticipated losing players _ save for linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   And, according to Pro Bowl linebacker Dexter Coakley, it was
very evident at last weekend's minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week later, Coakley and the Cowboys are singing a
different tune.
</P>
<P>
   The signing of former Tennessee Titans linebacker Joe Bowden to
a two-year deal yesterday immediately turned a weakness into a
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the weak link,'' Coakley said of the linebacking
corps, where the Cowboys are gambling that the undersized Dat
Nguyen can make up for the free-agent loss of Randall Godfrey
(Tennessee) in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were also void of experienced alternatives for
Nguyen or strong-side linebacker Darrin Hambrick, who won the job
by default last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely an upgrade,'' Coakley said. ``It puts us
right back to being one of the dominant groups in the defensive
scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not announced, but a source said the
eight-year veteran signed a contract that counts less than $700,000
against next year's salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys remain in negotiations with former Everman High
School star Barron Wortham, who also played linebacker for the
Titans last year, in an attempt to further bolster the position. A
deal could be done today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to have Joe Bowden join our team,'' Cowboys
owner Jerry Jones said. ``We are looking at anything we can to
improve at linebacker, and Joe Bowden makes us a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Wortham signs or not, the Cowboys are happy with what
Bowden does for their defense. The 5-foot-11, 235-pounder will
start out at strong-side linebacker, where he will compete with
Hambrick for the starting role.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bowden, who recorded 81 tackles in 16 starts at
strong-side linebacker during Tennessee's run to the Super Bowl
last season, can also play middle linebacker. Wortham is being
recruited to provide some insurance in case Nguyen doesn't pan out
in the middle. But Bowden is an option there as well.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that the competition at training camp will be
intense.
</P>
<P>
   And while Nguyen and Hambrick said they understand the concept
of how quality competition makes the Cowboys a better football
team, they say they don't plan on losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition makes me a better player,'' Nguyen said. ``I've
had to prove myself all my life. It motivates me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hambrick, who won the job last season because Quentin Coryatt
was sidelined by injuries, said he can't help but feel threatened
by Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have a good attitude about it,'' Hambrick said.
``I just want a chance to compete for my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones readily describes Bowden as a proven winner and an impact
player, and is equally excited about the type of leadership he will
bring to the defense. However, he says that the former Oklahoma
star wasn't promised a starting job and will have to compete with
Hambrick.
</P>
<P>
   No matter who starts, Jones is just pleased that the linebacker
depth will be better than it has been in several years.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden was initially leaning toward going back to Tennessee, but
became miffed when the Titans wouldn't give him a deal similar to
the five-year, $25 million contract they gave Godfrey. He also
turned down a one-year deal worth $1.3 million to stay in
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The Mesquite native said when he found out the Cowboys were
interested, he instructed his agent to get a deal done to bring him
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think that I have been a playing all these years and never
had the opportunity to come home,'' Bowden said. ``I'm excited. I'm
happy to be here. My mother still lives in Mesquite, and I got
family all over Dallas. This is really home.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar to the additions of Joey Galloway at receiver, Ryan
McNeil at cornerback and Jackie Harris at tight end, the Cowboys
believe they've hit a home run at linebacker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
