<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SHARKS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERIOUS ILLNESS REALLY NO MYSTERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Owen Nolan's mystery ailments have created
quite a stir regarding the NHL's lenient injury-disclosure policy.
Traditionally, there isn't one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just want to protect your players,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   So, the San Jose Sharks can and did officially give Nolan
``flu-like symptoms'' when he missed Game 2. Even though everyone
knows, or thinks they know, that Nolan's sore left shoulder and/or
sore left foot kept him out.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton used the same ``flu-like symptoms'' line to keep Todd
Marchant's concussion under wraps as long as possible.
</P>
<P>
   `` I guess you'd like us all to tell the truth,'' Hitchcock
said. ``I can tell you flu-like symptoms usually go back to
concussions, you learn that stuff. Upper body extremities usually
means one of the shoulders is usually done. Strep throat is usually
a groin pull or a hip flexor.''
</P>
<P>
   Although teams are technically not supposed to pass along
fraudulent information to the media, during the playoffs, no one
wants to reveal who's hurting where. But would professional hockey
players intentionally target an opposing player's injured body
part?
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt,'' Nolan said. ``If we knew someone had a bad
shoulder over there, they'd get hit every shift. You're not trying
to injure someone, but you want them to know they're going to get
hit, maybe they get rushed and make an error.''  &QL; 
Intact line
</P>
<P>
   Owen Nolan made a quick recovery in Game 3, scoring the
game-winning goal and playing 23 minutes, 11 seconds on 26 shifts,
including time on the power play and penalty kill.
</P>
<P>
   His return prompted Sharks coach Darryl Sutter to reunite the
team's most dangerous regular-season scoring line of winger Nolan,
winger Jeff Friesen and center Vincent Damphousse for the first
time in the playoffs. Damphousse set up Nolan's goal with a
terrific lead centering pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it worked,'' Friesen said. ``We had a lot of
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutter had used big Dave Lowry against the Blues to battle
defensemen Chris Pronger and Al MacInnis, as well as in the first
two games against the Stars. But Sutter has changed his thinking to
speed over brawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the lines will stay like that,'' Nolan said.  &QL; 
Honorable Sharks
</P>
<P>
   Two Sharks were selected as finalists for the NHL's annual
awards. Defenseman Brad Stuart is a finalist, along with New
Jersey's Scott Gomez and New York Rangers' Michael York, for the
Calder Memorial Trophy, awarded to the league's top rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Sharks center Mike Ricci is a finalist, along with Michal
Handzus of St. Louis and Detroit's Steve Yzerman, for the Frank J.
Selke Trophy, awarded to the most outstanding defensive forward.
Stars winger Jere Lehtinen won the award the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor,'' Ricci said, ``but I have other things to
worry about right now.''  &QL; 
Shark as seer
</P>
<P>
   A series prediction from Owen Nolan: ``It's going to be a
physical series, I think it's going to go six or seven games. The
team that wants it the most, works the hardest, is going to win
it.''  &QL; 
A better view
</P>
<P>
   Sharks coach Darryl Sutter finally got to see his team play with
a lead after going more than seven periods without scoring against
the Stars. He acknowledged the Stars are a different team when they
have to play from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we scored the two goals they were taking a few more
chances, probably getting some more shots, and conversely, with
those chances then maybe we got more odd-man situations than the
last two games total,'' he said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
