<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4804 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BESTFOODS-UNILEVER-AR     05-03 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTFOODS-UNILEVER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNILEVER SEEMS READY TO LIFT BESTFOODS BID
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though Bestfoods rejected an $18.4 billion takeover outright on
Tuesday, Unilever seemed poised to sweeten its offer on Wednesday
for the company, which makes Hellmann's mayonnaise and Thomas'
English muffins.
</P>
<P>
   Two executives close to the situation said they expected
Unilever to raise its cash bid of $66 a share by the end of the
week. Unilever first bid a range of $61 to $64. A stock analyst in
New York said a price of $70 was possible, given the target
company's solid business and the eagerness of Unilever, which makes
household products as well as packaged foods, to expand in the food
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed to favor a deal as they sent the stock of
Bestfoods up $10 11/16 on Wednesday, to $61 1/4, in New York Stock
Exchange trading.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods' chief executive, meanwhile, insisted that his company
had no desire for such a merger. And his board unanimously rejected
the offer, saying it did not think there was an opportunity for a
sale of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a ship that's going down the river right now that is
doing very well, thank you,'' said Charles R. Shoemate, who has
held the position of chief executive for the last 10 years. ``And
we're going to keep doing what we've been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Unilever annual meeting in London, the company's
co-chairmen, Niall FitzGerald and Antony Burgmans, repeated their
position that Bestfoods had until the end of Thursday to respond to
the offer. Executives with knowledge of the takeover attempt said
Unilever was lining up a $20 billion loan to finance the
transaction, suggesting it expected to prevail. The loan is being
syndicated by four banks: ABN Amro, Deutsche Bank, Warburg Dillon
Read, and Goldman, Sachs. Goldman, Sachs is advising Unilever in
the takeover effort. Bestfoods' bankers are Merrill Lynch and
Salomon Smith Barney, a unit of Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts speculated that a higher offer could be used to
coax friendly talks because it would be costly and time-consuming
for Unilever to attempt a hostile takeover given that there are
anti-takeover provisions in place at Bestfoods.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever, which is based in London and Amsterdam, has been on an
acquisition binge even though it announced plans in February to
shed more than 1,000 local and regional brands and to cut 25,000
jobs to focus on its best-performing businesses. Just three weeks
ago, it reached an agreement to buy Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade for $326
million. The same day, it announced it would pay $2.6 billion for
Slim-Fast Foods, the diet company.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the mergers lies one undeniable fact: the rapid
consolidation of the supermarket industry over the last two years
has shifted power from the food companies to the retailers. For the
companies to regain bargaining power, they, too, have to
consolidate, said Jeffrey G. Kanter, an analyst with Prudential
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always said the manufacturer has to fight back, and an
easy way of doing it is to get bigger,'' he said. ``They have to
have enough clout where they have products in every one of those
inner aisles and can go to the retailer with a larger voice.''
</P>
<P>
   The increasingly global operations of some retailers, like Royal
Ahold and Carrefours, put additional pressure on manufacturers to
grow. ``If those retailers say they want to do global sourcing and
cut deals for their chains, are you going to be able to deliver or
not?'' asked James Hagan, an assistant professor for global
marketing strategy at Cornell University. ``To a certain extent, a
merger can give you the scope to allow you to be a global
supplier.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding Bestfoods, which is one-fifth the size of Unilever, would
make Unilever, including Ben &AMP; Jerry's and Slim-Fast, larger than
Nestle, the global leader in packaged food.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods, which is based in Englewood Cliffs, N.J., has had
solid sales growth, about half of it generated by buying other
brands, and has many successful overseas divisions, particularly in
Latin America. Among its well-known products are Skippy peanut
butter, Knorr soups, Entenmann's baked goods, Mazola cooking oil
and Mueller's pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Though earnings have grown 10 percent or more annually over the
last 10 years, Bestfoods' share price has been disappointing. One
stock analyst said that the company could have bought back stock or
taken other steps to bolster its share price, rather than waiting
for Unilever to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods led other food stocks higher on Wednesday in an
otherwise dismal day in the market, while Unilever's American
depository receipts dropped $2 3/16, to $22 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   At $66 a share, companies like H.J. Heinz, which approached
Bestfoods about a possible merger last summer, would be unlikely
participants, Kanter said. Multinational giants like Nestle might
be interested, but would probably face antitrust issues, another
stock analyst said. A possible contender is Philip Morris, which
owns Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of acquisitions, so we are obviously in favor of
combining one business with another,'' Shoemate said. ``But big
does not make you good. You get good by being big in brand power
and profit growth. There are lots of examples of companies that
lose their focus and get big for big's sake.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4806 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-GERALDINE-FERRARO-ON-     05-03 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERALDINE-FERRARO-ON-CARDINAL-OCONNOR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING CARDINAL O'CONNOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 By GERALDINE FERRARO  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    I will miss John Cardinal O'Connor.
 &HT;    I haven't always felt that way, of course. Back during my 1984
campaign for vice president, in fact, there were plenty of times
when I wished fervently that he would simply go away.
 &HT;    But he didn't, and over the years I took the measure of a man
who, now that he has finally left us, leaves a void that will be
all but impossible to fill.
 &HT;    Then-Bishop O'Connor of New York burst into my consciousness
like a lion pouncing on its prey, and I don't mind admitting that I
was outraged by both the suddenness and the seriousness of his
attack.
 &HT;    As would be the case so often in years to come, the issue in
1984 was abortion. It was a battle of words, not substance, and it
was one that could never be resolved, because we had staked out our
positions and neither of us was going to be moved.
 &HT;    ``The Catholic Church's position opposing abortion is
monolithic,'' Bishop O'Connor asserted.
 &HT;    I agreed entirely, but felt that the Church didn't speak for all
Catholics on the issue. Many Catholics, including some lay Catholic
theologians, were pro-choice, I pointed out, myself among them.
 &HT;    ``The Catholic position regarding abortion is not monolithic,''
I summarized.
 &HT;    In the end, it was a disaster for all involved. We were talking
past each other, neither really trying to convince the other, and
the only winners were Ronald Reagan and George Bush, whose campaign
milked the argument between us for all it was worth, doing their
best to make it seem as if I were running against the bishop, not
Vice President Bush.
 &HT;    Needless to say, we didn't win the election.
 &HT;    It was several months before I had a chance to mend fences with
Bishop O'Connor. The occasion was his departure for Rome to be
invested as a cardinal, a prince of the Church.
 &HT;    I was genuinely happy for him, and wanted to congratulate him _
but I wasn't quite sure how to do it. Finally I decided to trust to
humor, and sent him a short note.
 &HT;    ``I want to add my congratulations to that of all your friends
on your elevation to cardinal,'' I wrote. ``I only wanted to be
vice president. You got to be a prince!''
 &HT;    I was a bit worried when I dropped that letter in the mail,
however. After all, I wasn't sure if O'Connor had a sense of humor
in the first place.
 &HT;    I was reassured when, several weeks later, I got a call from the
Archdiocese, inviting me to the Chancery for breakfast with the
cardinal. We talked for quite a while, but not about abortion _ we
both knew that was one of several issues on which we would never
agree.
 &HT;    But as we talked, it became clear that we agreed on so many
other things. I left the meeting that morning comfortable in the
knowledge that I had made a friend.
 &HT;    Over the next several years, on more than one occasion I found
my life in turmoil. Invariably, just when I needed it most, the
phone would ring and I would hear the cardinal's familiar voice
giving comfort, offering a prayer.
 &HT;    The fascinating thing about the man, I soon learned, was that
while he may have been a Prince of the Church in name, in spirit he
was very much a parish priest, always looking after his flock.
 &HT;    I guess that's what most defined him. He was a man of
contradictions, and most of them arose from conflicts between those
two roles.
 &HT;    He made headlines condemning abortion, but quietly provided
shelter for unwed mothers. He adamantly opposed gays marching in
the St. Patrick's Day Parade, but funded hospices for people with
AIDS.
 &HT;    He never pulled his punches in condemning what he believed to be
a sin, but he loved the ``sinners'' nonetheless, and quietly,
effectively, he made a difference in the lives of many of them.
 &HT;    His job required him to be a politician, and like many
politicians he engendered extreme emotional responses. Like no
Cardinal New York had known before, he seemed to splinter people
into opposing camps. People either loved him or hated him _ and
some of us did both at different times.
 &HT;    Maybe it was his military background that made him seem so rigid
on matters of faith, but maybe that also accounted for the ease he
felt with his brothers in arms in the political and business world.
 &HT;    But this soldier was also a television star, keenly aware of the
impact of television and deft in using it from the pulpit. His
sense of duty to Rome was traditional in the deepest sense, but he
was a man of the modern world when it came to using its media to
bring that message to his diocese and to the nation beyond.
 &HT;    His will be an extremely tough act to follow _ an activist
priest, a defender of dogma, a man of business acumen who was
politically knowledgeable and media-savvy, a prince of an ancient
church who left his mark on 20th-century New York and the United
States as a whole.
 &HT;    He came into my life as a lion and left it as a lamb. And I will
miss him.
 c.2000 Geraldine A. Ferraro  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Geraldine Ferraro was the Democratic vice-presidential
candidate in 1984. A former member of Congress, she is a political
analyst for Fox News and president of G&AMP;L Strategies in New York
and Arlington, Va., a corporate consultancy on workplace and
diversity issues.)
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _ _  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4809 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-GERALDINE-FERRARO-ON-     05-03 0971
</HEADER>
