<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-PRIMARIES-NYT &LR;      05-03 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PRIMARIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: GOP PROPOSAL TO REFORM PRIMARIES GETS SCRUTINY AND
SKEPTICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Republican leaders proposed scrapping the
current presidential nominating system, they immediately confronted
a series of questions, ranging from their motives to their chance
of success to whether their new idea would work as they hoped _ or
at least work better than the system they wanted to replace.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, unveiled Tuesday, would start the primaries with
the nation's smallest states, plus the District of Columbia, Puerto
Rico and three tiny U.S. territories. They could have primaries no
sooner than the first Tuesday in March. Slightly bigger states
could go in April, medium-size states in May, and big states in
June.
</P>
<P>
   As outlined by the former senator and Republican Party chairman
Bill Brock, the plan seeks to maintain and deepen the public's
sense of having a role in the choice of nominees by maintaining
competitive races through June, when nearly half the delegates
would be chosen. Brock also hopes the plan would make it somewhat
easier for underfinanced candidates to make an impact by keeping
the early stages of the race inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
   While many Democrats, instinctively assuming deviousness, were
trying Wednesday to figure out how the scheme would give the
Republicans an advantage, they could not find a lever.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the plan suddenly attracts public interest and support, a
remote possibility, there is nothing in it to benefit the
Republicans over the Democrats. Indeed, the burden of making some
politicians mad _ and Californians are already in a snit over the
idea of their primary being pushed back to June _ falls only on the
Republicans. Democrats can sit back and see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   As to the likelihood of success, Republicans can probably get
this plan past their rules committee, on which territories and
small states have one vote each, just like California.
</P>
<P>
   But they could have a difficult time at their convention, where
the big states pushed back to June have more votes. After that,
they would try to make some post-election deal with the Democrats
and try pushing the states to change their primary dates. In sum, a
very difficult task.
</P>
<P>
   But would it work? Previous efforts to change the system have
not always succeeded as the sponsors had hoped. Some failed
immediately. In 1988, for instance, Southern Democrats' effort to
exert conservative influence by grouping their primaries on what
became known as Super Tuesday failed, giving more aid to two
liberal candidates, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, than their favorite son, Sen. Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Others fail over time, like the 1974 Federal Election Campaign
Act, which ensured clean presidential races until the accountants
figured out soft money in 1988 and perfected it in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Two operational problems stand out. Nelson Polsby, a political
scientist at the University of California at Berkeley, said the
news media would thwart the plan by continuing to declare winners
on the basis of the early primaries. News organizations, he said,
``legitimately report early results and these early results
influence later results.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Patterson, a Harvard political scientist, said he thought
the first time a bunch of primaries came on the same day, the
results would be covered as if they were decisive.
</P>
<P>
   Brock disagreed. ``The press is composed of human beings, and
they very much like a contest, and that makes news.'' If the
contest lasted until the third group of states, in May, ``the odds
of anyone having mathematical certainty are zero,'' he said. ``I
think people would be very careful until the big states are heard
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Another major problem would be money. One dirty little secret of
the present system is that while it schedules primaries from
January until June, the federal matching grant system does not
provide money for a primary contest that lasts beyond April, when
recent races have been over. Even the wealthy Bush campaign, which
rejected public funding to avoid donation limits, would be flat
broke if it were still buying television time today.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Shrum, a veteran Democratic consultant now working for Vice
President Gore, said that ``for people who are relying on public
funding, it would be a huge problem.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``People spend early to try to get a knockout. They
would run out of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee, an early dropout from
the 2000 Republican race, said a stretched-out calendar would help
lesser-known candidates, but the goals would not be reached with
the current $1,000 limit on campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where we ever got the idea that it takes money to
put out The New York Times, and invade Normandy and to build New
York University _ but not to run for president,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   Brock said his critics were right _ ``if people acted as they do
now.'' He said if candidates prepared for a long haul, they would
spend more carefully.
</P>
<P>
   He said that would give ``lesser-known candidates a chance to
stay in, which is very much a part of our purpose.'' But, he said,
``maybe this will force us to address the insanity of present
campaign laws which promote the importance of money over issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell West, a political scientist at Brown University,
suggested that even without more money, the Brock system could work
if it forced candidates to reach voters in ways other than
television advertisements, by emphasizing debates, the Internet and
personal campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Even skeptics like Alexander said the proposed system would be
``much better than the crammed-up primaries we have today.'' Polsby
said ``it might shift the front load to middle front load.'' And
Brock said: ``There is no perfect system. We're trying to improve
the present system. We don't say this is nirvana.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
