r s BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     05-03 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ NEEDS TO STEP IT UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now on the threshold of taking one of the greatest pratfalls in
NBA history getting eliminated in the first round of the playoffs
by an eighth seeded team after winning 67 regular season games the
Los Angeles Lakers are taking solace in the fact that the deciding
fifth game against the Sacramento Kings will be staged at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers continue to play like they did in their two
unsightly losses in Sacramento, they will get beat again and
Shaquille O'Neal will enhance his reputation as being a post-season
choke artist of dizzying heights unparalleled by an athletic
performer of his magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers shouldn't lose Friday night against the Kings, but
they shouldn't have lost both games in the state capital, either.
</P>
<P>
   They not only stumbled ignobly over their press clippings, but
Shaquille O'Neal is being out-worked and even on occasion
out-played by, of all people, Vlade Divac.
</P>
<P>
   How can that freak of nature be happening?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a strange occurrence has unfolded on the way to
Shaquille O'Neal picking up his first MVP trophy and first NBA
title he has taken a snooze and reverted to the pacifistic form
that resulted in the Lakers the past two seasons being swept in
four straight by the Utah Jazz and San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Not statistically, of course.
</P>
<P>
   In his deepest state of somnolence, O'Neal always will get his
20 plus points and 15 plus rebounds against the Kings because of
his immense size and uncommon athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   But while Divac has been energetically scurrying around the
court, cajoling teammates and reacting emotionally to every
positive King development, O'Neal has retained the stoic
countenance of a high stakes poker player.
</P>
<P>
   That's the proper deportment if you're engaged in a card game at
the Bicycle Club, or Commerce Casino, but I'm not sure it's the
tack to take if you're the leader of a basketball team that
desperately needs to be jarred out of its lethargy.
</P>
<P>
   Not once during those Laker disasters in Sacramento did O'Neal
express anger at an official, or dress down a malingering teammate,
or do anything to indicate that his competitive fires were burning
strongly.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ol' Shaq Daddy has displayed more passion in a rap
video, or even in one of his cornball movies, than he did against
the Kings, who successfully have double and triple teamed him since
his 46-point Game 1 eruption.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was a total non-factor defensively in the 101-88 Game4
loss, as the Kings kept driving merrily around him for easy
baskets.
</P>
<P>
   He managed a mere one block in 46 minutes, the same total as his
caddy, Travis Knight, managed in a mere 60 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Where was O'Neal's regular season intimidation that inspired a
lot of us to favorably compare his play with that of the late Wilt
Chamberlain?
</P>
<P>
   Why did it seem as though his sneakers were stapled to the Arco
Arena floor?
</P>
<P>
   Is O'Neal hurt, and not telling anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Or is his trance a result of his unconsciously wanting the Laker
owner, Jerry Buss, to pick up a ton of extra money by playing an
extra playoff game at Staples Center?
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea what became of the inspired, motivated Shaquille
O'Neal who was so dominating throughout the NBA regular season and
the opening two games of the series against the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll have greater energy in Friday's game against the
Kings, but our big man has to be more dominating,'' says Jerry
West, the Lakers' top administrator. ``We expect to win at home,
but there are no guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even if Shaquille O'Neal rouses himself out of his
mysterious slumber, he will have to receive more assistance from
his Laker teammates against a young, animated Kings' team with a
talented power forward, Chris Webber, who has tormented A.C. Green
and Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   You know the Lakers are in serious trouble when Kobe Bryant
takes 30 shots, as he did Tuesday night against the Kings in a vain
effort to ignite the woeful Laker offense.
</P>
<P>
   This results in Bryant dribbling excessively, and that results
in inevitable turnovers by the Laker prodigy who seemed to be the
only player on the team to exert maximum energy against the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   While scoring 32 points to top the Lakers scoring, Bryant also
committed seven turnovers, which is too many for the team to be
effective.
</P>
<P>
   But don't blame Kobe Bryant for the Lakers' current predicament.
</P>
<P>
   The team didn't get anything in Sacramento out of Green, Horry,
Glen Rice, Ron Harper, Brian Shaw, Rick Fox and Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson supposedly coaches the Lakers, but I didn't notice him
doing his job against the Kings. He seemed as disinterested in the
proceedings as Shaquille O'Neal, not once complaining harshly to
the officials, not once even angrily scolding one of his listless
players.
</P>
<P>
   If such behavior doesn't change dramatically, the Lakers soon
will be relegated to the dustbin of athletic infamy, a team that
will be cruelly ridiculed like the Buffalo Bills and Atlanta Braves
have been for their post-season failures.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the Bills kept qualifying for Super Bowls and the
Braves have kept making World Series appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers now face the harrowing prospect and the widespread
scorn and ridicule that would go with it of not even making it out
of the first round of the playoffs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
