<SLUG> BC-OBIT-O'CONNOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S CARDINAL JOHN O'CONNOR IS DEAD AT 80
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cardinal John O'Connor, head of the New York
Archdiocese and one of the country's most outspoken Catholic
leaders, died Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night at the age of 80.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor had weakened steadily since August, when he underwent
an operation for a brain tumor. He had not appeared in public since
March 5, and even then he only spoke briefly to the congregation at
St. Patrick's Cathedral and did not read a sermon.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, for the first time in the 16 years that he led the
archdiocese, he was unable to watch the Easter Parade from the
cathedral steps.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal's spokesman, Joe Zwilling, said that the cardinal's
condition worsened Tuesday night. O'Connor's sister, other
relatives, and fellow clergy had been sitting with him, three
people at a time, in his residence behind St. Patrick's.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Bernard F. Law of Boston flew to New York Wednesday to
be at his side. The two have long been friends and ideological
allies. Law's spokesman, John Walsh, said: ``They were made
archbishop around the same time, raised to the role of cardinal at
the same time, and share geographical proximity, similarities in
outlook on the church, so they gravitated to one another. There was
a natural chemistry there, and this relationship grew even closer
during this very difficult time.''
</P>
<P>
   Law is one of several bishops rumored to be a possible successor
to O'Connor. Other widely mentioned possibilities include Bishop
Sean O'Malley of Fall River, Mass., and Auxiliary Bishop William
Murphy of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   However, nobody outside the Vatican knows or talks about such
matters with any certainty. When O'Connor's predecessor, Cardinal
Terence Cooke, died, nobody guessed the replacement would be
O'Connor, who had been a bishop in Scranton, Pa., and before that
vicar of the US Armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor was appointed to the archdiocese in 1984 and almost
instantly stirred up controversy by expressing Rome's views on
high-profile political issues in a far more outspoken manner than
his predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Right away, he publicly likened abortion to the Holocaust,
denounced homosexuality as a sin, and criticized Geraldine Ferraro,
then a Queens congresswoman running as the Democratic vice
presidential candidate, for supporting abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   These were not uniformly popular positions in the archdiocese,
which consists of 2.3 million Catholics in much of New York City,
its suburbs, and the Hudson Valley.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor defied easy categories, however, marching alongside
union workers, campaigning for a raise in the minimum wage, and
taking care, often anonymously, of dying patients in AIDS clinics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, after a trip to Jerusalem, he played a major role in
persuading the Vatican to admit and apologize for its record of
anti-Semitism. He became close friends with New York's Jewish mayor
of the time, Edward Koch. The two even wrote a book together.
</P>
<P>
   He was also friendly with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who is
Catholic. But, unlike Cardinal Francis Spellman, who was called
``The Powerhouse'' when he ran the Archdiocese from 1937 to 1967,
O'Connor never sought to play a role political affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, O'Connor considerably softened the
confrontational stance of his early days and was a popular
cardinal, though a less influential one than he may have been in an
earlier time.
</P>
<P>
   In Spellman's day, for instance, Irish Catholics formed a major
part of the city's power elite, Every cardinal in New York has been
of Irish descent. However, in recent years, the Irish have faded as
a unified ethnic bloc, and, apart from political considerations, a
growing percentage of the city's Catholics are now Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor submitted his resignation to the Vatican each year for
the past five years, a motion consistently ignored. It was widely
believed that Pope John Paul II would finally let him go last
January, when O'Connor turned 80, the age at which cardinals lose
their vote to choose a new pope, but he was kept on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Paulson of the Globe staff contributed to this report
from Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
