<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NAPSTER _ &LR;  The battle over music in cyberspace spilled onto the
streets of San Mateo, Calif., yesterday as Metallica guitarist Lars
Ulrich jawed with fans of Napster, the popular and controversial
music-sharing software.  &UR; BY BENNY EVANGELISTA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MACQ&AMP;A (COLUMN) _ &LR;  When I print e-mail or Web pages on my new iMac,
an abundance of extra sheets pour out, costing me much in wasted
paper as well as self-esteem. The last message I printed had three
pages of actual worthwhile info, but along with those, the printer
spat out three additional sheets with nothing but gibberish like
``mailbox:Macintosh%2OHD
/System%20Folder/Preferences/Netscape%20Users/.'' And when I print
a Web page, I get an 8.5-by-11 sheet filled, but then another sheet
with the left margin showing what didn't fit on the first page, as
if the Web site was designed for 9-inch paper. Hard to read, and
another paper waster. Am I the only person who has problems like
these? Can you help me?  &UR; COLUMN BY HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; PIANO _ &LR;  A new high-tech piano could be the perfect toy for the
musically challenged dot-com magnate with extra cash to burn. Lots
of extra cash.  &UR; BY BENNY EVANGELISTA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CISCO _ &LR;  David Hawkins nearly hit the jackpot in 1995. Just 10 days
after starting a job at a Palo Alto, Calif., networking startup,
Cisco Systems bought out the firm for roughly $30 million. Hawkins,
36, one of just 10 employees at Network Translation, ended up with
$100,000 in stock, which would be worth roughly $2 million if he
still held it today.  &UR; BY TODD &LR; 
 &UR; WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MEDIA (MEDIA BYTES COLUMN) _ &LR;  It was a glitzy party for a cheesy
movie. Tina Brown, the editor of Talk magazine, came to San
Francisco last week, unveiling for a tech and media crowd the
Miramax movie ``Takedown,'' the hyped-up story of notorious hacker
Kevin Mitnick and the effort to send him to prison.  &UR; COLUMN &LR; 
 &UR; BY DAN FOST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; PG&AMP;E _ &LR;  As many as 120 premature deaths could be avoided each year
if a pair of aging New England power plants owned by San
