<SLUG> BC-PG&AMP;E-DEATHS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DEATHS LINKED TO PG&AMP;E COAL PLANTS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As many as 120 premature deaths would be avoided
each year if a pair of aging New England power plants owned by San
Francisco's Pacific Gas and Electric Corp. met current
environmental standards, researchers from the Harvard School of
Public Health will report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The coal-burning plants, purchased by PG&AMP;E two years ago, have
been harshly criticized by Massachusetts environmentalists as being
among the worst polluters in the state.
</P>
<P>
   However, foes of the plants until now have lacked an
authoritative study addressing the health impact of airborne
emissions from the smokestacks at Salem Harbor and Brayton Point
near Somerset.
</P>
<P>
   That changes with release of the findings from Jonathan Levy and
John Spengler of the Harvard School of Public Health's Department
of Environmental Health. A copy of the findings was obtained by The
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``PG&AMP;E has consistently said that there's no evidence of health
impacts as a result of their plants,'' said Rob Sargent,
legislative director with the Massachusetts Public Intererst
Research Group, or MassPIRG.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Harvard report confirms our suspicions that there are
substantial impacts from these emissions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from reducing cases of asthma and other disorders, the
report emphasizes that lives could be saved if PG&AMP;E's two plants
met more stringent environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate that reducing emissions from the actual to the
target levels would result in 40 fewer premature deaths
attributable to Salem Harbor emissions and 80 fewer deaths
attributable to Brayton Point emissions per year,'' the report
says.
</P>
<P>
   A PG&AMP;E spokesperson was unavailable to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, coal-fired plants built before the early
1970s are exempt from meeting current environmental standards for
emissions.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard study's findings are based on what would happen if
the Salem Harbor and Brayton Point facilities were brought in line
with current standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these plants were built anytime in the last 25 years they
would be considered illegal,'' said Lori Ehrlich, a Salem area
accountant and co-founder of Salem Power Plant HealthLink, a
grassroots organization.
</P>
<P>
   The two plants are the target of a lawsuit by Boston's
Conservation Law Foundation charging that PG&AMP;E mishandled coal
waste at the facilities, allowing chromium, arsenic, mercury and
other toxic chemicals to seep into the groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard report notes that Massachusetts Gov. Paul Cellucci
has pledged to cut emissions from the state's worst-polluting power
plants, and that the Department of Environmental Protection is
drafting related guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   MassPIRG's Sargent said most local plant owners had submitted
``voluntary proposals'' for cleaning up their operations.
</P>
<P>
   Only PG&AMP;E, he said, offered a plan that would actually have
resulted in increased burning of coal, which would have increased
emissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not something we were happy about,'' Sargent said,
``and it was enough to convince the governor that voluntary plans
would not work.''
</P>
<P>
   Although PG&AMP;E officials say they have tried to work with
neighbors of the plants and with environmental groups, activists
counter that they have gotten nowhere in their dealings with the
utility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been astounded by PG&AMP;E's arrogance,'' Sargent said.
</P>
<P>
   The company held its annual shareholder meeting in Boston last
month _ the first time that it ever had been held outside the Bay
Area.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, PG&AMP;E's chief executive, Bob Glynn, was invited
to sit down with local residents to discuss ways to resolve the
situation. He did not say whether he would accept such an
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, PG&AMP;E reported an 80 percent surge in quarterly
earnings from operations, topping Wall Street's estimates.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
