<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4844 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-DELAY-LAWSUIT-HNS &LR;      05-03 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAY-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS' SUIT ACCUSES KEY REPUBLICAN OF EXTORTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
and STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an escalation of interparty warfare, Democratic
leaders sued House Majority Whip Tom DeLay on Wednesday, accusing
him of extortion and money laundering in connection with his
aggressive campaign fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual civil action, filed in U.S. District Court here
under federal anti-racketeering statutes, alleges that the Texas
Republican helped set up several tax-exempt conservative
organizations under the direction of former aides to avoid
disclosing the source and expenditure of millions in campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The federal complaint, submitted by the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee, accused DeLay and his closest political
associates of using his high-ranking position in the House to mount
a ``scheme to extort political contributions from individuals and
entities with interests before Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay or his surrogates promised ``legislative'' favors or other
actions in return for increased giving to the Republican Party, GOP
candidates or affiliated groups, the lawsuit charged, including
putting the squeeze on potential donors such as Microsoft chairman
Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   The effort, the suit alleges, was designed to help Republicans
maintain control of the House in this year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. DeLay is unfortunately conducting these activities under
the color of his office _ as he seeks through the use of systematic
extortion _ to coerce the contribution of millions of dollars to
Republicans and to intimidate those inclined to support
Democrats,'' said Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., who heads the
Democratic campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   In response, DeLay said he was ``saddened and disappointed'' by
the ``unfounded, politically motivated charges.'' Aides said the
congressman, who represents a suburban area of Houston, would have
more to say about it Thursday in a speech at the National Press
Club.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay press secretary Emily Miller called the charges ``invalid
and baseless,'' adding that the complaint was filed under an
anti-racketeering law often associated with organized crime just
for ``the pure shock value'' of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in his or her right mind would read through these
outrageous allegations and believe that the Democrats are acting in
any way other than pure ugly political venom,'' Miller said, adding
that DeLay will ask the court to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans quickly rallied around DeLay, one of the most
successful fund-raisers in GOP history. Several members accused the
Democrats of a mean-spirited effort to shut down ``legitimate''
conservative groups by ``impugning the character of the majority
whip.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy dismissed the criticism, calling the lawsuit ``a
serious complaint'' that would shine light on illegal campaign
fund-raising tactics used by DeLay since the Republicans won
control of the House in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before has a senior congressional and party leader
devised a scheme like this _ hammering contributors for money,
threatening to punish those who decline, and setting up a shadow
party structure outside the public view and our laws in order to
make it possible,'' said Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the lawsuit alleges that DeLay helped set up a
network of tax-exempt organizations outside the party to funnel
contributions to his favored GOP candidates and causes. The lawsuit
said donors were encouraged to contribute to the independent groups
to evade reporting requirements under federal election laws that
govern party fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint charges that the use of the groups, organized
under two provisions of the internal revenue code that do not
require them to report the source or expenditure of funds, amounts
to illegal money laundering by DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations named in the complaint are U.S. Family
Network, Americans for Economic Growth and the Republican Majority
Issues Committee. The three groups are run by former DeLay aides Ed
Buckham, Karl Gallant and Jim Ellis. The three men are part of
DeLay's inner circle and advise him on political matters.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint focuses a lot of attention on the Republican
Majority organization, a group headed by Gallant that is trying to
raise $25 million to use on voter drives and issue advertising in
the fall campaign. The group's effort is designed to offset the
huge expenditures that organized labor is expected to make this
year on behalf of Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Gallant called the Democratic action against
DeLay ``an attack by party hacks.'' He said his conservative issue
group uses the same tactics as the Sierra Club and other ``liberal
organizations'' that normally back Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit marked the third time in a year that the Democrats
have sought to curtail DeLay's formidable fund-raising network that
Washington insiders have called ``DeLay Inc.'' Democrats filed a
complaint with the Justice Department last year that went nowhere.
They also filed similar charges with the Federal Election
Commission, with no result so far.
</P>
<P>
   But the court filing represents a ratcheting up of the
interparty feuding this election year, when control of the House
could go either way in the November voting. DeLay is a prime target
of Democrats, not only because of his successful fund-raising
tactics but because he has emerged as the party's leading hardline
conservative spokesman since the retirement of former House Speaker
Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are asking the court to shut down DeLay's
independent fund-raising operations and to award unspecified
``damages'' under the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organization Act, known as RICO.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit contains little evidence collected by Democrats, and
relies primarily on news accounts of DeLay's activities. But
Democrats are hoping that the judge, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson,
will allow a discovery process to take depositions and pore over
DeLay's fund-raising records.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' use of a law widely thought to be aimed at
thwarting organized crime might appear to be hardball politics in a
different setting _ in a courtroom rather than on the stump. But
University of Houston law professor Sandra Guerra said a Supreme
Court decision in 1994 indicates that the case could have merit.
</P>
<P>
   In that decision, the court allowed the National Organization
for Women to proceed with its RICO lawsuit against anti-abortion
protesters who were allegedly engaged in extortion by threatening
violence against abortion-clinic workers and patients in an effort
to shut down the medical facilities. The anti-abortion group argued
unsuccessfully it was merely asserting its constitutional First
Amendment right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   But law professor David Crump, also of the University of
Houston, said the Democrats will have the heavy burden of
overcoming a federal judge's inevitable skepticism. He said the
judge would have to conclude before a trial begins that Congress
intended the anti-racketeering statute to cover the fund-raising
activities of a House member.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
