<SLUG> BC-CISCO-COPYING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PROGRAMMER WRITES CODE FOR BAD LUCK  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ David Hawkins nearly hit the jackpot in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 days after starting a job at a Palo Alto, Calif.,
networking startup, Cisco Systems bought out the firm for roughly
$30 million. Hawkins, 36, one of just 10 employees at Network
Translation, ended up with $100,000 in stock, which would be worth
roughly $2 million if he still held it today.
</P>
<P>
   But the San Mateo County resident's luck faded quickly after he
left Cisco in August 1996 to start a rival company, Meridian
Networks Systems of San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   After Hawkins' company showed off its first product at a trade
show in Las Vegas in 1997, Cisco accused the programmer of ripping
off its coveted software code and repackaging it as his own. Police
raided his home office and found copies of Cisco's software on two
of Hawkins' computers. He was charged with theft and illegal
copying.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after, Meridian folded ``under a cloud of litigation,''
and Hawkins was forced to find a job outside the computer industry,
said Dan Barton, Hawkins' attorney in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Although a Santa Clara, Calif., jury on Friday acquitted him of
misappropriation of trade secrets, Hawkins was found guilty of
illegally copying Cisco's ``source code'' and faces up to three
years in prison, Barton said. To make matters worse, Hawkins sold
his Cisco stock in 1996 and 1997, before it became worth a small
fortune, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hawkins has paid dearly for this,'' Barton said.
</P>
<P>
   Barton says Hawkins merely did what many programmers do when
they leave a company _ make copies of the computer files on their
work computer. Barton said Cisco pushed for charges simply to fight
off a potential competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not news that dominant companies often use their power in
anticompetitive ways,'' he said. Cisco declined comment on the
case.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors stand by their charge that Hawkins copied the
software in order to steal Cisco's product.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an ingrate,'' said Deputy District Attorney Frank
Dudley Berry Jr., pointing to the lucrative stock options Hawkins
received from Network Translation and Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   Berry also estimated that Hawkins stole software worth $2
billion, based on sales generated by products that use that code.
Barton disputes the estimate, adding that the value of tech
products erode quickly with time. Prosecutors were unable to show
that Cisco was actually harmed, because the software was not widely
distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins is to be sentenced June 22 by Judge Thomas Hastings.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
