<HEADER>
A4849 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-GIUILIANI-CAMPAIGN     05-03 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIUILIANI-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SAYS HELMS REFLECTS BROAD G.O.P.
</HEADLINE>
  By ELISABETH BUMILLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ In his first town hall meeting upstate, Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani said on Wednesday that he would, if elected
senator, support Jesse Helms as chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee and that he would not share a ballot with Pat
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said his support of Helms reflected his belief that
Republicans should broaden their party to different points of view.
That would make it ``much healthier than a party dominated by one
part,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is running as a moderate Republican, and Helms is
ardently conservative, opposed to abortion and equal rights for gay
people.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani, who is seeking the endorsement of the state's
fractious Independence Party in his campaign against Hillary Rodham
Clinton for U.S. Senate, also said he would not accept the
endorsement if the party put Buchanan on its ticket for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I could do that, but I'm hoping they don't do
that,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton, without mentioning Giuliani by name, has said
that her Republican opponent in the race should decline to run on
the Independence Party ticket if Buchanan, the conservative
commentator, is at the top of the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   At the event on Wednesday, the mayor was interviewed by Chris
Matthews, the host of MSNBC's cable program, ``Hardball,'' at the
Rochester Institute of Technology here. More than 500 students
attended the event, which was telecast live. Matthews and the
students asked questions on topics as diverse as Elian Gonzalez,
police brutality and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Matthews sat in straight-back chairs, surrounded by
students as Giuliani's media consultant, Adam Goodman, recorded the
scene on film.
</P>
<P>
   One student asked the mayor if he thought he had a good chance
of winning the Senate race, even if ``you have a reputation of
supporting police brutality.'' Giuliani, referring to the Amadou
Diallo shooting, responded that: ``It was a terrible thing that
happened. It was a great tragedy.'' But he added that a racially
mixed jury had found the police officers not guilty and that the
police were more restrained in New York than in other cities. ``You
just don't know that because the media doesn't cover that,'' the
mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Giuliani appeared relaxed throughout the hourlong program
even as Mr. Matthews and some other students sometimes questioned
him aggressively. Afterward, his campaign aides sought out
reporters to impress on them their view of the mayor's steadiness
under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that Clinton would never allow herself to get in this
environment,'' said Juleanna Glover Weiss, the mayor's campaign
press secretary. ``It's free flowing, it's thoughtful, it's
completely unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said at the event that he ``very much'' wanted to run
for the Senate _ ``I'm looking forward to it,'' he said _ despite
his recent discovery that he has prostate cancer. He added, ``My
whole hope and intention is to do it. I'd be very disappointed if I
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews also presented the mayor with quotes from a
now-well-known paper that Giuliani wrote as a student at Manhattan
College, in which he said that objections to Robert F. Kennedy's
running for Senate from New York as a carpetbagger were ``truly
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani laughed, and responded by quoting Winston Churchill:
``Any person who isn't a liberal at 20 has no heart. And any person
who isn't a conservative by 40 has no brain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
