<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACQ&AMP;A-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MAC Q&AMP;A: PREVENT PAPER WASTE BY USING PRINT PREVIEW OR UTILITIES  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: When I print e-mail or Web pages on my new iMac, an abundance of
extra sheets pour out, costing me much in wasted paper as well as
self-esteem. The last message I printed had three pages of actual
worthwhile info, but along with those, the printer spat out three
additional sheets with nothing but gibberish like
``mailbox:Macintosh%2OHD
/System%20Folder/Preferences/Netscape%20Users/.'' And when I print
a Web page, I get an 8.5-by-11 sheet filled, but then another sheet
with the left margin showing what didn't fit on the first page, as
if the Web site was designed for 9-inch paper. Hard to read, and
another paper waster.
</P>
<P>
   Am I the only person who has problems like these? Can you help
me?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: You're certainly not the only one who struggles with such issues
_ whole forests give their lives every week to make those unwanted
sheets. I don't have a set-and-forget solution, but I can offer
some suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   One is to switch from Netscape Navigator to Microsoft's Internet
Explorer and start using its nifty Print Preview feature. (It's on
the File menu in IE 4.5 and now 5.0.) Just showing you the bad news
in advance wouldn't be much of a help, but the preview page also
has radio buttons that let you decide whether or not to print
headers and footers, graphics and background colors. Best of all,
there are Shrink to Fit and Crop buttons that automatically make
the page fit on one sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Explorer 5 is free for downloading at
 &LR; www.microsoft.com/mac/download/en/default.asp. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you want to stick with Navigator, or if you want even finer
control over what you print, either of two top-notch shareware
utilities can help:
</P>
<P>
   -- John Moe's $10 Net-Print 8.2 ( &LR; www93.pair.com/johnmoe/ &LR; ) lets
you print (or save) just the text you've selected, instead of the
whole document, in your browser or almost any other application; it
even provides an easy way to print multiple chunks of text from
separate sources on a single sheet.
</P>
<P>
   -- MacEase's $24.95 WebPrint Plus ( &LR; www.kagi.com/MacEase &LR; 
 &LR; /webprintplusmainpage.html &LR; ) combines similar basic capabilities
with extra options like time- and date-stamping your selections and
adding personal notes. My favorite feature: a customizable keyboard
shortcut that immediately prints one copy of whatever you've
selected.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dumb Move by Apple
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: How can I get AppleWorks 6 to open Microsoft Word and Excel
files? I did it all the time with ClarisWorks and never had any
trouble, but the new AppleWorks doesn't even see the files.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: You've put your finger on a big problem with the latest version
of Apple's Swiss-Army-knife productivity package. Fortunately,
workarounds are already available, and more good news is on the
way.
</P>
<P>
   First, a bit of background. AppleWorks 5 and its predecessor,
ClarisWorks, could open some Word and Excel files, along with files
created by a variety of other PC and Mac word processing,
spreadsheet, database and graphics applications, because Apple used
to bundle a limited version of DataViz' MacLinkPlus
format-translation software. The DataViz technology was also
included with the Mac OS itself, versions 7.5 through 8.1.
</P>
<P>
   The bundled translators weren't the most up-to-date, so you
couldn't open files from the latest versions of Microsoft Office
unless you paid DataViz extra to upgrade. But at least you could
work with older Office formats and in particular with RTF (Rich
Text Format) and SYLK, standards created specifically to facilitate
sharing of files among applications and across platforms.
</P>
<P>
   But with Mac OS 8.5 and now AppleWorks 6, Apple opted not to
renew its bundling deal with DataViz. Thanks to Apple's own
QuickTime technology, the program can read and write more graphics
and multimedia formats than ever. But by itself, unless you have
DataViz translators installed, AppleWorks can no longer handle any
kind of file from Office except raw, unformatted text.
</P>
<P>
   This has to be one of the dumber moves Apple has made in years.
I have no problem with telling the handful of people who still need
to open, say, XyWrite or even MacWrite files to pay for a
third-party translation program.
</P>
<P>
   But the ability to read and write interchange formats such as
RTF and SYLK is a different matter altogether _ it was not only a
convenience to millions of users, but also an important defense
against charges that the Mac just didn't fit in a Windows-dominated
world. Taking it out is bound to make life harder for Mac champions
in countless schools, businesses and even families.
</P>
<P>
   All is not lost, though. If you owned AppleWorks 5 or
ClarisWorks, your old translation software will continue to work
with AppleWorks 6. If you're using the same system folder you used
with previous versions, the old translation options should just
show up in the format popups in the program's Open and Save
dialogs. If not, dig out your old installation CD or floppies and
use the Custom Installation option to reinstall just the format
translation software.
</P>
<P>
   For users just starting out with AppleWorks 6, neither of those
solutions is available, but I'm happy to report that Apple has just
delivered a partial solution: It has released an update called
AppleWorks 6.0.3, and one of its features is an RTF translator. For
those who already have AppleWorks 6, the update, including the
translator, is be free. See
 &LR; asu.info.apple.com/swupdates.nsf/artnum/n11671 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you really want to co-exist with your Office-using
colleagues _ whether they're on the Mac or PC _ without having to
bug them to save their files in RTF, you'll need translators for
the native formats of Office 97, 98 and 2000. Apple is not going to
provide those, so you'll need to look to DataViz. If you want them
only to import into and export from AppleWorks, get MacLinkPlus for
iMac, a retail package that lists for $49.95. (It actually works
with other Macs, too, including the iBook, but only within
AppleWorks.)
</P>
<P>
   If you want the option of using the translators in other
applications, in addition to AppleWorks, you'll need the full
MacLinkPlus Deluxe 11. Retail, it sells for around $99, but if you
can prove ownership of the older version bundled with Mac OS
7.5-8.1, you can upgrade for $39.95 plus shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   A final word on AppleWorks 6: If you're now using version 5,
think twice or three times before upgrading. Version 6 does have
some nifty new features, and the user interface has been cleaned
up, but I can't remember an Apple software product that's been
greeted with more gripes by early adopters. See, for example, the
reports collected at  &LR; www.macintouch.com/appleworks6.html &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Probably the 6.0.3 update will take care of some of these
problems, but there's still the matter of price: Apple isn't
offering a discount or even a rebate program for upgraders _ even
if you own the last release, it wants you to pay the full retail
price, $79, for the new one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Voice on iBook
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I'd like to try IBM's ViaVoice speech-recognition software on my
new iBook, but it doesn't have a microphone or even a jack for an
add-on mike. Is there any way to get my voice into the iBook?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: You're in luck _ just pay your fare and hop on the Universal
Serial Bus. A microphone manufacturer named Telex just announced
that its two USB microphones are now iBook-compatible, provided
that you've upgraded to Mac OS 9.0.4
( &LR; www.computeraudio.telex.com/news/040600.html &LR; ). The H-531
head-worn mike is $59.99; the M-560, a ``superdirectional'' desktop
model, is $69.99. Both also work with iMacs (no mention of other
USB Mac models) and USB-equipped PCs running Windows 98 or 2000.
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE WEEK: On April 27, I noted in a Chronicle feature on
desktop moviemaking that Apple didn't include video-editing
software with the Power Mac G4 or the latest PowerBook, even though
those models have FireWire ports that can connect to digital
camcorders. Just 24 hours later, Apple made iMovie, the easy-to-use
editing application bundled with iMac DV models, available free on
the Web ( &LR; www.apple.com/ &LR;   &LR; imovie &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Apple's press release said that it is for owners of the G4 and
the new PowerBook and that it requires Mac OS 9.0.4 and QuickTime
4.1. But anyone can download it, and users report that it seems to
work fine with blue-and-white G3s and even with older Mac models.
As for the software, the program's installer says the minimum
requirements are Mac OS 8.5 and QuickTime 4.0.
</P>
<P>
   Note that the download is 19.2 megabytes, and that doesn't
include the giant (and excellent) online tutorial that comes on the
iMac DV hard drive. If you have a slow Internet connection, or if
you want the tutorial, you can order the whole shebang on CD-ROM
for a $19.95 shipping and handling fee _ just call (800) 293-6617.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
