<HEADER>
A4851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SF-PAPERS-2TAKES-NYT     05-03 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-PAPERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTIMONY CLOUDS PROPOSAL BY HEARST TO BUY CHRONICLE
</HEADLINE>
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   San Francisco's two daily newspapers have made their names and
reputations covering the sometimes arcane and often vindictive
power struggles of their city, whose political fault zones have
made the most commonplace business interactions unstable. Now the
newspapers themselves have become front-page news.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over again since last August, the Hearst Corp.'s $660
million deal to buy The San Francisco Chronicle and abandon The San
Francisco Examiner seemed on the verge of completion. But over and
over again, it has foundered in the face of dogged opposition.
First, from Mayor Willie Brown Jr. and the district attorney,
Terence Hallinan, then from antitrust lawyers in the U.S. Justice
Department. And this week, a businessman and sometime politician
filed a lawsuit seeking to scuttle the sale of both newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the businessman, Clinton Reilly, prevails in his civil
antitrust action, his lawsuit has already claimed one victim. On
Tuesday, Hearst issued a statement saying that Timothy O. White,
the publisher of The Examiner, would take ``an indefinite leave of
absence'' after his testimony on Monday that he offered favorable
editorial treatment if the mayor dropped his opposition to Hearst's
purchase of The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was in a tough re-election campaign at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The course of the lawsuit, and the sale, may not turn on White's
sensational testimony, with its clear implication of journalistic
logrolling and dishonesty. Still, it did nothing to clarify the
deal's murky prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Broadwater, the managing director of Veronis Suhler &AMP;
Associates, Hearst's investment banker for the sale of The
Examiner, said Wednesday, ``None of us would have thought that,
nine months after the fact, we would not have closed the
transaction, we would not have gotten approval from Justice and we
would have had this local problem crop up.''
</P>
<P>
   White almost immediately disavowed his testimony, saying he was
``tired and confused'' by the question. But then Reilly's lawyer,
Joseph M. Alioto, the son of a former San Francisco mayor, produced
an e-mail message that White sent to George Irish, president of
Hearst Newspapers, on Sept. 1, the same day he had lunch with
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   In the message White wrote, ``I asked Willie how I was going to
justify to my superiors in New York wanting to support him and
cooperate with him when he was seeming to go out of his way to make
our lives difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion that the publisher of the first newspaper owned by
the legendary William Randolph Hearst had reverted to his old
habits of using the paper for political ends prompted a quick
reaction from company executives. Late on Monday, the Hearst Corp.
issued a statement saying, ``It is not now _ nor has it ever been _
a policy of The San Francisco Examiner to trade favorable editorial
coverage for any gains, including political influence.''
</P>
<P>
   An even stronger disavowal, drafted by Examiner journalists,
appeared on the paper's front page. It read in part: ``The newsroom
employees of The Examiner are proud that our editorial support is
not, and never has been, for sale. We fully expect any employee to
be held accountable for actions that undermine our editorial
integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   In the newsroom of The Chronicle, which has shared its building
and its profits with The Examiner for more than three decades, the
prospect _ however unlikely _ that the new owners might condone
such behavior prompted an equally strong reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Nanette Asimov, an education reporter, joined with dozens of
colleagues in supporting a petition that, she said, declared that
``the appearance of trading our integrity for favors is what we
abhor.'' The petition, Asimov added, calls on Hearst, the
newspaper's prospective owner, to declare that ``this is in no way
Chronicle policy.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, Brown, whose political dealings
have long been the subject of tough, even harsh coverage in The
Examiner, said he remembered no deal. In a telephone interview, the
mayor's deputy press secretary, Ron Vinson, quoted Brown as mocking
the notion of a deal by saying, jokingly: ``The Examiner didn't
keep up their end of the bargain. We've never gotten a break from
The Examiner editorial board.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, James A. Finefrock, the editor of The Examiner's
editorial pages, put a memorandum to his colleagues into the
paper's computer system saying: ``I don't know what Tim White said
or meant in his conversations with Willie Brown. But I do know that
Tim has never asked me to go easy on Brown or anyone else on our
editorial page, nor would he have succeeded had he tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Finefrock said in his memorandum that he wrote the newspaper's
endorsement of Brown's candidacy after all five members of the
editorial board had agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Other Examiner editors point to the newspaper's aggressive
coverage of a federal grand jury investigation of abuses in the
selection of contractors for the long-running expansion of San
Francisco International Airport. One of the people indicted on
charges of fraud last week in connection with the investigation
worked in a city agency.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Bronstein, the newspaper's executive editor, who was having
lunch with Mayor Brown on Sept. 1 when White joined them, said he
believed that the publisher's remarks to the mayor about
cooperation were ``entirely jocular.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing jocular about Reilly's lawsuit. The
Chronicle itself, in a recent, exhaustive reconstruction of the
star-crossed sale, called Reilly ``a wild card slipped into the
deck'' after all other obstacles to sale seemed to be overcome.
</P>
<P>
   He remains the lone opponent to the deal, now that Hearst,
succumbing to Justice Department pressure, found a buyer willing to
keep The Examiner running and keep San Francisco a two-newspaper
town.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
