<P>
   (NYT11) BEIJING -- May 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR MAY 7, 2000 --
JOURNAL-CHINA-COX-1 -- Returning to China five years after moving
away, journalist Julie Chao was stunned by the new sights in
Beijing: fashionably-dressed young men and women sipping mochas at
Starbucks, and mulling over living room furniture and bathroom
fixtures at Ikea. Massive new office buildings, indoor malls and
luxury apartment buildings dominate much of the urban landscape.
Beijing had become a far more international and modern city in just
a few years. But when a postal worker reached for her abacus to add
up her postage, it dawned upon Chao that some very fundamental
things haven't changed at all. Chao standing in Beijing where
bicycles are still the most common way to get around. (Cox News
Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- May 3, 2000 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT -- A central
vacuum system is a convenience, especially in large homes, because
it eliminates the need to drag a vacuum cleaner from room to room
or up and down the stairs. The heart of the system is the power
unit, which produces the suction for vacuuming. It consists of the
motor and dust-collection canister, and is usually located in the
basement, attic or garage. Because the unit remains in a fixed
location and need not be carried about, it utilizes a larger, more
powerful motor than portable ones. (Ed Lipinski/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- May 3, 2000 -- CHINA-U.S.-TRADE -- The
Clinton administration, stepping up its campaign for a China trade
package, on Wednesday promised Congress ``the most intensive
enforcement'' effort ever to hold Beijing to its commitments to
open its markets to U.S. goods and services. From left, Secretary
of Treasury Lawrence Summers, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman,
Commerce Secretary William Daley and Trade Representative Charlene
Barshefsky before the House Ways and Means Committee during a
hearing on trading with China, Wednesday. (Stephen Crowley/The New
York Times)
