<P>
   (NYT7) WINCESTER, Mass. -- May 3, 2000 -- COMMUTE-WORKPLACE --
Terry Murray feels most alive when he is on the move which is why
he spent five years making the two-hour one-way hike to and from
his job as an engineering manager at Bio-Rad Laboratories in
Cambridge, Mass. It wasn't until he strapped on a pair of in-line
skates and headed out the door one morning last year, though, that
his commute became really interesting. Rolling toward his job,
Murray skates through a commuter rail parking lot. (Michael
Quan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- May 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR MAY 7, 2000 --
SCHWARTZ-PHOTOGRAPHER -- Charles Schwartz, standing by the turret
of his camera obscura on the roof of his apartment building on the
Upper East Side. The photographic apparatus with its telescopic
lens and mirror of what surely is the only camera obscura of its
size in Manhattan, and one of the very few private devices of its
kind in the world, took three years and the combined efforts of a
structural engineer, an architect and an optics specialist to
complete. It is used as a workplace and storage area for Schwartz's
collection of photographs. ``Imagine, while I'm working the camera,
I'm actually sitting inside of it,'' he says. (Fred R. Conrad/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CULVER CITY, Calif. -- May 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR MAY 7,
2000 -- INDEPENDENT-TV -- Robert Greenwald in the editing room at
his California production studio, has seen producing options
narrow. In the past, with such Emmy Award-winning shows as ``The
Burning Bed'' and ``A Woman of Independent Means,'' Greenwald has
worked with a certain amount of leverage. ``You can have the most
brilliant people in the world running networks, but it's almost a
scientific impossibility for bureaucracies to be inventive and
edgy. They cannot. It's their nature.'' (Steve Goldstein/The New
York Times)
</P>
