<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SF-PAPERS-2NDTAKE-NYT     05-03 0260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-PAPERS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 
UNDATED: two-newspaper town.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Examiner, an afternoon paper whose 102,000 circulation is
less than one-fourth that of The Chronicle's, has remained
financially viable only because of the profit-sharing arrangement
that is part of the joint operating agreement between the two
papers, an agreement set to end when Hearst completes its deal to
buy The Chronicle from the Chronicle Publishing Co.
</P>
<P>
   After the Justice Department made it clear that a sale of The
Examiner was essential before it would consider approving Hearst's
purchase of The Chronicle, Hearst announced in March that it was
selling The Examiner to Ted Fang, a politically well-connected
supporter of Brown and the publisher of a group of neighborhood
newspapers. Hearst is providing Fang with $66 million over the
course of three years to keep The Examiner going.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, whose bid to buy The Examiner was rejected, is now
trying to convince Judge Vaughn R. Walker of U.S. District Court in
San Francisco that the sale is a sham and that The Examiner cannot
survive under Fang's stewardship. Still to testify in the trial are
Fang, Reilly and Hearst's president and chief executive, Frank A.
Bennack Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a soap opera, except it's real life,'' said Tom
Ammiano, the president of the city's Board of Supervisors who was a
candidate for mayor last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano added, facetiously: ``Do we want a two-newspaper town?
Maybe we should have a no-newspaper town. I'm joking, but people
feel the public trust has been betrayed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
