   (NYT21) SAN JOSE DE LAS MATAS, Dominican Republic, -- May 3,
2000 -- NY-CABBIES-DOMINICAN -- The coffins of livery cab drivers,
shipped back from New York nearly once a week during the city's
recent spate of killings, have badly shaken this poor mountain town
of 55,000, which for decades has sent its young men to drive the
streets of New York in pursuit of a decent, if dangerous wage.
Rafael Urena, a taxi driver who has two brothers who drive livery
cabs in New York, planned to join them but was told by his brothers
to wait because of the dangers. (Chris Hedges/The New York Times)
</P>
