<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTLNOTES0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Verona suddenly threat to Juventus in Serie A
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Just when Juventus looked to be pulling away with its
26th Serie A title in Italy, up jumped Verona to throw the fight
for the ``scudetto'' wide open.
</P>
<P>
   Verona, promoted from the lower divisions before the season,
upset Juve 2-0 on Sunday, with Fabrizio Cammarata scoring both
goals. That result, coupled with Lazio's 3-2 victory over Venezia,
brings the Rome club to within two points with two games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Europe's other major leagues also are going down to the
wire. Deportivo La Coruna's fragile lead in Spain also is two
points, thanks to a dramatic breakaway goal by Gustavo Lopez in the
75th minute to give Celta Vigo a 2-1 victory Saturday. Barcelona
blanked Atletico Madrid 2-0 to keep the pressure on.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, Bayer Leverkusen is looking more and more like
Bundesliga champions for the first time, after a 2-0 win over
Hamburg on Sunday to take a three-point lead over Bayern Munich
with two weeks remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester United wrapped up the English Premier League title
two weeks ago, but not without a dramatic twist. The club had
called off a $30 million transfer of PSV Eindhoven striker Ruud Van
Nistelrooy because of an ailing knee. To prove his fitness, the
young Dutch star then went out on the training pitch and suffered a
torn anterior cruciate ligament coming down awkwardly after a
header. He will be out for eight months, making him unavailable for
the Netherlands' ambitions of winning Euro 2000.
</P>
<P>
   BARCA NEEDS ANOTHER MIRACLE
</P>
<P>
   Barcelona turned in a miracle in overcoming a two-goal deficit
to best Chelsea in the European Champions League quarterfinals. The
favored Spanish giants will have to do better next week to advance
to the finals. Their Primera Liga rivals Valencia scored a smashing
4-1 victory Tuesday in the first semifinal leg.
</P>
<P>
   Valencia got two first-half goals from Miguel Angulo and another
on a penalty kick from Gaizka Mendieta before halftime. Barca's
only score came off the foot of Valencia defender Mauricio
Pellegrino for an own goal. But Claudio Lopez might have broken
Barca's back by making it a three-goal affair in second-half
stoppage time.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Real Madrid took a giant step toward making the
finals an all-Spanish affair in a 2-0 home victory over Bayern
Munich.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN2 will show the return legs of both series live, Bayern
Munich-Real Madrid on Tuesday and Barcelona-Valencia on Wednesday.
Air time is 2:30 p.m. both days.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: MATCHES CALLED OFF
</P>
<P>
   Players in all four professional divisions boycotted play last
weekend. The mass cancellations included the First Division ``El
Classico'' renewal between Buenos Aires giants River Plate and Boca
Juniors. The players' association called the strike to protest a
lack of security at a third-division match two weeks ago in which
10 players were attacked by opposing fans, who invaded the pitch.
The holdout could continue this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: TWO MORE QUALIFY
</P>
<P>
   The final weekend of the Torneo Verano regular season will be a
wild one: Five of the eight playoff spots are still to be
determined. Guadalajara earned a berth with a 4-0 rout of city
rivals U.A. de G., as Jesus Mendoza had a pair of goals. An
82nd-minute score from Martin Boasso earned Santos a 2-2 draw with
Leon and secured a playoff position.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLAND: OLSEN GETS THE SACK
</P>
<P>
   Facing relegation from the top flight for the first time in 14
seasons, Wimbledon fired former Norwegian World Cup coach Egil
Olsen on Monday, less than a day after Bradford City defeated the
Dons 3-0. Wimbledon has lost eight matches in a row.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: SAD TIMES IN SEVILLA
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish press raised questions has been
second-division-bound Sevilla's 3-2 loss to Oviedo over the
weekend. Meanwhile, Real Betis fired coach Guus Hiddink on Tuesday,
as it faces the possibility of making the drop with its crosstown
rival. Hiddink was 1-6-6 at Betis, which was routed 4-0 by Mallorca
on Sunday to run its winless streak to 11. Sevilla trailed 3-0
before scoring two late goals against Oviedo, which stays five
points ahead of Betis and one spot above the danger zone. Three
years ago, Betis lost to Sporting Gijon under questionable
circumstances, with Sevillia being relegated. As the game drew to
an end Sunday, Sevilla fans chanted, ``Bye-bye, Betis. You're going
down. We've got our revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: BARTHEZ DEMANDS TRANSFER
</P>
<P>
   AS Monaco goalkeeper Fabien Barthez is seeking a transfer from
the French first-division champions after alleging that manager
Claude Puel suggested that he threw a match last month against
Olympique de Marseille. Marseille fought off relegation in a 4-2
victory as Barthez, the bald French World Cup hero, had his worst
outing of the season. Club officials said Barthez misinterpreted
their concerns that he played poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
