<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OCONNOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CARDINAL JOHN O'CONNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, May 4:
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal John O'Connor, who died Wednesday after 16 years as the
voice of U.S. Catholicism, was a strong-willed, conservative
theologian whose views were tempered with a pastoral concern for
the sick, the weak and the poor. For the 2 million Roman Catholics
in the New York Archdiocese, the cardinal brought a return to a
rigorous traditional Catholicism. He passionately opposed abortion,
birth control, homosexuality, the ordination of women and even
baseball on Good Friday. Such views stirred controversy among many
New Yorkers and even some of his own parishioners, but he balanced
them with a plea for those in need, even when the needy were at
odds with his strong Catholic message.
</P>
<P>
   In the days when AIDS patients had trouble getting medical care,
he appealed to Catholic medical workers to help. He battled for
better conditions for immigrant drivers and underpaid health care
workers. Even in his last months, the cardinal mustered the
strength to speak out against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's plans to
require the homeless to work for their shelter. And he had begun to
worry that America was returning to the robber-baron era,
``creating a survival-of-the-fittest society.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing himself as ``a kid from an ordinary family in
Philadelphia,'' the cardinal was ordained into the priesthood in
1945. He became a Navy chaplain and rose to the rank of rear
admiral. In 1984, he became archbishop of New York and a year later
was named cardinal, replacing the quiet leadership of Cardinal
Terence Cooke. The shift was dramatic, with progressive New Yorkers
forced to adjust to a new cardinal who supported the war in Vietnam
and had compared abortion to the Holocaust, a statement that so
enraged Jewish leaders that one rabbi labeled it an ``obscenity.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in those early years that O'Connor proclaimed his
plain-spoken message not only from the pulpit at St. Patrick's
Cathedral on Fifth Avenue, but also at regular press conferences
after mass or on his own weekly television show. As a very public
priest in the nation's media capital, he soon became not only
America's top Catholic but also U.S. Catholicism's number one
conservative communicator. His critics began to label him a papal
disciplinarian who enforced Pope John Paul II's strict church
doctrine within his church as forcefully as he preached his
Catholicism in the less-obedient political arena.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, the cardinal's rhetoric softened and, although
never very far out of the city's political mix, he began to remove
the press conference from his weekly rituals. In one interview a
few years ago, he mused that the church might have been better off
``if, when I came here, I had just become a silent servant of the
people.'' It was a view his fans soundly rejected.
</P>
<P>
   He also regretted denouncing Salman Rushdie without first
reading ``The Satanic Verses'' and was distressed that his
challenge of Geraldine Ferraro's views on abortion was used against
her unfairly. The cardinal's supporters felt that his political
troubles arose when he tried to reassert the church's fundamental
principles as Pope John Paul II's agent in New York. But this firm
theological stand against reform or even moderation in his own
church also gave him clout as a mediator in other areas. The
cardinal was a strong force for ecumenism and worked to improve his
church's relations with the Jewish community. His career as
military chaplain and support of the Vietnam War, which he later
revised, nevertheless brought more attention to his anti-nuclear
stance and his push to cut defense spending. More recently, after
the shooting of Amadou Diallo by police last year, the cardinal
tried to bring all sides together to defuse racial anger ignited by
the innocent black man's death.
</P>
<P>
   As archbishop, he watched over a changing flock, with a growing
Hispanic community and diverse population of immigrants. O'Connor
will be remembered as the pope's dutiful emissary in New York City,
a powerful advocate for Catholic theology and human charity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
