<HEADER>
A4983 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-RAC-DERBY-HNS &LR;      05-03 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED M. FAOUR  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Neil Drysdale is not your typical Kentucky Derby
rookie.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, 9-5 favorite Fusaichi Pegasus and 6-1 shot War Chant will
be the trainer's first starters in the Run for the Roses when they
hold Saturday's 126th running of the race at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   But Drysdale has accomplished much in the sport, including being
named to the horse racing Hall of Fame on Tuesday. He has been to
Churchill with a potential Derby winner before, too. A.P. Indy, who
went on to become the 3-year-old champion and Horse of the Year in
1992, was scratched the morning of the Derby with a bruised foot.
</P>
<P>
   So you'll have to excuse Drysdale if he isn't excited about
having the race favorite after Wednesday's draw for post position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race day isn't here yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When it arrives, a full field of 20 3-year-olds will go 1\ miles
for a purse of $1 million in America's most famous race.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, with Kent Desormeaux riding, will break from
the No. 16 post; War Chant (Jerry Bailey) will break from the No. 9
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Among the contenders, the D. Wayne Lukas-trained High Yield got
the worst of it, drawing the No. 18 post. But Lukas won his fourth
Derby last year when Charismatic also broke from post 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's a good sign,'' he said. ``Each time that we've
won it, we've agonized a bit over the post position, and it turned
out all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Charismatic, Lukas' other winners _ Winning Colors
(1988, 11 post), Thunder Gulch (1995, 16) and Grindstone (1996, 15)
_ started from unfavorable posts.
</P>
<P>
   High Yield, with Pat Day up, will be part of a four-horse
betting entry (meaning if you bet on one, you collect on any of the
four) with the Lukas-trained Commendable (No. 13 post, Edgar Prado)
and a pair of horses trained by Todd Pletcher, Trippi (No. 6 post,
Jorge Chavez) and Impeachment (No. 15, Craig Perret). The horses
have common ownership, hence the same betting interest. The entry
is 5-1 in the morning line.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas' other horse, 30-1 Exchange Rate with Calvin Borel riding,
will break from post No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Pletcher has two other horses, including More Than Ready (John
Velazquez), which drew post position No. 10 and was made 10-1 by
oddsmaker Mike Battaglia. Pletcher also has Arkansas Derby winner
Graeme Hall (Shane Sellers), 20-1 from post No. 14.
</P>
<P>
   In the two-tiered, made-for-TV post draw, horses first are
assigned a selection order of 1-20. The connections then select
which post they want in that order. Bob Baffert, winner of two of
the last three Derbies, had first choice and took No. 8 for Captain
Steve, who is 8-1 and will be ridden by Robby Albarado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a cavalry charge anyway,'' Baffert said. ``At
least we didn't get stuck outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal's Hope, the sentimental favorite with 88-year-old trainer
Harold Rose, drew post No. 5 with Roger Velez riding in his first
Derby. The 1999 Juvenile Champion, Anees (Corey Nakatani), will
break from post No. 2 and was made 20-1 by Battaglia.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just shows how strong this field is,'' Battaglia said,
``that the juvenile champ is 20-1.''
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy will break from post 11 and was made the 4-1 second
choice.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the four-horse entry, there will be a two-horse
entry owned by Godolphin Stable _ China Visit and Curule. Though
Battaglia dismissed the pair at 50-1, China Visit is unbeaten in
two starts in Dubai.
</P>
<P>
   There will be three horses in the mutuel field (again, bet on
one and you get them all) _ Deputy Warlock, Ronton and Wheelaway,
all 30-1.
</P>
<P>
   But this might be Drysdale's year. He has contenders in Fusaichi
Pegasus and War Chant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both horses couldn't be feeling any better,'' Drysdale said.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus will try to become the first favorite since
Spectacular Bid in 1979 to win the Derby. His temperamental
behavior has been a big topic at Churchill all week, and Drysdale,
who had the 12th selection, passed up several inside posts to take
No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked it to keep him out of trouble,'' he said. ``I didn't
want him to stand in the gate too long in case something goes
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Little has gone wrong for Drysdale in his career. Besides A.P.
Indy, Drysdale has trained champions Princess Rooney, Hollywood
Wildcat, Tasso and Fiji. Drysdale, a native of England, has enjoyed
a spectacular 1999, with 73 victories.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, he'll look for the biggest win of all.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
