<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HALSHOPE-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAL'S HOPE IS ONE UNLIKELY STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Elsie Rose writes books, self-published. If
she hasn't made the bestseller list, it's understandable judging by
her latest work in progress, a sentimental and implausible tale
with an undetermined ending.
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of a kindly, 88-year-old horse trainer enjoying a
new lease on life after a major heart attack and the 3-year-old
colt he bred and owns. Oh, and the jockey, a 43-year-old getting a
second chance after nearly drinking himself off the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   And did we mention that the colt comes out of obscurity to win a
stakes race at 40-1, that the old man gets bold and enters him in
the Florida Derby and the beast wins that too?
</P>
<P>
   And did we leave out the part where the old man and the horse
and the jockey end up at the Kentucky Derby?
</P>
<P>
   Elsie Rose's subject is her husband, Harold Rose, his horse,
Hal's Hope, and jockey Roger Velez. If the story ends with a
victory in Saturday's Kentucky Derby, it will be too cute even for
the ``Afterschool Special.'' It just feels as if it's meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you're right,'' Harold Rose said, smiling gently in
stylish, frameless glasses and a cloth cap. ``It would be a nice
ending to a good story.''
</P>
<P>
   Who'd believe it? Except for the fact such things do happen at
the Derby, where, for much of the past decade, the trophy seemed to
be reserved for oldtimers who'd paid their dues
</P>
<P>
   Unbridled owner Frances Genter in 1990, Lil E. Tee owner Cal
Partee in 1992, Sea Hero owner Paul Mellon and trainer Mack Miller
in 1993, Grindstone owner William T. Young in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The chances of Rose and Hal's Hope following in the footsteps of
such sentimental favorites depends on whether you believe the
trainer's optimistic reading of the colt's Derby prep, a fade to
eighth and last behind High Yield and More Than Ready in the Blue
Grass Stakes at Keeneland.
</P>
<P>
   Hal's Hope, a son of Jolie's Halo and Rose-owned Mia's Hope, had
started the Blue Grass as the 7-2 third choice after leading all
the way to edge High Yield in the Florida Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many horses can't handle that (Keeneland) track, and
apparently, he's one of them,'' Rose said outside a Churchill Downs
barn. ``He ran down in (suffered abrasions in) both heels.''
</P>
<P>
   Can Hal's Hope bounce back? He has done it before, going from a
sixth-place finish to a maiden victory at 32-1 at Calder in
November, and from a fifth-place finish to an allowance win at 13-1
at the same Miami track in December.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe his handlers taught him about bouncing back.
</P>
<P>
   Rose's quadruple-bypass surgery last year forced the first break
in his training career since he sold his New York-area printing
business to take up racing full time in 1968. Doctors said he'd be
away from the barn for six weeks. He was back in three.
</P>
<P>
   Velez, a native Floridian, was out of racing for four years in
the early 1990s with a drinking problem. He lived with his mother
and worked at a flower shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like many young people, I made some bad choices,'' Velez said
the other morning. ``But fortunately, I found the right circle and
I turned my life around.''
</P>
<P>
   As Velez tells the story, a girlfriend dying of cancer made him
promise to clean up; meeting his wife, Patti, kept him clean.
Mounts from Rose revived his career.
</P>
<P>
   After Velez rode Hal's Hope to four victories in his first nine
starts, Rose was expected to replace him with an experienced Derby
jockey. In a final nod to good karma, Rose chose loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Four-time Derby-winning trainer D. Wayne Lukas, no less, finds
Rose's Bluegrass excuse plausible. ``Keeneland is a funny track,''
said Lukas, whose High Yield won the race. ``You can't handicap off
the Blue Grass.''
</P>
<P>
   High Yield won't be among the Derby favorites. Of course, he has
never drawn the smart money before, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the little people's horse,'' Velez said. ``He wasn't
supposed to win the Holy Bull (Stakes) at 40-1. He wasn't supposed
to win the Florida Derby. A lot of people are going to have a lot
of fun betting on him Saturday.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
