<HEADLINE>
DISNEY PROFITS SURGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Riding the popularity of ABC's hit game show
``Who Wants to be a Millionaire?,'' The Walt Disney Co. reported a
66 percent increase in quarterly earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Disney reported earnings of $161 million, or 18 cents per share,
compared with $97 million, or 13 cents per share, for the same
period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues increased 14 percent to $6.2 billion, from $5.4 billion
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings figures exclude Disney's interest in GO.com,
operated by Disney but publicly traded as a separate tracking
stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had told you a year ago that an innovative quiz show
would be the catalyst for the revitalization of ABC, you would have
probably thought I was sprinkling a little too much pixie dust,''
said Disney Chairman Michael Eisner in a conference call with
analysts and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire?'' is driving more than just the
resurgence of a once-struggling television network, however, said
analyst Kurt Billick of UBS Warburg Securities in San Francisco.
It's the linchpin of Disney's fortunes as well.
</P>
<P>
   That dependence on one giant success poses risk for investors,
Billick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything rides on the question what happens to
`Millionaire'? If `Millionaire' is strong, then I think you're
going to see the company continue to perform well,'' Billick said.
``Broadcasting is carrying the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's Media Networks division, which includes ABC,
showed a 24 percent increase in revenues from levels in the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Theme parks are a consistent profit center for Disney, Billick
said.
</P>
<P>
   As the company rolls out four new parks by 2005, that sector is
expected to continue to perform well, said Tom Staggs, Disney's
chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   The company's home video and consumer products divisions
continued to struggle. Both were targeted for improvement in
Eisner's four-point plan outlined in his December letter to
shareholders in the company's annual report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the proverbial battleship, it cannot turn on a dime.
Maybe a 50-cent piece,'' Eisner said.
</P>
<P>
   Billick said he expects Disney to show a little weakness in its
cable properties later in its fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Cable business costs are expected to increase as the company
pays more to Major League Baseball and the National Hockey League
for broadcast rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-00 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000503.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-03 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4988 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-PENALTIES-T     05-03 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PENALTIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIZARRE' PENALTIES LEFT STARS IN A GAME 3 LURCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Stars forwards Aaron Gavey and Blake Sloan
sat inches apart. Neither said a word.
</P>
<P>
   For the game's next 51 seconds, they were being forced to sit in
the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   Two impatient sets of eyes shifted from the ice, where time
seemed to fly, to the scoreboard, where it seemed to stand still.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on,'' Sloan thought as he glanced at the clock. ``Go
quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, with 12 seconds remaining in San Jose's five-on-three
power play, forward Mike Ricci scored the Sharks' first goal in
seven periods, five minutes and 42 seconds against the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Gavey stood up. He exited the box and skated to the bench,
leaving Sloan alone in the agony for another 81 seconds. They never
said a word. They didn't need to.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never feel good when they score and you are in the penalty
box,'' Gavey said. ``It's the longest skate in sports, and last
night it seemed even longer.''
</P>
<P>
   When you've just helped inject life into a Sharks team that had
been lifeless, the skate back to the bench seems an eternity. The
path to and from the box was well-worn by the time Game 3 ended
Tuesday and is a big reason Game 4 tomorrow has a new sense of
urgency for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   They know where the path can lead, and they know their chances
of sweeping the series died on that course. And they know they
can't go back down it tomorrow if they plan to win.
</P>
<P>
   This became evident as player after player sat in the box with
plenty of quality time to think.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the best example is like ``Slap Shot'','' Stars
defenseman Richard Matvichuk said. ``You sit there for two minutes
and you feel shame.''
</P>
<P>
   He's joking, of course. Or is he?
</P>
<P>
   The Stars spent 13 minutes, 48 seconds in shame in Game 3,
including 9:48 in the second period. Any longer, the Sharks might
start charging rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like we were short-handed the whole period,'' Stars
captain Derian Hatcher said. ``I had a hard time believing it was
only five penalties. It felt like it was seven or eight to be
honest.''
</P>
<P>
   But what _ beside feeling shame _ does a player exactly do while
he is in the box?
</P>
<P>
   ``You just watch the game and hope the penalty kill bails you
out of the jam you are in,'' Stars winger Scott Thornton said.
</P>
<P>
   Watch the clock. Pray. Try to ignore the obnoxious fan beating
on the glass behind you. Cheer. Drink water. Remember whether you
paid your electric bill. Grumble. Curse the officials under your
breath.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a way to make 120 seconds go faster, the Stars tried
it Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The last way probably was tried more than others.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say the Stars didn't exactly agree with all of the
calls against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to have a summer vacation, and I'm not paying the fine,
so I'm not going there,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said, before
later adding: ``There were some really bizarre calls.''
</P>
<P>
   The unsportsmanlike call against Matvichuk in the second period
was probably more bizarre than the others. The referees ruled he
took a dive, embellishing a hook by Sharks defenseman Brad Stuart.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Sharks were confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Matvichuk took that penalty, I thought for sure it was on
us,'' Stuart admitted, ``but then they got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Matvichuk: ``That's the first one I've seen called in the
playoffs. It was suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan said Sharks goalie Steve Shields took more of a dive on
the penalty that set up the five-on-three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I barely touched him,'' Sloan said. ``I was actually stopped
and trying to go back the other way to get out of the way. I went
to push off, my foot hit him, and he dove down. ... Yeah, he dove
on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Freak calls, not retaliatory swipes, were the reason for the
Stars' many trips to the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the Stars say they aren't worried about what
they'll do in the penalty box in Game 4. They don't plan to spend
as much time there. They think the penalties were more a factor of
how the game was called than being undisciplined.
</P>
<P>
   ``There weren't retaliatory,'' Hatcher said. ``Like Blake
Sloan's penalty. It was just more bad luck than anything. He's just
skating backwards. ... I won't say anything else. It's just bad
luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, bad luck brought Sloan and Gavey inches apart. Neither said
a word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Sloan said. ``You just want to sit there and
stew.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
