<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-LEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAFS EVEN SERIES WITH DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
  By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Just when it appeared that the New
Jersey Devils and the Toronto Maple Leafs were headed for overtime,
Tomas Kaberle of Toronto found himself alone with the puck outside
the left circle in the Devils' zone. With a crowd in front of
Martin Brodeur, Kaberle puckered the net on a left-handed shot with
1 minute 35 seconds left in the third period _ his first goal of
the postseason _ to give the Maple Leafs a 3-2 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's victory evened the Eastern Conference semifinal series
at two games apiece. Game 5 of the best-of-7 series will be played
in Toronto on Saturday, then the series will return to Continental
Arena Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing 2-1 since the first period, the Devils tied the
game on Claude Lemieux's first goal in the playoffs with 5:46 left
in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Gomez scored the first goal in the game for the Devils
against Curtis Joseph, who had 34 saves. The Maple Leafs took the
lead on first-period goals by Jonas Hoglund and Darcy Tucker
against Brodeur, who made 19 saves.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's top line finally produced its first points in the
series, combining for Toronto's first goal in the game and the
first in the opening period in 10 games in the playoffs for the
Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Thomas won a battle against the boards in the neutral zone
and passed the puck to Mats Sundin. The center man relayed the puck
to Hoglund, who beat Brodeur between the pads from the bottom of
the right circle, 10 minutes 1 second into the game.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second goal in the playoffs for Hoglund and it tied
the score after Gomez had put the Devils in the lead with his third
goal in the playoffs and second in as many games, at 1:41.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, on a power play, came on a rebound from close range on
the left after a shot by Lemieux from the right circle was put
there by Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, who was in the penalty box when Gomez opened the
scoring, gave the Maple Leafs the lead with 3:58 left in the first,
lofting a backhander over the fallen Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   With a little luck from the post, Brodeur made perhaps the best
save in the series in the 11th minute. With his teammates out of
position in their zone, Brodeur sprawled across his crease to his
right to stop Sergei Berezin after a setup by Hoglund. He reached
behind him to cover the puck with his glove after it had hit the
post, but he did it while on the seat of his pants to a standing
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto had the better chances during the second period. Players
were crashing each other against the boards, but no goals came
despite three manpower advantages in the period, two by the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had a man advantage in the 11th minute but it seemed
they should have had a two-man edge because Joseph got away with a
slash on Jason Arnott. Only Sundin was sent to the penalty box, for
holding. The Devils failed on that advantage and also when Wendel
Clark was caught high-sticking Ken Daneyko in the 16th minute. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
