u a BC-OCONNOR-SUCCESSOR-NYT     05-03 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCONNOR-SUCCESSOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROCESS OF CHOOSING ARCHBISHOP'S SUCCESSOR IS SHROUDED IN SECRECY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CARDINAL-OCONNOR-OBIT) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The death of Cardinal John O'Connor on Wednesday
night brings new urgency to the question of who might succeed him
as New York's ninth archbishop and the spiritual leader of of 2.4
million Roman Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   The question may be an obvious one for anyone wishing to look
ahead to the future of the archdiocese, whose leader plays a
pre-eminent role in the Catholic Church in America. But the answer,
for now, is deeply obscure.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the appointment of an archbishop is not an open
process. Instead, it is a matter that rests in the hands of the
Vatican, and is shrouded in such secrecy that the appointments to
head some of the most important archdioceses in the United States
have often come as a surprise to those within the church who
thought they were in the know.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the appointment process begins in
Washington and moves to Rome.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the papal nuncio, a prelate appointed by the
Vatican who functions as its ambassador to the federal government
and also as Rome's representative to the American church, comes up
with a short list of possible candidates when an archdiocese or
diocese becomes vacant, or is about to become so.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1998, the nuncio in Washington has been Archbishop Gabriel
Montalvo, 70, a native of Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He draws up a list of three names,'' said the Rev. Thomas
Reese, editor of America magazine, a Jesuit publication, and author
of ``Archbishop: Inside the Power Structure of the American
Catholic Church,'' (Harper &AMP; Row, 1989).
</P>
<P>
   Those choices, Reese added, are based on the nuncio's research,
with information obtained through conversations with other American
cardinals, bishops and prominent Catholics. The discussions are
conducted in the strictest secrecy and those consulted promise they
will not even mention that they have been approached.
</P>
<P>
   But if the past is any guide, a few details can be hazarded
about the candidates likely to be recommended for a major
archdiocese like New York _ whose occupant can expect to be named a
cardinal, with the right to vote in the selection of a future pope.
</P>
<P>
   Because of New York's importance in the American Catholic world,
anyone considered is likely to have experience as head of another
archdiocese or a diocese. He is also likely to be a senior figure
in the church, in his late 50s or 60s. He may have studied or
worked in church institutions in Rome. And he may have a doctorate.
</P>
<P>
   The nuncio ranks his three candidates, then forwards the
recommendations to Rome, to be considered by the Congregation for
Bishops, the Vatican body charged with making the final
recommendations of men to head dioceses worldwide. The congregation
is composed of ``mostly cardinals, some of whom are resident in
Rome, and some are diocesan bishops around the world,'' said the
Rev. John Beal, a professor of canon law at Catholic University of
America. ``For example,'' he added, ``Cardinal O'Connor for a very
long time was a member of the congregation.''
</P>
<P>
   After its deliberations, the congregation sends its selection to
the pope, who may accept it or reject it, asking the congregation
to go back over the list. Or, Beal said, the pope may choose
someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Even before O'Connor underwent surgery for removal of a brain
tumor, there had been speculation throughout church circles over
who his successor might be. Names mentioned have ranged fairly
widely, from Northeastern prelates, like Bishop Henry J. Mansell of
Buffalo, to others outside the region, like Archbishop Justin F.
Rigali of St. Louis, who long worked in Vatican diplomatic circles
and is considered close to Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, choosing a person for New York is a matter that
rests with the pope alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't underestimate the possibility of surprise,'' Beal said.
``I recall that no one had predicted that Cardinal O'Connor would
go from Scranton to New York when it happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
