<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER FACES A FINE BY FCC UNIT
</HEADLINE>
  By By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cable bureau of the Federal Communications Commission blamed
Time Warner Cable Wednesday for cutting off ABC television stations
to 3.5 million subscribers, declaring that Time Warner's action had
violated a federal regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC said it would separately consider what enforcement
action to take, but a spokesman for the agency said Time Warner was
likely to face a fine.
</P>
<P>
   The fine, an FCC official said, will be based on a charge of at
least $7,500 per violation per day in the areas that were blacked
out. Because seven areas lost access to ABC stations, Time Warner
could be liable for seven violations but in any event the amount of
the fine will not exceed $250,000, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the FCC chairman, William E. Kennard, said:
``Time Warner Cable committed a clear violation of FCC rules.
Unfortunately millions of consumers paid the price.'' He added,
``No company should use consumers in a private contract dispute.''
</P>
<P>
   The violation occurred, the FCC said, because Time Warner pulled
ABC stations off its cable systems in the middle of a ratings
sweeps month.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner, after a protracted impasse in negotiations with The
Walt Disney Co., the parent of ABC, stopped sending ABC-owned
stations to areas around the country, including New York, Los
Angeles and Houston, on Monday. The two sides agreed Tuesday to an
extended deadline in their talks and ABC's signals were restored.
</P>
<P>
   The general counsel for Time Warner Cable, Marc Apfelbaum, said
in response to the FCC announcement that the company would ``pursue
a further review'' of the decision. In a statement, he questioned
why only the cable bureau and not the entire commission made the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we agree this ambiguous rule needs clarification,''
Apfelbaum said, referring to the sweeps month rule, ``it is
unfortunate that on an important issue affecting the entire cable
industry, and where there was no emergency, that this was done
without the full commission being involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney executives applauded the decision. Michael Eisner, the
Disney chairman, said during a conference call with securities
analysts that Time Warner had damaged Disney's brand name and
reputation by treating ABC shabbily.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Peter F. Vallone, the speaker of the New York City
Council, met with Barry Rosenblum, the president of Time Warner
Cable, in New York and contended that Time Warner had violated its
franchise agreement with the city. Vallone said he believed the
company had an obligation to reimburse customers for part of their
cable bill this month.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Luftman, a spokesman for Time Warner Cable, said the
company was not ready to announce a rebate but said, ``Our
intention is to go further than that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
