<HEADLINE>
AGCO CORP. TO CLOSE PLANT, LAY OFF 500 EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Mo. _ Agco Corp., citing the weak farm economy,
said Wednesday it will close its Independence combine and tractor
plant at the end of June and lay off 500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Duluth, Ga., company said the industrywide slump in the
demand for agricultural equipment led to the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Independence plant has experienced seasonal layoffs through
the years. Nevertheless, Wednesday's announcement surprised the
work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a shock,'' said Jerry Johnson, sub-director of
District 11 of the United Steelworkers of America union in
Independence. ``It would've been less surprising three years ago
when the industry was at an all-time low. But production picked
back up after that, although things have slowed down in the past
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The plant has manufactured the ``Gleaner'' line of combines as
well as tractors under the ``White'' and ``AGCO Allis'' names.
Formerly operated by Deutz-Allis Corp., the plant was part of a
management buyout in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Agco said the products made in Independence will be moved to its
facility in Hesston, Kan., or handled by third-party manufacturers.
Although the company said there could be opportunities for some
employees to transfer, Johnson said such prospects seemed unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations on a severance package that addresses issues like
health insurance, pensions and job-placement assistance will begin
in mid-May, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Agco has about 320 hourly union employees and about 180 salaried
employees, said Lorna Robinson, an Agco spokeswoman. The company
declined to disclose the plant's annual payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Ratliff, Agco's executive chairman, said a globalwide
decline in demand for farm equipment has led to underutilized
plants in Agco's system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize this decision will impact hundreds of dedicated
employees that have contributed to the growth of Agco and have not
entered into it without consideration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Agco already consolidated production from a plant in Ohio to
Hesston, Robinson said. Products made at an Agco plant in Lockney,
Texas, also are in the process of moving to Hesston, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the Independence shutdown eventually will save
the company $10 million annually. The company will take a $20
million charge this year to close the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Agco said production will stop June 30 and the plant will be
completely vacated by the end of this year. Agco plans to sell the
524,000 square-foot facility.
</P>
<P>
   Before the farm crisis of the early 1980s, the plant employed as
many as 1,300 people.
</P>
<P>
   The Independence Chamber of Commerce is working with Agco and
Missouri Job Service to conduct a job fair for the laid-off Agco
work force, said Rick Hemmingsen, the chamber president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing but not surprising it happened,''
Hemmingsen said. ``We fully realize the global consolidation
happening in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The chamber has many members who already have expressed interest
in taking part in the job fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know these workers are very capable, and hopefully, we'll
be able to help them in the transition,'' Hemmingsen said.
``Depending on skill levels, there are comparable-paying jobs out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   But one economist said finding similar-paying work in the
manufacturing sector would not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demand in the economy is for high-tech, computer-skills
jobs and lower-paying jobs in services and retail,'' said Frank
Lenk, director of research services with the Mid-America Regional
Council. ``Manufacturing employment has been fairly stable over the
last decade. That puts the (Agco employees) in a tough bind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
