<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTMONEY-PLAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS DROP PLAN TO DELAY IDENTIFYING `SOFT MONEY' DONORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats have abandoned a policy of delaying
disclosure of ``soft money'' contributions to fund-raising
committees affiliated with Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan and other
candidates for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee came under fire
last week for deciding to withhold the names of contributors to
committees such as Missouri 2000, which was set up in conjunction
with Carnahan's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Under that policy, $117,000 in donations to Missouri 2000 would
not be reported until the money was transferred to the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee, rather than monthly, as was done
previously.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have decided to return to our previous policy to disclose
and itemize contributions on a monthly basis,'' Jim Jordan,
political director of the senatorial committee, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said the initial change was made for bookkeeping reasons,
but he said Carnahan and other Senate candidates wanted more timely
disclosure of contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been contacted by several of our campaign committees
who feel rather strongly we should be disclosing this on a regular,
predictable and frequent basis,'' Jordan said. Carnahan campaign
spokesman Tony Wyche said the governor had asked for the change.
</P>
<P>
   The sources of the $117,000 in soft money to Missouri 2000, who
donated the money in March, will be disclosed May 20 along with
April contributions, Jordan said. In subsequent months, donors will
be disclosed on the 20th day of the following month.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money represents unlimited and corporate contributions that
individual candidates are not allowed to accept. Instead, it goes
to parties' national committees for various spending that advances
their causes.
</P>
<P>
   Most campaign reports by law must be filed quarterly, but Jordan
said last week that Democrats had found a legal exception for soft
money donations to so-called joint committees, such as Missouri
2000. Lawyers thought that names of contributors could be kept
under wraps indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said ``the carping of Republicans'' and others had
nothing to do with the change in policy, which affects not only the
Carnahan committee but also the committees of Hillary Rodham
Clinton and several other Democratic Senate candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
