<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACADEMY-CLOSING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS PLEAD FOR MONEY TO SAVE MILITARY ACADEMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOONVILLE, Mo. _ Cally White, Patrick Griffin, Jerra Rhea and
Nikki Marino, teen-agers from across the country, shared a dislike
for Kemper Military School when they first arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Too much structure. Too much discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Now the students share the opposite feeling _ adoration _ for
this 156-year-old school where they live together, study together
and grow up together.
</P>
<P>
   This campus of old, red-brick buildings in the middle of
Missouri is their second home _ a home they don't want to say
goodbye to if the school must close.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said it is highly likely Kemper Military School
and College will shut down May 13, the day money will run out to
keep the school going.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Lt. Col. Tom Challender, the school's director of alumni
affairs, said there still is hope that alumni and friends of the
school will come to the aid of this institution that has been
educating teen-agers since 1844.
</P>
<P>
   Challender's office phone rang continuously Wednesday after
people learned of the likely closing, with many graduates offering
thousands of dollars in donations.
</P>
<P>
   But the $1.3 million needed to keep the school open will be hard
to find.
</P>
<P>
   School president Edward E. Ridgley announced the likely closing
on the school's Web site Tuesday. He would not comment Wednesday on
the school's financial situation.
</P>
<P>
   The students are trying to get financial help for Kemper
Military, where middle school, high school and junior college
students learn academic subjects as well as the traditions of the
U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
   In handwritten letter after handwritten letter, the students
this week have begged alumni for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day after day I look at Kemper as my savior,'' one student
wrote. ``From this school I have learned purpose. I have gained
some encouragement back into my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Another wrote: ``This place has straightened me out &AMP; gave me
the strength I need to get through life. This is my home. These
people here are my family....This school saved so many kids
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Many cadets said the closeness to other students and teachers is
what makes them glad they attend Kemper.
</P>
<P>
   Cally White, a high school junior in a blue cadet uniform, her
brown hair pulled back in a bun, said she has learned honor and
respect in a year at Kemper. She's miles away from her home in New
Hampshire, but she has found love and acceptance here.
</P>
<P>
   She has learned to hold her head up, discipline herself and take
on challenging classes.
</P>
<P>
   White said her parents are in shock about the school's pending
closure, and her father has offered to maker a donation.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't thought yet about where she might go to school in the
fall if the school closes. Finals are next week, and she wants to
stay focused on doing well.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Griffin, a high school senior who came to Kemper from
Washington state two years ago, said he has become a new person.
Griffin said he was a slacker and drug abuser in his public high
school, but now considers himself an achiever and thanks his mom
for sending him to a military boarding school.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got people from all around the country and the world,
and we make it work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken Griffin gave a big smile when he said his
parents will come to Missouri for his graduation May 13. His plans
for the fall aren't firm yet, but he eventually wants to go into
the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Kemper's closing saddens Samuel Mackey, a 19-year-old from
Kansas City who is a first-year student in the junior college.
</P>
<P>
   He pays Kemper's annual $18,000 tuition with an ROTC
scholarship, after he participated in Junior ROTC at Westport High
School.
</P>
<P>
   He said Kemper is a lot safer than Westport was, without the
fights and the drugs he said were common there. When he first
arrived, he couldn't believe all the rules, the push-ups and the
sit-ups, and the insistence on respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Whoa, what have I gotten myself into?' '' he said.
But since then, he's enjoyed his schoolwork and ROTC.
</P>
<P>
   If Kemper closes, he hopes to take his ROTC scholarship to the
University of Missouri-Columbia, where he had planned to go for his
third and fourth years of college.
</P>
<P>
   But until school officials announce their final decision on
whether to close the school, Mackey said he and his brother and
sister cadets are ``just floating up in the air.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
