A5029 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DEATH-JURY-KAN &LR;      05-03 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-JURY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JURY RECOMMENDS DEATH PENALTY IN MURDER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For the first time in 44 years, a federal
jury in Kansas City has recommended the death penalty in a murder
case.
</P>
<P>
   After five hours of deliberation over two days, jurors on
Wednesday told U.S. District Judge Gary Fenner that German C.
Sinisterra, 35, should die by lethal injection for his role as
trigger man in the 1998 murder of drug dealer Julian Colon.
</P>
<P>
   Death sentences are automatically appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should be commended for the courage of your verdicts,''
Assistant U.S. Attorney Jeffrey Valenti told jurors. ``It's time to
finish the job.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury returned to court after lunch to begin hearing penalty
arguments against Arboleda A. Ortiz, Sinisterra's co-defendant.
Ortiz, 33, and another co-defendant, Plutarco Tello, 34, also could
face a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing closing arguments in Ortiz's case, the jury
adjourned at about 4 p.m. It is scheduled to return Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Should the jury not reach a unanimous verdict for capital
punishment, Ortiz and Tello would automatically be sentenced to
life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's sentence, which Fenner must impose, is the first
federal death-sentence handed down in the Western District of
Missouri since Jan. 25, 1956. That year, a jury needed only 15
minutes to recommend that California robber and arsonist Arthur
Ross Brown be executed for the abduction and slaying of Wilma Allen
from a Brookside shopping area.
</P>
<P>
   Ross died in Missouri's gas chamber on Feb. 24, 1956.
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, a federal jury recommended death sentences for Carl
Austin Hall and Bonnie Brown Heady for the kidnapping and murder of
6-year-old Bobby Greenlease.
</P>
<P>
   Hall and Heady were executed for the kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   One other capital murder case currently rests on the federal
docket in Kansas City. If convicted of the abduction, sexual abuse
and killing last fall of 10-year-old Pamela Butler, Keith Nelson
also could face the death penalty. His trial is scheduled to begin
in October.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the jury convicted Sinisterra, Ortiz and Tello of
murdering Colon in a Prospect Avenue house after accusing him and
another man of stealing $240,000 in drug-trafficking profits.
</P>
<P>
   Colon, 23, and his nephew, Herberth Andres Borja-Molina, 17,
were bound with duct tape, taunted and beaten. But while Colon was
killed with a gunshot to the head, a similar shot meant for
Borja-Molina failed to find its mark and he feigned death.
</P>
<P>
   They were dumped in the trunk of a car, which was left in Swope
Park. Borja-Molina escaped and returned to testify against his
attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors described Sinisterra, Ortiz and Tello as a
professional hit squad, sent from Houston to enforce discipline in
Kansas City after the cocaine profits went astray.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers portrayed their clients as low-level drug ring
functionaries who had agreed to intimidate Colon and Borja-Molina,
but not kill them. They said a fourth co-defendant in the case,
Edwin R. Hinestroza, ultimately was responsible for the killings.
Hinestroza has not been arrested. He remains a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   After the jury returned the death sentence against Sinisterra, a
Colombian national, lawyers representing Ortiz scaled back plans to
present testimony from friends and family members. Larry Pace, an
assistant federal public defender, said jurors appeared unmoved by
similar testimony offered on Sinisterra's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Pace focused on the night of Nov. 28, 1998, and emphasized that
Colon was killed on the first floor of the house, while Ortiz was
dealing with Borja-Molina in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arboleda Ortiz doesn't deserve to die because he didn't kill
anybody,'' Pace said. ``If you are going to have a death penalty,
it should be reserved for people who intentionally kill other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Pace also assailed prosecutors for using testimony from
Borja-Molina, who acknowledged his role in Hinestroza's drug
business, but faced no charges from prosecutors in return for his
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Miller said that's a deal he'd
gladly make again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conspiracies hatched in hell do not have angels as
witnesses,'' Miller said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
