<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON CALLS ON GIULIANI TO REJECT INDEPENDENCE PARTY
</HEADLINE>
  By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT EDWARD, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton called on Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani Wednesday to reject the nomination of the
Independence Party if the organization nominates Pat Buchanan to
run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton again attacked Buchanan for making what she described as
bigoted and anti-Semitic statements. The first lady, without
mentioning Giuliani by name, said that her Republican opponent in
the race should decline to run on the Independence Party line if
Buchanan is at the top of the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not run on a ballot with him,'' Clinton said at a news
conference here as she traveled through the Adirondacks. ``And I
think that is the position that anyone who wants to represent all
of New York and all New Yorkers should be taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has repeatedly attacked Buchanan, though he stopped
short, on an appearance Wednesday night on MSNBC, of saying he
would not accept the support of the Independence Party if it
endorsed Buchanan as its presidential candidate. Giuliani's aides
have been pushing to win the Independence Party endorsement, in the
belief that it could provide Giuliani an important source of votes
in what is expected to be a close election. The Independence Party
is the New York arm of the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I could do that, but I'm hoping they don't do
that,'' Giuliani said at the prospect of running on the same ticket
as Buchanan. ``I'm hoping they make some other choice. I think it's
a very important party; the Independence Party is a very important
party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they ended up doing that,'' Giuliani added, ``then I'd have
to think long and hard about it. I probably wouldn't want to be on
that ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton eagerly attacked Buchanan, the conservative commentator,
at her news conference Wednesday after he attacked her on Tuesday,
while praising Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made her comments at the start of a two-day sweep into
the Adirondacks and the Republican heart of upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who moved to New York in January, sounded almost like a
tourist promoter as she recounted her travels through the state,
learning about local issues and history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am finding that as I talk about it, more New Yorkers are
saying, `I didn't know that; I had no idea that was going on in the
north country or western New York,''' she said. ``I am hoping not
only will I have a very firm grounding in what goes on all over the
state but that more New Yorkers will learn about the history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
