<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF
</HEADLINE>
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH SEEKS HELP: Gov. George W. Bush of Texas reached out
Wednesday for an experienced Republican hand, Andrew H. Card Jr.,
to watch over Bush's interests at this summer's national convention
in Philadelphia. Card, vice president for governmental relations
for the General Motors Corp., worked in the White House under
President George Bush as deputy chief of staff and later was
transportation secretary. He is the second member of the elder
Bush's cabinet to join the governor's political organization in
recent weeks. The first was Dick Cheney, President Bush's defense
secretary, who was chosen to run the governor's vice presidential
search committee.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Alison Mitchell
</P>
<P>
   THE ISSUES
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION RIGHTS ALERT: The National Abortion Rights and
Reproductive Action League is promoting Vice President Al Gore with
a television ad warning that if Governor Bush is elected President,
he will appoint Supreme Court justices who will overturn Roe vs.
Wade, the landmark abortion rights decision. The ads also warn that
Bush ``even supports a constitutional amendment to outlaw
abortion.'' Bush is on record as saying that he will appoint
justices who will ``strictly interpret'' the Constitution. Kate
Michelman, president of the league, says the right to a legal
abortion is in danger because two or more supporters may leave the
court in the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   _ By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
